<HEAD>I. Sammlung des Ms. Vernon, Bruchst&uuml;ck einer metrischen Uebertragung von Legenden aus des Jacobi a Voragine "Legenda Aurea".</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000008.tif" N="[2]">


<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000009.tif" N="[3]">
<HEAD>1. S. Paula.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>Der Anfang, c. 250 V., fehlt im Ms. Vernon, da ein Blatt hier ausgefallen ist. Das lateinische Original dieser Legende, wie der ganzen Sammlung, ist des Jacobi a Voragine (c. 1290) bekannte "Legenda aurea", aus der der Dichter einzelne Legenden w&ouml;rtlich metrisch &uuml;bertragen hat; Paula findet sich daselbst in cap. 29; de sancta Paula (ed. Gr&auml;sse Dresd. &amp; Lips. 1846).<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>In der Edit princ. Dresd. 1472 fehlt diese Legende der Paula. Eine Prosa&uuml;bertragung derselben, aber unter dem Titel S. Pauline statt Paula, enth&auml;lt die altenglische Uebersetzung der Leg. Aur. (Ms. Egert. 876, Harl. 630, Harl 4775), welche im Anfange des 15 Jhdts. von mehreren "Doctoren der Theologie" nach der franz&ouml;sischen Uebersetzung des Jehan de Vignay angefertigt und sp&auml;ter von Caxton &uuml;berarbeitet und gedruckt wurde; diese engl. Uebertragung ist bereits sehr verderbt.</P></NOTE></P><P>Der im Anfang ausgefallene Theil erz&auml;hlte, wie Paula, deren Leben mit des Hieronymus, ihres Freundes und Biographen, eigenen Worten geschildert wird, eine edle R&ouml;merin war, von solcher Tugend und G&uuml;te, dass es unm&ouml;glich w&auml;re sie nach Verdienst zu preisen; wie der Edelstein die anderen Gesteine, wie die Sonne der Sterne Heer verdunkelt, so &uuml;berstrahlte sie Alle durch Demuth und Mildth&auml;tigkeit; durch Ge|burt und Reichthum hervorragend, erschien sie die geringste unter den Weibern. Nach dem Tode ihres Gemahls, dem sie f&uuml;nf Kinder geschenkt, besuchte sie, nur von ihrer Tochter Eustochium begleitet, das heilige Land und weilte andachtsvoll an den St&auml;tten wo Christus gelebt und gelitten hatte. So dem&uuml;thig, dass man sie f&uuml;r die letzte der M&auml;gde halten konnte, so enthaltsam, dass sie nur wenig und auf hartem Boden schlief, beweinte sie geringe S&uuml;nden als habe sie die gr&ouml;ssten Verbrechen begangen. Ihre Wohlth&auml;tigkeit war so gross, dass Hieronymus sie einmal desshalb tadelte, auf die Worte des Apostels<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vgl. 2 Corinth. 8, 13-14. Der Text der Vulgata stimmt nicht w&ouml;rtlich mit der oben citirten Stelle &uuml;berein.</NOTE> hinweisend: "non ut aliis refrigerium sit, vobis autem tribulatio, sed ex aequalitate in hoc tempore, ut vestra abundantia sit ad illorum ino|piam et illorum abundantia sit ad vestram inopiam" (&mdash; hier schliesst der englische Text an, V. I &mdash;), und ihr bemerkte: et providendum esse, ne quod libenter faceret semper facere non posset (so V. 2-5). Ihre Entgegnung siehe V. 6.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>"Ei&thorn;ur o&thorn;ur &thorn;us to clo&thorn;un and fede;</L>
<L>Such purueaunce men schulde make</L>
<L>&THORN;at charite gunne not to slake,</L>
<L>But as he gladliche nou &yogh;iue&thorn; and do&thorn;</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at he mowe do afturward for&thorn;."</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eos word was heo nouht aferd,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">der latein. Text in der Leg. Aur. cap. 29 (ed. Gr&auml;sse) f&auml;hrt fort: Quae illa mira verecundia (et sermone parcissimo peritissimoque) dissolvebat, testem invocans dominum (engl. directe Rede) se pro illius nomine cuncta facere et hoc habere voti ut mendicans ipsa moreretur, ut unum nummum filiae non dimitteret et in funere suo ali|ena sindone involveretur.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000010.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>Ful myldeliche heo onswerd:</L>
<L>"God i take to my witnes,</L>
<L>For his loue do i &thorn;is godnes;</L>
<L N="10">And also hit is my disir</L>
<L>To dye a pore beggir,</L>
<L>No peni to my douhtres leue,</L>
<L>So clene awey my good to &yogh;eue</L>
<L>&THORN;at of myn owne leue nouht bihynde.</L>
<L N="15">A schete, my bodi in to wynde,</L>
<L>Of moni men &thorn;at her liue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad extremum inferebat:) Ego si petiero, multos inveniam qui mihi tribuant; iste mendicans si a me non acceperit quid ei possum etiam de alieno tribuere, si mortuus fuerit, a quo ejus anima requireretur? (V. 22 Zusatz des Dichters)</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if i bidde, &thorn;ei wol me &yogh;iue;</L>
<L>A beggere &yogh;if he aske of me</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur monnes &thorn;ing &thorn;auh hit be,</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;if I from him &thorn;enne torne myn e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne for faute &thorn;e pore mon dye,&mdash;</L>
<L>I take witnes of seint Poule&mdash;</L>
<L>God of me wol aske his soule."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is wommon of so gret nobleye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nolebat in his lapidibus effundere pecuniam qui cum terra et saeculo transituri sunt, sed in vivis lapidibus qui volvuntur super terram (32-33 erkl&auml;r. Zusatz), de quibus in Apocalipsi Johannis: civitas magni regis exstruitur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">Wolde not spende hire moneye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo hedde kept for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L>In to suche precious stones</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;is world and eor&thorn;e here</L>
<L>Passen awey al in fere,</L>
<L N="30">But to stones &thorn;at meuen and lyue,</L>
<L>To whuche God ha&thorn; his grace i&yogh;iue:</L>
<L>In eor&thorn;e her &thorn;at ben pore</L>
<L>And sum tyme hungren and &thorn;ursten sore,&mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whuche, wi&thorn;oute lipse,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">lipse: ellipse.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">Seint Jon seide in &thorn;e Apocalipse:</L>
<L>&THORN;e cite of &thorn;e grete kynge</L>
<L>Is mad ouer alle &thorn;inge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O&THORN;ur souuel vsede heo non<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Exceptis festis diebus vix oleum in cibo accipiebat, ut ex hoc uno aestimaretur quid de vino et de liquamine et piscibus et lacte et melle et ovis et reliquis quae gustui suavia sint judicarit,</NOTE></L>
<L>But oyle wi&thorn; hire bred alon,</L>
<L N="40">But hit were &thorn;e grettore festeday;</L>
<L>&THORN;en lutel mete wolde hire pay.</L>
<L>Of hony o&thorn;ur milk or elles fisch</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur eiren comen non in heore disch,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur metes &thorn;at to mou&thorn; ben swete,</L>
<L N="45">Ful luyte of hem heo wolde ete. &mdash;</L>
<L>Sum men &thorn;er ben neuer&thorn;eles:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in quibus sumendis quidam se abstinentissimos putant et, si his ventrem ingurgitaverint, tutam pudicitiam suspicantur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;auh &thorn;ei vsen no gret deyntes,</L>
<L>Her wombes &thorn;ei wollen wi&thorn; such metes fille</L>
<L>And chastite &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei spille,</L>
<L N="50">And &yogh;it &thorn;ei wene hit beo clannes</L>
<L>Hem to fulle wi&thorn; suche mes. &mdash;</L>
<L><STAGE>(JERONIMVS dicit:)</STAGE> But i kneu&yogh; a mon of &thorn;e Susurron &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Jeronimus dicit eingeschoben, wie 133, 212.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Novi susurronem quendam, quod genus hominum vile est, quasi benevolum nuntiasse quod prae nimio fervore virtutum quibusdam vide|retur insana et cerebrum illius diceret confovendum (engl. directe Rede). Cui illa re|spondit: Theatrum facti sumus mundo et angelis et hominibus: nos stulti propter Christum, sed stultum Dei sapientius est hominibus (71-72 nicht im lat.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is a schrewed nacion (!) &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at seide to hire on &thorn;is maneere:</L>
<L N="55">"&THORN;ou &thorn;i self spillest here,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art so feruent in vertue</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum men seyn &thorn;art waxen newe</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;i witte; &thorn;erfore i red,</L>
<L>Cumforte &thorn;i brayn beter wi&thorn; sum bred</L>
<L N="60">And wi&thorn; sum substancial mete,</L>
<L>&THORN;i wit a&yogh;eyn forte gete,</L>
<L>And take &thorn;e to ano&thorn;ur scole,</L>
<L>For men &thorn;e holde but a fole."</L>
<L>&THORN;enne heo him ful sone onswerd,</L>
<L N="65">As wommon &thorn;at of God was ferd:</L>
<L>"To gode angeles and to men</L>
<L>Spectacle mad forso&thorn;e we ben:</L>
<L>For Cristes loue we ben holden vnwys;</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;enk on &thorn;is:
<PB REF="00000011.tif" N="5"></L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is to God folye</L>
<L>To men hit is wisdam and joye."</L>
<L>&THORN;us holy writ bere&thorn; witnes &mdash;</L>
<L>Good is beo war bo&thorn;e more and les.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN Abbei of men of religioun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post virorum monasterium, quod viris tradiderat gubernandum, plures virgines, (quas ex diversis provinciis congregaverat, tam nobilis quam mediocris et infimi generis), in tres turmas et monasteria divisit, (ita dumtaxat ut opere et cibo separatae psalmis et oratione jungerentur).</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">Heo hedde mad, of gret renoun;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;art aus &thorn;ou art versehmolzen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at, wi&thorn;outen wene,</L>
<L>Heo gederde of maidens clene</L>
<L>&THORN;reo wel feire cumpaignies</L>
<L>And hem sette in feir abbeyes,</L>
<L N="80">God to serue day and niht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made alle &thorn;ing, derknes and liht.</L>
<L>Whon eny of hem bigonne to chide,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Jurgantes inter se sermone lenissimo foederabat,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; softe wordes in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Heo wolde hem ouercome anon</L>
<L N="85">And loueliche make hem aton.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e &yogh;onge in hote blood<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lasci|vientem adolescentularum carnem crebris et duplicatis frangebat jejuniis, malens eas stomachum dolere quam mentem, dicens munditiam corporis atque vestium animae esse immunditiam, et, quod inter saeculi homines vel leve putatur vel nihil, hoc in monasteriis gravissimum esse delictum dicebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bigonne to waxe wylde of mod:</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh &thorn;ei were neuer so nessche,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fastyng heo maad hem chast heor flesche:</L>
<L N="90">For &thorn;e bettre heo chose and toke</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e wombe ra&thorn;ur &thorn;en &thorn;e &thorn;ouht oke.</L>
<L>Heo seide: "clannes of bodi in clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Is ofte &thorn;e soule defoulyng" &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo seide, for &thorn;ei schulde nouht</L>
<L N="95">Haue to muchel in heor &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>Bisynesse of gret aray</L>
<L>For &thorn;e bodi, niht ne day. &mdash;</L>
<L>Deedes &thorn;at men holden no trespas</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world in certeyn cas,</L>
<L N="100">Idon in cloystre heo hem heold</L>
<L>Ful gret trespas, as heo feld.</L>
<L>To hem heo wolde, whon &thorn;ey weore seke,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">hem doppelt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">cumque aliis languentibus large praeberet omnia et esum exhiberet carnium, si quando ipsa aegrotaret, sibi non in|dulgebat, et in eo inaequalis videbatur quod in aliis clementiam, in se duritiam com|mutabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Flesch and fisch let dihten hem eke,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">hem doppelt.</NOTE></L>
<L>But, &thorn;ouh hire self weore seek also,</L>
<L N="105">Heo nolde not ete neuer &thorn;e mo:</L>
<L>To o&thorn;ure heo schewed hire godnes,</L>
<L>And to hire self al hardnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN a somer hit biful,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Referam quod expertus sum:) Mense Julio ferventissimis aestibus incidit in ardorem febris; et post desperationem cum Dei misericordia respi|rasset et medici suaderent ob refectionem corporis vino esse opus tenui et parvo, ne aquam bibens in idropisim verteretur,</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e Mone&thorn; of Jul,</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at al hire bodi, hond and fote,</L>
<L>Was taken wi&thorn; a feuere hote;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde ibrouht hire so lowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e heo mihte bre&thorn; blowe.</L>
<L>But aftur &thorn;at wi&thorn; Godus gras</L>
<L N="115">Of &thorn;at seknes heo mended was.</L>
<L>&THORN;en leches hire counseyled and bad,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordus softe and eke sad,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo schulde vse to drinke wyn,</L>
<L>A luitel &thorn;unne, but not to fyn;</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ei seiden wi&thorn; o vois alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo mihte lihtliche falle</L>
<L>In to a dropesye and synke,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at heo watur dude drinke.</L>
</LG>
<STAGE>(JERONIMVS dicit:)</STAGE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En i bigon priueliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et ego clam beatum episcopum Epiphanium (127 Zus.) rogarem ut eam moneret, immo compelleret vinum bibere,</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">To preye &thorn;e pope ful specialiche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was icalled Ephiphayn &mdash;</L>
<L>Of his presence heo was euer fayn, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde bidde hire and constreyn</L>
<L>Wyn to drinke wi&thorn;outen feyn.
<PB REF="00000012.tif" N="6"></L>
<L N="130">But heo parceyued sone hit,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(ut erat prudens et sollertis ingenii,) statim sensit insidias et, subridens, meum esse quod ille diceret intimavit. (Quid plura?)</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo louh and seide hit was my wit</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pope Epiphayn</L>
<L>So schulde hire bidde and to hire sayn.</L>
<L>Whon i sauh &thorn;at heo so louh,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum beatus <I>pontifex</I> (engl. I, sc. Ierom) post multa horamenta exiisset foras, quaerenti mihi quid egisset, respondit: Tan|tum profeci ut ipsa mihi seni homini paene persuaserit ut vinum non bibam (der engl. Text setzt eine andere Lesart des Orig. voraus?</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">Out of &thorn;e hous I me drouh.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at i was out iwor&thorn;e,</L>
<L>I abod til heo com for&thorn;e;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">heo statt he?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en I him asked hou he hedde isped</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wordus &thorn;at I him red.</L>
<L N="140">He onswerde &thorn;at heo him bad</L>
<L>To bidde an holde mon, &thorn;at wolde be lad,</L>
<L>Wyn forte drinke, for heo wolde non,</L>
<L>For frendes counseyl ne for fon.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at heo serwe schulde make<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In luctu mitis erat et suorum mor|tibus frangebatur maxime liberorum, nam et viri et filiorum dormitione saepe pericli|tata est,</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">For de&thorn;, for hire children sake,</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;erwi&thorn; heo was meke;</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles heo was ofte seke</L>
<L>For hire hosebondes di&yogh;inge</L>
<L>And for hire children departynge,</L>
<L N="150">Out of &thorn;is world whon &thorn;at &thorn;ei went;</L>
<L>But euermore heo tok entent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et cum os stomachumque signaret et matricis dolorem crucis niteretur im|pressione lenire, (superabatur affectu et credulam mentem parentis viscera consterne|bant animoque vincens fragilitate corporis vincebatur &mdash; Der engl. Dichter folgt hier dem wohl verdorbenen oder in seinen Antithesen nicht bequemen Text seiner Vor|lage nicht genau, vgl. V. 156-159).</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; signe of &thorn;e holy crois</L>
<L>Hire mou&thorn; to stoppe and hire vois,</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;ouht also heo wolde refreyne,</L>
<L N="155">On God &thorn;erfore &thorn;at heo nolde pleyne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;auh monkynde, &thorn;at is so frele.</L>
<L>For frendes de&thorn; wol make gret dele,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good bileeue and sad preyere</L>
<L>Hire soule heo cumforted here.</L>
<L N="160">Studefastliche heo set hire wit<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Scripturas sanctas tenebat memoriter, et cum amaret historiam et illam veritatis diceret fundamentum, magis sequebatur intel|ligentiam spiritualem et hoc culmine aedificationis animae protegebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>In muynde to haue holy writ;</L>
<L>Heo louede wel good stori</L>
<L>And clept hit foundement of so&thorn;fastnus, witerly.</L>
<L>Whon heo hit herde, was hire vertue</L>
<L N="165">Parfytliche forte suwe</L>
<L>&THORN;e spirituel vndurstondyng,</L>
<L>To kepe hire soule in good lyuyng.</L>
<L>Heo hedde also &thorn;is vertu<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Loquar et aliud, quod fortasse aemulis videtur incredulum:) Hebraeam linguam, (quam ego ab adolescentia multo labore et sudore ex parte didici et infatigabili meditatione non desero, ne ipsa ab ea deseratur,) discere voluit et consecuta est ita, ut psalmos hebraice caneret et sermonem absque ulla latinae linguae proprietate personaret &mdash; quod quidem usque hodie in sancta filia Eustochia ejus cernimus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo cou&thorn;e speken Ebru,</L>
<L N="170">In so muchel, wi&thorn;outen lesynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wolde bo&thorn;e rede and synge</L>
<L>&THORN;e salmus of &thorn;e sauteer</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen fayle al in feer,</L>
<L>Vppon hire tonge feire hit felle</L>
<L N="175">On Ebru hire tale to telle.</L>
<L>So dude aftur hire hir douhtur dere,</L>
<L>Eustoche, &thorn;at wel cou&thorn;e lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOu who mihte wi&thorn;oute wepyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Hucusque navigavimus pro|speris ventis et crispantia maris aequora labens carina sulcavit; nunc in scopulos incurrit oratio,) quis enim posset siccis oculis Paulam narrare morientem?</NOTE></L>
<L>Telle of &thorn;is wommons departyng</L>
<L N="180">Out of &thorn;is world at Godus wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo disirede euere to folfulle?</L>
<L>In to a wondur gret seknes<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Incidit in gra|vissimam valetudinem, immo quod optabat invenit: ut nos desereret et domino plenius jungeretur. (Quid diu differo et dolorem meum in aliis immorando facio longiorem?)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is wommon fel, wi&thorn;outen les;
<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>&THORN;en hed heo founden hire desire</L>
<L N="185">To wende to &thorn;at lord and sire</L>
<L>&THORN;at made alle &thorn;ing of nouht</L>
<L>And wot bo&thorn;e dede and &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>Whon heo feled wel &thorn;at heo schulde dy&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sentiebat (prudentissima feminarum) adesse mortem (et) frigescente jam parte corporis atque membrorum (solum animae teporem in sacro et sancto pectore palpitare,), et nihilominus, (quasi ad suos pergeret alienosque despiceret,) illos versiculos susurra|bat: domine dilexi decorem domus tuae et locum habitationis gloriae tuae et quam dilecta tabernacula tua domine elegi abjecta esse in domo Dei mei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire limes woxun cold, &thorn;en fayled &thorn;e e&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="190">But &yogh;it such streng&thorn;e as heo had,</L>
<L>&THORN;eos versicles heo seide and bad:</L>
<L>Domine dilexi decorem domus tue</L>
<L>Et locum habitacionis glorie tue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e salm hol and sum</L>
<L N="195">Quam dilecta tabernacula tua domine vir|tutum,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men mihte here hire sey</L>
<L>Elegi abiecta esse in domo dei mei</L>
<L>Magis quam habitare in tabernaculis pec|catorum,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e bre&thorn; was hire binum.</L>
<L N="200">But neuer&thorn;eles heo lay ful stille,</L>
<L>Heo onswerd no mon at his wille.</L>
</LG>
<STAGE>(JERONIMVS dicit:)</STAGE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ich hire asked hou &thorn;at hit was<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cumque a me interrogaretur cur taceret, cur nollet respondere, inclamanti an doleret aliquid, graeco sermone respondit: nihil se habere molestiae, sed omnia quieta et tranquilla perspicere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ur heo soffred ou&yogh;t peine in &thorn;at plas,</L>
<L>And whi heo nolde not onswere</L>
<L N="205">To men &thorn;at calden vppon hire &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>On Gru heo onswerde wi&thorn; good fyaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at God hir hedde isent &thorn;at chaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo feled no maner greef,</L>
<L>But al was pes: &thorn;at was hire leef.</L>
<L N="210">Aftur &thorn;at made heo no res,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post hoc obmutuit et clausis oculis, (quasi humana despiceret, 213 Zus.) usque ad expirationem animae eosdem repetebat versiculos, vix ut aure apposita quod dicebat audire possemus.</NOTE></L>
<L>But sweteliche heold hire pes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en hire e&yogh;en wenten to geder,</L>
<L>And feir and clene as swannes fe&thorn;er,</L>
<L>But euer &thorn;e tonge gon to sey</L>
<L N="215">Elegi abiecta esse in domo dei mei,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men mihte vnne&thorn;e ihere,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e versus tofore al in fere,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;e gost heo hedde i&yogh;iue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; God euermore to liue.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;en &thorn;e monkes of &thorn;at hous<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Tota ad funus ejus Palaestinarum ur|bium turba convenit.) Quem enim monachorum latentium in eremo cellula sua tenuit, quam virginum cubiculorum tenuerunt secreta (anders im engl.), sacrile|gium putabat qui non tali feminae ultimum reddidisset officium, donec supter eccle|siam (et juxta specum domini) conderetur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo hedde mad so glorious,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e maydens also</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo to gedere hedde gedered &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Token hir bodi wi&thorn; dreri mood</L>
<L N="225">And to &thorn;e place &thorn;er heor chirche stod</L>
<L>Ful deuoutliche &thorn;ei hit bare,</L>
<L>And buried hit riht sone &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Faste bi vndur &thorn;e churche</L>
<L>&THORN;at god for hire wondres do&thorn; worche.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;at st. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">&THORN;en Eustoche, hir douhtur, leope<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Venerabilis filia ejus virgo Eustochium (quasi ablactata super matrem suam abstrahi a parente non poterat, deosculari oculos, haerere vultui, totum corpus amplexari) et se cum matre velle sepelire.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hire sepulcre, forte wepe;</L>
<L>So gret deol heo made, parde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire iburied heo wolde haue be.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Testis est Jesus nec unum quidem nummum ab ea filiae derelictum, sed magis tribuens egenis (die engl. Prosa&uuml;bertragung des Ms. Egert. 876 hat hier: she lefte neuer a peny to her doughter but <I>money of straungers</I>) et, quod his difficilius est, fratrum et so|rorum immensam multitudinem, quam et sustentare arduum est et abjicere impium est. (V. 242-245 Zus.)</NOTE></L>
<L>God is witnesse, i dar wel say,</L>
<L N="235">Hir modur wi&thorn; hire lafte no money,</L>
<L>But ra&thorn;ur in o&thorn;ur mennes dette;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was hard to hem &thorn;at wer sette</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh hire in religiun,</L>
<L>Monkes and maidens of deuociun;
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="8"></L>
<L N="240">&THORN;enne was hard hem for&thorn; to fynde,</L>
<L>And worse was (ha) left al bihynde.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is storie, hol and sum,</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; to ou &thorn;us seint Jerom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kneuh hire lyf and hire ende.</L>
<L N="245">&THORN;erfore haue&thorn; hit wel in mynde!</L>
<L>Fare wel, Paula, and prey for vs<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vale o Paula et cultoris tui ultimam senectutem orationibus juva.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Godus sone, &thorn;at is Jhesus!<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. lef mit klein &uuml;berschr. t; zu lesen ist: (to) leve oder ha left.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="life">
<HEAD>2. S. Ambrosius.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">2) Ueberschrift im Ms.: de nomine Ambrosii. Das lat. Original s. Leg. Aur. cap. 57 de s. Ambrosio. In der altengl. Prosa&uuml;bers. (Ms. Egert. 876) fehlt die Deutung des Namens, die aber in Caxton's Ausg. wieder aufgenommen ist.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HErkene&thorn;, sires! for my purpose</L>
<L>Is ou to telle of seint Ambrose.</L>
<L>But furst his name i wol expoune:</L>
<L>Lustne&thorn; wi&thorn; good deuocioune!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">V. 1-4 Einl. des Dich|ters.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">Ambra is a spicerye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ff. vgl. L. A.: Ambrosius dicitur de ambra, quae est species valde redolens et pretiosa: iste enim ecclesiae valde pretiosus exstitit et in dictis et in factis suis valde redoluit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of gret pris, smelle&thorn; swotelye:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof is called &thorn;is name Ambrose:</L>
<L>For riht as hit sauere&thorn; in monnes nose</L>
<L>Riht so dude he in word and dede,</L>
<L N="10">Monnes soule to gete gret mede;</L>
<L>And precious was to holy churche:</L>
<L>Doctur he was and tauhte to worche</L>
<L>Cristene men heore God to plese,</L>
<L>In charite to lyue and pese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="15">O&THORN;er elles &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t sei &thorn;at Ambros<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vel dicitur Ambr. ab ambra et syos, quod est Deus, quasi ambra Dei: Deus enim per eum quasi per ambram ubique redolet; fuit enim et est bonus odor Christi in omni loco.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is seid of ambra and syos:</L>
<L>Syos is to seyn "God" riht,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Good st. God.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ambrum good sauour pliht.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne, for he wi&thorn; good preching</L>
<L N="20">Made men knowe God ouer alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>God is good sauur to vche mon</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his techinge, &thorn;at good con.</L>
<L>For Ambros is and also was</L>
<L>Good Cristes sauour in eueri plas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">O&THORN;er &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t wel diuise<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vel dicitur ab ambor (engl. ambrum), quod est pater luminis, et sior (engl. sion), quod est parvulus: quia pater in multorum filiorum spi|rituali generatione, luminosus in sacrae scripturae expositione et parvulus in sua humili conversatione.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e nome of Ambros in &thorn;is wyse:</L>
<L>Ambrum is to seye fadur of liht,</L>
<L>And syon a luytel child ful riht.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Ambros him seluen</L>
<L N="30">Is fadur of moni gostliche children,</L>
<L>He was lihtful in expounyng</L>
<L>Holy writ, wi&thorn;outen lesyng,</L>
<L>In conuersaciun he was eke</L>
<L>Riht as a chyld wondurliche meke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="35">O&THORN;ur &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t expoune hit, and not varie,</L>
<L>As sei&thorn; &thorn;e bok, iclept Glosarie:</L>
<L>Ambrum is heuenlich smel of sauour:</L>
<L>So sauerede he in halle and bour</L>
<L>In gode fame and contemplaciun,</L>
<L N="40">He hedde gret deuociun.</L>
<L>Celestis Ambrosia, wi&thorn;outen lete,</L>
<L>Is vndurstonden Angles mete:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to seyn &thorn;at inward siht</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ambrose hedde in God Almiht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="45">&THORN;Is word also Ambrosium</L>
<L>Is to seyn al and sum</L>
<L>An heuenliche honycombe:
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde seint Ambrose in his wombe</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh swetnesse of exposicioun</L>
<L N="50">Of holy writ in religioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">35-50 Vel sicut dicitur in Glossario: ambrosia, esca angelorum, ambrosium coeleste mellis favum: fuit enim coelestis odor per odoriferam fa|mam, sapor per contemplationem intimam, coeleste mellis favum per dulcem scri|pturarum expositionem, esca angelica per gloriosam fruitionem. (Die Erkl&auml;rung V. 37 nicht im lat., vgl. V. 23; sie scheint vom englischen Dichter selbst hinzugef&uuml;gt zu sein). &mdash; (51-54 Zusatz.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Now haue I expouned his name,</L>
<L>And hou he sauered in gode fame.</L>
<L>Herkne&thorn; nou, hosbonde and wyf,</L>
<L>And i schal tellen ou of his lyf,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ejus vitam scripsit Paulinus Nolanus episcopus ad Augustinum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Riht as a clerk, was clept Paulin,</L>
<L>Wrot hit to seint Austyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AMbrose of Rome was prefecte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ambrosius, filius Ambrosii praefecti Romae, cum in cunabulis in atrio praetorii esset positus et dormiret, examen apum subito veniens faciem ejus et os ita complevit, ut quasi in alveolum suum intrarent pariter et exirent.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of his wyf wi&thorn;outen lette</L>
<L>He gat a child, was clept Ambrose,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at mon was aftur of gret lose.</L>
<L>Hit bifel vppon a day,</L>
<L>Whil he was &yogh;ong, in cradel he lay.</L>
<L>And, forte stille him of his wepe,</L>
<L>Rokked he was and fel on slepe;</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;er he lay wi&thorn; open mou&thorn;.</L>
<L>&THORN;en ful a cas wondur selcou&thorn;:</L>
<L>For sodeynliche a cumpaygnye</L>
<L>Of beon &thorn;er come, swi&thorn;e monie,</L>
<L>His mou&thorn; &thorn;ei fulden and his face &mdash;</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at men se&yogh;en wel in &thorn;at place, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei fullen in and out blyue</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei&yogh; his mou&thorn; hedde ben heor hyue.</L>
<L>And afturward &thorn;ei toke &thorn;e fliht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae postea evolan|tes in tantam aeris altitudinem sublevatae sunt, ut humanis oculis minime vide|rentur.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e eir so fer on hiht</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at no mon mihte on eor&thorn;e wi&thorn; e&yogh;e</L>
<L>Seo &thorn;is ben whodur &thorn;ei dude fli&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Whon his fadur &thorn;is wondur hedde seyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo peracto territus pater ait: Si vixerit infantulus iste, aliquid magni erit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He seide, as mon &thorn;at was riht fayn:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is child, i wot, so mot i &thorn;eo,</L>
<L N="80">Sum gret mon schal he beo."</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;is child com to fourtene &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Postea cum adolevisset et videret matrem et sororem, sacram vir|ginem, manus sacerdotibus osculari, ipse ludens sorori dextram offerebat, asse|rens et sibi id ab ea fieri opportere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of age, he wente ofte tyme in fere</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; modur and sustur to &thorn;e churche,</L>
<L>Goode dedes forte worche.</L>
<L N="85">He tok good hede to vndurstonde</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;ei cussed &thorn;e prestes honde.</L>
<L>Whon he com hom, he wolde, iwis,</L>
<L>Profre his sustur his hond to cus,</L>
<L>And he wolde sei on his pleying</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;at moste heo do nedelyng.</L>
<L>For he was &yogh;ong, non hede heo tok,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Illa vero, ut adolescentem et nescientem quid diceret, respuebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo wolde him bidde go to his bok.</L>
<L>Whon he was lettred and vndurstod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Romae igitur litteris eruditus, cum causas prae|torii splendide peroraret,</NOTE></L>
<L>Monye causes, bi &thorn;e rod!</L>
<L N="95">In &thorn;e noble cite of Rome</L>
<L>Sikerliche he vndurnome,</L>
<L>Rihtfuliche he hedde in meude<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. he st. hem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lawefuliche brouhte hem to ende.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e emperour parceyued &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a Valentiniano imperatore ad regendam Liguriam Emiliamque provinciam directus est.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">To him he sende anon iwis,</L>
<L>To gouerne &thorn;e prouinces of Lygurie</L>
<L>And also of Emylye.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he com to Melan,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cumque Mediolanum venisset et ibi|dem episcopus tunc deesset, convenit populus, ut sibi de episcopo provideret.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er of &thorn;e bisschop ded was &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;e peple gedrede euerichon</L>
<L>To chese to bisschop sum god mon.</L>
<L>But heretykes dwelled hem amon(g),<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed cum inter Arianos et catholicos de eligendo episcopo seditio non modica oriretur,</NOTE></L>
<L>Weren called Arrianus, of wit ful strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sumwhat weren out of bileeue.</L>
<L N="110">Gode fei&thorn;ful men and &thorn;ei &thorn;enne streue</L>
<L>Who schulde beo bisschop and hed;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei neore not alle in on red,
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>&THORN;er ros a gret sediciun</L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;at ilke elecciun.</L>
<L N="115">Ambrose &thorn;enne wi&thorn; gret res<NOTE PLACE="foot2">illuc Ambr. causa sedandae seditionis perrexit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tok &thorn;ider &thorn;e wey, to make al pes.</L>
<L>As sone as he &thorn;enne comen was</L>
<L>&THORN;ider as &thorn;e pepul was gedred in plas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et statim vox infantis insonuit, dicens Ambrosium episcopum (engl. directe Rede),</NOTE></L>
<L>A vois anon of an innocent</L>
<L N="120">Was herd of alle, verement!:</L>
<L>"I put &yogh;ou alle in sad hope,</L>
<L>Ambrose schal ben oure bisschope."</L>
<L>&THORN;ei sented alle to &thorn;at vois,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sented = assented.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">cujus voci omnes unanimiter consenserunt, Ambrosium episcopum acclamantes (engl. dir.).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ambrose", &thorn;ei crieden wi&thorn; gret noys,</L>
<L N="125">"To vr bisschop we wol haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he assente, onliche we craue".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he &thorn;us vndurstod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo ille cognito, ut eos a se terroribus removeret, ecclesiam exiens (129 ist Ausf&uuml;llsel) tribu|nal conscendit et contra consuetudinem suam tormenta personis adhiberi jussit (135-140 erkl&auml;r. Zusatz).</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fere he wolde ha torned heore mod,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it he dude ano&thorn;ur &thorn;ing:</L>
<L N="130">To &thorn;e juges seete he wente hi&yogh;ing</L>
<L>And a&yogh;eynes his olde wone</L>
<L>Sum men tofore him dude he come,</L>
<L>Als he sat for juggement,</L>
<L>And hem comaunded to turment&mdash;</L>
<L N="135">For &thorn;e pepul schulde wel se</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde ben ful of cruwelte.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holy mon caste &thorn;at,</L>
<L>For he disired non such stat,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ei schulde ha lost heor hope</L>
<L N="140">Him haue had to heore bisschope.&mdash;</L>
<L>But &thorn;e peple for al his gyse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum faceret, populus nihilominus acclamabat: Pecca|tum tuum super nos.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cried on him vppon &thorn;is wyse:</L>
<L>"Let beo &thorn;i fare, mak hit not &thorn;us!</L>
<L>&THORN;i sunne &thorn;er of falle hit on vs."</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;en was he stourbled in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and e&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc ille turbatus domum rediit et philosophiam profi|teri voluit. Quod ut ne faceret, revocatus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wente him hamward in gret hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>He wolde to philosophye him (ha) pro|fessed.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">im Ms. fehlt ha oder haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>But he was called a&yogh;eyn and cessed.</L>
<L>And for he nolde bisschop haue ben,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Publicas mulieres publice ad se ingredi fecit, ut, his visis, ab ejus electione populum revocaret.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">He made &thorn;e moste comun wommen</L>
<L>Openliche come to his in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bisschopriche for he nolde wyn,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;au&yogh; he dude not bote good,</L>
<L>He wolde haue mad &thorn;e peple wood,</L>
<L N="155">Ano&thorn;ur mon forte haue chose</L>
<L>And of him laft heore purpose.</L>
<L>&THORN;e peple euere and ay in on<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed cum nec sic proficeret, sed semper populum peccatum suum super nos acclamare videret,</NOTE></L>
<L>On him &thorn;ei criede euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei wolde bere al &thorn;e synne,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at bisschophede so he wolde winne.</L>
<L>He sau&yogh; &thorn;at he &thorn;us miht not spede:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fugam media nocte concepit; cumque Ticinum se pergere putaret, mane ad portam civitatis Mediolanensis, quae Romana dicitur, invenitur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e nexte niht wi&thorn;oute nede</L>
<L>He stal awey and wolde haue gon</L>
<L>To &thorn;e toun of Ticinun anon.</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;iderward, &thorn;e so&thorn;e to say,</L>
<L>He wende he hedde holden &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>Whon hit was day, he loked aboute:</L>
<L>&THORN;en sau&yogh; he wher he stod &thorn;er oute:</L>
<L>At on of &thorn;e &yogh;atus of Melan,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at is called &thorn;e &yogh;ate Roman.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui inventus cum custodiretur a populo, missa relatio est ad clementissimum imperatorem Valentinianum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;enne men sone him fonde</L>
<L>At &thorn;e &yogh;ate, &thorn;er he dude stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei him kepte and word sent</L>
<L>To &thorn;e emperour Valentinian, verrement,</L>
<L N="175">Hou &thorn;ei to bisschop him hedde ichose,</L>
<L>Preyeden him assente to heor purpose.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour &thorn;enne ful joyful was<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui summo gaudio accepit, quod judices a se directi ad sacerdotium peterentur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at him schulde falle so feir a caas</L>
<L>&THORN;at a juge, &thorn;at he hedde isent
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="11"></L>
<L N="180">To kepe his lawes wi&thorn; good entent,</L>
<L>Was ichose so fei&thorn;fuliche</L>
<L>A bisschop to beo verreyliche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prefecte, &thorn;at corteis was of wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Laetabatur enim probus praefectus, quod verbum suum fuerat in eo adimple|tum; dixerat enim, cum proficiscenti mandata donaret: vade, age, non ut judex, sed ut episcopus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was glad &thorn;at he &thorn;at schulde folfille;</L>
<L N="185">For, whon Ambrose was to Melan sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prefecte seide wi&thorn; good talent:</L>
<L>"Go for&thorn; now, as no domusmon,</L>
<L>But as bisschop ouer mony on."</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at &thorn;eos ti&thorn;inges &thorn;us hynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Pendente relatione, iterum absconditur, sed inventus, cum ad|huc esset catechumenus, baptizatur et VIII die in episcopalem cathedram sublima|tur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">Ambrose him hudde, wi&thorn;oute lesynge;</L>
<L>But he was founden amongus hem.</L>
<L>He leued wel, but him lakked baptem:</L>
<L>&THORN;en was he cristened in watur cler</L>
<L>And &thorn;e eihte&thorn;e day set in bisschops chayer.</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;enne at &thorn;e four &yogh;eres ende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem post annos IV Romam ivisset et soror sua, sacra virgo, ejus dex|tram oscularetur, sibi ridens ait: Ecce, ut dicebam tibi, sacerdotis manum oscularis.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Rome forso&thorn;e gan he wende.</L>
<L>His sustur &thorn;at maiden was, an holy wom|mon,</L>
<L>His riht hond heo custe anon.</L>
<L>He smyled and seide: "suster, hit is wust,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;ou hast cussed a prestes fust;</L>
<L>I seide &thorn;e sum tyme hit moste so be,</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ou leuedest not me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel afturward sikerliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem in quandam civitatem pro quodam episcopo ordinando ivisset et ejus electioni Justina imperatrix et alii haeretici contradicerent, volentes ut aliquis de sua secta ordinaretur,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in a cite voyded a bisschopriche.</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;ider he went al in certeyne,</L>
<L>A bisschop &thorn;er forte ordeyne.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;er on ichosen was,</L>
<L>&THORN;en nolden heo assente to &thorn;at caas,</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperice, was clept Justine,</L>
<L N="210">Ne o&thorn;ur heretykes monye and fyne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei wolden &thorn;at &thorn;e eleccioun</L>
<L>Hed fallen vppon on of here sori reli|gioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Of secte of &thorn;e arian st. of &thorn;e secte of arian wie 213. 276. 286.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en a maiden of secte of &thorn;e Arian<NOTE PLACE="foot2">una de Arianorum virginibus impudentior caeteris (tribunal con|scendit et) beatum Ambrosium per vestimentum apprehendit, volens ipsum ad partem mulierum trahere, ut ab iis caesus de ecclesia cum injuria pelleretur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hedde &thorn;ou&yogh;t haue wrou&yogh;t Ambroses ban;</L>
<L N="215">To seint Ambrose anon heo stert</L>
<L>And tok him smartly bi &thorn;e skert,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e wymmen heo wolde him haue drawe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei him wolde ha smite ful fawe,</L>
<L>Him boren an honde &thorn;en vuel talent</L>
<L N="220">And, bi &thorn;e lawe! &thorn;enne him haue schent</L>
<L>And from his churche wrongfuly</L>
<L>Haue put him out wi&thorn; vileny.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne to hire he seide corteisly:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui Ambr. ait: Etsi ego indignus tanto sacerdotio, tibi tamen non convenit in qualemcunque sacerdotem manus injicere: unde timere debuisti judicium Dei, ne tibi aliquid con tingat.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Prest ich am, &thorn;au&yogh; i beo not wor&thorn;i.</L>
<L N="225">Forso&thorn;e, &thorn;ou art vuele itauht,</L>
<L>To set hond on prest bi seme&thorn; &thorn;e nauht.</L>
<L>Godus dom &thorn;ou scholdest haue in drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nost what may falle to &thorn;i mede."</L>
<L>Hit byfel as he seid:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod dictum exitus confirmavit: nam die alio mortuam ad sepulcrum usque deduxit, gratiam pro contumelia rependens; quod factum omnes perterruit:</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">Heo was on morwen ded on bere ileyd.</L>
<L>Touward hire graue of his godnesse</L>
<L>&THORN;en he hire ladde for al hire schrewed|nesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;en alle men &thorn;at &thorn;is wondur herd</L>
<L>Of God and him woxun aferd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="235">AFtur &thorn;at, in certeyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post hoc Mediolanum reversus, innumeras insidias a Justina imperatrice pertulit, muneribus et honoribus adversus eum populum excitante.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Melan he tornde a&yogh;ein.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Justine, &thorn;at emperice,
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>Of maners wox bo&thorn;e wylde and nice,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e peple heo worschiped moni on</L>
<L N="240">And &yogh;iftus &yogh;af to vche mon,</L>
<L>Hem to sture a&yogh;ein Ambrose&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was iwis an vuel purpose.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weoren aboute, of vuel wil<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo multi eum in exsilium pellere niterentur,</NOTE></L>
<L>To haue put him in exil.</L>
<L N="245">A schrewe &thorn;er was among o&thorn;ur&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">unus eorum caeteris infelicior in tantum furorem excitatus est, ut juxta ecclesiam domum sibi locaret ac in ea quadrigam paratam haberet, quo procurante Justina facilius raptum ad exsilium deportaret.</NOTE></L>
<L>I trouwe he was &thorn;e deueles bro&thorn;ur&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so wod in his doyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi his chirche he made his dwellyng</L>
<L>And in his hous he hedde redye</L>
<L N="250">A cart, seint Ambrose to carie</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e lond, fox of fyl,</L>
<L>Whon he weore dampned to exil,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no bodi wox so bolde</L>
<L>In londe him aftur forte holde;</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;is was &thorn;e cast of Justine,</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperice, a schrewe ful fyne.</L>
<L>But bi Godus ordinaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed Dei judicio ipso die quo eum rapere arbitrabatur, in eadem quadriga de ea|dem domo in exsilium pulsus est. (Cui tamen Ambr. reddens bona pro malis, sumptus et necessaria ministravit.)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;enne bifel &thorn;is ilke chaunce:</L>
<L>He &thorn;at hedde arayed &thorn;e cart</L>
<L N="260">He was exiled swi&thorn;e smart</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;at ilke same day</L>
<L>&THORN;at wende to ha lad Ambrose away,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e same cart he was caried</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at lond, and foule ihari&yogh;ed.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">wende = wende he, wie 714 wolde, 961 knewe, Theod. 314 leued.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">SEint Ambrose was &thorn;e furste man<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cantus et officium in ecclesia Mediolanensi cele|brari instituit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e churche of Melan</L>
<L>Ordeyned offyces and songe</L>
<L>And melodye of vois and tonge.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite of Melan<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Erant et tunc temporis Mediolani multi a daemonibus obsessi, qui se torqueri ab Ambrosio magnis vocibus clamabant;</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">Was &thorn;at tyme moni a man</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel acumbred were</L>
<L>And weren ibrouht in muchel fere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel made hem crie in heore turment</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ambrose hedde hem ischent.</L>
<L N="275">But Justine, &thorn;at wikked womman,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Justina autem et multi Arianorum, cum simul habitarent, dicebant Ambrosium pecunia homines comparare qui se ab immundis spiritibus vexari mentirentur et ab Ambrosio dicerent se torqueri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; heretykes of &thorn;e secte of Arrian,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to gedere token heore dwellyng,</L>
<L>On Ambrose maden a lesyng:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei seiden hit was so&thorn; verrey</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at Ambrose wi&thorn; his money</L>
<L>Hedde hured men to &thorn;at entent,</L>
<L>To sei&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel hem dude turment,</L>
<L>And eke of Ambrose verreyliche</L>
<L>&THORN;is lesyng &thorn;ei maden falsliche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">HIt bifel sodeynliche &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc subito unus ex illis Arianis qui adstabant, arreptus a daemonio in medium prosiluit atque clamare coepit: Utinam sic torqueantur ut torqueor, qui non credunt Ambrosio!</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at on of &thorn;e secte of Arrian</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel sone was take;</L>
<L>For wod he grenned and gon to quake,</L>
<L>He fel adoun among hem alle</L>
<L N="290">And gon to crye and to calle:</L>
<L>"I wolde &thorn;at alle &thorn;at nou ne purpose,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">ms. non statt nou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at nou ne byleeue on Ambrose,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">ms. non statt nou.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei ne weore turmented als am I &mdash;</L>
<L>I suffre serwe, sikerly!"</L>
<L N="295">Confuys &thorn;enne was &thorn;at cumpaygnye;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At illi confusi in piscinam demersum hominem necaverunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ei him slowen for his crye</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne wi&thorn; heore oune honde</L>
<L>&THORN;ey him dreynte in a ponde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A maister heretyk &thorn;er was on,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam haereticus, acerrimus disputator et durus et inconvertibilis ad fidem, cum audiret Ambrosium praedicantem, vidit angelum ad aures ejus loquentem verba quae populo praedicabat.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">An hard mon of conuercion</L>
<L>And a scharp mon of wit
<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>To plede a&yogh;eynes holy writ.</L>
<L>Vppon a day he com to here</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose preche, &thorn;e peple to lere,</L>
<L N="305">And he sauh at Ambroses ere</L>
<L>An angel speke &thorn;e wordus &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e peple he dude preche &mdash;</L>
<L>Wel forte lyue he dude teche.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at siht he was ful feyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo viso fidem quam persequebatur coepit defen|dere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="310">To cristene fei&thorn; he tornde a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>And defended strongliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde dispysed falsliche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A coniuror &thorn;er was also<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam aruspex daemones advocabat et ipsos ad nocendum Am|brosio transmittebat, sed (reversi daemones renuntiabant, quod) non solum ad ipsum sed nec etiam ad fores domus suae appropinquare valebant, (quoniam ignis insupera|bilis omne illud aedificium communiret, ut etiam longe positi urerentur.)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;te to Ambrose worche wo;</L>
<L N="315">He calde vp fendes and for&thorn; hem sende,</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose forte schende.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei nedde pouwer, wi&thorn; no gin,</L>
<L>To neihe &thorn;e hous &thorn;at he was in,</L>
<L>Ne nou&thorn;ur nuy&yogh;e his persone &mdash;</L>
<L N="320">God &yogh;af him grace, &thorn;at sit in trone.</L>
<L>Hit bifel bi &thorn;at coniurour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Prae|dictus vero aruspex cum a judice propter quaedam maleficia torqueretur, clamabat amplius ab Ambrosio se torqueri.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he was take and put in tour.</L>
<L>Whon he was turmented for his misdede,</L>
<L>He seide seint Ambrose him put in drede;</L>
<L N="325">On seint Ambrose he cried out &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wondred on him &thorn;at stoden about.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was a mon in Melan<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quendam daemoniacum Mediolanum in|gredientem daemon dimisit, egredientem invasit; interrogatus de hoc daemon ait Am|brosium se timere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend was fallen on.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e citee whon he schulde go,</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e deuel wolde him fleo fro;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at he schulde outward wende,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at mon he wolde lende.</L>
<L>He was asked hou &thorn;at was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend onswered in &thorn;at cas</L>
<L N="335">And seide: awei from him he fledde,</L>
<L>For seint Ambrose sore he dredde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANo&thorn;ur mon bi nihtes tale<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Alius quidam nocte ejus cubiculum adiit, ut gladio ipsum necaret, prece ac pretio a Justina inductus; sed cum dextra gladium elevasset, ut ipsum percuteret, continuo aruit manus ejus. (Die bei Gr&auml;sse l. c. hier folgende Erz&auml;hlung von der Verweisung des Kaisers aus der Kirche fehlt im engl. wie auch in der Edit. princ.; sie folgt sp&auml;ter ausf&uuml;hrlich.)</NOTE></L>
<L>In to seint Ambroses chaumbre stale:</L>
<L>Justyne, &thorn;at wikked emperice,</L>
<L N="340">Him hedde i huired to beo so nice,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy mon forte sle</L>
<L>And afturward awey to fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon wi&thorn; his riht hond</L>
<L>His swerd out drouh, as brennyng brond,</L>
<L N="345">Forte haue smiten &thorn;is holy mon;</L>
<L>But his arm druyed vp anon,</L>
<L>He ne mihte on none wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; aftur do no seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANo&thorn;ur mon &thorn;e fend hedde take,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam a daemonio arreptus clamare coepit ab Ambrosio se torqueri. Cui Ambr.: Obmutesce, diabole, quia non te torquet Ambrosius sed tua invidia, quia illuc homines adscendere conspicis unde tu turpiter corruisti, nam Ambrosius nescit inflari. At ille statim obmutuit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">And turmented him wi&thorn; muchel wrake</L>
<L>And maad him crie in his wodnes:</L>
<L>"Ambrose me pyne&thorn; wi&thorn; wikkednes."</L>
<L>Ambrose seide: "pes, &thorn;ou foule fende!</L>
<L>Ambrose &thorn;e do&thorn; no &thorn;ing schende,</L>
<L N="355">But &thorn;yn envye, for &thorn;at &thorn;ou sest</L>
<L>Of cristen men, bo&thorn;e lest and mest,</L>
<L>Steyh&yogh;e vpward from whennes &thorn;ou fil;</L>
<L>Ambrose nis not inflat of wil."</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &thorn;enne ouercome wes</L>
<L N="360">And of his cri&yogh;ing heold his pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel vppon a day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice cum beatus Ambr. per civitatem pergeret, quidam casu lapsus est et in terra prostratus jaciebat: quod videns alter ridere coepit. Cui A.: Et tu, qui stas, vide ne cadas. Quo dicto statim lapsum doluit suum qui riserat alienum.</NOTE></L>
<L>As Ambrose wente bi &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>A mon slod a&yogh;eynes his wil,</L>
<L>Adoun to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e sone he fyl.</L>
<L N="365">Ano&thorn;ur mon, &thorn;at &thorn;er was,
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>Stod and louh at &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose &thorn;enne wi&thorn; deuocion</L>
<L>Seide: "&thorn;ou &thorn;at stondest, fal nou&yogh;t adoun!"</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e seint Ambrose &thorn;us hed seid,</L>
<L N="370">&THORN;e mon fel doun, on eor&thorn;e was leid,</L>
<L>And sori was for his oune fallyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e to&thorn;ur monnes fal made lauh|wyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Er was also &thorn;at tyme a mon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam etiam vice A. ad palatium Macedonii, magistri officiorum, ut pro quodam in|tercederet, venit; sed cum fores clausas invenisset nec intrandi copiam habere po|tuisset, ait: Et tu quidem venies ad ecclesiam et non clausis januis ingredi, sed apertis januis non valebis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was icalled Macedon,</L>
<L N="375">He was chef mayster of offyces,</L>
<L>Hem to rule and punissche vices.</L>
<L>Ambrose toward him went vppon a day,</L>
<L>For a pore mon him to pray;</L>
<L>But he his &yogh;ate fond ischut,</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;at ingoinge miht he non get.</L>
<L>&THORN;er of seint Ambrose was sumwhat irke</L>
<L>And seide to him: "&thorn;ou schalt come to kirke,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;ouh &thorn;e dore al open stonde,</L>
<L>In &thorn;er at schalt &thorn;ou not fonde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">HIt bifel sone afturward<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Elapso aliquo tempore metuens inimicos Macedonius ad ec|clesiam fugit et patentibus januis aditum reperire non potuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Macedon hedde enemys hard;</L>
<L>To chirche needes fleo moste he &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dore was open, he miht not in go.</L>
<L>&THORN;en was fallen &thorn;e purpose</L>
<L N="390">Of &thorn;e holy mon seint Ambrose.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was of so gret abstinence,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fuit etiam tantae abstinentiae, quod quotidie nisi in sabbato et die dominico et festis praecipuis jejunabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>For loue of god and reuerence,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fasted alway,</L>
<L>Saue saturday and sonday</L>
<L N="395">And o&thorn;ur principal festes,</L>
<L>He spared not for no gestes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was of so gret largesse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae etiam largitatis erat, quod omnia quae habere poterat ecclesiis et pauperibus, nil sibi retinens, tribuebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he deled al his richesse</L>
<L>To holichirche and to pore men;</L>
<L N="400">Nou&yogh;t to him self wolde he kepe &thorn;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was of so gret compassion<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae compassionis, ut, cum aliquis lapsum suum sibi confitebatur, sic amarissime flebat, quod illum similiter flere compellebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde for deuocion,</L>
<L>Whon eny mon dude to him knoweleche<NOTE PLACE="foot1">dude wohl zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>His sunne wolde and his wreche,</L>
<L N="405">He wolde wepe so bitterly</L>
<L>And &thorn;er of beo so sory,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e mon &thorn;at him so hedde ischriue</L>
<L>Schuld him repente sore to liue;</L>
<L>For his sunnes he wolde constreyne</L>
<L N="410">A mon to wepe and suffre peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was so ful of mekenesse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae humilitatis et laboris, ut libros quos dictabat propria manu scribebat, nisi cum infirmitate corporis gravaretur.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of trauayl: bo&thorn;e more and lasse</L>
<L>&THORN;e bokes &thorn;at he made, God hit wot,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his oune hondes he wrot,</L>
<L N="415">But he were greued in his bodi</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seknes o&thorn;ur wi&thorn; maladi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was so ful of pite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae autem pietatis et dul|cedinis, ut, cum alicujus sancti sacerdotis vel episcopi sibi obitus nuntiaretur, sic ama|rissime flebat, ut vix consolari valeret.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of swetnesse, parde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, whon men tolden him ti&thorn;ing</L>
<L N="420">Of bisschopes o&thorn;ur prestes di&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>He wolde so wepe and gret deol make,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no cumfort wolde he for&thorn; take.</L>
<L>Whon men made him &thorn;en askyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem interrogaretur cur viros sanctos, qui ad gloriam proficiscebantur, sic fleret, ajebat: Ne putetis me flere quod recesse|rint, sed quia me praecesserunt et quia difficile invenitur qui tam dignus ejus officii habeatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at he made such serwyng
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="15"></L>
<L N="425">And wepte for holy men and murie</L>
<L>&THORN;at passed weren vp to glorie,</L>
<L>He wolde onswere: "ne leeue &yogh;e nouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at i &thorn;us wepe and falle in &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world for &thorn;ei ben gon</L>
<L N="430">To him &thorn;at mad vs euerichon,</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ei ben gon tofore me,</L>
<L>And for hit is hard, so mot i &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Forte fynden aftur such a mon</L>
<L>&THORN;at such an offys so wel do con."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="435">HE was of so good constaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae etiam constantiae et fortitudinis, quod imperatoris vel principum vitia non palpabat sed eos voce libera constantissime arguebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>And strong in spiryt in eueri chaunce:</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh emperour or kyng in dede were nice,</L>
<L>He nolde not suwe hem in no vice,</L>
<L>But he wolde in certeyne</L>
<L N="440">Wi&thorn; opene vois him wel repreyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Er was a mon &thorn;at wikkedliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum quidam vir quoddam flagitium perpetrasset et coram eo adductus fuisset, dixit A.: Oportet illum tradi Sathanae in interitum carnis, ne talia deinceps audeat perpetrare. Quem eodem momento, cum adhuc sermo esset, more ejus immundus spiritus discer|pere coepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>An vuel dede hedde don openliche.</L>
<L>Tofore Ambrose whon men him brouht,</L>
<L>He seide, as hit was in his &thorn;ouht:</L>
<L N="445">"Hit bihoue&thorn;, seid Ambrose, &thorn;at &thorn;is man</L>
<L>Beo bitaken to Sathan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whe&thorn;er he beo hard o&thorn;ur nessche</L>
<L>Him to chastise in his flessche."</L>
<L>&THORN;at word vnne&thorn;e Ambrose hadde seid,</L>
<L N="450">&THORN;at &thorn;e mon al wod abreyd,</L>
<L>A wikkede spirit &thorn;e bodi torment,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e soule schulde not be schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme bi godus dome<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice, ut ajunt, cum beatus A. Romam pergeret et in quadam villa Tusciae (engl. Trissye) apud quendam hominem nimium locupletem hospitatus fuisset, illum hominem super statu suo sollicite requisivit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Ambrose tok &thorn;e wei to Rome,</L>
<L N="455">And in a toun, &thorn;at hette Trissye,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. trissye st. Tuscie.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was herborwede, sikerlye,</L>
<L>At a riche monnes hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;er he in dwelled and his spous.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose apposed &thorn;is man</L>
<L N="460">Of his stat hou hit stod &thorn;an.</L>
<L>He seide: "Sire, so mot i &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui ille respondit: Status meus, domine, semper felix exstitit et gloriosus; ecce enim divitiis infinitis abundo, servos et famulos quam plures habeo et omnia semper ad vota habui nec unquam mihi aliquid adversum accidit vel quod contristaret evenit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ich am in gret prosperite,</L>
<L>Mi self, mi wyf and min hous,</L>
<L>We ben wondur glorious:</L>
<L N="465">Ich haue plente of richesse,</L>
<L>Men and wymmen, more and lesse,</L>
<L>Me to serue niht and day</L>
<L>Euer more to my pay;</L>
<L>Ich haue moni a mon ful fyn,</L>
<L N="470">Children, nevues and cosyn,</L>
<L>I haue alle &thorn;ing at my wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;er nul no wiht me greue ne spille;</L>
<L>I hedde neuere aduersite,</L>
<L>Ne gret serwe ful non on me."</L>
<L N="475">Whon seint Ambrose &thorn;eos wordes herd,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod audiens A. vehementer obstupuit et his qui erant secum in comitatu dixit: Surgite et hinc quantocius fugiamus, quia dominus non est in loco isto; festinate, filii, festinate, nec in fugiendo moram facite, ne nos hic divina ultio apprehendat et in peccatis illorum pariter nos involvat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wondurliche he was aferd,</L>
<L>And to hem &thorn;at were of his cumpaygnye</L>
<L>He bad hem faste &thorn;eonnes hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>"For i wot wel now in &thorn;is space</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;at God nis not in &thorn;is place;</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;e we faste on vre goyng,</L>
<L>And as we gon make&thorn; no dwellyng,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;orwh Godus veniaunce</L>
<L>Vs falle vppon sum mischaunce</L>
<L N="485">For &thorn;is ilke monnes sinne,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">of causal, mit dem Infin. als Gerund.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his hous now dwellen inne."
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e Ambrose and his meyne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo fugerent et aliquantulum processissent, subito se terra aperuit et hominem illum cum universis qui ad illum pertinebant ita ab|sorbuit, ut nullum inde vestigium remaneret.</NOTE></L>
<L>Weoren passed out from &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sodeynliche opened &thorn;e eor&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;er lafte nou&thorn;ur &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ne feor&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at hous dwelled and swonken,</L>
<L>But alle in to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;ei sonken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hem no steppe was seyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e hous stod al was pleyn.</L>
<L N="495">Whon seint Ambrose &thorn;is biheold,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cernens A. dixit: Ecce, fra|tres, quam misericorditer Deus parcit, cum hic adversa tribuit, et quam severe irasci|tur, cum semper prospera elargitur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his meyne &thorn;at stod in feld,</L>
<L>He seide: "lo, how merciful God is</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at soffren here iwis</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world aduersite,</L>
<L N="500">And of his grace sende&thorn; so to be,</L>
<L>And hou he punissche&thorn;, her mow &yogh;e se,</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;at han al prosperite."</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilke same plas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In eodem autem loco fovea quaedam pro|fundissima remansisse dicitur, quae (usque hodie in hujus facti testimonium) perse|verat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ere as bifel &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L N="505">Is a deop put alway,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer schal laste, as men say.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF alle maner vuel &thorn;e rote<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem A. radicem omnium malorum, avaritiam, magis ac magis in hominibus crescere cerneret et maxime in his qui erant in potestatibus constituti, (apud quos omnia pretio vendebantur,) nec non et in his qui erant sacris ministeriis deputati, vehementer ingemuit et se de hujus saeculi aerumna liberari instantius exo|ravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is auarice iclept and ihote.</L>
<L>And whon he sauh &thorn;at in monkuynde</L>
<L N="510">Auarice was most in muynde,</L>
<L>Among holy churche and worldly men,</L>
<L>Muche deol he made &thorn;en;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world, so sori place,</L>
<L>He preyed God &thorn;at in schort space</L>
<L N="515">He schulde him bringe at his wille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at his soule schulde not spille.</L>
<L>God hit him graunted specialiche:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui cum se id obtinuisse gauderet (im engl. erkl&auml;rt),</NOTE></L>
<L>An angel him warned priueliche.</L>
<L>Whon he was war of &thorn;at day</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;at he schulde passe hennes away,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he was joyful and feyn</L>
<L>And tolde his bre&thorn;eren in certeyn<NOTE PLACE="foot2">revelavit fratribus quod usque ad resurrectionem dominicam secum esset.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at til &thorn;e feste of &thorn;e resureccioun</L>
<L>He schulde wi&thorn; hem dwelle her doun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="525">A fewe dayes tofore he fel seek,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ante vero paucos dies quam lectulo detineretur, cum XLIIII psalmum cum notario dictaret,</NOTE></L>
<L>He was aboute &mdash; i telle ow ek &mdash;</L>
<L>Forte endyte wi&thorn; wit ful cler</L>
<L>&THORN;e foure and fourti&thorn;e psalm of &thorn;e sauter,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him was his notarie:</L>
<L N="530">&THORN;at sauh on him a siht of glorie:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">subito ipsi, vidente notario, in modum scuti brevis ignis caput ejus operuit atque paulatim per os ejus, tanquam in domum habitator, intravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sodeynliche in maner of a scheld</L>
<L>A schort fuir his hed &thorn;en held</L>
<L>And lutlum and lutlum<NOTE PLACE="foot1">lutlum by little, alter dat. plur.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to his mou&thorn; crep hole and sum,</L>
<L N="535">As &thorn;ouh hit hedde ben in to his hous;</L>
<L>&THORN;en wex his face al glorious<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc facies tanquam nix effecta est, sed postmodum ad suam speciem reversa est.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lyk to snouh hit wox al whit,</L>
<L>But aftur to his oune kynde turned hit.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day he made an endyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ipso igitur die scri|bendi et dictandi finem fecit nec ipsum psalmum explere potuit, post igitur paucos dies infirmitate corporis laborare coepit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="540">Of writyng and endyting,</L>
<L>&THORN;at psalm &thorn;en mihte he not parfourme &mdash;</L>
<L>Nere Godus wille, &thorn;at mihte men mourne.</L>
<L>A fewe daies aftur &thorn;at</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seknes he was al to squat.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">&THORN;En &thorn;e eorl of Ytalie<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc comes Italiae cum Mediolani esset, nobiles convocavit, dicens, quod, tanto viro recedente, periculum esset ne Italiae interitus immineret;</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>At Melan was and mad him murie;</L>
<L>But, whon he herde of &thorn;is ti&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>He made del and gret mournynge</L>
<L>And gedered to gedre alle &thorn;e grete</L>
<L N="550">Of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute; on an aftur mete,</L>
<L>And seide to hem: he dredde peril,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;er schulde falle sum il</L>
<L>To &thorn;at ilke cuntray,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at Ambrose wer gon away;</L>
<L N="555">&THORN;erfore he preyed &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulde gon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rogavitque ut ad virum Dei accederent rogantes ut sibi adhuc spatium vivendi (uno anno) a domino impetraret.</NOTE></L>
<L>To seint Ambrose swi&thorn;e anon,</L>
<L>To preye him preye God wi&thorn; good face</L>
<L>Forte sende him lengor space,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hem to dwelle sumwhat more,</L>
<L N="560">&YOGH;if &thorn;at his swete wille wore.</L>
<L>Riht so &thorn;ei seiden and he hem herd,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod ille ut ab illis au|divit, respondit: Non ita inter vos vixi, ut me vivere pudeat, nec mori timeo, cum bonum dominum habeamus.</NOTE></L>
<L>But riht anon he onswerd:</L>
<L>"I haue not liued amongus &yogh;ou</L>
<L>&THORN;at i am not aschomed nou,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">not pleonastisch.</NOTE></L>
<L N="565">Ne i drede not to dye, iwis:</L>
<L>We haue to lord &thorn;e kyng of blis."</L>
<L>Four dekenes of his,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Eo tempore quatuor ejus dyaconi invicem convene|runt tractantes inter se quis post ejus obitum bonus esset. Cum ergo a loco in quo vir Dei Ambrosius jacebat, longe essent et Simplicianum ita silenter nominassent, ut vix invicem se audirent, ille ab iis longe positus tertio exclamavit: senex, sed bonus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ei herden of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei come to gedere in &thorn;at plas</L>
<L N="570">&THORN;er he seek ileyd was,</L>
<L>Sumwhat also &thorn;ei stoden afer,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he scholde not hem her.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei gonne to treten in &thorn;at hour</L>
<L>Who mihte be best his successour;</L>
<L N="575">Amonges hem softly &thorn;ei seiden &thorn;an</L>
<L>Hit were best chese Simplician.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ouh &thorn;ei made no gret nois,</L>
<L>He onswerd, as he hed herd heore vois,</L>
<L>&THORN;ries he seide wi&thorn; mylde mod:</L>
<L N="580">"He is old, but he is god."</L>
<L>Alle foure &thorn;en woxen aferd,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod audientes territi fugerunt et nonnisi illum post ejus obitum elegerunt, (in loco autem in quo jacebat vidit Jesum ad se venientem et sibi vultu alacri arridentem.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ei his vois herd.</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles, whon he was ded,</L>
<L>Symplician &thorn;ei chosen to heore hed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="585">&THORN;E bisschop of Vercellenen &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Honoratus vero, episcopus Vercellensis, qui beati Ambrosii obitum exspectabat, cum se sopori dedisset, vocem tertio se clamantis audivit: surge, quia mox est reces|surus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Honoratus him cleped men &mdash;</L>
<L>He bod Ambrosus passyng.</L>
<L>But as he fel on slepyng,</L>
<L>He herde a vois &thorn;ries &thorn;o</L>
<L N="590">Sei&yogh;e: "rys, for nou he schal for&thorn; go!"</L>
<L>He ros and &thorn;enne to Melan went<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui consurgens Mediolanum concitus venit et ei dominici corporis sa|cramentum dedit; moxque ille manus in modum crucis expandit et ultimum spiritum inter verba oris efflavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And ministred to Ambrose &thorn;e sacrement.</L>
<L>And he in maner of &thorn;e crois</L>
<L>His hondus streihte, wi&thorn;oute nois;</L>
<L N="595">In preyers, as he bisied him most,</L>
<L>To god he &yogh;eld vp &thorn;e gost.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon regned in lyf ful fyne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Floruit circa annos domini 379 (!)</NOTE></L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e &yogh;eres &thorn;re hundred heihti and nyne</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e date of vr lord,</L>
<L N="600">An holi mon in dede and word.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chirche an ester niht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem in nocte paschae corpus ejus ad ecclesiam fuisset delatum, plurimi infantes bapti|zati eum viderunt, ita ut aliqui eum sedentem in cathedra tribunali dicerent (606 Zus.), alii adscendentem digito suis parentihus demonstrarent, nonnulli vero stellam super corpus ejus se videre narrarent (614 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>As men him beren for&thorn; riht,</L>
<L>Cristen children and innocent</L>
<L>Seiden &thorn;ei sauh him verrement</L>
<L N="605">As a juge sitte in a chayer,</L>
<L>Riht as &thorn;e sonne briht and cleer;</L>
<L>Summe wi&thorn; heore fyngres, verreyliche,
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>Scheweden heore frendes openliche</L>
<L>Vpward hou &thorn;ei sauh him stihe</L>
<L N="610">Wi&thorn; heore bodiliche ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Summe seiden &thorn;ey se&yogh;en wel a fyne</L>
<L>A sterre ligge briht and schyne</L>
<L>Euene aboue vppon his brest &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. vppen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Signe hit was of wel god rest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="615">&THORN;Er was a prest, sat at a fest,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam presbiter cum in convivio cum multis aliis esset et sancto Ambrosio detrahere coepisset, eum continuo plaga per|culit et de convivio ad lectum ductus vitam finivit (621 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Wher men of Ambrose speeken mest;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prest bigon him to bakbyte</L>
<L>And bi his godnes he set luyte:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seknesse he was smiten anon,</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;at to his bed &thorn;en moste he gon &mdash;</L>
<L>I not wher he dude him schriue,</L>
<L>But &thorn;er he mad ende of his lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALso in &thorn;e cite of Cartage<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In urbe Cartha|giniensi cum tres episcopi simul convivarent et unus eorum beato A. detraxisset, re|latum est quid illi presbitero qui sibi detraxerat accidisset.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;(r)e bisschops of gret parage<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;e st. &thorn;re.</NOTE></L>
<L N="625">Weren iset at a fest</L>
<L>And iserued at &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>But on of hem gon to bacbyte</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose wi&thorn; gret dilyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;en of &thorn;e prest on him told</L>
<L N="630">Hou hit bifel, &thorn;at was so bold</L>
<L>To speke harm of &thorn;at mon,</L>
<L>And hou vengaunce ful him vppon.</L>
<L>He onswerde: so god him spede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum ille vili|penderet, subito letale vulnus accepit et extremum continuo diem clausit. &mdash;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erof tok he but luytel hede.</L>
<L N="635">And sodeynliche a de&thorn;es wounde</L>
<L>Him tok, anon he fel to grounde &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he made his laste ende</L>
<L>For bacbytyng of Godus frende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOte &yogh;e nou &thorn;is, for hit is able:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Notandum, quod beatus A. in multis commendabilis fuisse videtur. Primo in liberalitate, quia omnia quae habebat pauperum erant; unde refert de se ipso (646 Zus.), quod imperatori petenti basilicam sic respondit (et est in decreto XXIII qu. VIII, convenior etc.):</NOTE></L>
<L N="640">In mony &thorn;inges he was comendable,</L>
<L>Furst in liberalite:</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at hedde he</L>
<L>To pore folk forso&thorn;e he &yogh;af</L>
<L>&THORN;at bedreden weore or wente wi&thorn; staf.</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;erfore of him a tale men telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is as so&thorn; as gospelle:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN emperour to him sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde wi&thorn; good talent</L>
<L>&YOGH;elde vp a noble churche to him &mdash;</L>
<L N="650">For he &thorn;ou&yogh;te, wi&thorn; wille ful grim,</L>
<L>Hit to heretykes haue &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at were not wor&thorn;i &thorn;er in to lyue &mdash;</L>
<L>He seide &thorn;at he was of al &thorn;ing lord</L>
<L>And wolde hit haue at o word.</L>
<L N="655">Ambrose onswerde wi&thorn; honour:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Si a me peteret quod meum esset, id est fun|dum meum, argentum meum et huiusmodi meum, non refragarer, quamquam omnia quae mea sunt pauperum sunt (663-675 nicht im latein. Text bei Gr&auml;sse).</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;at, he seide, &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>Asked of me &thorn;ing &thorn;at myn wer,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh hit were gold or seluer</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles hous or lond,</L>
<L N="660">Hit scholde beo redi to his hond,</L>
<L>And &thorn;auh al &thorn;at i haue here, i wot wel,</L>
<L>Is pore mennes catel &mdash;</L>
<L>So ich hit holde, and euer schal be</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh Godus oune charite.</L>
<L N="665">But holichirche to God do&thorn; longe,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore as wel he mihte me honge</L>
<L>As make me &yogh;iue him such a &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Hit weore a cursed doyng,</L>
<L>For, &thorn;auh he beo muchel of miht,</L>
<L N="670">To such &thorn;ing ha&thorn; he no riht".</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;is gode mon, iwis,</L>
<L>Knouleched &thorn;at al &thorn;at was his</L>
<L>Was pore mennes at heore nede &mdash;</L>
<L>Such a prelat god wol spede.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="19"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="675">ALso he was comendable, wi&thorn;outen les,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Secundo in munditiae puritate: fuit enim virgo; unde refert Hieronymus eum dixisse: virginitatem non solum efferimus sed etiam servamus.</NOTE></L>
<L>In puirte of clannes:</L>
<L>For he was a mayden clene &mdash;</L>
<L>Leeue hit wel wi&thorn;outen wene! &mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Jerom telle&thorn; he herde him say</L>
<L N="680">&THORN;eos wordus to him vppon a day:</L>
<L>"We speken not onliche of maydenhede,</L>
<L>But we hit kepe also in dede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN studefastnesse also of fe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tertio in fidei firmitate; unde dixit, cum imperator peteret basilicam, (et est in eodem ca|pitulo): prius est ut animam mihi quam sedem auferat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comendable he was al wei.</L>
<L N="685">&THORN;er as i aboue seid:</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e emperour him vpbreid,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;e chirche he wolde haue had,</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose ra&thorn;ur him bad</L>
<L>Furst his lyf take him fro</L>
<L N="690">&THORN;en his fei&thorn; &mdash; he seide him so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN couetise of martirdom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quarto in martirii aviditate; unde legitur in epistola sua de basilica non tradenda, quod praepositus Valentiniani Ambrosio mandavit dicens: Tu contemnis Valentinianum, caput tibi tollo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forte come to &thorn;at blessede hom,</L>
<L>He was to comende witerli.</L>
<L>I schal &yogh;ou telle &thorn;e skile whi.</L>
<L N="695">Whon Valentinian &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>His churche coueyted wi&thorn; errour &mdash;</L>
<L>As i tolde &yogh;ou a luitel bifore &mdash;,</L>
<L>An officer greued Ambrose sore</L>
<L>For he nolde not &thorn;erto assent,</L>
<L N="700">And sende word to him wi&thorn; gret talent:</L>
<L>"&THORN;en &thorn;ou wolt not fulfille</L>
<L>Mi lord, &thorn;e emperoures, wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;in heued &thorn;erfore I wol haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;i lyf, &thorn;i self schaltou not saue."</L>
<L N="705">Ambrose onswerde loueliche:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cui Ambrosius: Deus permittat tibi ut facias quod minaris, atque utinam Deus avertat eos ab ecclesia, in me omnia tela sua convertant et meo sanguine sitim suam expleant. (713-4 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>"God &yogh;iue &thorn;e grace smartliche</L>
<L>To parfourne &thorn;i manase,</L>
<L>Whon euer &thorn;e luste and what place!</L>
<L>Wolde god &thorn;at on &thorn;at maneer</L>
<L N="710">From holi chirche to turne heore vuel cher<NOTE PLACE="foot1">to vor d. Infin., weil wolde erst folgt; oder ist V. 710 and vengen st. avengen verschrieben?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolden and vengen hem al on me</L>
<L>And kele heore &thorn;urst in sleing me!"</L>
<L>Of his de&thorn; he &yogh;af luyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;erwi&thorn; his chirche wolde quite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">IN bisynes of orisoun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quinto in orationis instantia; (unde dicitur de eo et habe|tur in libro XI hystoriae ecclesiasticae): Ambr. adversum reginae furorem non se manu defensabat aut telo, sed jejuniis et continuatis vigiliis, sub altari positus per obsecrationes defensorem sibi et ecclesiae Deum parabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was comendable of deuocioun.</L>
<L>A&yogh;eines &thorn;e emperice Justine</L>
<L>&THORN;at proued he wel wi&thorn; hert ful fine,</L>
<L>For a&yogh;eynes hire woodnes</L>
<L N="720">He schewed alle goodnes,</L>
<L>He fendet him not a&yogh;eynes hire</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur wi&thorn; scheld ne wi&thorn; spere,</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; wakyng and preyer,</L>
<L>Vndur an holy auter</L>
<L N="725">He preied God his chirche defende</L>
<L>And of mendyng grace hire sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was comendable and &yogh;ep<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sexto in lacryma|rum abundantia: habuit enim tria genera lacrymarum, scilicet lacrymas com|passionis pro aliorum culpis, &mdash; unde dicit Paulinus de eo in legenda, quod, cum aliquis lapsum sibi confitebatur, sic amarissime flebat, quod illum similiter flere compellebat (vgl. V. 401 ff.) &mdash;,</NOTE></L>
<L>In habundaunce of teres and wep.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo maner of teres here</L>
<L N="730">He vsud &mdash; nou &yogh;e mowe hem lere:</L>
<L>Furst he hedde teres of compassiun,</L>
<L>For he wolde wepe for deuociun</L>
<L>For hem &thorn;at hedden don amis</L>
<L>And gulti weren in heore dedis;</L>
<L N="735">Paulin sei&thorn; for &thorn;at of him aboue:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">aboue, s. v. 401.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon eny wiht him schrof to him forloue</L>
<L>Of eny gult &thorn;at he hedde don,
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he wolde wepe anon,</L>
<L>And riht so he wolde constreyne</L>
<L N="740">&THORN;e mon to wepe for his peyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANd teres he hedde of deuociun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lacrymas devotionis pro aeternis desi|deriis, &mdash; unde supra dictum est a Paulino, quod, cum interrogabatur cur sanctos qui moriebantur sic fleret, respondit: Ne me putetis flere quod recesserint, sed quia me ad gloriam praecesserunt (s. oben V. 417 ff.) &mdash;,</NOTE></L>
<L>Euer to preye, in feld and toun,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world forte go &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was his disyr euer mo;</L>
<L N="745">&THORN;erfore &mdash; tofore as hit is seid &mdash;,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">s. oben 417 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at Paulin him wolde vpbreid</L>
<L>And aske whi he wepte so sore,</L>
<L>Whon holi men dyed him bifore</L>
<L>&THORN;at in to joye weren ipast</L>
<L N="750">&THORN;at wi&thorn;outen ende schal last,</L>
<L>He bad him leeue neuer &thorn;e mo</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made deol and wepte so<NOTE PLACE="foot1">im Ms. fehlt ne?</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ei passed &thorn;is world fro,</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ei weore tofore him go</L>
<L N="755">To &thorn;e kyngdom of blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer schal laste wi&thorn;outen mis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF compassioun eke he hedde &thorn;e tere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lacrymas compassionis pro aliorum injuriis, &mdash; unde ipse dicit de se (et est in decreto in superiori capite:) Adversus milites Gothos lacrymae meae arma sunt mea, satis enim munimenta sacer|dotis sunt, aliter nec debeo nec possum resistere (765-6 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>For hem &thorn;at wronges suffreden here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knihtes &thorn;at weren fers and grim</L>
<L N="760">He onswerde, &thorn;at weren sent to him</L>
<L>From Valentinean &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;te him to worche harde stour,</L>
<L>He seide: "ich vse nou&thorn;ur spere ne charmes,</L>
<L>Mi bitter teres beo&thorn; myn armes" &mdash;</L>
<L N="765">And so &thorn;ei schulde to alle clerkes</L>
<L>&THORN;at suwen wole seint Ambrose werkes &mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;eos, he seide, ben prestes defens,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur nul i make no resistens."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E bok also bere&thorn; witnes:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Septimo in forti constantia; cuius constantia maxime in tribus apparet: primo in defen|sione catholicae veritatis, &mdash; (unde dicitur in libro XI ecclesiasticae hystoriae, quod) Justina, mater Valentiniani imperatoris, Arianae haereseos alumna, coepit con|turbare ecclesiarum statum, comminari sacerdotibus depulsiones et exsilia, nisi Arimi|nensis concilii decreta revocarent (785-790 erkl&auml;r. Zus.), quo bello ecclesiae murum ac turrim validissimum pulsabat Ambrosium. (Ein im lat. hier folgender anderer Aus|spruch &uuml;ber des A. Glaubensmuth aus der praefatio desselben Buches fehlt im engl.) &mdash;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="770">He was comendable in studefastnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;at bisemed in &thorn;reo &thorn;inges</L>
<L>&THORN;at he vsud in his liuinges:</L>
<L>Furst in defendyng &mdash; as &thorn;e bok sei&thorn; &mdash;</L>
<L>Of so&thorn;nes of holichirches fei&thorn;.</L>
<L N="775">Whon &thorn;e modur of Valentinian,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Justine men called &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche meyntened mani a man</L>
<L>In &thorn;e heresy of Arrian,</L>
<L>Bigon to distorble &thorn;e stat</L>
<L N="780">Of holichurche, and mony prelat</L>
<L>And prestes manased to exile,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolde reuoke &thorn;e counsyle</L>
<L>&THORN;at was iholde in &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;at men cleped Arimminence:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Arimninence.</NOTE></L>
<L N="785">In &thorn;e whuche alle &thorn;e clergye</L>
<L>Hedde dampned &thorn;e heresye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Arrianes lore</L>
<L>And heretykes icorsed &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er vppon was mad a decre,</L>
<L N="790">&THORN;at euermore schulde iholde be;</L>
<L>Ambrose of hire tok non hede,</L>
<L>But stod studefast at &thorn;at nede</L>
<L>And he him self was wal and tour,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. hin st. him.</NOTE></L>
<L>To kepe holichirches honour,</L>
<L N="795">And he on hond tok &thorn;at batayle &mdash;</L>
<L>Hem he distruyed wi&thorn;oute fayle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was comendable ek parde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">secundo in tuitione ecclesiasticae libertatis, &mdash; unde, cum imperator auferre vellet quandam basilicam, opposuit se Ambrosius contra imperatorem, (sicut ipse testatur et est in decreto XXIII quaest. VI):</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>In kepyng of &thorn;e liberte</L>
<L>Of holichurche wi&thorn; honour.</L>
<L N="800">&THORN;erfore, whon &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>A chirche from him wolde haue take,</L>
<L>He hit wi&thorn;stod for Godus sake</L>
<L>And he onswerd, as mon wel sage,</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at wer sent on message(!):</L>
<L N="805">"I am comaunded, he seide, of knihtes<NOTE PLACE="foot2">convenior ipse a comitibus ut per me basilicae fieret matura traditio, dicentibus imperatorem iussisse (:jure suo tradi debere);</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;e emperoures mihtes</L>
<L>&THORN;at i schulde wi&thorn;outen irke</L>
<L>Delyuere vp to him a kirke.</L>
<L>I onswered (!) wi&thorn;outen lesyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">respondi: si patrimonium petit: invadite, si corpus: occurram, vultis in vincula: imponite, (vultis in mortem: voluntatis est mihi); (non ego me vallabo con|fusione populorum) nec altaria tenebo vitam obsecrans, sed pro altaribus gratius im|molabor; mandatur tradere basilicam, urgemur igitur praeceptis regalibus, sed con|firmamur scripturae sermonibus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="810">&YOGH;if &thorn;at &yogh;e aske weddyng,</L>
<L>Take&thorn; me for&thorn; wi&thorn; ou away &mdash;</L>
<L>I schal &yogh;ou suffre, par ma fay;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if my bodi &yogh;e wolde hent,</L>
<L>I wol come to &yogh;ou, verreyment;</L>
<L N="815">&YOGH;if &yogh;e wole me bynde wi&thorn; bondes,</L>
<L>I schal neuere fleo &yogh;or hondes,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur to chirche ne to auter,</L>
<L>Beo &yogh;e neuer so strong ne feer;</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e auter wi&thorn; god wil</L>
<L N="820">I schal me putte in to peril.</L>
<L>I am comaunded delyuere &thorn;e chirche:</L>
<L>&THORN;at were a wondur werk to worche!</L>
<L>&THORN;e biddyng of &thorn;e emperour</L>
<L>&THORN;rete&thorn; me wi&thorn; gret irrour,</L>
<L N="825">But holy writ comferme&thorn; me</L>
<L>&THORN;at sei&thorn; &thorn;us, in good lewte:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&THORN;at bezieht sich auf holy writ, w&auml;hrend lat. Qui respondit auf Ambr.; allerdings sind die 827-8 folg. Worte aus Job 2, 10 (Vulg.: quasi una de stultis mulieribus locuta es.) &mdash; Die ganze Rede des Ambr. ist aus verschiedenen Stellen seiner Schriften zusammengetragen.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui respondit (engl. bezieht anders): Tanquam una ex insipientibus locuta es; noli gravare te, imperator, ut putes te in ea quae divina sunt jus habere; ad imperatorem palatia pertinent, ad sacerdotes ecclesiae.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ispoken on &thorn;e gyse</L>
<L>As on of &thorn;e wymmen &thorn;at weren vnwyse.</L>
<L>"&THORN;erfore, emperour, greue not &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="830">Ne trowe &thorn;ou not, he seide, parde,</L>
<L>No maner riht &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t haue</L>
<L>In heuenlich &thorn;inges no&thorn;ur hem craue;</L>
<L>Paleises longen to emperours,</L>
<L>And halewed chirches ben prestes tours.</L>
<L N="835">&YOGH;if seint Naboth wi&thorn; his oune blood<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sanctus Naboth vineam suam proprio cruore defendit; si ille vineam suam non reddidit, nos trademus Christi ecclesiam? tributum Caesari est, non negetur, ecclesia Dei est, Caesari utique non donetur.</NOTE></L>
<L>His vyn&yogh;ard defendet wi&thorn; herte god,</L>
<L>For he hit wolde not vp &yogh;elde:</L>
<L>I hope &thorn;at god schal ben vr schelde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sunful dede schul we not worche<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;at st. &thorn;at &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="840">To &yogh;elde &thorn;e emperour vr churche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tribute is duwe to Cesar &mdash;</L>
<L>Hit to deni&yogh;e vche mon bi war! &mdash;</L>
<L>Holychirche is godus al one,</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour &thorn;erwi&thorn; ha&thorn; not to done.</L>
<L N="845">&YOGH;if he aske ou&yogh;t &thorn;at is myn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Si de me aliquid compellaretur aut posceretur: fun|dus aut domus aut aurum aut argentum, id quod juris mei esset libenter offerrem; templo Dei nihil possum decerpere nec detrahere, cum illud custodiendum, non decerpendum acceperim.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lond or rente or gold so fyn,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gode wille I wolde him take</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof no daunger make;</L>
<L>But I mai not &yogh;iue awei</L>
<L N="850">Godus temple, ne hit bitray,</L>
<L>Ne to no temperel lord hit &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh he beo gret in toun and felde;</L>
<L>Forte kepe hit is me take,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t to &yogh;elde vp, for godus sake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="855">HE was also comendable,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tertio in objurgatione vitii et omnis iniquitatis, &mdash; (unde legitur in hystoria tripartita in quadam chronica, quod,) [der engl. Text mit eigenem Titel.]</NOTE></L>
<L>For he hem wolde blame &thorn;at wer not stable,</L>
<L>And repreyne hem of wikkednesse,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e more and eke lesse.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000028.tif" N="22">
<HEAD>De Theodosio imperatore.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel sum tyme in certeyn<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cum apud Thessalonicam orta seditione quidam judices fuissent a populo lapidati, Theodosius imperator indignatus jussit omnes interimi, nocentes ab innocen|tibus non secernens, ubi fere 5000 hominum sunt occisa.</NOTE></L>
<L N="860">In &thorn;e cite of Tessaleyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er was a gret rysing</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pepul &thorn;er dwellyng</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;e juges of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pepul hem stened and duden <I>of</I> dawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. to dawe st. of dawe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="865">Teodosius &thorn;e emperoure</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; was wro&thorn; and gon to loure,</L>
<L>He comaunded men hem to sle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non of alle awey schulde fle;</L>
<L>Bote he dude no&thorn;ing goodly,</L>
<L N="870">For he slouh gulti and vngulti:</L>
<L>&THORN;e noumbre was, men seide in londe,</L>
<L>Almost to fyf &thorn;ousunde.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum igitur imperator Mediolanum venisset et ecclesiam intrare vellet, occurrit ei A. ad januam eique adi|tum prohibuit, dicens:</NOTE></L>
<L>To Melan wente wi&thorn; gret honour,</L>
<L N="875">In to &thorn;e chirche he wolde haue gon.</L>
<L>Ambrose a&yogh;eines him com anon</L>
<L>And, whon he com riht to &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>He him forbad cum in &thorn;er ate.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Ambrose him gan vbbreide</L>
<L N="880">And &thorn;eose wordus to him seide:</L>
<L>"Whi woldust &thorn;ou nouht, sir emperour,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cur, imperator, post causam tanti furoris non agnoscis molem tuae praesumtionis, sed forte recognitionem peccati prohibet potestas imperii? decet te ut vincat ratio potestatem; princeps es, o imperator, sed conservorum. (895-96 Zus.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;i wodnes and errour</L>
<L>Knowleche &thorn;i presumcioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast wrouht as feloun?</L>
<L N="885">But parauenture hit may be</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e grete miht of &thorn;yn emperorite</L>
<L>Make &thorn;at &thorn;ou nult nou&yogh;t knowleche</L>
<L>&THORN;i foule sunne and &thorn;y wreche.</L>
<L>Hit schulde ben euere in &thorn;i dome</L>
<L N="890">Resoun, &thorn;i miht to ouercome;</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh &thorn;ou beo prince and emperour</L>
<L>Ouer men wi&thorn; gret honour,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schuldest &thorn;enke bi good steem</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nart but riht as on of hem</L>
<L N="895">Tofore god, &yogh;if &thorn;ou take hede.</L>
<L>Avise &thorn;e wel of &thorn;i dede!</L>
<L>Hou dorstest &thorn;ou beo so bold<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quibus ergo oculis adspicies communis domini templum (900 Zus.), quibus pedibus calcabis sanctum pavimentum, quomodo manus extendes de quibus adhuc sanguis stillat injustus, qua praesumtione ore tuo poculum sanguinis ejus per|cipies, dum furore tuorum sermonum tantus injuste sit sanguis effusus?</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;in e&yogh;en to bi hold</L>
<L>&THORN;e temple of vr alre lord,</L>
<L N="900">O&thorn;ur so hardi to speke a word?</L>
<L>Hou mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou fynde in &thorn;in entent</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i feet to gon on &thorn;e pament?</L>
<L>Hou mihtest &thorn;ou wi&thorn; eny moode</L>
<L>Holde vp &thorn;in hondes to &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="905">&THORN;at &yogh;it aren fouled wi&thorn; &thorn;e blod</L>
<L>Of innocens, whon &thorn;ou were wood?</L>
<L>Hou mihtest &thorn;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;i mou&thorn;</L>
<L>His blod receyue &thorn;at for vs cou&thorn;</L>
<L>Mon bicom, riht as beo we,</L>
<L N="910">And for vs dye on rode tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;i mou&thorn; &yogh;af juggemens</L>
<L>For to sle innocens</L>
<L>And hem &thorn;at were not gulti</L>
<L>As hem &thorn;at trespast verreyli?</L>
<L N="915">Go for&thorn;, he seide, &thorn;erfore &thorn;i way,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">recede ergo, recede, ne secundo peccato priorem nequitiam augere contendas; suscipe vin|culum quo te dominus nunc ligavit: est enim medicina maxima sanitatis. (923-4 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Leste &thorn;i secunde sunne to day</L>
<L>Eche &thorn;i former wikkedhede</L>
<L>And god take vengaunce of &thorn;i dede!</L>
<L>&THORN;e bond &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &thorn;e wi&thorn; ibounde</L>
<L N="920">Tak hit, and walk for&thorn; on &thorn;e grounde!</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e moste medecin</L>
<L>&THORN;at mon may take for his sin" &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was to sei: for his misded</L>
<L>From holychirche he was departed.
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="23"></L>
<L N="925">&THORN;e emperour &thorn;en was aschamed<NOTE PLACE="foot2">His sermonibus imperator obediens, gemens et flens ad regalia remeavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And obbeyed, as he &thorn;at was blamed;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret deol and wi&thorn; wepyng</L>
<L>Hamward he rod to his dwellyng.</L>
<L>Sire Rufin, maister of his knihtes,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo diu in fletu mansisset, Rufinus, magister militum, causam tantae tristi|tiae inquisivit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="930">Asked him anon rihtes</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at he loked so dreri,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of cher was so sori?</L>
<L>He onswerde: "&thorn;ou wost wel luyte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui ille: Tu, inquit, mea mala non sentis, quia servis et mendi|cantibus aperta sunt templa, mihi vero ad ea ingressus non est &mdash; et haec dicens sin|gula verba singultibus interrumpebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>What is my wo or myn edwyte;</L>
<L N="935">For to beggers and to bonde men</L>
<L>&THORN;e temple &yogh;ates open ben,</L>
<L>To my self &thorn;at am al on</L>
<L>Ingoyng nou is &thorn;er non."</L>
<L>And euere as he &thorn;eos wordes seid</L>
<L N="940">He wept and snobbed and ofte abreid.</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide Rufin, &thorn;at kniht:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui Rufinus: Curro, si vis, ad Ambrosium, ut tibi solvat vinculum quo te ligavit (944 u. 8 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>"I schal not stunte but anon riht</L>
<L>Renne to Ambrose, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for&yogh;iue &thorn;e &thorn;i gilt,</L>
<L N="945">And also, &thorn;at he take on honde</L>
<L>To vnbynde &thorn;e of &thorn;at bonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bond &thorn;e wi&thorn; last,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh power of holichirche so fast."</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour onswerde &thorn;an:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ille: Non poteris sua|dere Ambrosio, quia non verebitur imperialem potestatem, ut legem possit praevaricari divinam.</NOTE></L>
<L N="950">"&THORN;ou schalt not ouercome &thorn;at man</L>
<L>For no fere of no miht</L>
<L>Of emperour, kyng ne kniht,</L>
<L>For no mon may make him wi&thorn; awe</L>
<L>To don a&yogh;eynes godus lawe."</L>
<L N="955">But Rufin biheet wel inowe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed cum ille promitteret quod eum flecteret, eum imperator ire prae|cepit, et ipse post paululum est secutus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde make him bowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour bad him go tofore,</L>
<L>And he him suwed wi&thorn; herte sore.</L>
<L>Anon as seint Ambrose<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mox autem ut A. Rufinum vidit, ait: Impudentiam canum imitatus es, o Rufine! tantae videlicet necis auctor exsistens et nec pudorem ex fronte detergens non erubescis contra majestatem latrare divinam.</NOTE></L>
<L N="960">Sauh Rufin come, his purpose</L>
<L>Knewe and seide wi&thorn; vois ful round:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou art vnschomefast as an hound:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were autour of &thorn;at slauhter,</L>
<L>But &thorn;er of nou &thorn;ou makest lauhter</L>
<L N="965">And in &thorn;i forehed nis no schame,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou dredest for no blame</L>
<L>Forte berke and wod be</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes godus maieste."</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles for &thorn;e emperour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cumque Rufinus pro imperatore supplicasset et diceret eum sequi, superno zelo accens u s (engl. bezieht anders, als ob accens u m zu lesen; 976 Zus.) Ambrosius ait:</NOTE></L>
<L N="970">Rufin preyed him at &thorn;at hour</L>
<L>&THORN;at he him &thorn;enne wolde vnbynde,</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;at he com him bihynde,</L>
<L>Him suwyng so for his loue</L>
<L>&THORN;at in heuene sitte&thorn; aboue,</L>
<L N="975">Istured of &thorn;e holi gost,</L>
<L>"His herte is sori, wel &thorn;ou wost."</L>
<L>&THORN;en Ambrose gan to sey:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e tofore i telle, &thorn;e wey<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ego tibi praedico quoniam ingredi eum sacra limina prohibeo; si vero potestatem in tyrannidem mutaverit, necem libenter suscipio. Quod cum Rufinus imperatori nuntiasset,</NOTE></L>
<L>I forbeode him algate,</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;at he entre in not atte &yogh;ate</L>
<L>Of Godus oune holy place,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he haue geten grace;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. genten st. geten.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at he wi&thorn; tirauntrie</L>
<L>Eny &thorn;ing do to my bodye,</L>
<L N="985">&THORN;ouh he me sle, for godus sake</L>
<L>Ful gladliche &thorn;e de&thorn; schal i take."</L>
<L>&THORN;at Rufyn &thorn;e emperour tolde</L>
<L>And wherto &thorn;at he schulde him holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour mekeliche "forso&thorn;e" he seide,</L>
<L N="990">"Hou so euere he me vpbreide,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Pergam, inquit, ad eum, ut justas in faciem contumelias recipiam.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>I schal to him go to his place</L>
<L>And suffre him to myn oune face</L>
<L>Sei, what so euer his likyng be,</L>
<L>And take hit wi&thorn; god charite."</L>
<L N="995">Whon he to seint Ambrose com,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo venisset et sua solvi vincula postulasset, occurrens Ambrosius et ingres|sum prohibens ait: Quam poenitentiam ostendisti post tantas iniquitates?</NOTE></L>
<L>He preyed wi&thorn; good deuocion</L>
<L>&THORN;at he his grace mihte fynde,</L>
<L>His harde bondes to vnbynde.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose ran him a&yogh;ein</L>
<L N="1000">And bad him trauayle not in veyn,</L>
<L>For he him bad schortly also</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e churche schold he not go,</L>
<L>And seide: "mon, &thorn;ou art ful lewed,</L>
<L>What penaunce hastou nou ischewed</L>
<L N="1005">For &thorn;i grete wikkednesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;i sunne and &thorn;yn vnbuxumnesse?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour wi&thorn; gret deol<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ille: Tuum est imponere, meum obtemperare (1011-2 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sire", he seide, "i wot wel,</L>
<L>Hit falle&thorn; to &thorn;e, comaunde me,</L>
<L N="1010">And me, obeysaunt forte be.</L>
<L>What euer &thorn;ou bidde for my soule hele,</L>
<L>I schal hit do eueridele."</L>
<L>Neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;e emperour for&thorn;wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Verum cum im|perator allegaret quod et David adulterium et homicidium commisisset (1017-8 Zus.), ait Ambrosius: Qui secutus es errantem, sequere corrigentem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alegged hou &thorn;e kyng Dauid</L>
<L N="1015">Hedde idon auoutrye</L>
<L>And monnes slauhtre wi&thorn; felenye,</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;at he &yogh;it hedde space</L>
<L>Him to amende &thorn;orwh Godus grace.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose &thorn;enne wi&thorn;outen weer</L>
<L N="1020">Onswerd him on &thorn;is maneer:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou haue suwed Dauid in vuel doyng,</L>
<L>Suwe his dede in amendyng!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour &thorn;at so mekeliche tok<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod ita gratanter imperator suscepit, quod publicam poenitentiam non recusavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at open penaunce he not forsok,</L>
<L N="1025">But, riht as Ambrose bad him don,</L>
<L>Parfourned his penaunces euerichon.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose him reconsyled<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum igitur, reconciliatus, ecclesiam intrasset et intra cancellos staret, requirit A. quid ibi exspectaret.</NOTE></L>
<L>To holychirche and him asoyled.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour in to &thorn;e chirche wente &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="1030">In to &thorn;e chauncel he dressed him &thorn;ro;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;ro = quickly.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his deuociun &THORN;er he stod,</L>
<L>Ambrose him asked wi&thorn; mylde mod</L>
<L>What he abod &thorn;at he stod &thorn;er.</L>
<L>And he onswerd wi&thorn; mylde cher:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui cum diceret se perceptionem sacrorum mysteriorum exspectare, ait Ambrosius: O imperator, interiora Ioca tantum sacerdotibus (1040 Zus.) sunt collo|cata; egredere igitur et' hanc exspectationem cum caeteris communem habe; pur|pura namque imperatores facit, non sacerdotes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1035">"Sire, he seide, wi&thorn; myn entent</L>
<L>Is to receyue &thorn;e sacrament."</L>
<L>Ambrose spared for non honour,</L>
<L>But seide: "&yogh;e, sire emperour,</L>
<L>&THORN;is place is ordeynt onliche for prestes,</L>
<L N="1040">And not for lewed men ne beestes.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e churche &thorn;erfore go doun</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur men in comoun</L>
<L>Stond and bidde &thorn;i preyere;</L>
<L>&THORN;er schulde no such mon stonden here.</L>
<L N="1045">&THORN;yn aray of purpur palle</L>
<L>Make&thorn; an emperour wel wi&thorn; alle,</L>
<L>Prestes, &thorn;ouh, ne make&thorn; hit non."<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;ouh demonstr., jedoch; so h&auml;ufig.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour forso&thorn;e ful son<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui imperator protinus obedivit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Obeisaunt was to his biddyng,</L>
<L N="1050">Out of &thorn;e chauncel tok his going</L>
<L>And stod adoun in &thorn;e bodi</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e chirche, as mon modi.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur tyme whon &thorn;e emperour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo, Constantinopolin reversus, extra cancellos staret (engl. ausgef&uuml;hrter),</NOTE></L>
<L>To Constantynople wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L N="1055">Was comen and wolde here messe,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e churche wi&thorn; more and lesse</L>
<L>He went and tok his stondyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e chauncel, aftur &thorn;e teching</L>
<L>Of seynt Ambrose, &thorn;e noble clerk,</L>
<L N="1060">&THORN;at him tauhte to worschipe prest and clerk.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bisschop &thorn;enne of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mandavit eidem episcopus ut intraret (engl. dir.); et ille ait:</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e emperour so fre</L>
<L>Seide: "sire, hit beseme&thorn; ou wel</L>
<L>To go in to &thorn;e chauncel,</L>
<L N="1065">&THORN;er to make &yogh;oure standyng</L>
<L>Or, &yogh;if ow luste, &yogh;oure knelyng".</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour &thorn;enne gon to say:</L>
<L>"I lernde sum tyme on a day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vix discere potui quod differentia sit imperatoris et sacerdotis, vix enim veritatis inveni magistrum, Ambrosium namque solum novi vocari pontificem. &mdash;</NOTE></L>
<L>What is &thorn;e difference</L>
<L N="1070">In doyng of reuerence</L>
<L>Bitwene a prest and an emperour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chauncel is place of prestes honour.</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e among old or newe</L>
<L>Fond i euere mayster trewe,</L>
<L N="1075">But i put &yogh;ou out of whonhope:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">whonhope mit unorg. h, wie whinges 3, 363.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ambrose is wor&thorn;i be called bisschope."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>COmendable he was eke and fyn<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Octavo insana doctrina, (ejus namque doctrina habet altam profundi|tatem:) Hieronymus de XII doctoribus: "Ambrosius super profundorum pinna rap|tus et aeris volucer, quamdiu in profundum ingreditur, fructum de alto capere videtur".</NOTE></L>
<L>In his holy doctrin.</L>
<L>Ierom, &thorn;at speke&thorn; of doctours twelue,</L>
<L N="1080">Ambrose comende&thorn; ouur o&thorn;ur him selue</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; of him in &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is lyk to a brid &thorn;at set were</L>
<L>Vppon a pynacle to fleo an hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>As eny mon mihte seo wi&thorn; e&yogh;e:</L>
<L N="1085">&THORN;e herre he fleo&thorn; to take &thorn;e wynde</L>
<L>Euer &thorn;e beter he may fynde:</L>
<L>So ferde he in his &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>For euer &thorn;e furror &thorn;at he souht</L>
<L>&THORN;e saddor grount and fruit he fond &mdash;</L>
<L N="1090">His bokes witnessen, itake an hond.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore nou his sentence<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Firmam soliditatem:) Hieronymus ibidem: "Ejus omnes sententiae fidei et ecclesiae et omnium virtutum firmae sunt columnae".</NOTE></L>
<L>Is of stable credence</L>
<L>And piler, as seint Jerom sei&thorn;,</L>
<L>Of holy churche and of &thorn;e fei&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1095">HOse of him tok hede o&thorn;ur cure,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Elegantem venustatem (sc. habet doctrina; im engl. missverstanden): Augustinus (in libro de nuptiis et con|tractibus: "Pelagius haeresiarcha sic laudat Ambrosium, ut dicat:) beatus Ambrosius episcopus in cuius praecipue libris romana lucet fides, qui scriptores inter lati|nos (!) flos quidam emicuit". (et subdit Augustinus:) "cuius fidem et purissimum in scripturis sensum ne inimicus quidem ausus est reprehendere".</NOTE></L>
<L>He was of comely stature,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto of so gret wit</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Austin comende&thorn; hit</L>
<L>And sei&thorn;: &thorn;at &thorn;e fei&thorn; of Rome</L>
<L N="1100">Of seint Ambroses bokus come,</L>
<L>And of al translatours in to latyn</L>
<L>He was flour enditour fyn;</L>
<L>He was so fei&thorn;ful and pure of wit</L>
<L>&THORN;at an enemy miht not repreyne hit.</L>
<L N="1105">He was of such auctorite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Magnam aucto|ritatem, quia antiqui scriptores (sicut Augustinus) verba sua pro magna auctoritate habebant;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at olde doctours wolden, parde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his ensaumples for his sake</L>
<L>For gret auctorite was take.</L>
<L>Seint Austin tolde to Januarie<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Jannarie.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">unde refert Augustinus ad Januarium, quod, cum mater ejus mirata fuisset cur Mediolani sabbato non jejunaretur, et de hoc Augustinus Ambrosium in|terrogasset, ait Ambrosius: cum venio Romam, jejuno sabbato; sic et tu, ad quam forte ecclesiam veneris, ejus morem serva, si cuiquam non inde vis scandalum esse nec quemquam tibi. et subdit Augustinus: Ego de hac sententia etiam atque etiam cogitans, ita semper habui, tamquam coelesti oraculo acceperim.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1110">&THORN;e tale, &thorn;at i nul not in varie:</L>
<L>&THORN;at his modur hedde gret wondring</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at men vsud no fastyng</L>
<L>At Melan on &thorn;e saterday &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was no&thorn;ing &thorn;e Romaynes lay &mdash;;</L>
<L N="1115">&THORN;erfore Austyn asked Ambrose</L>
<L>&THORN;er of what was &thorn;e purpose.</L>
<L>He onswerde wi&thorn; good dome</L>
<L>And seide: "whon i come at Rome,</L>
<L>I kepe &thorn;e maner of &thorn;at fay
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="26"></L>
<L N="1120">And &thorn;enne i faste &thorn;e saturday.</L>
<L>To what churche so euer &thorn;ou cum,</L>
<L>&THORN;er of kep &thorn;ou &thorn;e custum,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou nult desclaundred beo</L>
<L>Ne o&thorn;ur men for loue of &thorn;e".</L>
<L N="1125">Seint Austin seide &thorn;at sentence</L>
<L>He hedde in as gret reuerence</L>
<L>And euer hit to haue in mende</L>
<L>As from heuene hit God hed sende. &mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is lyf is &thorn;er no more.</L>
<L N="1130">God &yogh;if vs grace to beo not lore!</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="life">
<HEAD>3. De quadam virgine in Antiochia.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">3) Das Orig. s. Leg. Aur. cap. 62 (in der Edit. princ. fehlt diese Legende): De vir|gine quadam Antiochena. Der im engl. nach V. 181 stehende weitere Titel: Que|dam virgo inuite in lupanari posita seruavit pudicitiam, geh&ouml;rt ders. Erz&auml;hlung an und ist ganz &uuml;berfl&uuml;ssig.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Antioche, as men han sayde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vgl. L. A.: Virgo quaedam fuit Antiochiae, cujus hystoriam Ambrosius in II libro de virgmibus recitat in haec verba (4 Zus., ebenso 10):</NOTE></L>
<L>Dwellede sum tyme a mayde</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a wommon of god fame &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bok telle&thorn; not hire name,</L>
<L N="5">But seint Ambrose, hose lust to lok,</L>
<L>In his secunde bok</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made of maydens clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e storie of hire al bidene</L>
<L>Telle&thorn; vs on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L N="10">Herkne&thorn; now, and &yogh;e mowe here!</L>
<L>At Antioche in &thorn;at cuntre<NOTE PLACE="foot2">An|tiochiae nuper virgo quaedam fuit, fugitans publici visus ostentationem.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er was a mayden feir and fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire peyned wi&thorn; al hire mihtes</L>
<L>To holde hire out of comun sihtes;</L>
<L N="15">Fleo heo wolde and huide hire &thorn;en,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo neore not ise&yogh;en of men.</L>
<L>But &thorn;e more &thorn;at heo hire hud,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed quo magis vitabat oculos, incendebat affectus eo amplius impudicos.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more men coueytud</L>
<L>Hire feirnes forte se.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;er of hedde heo no deynte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Puichritudo enim audita et non visa plus desideratur duobus stimulis cupiditatum: amoris et cognitionis, dum et nihil occurrit quod minus placeat, et plus putatur esse quod placeat; quod non index oculus explorat, sed animus amator exoptat (engl. f&uuml;hrt freier aus).</NOTE></L>
<L>For feirnes iherd and not seyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e more disired is, certeyn,</L>
<L>A mon is stured on &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; twey kene prikkes of couetise:</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;e ton is loue wi&thorn;oute doyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;ur is knowyng of &thorn;at &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is: whon mon loue&thorn; hotly</L>
<L>And ne ha&thorn; not his purpos fully,</L>
<L>And luytel plesed &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;at beo he,</L>
<L N="30">Wel more plesaunce he wene&thorn; &thorn;er be;</L>
<L>&THORN;e e&yogh;e &yogh;iue&thorn; not &thorn;e juggement,</L>
<L>Bote wel disire&thorn; to parfourne his talent:</L>
<L>So wilful loue wene&thorn; he se</L>
<L>Of whom he &thorn;enke&thorn; al &thorn;e beute,</L>
<L N="35">Al &thorn;ouh &thorn;e e&yogh;e seo hit nouht,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e knowyng &thorn;en is in &thorn;e &thorn;ouht;</L>
<L>In hope &thorn;erfore is heore lykyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; e&yogh;e to seo &thorn;e same &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Forte cese such hopyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Itaque sancta virgo, ne diutius alereturpotiendae spes cupiditatis, integritatem pudoris professa sic restrinxit improborum facies, ut jam non amaretur sed proderetur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;is mayden made auouwyng</L>
<L>Of chastete and clannes</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto let hire self profes &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo dude men to restreyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire louede al in veyne,</L>
<L N="45">For &thorn;ei schulde loue hire no more,</L>
<L>But let hire passe as &thorn;ing forlore.</L>
<L>Nou gode men of deuocion<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ecce persecutio.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mow here of persecucion.
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>&THORN;is mayde &thorn;at coude not fleo away,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Puella, fugere nescia, aetate pavida ne incideret in insidiatores pudoris, animam ad virtutem paravit, tam religiosa ut mortem non timeret, tam pudica ut mortem ex|spectaret.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">In drede liuede day by day</L>
<L>Leste heo hed fallen among hire fon</L>
<L>&THORN;at al wey spyed hire vppon;</L>
<L>Heo grei&thorn;ed hir wil of good clannes</L>
<L>To vertuwes and parfytnes;</L>
<L N="55">Heo was so religious &thorn;at heo ne dredde</L>
<L>Ne de&thorn; of mon wi&thorn; knyf ne bedde,</L>
<L>Heo was also &thorn;erto so clene</L>
<L>&THORN;at de&thorn; heo bod, wi&thorn;outen wene,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Venit enim coronae dies, maxima omnium exspectatio; producitur puella duplex professa certamen, castitatis et religionis (70-1 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Atte vche mon aboute al way.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Hier fehlt ein Vers im Ms., etwa: &thorn;o &thorn;at icomen was &thorn;e day.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at heo schulde for deuocioun</L>
<L>Of martirdom take &thorn;e croun,</L>
<L>Tofore hem &thorn;at hire loued had</L>
<L>Heo was brouht and for&thorn; ilad.</L>
<L>&THORN;en bihoued hire, certeyn,</L>
<L N="65">Stifly stonde in batayles tweyn:</L>
<L>Forte kepe wi&thorn; charite</L>
<L>&THORN;e religiun, and &thorn;e chastite</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo hedde ymad a vow to<NOTE PLACE="foot1">to statt &thorn;o?</NOTE></L>
<L>Forte kepe euere mo.</L>
<L N="70">Heo was &thorn;rat forte beo ded,</L>
<L>But heo wolde do aftur sum red.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei se&yogh;en hire deuociun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed ubi viderunt con|stantiam professionis, metam (? der Dichter las metum) pudoris, paratam ad cruciatus, erubescentem ad adspectus, excogitare coeperunt quemadmodum spem castitatis, reli|gionem, tollerent, (ut, cum id abstulissent quod erat amplius, etiam id eriperent quod de|relinqueretur).</NOTE></L>
<L>And constaunce of perfecciun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heo was schomeful, and not bolde,</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at men hire schulde biholde,</L>
<L>And for drede to leose hire clannes</L>
<L>Was redi wi&thorn; al mekenes</L>
<L>Forte suffre al &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei casten to don hire &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="80">For &thorn;ei parceyued hire deuociun</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo hedde, &thorn;at hire religiun</L>
<L>Wolde kepe hire chastite</L>
<L>And make men heore loue to fle:</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;ei caste alle wi&thorn; felenye</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at hope &thorn;ei mihte distruye:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Aut sacrificare virginem aut lupanari prostitui jubetur. (Quomodo colunt Deos suos qui sic vindicant, aut quemadmodum ipsi vivunt qui ita judicant?)</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur to make hire do sacrefyse</L>
<L>To false goddus on heor wyse,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles &thorn;ei casten, as fendes fel,</L>
<L N="90">To puyten hire to &thorn;e bordel.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Haec puella (non quod de religione ambigeret, sed quod de pudore trepidaret,) ipsa secum inquit: "Quid agimus hodie? aut martir aut virgo, altera nobis invidetur corona.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at heo vndurstod &thorn;is,</L>
<L>To hire self heo seide iwis:</L>
<L>"A lord God, what do we now?</L>
<L>For &thorn;at i wole kepe my vow,</L>
<L N="95">To day martir moste i be,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur kepe my maidenhod, parde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed nec virginis nomen agnoscitur ubi virginitatis auctor negatur; nam quemadmo|dum virgo, si meretricem colas, quemadmodum virgo, si adulterum diligas, quemad|modum virgo, si amorem petas? (!)</NOTE></L>
<L>I wot riht wel, &thorn;e to coroun</L>
<L>I schal take wi&thorn; deuocioun,</L>
<L>Bote heo nis not wor&thorn;i bere maidens name</L>
<L>&THORN;at forsake&thorn; &thorn;e lord of &thorn;at fame;</L>
<L N="100">Hou schulde heo beo mayden holde</L>
<L>&THORN;at hordom herie&thorn; wi&thorn; herte bolde?</L>
<L>Or hou schulde mayden bi holden heer</L>
<L>To caste hire loue to avouter?</L>
<L>Or hou schulde heo be mayden</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;at disire&thorn; loue of men?</L>
<L>Hit is more betur beo mayden of &thorn;ouht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tolerabilius est mentem virginem quam carnem habere; utrumque bonum, si liceat, et si non liceat saltem non homini castae sed Deo simus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en of &thorn;e flesch &thorn;at serue&thorn; of nouht.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e beo goode whose moote</L>
<L>From er&thorn;ly streng&thorn;e kepe hire cote;</L>
<L N="110">And, &yogh;if we mou not for such power</L>
<L>Kepe vr flesch clene her,</L>
<L>To vr God &thorn;at is so good</L>
<L>Kepe vs chast in &thorn;ouht and mood &mdash;
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>For of &thorn;e wil he take&thorn; hede,</L>
<L N="115">Whon he schal quite a monnes mede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bible bere&thorn; witnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et Raab meretrix fuit, sed postquam domino credidit, salutem invenit;</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a wommon of vnclennesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at tyme was Raab iclept,</L>
<L>But aftur &thorn;at heo for hir sunnes wept</L>
<L N="120">And in God hedde good bileue,</L>
<L>And God hele hire sone had &yogh;eue.</L>
<L>And also &thorn;e byble witnesse&thorn; hit:</L>
<L>&THORN;e noble wommon Judit,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et Judith se, ut adultero placeret, ornavit, quae tamen quia hoc religione, non amore, faciebat, nemo eam adulteram judicabat. (130 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Forte plese an auouter,</L>
<L N="125">Made hire gay and liht of cher;</L>
<L>For heo dude &thorn;at not for loue</L>
<L>Ne for no displesyng of God aboue,</L>
<L>&THORN;er wente no mon bi &thorn;e wey</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo avouteres was wolde sey".</L>
<L N="130">And &thorn;en heo seide: "beo my hode,</L>
<L>Nou ben &thorn;ese ensaumples goode:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bene successit exemplum, nam, si illa, quae se commisit religioni, et pudorem servavit et patriam, fortassis et nos servando religionem servabimus etiam castitatem;</NOTE></L>
<L>For, &yogh;if Judit dude &thorn;at for religiun</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; good deuociun</L>
<L>Kept hir clannes and hire cuntre,</L>
<L N="135">In hap hit may falle so by me:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if i kepe my religiun wel,</L>
<L>I may me kepe chast eueridel.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;it, heo seide, i seo more:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quodsi Judith pudicitiam religioni praeferre voluisset, perdita prima etiam pudicitiam perdidisset".</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if Judit hedde iput bifore</L>
<L N="140">Clannes ra&thorn;er &thorn;en religioun,</L>
<L>Par auntre heo hedde ifallen doun</L>
<L>And lost cuntrei and clannes</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e name of goodnes".</L>
<L>&THORN;e wordus in herte heo heold wel</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;at crist seide in &thorn;e gospel:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Itaque talibus informata exemplis silenter animo tenens verba domini, quibus ait: "Quicunque perdiderit animam suam propter me, inveniet eam", flevit et tacuit, ne eam vel loquentem adulter audiret, nec pudoris elegit injuriam sed Christi recusavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who so leose&thorn; his lyf for me</L>
<L>He schal hit fynde a&yogh;ein, parde.</L>
<L>Whon heo &thorn;us hedde i&thorn;ouht and seid,</L>
<L>Wondurliche heo abreyd</L>
<L N="150">And wepte sore and heold hire pes,</L>
<L>Lest eny auouter hed herd hire res;</L>
<L>Ne heo chese nou&yogh;t of hire clannes</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrong, but refused wi&thorn; mekenes</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrong don to Crist of miht,</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;at lord is of alle riht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Ambrose bit us take nou hed<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. non.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Aestimate utrum adulterare potuerit corpore quae nec voce adulteravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wommon maydenhed:</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er hir bodi miht do auoutrie,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hit weore constreyned be maistrie,</L>
<L N="160">Whos vois to lecherie nolde assent,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh &thorn;e bodi schulde beo torent.</L>
<L>Sum tyme mi resun aschomed was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Jamdudum verecundabatur oratio mea et quasi adire gestorum seriem crimino|sam atque explanare formidat. Claudite aures, virgines Dei! ducitur puella Dei ad lupanar; sed aperite aures, virgines Dei! virgo prostitui potest, adulterari non potest; ubicunque dei virgo est, templum Dei est, nec lupanaria infamant castitatem, sed castitas etiam loci abolet infamiam (engl. bezieht loci falsch).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ambrose sei&thorn;, to here &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>Or of &thorn;e orible doing</L>
<L N="165">To schewe ouht in seying;</L>
<L>But alle &yogh;e Godus maidenes clene,</L>
<L>Schutte&thorn; &yogh;or eres al bidene!</L>
<L>For &thorn;enne &thorn;is mayden &mdash; &thorn;at was del!&mdash;</L>
<L>Lad heo was to &thorn;e bordel.</L>
<L N="170">Bot, &thorn;auh &yogh;or e&yogh;en renne on teres,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it, maidenes, opene&thorn; &yogh;or eres</L>
<L>And vndurstonde&thorn;: sikerli,</L>
<L>A maiden wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e may beo le&yogh;e bi,</L>
<L>But a&yogh;eines hir wil such vilenye</L>
<L N="175">Schal beo told for non avoutrye;</L>
<L>For wher so euere Godus maiden is,</L>
<L>&THORN;er Godus temple is, iwis,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e bordel place, parde,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>Defame&thorn; no&thorn;ing chastite,</L>
<L N="180">But chaste place is of god name</L>
<L>And do&thorn; awey al vuel fame.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hier hat der engl. Text eine &uuml;berfl&uuml;ssige Ueberschrift: Quedam virgo inuite in lupanari posita seruauit pudicitiam.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOu, &yogh;e maidens, alle and sum,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Ingens petulantium concursus fit ad for|nicem). Discite martiris miracula sanctae virginis (!), discite locorum vocabula, clau|ditur intus columba, strepunt accipitres foris, certant singuli quis praedam primus invadat (190&mdash;3 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Lerne&thorn; &thorn;e miracles of martirdom,</L>
<L>Lerne&thorn; also wi&thorn; liht faces</L>
<L N="185">&THORN;e nomes of such maner places!</L>
<L>In hous is schut a coluere meke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sparhaukes wi&thorn;outen heor preies seke,</L>
<L>Vche wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur striue&thorn;, par fey,</L>
<L>Whuch schal furst take &thorn;at prey.&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. wey st. prey.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">&THORN;us Ambrose sei&thorn; beo &thorn;at maiden</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;ulke lecherous men</L>
<L>&THORN;at lykyng of hire wolden haue had,</L>
<L>Aftur to bordel &thorn;at heo was lad.&mdash;</L>
<L>But whon heo was comen in to &thorn;at hous,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At illa manibus ad coelum levatis quasi ad domum ora|tionis venisset, non ad libidinis deversorium (engl. anders):</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">A heef vp hire hondes glorious,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">A = heo.</NOTE></L>
<L>As to an hous of good preyere</L>
<L>Heo hedde icomen, masse to here&mdash;</L>
<L>Heo heold hit non hous of lecherie,</L>
<L>But ra&thorn;ur a feir diuersorie,&mdash;</L>
<L N="200">And &thorn;enne heo seide wi&thorn; mylde mood:</L>
<L>"Crist, &thorn;at art bo&thorn;e mon and God,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">"Christe, inquit, domuisti virgini (! engl. las virgis) feros leones: potes domare etiam hominum feras mentes; Chaldaeis roravit (!) ignis, Judaeis sese unda suspendit misericordia tua, non natura sua, Susanna ad supplicium genua flexit et de adulteris triumphavit, aruit dextra quae templi tui dona violabat:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hast ichasted lyouns feer</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;erdes in eor&thorn;e heer,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mai&yogh;t chaste at &thorn;i willyng</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e woode &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of men liuing,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Caldeyes &thorn;e fuir a&yogh;ein rauht,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e Jewes &thorn;i merci was hauht,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e watur drouh bihynde,</L>
<L>Huld vp also not of his owne kynde;</L>
<L N="210">Susanne at hire torment</L>
<L>kneled to &thorn;e wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L>And of hem hed heo maistrie</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde ha wrouht wi&thorn; hire auoutrie;</L>
<L>&THORN;e riht hond also, sikerlye,</L>
<L N="215">Of him weorned and wox al drie</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde defouled wi&thorn; vn&thorn;riftes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i temple &thorn;e feire &yogh;iftus:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;i feire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou &thorn;at same temple &thorn;at is &thorn;yne<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nunc templum ipsum attrectatur tuum, ne patiaris incestum sacrilegii, qui non passus es furtum (220 erkl. Zus.)! benedicatur et nomen tuum, ut quae ad adulterium virgo veni virgo discedam".</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei ben aboute to foule and tyne:</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at is my bodi, I vndurstonde.</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;ou take me in to &thorn;yn honde,</L>
<L>Ne suffre no mon, mest ne leste,</L>
<L>Of sacrilege to do inceste</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; me, as &thorn;ou art al weldyng</L>
<L N="225">And hast not suffred stelyng!</L>
<L>Nou, lord, iblessed beo &thorn;i nome,</L>
<L>And euer more kep me from schome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I to auoutrie am icome,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Das Relat. ist ausgelassen nach J.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mayde mowe passe hol and sume!"</L>
<L N="230">Vnne&thorn;e heo hedde an ende ymad<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vix compleverat orationem et ecce miles specie terribilis i1rupit &mdash; quemadmodum virgo tremuit, (cui populus tremens cessit)!</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at preyere &thorn;at heo bad,</L>
<L>&THORN;er com in to hire wi&thorn; good spede</L>
<L>A mon array&yogh;ed as kniht in wede,</L>
<L>A muche mon and a grim.</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;is maiden, whon heo lokud on him,</L>
<L>Heo was aferd sumwhat &thorn;on</L>
<L>To ben al one wi&thorn; such a mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;en com &thorn;at lessun to hire mende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed illa non immemor lectionis, "Et Daniel, in|quit, supplicium Susannae spectaturus advenerat et quam populus damnaverat unus absolvit: potest et in hoc lupi habitu ovis latere; habet et Christus milites suos, qui etiam legiones habet;</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Susanne, &thorn;at wommon hende,</L>
<L N="240">And &thorn;enne heo seide softly sum del:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e innocent child Daniel</L>
<L>Com to abyde &thorn;e passiun</L>
<L>Of Susanne wi&thorn; discreciun,
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>And, &thorn;auh &thorn;e peple hire dampned had,</L>
<L N="245">He alone wi&thorn; vois ful sad</L>
<L>Asoiled hire fro &thorn;at dampnyng</L>
<L>And demed &thorn;e juges to dy&yogh;ing.</L>
<L>Hit may bifalle, heo seide, parde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vndur wolues clo&thorn;ing a schep &thorn;er be.</L>
<L N="250">Vr lord Crist ha&thorn; his knihtes</L>
<L>And also legiouns of gret mihtes."</L>
<L>And to hir self &yogh;it heo gon say:</L>
<L>"A smiter &yogh;if &thorn;er beo to day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">aut fortasse percussor intravit: ne verearis, anima! et tales solent martires facere".</NOTE></L>
<L>Me to sle, nou icomen in,</L>
<L N="255">Wi&thorn; eny streng&thorn;e or elles gin,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; staf or ston o&thorn;ur elles swerd,</L>
<L>Mi goode soule, beo not aferd!</L>
<L>For suche men for Godus sake</L>
<L>Ben wont martires for to make!"</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;e fei&thorn; of &thorn;is mayden<NOTE PLACE="foot2">O virgo, fides tua te salvam fecit (262&mdash;3 Zus.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Saued hire from wikked men&mdash;</L>
<L>As I schal nou&thorn;e &yogh;ou tel,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wole herken me wel.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e kniht "suster", he seid,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui miles: "Quaeso ne paveas, soror! huc veni salvare animam, non per|dere(!); serva me, ut ipsa serveris!</NOTE></L>
<L N="265">"Beo not aferd ne abreid!</L>
<L>As a bro&thorn;ur I am come,</L>
<L>Mi soule to saue atte day of dome.</L>
<L>Kep &thorn;ou me, and i schal &thorn;e,</L>
<L>I preye &thorn;e for charite!</L>
<L N="270">I com hider as avouter:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quasi adulter ingressus, si vis, martir egrediar. Vestimenta mutemus, conveniunt mea tibi et tua mihi, sed utraque Christo; tua vestis me verum militem faciet et mea te virginem;</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt, i schal go out marter.</L>
<L>Chaunge we nou vre clo&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>For hit wole beo wel semyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i clo&thorn;ing beo don on me,</L>
<L N="275">And also myne vppon &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For, so&thorn; to seye, &thorn;is is my list</L>
<L>&THORN;at bo&thorn;e two we seruen Crist.</L>
<L>&THORN;i clo&thorn;ing schal make me verrey kniht,</L>
<L>And my clo&thorn;ing &thorn;e maiden briht.</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;ou schalt be clo&thorn;ud swi&thorn;e wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bene tu vestieris, ego melius exuar ut me persecutor agnoscat.</NOTE></L>
<L>But i moste beo spoyled eueridel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;at pursuwe&thorn; so harde &thorn;e</L>
<L>Mowe riht wel knowe me.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sume habitum qui abscondat feminam, trade qui consecret martirem! indue chlamydem quae occultet membra virginis et servet pudorem, sume pileum qui tegat crines, abscondat ora: solent erubescere qui lupanar intraverunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tac &thorn;ou nou my clo&thorn;ing on</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;at wel wol huyde a wommon,</L>
<L>And tak me &thorn;yne anon riht her:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei mowe me halewe a marter.</L>
<L>Do on my mantel &thorn;at is so syde,</L>
<L>A maidenes membres &thorn;at wol hyde;</L>
<L N="290">Set myn hat vppon &thorn;yn hed,</L>
<L>To huide &thorn;in her and eke &thorn;i sched,</L>
<L>Hit wole also schadewe &thorn;i faas,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt go for&thorn; &thorn;i paas:</L>
<L>Aschomed, forso&thorn;e, woned &thorn;ei ben</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at in to bordel entren.</L>
<L>Wayte wel, whon &thorn;ou art gon oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sane cum egressa fueris, ne respicias retro, memor uxoris Loth, quae naturam suam, quia impudicos licet castis oculis adspexit, amisit (304&mdash;5 Zus.); nec vereare(!), ne quid pereat sacrificio (310&mdash;2 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke not a&yogh;ein, for no doute:</L>
<L>Of Lothus wyf loke &thorn;ou haue mynde,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at heo lost hire ownekynde,</L>
<L N="300">For heo loked hire bihynde</L>
<L>On hem &thorn;at to God weoren vnkynde;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ouh hir oune e&yogh;en weren clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo biheold, wi&thorn;outen wene,</L>
<L>Was vnclene &mdash; &thorn;erfore &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="305">Distruy&yogh;ed was &thorn;orwh Godus grace.</L>
<L>To no mon loke &thorn;ou verreyed beo</L>
<L>Who &thorn;at &thorn;ou art, whom euer &thorn;ou seo,</L>
<L>For hit mihte falle on &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Sumwhat to perissche of vr sacrefyse"&mdash;</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at forso&thorn;e to hire seide he</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for hire wolde martired be;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to hire he seide: "&thorn;ou trist,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ego pro te hostiam Deo meo reddam, tu pro me militem Christo, habens bonam militiam castitatis quae stipendiis militat sempiternis, loricam justitiae quae spirituali munimine corpus in|duat, scutum fidei quo vulnus repellas, galeam salutis.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e i schal me offre to Crist.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>And loke &thorn;erfore bo&thorn;e day and niht</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;at for me &thorn;ou beo good kniht</L>
<L>To Crist, &thorn;at wi&thorn; good chiualri</L>
<L>Clannes &thorn;ou kepe and beo holi</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ilke same huyre</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;outen ende schal duyre.</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e habergoun of rihtwysnes</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou haue wi&thorn; meknes&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at hit &thorn;i bodi close,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt not flecche from &thorn;i purpose,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;at st. &thorn;ou.</NOTE></L>
<L>But specialiche of &thorn;i bodi</L>
<L N="325">Hit wol beo keper from vileny.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou haue &thorn;e scheld of fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>For, as &thorn;e holy bok sei&thorn;,</L>
<L>Sinful woundes &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn;stonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hit take wel for&thorn; on honde.</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e helm of hel&thorn;e also &thorn;ou take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol &thorn;e saue from eueri wrake.</L>
<L>&THORN;er vre defence is, iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ibi enim est praesidium nostrae salutis ubi est Christus, quoniam mulieris caput est vir, virginum Christus".</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er Jhesu Crist him seluen is:</L>
<L>A wommones hed is ay mon,</L>
<L N="335">But maidenes hed is Crist al on".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et inter hae verba chlamyden exuit, suspectus tamen adhuc habitus et per|secutoris et adulteri.</NOTE></L>
<L>Among &thorn;eos wordus &thorn;is ilke kniht</L>
<L>Dude of his mantel in hire siht,</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles in her ei&yogh;e &thorn;er</L>
<L>Sumwhat semed of auouter</L>
<L N="340">And eke of an enemy,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clo&thorn;ing suspecte was, pardi.</L>
<L>Hire hed &thorn;auh adoun heo bent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Virgo cervicem, chlamydem coepit miles offerre.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e kniht wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bli&thorn;e cher and hi&yogh;ing fast</L>
<L N="345">His mantel on hire hedde icast.</L>
<L>Wondur couplyng in such a place<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae pompa illa, quae gratia, cum in lupanari de martirio certarent. Addantur personae miles et virgo, hae dissimiles inter se natura &mdash; sed Dei misericordia consimiles, (ut compleatur oraculum: tunc lupi et agni simul pascentur:) ecce agna et lupus non solum simul pascentur sed etiam immolantur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er was bitwene bost and grace,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei in hous of hordom</L>
<L>Striuen so faste of martirdom.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="350">NOu to gedere beo &thorn;er tweyn,</L>
<L>A maiden and a kniht, certeyn;</L>
<L>Vnlicchi &thorn;ouh &thorn;ei ben of kuynde,</L>
<L>Lichchi inouh in &thorn;ouht and mynde;</L>
<L>Nou ben ifed to geder wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L N="355">A wolf, a lomb in o pastour,</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t onliche to gedere so,</L>
<L>Bote to God offred bo&thorn;e two.</L>
<L>Whon heo hed chaunged hire clo&thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Quid plura?) Mutato habitu evo|lat puella de laqueo: jam non suis alis, utpote quae spiritualibus ferebatur &mdash; et, quod nulla unquam viderunt saecula, egreditur de lupanari virgo Christi.</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn; heo wente wi&thorn; gret hi&yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="360">Out of &thorn;at hous, as brid fro gren,</L>
<L>Heo fleih awei and scaped &thorn;en:</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh Godus grace heo was bore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; spirituel whinges, and nou&yogh;t ilore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was neuer sei&yogh;en but &thorn;at day:</L>
<L N="365">A maiden from bordel plas gon away;</L>
<L>But heo was Cristes maiden iwis</L>
<L>&THORN;at kepte hire and alle his.</L>
<L>&THORN;e rauinoures &thorn;at hire abiden<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At illi qui videbant oculis et non videbant corde (engl. anders) (ceu raptores ad agnam lupi fremuere ad praedam).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne se&yogh;en hire nout; &thorn;en in &thorn;ei slyden,</L>
<L N="370">For &thorn;ei wenden swi&thorn;e wel</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden ha founden in &thorn;e bordel.</L>
<L>On entrede faste wi&thorn; gret hei&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unus, qui erat immodestior, introivit; sed ubi hausit oculis rei textum, "Quid hoc, inquit, est? puella ingressa est, sed vir videtur. Ecce non fabulosum illud: cerva pro virgine, sed quod verum est: miles ex virgine.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e moste schrewe of &thorn;e cumpaignie.</L>
<L>Whon he sauh &thorn;er &thorn;e kniht sittyng</L>
<L N="375">In a maydens clo&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"A ha", he seide, "what is &thorn;is gyn?</L>
<L>A mayden, forso&thorn;e, wente her in,</L>
<L>But now, forso&thorn;e, as i seo con,
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>&YOGH;onde sitte&thorn; a verrei mon.</L>
<L N="380">Nou is seo so&thorn; as men han sayde:</L>
<L>Lo heer an herte for a maide,</L>
<L>Hit is so&thorn;, as to my siht:</L>
<L>Of a mayden we haue a kniht.</L>
<L>I haue ofte herd men seye a clatur<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At etiam audieram, et non credideram, quod aquas Christus in vina convertit; jam mutare coepit sexum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="385">&THORN;at in to wyn Crist torned &thorn;e watur,</L>
<L>And nou he leue&thorn; not beohynde</L>
<L>For to chaunge monnes kynde.</L>
<L>Go we heonne, for &yogh;it we ben<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Recedamus hinc, dum adhuc quod fuimus sumus; numquid et ipse mutatus sum qui aliud cerno quam credo?</NOTE></L>
<L>As we weren-hit is wel sen.</L>
<L N="390">Whe&thorn;er i beo chaunged, nou i meue,</L>
<L>On forte seo, ano&thorn;ur to leeue?</L>
<L>Whon i com to &thorn;e bordel sted,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad lupanar veni: cerno vadimonium: et tamen dum mutatur(!), egrediar: pudicus exibo qui adulter in|travi. Iudicio rei, quia debebatur tanto corona victori, damnatus est pro virgine qui pro virgine comprehensus est (der engl. Dichter macht auch den Anderen zum M&auml;r|tirer, vgl. 399).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er me &thorn;inke&thorn; i seo a wed</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at was ido,</L>
<L N="395">And i my self am chaunged also:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is hous chast schal i go,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as avouter com in wel &thorn;ro".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel aftur, certeyn,</L>
<L>For Godus loue &thorn;at mon was slayn.</L>
<L N="400">And riht also was &thorn;e kniht.</L>
<L>But &thorn;at was a wondur siht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ita de lupanari non solum virgines sed etiam martires exierunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at out of &thorn;e bordel schulde take &thorn;e wey</L>
<L>A mayden clene and martires twey.</L>
<L>Hit is told &thorn;at, whon &thorn;is kniht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fertur puella ad locum supplicii cucurrisse, certasse ambos de nece (408-12 nicht im lat.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">Touward his juwyse was idiht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maiden to &thorn;at place ron</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; him &thorn;us striue bigon:</L>
<L>"Wenestou, heo seide, &thorn;at &thorn;ou for me</L>
<L>Schalt take &thorn;e juwyse and ded be,</L>
<L N="410">And i so schulde leose my mede</L>
<L>&THORN;at i schulde haue for martirhede?"</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e kniht seide: "certeyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ille diceret: "Ego sum jussus occidi, te absolvit sententia, quon|iam me tenuit", at illa clamavit: "Non ego te vadem mortis elegi, sed praesidem pudoris optavi; si pudor quaeritur, manet sexus: si sanguis exponitur, fidejussorem non desi|dero! unde dissolvam habeo, in me lata est sententia quae pro me lata est.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am sent hider to beo slayn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sentence, mayden, asoyle&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="415">Whon &thorn;at hit passe&thorn; on me".</L>
<L>&THORN;en heo cried and seide: "nay, nay,</L>
<L>I ches &thorn;e not my wed to lay</L>
<L>For my de&thorn;, but i &thorn;e ches</L>
<L>To beo pris of my clannes;</L>
<L N="420">For &thorn;auh my clanhed beo isouht,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it my kuynde chaunge&thorn; nouht;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at men asken my blood,</L>
<L>I nul hit not borewen, beo &thorn;e rod!</L>
<L>For i haue &thorn;is ilke day</L>
<L N="425">Wher of my self forte pay.</L>
<L>In me &thorn;is sentence is &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>For me hit is &thorn;at i not liue.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Certe si pecuniae te fidejussorem dedissem et, absente me, judex tuum censum foeneratori adjudicasset, eadem me sententia convinceres meo patrimonio solvere tuos nexus; si recusarem, quis me indignam morte censeret? quanto major est capitis hujus censura?</NOTE></L>
<L>Herken hou i schal hit schawe</L>
<L>Bi good proces of &thorn;e lawe:</L>
<L N="430">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou heddest for mypreyere</L>
<L>Mi borwh bicomen for money here</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at for myn absence</L>
<L>&THORN;e juge hedde &yogh;iuen such a sentense</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou to him schuldust make &thorn;e pay</L>
<L N="435">Of whom i borwed &thorn;e monay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same sentence condempne schuld me</L>
<L>To paye to &thorn;e &thorn;at ilke mone</L>
<L>Of myn oune heritage,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at i were of ful age;</L>
<L N="440">&YOGH;if i refused &thorn;at to pay,</L>
<L>Who is &thorn;at, &thorn;at nolde say</L>
<L>&THORN;at I nere wor&thorn;i to beo dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at so vnkuyndely quit &thorn;i mede?</L>
<L>Nou &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t seo &thorn;e same skile</L>
<L N="445">In &thorn;is doyng, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou wile.
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>Nou wol I wi&thorn; good entent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Moriar innocens ne moriar nocens; nihil medium est hodie: aut rea ero san|guinis tui aut martir mei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ur dye an innocent</L>
<L>&THORN;en liuen a while and lete &thorn;e dye</L>
<L>And leose so innocencie;</L>
<L N="450">To day for me schal go no mene &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at, forso&thorn;e, &thorn;ou schalt wel sene:</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur i schal beo gulti of &thorn;i blood</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur martir beo wi&thorn; mylde mood.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I beo sone comen a&yogh;ein hom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Si cito redii, quis me audeat excludere? si moram feci, quis me audeat absolvere?</NOTE></L>
<L N="455">Who is so hardi holde me &thorn;er from?</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at I haue dwelled to longe,</L>
<L>Me to asoyle ho dar vndurfonge?</L>
<L>I haue agulted more to &thorn;e lauh,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">plus legibus debeo, rea non solum fugae meae sed etiam caedis alienae.</NOTE></L>
<L>For out of prisun &thorn;at i flauh,</L>
<L N="460">And I am gulti, &thorn;ow wost, also</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e to &thorn;ur monnes de&thorn; &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&THORN;at in to prisun tok &thorn;e way</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore was slayen &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>I &thorn;e telle wi&thorn; open bre&thorn;:</L>
<L N="465">Mi membres suffisen to &thorn;e de&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sufficiunt membra morti quae non sufficiebant inju|riae; est in virgine vulneri locus qui non erat contumeliae: ego opprobrium declinavi, non martirium; tibi cessi vestem, non professionem mutavi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche, forso&thorn;e, nou&yogh;t gon longe,</L>
<L>Weore not sufficient to &thorn;e wronge.</L>
<L>A maiden ha&thorn; on hire bodi</L>
<L>Place, woundes on to suffri,</L>
<L N="470">To whom, leeue wel! hit is non ese</L>
<L>Ne no good, mon forte disese.</L>
<L>Sclaundre &thorn;auh &thorn;at i fled in &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde vp martirdom to &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t i nouht:</L>
<L>&THORN;auh I my clo&thorn;ing leide adoun,</L>
<L N="475">I chaunged not my professioun.</L>
<L>Tofore me to de&thorn; &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest go,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quodsi mihi praeripis mortem, non redemisti me sed circumvenisti.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast not bou&yogh;t me from wo,</L>
<L>And i may sei in herte &thorn;en sone:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast me gyled and vndurgone.</L>
<L N="480">Be war, be war, I preye nou &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cave quaeso, ne con|tendas, cave ne contradicere audeas! noli eripere beneficium quod dedisti, (dum mihi hanc sententiam negas, illam restituis superiorem: sententia enim sententia su|periore mutatur, si posterior me non tenet, superior sententia tenet).</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;einsei me not, strif not wi&thorn; me!</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me &yogh;af, &thorn;e benefice,</L>
<L>To take hit me fro, be not so nice!</L>
<L>We schul make good al vr biheste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Possumus utrique satisfacere sententiae(!), si me prius patiaris occidi; in te habent aliam quam exerceant poenam, (in virgine obnoxius pudor est).</NOTE></L>
<L N="485">To god, wi&thorn;outen eny cheste,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou me soffre now in certeyn</L>
<L>Furst ar &thorn;ou forte beo sleyn;</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur peyne vppon &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ei han icast to do, parde.</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;e more joyful &thorn;ou shalt beo,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Itaque gloriosior eris, si videaris de adultera martirem fecisse, quam de martire adulteram reddidisse."</NOTE></L>
<L>Of avouteres &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou seo</L>
<L>A martir &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast maad,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;er aftur &thorn;e more sad,</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;at &thorn;ou furst a martir were</L>
<L N="495">And lafte me aftur to avoutere".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;us hed striuen,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Quid exspectatis?) duo contenderunt et vicerunt: nec divisa est corona sed addita.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;e dom was i&yogh;iuen</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e forso&thorn;e weoren do to dede &mdash;</L>
<L>God &thorn;erfore ha&thorn; quit heore mede.</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;e biginnyng of &thorn;is martirdom<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ita|que sancti martires invicem sibi beneficia conferentes, altera principium martirio, dedit alter effectum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Furst of &thorn;at mayden com,</L>
<L>But &thorn;e kniht &thorn;e effecte folfuld,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he was furst iculd;</L>
<L>But, as God wolde for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L N="505">&THORN;ei toke heor coroune bo&thorn;e at ones.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000040.tif" N="34">
<HEAD>De duobus veris amicis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SUm tyme men reden &thorn;at &thorn;er was<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ff. im engl. mit eigenem Titel; das folg. ist aber nur der Schluss der Ge|schichte.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">At etiam philosophorum gymnasia Damonem et Synthiam Pythago|reosincolas(!) ferunt (510-1 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>In a cuntre, clept pittogoras,</L>
<L>Dwellynge &thorn;ere twey men,</L>
<L>Iclept Sithia and Climonen;</L>
<L N="510">To gedere &thorn;ei loued hem wondur wel</L>
<L>And frendes weoren at mur&thorn;e and mel.</L>
<L>A tiraunt &thorn;er was of wikked red,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quorum unus, cum esset morti adjudicatus, commendandorum suorum tempus poposcit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jugged &thorn;at on to ben ded.</L>
<L>Anon riht &thorn;en in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="515">He preyed &thorn;e tiraunt of sum space,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his good he mihte dispose</L>
<L>As he hedde cast in purpose.</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e tiraunt leeued &thorn;on<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tyrannus autem astutissimus, cum reperiri non posse existimaret, petivit ut sponsorem daret, qui pro se feriretur, si ipse moram faceret.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde ha founde no mon</L>
<L N="520">In &thorn;at caas his borwh haue be,</L>
<L>Anon riht graunted he,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a borwh he mihte fynde</L>
<L>In &thorn;at caas wolde him bynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Das Relat. ausgelassen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he ne come not at his day,</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e de&thorn; to take for him, in fay.</L>
<L>His felawe &thorn;enne his borwh bicom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Quid de duobus praeclarius, nescio; utrumque praeclarum:) alter vadem mortis invenit, alter se obtulit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e to&thorn;ur wente him hom.</L>
<L>&THORN;e day was come, he was ful longe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Itaque cum reus moram supplicio faceret, fidejussor sereno vultu mortem non recusavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>His borwh &thorn;e de&thorn; schulde vndurfonge.</L>
<L N="530">And as he was riht atte caas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum duceretur, amicus reversus est, cervicem substituit, colla subjecit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;ur com in to &thorn;e plaas,</L>
<L>His nekke for&thorn; he streihte ariht,</L>
<L>To saue his borwh, as he hedde hiht.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e tiraunt wondrede &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc admiratus tyrannus cario|rem philosophis amicitiam quam vitam fuisse, petivit ut ipse ab ipsis quos damnaverat in amicitiam reciperetur. Tantam virtutis esse gratiam (ut tyrannum inclinaret.) Digna laude, sed minora nostris:</NOTE></L>
<L N="535">&THORN;at &thorn;eose two men were more cheer</L>
<L>Of heore loue &thorn;en of heore lyue;</L>
<L>He preyed hem him to receyue</L>
<L>In to heore loue for euer more,</L>
<L>And he heore lyf hem graunted &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;is was grace of gret vertue,</L>
<L>Frendschipe to kui&thorn;e, to old and newe;</L>
<L>But &thorn;is was lasse wor&thorn;i of meed</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e knihtes and &thorn;e maiden ded:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke weren bo&thorn;e men,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nam illi ambo viri, hic una virgo, quae primo etiam sexum vinceret; illi amici, isti incogniti; illi tyranno uni se obtulerunt, isti tyrannis pluribus ac etiam crudelioribus: quod ille pepercit, isti occiderunt; (inter illos in uno obnoxia necessitas, in his amborum voluntas libera; hoc quoque isti pruden|tiores, quia) illis studii sui finis amicitiae gratia, istis corona martirii: illi enim cer|taverunt hominibus, isti domino. Haec Ambrosius.</NOTE></L>
<L N="545">&THORN;e &thorn;ride was a wommon clen</L>
<L>&THORN;at is more frele of kuynde</L>
<L>&THORN;en mon, as bokus maken muynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke were frendes of long tyme met,</L>
<L>&THORN;eos weoren vnknowen, and no steuene set;</L>
<L N="550">&THORN;ulke to on tiraunt hem &yogh;olde,</L>
<L>But &thorn;eose to moni on, stout and bolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren more cruel &thorn;en was he,</L>
<L>For he hem spared, &thorn;eose let hem sle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei for loue de&thorn; wolde haue nome,</L>
<L N="555">But &thorn;eose for &thorn;e croune of martirdome;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke hedden heore &thorn;onk tofore men,</L>
<L>But &thorn;eos tofore God glorious ben.</L>
<L>&THORN;is lyf endyted seint Ambrose</L>
<L>On latyn. tak hede to his purpose!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000041.tif" N="35">
<HEAD>4. De S. Theodora.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">4) S. Leg. Aur. cap. 92: de s. Theodora.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Alisaundrie, tel i ow con,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Theodora nobilis mulier et sponsa apud Alexandriam tempore Zenonis imperatoris virum habebat divitem et timentem Deum.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e emperours tyme Zenon</L>
<L>Dwelled a wommon &mdash; &thorn;e bok sei&thorn; swa &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at men called Theodora,</L>
<L N="5">A noble wommon and a feir,</L>
<L>And hire hedde iweddet a riche heir,</L>
<L>A semely mon and muri of mod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God dredde and dude muche good.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel, so ful of tricherie,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dyabolus autem, Theodorae invidens sanctitati, virum quendam divitem in illius concupiscentiam incitavit, qui eam crebris nuntiis et muneribus molestabat ut assen|sum sibi praeberet.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">To &thorn;is wommon hedde envye,</L>
<L>Tempted so a riche mon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he coueyted &thorn;is wommon.</L>
<L>Messagers &thorn;en he hire sent,</L>
<L>And &yogh;iftus, to haue hire assent.</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e messagers heo forsoke,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed illa nuntios respuebat et munera contemnebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his &yogh;iftus non heo toke.</L>
<L>He bisied him &thorn;ou&yogh; neuer&thorn;eles,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In tantum autem eam molestabat, quod ipsam quietem habere non permitteret et paene deficere videretur;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo mihte wel haue no pes,</L>
<L>And put him to &thorn;ou&yogh;t and trauayle,</L>
<L N="20">Til he bigon neihond to fayle.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">he st. heo?</NOTE></L>
<L>Atte laste ful wikkedliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tandem quandam magam ad eam misit, quae eam ut viri illius misereretur sibique consentiret plurimum hortabatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;at wommon he sent a wicche,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire to talke his entent</L>
<L>And forte maken hire assent.</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;e wicche wi&thorn; sotyl wordus &thorn;an</L>
<L>Bigon to talke to &thorn;is womman,</L>
<L>And hou &thorn;at heo scholde bere &thorn;e gult</L>
<L>For &thorn;at mon, &yogh;if he weore spilt.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode wyf seide: "for Godus ei&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae cum diceret se coram oculis Dei cuncta cernentis tam grande peccatum nunquam committere (engl. dir.), malefica adjunxit (33&mdash;4 Zus.):</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">I dar me not auntren, &thorn;ou&yogh; i schulde di&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; his e&yogh;en whateuer we do</L>
<L>Seo&thorn;, tyde and tyme, and euermo".</L>
<L>&THORN;e wicche &thorn;en &thorn;e fend was wors &mdash;</L>
<L>Alle suche haue Godus curs! &mdash;</L>
<L N="35">And seide: "al &thorn;at euere is don bi day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidquid in die fit, hoc utique Deus scit et videt, quidquid autem advesperascente et occidente sole committitur, Deus minime intuetur.</NOTE></L>
<L>God almihti seo wel may,</L>
<L>But, aftur &thorn;e sonne is for&thorn; gon,</L>
<L>He may seo no&thorn;ing what we don."</L>
<L>&THORN;en onswerd &thorn;e gode wyf:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dixitque puella maleficae: Numquid veritatem dicis? Et illa: Etiam dico verita|tem.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">"Is &thorn;at so&thorn;, bi &thorn;i lyf?"</L>
<L>And heo onswerd: "dame, beo my fey,</L>
<L>Hit is so&thorn; nou &thorn;at i sey".</L>
<L>Heo was bigyled verreylichche,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Decepta puella verbis maleficae dixit ut advesperascente die virum ad se venire faceret, et voluntatem suam adimpleret (engl. dir.).</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;en heo seide to &thorn;e wicche:</L>
<L N="45">"&THORN;at &thorn;ou seist, nou i beoleeue.</L>
<L>Bid him come nou sone at eue:</L>
<L>I schal beo redi to folfulle;</L>
<L>When &thorn;at he come&thorn;, al his wille".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon &thorn;at &thorn;e wicche hed told him &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum viro retu|lisset, ille, vehementer exsultans, hora qua condixerat ad eam venit secumque concu|buit et abscessit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">He was a joiful mon, iwis,</L>
<L>And atte same tyme he com</L>
<L>And fond Theodora at hom;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire he dude what him lust,</L>
<L>And went his wei, whon he hedde cust.</L>
<L N="55">Whon heo bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t hire aftur wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Theodora autem, ad se ipsam rediens, amarissime flebat et faciem suam percutiebat, dicens: Heu heu me, perdidi animam meam, destruxi aspectum de|coris mei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo weopte and made muche deol</L>
<L>And beot hire owne face ful sore,</L>
<L>And among criede euer more</L>
<L>"Allas allas, what haue i do!
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="36"></L>
<L N="60">Mi soule is lost for euermo,</L>
<L>I haue destruy&yogh;ed nou &thorn;e siht</L>
<L>Of my beute, &thorn;at was so briht".</L>
<L>Whon hir hosebonde comen hom was,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vir autem ejus domum rediens et uxorem suam sic desolatam et moe|rentem videns, causam tamen nesciens, eam consolari nitebatur; sed illa nullam con|solationem percipere volebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>He biheold hire in &thorn;e fas,</L>
<L N="65">And whon he sauh hire heui cher,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he hedde gret wonder.</L>
<L>He asked hire what hire was.</L>
<L>Heo nolde him not telle of &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>And he hire cumforted ofte si&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="70">But for no &thorn;ing wolde heo beo bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwen, whon hit was day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mane autem facto quoddam monasterium moni|alium adiit et abbatissam interrogavit an Deus quoddam grave delictum, quod die advesperascente commiserat, scire posset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo wente hir to an abbay</L>
<L>Of nonnes, and of &thorn;at abbes</L>
<L>Heo asked sone, wi&thorn;outen les,</L>
<L N="75">Whe&thorn;er God mihte wite a gret trespas</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo dude &thorn;e niht &thorn;at last was</L>
<L>Tofore, aftur &thorn;e sonne went doun.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbesse onswered wi&thorn; deuocioun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui illa: Nihil Deo abscondi potest et Deus scit et videt omne quod fit, quacumque hora illud committatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at "God so mihtful is al way</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at he seo&thorn; as wel bi niht as day</L>
<L>And wot al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ido,</L>
<L>What tyde, what tyme, what vre also".</L>
<L>Heo onswerde, wepyng bitterli:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae, flens amare, dixit: Da mihi librum sancti evangelii, ut sortiar memet ipsam.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Reche me &thorn;e bok of &thorn;e Ewangeli,</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;at i mowe assaye, for i wite mot,</L>
<L>What schal me falle nou for my lot".</L>
<L>Heo opened &thorn;e bok. anon heo fond<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Aperiens reperit: Quod scripsi scripsi (engl. erkl.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wordus &thorn;at Pilat seide her in lond,</L>
<L>On Latyn &thorn;at is: Quod scripsi scripsi,</L>
<L N="90">And on Englisch is, sikerli:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at haue i writen &thorn;at wrot I",</L>
<L>To &thorn;e men &thorn;at stod him bi.</L>
<L>Theodora went hir hom &thorn;an,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Rediens ergo domum, dum quadam die vir suus abesset, comam suam praecidit, vestimenta viri assumens ad quoddam monasterium monachorum (quod per octo milliaria distabat) festinabat et ut ibidem cum monachis reciperetur petiit,</NOTE></L>
<L>As a ful sori womman.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="95">HIt bifel vppon a day</L>
<L>Hir hosebonde was out of &thorn;e way:</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne of hire owne witte</L>
<L>Al hire her awey heo kutte,</L>
<L>And in monnes clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L N="100">Tok &thorn;e wey wi&thorn; gret hi&yogh;ing</L>
<L>Touward a munstre of monkes blake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er heo preyed for Godus sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at amonges o&thorn;ur men</L>
<L>A monk of &thorn;e hous heo mihte ben.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;ei wende heo hedde ben a mon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei asked hire &thorn;on</L>
<L>What was hire rihte name &mdash;</L>
<L>Heo schulde hem telle wi&thorn;oute blame.</L>
<L>Hire name, &thorn;at was femynyn</L>
<L N="110">Of gendre, heo turned in to masculyn:</L>
<L>Theodora hire name was, parde,</L>
<L>But Theodorus heo hiht, seide heo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En of &thorn;at mon &thorn;e monkes were glad<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et quod petiit impetravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And token him in wi&thorn; chere ful sad.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;at tyme monkes neih lewed men were.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon &thorn;ei dude among hem schere</L>
<L>And to bere &thorn;e blac abyt</L>
<L>Of heore ordre wi&thorn; good dilyt.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei putten him to an offyce &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">abbas fratrem Theodorum vocavit et ut boves jungeret et oleum de civitate afferret praecepit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at nou&thorn;e schulde bi holde nyce &mdash;:</L>
<L>To &yogh;oke &thorn;e oxen, so mot i &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And fette oyle at &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>Theodorus feir and wel<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Illa vero officia omnia humiliter faciebat (et ejus servitium omnibus gratum fuit. Post aliquot ergo annos</NOTE></L>
<L>Dude his offys eueridel.</L>
<L N="125">Hire hosebonde was ful sori<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vir autem ejus plurimum flebat, timens ne cum viro altero recessisset.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of chere al dreri,
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>For he wende heo hedde beo gon</L>
<L>Awey wi&thorn; sum o&thorn;ur mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON a tyme God almiht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ecce angelus domini sibi dixit: Surge mane et sta in via martirii Petri apostoli, et quae tibi obviaverit ipsa tua uxor erit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Him cumforted bi an angel briht,</L>
<L>And seide to him: "vppon alle wyse</L>
<L>Loke to morwe &thorn;at &thorn;ou rise</L>
<L>And stonde in &thorn;e same way</L>
<L>&thorn;er Petur and Poul vppon a day</L>
<L N="135">For Cristes loue tok martirdome;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e furste wommon &thorn;at &thorn;ou seost come</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo hit is &thorn;at is &thorn;y wyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou louedest as &thorn;y lyf".</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwen he tok &thorn;e pas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo facto Theodora cum camelis venit et virum suum videns et recognoscens intra se dixit: Heu me, vir bone meus, quantum laboro, ut eripiar a peccato quod feci in te.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Til he com to &thorn;e same plas.</L>
<L>Theodora wi&thorn; hire chamayles</L>
<L>Com &thorn;er for&thorn;, to fette hire oyles.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at heo sauh hire hosebonde,</L>
<L>Heo kneo him wel, bo&thorn;e fot and honde,</L>
<L N="145">And to hire self softly heo seid,</L>
<L>And sykede sore in herte and breyd:</L>
<L>"Allas allas, my gode fere,</L>
<L>Hou sore i trauayle in eor&thorn;e here,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at sunne dilyuered to be</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;at i haue sunged a&yogh;eines &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at heo neih&yogh;ed him neih,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem appropinquasset, salutavit eum dicens: Gaudeat dominus meus. Ille autem eam penitus non cognovit; sed cum diutissime exspectaret et se deceptum clamaret (161 Zus.), facta est vox ad eum dicens: Ille qui te heri mane salutavit uxor tua erat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; open vois al an heih</L>
<L>&THORN;enne to him heo seide &thorn;is word:</L>
<L>"Stonde&thorn; murie, sire, my lord!"</L>
<L N="155">And he stod stille al in &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>For outurliche he kneuh hir nouht.</L>
<L>Whon heo was bi him passed hir way</L>
<L>And he hedde longe abide &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>He gan to crie and faste he weyled<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. hee, aus heo corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And seide &thorn;at he was bigyled.</L>
<L>In his bed whon he was leide,</L>
<L>At niht a vois to him seide:</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at &thorn;e saluwed &yogh;esterday</L>
<L>Was &thorn;i wyf, sire, in good fay".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">THeodora forso&thorn;e wes<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae autem sanctitatis fuit beata Theodora, ut multa miracula faceret: nam et hominem a bestia laceratum eripuit et suis precibus suscitavit, ipsam quoque bestiam insecuta maledixit, quae subito mortua corruit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of so gret holynes</L>
<L>&THORN;at God for hire miracles wrouhte</L>
<L>For moni men, as heo bisou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A wylde best hedde al totoren</L>
<L N="170">A mon and al most forloren,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">nach almost fehlt was?</NOTE></L>
<L>But heo saued &thorn;at mon, certeyn,</L>
<L>And him reised vp a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e best heo corsed witerliche,</L>
<L>And hit fel doun ded sodeynliche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">&THORN;E deuel hedde gret enuye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dyabolus autem, suam sanctita|tem ferre non volens, eidem apparuit dicens: Meretrix prae omnibus et adultera, re|liquisti virum tuum, ut huc venires et me contemneres; per virtutes meas tremendas in te suscitabo proelium, et si non te fecero crucifixum negare, non dicas quia ego sum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is wommon was so holye;</L>
<L>To hire he apeered vppon a day</L>
<L>And grimliche gon to hire say:</L>
<L>"Now artou wel imet,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;ow vyle foule stumpet,</L>
<L>Ouer al o&thorn;ure more and lesse</L>
<L>&THORN;ou foulest avouteresse!</L>
<L>&THORN;in hosebonde &thorn;ou hast forsake,</L>
<L>And here &thorn;i dwellyng &thorn;ou hast take,</L>
<L N="185">For &thorn;ou woldest me dispise.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. stumpet st. strumpet.</NOTE></L>
<L>I schal &thorn;e quyte on o&thorn;ur wyse:</L>
<L>I &thorn;e telle wi&thorn;outen fayle,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e i schal reyse a batayle,</L>
<L>I schal &thorn;e make wi&thorn; muchel wrake</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;e crucifixe forte forsake;</L>
<L>And but &thorn;at hit beo so, verreily,</L>
<L>Sei &thorn;ou &thorn;at I nam not I".
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at heo hed herd his vois,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ipsa autem signum crucis sibi edidit, et protinus daemon evanuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo schewed him &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e crois,</L>
<L N="195">And &thorn;enne &thorn;e schrewe anon riht</L>
<L>Vanischt awey out of hire siht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel, as &yogh;e schul here,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qua|dam autem vice, dum de civitate cum camelis rediret et in quodam loco hospitata fuisset, puella quadam nocte ad eam venit dicens: Dormi mecum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon a tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute; as heo com</L>
<L N="200">Wi&thorn; hire chamayles, forte gon hom:</L>
<L>Heo was herborwed in a plas</L>
<L>And to bedde ibrouht was.</L>
<L>A damisele com to hire &thorn;on,</L>
<L>As &thorn;auh hit hedde beo to a mon,</L>
<L N="205">And seide: "sire, so mote &thorn;ou &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To niht slep &thorn;ou wi&thorn; me!"</L>
<L>Theodora &thorn;enne &thorn;at forsok,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae cum respueret, ivit ad alterum qui in eodem loco jacebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e maide &thorn;e wey &thorn;en tok</L>
<L>To ano&thorn;ur monnes bed</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;at in &thorn;at same hous was leid.</L>
<L>Whon hire wombe was gret iwaxe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem ejus venter intumuisset et de quo concepisset interrogata fuisset, ait: Monachus ille Theodorus dormivit mecum (216 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Mony men &thorn;enne gonne hire aske</L>
<L>Whos &thorn;at child mihte &thorn;enne be.</L>
<L>"Theodorus &thorn;e monk ha&thorn; le&yogh;en bi me"</L>
<L N="215">Heo seide, and was no&thorn;ing aschamed,</L>
<L>And al, for he schulde beo blamed.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e child was ibore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Natum igitur puerum ad abbatem monasterii trans|miserunt (219 u. 221&mdash;2 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon riht wi&thorn;outen more</L>
<L>&THORN;e men, &thorn;at weren of vuel entent,</L>
<L N="220">To &thorn;e abbot &thorn;e child &thorn;ei sent</L>
<L>And seiden: his monk was waxen to wyld:</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde igeten him such a child.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &thorn;enne his monk gan blame<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui cum Theodorum increparet et ille sibi in|dulgeri peteret, scapulis suis puerum imposuit et de monasterio projecit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ilke wikkede fame,</L>
<L N="225">And, &thorn;ouh he neore not gulty,</L>
<L>He asked for&yogh;iuenesse mekely.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e abbot anon riht &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wende hit hedde beo riht so,</L>
<L>And caste &thorn;e child in &thorn;e monkes lap</L>
<L N="230">And bad hem bo&thorn;e vuel hap,</L>
<L>He put hem bo&thorn;e from &thorn;at abbey</L>
<L>And bad him go for&thorn; on his wey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THeodora &thorn;enne seuen &yogh;eer<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Illa autem abjecta per septem annos extra monasterium mansit et de lacte pecorum infan|tem nutrivit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heold hire fro &thorn;e munster;</L>
<L N="235">Wi&thorn; milk of beestes, tame and wyld,</L>
<L>Heo norissched feire vp &thorn;at chyld.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E deuel forso&thorn;e wi&thorn; gret anuye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dyabolus autem, tantae ejus patientiae invidens, in speciem viri sui se transfiguravit eique dixit: Quid hic agis, domina mea? ecce langueo pro te nec aliquam consolationem recipio; veni ergo, lux mea, quia, si cum viro aliquo jacuisti, hoc tibi indulgeo.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hire pacience hedde envye,</L>
<L>And in liknesse of hire hosebonde</L>
<L N="240">Tofore hire &thorn;enne gon he stonde</L>
<L>And seide to hire: "bi &thorn;i lyf,</L>
<L>What dostou here, myn owne wyf?</L>
<L>Lo hou sek I am for &thorn;e!</L>
<L>I may no cumfort take to me.</L>
<L N="245">Cum wi&thorn; me, my swete leue,</L>
<L>And i &thorn;e, certes! schal for&yogh;eue</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny mon ha&thorn; bi &thorn;e ley&yogh;en,</L>
<L>I nul &thorn;e &thorn;e lasse louen, certeyn".</L>
<L>Heo wende hire hosbonde he hed bene,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At illa, credens virum suum esse, dixit ad illum: Nunquam amplius tecum manebo, quia filius Johannis militis jacuit mecum, et volo agere poenitentiam de eo quod in te peccavi. Et cum orasset, statim evanuit (et daemonem fuisse cognovit.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">And him onswerde wi&thorn; herte clene:</L>
<L>"I schal neuer dwelle wi&thorn; &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>Min herte, iwis, hit is ful sore,</L>
<L>For I sunged foule a&yogh;eines &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Whon Jon, &thorn;e knihtes sone, lay bi me".</L>
<L N="255">In to hire preyere heo ful &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e deuel vanischt hire fro.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>&THORN;E deuel eftsones wi&thorn; wyles cast<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Altera iterum vice dyabolus volens eam terrere, in similitudinem ferarum ter|ribilium daemones ad eam venerunt, et vir quidam instigans eas dicebat: Comedite meretricem hanc. Ista autem oravit, et evanuerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire to fere, and atte last</L>
<L>In wylde beestes liknes</L>
<L N="260">Deueles, bo&thorn;e more and les,</L>
<L>To hire he sent, and a man</L>
<L>Hem suwed and seide &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Go for&thorn;, &yogh;e beestes, euerichon</L>
<L>And ete&thorn; &thorn;is comuyn wommon!"</L>
<L N="265">To God &thorn;enne heo made hire preyere:</L>
<L>&THORN;ei vanischt awey alle in fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF knihtes heo sauh a cumpaygnie<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Altera vice multitudo mili|tum veniebat, quam princeps praecedebat, et eum caeteri adorabant; dixeruntque mi|lites Theodorae: Surge et adora principem nostrum. Quae respondit: Dominum deum adoro. Quod cum principi nuntiatum fuisset, jussit eam adduci et tot tormentis affici, ut mortua putaretur; et postmodum omnis turba evanuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur tyme wi&thorn; hire e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And as a prince tofore hem dude gon<NOTE PLACE="foot1">as wohl zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">And &thorn;ei him worschiped euerichon,</L>
<L>To Theodora &thorn;e knihtes gon sei:</L>
<L>"Arys vp al in good fey</L>
<L>And vre prince loke &thorn;ou adoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord is of gret honoure!"</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;en heo onswerde anon riht:</L>
<L>"I worschipe him wi&thorn; al my miht:</L>
<L>Mi lord God, of mihtes most,</L>
<L>And bouht vs alle &thorn;at weren lost".</L>
<L>To heore prince a&yogh;ein &thorn;ei breid</L>
<L N="280">And tolden him what heo hedde iseid.</L>
<L>And he comaunded wi&thorn; gret talent</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde hire trauayle wi&thorn; torment,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at heo weore wel neih dede,</L>
<L>"Loke &yogh;e quyte hire so hire mede!"</L>
<L N="285">And &thorn;en &thorn;ei alle vppon o fliht</L>
<L>Vanisch(t) awey out of hire siht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E deuel in ano&thorn;ur wyse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Alia iterum vice vidit ibidem aurum multum, quae, signans se, illud refugit et Deo se recommendavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tempted hire wi&thorn; couetyse:</L>
<L>For on a tyme heo say muche gold</L>
<L N="290">And o&thorn;ur tresur monyfold.</L>
<L>Heo blessed hir &thorn;enne wi&thorn; &thorn;e crois</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;outen more nois</L>
<L>Heo preyed God to ben hire help,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, where he loue&thorn;, wol not &yogh;elp.</L>
<L N="295">Heo fley&yogh; &thorn;erfro as hitterly</L>
<L>As mon wolde from an enemy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANo&thorn;ur tyme &thorn;er com to hire<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Altera etiam vice vidit quendam, canistrum plenum omni genere ciborum feren|tem et dicentem sibi: Dicit princeps qui te cecidit: tolle, comede, quia nesciens fecit hoc. Illa autem se signavit, et protinus evanuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A mon &thorn;at a basket dude bere,</L>
<L>Ful of alle maner of mete,</L>
<L N="300">And seide: "&thorn;e prince &thorn;at &thorn;e bad bete</L>
<L>Bad &thorn;ou schuldest take &thorn;erof and ete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at for no&thorn;ing &thorn;ou schuldest lete;</L>
<L>For vnwityng he bad his men,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; wrong, bete &thorn;e &thorn;en".</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;enne wi&thorn; &thorn;e crois heo hire blessed,</L>
<L>And anon &thorn;enne hit vanisched.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;e seuen &yogh;eres ende<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Completis autem septem annis abbas, patientiam ejus considerans, eam reconciliavit et cum puero suo in monaste|rium introduxit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot tok riht wel to muynde</L>
<L>Theodorus longe pacience,</L>
<L N="310">And of good concience</L>
<L>His monk reconciled a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his child in munstur to ben.</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at al two &yogh;er<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ubi cum duos postmodum annos laudabiliter peregisset, puerum accepit et secum illum in cella sua clausit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; monkes in cloistre liued in fer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="315">VPpon a day wi&thorn;outen were</L>
<L>In to hire celle heo wente hire,</L>
<L>In to hire &thorn;at child heo clept</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo so longe tofore hed kept,</L>
<L>And, whon heo adoun was set,</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e dore to hire faste heo schet.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e abbot of &thorn;is wuste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum abbati revelatum fuisset, misit quosdam monachos, qui diligentius auscultarent quidnam cum eo loqueretur.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>He sende his monkes forte luste,</L>
<L>Priueyliche forto here</L>
<L>What &thorn;ei tweyne speken ifere.</L>
<L N="325">Heo tok &thorn;e child loueliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Illa autem, puerum amplexans et deosculans, dixit: Fili mi dulcissime, tempus vitae meae venit; relinquo te Deo, ipsum patrem et adjutorem habeas, fili dulcissime, jejuniis et orationibus insistas et fratribus tuis devote servias.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hir armes, ful sweteliche</L>
<L>Custe hit and seide: "child, haue in mende:</L>
<L>Tyme is comen of my lyues ende.</L>
<L>To God of heuene nou leue i &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="330">A good mon loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Tac him &thorn;in helpere and &thorn;i syre:</L>
<L>He wol quite &thorn;e wel &thorn;in hire.</L>
<L>Mi swete sone, beo bisy ay</L>
<L>Him to serue bo&thorn;e niht and day</L>
<L N="335">Wi&thorn; fastynge and god preyere,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt liuen here,</L>
<L>Deuout loke on alle wyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou beo in &thorn;i bre&thorn;er seruyse."</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at word heo &yogh;ald &thorn;e gost<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hoc dicens, spi|ritum tradidit (et in domino feliciter obdormivit circa annos domini CCCCLXX): quod puer cernens plurimum flere coepit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="340">To God, &thorn;at is of mihtes most.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e child &thorn;erof was war,</L>
<L>He wepte and made muche car.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E abbot &thorn;at same niht at euen<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In ipsa autem nocte visio abbati monasterii monstrata est in hunc modum: nuptiae maximae parabantur, et veniebant ordines angelorum et prophetarum et martirum et omnium sanctorum, et ecce in medio eo|rum mulier sola, gloria ineffabili circumdata, et venit usque ad nuptias et sedit super lectum, et omnes adstantes advocabant eam;</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te he say al in his sweuen</L>
<L N="345">A wondur swi&thorn;e gret weddyng,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er to was a gret comyng</L>
<L>Of angeles, prophetes, grete and smal,</L>
<L>Of martires and of halewes al;</L>
<L>And hem among was a wommon,</L>
<L N="350">Wi&thorn; wondur gret blisse bigon;</L>
<L>Whon heo com to &thorn;at weddyng,</L>
<L>Vppon a bed was hire sittyng,</L>
<L>And as &thorn;ei stoden hire aboute</L>
<L>&THORN;ei worschiped hire, al &thorn;e route.</L>
<L N="355">And &thorn;en he herde a vois sei &thorn;us:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et ecce vox dicens: Hic est, abbas, Theodorus, qui falso de puero accusatus est, VII tempora super ea mutata sunt, castigata est enim, quia cubile viri sui coinquinavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Abbot, &thorn;is is Theodorus</L>
<L>&THORN;at falsliche acuised was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at child in &thorn;i plas;</L>
<L>Seuen tymes wi&thorn;outen les</L>
<L N="360">Vppon hire chaunged &thorn;er wes.</L>
<L>Heo was chastised tofore hire ded,</L>
<L>For heo brac hire spoushed".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot ros him vp anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Excitatus autem abbas concitus cum fratribus ad cellam ejus ivit et eam jam defunctam invenit, et intrantes et discooperientes ipsam esse feminam invenerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And waked his bre&thorn;eren euerichon.</L>
<L N="365">And whon &thorn;ei to &thorn;e celle were gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei founden hire ded as eny ston.</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;ere &thorn;enne &thorn;ei vnheled:</L>
<L>A wommon &thorn;er &thorn;ei say&yogh; and feled.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e abbot was aschamed<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Misitque abbas pro patre puellae quae eam infamaverat, et dixit illi: Vir filiae tuae mortuus est; et auferens vestimentum mulierem esse cognovit. Factus est igitur timor magnus super omnes qui hoc audierunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">And sent aftur hir fadur &thorn;at hire defamed.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e mon is ded, he seide, verreyli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i dou&yogh;tur hedde child bi".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e clo&thorn; was taken hire fro,</L>
<L>A wommon he sauh, he wuste wel &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;ei weoren aferd and aschamed</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at euere hire hedde defamed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN angel, &thorn;at from God was sent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Angelus autem domini abbati locutus est: (Surge velociter), equum adscende et vade in civitatem et, si quis obviaverit, assume et tecum adduc.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbot seide &thorn;is entent:</L>
<L>"Tac &thorn;in hors, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ride</L>
<L N="380">In to &thorn;e cit&eacute; in &thorn;is tyde;</L>
<L>Whomeuer &thorn;ou metest, whon &thorn;ou comest &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Tac him wi&thorn; &thorn;e and bring him hider!"
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot rod for&thorn; his way.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui dum pergeret, quidam vir currens sibi obviavit. Quem cum abbas inter|rogaret quo pergeret, ille ait: Mulier mea mortua est et vado videre eam (388 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>A mon he mette and he gon say</L>
<L N="385">And asked also "whodur rennest &thorn;ou?"</L>
<L>And he onswerede "I hi&yogh;e me nou</L>
<L>To seo my wyf &thorn;at nou ded is &mdash;</L>
<L>Of hire haue i had ful gret mis".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &thorn;en tok &thorn;is mon him wi&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et assumsit abbas virum Theodorae (in equum), et venientes plurimum fleve|runt et ipsam cum multis laudibus sepelierunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">And wenten wepyng bi feld and fri&thorn;,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at &thorn;ei to &thorn;e abbei com,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e monkes &thorn;ei founden at hom.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi &thorn;enne wi&thorn; swete song</L>
<L>&THORN;ei burieden &thorn;o hem among.</L>
<L N="395">And in &thorn;at ilke same celle<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vir autem ejus cellam uxoris suae Theodorae accepit (398 Zus.) et ibidem permanens tandem in domino obdor|mivit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er Theodora was wont to dwelle,</L>
<L>He dwelled aftur al his lyue</L>
<L>And preyed for his noble wyue,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last to God he went,</L>
<L N="400">Blisse to haue, verreyment.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child also &thorn;at his wyf<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Puer autem Theodorae, nutricem sequens, omni morum honestate polle|bat, ita quod mortuo abbate monasterii in abbatem ipse unanimiter est electus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hedde inorissched in hire lyf,</L>
<L>Among his bre&thorn;eren iloued so was</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was chosun of &thorn;at plas</L>
<L N="405">Heore abbot and heore hed to be,</L>
<L>Hem to gouerne in charite,</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at he to God was go</L>
<L>&THORN;at abbot was tofore him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>God graunte vs grace wel to do,</L>
<L N="410">And &yogh;iue us heuene blisse also!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="life">
<HEAD>5. S. Bernard.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">5) Das lateinische Original s. Leg. Aur. cap. 120 de S. Bernardo. Die den latei|nischen Text einleitende Ableitung des Namens (: a ber quod est puteus vel fons, et nardus quae, ut dicit Glossa super cantica, herba est humilis et calidae naturae et odorifera) und die Angabe dass das Leben des Heiligen "Wilhelmus abbas sancti Theodorici, socius beati Bernardi et Hernaldus abbas Bonae Vallis" geschrieben, fehlt auff&auml;lliger Weise in der engl. Uebertragung, welche doch sonst die Etymologieen der Leg. Aur. wiedergibt.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Bernard born was at Burgoyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bernardus in Burgundia castro Fontanis ex nobilibus valde et religiosis parentibus ortus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e castel men calle&thorn; Fountayne,</L>
<L>Of wondur noble kinred</L>
<L>Of gentrie and of goodhed.</L>
<L N="5">His fader was a wor&thorn;i kniht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cujus pater Coelestinus (alii codd.: De|celinus) miles saeculo strenuus, nec minus Deo religiosus,</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to &thorn;e world and to God almiht,</L>
<L>Men called him sir Tecelyn.</L>
<L>He hedde also a modur fyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mater vero Aaleth nuncupata est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at men called tofore hire de&thorn;</L>
<L N="10">Bi &thorn;ulke day&yogh;es dame Aaleth.</L>
<L>Seuen children in &thorn;at londe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Haec septem filios genuit, sex mares et feminam unam,</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo hedde bi hire hosebonde:</L>
<L>&THORN;e sixe weor knaue children, as men saide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e was a mayde;</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;e knaue children vchone monkes were,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mares autem omnes monachos futuros, feminam autem sanctimonialem (promiserat &mdash; dieses Verb fehlt auch in Ed. princ.). Mox autem, ut filium partu ediderat, manibus propriis ipsum Deo offerebat,</NOTE></L>
<L>A nonne bicom heore douhtur deore.</L>
<L>Heo was wont wi&thorn; herte myld,</L>
<L>As sone as heo hedde ibore a child,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire oune hondes deuoutely</L>
<L N="20">Offre hit heo wolde to God almihti.</L>
<L>Hem to norissche heo wolde not lete<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alienis uberibus ipsos nutriri refugiebat, quasi cum lacte ma|terno materni quodammodo boni infundens iis naturam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; milk and wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur mete</L>
<L>Non o&thorn;ur wommon, witerly,
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>But al hir oune body:</L>
<L N="25">Heo trouwed wel, wi&thorn;outen lees,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if &thorn;at eny goodnes</L>
<L>Hedde ben in &thorn;e modur kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e child hit schulde best fede and fynde.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei woxen ou&yogh;t of stature,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem crevissent, quamdiu sub manu ejus erant, eremo magis quam curiae nutriebat, cibis grossioribus et communibus pascens eos quasi continuo ad eremum transmittendos.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">Whil heo of hem hedde &thorn;e cure</L>
<L>Heo norissched hem ra&thorn;ur to desert</L>
<L>&THORN;en in court to lyue apert:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; comuyn metes and boystous</L>
<L>Heo hem norissched in heor hous,</L>
<L N="35">For &thorn;ei schulde not aftur ben aferd</L>
<L>Hardnes to soffre in desert.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon &thorn;at wommon meke and mylde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum igitur tertium filium, scilicet Bernardum, adhuc gestaret in utero, vidit somnium prae|sagium futurorum:</NOTE></L>
<L>In wombe hedde &thorn;e &thorn;ridde childe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was icalled afturward</L>
<L N="40">At &thorn;e cristendom Bernard,</L>
<L>Heo hedde a sweuene of him, wituring</L>
<L>What he schulde beo in tyme comyng:</L>
<L>Hir &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;at in hir wombe heo had<NOTE PLACE="foot2">catellum scilicet totum candidum, totum in dorso subrufum et latrantem in utero se habere.</NOTE></L>
<L>A luytel whel&thorn;, of mou&thorn; ful glad,</L>
<L N="45">And was as whit as swannes federe,</L>
<L>His bac was rouh eke al to gedere.</L>
<L>And to a good holi man<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum cuidam viro Dei exposuisset, ille prophetica voce respondit:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e goode wyf tolde hire sweuene &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And he onswerde, as a prophete:</L>
<L N="50">"I schal &thorn;e telle what is &thorn;i meete:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Optimi catelli mater eris, qui domus Dei custos futu|rus magnos contra inimicos dabit latratus; erit enim praedicator egregius et multos medicinalis linguae gratia curaturus (61-2 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt beo modur of a whelp</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal bo&thorn;e berke and &yogh;elp</L>
<L>And also &thorn;erto gret noyse make</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes enemys for Godus sake,</L>
<L N="55">For &thorn;er schal bi tak eto him<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bi = be, wie &ouml;fter im Ms. Vernon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Godus hous for to &yogh;em;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei: wi&thorn;outen let</L>
<L>He schal beon a prechour gret</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e medecyn of his tonge</L>
<L N="60">Of sunne hele bo&thorn;e olde and &yogh;onge,</L>
<L>He schal beo mon of holy churche,</L>
<L>Of grete wondres &thorn;er inne worche".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Aehnliche Constr. s. Ambr. 486.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHil he was &yogh;ong and tendre ek,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem Bernardus ad|huc puerulus esset et gravi dolore capitis aegrotaret, venientem ad se mulierculam, ut dolorem suis carminibus mitigaret, cum indignatione nimia exclamans repulit et ab|jecit;</NOTE></L>
<L>His hed ook: &thorn;at made him sek.</L>
<L N="65">Forte sauen him of &thorn;at harme,</L>
<L>&THORN;er com a wommon his hed to charme.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he &thorn;erof was war,</L>
<L>He criede and made muche far</L>
<L>And bad men schulde hire bidde for&thorn; gon,</L>
<L N="70">For of hir charmes wolde he non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e child anon, witterli,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pueruli autem bono zelo misericordia Dei non defuit, sed tunc continuo sur|gens liberatum se esse cognovit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore felede Godus merci,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ache was went awey,</L>
<L>And he aros and went to pley.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="75">VPpon a cristemasse niht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In sacratissima dominicae nativitatis nocte cum puer Bernardus matutinale officium in ecclesia exspectaret et qua hora noctis Christus natus fuisset, scire cuperet,</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e churche he wente for&thorn; riht</L>
<L>And abod &thorn;er wi&thorn;inne;</L>
<L>And whon matyns schulde biginne,</L>
<L>He coueyted wi&thorn; al his miht</L>
<L N="80">To wite what hour of &thorn;e niht</L>
<L>Crist vr saueour was bore.</L>
<L>And as he stod in &thorn;ouht &thorn;erfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">apparuit ei puerulus Jesus, quasi iterum ante oculos suos nascens ex utero matris.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;t he sauh child Jhesus</L>
<L>As he boren was amongus vs,</L>
<L N="85">In &thorn;e tyme riht of &thorn;e bur&thorn;e,</L>
<L>As hit hed ben wi&thorn; muchel mur&thorn;e</L>
<L>Of his modur riht &thorn;enne, so dere,
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>As heo in trauaylyng were.</L>
<L>He leeuede euer aftur &thorn;at &thorn;at same hour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unde, quamdiu vixit, hanc fuisse horam nativitatis dominicae semper putavit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">Jhesus was boren, vr sauiour.</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;at tyme his wit was more bri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ab illa ergo hora in his quae ad illud pertinent sacra|mentum, et sensus ei profundior (v. 91 <I>u</I>. 95) et sermo copiosior datus est;</NOTE></L>
<L>To knowe and seo wi&thorn; spirituel liht</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament of incarnaciun;</L>
<L>&THORN;en was him &yogh;iuen deuociun</L>
<L N="95">And deppore wit to vndurstonde,</L>
<L>And copious to beo of tonge in londe.</L>
<L>Afturward &thorn;erfore wel sone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">unde et postmodum in laudem genitricis et geniti inter ipsa suorum tractatuum initia insigne opusculum edidit, in quo illam lectionem evangelicam: Missus est angelus Gabriel, explanavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of vr ladi and hire sone</L>
<L>In &thorn;e biginning of his makyng</L>
<L N="100">He made a wondur worching,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is: a lessun of gret leornyng,</L>
<L>To vche monnes heryng,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whuche he expouned &thorn;e gospel</L>
<L>Missus est angelus Gabriel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">WHen &thorn;e fend kneuh his purpos,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Videns antiquus hostis propositum pueri (tam salubre), ejus casti|tatis proposito incidit multosque sibi laqueos tentationis opposuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was aboute destruye his los</L>
<L>And mad him moni a temptaciun</L>
<L>Of chastite, to leue his deuociun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme on a wommon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum enim aliquando in quandam feminam oculos defixos aliquamdiu tenuisset, continuo de se ipso erubescens in semet ipsum severissimus ultor insurgit ac in stagnum gelidarum aqua|rum insiliens tamdiu ibidem permansit, donec paene exsanguis effectus a calore carnalis concupiscentiae totus refriguit.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">genannt ist; der Dichter las blos puella) in lectum dormientis se nuda injecit, quam ille sentiens cum omni pace et silentio partem ei lectuli, quam occupaverat, cessit et in latus alterum se conver|tens dormivit;</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">To loke hire wi&thorn; e&yogh;en liked him &thorn;on;</L>
<L>And whon him self he hedde bi&thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>He wox aschamet and nolde hir nouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to pyne his oune flesch,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so frele, him &thorn;hou&yogh;te, and nesch,</L>
<L N="115">In to a pol &thorn;at was froren</L>
<L>He sturte sone in &mdash; he was not boren;</L>
<L>So longe forso&thorn;e &thorn;er he stood</L>
<L>Forte kele his hote blod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was in poynt almost</L>
<L N="120">Forte haue &yogh;olden vp &thorn;e gost.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SOne aftur &thorn;e damysel<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Circa idem tempus instinctu daemonis puella quaedam (im engl. dasselbe M&auml;dchen, welches</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fend hedde tempted &amp; mad so fel</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo crep in to &thorn;e bed</L>
<L>&THORN;er he to slepe hed leid his hed.</L>
<L N="125">Whon he hire feled in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>He tornde him to &thorn;at o&thorn;ur syde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e bed, and nouht he seide</L>
<L>Ne made no noyse ne no&thorn;ur abreyde,</L>
<L>And leet hire haue &thorn;at partye</L>
<L N="130">&THORN;at heo com in ate forte lye,</L>
<L>And he him self on slep fyl.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ms. fel, in fyl corrigirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And heo lay stille a luytel whil,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">misera vero illa aliquamdiu sustinens et exspectans, deinde pal|pans et stimulans, novissime, cum immobilis ipse persisteret, illa licet impuden|tissima esset, erubuit et horrore ingenti atque admiratione perfusa surgens aufu|git.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en heo groped him atte laste</L>
<L>And put vppon him swi&thorn;e faste.</L>
<L N="135">But whon heo sau&yogh; he wolde not stire,</L>
<L>&THORN;at forso&thorn;e aschomed hire,</L>
<L>And gretliche wondred and aros</L>
<L>And dude hire for&thorn; out of &thorn;at clos.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum iterum in domo cuiusdam matronae hospitaretur, illa adolescen|tem aspectu decorum considerans, vehementer in concupiscentiam ejus exarsit,</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EFtsones in his lyf</L>
<L N="140">He was herborwed wi&thorn; an hosewyf.</L>
<L>For he was semely in hire e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>On him heo gan loke and prye,</L>
<L>Heo coueyted inwardliche</L>
<L>He schulde ha knowen hire flescliche.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="44"></L>
<L N="145">Heo let maken a bed ful sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">cum autem seorsim lectum sibi sterni fecisset, ipsa impudenter et silenter de nocte surgens ad eum accessit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him self to liggen in al one.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he to bed was brouht,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hosewyf wolde do as heo &thorn;ouht:</L>
<L>Al wi&thorn; silence and wi&thorn; pes</L>
<L N="150">Vp heo ros, and made no res,</L>
<L>heo ne spared for no grim</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e bed to go to him.</L>
<L>Whon he hire feled, he cried out<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quam ille sentiens, protinus exclamavit: latrones, latrones! Ad quam vocem mulier fugit, familia surgit, lucerna accenditur, latro quae|ritur, sed minime invenitur.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide: "&thorn;eues ben her about".</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;e hosewyf was aferd &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Vp heo ros, awey heo ran.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruauns alle at &thorn;at cri</L>
<L>Risen vp wel smartly</L>
<L>And souhten &thorn;e hous anon wi&thorn; liht,</L>
<L N="160">But &thorn;ei ne founden no wiht.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad lectulos singuli redeunt, quiescunt caeteri, sed non illa misera requiescit, nam denuo exsurgit, Bernardi lectulum petit, sed ille: latrones, latrones! denuo exclamavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e seruauns wente to bedde wel prest</L>
<L>And wenden forte ha taken heore rest &mdash;</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e sori hosewyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ouhte neuer forte &thorn;rif:</L>
<L N="165">To Bernardus bed heo wente eftson.</L>
<L>And he criede "out, out" anon,</L>
<L>"Aryse&thorn;, men, loke &yogh;e ne blynne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er ben &thorn;eoues her inne".</L>
<L>&THORN;ei risen and souhten bisyliche,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Latro iterum quaeritur, sed nequaquam (ab eo qui solus noverat publicatur),</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">&THORN;ei founden no mon, treweliche.</L>
<L>Whon vche mon for his best<NOTE PLACE="foot2">usque tertio improba mulier sic repulsa vix tandem metu vel desperatione victa cessavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was gon to take eftsones rest,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde tyme heo wolde ha sayed,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sayed = assayed.</NOTE></L>
<L>But for fere heo was affrayed,</L>
<L N="175">And, for heo sauh hit nolde not be,</L>
<L>Heo let him ligge in pes, parde.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwen, whon hit was day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem sequenti die iter ageret, arguentes eum socii, quod totiens latrones somniaverit, perquirebant.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he hedde itake his jurnay,</L>
<L>In his sleep what he was dreiht</L>
<L N="180">His felawes asked him &thorn;at niht,</L>
<L>Whi he so faste on &thorn;eoues cried,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er mihte non beon aspyed.</L>
<L>He seide and swor: "so mot i cheue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quibus ille ait: Veraciter hac nocte insidias sum perpessus latronis, quia hospita mihi nitebatur auferre thesaurum irrecuperabilem castitatis.</NOTE></L>
<L>I was biset wi&thorn; a &thorn;eoue,</L>
<L N="185">For &thorn;e hosewyf of &thorn;e hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;er we hedde iherborwed vs,</L>
<L>Mi tresour of chastite</L>
<L>Heo wolde ha boren awey, parde;</L>
<L>To me &thorn;at wolde ha ben gret pein:</L>
<L N="190">I schulde hit neuere (ha) rekeuered a&yogh;ein".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">im Ms. fehlt ha; sollte es in hit versteckt sein?</NOTE></L>
<L>He sauh he miht not dwelle siker<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Perpendens igitur non esse tutum cohabitare serpenti, fugam meditari coepit,</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a serpent wi&thorn;outen biker:</L>
<L>He him caste hou he mihte fle,</L>
<L>To lyue in pes and charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="195">&THORN;En he forsok &thorn;e worldly &thorn;ewes,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et ordinem Cister|ciensium extunc ingredi deliberavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>To take &thorn;e ordre of Sistewes.</L>
<L>Whon his bre&thorn;eren knewen his &thorn;ouht,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum fratres ejus cognoscerent et eum ab hoc proposito modis omnibus prohiberent,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei him forboden he schulde nouht;</L>
<L>But God &thorn;at grace &thorn;en him sent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tantam ei gratiam dominus contulit, ut (non solum ipse a conversione non prohiberetur, sed) omnes fratres suos et multos alios ad religionem domino lucraretur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at he torned heor aller talent</L>
<L>To ben men of religiun,</L>
<L>And moni ano&thorn;ur wi&thorn; deuociun</L>
<L>He won to God wi&thorn; his techyng</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his goode lyuyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">HE hedde a bro&thorn;ur, &thorn;at was a kniht,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Gerardus tamen frater ejus, miles strenuus, haec fratris verba vana putabat et ejus omnino monita repellebat;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of his wordus lette pure liht
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he spac al in veyn,</L>
<L>Gerard was his nome, certeyn.</L>
<L>Bernard bi wei of charite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tunc Bernardus (fide jam igneus et) fraterno caritatis zelo mirum in modum exasperatus: Scio, inquit, frater mi, scio, sola vexatio intellectum dabit auditui (215 Zus).</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">Sumwhat meued was, for he</L>
<L>Aftur his counseil nolde nou&yogh;t do,</L>
<L>And to him he seide &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Bro&thorn;ur myn, wi&thorn;outen wening</L>
<L>I knowe riht wel &thorn;i menyng.</L>
<L N="215">Aftur holichirche sei&yogh;ing</L>
<L>Tribulaciun onliche schal &yogh;iue &thorn;e vndur|stonding".</L>
<L>His finger he put &thorn;en to his syde:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Digitumque lateri ejus apponens: Veniet, inquit, dies, et cito veniet, quando lancea latus hoc perforabit et ad cor tuum consilio, quod abjicis, viam dabit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Or ouht longe hit schal beotyde",</L>
<L>He seide, "&thorn;e day schal not longe abyde,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at a spere schal perse &thorn;i syde;</L>
<L>And riht so for&thorn; to &thorn;in herte</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou felest hit so smerte,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt repente wi&thorn;outen fayl</L>
<L>&THORN;ou neddest don aftur my counsayl".</L>
<L N="225">A fewe dayes afturward<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post paucos dies Gerardus ab inimicis capitur et in loco cui frater digitum im|posuerat infixam lanceam gestans, trahitur et in custodia vinculatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Enemys token sire Gerard:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e same place stak a spere</L>
<L>&THORN;er his bro&thorn;ur putte his fyngere;</L>
<L>He was ibounden swi&thorn;e fast'</L>
<L N="230">And &thorn;erto in prisun cast.</L>
<L>Whon seint Bernard herde of &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad quem Bernardus veniens, cum sibi loqui non permitteretur, ad eum exclamavit (236 Zus.): Scio, frater Gerarde, quia in proximo ituri sumus et monasterium intraturi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him to speke he wente, iwis;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei &thorn;at hedden him in kepyng</L>
<L>Wolde not soffre heor spekyng.</L>
<L N="235">&THORN;erfore seint Bernard cryed al out,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte here and al &thorn;e rout:</L>
<L>"Wite &thorn;ou wel, bro&thorn;ur Gerard,</L>
<L>Not long tyme her afturward</L>
<L>We schullen to gedere take &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="240">In to an abbeye to dwelle al way".</L>
<L>&THORN;e same niht riht, as he seet,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ea|dem nocte compedes de ejus pedibus ceciderunt et, ostio per se aperto, laetus aufugit,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fetres fullen fro his feet,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prisun dore eke ful abrod,</L>
<L>And he him self out &thorn;erate glod.</L>
<L N="245">Whon to his bro&thorn;ur he was come,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">indicavitque fratri se mutasse propositum et fieri velle monachum.</NOTE></L>
<L>He tolde him al hou he was nome,</L>
<L>And seide: "i kepe no knihtes los,</L>
<L>Ichaue ichaunged my purpos;</L>
<L>I haue trauayled and eke iswonke,</L>
<L N="250">But i &thorn;enke to ben a monke".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF &yogh;eeres two and twenti<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Anno ab incarnatione domini MCXII, a constitutione domus Cisterciensium XV, servus Dei Bernardus, annos nactus circiter XXII, cum sociis amplius quam XXX ordinem Cisterciensium ingressus est (im engl. frei geordnet).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of age Bernard was, witerli,</L>
<L>Whon he wi&thorn; felawes &thorn;ritti</L>
<L>Tok &thorn;e ordre deuoutli</L>
<L N="255">Of Cistewes, &thorn;e whuche hous,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof &thorn;e constitucioun glorious,</L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;at fol fiftene &yogh;er</L>
<L>Was ifoundet, good and cler;</L>
<L>&THORN;e date of vr lord him selue</L>
<L N="260">A &thorn;ousund an hundrut and twelue</L>
<L>Was, whon seint Bernard was ischore</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his bre&thorn;eren, as i seide bifore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon &thorn;is children glorious<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem Bernardus cum fratribus suis domum paternam egrederetur (265-6 Zus.),</NOTE></L>
<L>Wenten out of heor fadur hous</L>
<L N="265">Toward &thorn;e hous of Cistewes,</L>
<L>To god, for &thorn;ei wolde haue gode &thorn;ewes:</L>
<L>Gy, &thorn;at was &thorn;e furste childe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Guido primogenitus, videns Nivardum fratrem suum minimum puerum ludentem in platea cum pueris (272 Zus.): Eya, inquit, frater Nivarde, ad te solum respicit omnis terra possessionis nostrae.</NOTE></L>
<L>Say&yogh; his &yogh;onge bro&thorn;ur murie and wilde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Niuard was cald, verreyment,
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="46"></L>
<L N="270">Pley&yogh;e him vppon &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur children of his age,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lusten wel to pleye and rage.</L>
<L>He seide to him: "bro&thorn;ur Nyuard,</L>
<L>Herken &thorn;ou nou hiderward!</L>
<L N="275">To &thorn;e schal falle feld and toun,</L>
<L>Vr lond and vre possessioun".</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;ur &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;auh he were wyld,</L>
<L>He onswerd no&thorn;ing as a child:</L>
<L>"A, he seide, heuene &yogh;e schul haue</L>
<L N="280">And &yogh;e leue me lond onliche to craue?</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; in my resoun</L>
<L>&THORN;is is non euene diuisioun".</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his fadur a luytel while<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Modico igitur tempore cum patre remansit, sed fratres postmodum secutus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>He dwelled aftur wi&thorn;outen gyle,</L>
<L N="285">And aftur &thorn;at wi&thorn; deuociun</L>
<L>He suwed his bre&thorn;eren in to religiun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon Bernard hed taken his abyt,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ingressus igitur ordinem, servus Dei Bernardus ita totus in spiritum absorptus est (291) et Deo totaliter occupatus (288), ut jam nullis sensibus corporis uteretur;</NOTE></L>
<L>In God he hedde so gret dilyt</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his bodiliche witte</L>
<L N="290">Out of vse he hedde flitte,</L>
<L>And al his spiret outurliche</L>
<L>Was rauischt so heuenliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at, whon he hedde iben a &yogh;er<NOTE PLACE="foot2">jam quippe annum in cella novitiorum exegerat et adhuc an domus haberet testu|dinem, ignorabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur nouices in fer</L>
<L N="295">In an hous wi&thorn;inne &thorn;e plas</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e nouices ordeynd was,</L>
<L>He nuste neuere beo his e&yogh;e</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;eron weore a rof on hi&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e gable ende of &thorn;e churche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Multo tempore ecclesiam intrans et exiens, in capite, ubi tres erant, unam tantum putabat esse fenestram.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Ben &thorn;reo wyndouwus of noble worche:</L>
<L>Long tyme he went in and out,</L>
<L>And so luytel loked him about</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wende, bi seint Jon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er hedde ben but on.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">&THORN;E abbot &thorn;en of Sistews<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Abbas autem Cisterciensium fratres ad aedificandum domum Claraevallensem misit et iis Bernardum in abbatia praefecit,</NOTE></L>
<L>Sende monkes to Clereuaus,</L>
<L>Gode men and religious,</L>
<L>Forte builde &thorn;er an hous.</L>
<L>Tofore hem alle, God hit wot,</L>
<L N="310">He mad Bernard heore abbot.</L>
<L>&THORN;er long tyme in pouerte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">qui (sc. Bernardus, im engl. die M&ouml;nche) multo ibidem tempore in nimia paupertate degebat et pulmenta saepius ex foliis fagi conficiebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei lyueden and wi&thorn; charite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ofte &thorn;ei eten bechene leues,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er growed among &thorn;e greues.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="315">SEint Bernard wok bo&thorn;e day and niht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vigilabat autem servus Dei ultra possibilitatem humanam, nullum enim tempus se magis per|dere conqueri solebat quam quo dormivit,</NOTE></L>
<L>More &thorn;en monkuynde feire bere miht;</L>
<L>Ofte he wolde pleyne wi&thorn;outen bost</L>
<L>And sei: &thorn;er was no more tyme lost</L>
<L>&THORN;en while he lay to slepyng;</L>
<L N="320">And euere he made a liknyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">idoneam satis reputans comparatio|nem somni et mortis, ut sic dormientes videantur mortui apud homines quomodo apud Deum mortui dormientes (322 u. 326 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Bytwene slep and monnes de&thorn;:</L>
<L>"Saue onliche a luytel bre&thorn;,</L>
<L>A ded mon to God on slep is holde,</L>
<L>A slepyng mon to men is tolde</L>
<L N="325">As good as ded for &thorn;e tyme,</L>
<L>Bi niht or day, vndurne or pryme".</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he herde &thorn;erfore on route<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unde etiam, si quem forte durius stertentem audierit seu minus composite viderit jacentem, patienter ferre vix potuit et carnaliter seu seculariter eum dormire causabatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or esyliche ligge wi&thorn; clo&thorn;us aboute,</L>
<L>To him hit was so gret offence</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e he mihte his pacience
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>To constreyne, &thorn;at he nolde sei openliche<NOTE PLACE="foot1">to beim Inf. nach einem H&uuml;lfsverb, wie Ambr. 710.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hit was to wordliche</L>
<L>Or elles to muche loue of flesche,</L>
<L>A mon to kepe him self to nessche.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">absoluter Infin., wie 146. 3, 471 u. &ouml;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">He tok non hede of no dylyt<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad comedendum vix aliqua voluptate trahebatur appetitus, sed solo timore defectus sic accede|bat ad sumendum cibum quasi ad tormentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of metes, ne of appetyt,</L>
<L>But onliche to susteyne his kynde,</L>
<L>To serue his God wi&thorn; good mynde,</L>
<L>To mete he went wi&thorn; such entent</L>
<L N="340">As touward his owne turment.</L>
<L>Whon he hedde eten, he wold him bi&thorn;ink<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post cibum, quantum co|mederit semper cogitare solitus erat; si quando vel ad modicum mensuram solitam excessisse se deprehendit, impune abire non patiebatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of his mete and eke of his drynk</L>
<L>Wher he hedde don ari&yogh;t his cure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he passed not his olde mesure;</L>
<L N="345">And &yogh;if he parseyued &thorn;at he hedde so don,</L>
<L>He him repente wolde anon.</L>
<L>He kepte him so fro glotenye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sic gulae illecebras edomuerat, ut ipsam quoque saporum discretionem ex magna parte perdiderit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e more partye</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nedde discreciun ne sauour<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;at scheint zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">Of metes ne drinkes ne o&thorn;ur licour;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore o&thorn;urwhile he wolde drynke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nam et oleum, sibi per errorem aliquando propositum, bibit et penitus ignoravit, nec prius id est cognitum, donec quidam ejus labia miraretur inuncta;</NOTE></L>
<L>Oyle for watur, and nou&yogh;t &thorn;eron &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at recheles men</L>
<L>Serued him of drinken &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="355">Ne hit nas parseyued no more</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at his lippes &thorn;erof dude glore.</L>
<L>He eet ofte tyme rau blood<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sangui|nem crudum insuper, per errorem sibi oblatum, pro butyro multis diebus noscitur comedisse; solum autem aquam sibi sapere dicebat, eo quod, dum sumeret, fauces et guttur ejus refrigeraret.</NOTE></L>
<L>In stude of buttur, wi&thorn; good mod,</L>
<L>Whon he was serued rechelesliche:</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;erof he tok hit meokeliche.</L>
<L>He seide &thorn;at watur onliche</L>
<L>Sauered him verreyliche,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at hit wolde riht weel</L>
<L>His jouwes and his &thorn;rote keel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="365">AMong his frendus &thorn;at he loued wel<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidquid in scripturis didicerat, maxime in silvis et in agris meditando et orando se confitebatur accepisse (370 Zus.) et nullos se ali|quando magistros habuisse nisi quercus et fagos, inter amicos dicere solebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was wont forte tel</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his lernynge of clergye</L>
<L>Was in &thorn;enkynge and preying deuoutlye</L>
<L>Among wodus and feldes wy(l)de:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. wyde st. wylde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="370">&THORN;er he wolde wake wi&thorn; herte ful mylde;</L>
<L>Oo&thorn;ur maister hedde he non</L>
<L>But okus and beches, swi&thorn;e gret won.</L>
<L>Knowleche he wolde ofte tyme also<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Denique confessus est, aliquando meditanti vel oranti sacram omnem velut sup|positam vel expositam sibi apparuisse scripturam.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he louede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;at, whon he was in meditaciun</L>
<L>Or in preyer wi&thorn; deuociun,</L>
<L>Al maner &thorn;ing of holy writ</L>
<L>Was vndurput to his wit</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles expouned verreyli,</L>
<L N="380">Wi&thorn;outen eny maistri.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ONes he bi&thorn;ouhte him on a speche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quodam tempore (sicut ipse in canticis refert,) cum inter loquendum ex his quae suggerebat spiritus, etsi non infideli, minus tamen fidenti animo reservaret, ut haberet quid diceret, denuo tracta|turus,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e holigost dude him teche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche, &thorn;ouh he leeued hit wel,</L>
<L>He nedde hit not in mynde eueridel;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">hit nach d. Relat., nicht unh&auml;ufig.</NOTE></L>
<L N="385">&THORN;erfore he &thorn;ouhte what o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing</L>
<L>He mihte take in tretyng.</L>
<L>A vois to him &thorn;en gon sey:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ecce vox ad eum venit dicens: Donec istud tenueris, aliud non acci|pies.</NOTE></L>
<L>"In veyn &thorn;ou trauaylest, al in fey;
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>Aftur o&thorn;ur matere &thorn;ar &thorn;e nou&yogh;t craue,</L>
<L N="390">Til &thorn;at &thorn;ou holde and in muyde haue</L>
<L>&THORN;at furst was put in to &thorn;i wit.</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on &thorn;erfore and hold wel hit!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN clo&thorn;ing pouerte lyked him euere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In vestibus ei semper paupertas placuit, sordes numquam, nimirum animi fore judices ajebat (!) (aut negligentis) aut inaniter apud se gloriantis aut foris humanam gloriam affectantis; proverbium illud in ore ejus frequenter, semper in corde erat: Qui hoc facit quod nemo, mirantur omnes.</NOTE></L>
<L>But vnclennesse louede he neuere.</L>
<L N="395">Whon he sauh men wi&thorn; veyn glorie</L>
<L>Haue likyng in heore oune e&yogh;e</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles in o&thorn;ur mennes siht,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof forso&thorn;e he wolde lete liht.</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;ur wi&thorn; herte or wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="400">A prouerbe &thorn;at he riht wel cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>He wolde sey on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e mowe nou&thorn;e ihere:</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;at do&thorn; no man,</L>
<L>On him wondre&thorn; vche mon &thorn;an."</L>
<L N="405">&thorn;er tofore mony a &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unde et cilicium pluribus annis portavit, quamdiu occultum esse potuit, sed ubi hoc cognitum esse sensit, continuo illud abjiciens ad communia se convertit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Next his bodi he wered &thorn;e here,</L>
<L>As longe as hit priue was;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at he wuste men knewe &thorn;e cas,</L>
<L>From him awey he dude &thorn;e here</L>
<L N="410">And tornede to comun manere.</L>
<L>He his herte neuer cast<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nunquam sic risit, ut non potius ad ridendum quam ad reprimendum vim sibi facere oporteret et risui suo magis sti|mulum adhibere quam frenum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Inwardly to lauhwhe so fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nas bisy hit to restreyne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his mihtes and to refreyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="415">HE wolde sey ofte wi&thorn; concience<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem patientiae genus solitus erat dicere tripar|titum, videlicet ad verborum injurias, ad damna rerum, ad corporis laesionem (418. 420. 422-4 Zus.), hanc ipse his exemplis se habere probavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;reo &thorn;inges stod pacience:</L>
<L>In soffring wrong of vuel word</L>
<L>Of comun mon or of lord;</L>
<L>And in los of vre &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot1">los = loss.</NOTE></L>
<L N="420">Meble, ded o&thorn;ur lyuyng;</L>
<L>And in hurtyng of vre bodi,</L>
<L>Druye strok o&thorn;ur blodi,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles fals enprisonement &mdash;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at may &thorn;eose suffre, is pacient.</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;at he was pacient and wise,</L>
<L>Bi ensaumples he proued on &thorn;is wyse:</L>
<L>An apistle to a bisschop he wrot<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum enim cui|dam episcopo amicabiliter admonens quandam scripsisset epistolam, (430 Zus.), ille vehementer exacerbatus amarissimam scripsit ei epistolam (in principio) ita dicens: Salutem et non spiritum blasphemiae &mdash; tamquam ex spiritu blasphemiae ita scripsis|set.</NOTE></L>
<L>And him amonested, God hit wot,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; riht parfyt charite,</L>
<L N="430">A certeyn defaute he schulde fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e epistle to &thorn;e buschop was lo&thorn;,</L>
<L>He wrot a&yogh;eyn, as mon al wro&thorn;, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he him hedde scorned, wel he wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore in &thorn;e lettre &thorn;at he a&yogh;ein sende</L>
<L N="435">He ne seide good day no&thorn;ur god morn,</L>
<L>But: "sauluc&yogh; and nou&yogh;t &thorn;e spiryt of scorn".</L>
<L>Whon Bernard &thorn;is lettre vndurstood,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad quod ille: Ego spiritum blasphemiae me habere non credo nec male|dixisse cuiquam aut maledicere me velle scio, praesertim principi populi mei.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wrot a&yogh;ein wi&thorn; mylde mood:</L>
<L>"I leeue &thorn;at i haue nouht</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;e spirit of scorn, in word ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne corse no mon i can</L>
<L>Or wille to curse, child ne man,</L>
<L>And also nou&thorn;ur nomeliche</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at gouerne&thorn; principaliche</L>
<L N="445">&THORN;e peple and is souereyn &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at weore to me a werk of veyn".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN abbot him toward vppon a day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam abbas pro uno coenobio construendo sexcentas marcas eidem misit argenti, sed tota pecunia, dum deferretur, a praedonibus sublata est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Six hundred mark him sent of pay,</L>
<L>A newe abbey forte make
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="49"></L>
<L N="450">In a plas, for Godus sake.</L>
<L>Toward him as hit schulde come,</L>
<L>&THORN;eues &thorn;e men hit hedden binome.</L>
<L>Whon seint Bernard wuste of &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo audito nihil aliud dixit nisi: Benedictus Deus, qui nobis pepercit ab onere, sed et illis, inquit, qui tulerunt, levius est ferendum, tum quia hoc humana(!) cupiditas sustulit, tum quia magna pecunia magnam iis tentationis occasionem ingessit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He seide no&thorn;ing elles, iwis,</L>
<L N="455">But: "blessed beo God &thorn;at &thorn;us ha&thorn; spared</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at charge we schulde ha cared!</L>
<L>But we mosten take &thorn;e lihtor heed</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at hit toke, so God vs speed;</L>
<L>On is for &thorn;e Romayns couetyse<NOTE PLACE="foot1">lat. humana cupiditas; &uuml;ber die Raubsucht der "Romayns" vgl. Alex. Ms. Laud 622. v.571.</NOTE></L>
<L N="460">&THORN;at hit tok awey on heore wyse,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;ur is, for &thorn;e grete soun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at moneye &yogh;af hem occasiun</L>
<L>Hit to take so, witerly.</L>
<L>God of hem nou haue merci".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">VPpon a tyme he was at hom,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam in|super canonicus regularis ad eum venit et ut in monachum reciperetur instanter ro|gavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A chanoun ruleer to him com</L>
<L>And made to him a gret preyer,</L>
<L>A monk &thorn;at he wolde him scher.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard him onswered, in certeyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui quum ille non acquiesceret sed ad suam ecclesiam redire persuaderet: Ad quid ergo, ait ille, in libris tuis perfectionem tantopere commendasti, si eam non exhibes cupienti? utinam illos tuos tenerem libros, ut eos penitus lacerarem!</NOTE></L>
<L N="470">And bad him go to his churche a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chanoun him &thorn;enne gon vbbreyd</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is maner to him seid:</L>
<L>"Wherto wi&thorn; so gret deuociun</L>
<L>Hastou comendet &thorn;i religiun</L>
<L N="475">In &thorn;i bokes, as a clerk,</L>
<L>And to him &thorn;at coueyte&thorn; &thorn;at werk</L>
<L>Graunte hit &thorn;ou nult for no&thorn;ing?</L>
<L>I holde hit but a fodyng.</L>
<L>Wolde God in hond i hade</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;e bokes &thorn;erof &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast made:</L>
<L>Ful vuel &thorn;auh hit schulde &thorn;e dere,</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e i wolde hem al totere!"</L>
<L>Seint Bernard seide in good fey:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui ille: In nullo eorum legisti non posse te in tuo claustro esse perfectum; morum cor|rectionem, non locorum mutationem in libris omnibus commendavi.</NOTE></L>
<L>"In no bok. i dar wel sei,</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;at euer i made, &thorn;at &thorn;oa sauh &yogh;ite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou raddest neuure &thorn;eron iwrite</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mihtest not beo parfyt</L>
<L>In &thorn;i cloystre, &yogh;if &thorn;ou heddest delyt;</L>
<L>Of mennes maners amendyng,</L>
<L N="490">And not &thorn;e places chaungyng</L>
<L>I haue comendet in my bokus,</L>
<L>Vppon hem hose riht lokus".</L>
<L>&THORN;e chanoun was &yogh;ong and hot of blod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ille vero insanus (493 Zus.) in eum impetum faciens tam graviter maxillam ejus percussit, ut succederet rubor ictui et tumor (der Dichter las timor?) rubori.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, as a mon &thorn;at waxen weore wod,</L>
<L N="495">He smot seint Bernard vndur &thorn;e chek,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wox red and aferd ek.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at stoden abouten hem &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Iam, qui ad|erant, in sacrilegum insurgebant, sed praevenit eos servus Dei, clamans et adjurans per nomen Christi ut nullatenus tangeretur nec sibi quidquid injuriae inferretur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wolden ha risen vppon &thorn;at man,</L>
<L>But Godus seruaunt wi&thorn;outen blame</L>
<L N="500">Hem forbad on Godus name</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei schulde him non harm do</L>
<L>But let him passe feire hem fro.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at nouices schulden ben schorn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Novitiis autem intrare volentibus dicere consueverat: Si ad ea quae intus sunt festinatis, hic foris dimittite corpora quae de saeculo attulistis, soli spiritus ingredian|tur, caro autem non prodest quidquam.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem he wolde seye biforen:</L>
<L N="505">"&YOGH;if &thorn;at &yogh;e he&yogh;e nou bisyliche</L>
<L>To &thorn;ing &thorn;at beon wi&thorn;inne, deuoutliche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;or bodies wi&thorn;outen loke &thorn;ei beo laft</L>
<L>From &thorn;e world and al his craft,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e com fro, and come&thorn; in</L>
<L N="510">Onliche in spirit, wi&thorn;outen gin;</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if &yogh;e take good hede of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesch profyte&thorn; no&thorn;ing iwis".
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>HIs fadur, &thorn;at Tecelyn hedde to nome<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Pater ejus, qui solus domi reman|serat, ad monasterium ivit et ibidem post aliquod tempus in senectute bona decessit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al one was laft at home,</L>
<L N="515">To &thorn;e munster &thorn;en he went</L>
<L>And dwelled toward &thorn;at couent,</L>
<L>And afturward soone in good elde</L>
<L>To God of heuene &thorn;e gost he &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>He hedde a suster &thorn;at tyme also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Soror autem ejus, saeculo nupta, cum in divitiis et deliciis saeculi periclitaretur, quadam vice fratres suos ad monasterium visitatura accessit; cumque venisset cum comitatu et apparatu superbo (524-5 Zus.), ille eam tanquam rete dyaboli ad animas capiendas abhorruit nec ad videndam eam exire aliquatenus acquievit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="520">&THORN;at wedded was and riche &thorn;erto:</L>
<L>Vppon a day wi&thorn; gret delyte</L>
<L>Heo wente hire bre&thorn;eren to visyte.</L>
<L>Whon heo to &thorn;e abbey com,</L>
<L>Heo fond hire bre&thorn;eren alle atom;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">atom = at hom.</NOTE></L>
<L N="525">But, for heo com in stout aray,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; moni men, and hire self gay,</L>
<L>Seint Bernard wolde hire not se,</L>
<L>As a &thorn;ing of horriblete,</L>
<L>And seide: heo was lyk &thorn;e deueles nette,</L>
<L N="530">To take mennes soulus &thorn;at were isette.</L>
<L>On of hire bre&thorn;eren was porteer,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Videns illa, quod nullus fratrum suorum occurreret (535), sed ab uno eorum, qui tunc porta|rius erat, stercus involutum diceretur (531),</NOTE></L>
<L>And he hire seide: "what dostou heer?</L>
<L>&THORN;ow art lyk a toord, he seide,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a feir clo&thorn; weore leyde".</L>
<L N="535">Whon heo sauh al in certeyn</L>
<L>Non of hire bre&thorn;eren coomen hire a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>Weopynge heo seide &thorn;an:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tota in lacrymis resoluta est. Etsi peccatrix sum, inquit, pro talibus Christus mortuus est: quia enim peccatricem me sentio, idcirco consilium et colloquium bonorum requiro; et si despicit frater meus carnem meam, ne despiciat servus Dei animam meam; veniat et praecipiat, et, quid|quid praeceperit, adimplebo.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;auh i beo a sunfol womman,</L>
<L>For suche Crist dyede for his pite</L>
<L N="540">And he may haue merci on me;</L>
<L>And for i knowe my sunfolhede</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in word, &thorn;ou&yogh;t and dede,</L>
<L>I com gode men forte seche,</L>
<L>Me to counseyle and to teche.</L>
<L N="545">And &thorn;ou&yogh; my bro&thorn;ur my bodi foule</L>
<L>Dispise, &yogh;it schulde he not my soule</L>
<L>Bustousliche &thorn;us nou forsake,</L>
<L>But as Godus seruaunt hit to him take.</L>
<L>Let him come and comaunde me:</L>
<L N="550">I schal hit do, what euer hit be".</L>
<L>Whon he herde of &thorn;is biheste,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hanc ergo promissionem tenens, exiit ad eam cum fratribus (554 Zus.),</NOTE></L>
<L>To hire he wente wi&thorn;outen cheste</L>
<L>And tok wi&thorn; him his bre&thorn;eren alle,</L>
<L>Whon he hed beden hem for&thorn; calle.</L>
<L N="555">Seint Bernard wuste wel bi Godus lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et quia eam a viro separare non poterat, primo omnem ei mundi gloriam interdixit (562 Zus.) et formam matris imitandam eidem indicens (illam dimisit).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo miht not hire wi&thorn;drawe,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at hire lasted &thorn;e lyf,</L>
<L>From him &thorn;at hedde hire taken to wyf;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore wi&thorn; god mekenesse</L>
<L N="560">He hire forbed &thorn;e bisynesse</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is world, and eke &thorn;e blis</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &mdash; forso&thorn;e, nouht hit nis! &mdash;</L>
<L>And comaundet hire for Godus sake</L>
<L>Ensaumple of hire modur take</L>
<L N="565">And suwen hire in good liuyng,</L>
<L>In preyers and in fastyng.</L>
<L>Heo torned hir hom hi&yogh;ingliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Illa vero rediens ita repente mutata est, ut in medio saeculi vitam duceret eremiticam et ab omni saeculo prorsus se faceret alienam.</NOTE></L>
<L>And chaunged was al sodeynliche:</L>
<L>He tok non hede &thorn;at heo was wyf,</L>
<L N="570">But ladde holy hermites lyf,</L>
<L>As &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;e world heo hedde forsake</L>
<L>And to God hire al bitake.</L>
<L>Atte last wi&thorn; mony a preyere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tandem pre|cibus multis virum suum vicit et ab ipso (alii codd.: ab episcopo) absoluta monaste|rium intravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Heo ouercom hire hosebonde dere,</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;at he &yogh;af hire leue feir and wel</L>
<L>In an abbey for to dwel;
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>A nonne &thorn;erinne heo was ischore</L>
<L>And serued God so euermore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Infirmatus aliquando vir Dei, cum extremum jam spiritum tra|here videretur,</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme seint Bernard</L>
<L N="580">Was itaken wi&thorn; seknesse hard,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit was a comuyn sawe</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;at he dude drawe.</L>
<L>His spirit rauisched was anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">in excessu mentis suae ante tribunal Dei visus est praesentari, affuit autem et Sathan ex adverso improbis eum accusationibus pulsans.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tofore God, sittinge in tron,</L>
<L N="585">And &thorn;er was al redi &thorn;e fend Sathan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him &thorn;ere accused &thorn;an.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he his tale hedde told,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ubi vero ille omnia fuerat prosecutus et viro Dei pro sua fuit parte dicendum, nihil terri|tus aut turbatus ait:</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Bernard dredde not, but was bold</L>
<L>And seide: "for myn vnwor&thorn;ines<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fateor, non sum dignus ego, nec propriis possum meritis obtinere regnum coelorum; caeterum duplici jure illud obtinens dominus meus, here|ditate scilicet patris et merito passionis, altero ipse contentus alterum mihi donat; (ex cujus dono jure illud mihi vindicans non confundor).</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">Of meryt o&thorn;ur of goodnes</L>
<L>I knowleche wel I may not craue</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdom of heuene for to haue;</L>
<L>But for my lord ha&thorn; double riht</L>
<L>To &thorn;at kyngdom so ful of liht:</L>
<L N="595">Bi wei of heritage of his fader</L>
<L>And bi merit of his passion togeder,</L>
<L>He is wel payed of &thorn;at one,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;ur he me &yogh;af as Godus sone".</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend confuis wente awey &thorn;an,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Confusus in hoc verbo inimicus, (conventus ille solutus) et vir Dei in se reversus est (601-2 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="600">&THORN;e spirit a&yogh;ein to &thorn;at man</L>
<L>Turned: and &thorn;erwi&thorn; he awoke</L>
<L>And lyfliche aboute him he gon loke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE abstined him so wondurliche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tanta autem abstinentia, labore et vigiliis corpus suum attrivit, quod et gravis|sima et fere continua aegritudine languens conventum vix sequi posset (610 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>And trauailed and waked so bisyliche,</L>
<L N="605">His bodi he brouhte so lowe eke:</L>
<L>&THORN;at continueliche he was so nei&yogh; seke,</L>
<L>In so muchel &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e</L>
<L>Him serue nolde his oune bre&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e couent forte suwe &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="610">To &thorn;e chirche whon &thorn;ei schulde go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme wi&thorn; seknesse stronge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice dum gravissime infirmaretur, fratribus pro eo instanter orantibus aliquantulum convaluisse se sensit; congregatis autem fratribus dixit:</NOTE></L>
<L>He was itaken, &thorn;at heold him longe;</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;eren for him preyed so faste:</L>
<L>He fond him amendyng atte laste.</L>
<L N="615">Aboute him he gedred hem euerichon</L>
<L>And to hem alle he seide anon:</L>
<L>"Wherto, my bre&thorn;eren dere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quid tene|tis miserum hominem? fortiores estis et invaluistis, parcite, quaeso, parcite et sinite me abire.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wrecched mon holde &yogh;e &thorn;us here?</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben strengore &thorn;en I,</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;erfore &yogh;e han &thorn;e mastri</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &yogh;or preyere touward our God.</L>
<L>I prei&yogh;e ow alle wi&thorn; mylde mood:</L>
<L>Spare&thorn; me, i preye ou, spare&thorn; me nou</L>
<L>And lete&thorn; me passe hennes from &yogh;ou!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="625">OFte forso&thorn;e wi&thorn; good hope<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A multis autem civitatibus vir Dei in episcopum electus, prae|cipue a civitate Ianuensi et civitate Mediolanensi, petentibus se (nec annuens nec im|probe renuens) dicebat: se non esse suum (der Dichter las servum), sed aliorum servitio deputatum (634 Zus.). (Fratres autem ex consilio viri Dei sibi provide|rant et summi pontificis auctoritate muniti erant, ne quis gaudium suum ab iis tollere</NOTE></L>
<L>He was chosun to beo bisschope,</L>
<L>But specialiche of citees tweyn:</L>
<L>Ianuesse and Melayn;</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei asked his assent,</L>
<L N="630">He onswered &thorn;us, verreyment:</L>
<L>"Seruaunt, he seide, am I non,</L>
<L>But I am deputet nou al on</L>
<L>To &thorn;e seruyse of o&thorn;ur men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at as wor&thorn;i as I ben".
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="52"></L>
<L N="635">Bi counseil of seint Bernard &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolde chese hem ano&thorn;ur man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme wi&thorn; good delyte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quodam tempore cum fratres Cartusienses (640 Zus.) visitasset et ipsi ab eo in omnibus plurimum aedificati fuissent, unum fuit quod prae|dicti loci priorem aliquantulum movit, scilicet quod sella, cui equitando insidebat, minus (der Dichter las nimis?) neglecta erat (et parum praeferens paupertatem).</NOTE></L>
<L>He rod out to visyte</L>
<L>&THORN;e freres of Charthous &mdash;</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;at is an ordre glorious.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wi&thorn; gret deuocioun</L>
<L>He tauht hem good edificacioun.</L>
<L>But o &thorn;ing &thorn;er was of liht repreue</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e hous gon meue:</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;at &thorn;e sadel semed al forlet</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Bernard inne set.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;e prior tolde to<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod quum dictus prior uni ex fratribus et ille viro Dei retulisset, non minus ipse miratus, qualis esset sella, quaerebat; nam a Claravalle usque ad Cartusiam venerat et tamen, qualis esset sella, penitus ignorabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>On of his bre&thorn;eren &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;enne to seint Bernard</L>
<L N="650">Spak &thorn;erof afturward.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard &thorn;erof wondur had</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sadul bringe to him he bad;</L>
<L>He hedde riden fro Cleruous</L>
<L>Til he com to Charthous,</L>
<L N="655">What maner sadel he rod inne</L>
<L>Wuste he neuere, more ne mynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON a tyme his wey lay<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Juxta lacum Lausannensem to|tius diei itinere pergens, penitus eum non vidit (aut se videre non vidit).</NOTE></L>
<L>Al a dayes jurnay</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e lake of Lausan,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Lansan.</NOTE></L>
<L N="660">&THORN;at knowe&thorn; wel mony a man.</L>
<L>He wente so &thorn;er al in &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e lake sauh he nouht.</L>
<L>At niht whon his felawes eke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum enim sero facto de eodem lacu socii loquerentur, interrogavit eos ubinam lacus ille esset. Quod illi audientes plurimum admirati sunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at lake gunne to speke,</L>
<L N="665">He hem asked for his oune sake</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde him telle wher was &thorn;e lake.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ey so asken him herde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wondred muchel whi he so ferde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E hei&yogh;enes of his name<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vincebat sane in eo sub|limitatem nominis humilitas cordis, nec tam poterat universus eum erigere mundus quam se ipse dejicere solus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="670">Wi&thorn; meknes of herte he ouurcame;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e world miht him not reise:</L>
<L>So he him self wolde dispreyse.</L>
<L>Of men he was holden mest,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Summus reputabatur ab omnibus, infimus ipse se reputans, et quem sibi omnes, ipse se nemini praeferebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>But he him self heold aller lest;</L>
<L N="675">Eueri mon wolde him putte for&thorn;,</L>
<L>But he huld him self lest wor&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ofte tyme he wolde knowleche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Denique, sicut sae|pius fatebatur, inter summos quoque honores et favores populorum alterum sibi mutuatus (engl., als ob mutatus) hominem videbatur seque potius reputabat absentem, velut quoddam somnium suspicatus (686 Zus.);</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at, whon he herde of him gret speche</L>
<L>And was among most honour</L>
<L N="630">And in &thorn;e peples feire fauour,</L>
<L>Bi him self he &thorn;houte ri&yogh;t wel</L>
<L>As mon &thorn;at weore chaunged eueridel,</L>
<L>And he him self hedde such entent</L>
<L>&THORN;at he huld him as absent,</L>
<L N="685">And trouwed hit hedde ben a sweuen</L>
<L>&THORN;at falle&thorn; on him &thorn;at slepe&thorn; at euen.</L>
<L>But whon he was among symple men,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ubi vero simpliciores fratres erant, et amica semper humilitate frui ibi se invenisse gaudebat et in propriam rediisse per|sonam.</NOTE></L>
<L>As his bre&thorn;eren weoren &thorn;en,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte vse his mekenes</L>
<L N="690">Wi&thorn; frendschipe and goodnes:</L>
<L>&THORN;en he wolde be wondur glad,</L>
<L>As mon &thorn;at to lyf beo turned had.</L>
<L>Euere a mon mihte him fynde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Semper autem inveniebatur aut orans aut legens aut scribens aut meditans aut fratres verbo aedificans.</NOTE></L>
<L>Preyinge or redyng or writynge
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="53"></L>
<L N="695">Or in good meditacion</L>
<L>Or to his bre&thorn;eren in edificacion.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme he stod vp to preche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice cum populo praedicaret et omnes verba ejus attente ac devote susciperent, ejus animo quaedam talis irrepsit tentatio (704 Zus.): Vere nunc optime praedicas et ab hominibus libenter audiris et sapiens ab omnibus reputaris.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e peple, and hem dude teche;</L>
<L>Men herden him bisyliche</L>
<L N="700">And token his wordus deuoutliche.</L>
<L>Whil he &thorn;us was in his predicacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;er ful on him such a temptacion</L>
<L>&THORN;at to him self: him &thorn;hou&yogh;te, he seide,</L>
<L>As he auctorites for&thorn; leide:</L>
<L N="705">"For &thorn;ou prechest nou in &thorn;e best</L>
<L>And &thorn;e herkne&thorn; nou bo&thorn;e mest and lest,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e to loke &thorn;ei ben bolde,</L>
<L>Of hem alle wys &thorn;ou art holde".</L>
<L>Whon he bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him vppon &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At vir Dei tali tentatione pulsari se sentiens, parumper substitit et an procederet vel finem faceret cogitare coepit,</NOTE></L>
<L N="710">Temptacion he hit heold iwis,</L>
<L>A luytel while stille he stod</L>
<L>And bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t him on his mood</L>
<L>Wher him weore bettere for&thorn; to sey</L>
<L>Or elles let of and go his wey.</L>
<L N="715">&THORN;orwh Godus help, &thorn;at nul not fayle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">statimque divino con|fortatus auxilio tentatori silenter respondit: Nec per te incepi nec per te dimittam. sicque securus praedica ionem usque ad finem prosecutus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anon riht of good counsayle</L>
<L>To &thorn;e temptour softeliche</L>
<L>He seide &thorn;eos wordus wyslyche:</L>
<L>"Beo &thorn;e made I not my biginninge,</L>
<L N="720">Ne for &thorn;e nul I make non endynge",</L>
<L>And for&thorn; &thorn;en aftur deuoutliche</L>
<L>He prechede &thorn;e peple bisyliche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A monk ones he hedde wi&thorn; him.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Monachus quidam, qui in saeculo ribaldus fuerat atque lusor (726 Zus.), maligno stimu|latus spiritu ad saeculum redire voluit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e world was sum tym</L>
<L N="725">A ribaut and a pleyer grete,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he mihte wi&thorn; felawes mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel him tempted so, certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e world he wolde go &yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>Whon Bernard sauh he wox so bolde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem beatus Bernardus eum retinere non posset, interrogavit eum unde victurus esset.</NOTE></L>
<L N="730">&THORN;at he him no&thorn;ing mihte wi&thorn;holde,</L>
<L>He asked him, as he hedde i&thorn;riue!</L>
<L>Hou he schapt him forte lyue.</L>
<L>Anon he onswerd and gon to seye:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui respondit: Ad taxillos ludere scio et inde vivere potero.</NOTE></L>
<L>"At &thorn;e echesse i con wel pleye:</L>
<L N="735">&THORN;erwi&thorn; schal I liue riht wel</L>
<L>And winne &thorn;at me nede&thorn; eueridel".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard &thorn;en gon to him seye:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ille: Si tibi capitale commisero, vis singulis annis ad me redire et mecum lucrum dividere?</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;if i take &thorn;e &thorn;e chef moneye,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; to pleye, woltou be my feer</L>
<L N="740">And come a&yogh;ein &yogh;er bi &yogh;er</L>
<L>And parte wi&thorn; me half &thorn;i wynnyng</L>
<L>And take &thorn;e to&thorn;urdel to &thorn;i liuyng?"</L>
<L>Whon he &thorn;at herde, he was ful glad<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod ille audiens ga|visus est et se libenter sic acturum promisit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erof wi&thorn; him god couenaunt mad.</L>
<L N="745">Seint Bernard in hy&yogh;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Viginti igitur solidos ei dari prae|cepit, et ille cum illis abiit. Hoc autem faciebat vir sanctus, ut eum iterum revocare posset, sicut et postmodum factum est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comaundet him twenti schilyng.</L>
<L>He &thorn;enne &thorn;erwi&thorn; went his wey,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his felawes in &thorn;e world to pley.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard dude &thorn;is, for certeyn,</L>
<L N="750">Forte make him come a&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L>And so hit ful &thorn;e nexte &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Anon riht as &yogh;e schul here.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon went aboute faste to pleye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ille igitur abiens totum perdidit (756 hu|mor. Zus.) et ad portam confusus rediit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lost faste his moneye,</L>
<L N="755">Atte laste he lost al togedere</L>
<L>And leue hedde to pley him wi&thorn; a fedre.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbey &yogh;ate &thorn;en he went,</L>
<L>As a mon wor&thorn;i beo schent.</L>
<L>Whon seint Bernard &thorn;erof herde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quo audito vir Dei ad eum laetus exiit extenditque gremium, ut simul dividerent lucrum.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="54"></L>
<L N="760">Ful gladly out to him he ferde</L>
<L>And huld his lappe abrod, lau&yogh;whyng,</L>
<L>And asked him half his wynnyng.</L>
<L>He seide: "fadur, nay nay,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui ille: Nihil, pater, lucra|tus sum, sed etiam capitali nostro nudatus sum; si vultis, pro nostro capitali recipite me.</NOTE></L>
<L>But I haue lost vr chef monay.</L>
<L N="765">I preye ow for charite,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at moneye tac nou me".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard of his godnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui Bernardus benigne respondit: Si ita, inquit, est, melius est ut hoc reci|piam, quam simul utrumque perdam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seide &thorn;us to him wi&thorn; mekenesse:</L>
<L>"Se&thorn;&thorn;e hit is so, beter me is</L>
<L N="770">Take &thorn;e, &thorn;en leose al at onus".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Bernard to a place wolde go,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice dum beatus Bernardus ju|mento insidens aliquo pergeret, cuidam rustico, materia sic se offerente, de cordis instabilitate in oratione est conquestus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon his hors he set him &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;e wei as he rod,</L>
<L>He mette wi&thorn; a boistes mon of mod;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">boystes st. boystous.</NOTE></L>
<L N="775">For&thorn; wi&thorn; him &thorn;en gon he walke,</L>
<L>Of diuerse maters &thorn;ei gunne to talke.</L>
<L>Atte laste, wi&thorn;outen fable,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei speken hou a mon schulde beo stable</L>
<L>And &thorn;enke vppon non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="780">Whyl he weore in his preying.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cheorl &thorn;erof hedde dispyt<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod ille audiens mox eum despexit et in orationibus suis cor firmum et stabile habere se dixit (im engl. andere Wendung).</NOTE></L>
<L>And bad he schulde him nou&yogh;t edwyt,</L>
<L>He seide his herte was al stable,</L>
<L>"And forte preye hit is nou&yogh;t able,</L>
<L N="785">But hit beo wi&thorn;outen eny lettyng</L>
<L>Of eny o&thorn;ur maner &thorn;yng".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard caste &thorn;enne anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Volens autem Bernardus eum convincere et a sua temeritate coercere, dixit: Se|questare paulisper a nobis et tota qua poteris intentione orationem dominicam in|choato: quam si absque aliqua cordis intentione et vagatione finire poteris, jumentum, cui insideo, tuum procul dubio mox habebis; tu autem mihi in fide tua spondeas, quod si aliud ibidem cogitaveris, hoc mihi aliquatenus non celabis.</NOTE></L>
<L>To ouercome his presumpcion;</L>
<L>"&THORN;at i schal seo", he seide, "parde!</L>
<L N="790">Wi&thorn;drauh &thorn;e sumwhat from me,</L>
<L>&THORN;i pater noster loke &thorn;ou biginne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e entent &thorn;at &thorn;e is inne;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou mowe wi&thorn; stable mende</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen lettyng make an ende,</L>
<L N="795">&THORN;e hors, forso&thorn;e, &thorn;at i on sit,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou so&thorn; seye, &thorn;ow schalt haue hit!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt bihote me bi &thorn;i fey</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;e so&thorn;e sey".</L>
<L>&THORN;en wox he a wel glad monne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Laetatus ille et tamquam jumentum jam lucratum se reputans, audacter secedit et se ipsum recolli|gens orationem dominicam dicere inchoavit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="800">His hors he wende he hedde wonne.</L>
<L>Hardiliche he wente him fro,</L>
<L>His pater noster bigon he &thorn;o</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; as god wille and talent</L>
<L>As he cou&thorn;e, and good entent.</L>
<L N="805">He nas vnne&thorn;e &thorn;e middel ipast,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vix orationis explevit dimidium, et ecce importuna cogitatio de sella cordi suo se ingerit, utrum eam habere debeat cum jumento.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at in his herte anon he cast</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er he mihte &thorn;e sadel craue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e hors &thorn;at he schulde haue.</L>
<L>Whon he abreid out of &thorn;at &thorn;ouht,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod ille advertens concitus ad Bernardum rediit (810 Zus.) et quid in ipsa oratione sollicite cogitaverit indicavit, et de se postea temere non prae|sumsit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="810">He wuste wel he was wor&thorn;i nouht.</L>
<L>He wente for&thorn; to &thorn;at holy mon</L>
<L>And tolde al to gedre &thorn;on</L>
<L>What mater ful in his mende,</L>
<L>His pater noster or he mihte ende,</L>
<L N="815">And &yogh;af him to deuocioun,</L>
<L>Forsok eke his presumpcioun.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">771-816) Dieselbe Erz&auml;hlung findet sich in der Evangeliensammlung des Ms. Vernon.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE hedde ischoren his kinnes man,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Frater Robertus ejus monachus et secundum saeculum propinquus in ado|lescentia sua quorundam persuasione deceptus Cluniacum se contulerat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at frere Robert men called &thorn;an:</L>
<L>&THORN;at men brouhten aftur in such deuocion
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="55"></L>
<L N="820">&THORN;at he wente to &thorn;e abbey of Cloun;</L>
<L>He wende he hedde idon riht wel,</L>
<L>And was bigyled eueridel.</L>
<L>His fadur was war of &thorn;at gyle<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vene|rabilis autem pater postquam aliquamdiu dissimulavit, eundem statuit per epistolam revocare.</NOTE></L>
<L>And suffrede hit a luytel whyle,</L>
<L N="825">But he him bi&thorn;ou&yogh;te atte laste</L>
<L>And him to reuoken &thorn;en he caste</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbeye, as he wel wust,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at he was ischoren furst.</L>
<L>As Bernard a lettre gon to endyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quam cum sub divo dictaret et alius monachus eam ex ore suo con|scriberet, subito inopinatus imber erupit, et hic qui scribebat chartam complicare vo|luit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="830">Ano&thorn;er monk also hit to write:</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei seten &thorn;er oute, in certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;er fel a gret drift of reyn;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;e lettre a writen scholde,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">a = ha, haue.</NOTE></L>
<L>For fere togedere he gan hit folde.</L>
<L N="835">To him &thorn;en seyde seint Bernard:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui Bernardus: Opus Dei est, scribere ne formides. Scripsit ergo epistolam in medio imbre sine imbre; cum enim undique plueret, (ibidem tamen molestiam im|bris virtus expulit caritatis).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Loke &thorn;ou beo no&thorn;ing aferd</L>
<L>To write for&thorn;, as a clerk,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is is nou Godus werk".</L>
<L>Among al &thorn;e reyn &thorn;e lettre he wrot:</L>
<L N="840">&THORN;eron ful no drope, God hit wot,</L>
<L>Hit reyned aboute oueral,</L>
<L>But &thorn;eron ful nou&thorn;ur gret ne smal.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN a munstre &thorn;at he hedde mad,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum quoddam monasterium, quod vir Dei con|struxerat, occupasset muscarum incredibilis multitudo, ita ut omnibus gravem mole|stiam generarent, ille dixit: Ego excommunico eas. Mane autem omnes pariter mortuas invenerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a couent of beryng sad,</L>
<L N="845">Hit biful &thorn;at mony anuy&yogh;es</L>
<L>&THORN;ey hedden &thorn;erin &thorn;orwh noumbre of fli&yogh;es.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at com to Bernardus ere,</L>
<L>"I hem curse", he seide, "al in fere".</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwe alle weore founde</L>
<L N="850">Ded liggyng vppon &thorn;e grounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme &thorn;e pope him sent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum a summo pontifice Mediolanum missus fuisset, ut ipsos cum ecclesia reconciliaret, et jam Papiam rediisset (856-7 Zus.),</NOTE></L>
<L>To Melan to &thorn;is entent,</L>
<L>&THORN;er to dwelle a luytel whyle,</L>
<L>Hem and heore chirche to reconcyle</L>
<L N="855">&THORN;at dwelleden in &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey hedden trespassed, parde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at dede he dude deuoutelye</L>
<L>And was tornd a&yogh;eyn to Papye.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cite &thorn;er was a mon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quidam uxorem suam daemoniacam ad eum adduxit,</NOTE></L>
<L N="860">&THORN;at hedde to wyf an old wommon</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fend so cumbred had</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo was verrey wod and mad.</L>
<L>In hope of hele to seynt Bernard</L>
<L>He hire brouhte afturward.</L>
<L N="865">Anon riht in &thorn;at tyde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">moxque per os miserae mulieris diabolus in contumelias ejus prorupit, dicens: Non me de agnicula (Graesse: ani|cula) mea hic porrulos edens et brassicas devorans (sc. Bernardus, der Dichter bezieht diese Attribute auf agnicula) pellet.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e wommones mou&thorn; he gan chide<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. wommons.</NOTE></L>
<L>To seint Bernard and gan to seyn:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou schalt not putte me out a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is luttel schepes bodi,</L>
<L N="870">&THORN;at gnawe&thorn; lekes a(n)d weodes wi&thorn; foly".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. ad st. and.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Bernard bad hem denoutely<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At vir Dei ipsam ad ecclesiam beati Syri remisit,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e churche of seint Syri</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde hire lede tofore &thorn;at mele,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at heo mihte geten hire hele.</L>
<L N="875">But seynt Syri on Godus part<NOTE PLACE="foot2">beatus autem Syrus hospiti suo deferre voluit nec eidem aliquid curationis impendit, sicque iterum ad beatum Bernardum adducta est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ouhte to do worschipe to seint Bernard,</L>
<L>And lete hire passe as heo com.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei tornd alle a&yogh;ein hom,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>And a&yogh;eyn to seint Bernard</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;ey hire ladden afturward.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend seide &thorn;an wi&thorn; gret schout:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc diabolus per os ejus garrire coepit ac dicere: Non me expellet Syrulus nec ejiciet Bernardinus (Ed. pr. Bernardus).</NOTE></L>
<L>"Seint Syri me na&thorn; not cast out,</L>
<L>Ne Bernard schal neuer &thorn;e mo".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard onswered anon riht &thorn;o:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad haec servus Dei respondit: Nec Syrus nec Bernardus te ejiciet, sed dominus Jesus Christus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="885">"Nou&thorn;ur Syry ne Bernard &thorn;e schal out cast,</L>
<L>But Jhesus Crist atte laste".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard made his orisoun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mox ut ille ora|tionem effudit, spiritus nequam dixit: Quam libenter egrederer ab hac anicula, gra|viter molestatus in ea! quam libenter egrederer! sed non possum, quia nonvult magnus dominus.</NOTE></L>
<L>To God wi&thorn; gret deuocioun:</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e fend &thorn;en gon to sey:</L>
<L N="890">"Ful fayn wolde i go my wey</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is luytel croume brid</L>
<L>&THORN;er mony day i haue me hid,</L>
<L>For nou i suffre muche wo,</L>
<L>And fayn wolde I henne go,</L>
<L N="895">But i may not haue mi miht</L>
<L>For &thorn;e grete lord of riht".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard &thorn;enne asked &thorn;is word:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui sanctus: Et quis est magnus dominus? Cui ille: Jesus Nazarenus. Ad quem vir Dei: Vidistine unquam eum? Quo respondente: Etiam, &mdash; ait: Ubi eum vidisti? Et ille: In gloria. Et sanctus: Et tu in gloria fuisti? Quo re|spondente: Utique, &mdash; ait: Quomodo inde exiisti? Et ille: Cum Lucifero multi ceci|dimus. Haec autem omnia voce lugubri per os vetulae omnibus audientibus loque|batur. Dixitque ei vir Dei: Numquid in illam gloriam redire velles? At ille miro modo cachinnans ait: Modo tarde est.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Who is &thorn;at ilke grete lord?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend onswerde wi&thorn; foul bre&thorn;:</L>
<L N="900">"Hit is Jhesus of Nazare&thorn;".</L>
<L>"Bernard him asked for &thorn;e nones:</L>
<L>"Sauh &thorn;ou him euere? sei me at ones!"</L>
<L>And he onswerde &thorn;enne a&yogh;eyn:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, &yogh;e haue i him seyn".</L>
<L N="905">"Where?" qua&thorn; Bernard, "tel me &thorn;is!"</L>
<L>And he onswerde and seide: "in blis".</L>
<L>"In blis", qua&thorn; Bernard, "hastou be?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, wite &thorn;ou &thorn;at riht wel! "qua&thorn; he.</L>
<L>"Hou", qua&thorn; Bernard, "ful &thorn;ou &thorn;er fro?"</L>
<L N="910">"Wi&thorn; Lucifer", qua&thorn; he, "and moni mo".</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eose wordus brode and cou&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend spac wi&thorn; &thorn;e wommones mou&thorn;.</L>
<L>Bernard seide: "&thorn;en tel me &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Woldustou not gon a&yogh;ein to blis?"</L>
<L N="915">He made a mouwe, &thorn;at foule mate,</L>
<L>And seide: "nou&thorn;e hit is to late".</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh preyere of seint Bernard &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc orante viro Dei daemon de muliere exiit. Sed cum vir Dei inde recessisset, diabolus iterum ipsam invasit; vir autem ejus post eum accurrens, quod acciderat indicavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He went out of &thorn;at womman.</L>
<L>But as sone as Bernard was gon,</L>
<L N="920">In to &thorn;e wommon he wente anon.</L>
<L>Hire hosebonde &thorn;enne anon riht</L>
<L>Aftur him ran wi&thorn; fot liht</L>
<L>And tolde him in &thorn;at plas</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at &thorn;e fend icomen a&yogh;eyn was.</L>
<L N="925">Seynt Bernard him tok a luyte bok,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ille autem collo ejus alligari chartulam continentem haec verba praecepit: In nomine domini nostri Jesu Christi praecipio tibi, daemon, ne hanc mulierem amodo contingere praesu|mas.</NOTE></L>
<L>A scrouwe iwriten on to lok,</L>
<L>And bad him byde not to longe</L>
<L>Aboute hire nekke hit forte honge.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at scrouwe was no more ne min</L>
<L N="930">But &thorn;eose wordus on latin:</L>
<L>In nomine domini nostri Jhesu Cristi pre|cipio tibi, demon, ne hanc mulierem amodo contingere presumas &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei vnto &thorn;e ende:</L>
<L>"I &thorn;e comaunde, &thorn;ou foule fende,</L>
<L>In vr lord Jhesu Cristes name,</L>
<L>&THORN;is wommon &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne touche ne tame &mdash;</L>
<L N="935">No more loke &thorn;ou beo so hardi".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e hosbonde hedde so don so&thorn;ly,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod cum factum fuisset, ad eam postea non est ausus accedere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fend nas so hardi afturward</L>
<L>To come a&yogh;ein, for seint Bernard.
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>AT Aquitayne was a wommon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Apud Aquitaniam quaedam mulier miserabilis erat, quae a quodam daemone petulante et incubo vexabatur. Sex enim annis abusus est ea et incredibili vexavit libidine.</NOTE></L>
<L N="940">&THORN;at a fend hedde so bigon</L>
<L>And idon so gret anuye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; hire he dude lecherye &mdash;</L>
<L>Such a fend, as &thorn;e bok telle&thorn; vs,</L>
<L>Is icalled Incubus.</L>
<L N="945">Sixe &yogh;er so he hire schent</L>
<L>And dude wi&thorn; hire his talent.</L>
<L>Hit bifel vppon a day<NOTE PLACE="foot">Adveniente autem illuc viro Dei, daemon mulieri, ne ad eum accede|ret, vehementer minatur, quia nil ei prodesse posset et recedente eo ipse, qui fuit ejus amator, crudelissimus fieret persecutor.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Bernard was comen to &thorn;at cuntray.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend hir bad "beo not so hardi</L>
<L N="950">Seint Bernard &thorn;at &thorn;ou come not ny&yogh;";</L>
<L>He seide hit schulde hire profyte nouht,</L>
<L>And seide he hedde cast in his &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if &thorn;at heo wente to him,</L>
<L>He wolde to hire beo ful grim</L>
<L N="955">And, riht as he hedde loued hire wel,</L>
<L>He wolde hire pursuwe fers and cruel.</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;e wommon &thorn;on<NOTE PLACE="foot">At illa secure ad virum Dei accessit et, quae pateretur, cum multo gemitu enarravit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wente to &thorn;at holy mon</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; seruhfol wepyng</L>
<L N="960">Tolde him &thorn;e maner of doyng.</L>
<L>"Wommon, he seide, in &thorn;e nome of &thorn;e trinite<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cui ille: Tolle hunc meum ba|culum et in tuo lectulo pone, et, si quid agere potest, agat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tac nou here my staf to &thorn;e</L>
<L>And in &thorn;i bed loke &thorn;ou hit lay;</L>
<L>What he may do &thorn;enne, let him assay".</L>
<L N="965">&THORN;e wommon to bedde wente &thorn;at niht<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quod cum fecisset et in lectulo suo recumberet, adest ille continuo; sed nec ad consuetum opus nec ad ipsum cubile praesumit accedere, sed acerrime minatur, quod illo recedente se de ea atro|citer vindicabit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leide &thorn;at staf bi hire doun riht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend &thorn;enne com anon,</L>
<L>Riht as he was iwont to don,</L>
<L>But he nas not so hardi</L>
<L N="970">Hire bed to neihe, to ligge hire by,</L>
<L>But he hir manased &thorn;enne anon</L>
<L>Heo schulde abugge, wer Bernard gon.</L>
<L>Whon heo to seint Bernard tolde &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Quod cum illa Bernardo retulisset, ille populum convocavit et omnes candelas in manu accensas habere praecepit daemonemque cum universo qui aderat coetu excommunicavit ac ne ad illam vel aliam deinceps accessum haberet interdixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He called &thorn;e peple togedere iwis</L>
<L N="975">And bad &thorn;at vche mon schulde fonde,</L>
<L>A brennynge candel holde in his honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wi&thorn; candel, bok and belle</L>
<L>&THORN;ey corsud &thorn;e foule fend of helle</L>
<L>And comaunded him in Godus name</L>
<L N="980">He schulde no more hir neih&yogh;e ne blame.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was &thorn;e wommon wi&thorn; good entent<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sicque illa a tali illusione penitus liberata est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Delyuered of &thorn;at encumbrement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E pope him sende, in certayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cum in eadem provincia vir sanctus legatione fungeretur, ut ducem Aquitaniae ecclesiae recon|ciliaret, et ille modis omnibus reconciliari renueret,</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e prouince of Aquitayn,</L>
<L N="985">&THORN;e duyk &thorn;erof, &thorn;at corsud was,</L>
<L>To reconcyle: &thorn;at was &thorn;e cas &mdash;</L>
<L>And meke to beo to holy churche.</L>
<L>But he forsok &thorn;at werk to worche.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard to &thorn;e auter went,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vir Dei ad altare celebra|turus accessit, ipso duce tamquam excommunicato prae foribus exspectante.</NOTE></L>
<L N="990">To make &thorn;e holi sacrament,</L>
<L>And, while his masse he was aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;e corsud duyk stod &thorn;e churche wi&thorn;oute.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e masse was come so neih<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cum autem Pax domini dixit, corpus dominicum super patenam ponit et secum tollit atque ignea facie et flammeis oculis foras egreditur et verbis terribilibus comitem aggreditur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Bernard seide Pax domini,</L>
<L N="995">Goddus bodi he tok &thorn;en</L>
<L>And leyde vppon &thorn;e paten,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; furi face and brennyng e&yogh;e</L>
<L>He bar hit to &thorn;e duyk in hei&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>To him &thorn;enne &thorn;eos wordus he spake</L>
<L N="1000">And seide: "vre wordus and us &thorn;ou hast forsake,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Rogavimus te, inquit, et sprevisti nos; ecce ad te processit virginis filius, qui est dominus ecclesiae quam tu persequeris; adest judex tuus, in cujus nomine omne genu curvatur; adest judex tuus, in cujus manibus illa anima tua deveniet; numquid et ipsum sicut servos ejus contemnes? resiste ei, si vales (1015-6 Wiederholung).</NOTE></L>
<L>We haue &thorn;e preyed, &thorn;ou wolt not here.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore loke and seo nou heere</L>
<L>&THORN;at maydenes sone is and lord ful riht</L>
<L>Of holichurche, and God of miht,</L>
<L N="1005">&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast pursuwed so longe.</L>
<L>Aske merci and vndurfonge:</L>
<L>Heer is &thorn;i juge, seo and fele,</L>
<L>To whom on kneo vche mon schal knele;</L>
<L>Heer is &thorn;i juge hol and sum,</L>
<L N="1010">In to whos hond &thorn;i soule schal cum.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">cum aus com corrigirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him nou forsake o&thorn;ur dispyse</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wolt not on &thorn;e same wyse</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou hast herbifore</L>
<L>Hem &thorn;at to &thorn;e han spoken herfore!</L>
<L N="1015">For Goddes seruauns &thorn;ou wolt not here,</L>
<L>I haue &thorn;e brouht him self, &thorn;i lord, lo here!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou maiht wi&thorn; eny riht</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;stonde, let seo nou al &thorn;i miht!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Statimque dux totus irriguit et membris omnibus dissolutis ad pedes ejus proti|nus prosiluit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e duyk wox &thorn;enne swi&thorn;e sore aferd</L>
<L N="1020">And qwok, hond, foot and berd,</L>
<L>Doun at his feet &thorn;er he fil,</L>
<L>Meoke, to suffre al maner skil.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard &thorn;enne, as he stod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quem vir sanctus calce pulsans surgere jubet et Dei audire senten|tiam. Ille autem (engl. emperour f&uuml;r duyk) tremebundus surrexit et quidquid vir sanctus praecipiebat, protinus adimplevit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Put him a luytel wi&thorn; his fot</L>
<L N="1025">And bad him rise, wi&thorn; good reuerence</L>
<L>To here Godus sentence.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour ros vp wi&thorn; gret fere<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Emperour, hier gesagt vom Herzog.</NOTE></L>
<L>And herkned wel wi&thorn; herte and ere</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at euere seint Bernard bad,</L>
<L N="1030">And parfourned hit wi&thorn; herte ful sad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme, al in certayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum regnum Germaniae pro qua|dam magna sedanda discordia servus Dei intrasset,</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e kyngdom of Germayn</L>
<L>Seint Bernard tok &thorn;e wey for&thorn;word,</L>
<L>For to seese a gret disscord</L>
<L N="1035">&THORN;at was &thorn;er amongus hom.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;a(t) he &thorn;ider com,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;a st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e erchebisschop a&yogh;ein him sent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">archiepiscopus quidam (so Ed. princ., Graesse liest Moguntinensis) venerabilem quendam clericum obviam ei misit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wor&thorn;i clerk of good entent,</L>
<L>Him to welcome curteisliche</L>
<L N="1040">In to &thorn;at ilke bisschopriche.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e clerk seynt Bernard mette,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui dum clericus se sibi obviam a suo domino missum fuisse diceret, vir Dei respondit: Alius dominus misit te.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loueliche &thorn;enne he him grette</L>
<L>And seide: his lord him sente had,</L>
<L>Him to welcome wi&thorn; herte glad.</L>
<L N="1045">Seint Bernard onswerd wi&thorn; dim entent:</L>
<L>"Ano&thorn;ur lord, sire, &thorn;e ha&thorn; sent".</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk wondred gretly &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Miratus ille, se nonnisi a suo domino ar|chiepiscopo missum fuisse affirmabat (engl. dir.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his wordus, whi he seide so,</L>
<L>And seide: "sire, al wi&thorn; good hope</L>
<L N="1050">From my lord &thorn;e erchebisschope</L>
<L>I am sent ow a&yogh;ayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &yogh;or comynge is riht fayn".</L>
<L>Seint Bernard seide &yogh;it eftsonus<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Econtra servus Christi dicebat: Falleris, fili, falleris; major dominus est qui misit te, Christus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Qweynte wordus for &thorn;e nonus:</L>
<L N="1055">"&THORN;ou art bigyled, sone dere,</L>
<L>For a grettore lord wi&thorn;outen were</L>
<L>Sent &thorn;e to me aftur his list:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is vr lord Jhesu Crist".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e clerk &thorn;is vndurstod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod clericus intelligens ait: Putas, quod monachus velim fieri? absit hoc a me! non cogitavi nec adscendit super cor meum.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="59"></L>
<L N="1060">He onswerde wi&thorn; milde mod:</L>
<L>"Wenestou a monk &thorn;at i wolde be?</L>
<L>God hit forbeode &thorn;at falle on me!</L>
<L>Hit com neuer &yogh;it in my &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Ne in myn herte falle schal hit nouht".</L>
<L N="1065">But as &thorn;ei wolken bi &thorn;e wey,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Quid plura?) In eodem itinere saeculo valefecit et a viro Dei habitum suscepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Bernard tornde his herte, in fey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;e world &thorn;enne al forsok</L>
<L>And habyt of monk of him he tok.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme &thorn;orwh Goddus miht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum quendam militem valde nobilem ad or|dinem recepisset, et virum Dei quodam tempore sequeretur, gravissima coepit tenta|tione pulsari.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1070">Seint Bernard hed schoren in a kniht</L>
<L>&THORN;at in werres tofore hedde iswonke</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne was bicome a monke.</L>
<L>Hit bifel sone afturward</L>
<L>&THORN;at, as he folewed seint Bernard,</L>
<L N="1075">Sodeynliche ful him vppon</L>
<L>A wonder gret temptacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;at made him wondur sori</L>
<L>And of cher ful dreri.</L>
<L>On of his bre&thorn;eren asked him &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem eum quidam de fratribus tam tristem videret, causam tantae tristitiae requisivit. Cui ille respondit: Scio, inquit, scio, quod nunquam am|plius laetus ero.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1080">What him mihte beo, to loke so.</L>
<L>He onswerde wondurliche</L>
<L>And seide: "i wot wel sikerliche,</L>
<L>Heraftur schal i not, parde,</L>
<L>Neuer in herte muri be".</L>
<L N="1085">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur monk in gret hi&yogh;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod verbum cum dictus frater ad servum Dei retulisset, ille pro eo attentius oravit, statimque ille frater, qui tam graviter tentatus et tam tristis erat, tantum caeteris apparuit jucundior et hilarior quantum prius caeteris tristior.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tolde seint Bernard his seying.</L>
<L>Bernard preyed God wi&thorn; deuocion</L>
<L>His monk delyuere of &thorn;at temptacion.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e monk wox al muri</L>
<L N="1090">&THORN;at tofore was so sori,</L>
<L>And gladdore of chere &thorn;en eni o&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>&THORN;en a monk, on was his bro&thorn;ur,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem ei (dictus) frater verbum moestitiae, quod locutus fuerat, amicabiliter improperaret, ille respondit et dixit: Etsi tunc dixi: numquam amplius laetus ero, sed nunc dico: nunquam amplius tristis ero.</NOTE></L>
<L>Blamed him for his heuynes</L>
<L>And bad him &thorn;enke on holynes.</L>
<L N="1095">"I seyde and onswerde sum tyme to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at i schulde neuer glad be,</L>
<L>But nou i sey, sikerly,</L>
<L>In herte schal i neuer beo sori".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Irelond dwelled, sikerly,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum sanctus Malachius, episco|pus Hyberniae, cujus vitam plenam virtutibus ipse descripsit (1101 Zus.), ad Christum feliciter in monasterio suo migrasset, et vir Dei pro eo hostiam salutarem offerret (1105-6 Erkl. des Dichters),</NOTE></L>
<L N="1100">A bisschop, was called seint Malachi,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Bernard louede wel</L>
<L>And endyted his lyf eueridel.</L>
<L>Whon seint Malachi ded was,</L>
<L>Bernard for him song an hei&yogh; mas &mdash;</L>
<L N="1105">Of Requiem i trouwe hit were,</L>
<L>For a miracle &thorn;at ful &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>God schewed to Bernard iwis<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gloriam ejus Deo revelante cognovit et eodem inspirante post communionem formam orationis mutavit (1113-4 Zus.), laeta voce sic dicens: Deus qui beatum Malachium sanctorum tuorum meritis coae|quasti, tribue, quaesumus, ut, qui pretiosae mortis ejus festa agimus, vitae quoque imitemur exempla.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at Malachi was in blis,</L>
<L>And enspired him of an orisoun,</L>
<L N="1110">To seyn at his post-comoun.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e post-comoun was isonge,</L>
<L>He chaunged his orisoun wi&thorn; his tonge</L>
<L>Of Requiem &thorn;at he schulde seie,</L>
<L>And seide of seint Malachie:</L>
<L>Deus qui beatum Maluchiam sanctorum</L>
<L>tuorum meritis coequasti, tribue quesumus</L>
<L>ut qui preciose mortis eius festa agimus uite</L>
<L>quoque imitemur exempla, per Cristum.</L>
<L N="1115">&THORN;e chauntur hedde gret wondring<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui dum cantor innueret quod erraret, ait: Non erro, sed novi quod dico. Deinde accedens sacra ejus vestigia osculatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he fayled of his seying,</L>
<L>And made signe, as he stod a ferre:
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>Of his orisoun he dude erre.</L>
<L>And he seide: "i wot wel</L>
<L N="1120">&THORN;at i erre neuer a del".</L>
<L>&THORN;e chauntur ful adoun al mete</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grounde, to cusse his fete.</L>
<L>ONus in a lenton tym<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum, instante quadragesima, a multis fuisset tironibus(!) visitatus, iogavit eos ut in illis saltem sacris diebus a suis vanitatibus et lasciviis abstinerent.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men of Tirone visyted him.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Tirone als Eigenname, vgl. Susurron in Paula V. 52.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1125">&THORN;en he hem preyed goodliche</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde hem abstine deuoutliche</L>
<L>Vppon hei&yogh;e feste dawes</L>
<L>From vanytes and nice plawes.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei nolden on none maner<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quibus nullo modo acquiescentibus, jussit iis propinari vinum, dicens: Bibite poculum animarum. (1136 Zus.) 1137 Quo hausto, subito mutati recedunt et, qui modicum tempus dene|gaverant, totum tempus vitae suae Deo dederunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1130">Graunten him his preyer.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he comaundet hem &thorn;e wyn,</L>
<L>Such as he hedde, good and fyn.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at &thorn;e coupe was brouht,</L>
<L>He seide, as hit was in his &thorn;ouht:</L>
<L N="1135">"Drynke&thorn; nou &yogh;or soules drynke!"</L>
<L>&THORN;en on &thorn;at word &thorn;ei gonne to &thorn;enke.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei hedden dronke sweteliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weoren al chaunged, verreiliche:</L>
<L>Of wyldenesse tok &thorn;ei non hede,</L>
<L N="1140">But serued God, to gete hem mede.</L>
<L>ATte laste &thorn;e day com nei&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tandem beatus Bernardus morti feliciter appropinquans, ait fratribus suis:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Bernard schulde on dy&yogh;e.</L>
<L>To his bre&thorn;eren &thorn;en he gon say:</L>
<L>"&THORN;reo &thorn;inges loke &yogh;e kepe al way,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tria vobis observanda relin|quo, quae in stadio praesentis vitae, quo cucurri, memini me pro viribas observasse: nemini scandalum facere volui et, si aliquando incidit, celavi ut potui; minus semper sensui meo quam alterius credidi; laesus de laedente nunquam vindictam expetii: ecce caritatem, humili atem et pa ientiam vobis relinquo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1145">&THORN;at I haue kept in my liuyng,</L>
<L>As I leeue to my wityng:</L>
<L>I nolde neuere sclaundre more ne lesse</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if eny aros, I wolde hit cesse;</L>
<L>I &yogh;af lasse credence to myn owne wit</L>
<L N="1150">&THORN;en to o&thorn;ur mennes &yogh;it;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at me hurted eny mon,</L>
<L>Veniaunce &thorn;erof asked i non.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &yogh;e kepen wel also</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;reo same &thorn;inges euermo,</L>
<L N="1155">&THORN;at is: charite and mekenesse</L>
<L>And pacient beo to more and lesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;inges i leue to &yogh;ou,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore kepe&thorn; hem riht wel nou!"</L>
<L>MIracles he wrouht in toun and felde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Denique postquam multa miracula perpetrasset et CLX monasteria construxisset multosque libros et tracta|tus compilasset (1162 Zus.), consummatis vitae suae diebus circiter LXIII annis anno domini MCLIII inter filiorum manus obdormivit in domino.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1160">An hundred and sixti munstres he belde,</L>
<L>Bokus and tretes he compyled</L>
<L>And mony a mon he reconcyled.</L>
<L>Heer in &thorn;is world liuede he</L>
<L>Aboute sixti wintres and &thorn;re.</L>
<L N="1165">He lafte &thorn;is lyf and speche of word</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;eer of &thorn;e date of vr lord</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousund and hundred fifti and &thorn;re,</L>
<L>And from his bre&thorn;eren passed he,</L>
<L>To God, &thorn;at is of mihtes most,</L>
<L N="1170">Deuoutliche he &yogh;ald &thorn;e gost.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at he was ded, iwis,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post obitum suum multis gloriam suam manifestavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mony a mon he schewed his blis.</L>
<L>TO an abbot of an abbay<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cuidam enim abbati in quodam mo|nasterio apparuit et ut sequeretur admonuit. Qui abbas cum sequeretur, dixit ei vir Dei: Ecce ad montem Libani venimus, et tu hic manebis, ego autem illuc adscendam.</NOTE></L>
<L>He apered: &thorn;at he wel say &mdash;</L>
<L N="1175">And bad him anon riht &thorn;are</L>
<L>Him to suwe he schulde not spare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot dude as he him bad,</L>
<L>And for&thorn; wi&thorn; him &thorn;en he him lad.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne sone aftur hit biful
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="61"></L>
<L N="1180">&THORN;at &thorn;ei comen to a gret hul.</L>
<L>Seint Bernard seide: "to me entende,</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;is hul i mote astende,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. a stende st. ascende.</NOTE></L>
<L>But i &thorn;e telle wi&thorn;outen weer</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most dwelle stille riht heer".</L>
<L N="1185">&THORN;e abbot him asked &thorn;enne, wharto<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Interrogatus ab eo ad quid vellet adscendere: Discere, inquit, volo.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wolde steih vp on &thorn;at hul so.</L>
<L>&THORN;en he seide: "&yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt here,</L>
<L>&THORN;ider i go nou forte lere".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot him askede wi&thorn; wondring:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Miratus ille: Quid, inquit, vis discere, pater, cui nullum hodie in scientia cre|dimus esse secundum? Et ille: Nulla hic scientia, nulla veri cognitio: sursum scien|tiae plenitudo, sursum vera notitia veritatis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1190">"Fadur, what neode&thorn; &thorn;e of leornyng?</L>
<L>We trouwen &thorn;at of connynge</L>
<L>Beo not such ano&thorn;ur lyuynge".</L>
<L>And he onswerde wi&thorn; pacience:</L>
<L>"Heer nis no verrey science,</L>
<L N="1195">Ne no verrey knowyng</L>
<L>Wel neih of no maner &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Aboue of science is al fulnes,</L>
<L>Aboue is verrey knowyng of so&thorn;nes".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he him &thorn;us hedde told fore,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et in hoc verbo disparuit. Ille autem diem notavit et tunc virum Dei Bernardum de corpore migrasse invenit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1200">&THORN;e abbot of him seih no more.</L>
<L>He tok good hede what day &thorn;at was,</L>
<L>To wite what wolde falle of &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>And he fond so&thorn;ly atte last</L>
<L>At &thorn;at same day seint Bernard fast</L>
<L N="1205">Out of &thorn;is world to God aboue,</L>
<L>Of whom euere he hedde set his loue.</L>
<L>Mo miracles &thorn;en mon may telle<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Multa autem alia et paene innumerabilia miracula per servum suum Deus ope|ratus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>God wrouhte for him, as clerkes wite wel.</L>
<L>God for &thorn;e loue of seint Bernard</L>
<L N="1210">Of heueneriche blisse &yogh;eue us part!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="life">
<HEAD>6. S. Augustin.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">6) S. Leg. Aur. c. 124: de sancto Augustino. Der Text Gr&auml;sse's enth&auml;lt leider manche offenbare Unrichtigkeiten.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Austin was nempned &thorn;at name<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Augustinus hoc nomen sortitus est vel propter excellentiam dignitatis vel propter fervorem dilectionis vel propter etymologiam no|minis.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;reo causus of gret fame:</L>
<L>&THORN;e furst is excellence of dignite,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde is feruour of loue &amp; charite,</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is for &thorn;e kynde interpretacioun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at name of gret renoun.</L>
<L>Whi? furst for excellence of dignite,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Propter excellentiam, quoniam, sicut Augustus praecellebat omnes reges, sic et iste excellit omnes doctores (secundum quod dicit Remigius);</NOTE></L>
<L>For, riht as &thorn;e emperour Augustus in his mageste</L>
<L>Grettur is &thorn;en eny o&thorn;ur kyng,</L>
<L N="10">Riht so was Austin in his teching</L>
<L>Tofore o&thorn;ur doctours excellent</L>
<L>In declaryng holy writtes entent.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, whon o&thorn;ur doctours her<NOTE PLACE="foot2">unde alii doctores comparantur stellis, Daniel. XII: Qui ad justitiam eru|diant multos quasi stellae etc. &mdash;, hic autem comparatur soli, sicut patet in epistola, quae de eo cantatur: Quoniam sicut sol refulgens sic ipse refulsit in templo Dei.</NOTE></L>
<L>Weren liknet to &thorn;e sterres cler,</L>
<L>As Daniel witnesse&thorn; in his boke,</L>
<L N="15">Sey&yogh;ing &thorn;us, whose luste to loke:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ei &thorn;at techen mony men rihtwysnes</L>
<L>Ben lyk &thorn;e sterres in clernes";</L>
<L>But to &thorn;e sonne is Austyns liknyng,</L>
<L>As witnesse &thorn; &thorn;e epistle &thorn;at we of him syng,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at sei&thorn;: "he schon as sonne schinyng</L>
<L>In Godus temple wi&thorn; his techyng".</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde cause is, as I seide aboue,
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>Feruour in charite and loue:</L>
<L N="25">For, as &thorn;e mone&thorn; of August to his meete</L>
<L>Passe&thorn; o&thorn;ure in gret hete,</L>
<L>Riht so seint Austyn his herte wi&thorn;inne</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; heuenliche loue, forso&thorn;e, dude brinne.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to God al in good fei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">unde ipse in libro confessionum de se dicit: Sagittaveras tu cor meum caritate tua etc.; iterum ibidem: Aliquando intromittis me in affectum multum inusitatum introrsus, nescio ad quam dulcedinem; quae si perficiatur in me, nescio quod erit, quod vita ista non erit (Graesse: si vita aeterna non erit).</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">In &thorn;e bok of his confessions he sei&thorn;:</L>
<L>"Min herte, lord, &thorn;ou hast, ich wot,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i charite (i)schot";<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. so hot st. (i)schot, vgl. v. 447.</NOTE></L>
<L>And "o&thorn;urwhile &thorn;ou puttest me<NOTE PLACE="foot1">ff.) dies ist ein neues Citat.</NOTE></L>
<L>In an affeccioun nou&yogh;t wonte to be</L>
<L N="35">Wi&thorn;inne me, i not forso&thorn;e &thorn;er is<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. in not st. i not.</NOTE></L>
<L>Such a maner of swetnis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whuche parfourned &yogh;if &thorn;at hit be,</L>
<L>I not what hit schal beo in me,</L>
<L>But as a &thorn;ing &thorn;at in &thorn;is lyf</L>
<L N="40">Ne is nouht, so mot i &thorn;ryf".</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde cause make&thorn; mencion<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tertio propter etymologiam nominis: dicitur enim Augustinus ab augeo (46 erkl.) et astin, quod est civitas, et ana (<GAP DESC="Greek" EXTENT="">), quod est sursum; inde Augustinus quasi augens supernam civitatem, unde de eo cantatur: Qui praevaluit amplificare civitatem etc. (Der nun folg. Satz ist im engl. nicht &uuml;bersetzt: De qua civitate ipse dicit in libro XI de civ. Dei: Inest civitati Dei et origo et infor|matio et beatitudo, quoniam, si quaeratur unde sit, Deus eam condidit, si: unde sa|piens, a Deo illuminatur, si: unde felix, Deo fruitur; subsistens modificatur, con|templans illustratur, inhaerens jucundatur: videt et amat, in aeternitate Dei viget, in veritate Dei lacet, in bonitate Dei gaudet.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his names interpretacion:</L>
<L>For, as &thorn;e bok telle&thorn; vs,</L>
<L>&THORN;is name Augustinus</L>
<L N="45">Of "augeo auges" mad hit is:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is on Englisch "to eche", iwis,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is word: "austy", parde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is on Englisch "a cite",</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is word: "ana", in certeyn:</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;at is "aboue" forte seyn;</L>
<L>Augustinus is to seyn, in verite,</L>
<L>As hose sei&thorn;: echyng &thorn;e hei&yogh;e cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore of him men rede and synge</L>
<L>&THORN;at he passe&thorn; o&thorn;ere in echinge</L>
<L N="55">Of &thorn;at ilke grete cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw Godus grace and charite.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore of him hit is iseid<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vel, ut dicitur in Glossario: (Augusti|nus dicitur magnificus, felix, praeclarus;) fuit enim magnificus in vita, praeclarus in doctrina, felix in gloria (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>In Glosarie &mdash; &thorn;at is a bok ofte leyd &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Austyn was wondur gret in liuyng</L>
<L N="60">And more cler &thorn;en o&thorn;ure in teching</L>
<L>And celi mon he was in blis.</L>
<L>Clerkes recorden of him &thorn;is.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Ejus vitam compilavit Possidonius Calamensis epi|scopus, ut dicit Cassiodorus in libro de viris illustribus).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AUstin &thorn;e doctour, &thorn;e noble man,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Augustinus doctor egre|gius in provincia Africana civitate Carthaginiensi ortus, ex honestis valde parentibus, scilicet patre Patricio, matre Monica genitus, in liberalibus artibus sufficienter edoctus fuit, adeo ut summus philosophus et rhetor luculentissimus haberetur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Boren was in &thorn;e prouince of Affrican</L>
<L N="65">In &thorn;e cite of Chartous,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Chartous ist in dieser Leg. Carthago.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of worschipful kunreden and glorious;</L>
<L>His fader men called Patrik,</L>
<L>And his modur hihte Monik.</L>
<L>He was so lernd in vche art</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at of hem he hedde so gret part</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was a philosofre and a rethor,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e greste &thorn;at &thorn;enne was bor:</L>
<L>For Aristotiles bokes and o&thorn;ur moni on<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nam libros Aristotelis et omnes libros liberalium artium, quoscumque legere potui t, per se didicit et intellexit, sicut in libro confessionum testatur dicens:</NOTE></L>
<L>He radde wi&thorn;oute teching of mon,</L>
<L N="75">As he witnesse&thorn; in his bok<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Secundo propter fervorem dilectionis, quoniam sicut mensis Augustus valde fervet aestu caloris, sic et ipse valde incaluit igne divini amoris;</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>Of confessiouns, hose luste to lok:</L>
<L>&THORN;er he sei&thorn;, as &yogh;e mowe here,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. say&yogh; st. sei&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Riht clene on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Of artes &thorn;e bokes alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Omnes libros, quos libe|rales vocant, tunc nequissimus malarum cupiditatum servus per me ipsum legi et in|tellexi, quoscunque legere potui.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at liberales clerkes don calle,</L>
<L>As a seruaunt of wikked couetyse</L>
<L>Aftur myn oune wit and auyse</L>
<L>I radde al way and vndurstod</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at i radde wi&thorn; wylde mod".</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;is was also his seying<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Item in eodem: Quicquid est de arte loquendi et disserendi, quicquid de dimensionibus figurarum et de musicis et de numeris, sine magna difficultate nullo hominum tradente intellexi (engl. indirect).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e art of spekyng and of endy|tyng,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e mesures of figures and musek,</L>
<L>And of alle &thorn;e noumbres ek,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen eny gret lettyng</L>
<L N="90">He vndurstod in his redyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen monnes teching</L>
<L>Or eny o&thorn;ur witeryng:</L>
<L>"And &thorn;ou, lord God, wost riht wel<NOTE PLACE="foot2">scis, tu domine Deus meus, quia celeritas intelligendi et discendi acumen donum tuum est, sed non inde sacrificabam tibi: verum, quia scientia sine caritate non aedificat sed inflat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at al hasty lernyng eueridel</L>
<L N="95">And &thorn;e scharpe maner of lernyng</L>
<L>Is &thorn;i grace and &thorn;i &yogh;iuyng.</L>
<L>But neuer&thorn;eles on &thorn;at wyse</L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;at tyme dude i to &thorn;e no sacrifise;</L>
<L>Hit is so&thorn; &thorn;at science wi&thorn;outen charite</L>
<L N="100">Edefye&thorn; not, but make&thorn; a mon bilowen, parde".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. bi lowen st. blowen? oder bolwen?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>INto an errour &thorn;enne he fil<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In errorem Manichaeorum, qui Christum phantasticum fuisse affir|mant et carnis resurrectionem negant (102. 109-110 Zus.), incidit et in eo per an|nos IX (dum adhuc adolescens esset) permansit. (Ad has etiam nugas adductus est ut arborem fici plorare diceret, cum ab ea folium vel ficus tolleretur).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at mony a monnes soule dude spil,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ulke tyme heolden &thorn;e Manichees,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heretykes weren, wi&thorn;outen les:</L>
<L N="105">For &thorn;ei affermed sikerlye</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist nas bote a fantasye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei forsok &thorn;at alle men</L>
<L>Schulde rise in flesch, to lyue a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e dredful day of dom,</L>
<L N="110">Whon vs to juge Crist schal com.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos opiniouns heolde nyne &yogh;er,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">heolde = heold he.</NOTE></L>
<L>He and &thorn;e Manachees in feer.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon he was nine and twenti &yogh;er old<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum igitur esset annorum XIX (engl. unrichtig XXIX) et quondam librum cuiusdam philosophi (sc. Ciceronis), in quo vanitas mundi contemnenda (et philosophia appetenda) dice|batur, perlegeret, ex hoc quidem liber plurimum placuit, sed quia nomen Jesu Christi, quod a matre imbiberat, ibi non erat, dolere coepit; mater vero eius plurimum flebat et ipsum ad unitatem (al. veritatem) fidei reducere satagebat (128 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>And of witte was waxe al bold,</L>
<L N="115">He studied faste and gon to look</L>
<L>Vppon a philosofres bok:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sc. Cicero.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er he radde iwriten in verite:</L>
<L>A mon schulde dispise &thorn;is worldus vanite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bok lyked him swi&thorn;e wel,</L>
<L N="120">But, for he fond &thorn;erin neuer a del</L>
<L>Iwriten of vr lord Cryst,</L>
<L>Sori he was, &thorn;auh no wiht wist;</L>
<L>A luitel sauour of him he hed cauht,</L>
<L>As his modur hedde him tauht.</L>
<L N="125">His modur for him wept euer fast,</L>
<L>For he schulde torne atte last</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vnite of &thorn;e fei&thorn; &mdash;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e bok vs telle&thorn; and sei&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e bok of his confessiones<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qua|dam igitur vice, ut legitur in libro III confessionum, vidit se stare in quadam linea lignea licet tristem et quidam ei juvenis adstitit et causam tantae tristitiae requisivit; quae cum diceret: Perditionem mei filii deploro; ille respondit: Esto secura, quia ubi tu ibi ille &mdash; et ecce continuo filium suum juxta se stare vidit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">&THORN;e so&thorn;e is writen for &thorn;e nones:
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>His modur &thorn;houhte &thorn;at heo stood</L>
<L>Vppon a tyme wi&thorn; entent good</L>
<L>In an euen for&thorn;riht lyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde beo marked wi&thorn; &thorn;red of twyne,</L>
<L N="135">And, &thorn;ouh heo weore in herte sori,</L>
<L>Heo sauh bi hire stonde a child louely,</L>
<L>And asked hire &thorn;e cause whi<NOTE PLACE="foot1">and relativisch.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo was so sori.</L>
<L>And heo onswerde riht anon:</L>
<L N="140">"I weope for Austin, my son:</L>
<L>I drede euere of his leosyng,</L>
<L>But God beo his helpyng".</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;ur onswerde: "no&thorn;ing so!</L>
<L>Beo riht siker and leue &thorn;i wo,</L>
<L N="145">For &thorn;er as &thorn;ou art &thorn;er is he.</L>
<L>Leeue wel! hit schal non o&thorn;ur be".</L>
<L>And as heo loked hire bisyde,</L>
<L>Heo sauh anon riht in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at Austin stod hire by.</L>
<L N="150">And heo him tolde &thorn;en openly<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hoc cum Augustino re|tulisset, ille ait: Falleris, mater, falleris nec sic tibi dictum est, sed: ubi ego ibi tu. Econtra illa dicebat: Non, fili, mihi dictum est: ubi ille ibi tu, sed: ubi tu ibi ille (Gr&auml;sse liest unrichtig: Non, fili; mihi . . . sed non: . . .)</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou on seide to hire parde:</L>
<L>&THORN;er as &thorn;ou art &thorn;er is he.</L>
<L>And he onswerde: "nay, modur, nay,</L>
<L>He seide riht &thorn;us, as i leeue may:</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;er as I am &thorn;er art &thorn;ou".</L>
<L>And heo seide: "sone, &thorn;ou gabbest nou!</L>
<L>For hit nas not iseid to me:</L>
<L>&THORN;er as he is &thorn;er art &thorn;ou, parde,</L>
<L>But: &thorn;er as &thorn;ou art &thorn;er is he &mdash;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at was &thorn;e word was seid to me".</L>
<L>His modur wi&thorn; riht good entent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Rogabat igitur sedula mater (quasi importuna) quendam episcopum (sicut in eodem libro confessio|num Augustinus testatur), ut pro filio suo intercedere dignaretur. Qui (tanta quodam|modo importunitate devictus) prophetica voce respondit: Vade secura, quia impossi|bile est ut filius tantarum lacrymarum pereat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Preyed a bisschop, verreyment,</L>
<L>For hire sone &thorn;at he schulde preye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he weore brouht in to rihte weye.</L>
<L N="165">Of hire preyere he lihtly dude lete,</L>
<L>But seide to hire as a prophete:</L>
<L>"Fare wel, he seide, and haue no fere!</L>
<L>For an inpossible &thorn;ing hit were</L>
<L>&THORN;at tat child ilost schulde beo<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;at tat st. &thorn;at &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">For whom &thorn;i teres so faste doun fleo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Chartouse he tau&yogh;te mony &yogh;eres<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem apud Carthaginem multis annis rhetoricam docuisset, occulte matre nesciente Romam venit et ibi disci|pulos congregavit. (Cum autem mater usque ad portam eum secuta fuisset, ut aut eum retraheret aut secum iret, ipse eam decipiens nocte latenter recessit; quod illa mane considerans aures Dei clamoribus implebat; quolibet autem die, mane et ves|pere, ad ecclesiam ibat et pro filio orabat &mdash; im engl. fehlt dieser Satz, der in dem lat. Text des Dichters gefehlt zu haben scheint).</NOTE></L>
<L>Rethorike to his scholeres.</L>
<L>&THORN;en priueliche aftur his oune dome</L>
<L>He stal awey and wente to Rome,</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;at his modur schulde not wite,</L>
<L>Leste heo &thorn;erfore wi&thorn; him hedde flite.</L>
<L>&THORN;er ful to him gret repeyre</L>
<L>Of clerkes, to lerne bo&thorn;e wel and feire.</L>
<L>&THORN;at same tyme men of Melan<NOTE PLACE="foot2">His temporibus Mediola|nenses (Gr&auml;sse liest unrichtig: Athenienses), a (Symmacho) praefecto Romanorum petierunt sibi doctorem in rhetorica destinari. Praesulabatur tunc ibi vir Dei Am|brosius et ad preces Mediolanum illuc(!) mittitur Augustinus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">To &thorn;e prefecte of Rome senden &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Hem to seenden witerlike</L>
<L>A doctour in rethorike;</L>
<L>Bisschop &thorn;at tyme wi&thorn;outen glose</L>
<L>Of Melan was seint Ambrose.</L>
<L N="185">&THORN;enne wi&thorn; good entent and fyn</L>
<L>To Melan was sent seint Austyn.</L>
<L>On him was euere his modur &thorn;enkyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mater autem eius quiescere non valens cum multa difficultate ad eum venit et ipsum jam nec vere Manichaeum nec vere catholicum reperit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And, forte seo him, com wi&thorn; hy&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>Forte herken of his stat.
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="65"></L>
<L N="190">But &thorn;en wox heo sumwhat mat,</L>
<L>For heo fond him not fulliche holdyng</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e Manachees erryng</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur fulliche in rihte wei</L>
<L>Of alle cristene mennes fei.</L>
<L N="195">Whon he com to Melan,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Coepit autem Augustinus beato Ambrosio adhaerere (196 Zus.) et ejus praedicationes frequenter audire. Erat autem valde in praedicatione suspensus, ne quid contra ipsam Manichaeorum haeresin vel pro ipsa diceretur(!)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erof was glad moni a man,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e bisschop seint Ambrose</L>
<L>Was a mon of gret lose</L>
<L>And preched ofte swi&thorn;e wel</L>
<L N="200">To alle maner of pepel,</L>
<L>Austin hedde gret likyng</L>
<L>Forte go here his preching.</L>
<L>Ambrose in his sarmoun</L>
<L>Hedde euer gret discrecioun</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;at a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e heresyes on Manachees,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. on st. of.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er fore, nou&thorn;ur more no les<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. non &thorn;er fore st. nou&thorn;er fore oder nou&thorn;er &thorn;erfore.</NOTE></L>
<L>He nolde him entremete ne seye,</L>
<L>But take ra&thorn;ur ano&thorn;ur weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme, &thorn;auh, afturwarde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam enim (!) vice contra illum errorem Ambrosius diu|tius disputavit et ipsum apertis rationibus et auctoritatibus confutavit; ita, ut error ille a corde Augustini penitus pelleretur.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">Ambrose disputed wondur harde</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein &thorn;at ilke heresye,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; strong resun hit to distruye;</L>
<L>So longe he spac of &thorn;is mateer</L>
<L>&THORN;at Austyn &thorn;hou&yogh;te his sei&yogh;ing cler</L>
<L N="215">And from his herte outurliche</L>
<L>Putte &thorn;ulke heresye, verreyliche.</L>
<L>What ful afturward of &thorn;at,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quid autem post hoc sibi contigerit, ipse in libro confessionum narrat, dicens:</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e bok of confessiouns he telle&thorn; sum|what</L>
<L>And sei&thorn;: "whon I &thorn;e kneuh furst ariht,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum te primum cognovi, reverberasti infirmitatem adspectus mei, radians in me vehementer, et contremui (amore et) hor|rore et inveni me longe esse a te, in regione dissimilitudinis, tanquam audirem vocem (tuam) de excelso: cibus sum grandium, cresce (der Dichter las crede) et man|ducabis me, nec tu me mutabis in te, sicut cibum carnis tuae, sed tu mutaberis in me.</NOTE></L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e syknesse &thorn;ou beetest of my siht,</L>
<L>Schynynge wi&thorn;inne me wondurliche,</L>
<L>And I for fere qwok, treweliche,</L>
<L>I fond fro &thorn;e &thorn;at fer I was,</L>
<L>As in a kyngdam of vnlikenes,</L>
<L N="225">As i hedde herd a vois from hiht</L>
<L>&THORN;at to me hed seid &thorn;us riht:</L>
<L>To grete men I am &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>Bileeue: and me &thorn;en &thorn;ou schalt ete!</L>
<L>But in to &thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt not chaunge me,</L>
<L N="230">As mete &thorn;at &thorn;ou puttest in to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>But i schal make bi charite</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schalt beo chaunged in to me".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHon he Cristes weyes lyked wel,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem (sicut ibidem refert) via Christi sibi placeret, sed per istas angustias adhuc ire pigeret, immisit dominus in mentem ejus ut ad Simplicianum, in quo lucebat lux: divina scilicet gratia, pergeret, ut sibi aestus suos secum conferenti proferret, quis esset aptus modus vivendi ad ambulandum in via Dei, (in qua alius sic, alius sic ibat).</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;e streitnesse schomed him sumdel.</L>
<L N="235">God putte in to his &thorn;ouht &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde go to Simplician &mdash;</L>
<L>In whuche mon &thorn;at tyme was</L>
<L>Muche good liuynge and Godus gras, &mdash;</L>
<L>Forte telle him his herte brennyng</L>
<L N="240">To leorne &thorn;e maner of good liuyng,</L>
<L>Hou he miht best day bi day</L>
<L>Rihtfulliche gon in Godus way.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of God, vr lord,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Displicebat enim ei quidquid agebat in saeculo, prae dulcedine Dei et decore domus ejus, quam dilexit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he dude in &thorn;is world</L>
<L N="245">Hit him displesed outerly</L>
<L>For &thorn;e swetnesse of him an hei&yogh;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e swetnesse of his hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he louede, so glorious.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>SImplician, &thorn;at noble man,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Simplicianus autem coepit eum hortari, ipse quoque se ipsum hortari et dicere: Quot pueri et puellae intra ecclesiam domini Deo serviunt, et tu non poteris quod iste et iste? an vero iste et iste in se ipsis possunt et non in Deo suo? quid in te stas et non stas? projice te in eum et excipiet te et sal|vabit te.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Bigon to amonesten him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And so he dude him self also,</L>
<L>Seint Austyn, and seide &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"A, hou moni children ben &thorn;er now</L>
<L>And maydens &thorn;at han imad a vou,</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;at seruen God in holy churche</L>
<L>And mony a good dede don worche!</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not beo he</L>
<L>&THORN;at may do as he and heo?</L>
<L>Or elles &thorn;eos men and &thorn;eos wymmen</L>
<L N="260">So mihti of hem self ben</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei mowen so do &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And nouht in God, &thorn;at almihti is?</L>
<L>Wherto stondest &thorn;ou in &thorn;i self as ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it ne stondest &thorn;ou riht nouht?</L>
<L N="265">Caste &thorn;i self in him anon,</L>
<L>And he schal &thorn;e take to him al on</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;at &thorn;ou art not i wele,</L>
<L>He him self wol &thorn;e hele".</L>
<L>AMong &thorn;is speche bo&thorn;e more and min<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Inter horum colloquia memoria Victorini in medium venit; unde ex|hilaratus Simplicianus narrat, qualiter ibidem adhuc gentilis ob sui sapientiam Romae (, quod maximum tunc erat,) statuam in foro meruisset et qualiter se saepius christia|num dicebat; cui quum Simplicianus diceret: non credo nisi te in ecclesia videro, ille jocando dicebat: numquid parietes faciunt hominem christianum?; tandem dum ad ecclesiam venisset et ei (tamquam verecundo occulte) liber, ubi erat symbolum fidei, (ad legendum et pronuntiandum, ut tunc moris erat,) datus fuisset, ille (in altum adscen|dit et) alta voce pronuntiavit, (mirante Roma, gaudente ecclesia, omnes autem subito perstrepuerunt: Victorinus, Victorinus, cito sonuerunt et cito siluerunt.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">&THORN;ei hedden muynde of on Victoryn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Simplician wi&thorn; glad cher</L>
<L>Tolde Austyn on &thorn;is maner</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he wuste wel &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at Victorin was an he&thorn;en man</L>
<L N="275">And, for of wit he was so sage,</L>
<L>&THORN;er was imad an ymage</L>
<L>Of him and set vp at Rome</L>
<L>For worschip of his wisdome,</L>
<L>And he wolde seye ofte among men</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at he was ful cristen,</L>
<L>Simplician wolde seie: "parde!</L>
<L>I leeue hit not, til I &thorn;e se</L>
<L>In holy churche wi&thorn; charite</L>
<L>And beo, as cristene men be",</L>
<L N="285">Bourdyng he wolde aske &thorn;an</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;e walles maden a cristen man;</L>
<L>Atte last to churche he went,</L>
<L>And him was a bok brouht, verreiment,</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e whuche was writen &thorn;e crede:</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;en al aloud he gan hit rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men miht him here,</L>
<L>Til he hedde pronounced al ifeere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANo&thorn;ur frend of Austines eke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc etiam ab Africa quidam amicus Augustini, nomine Pontianus, supervenit et vitam et miracula illius magni Antonii, qui nuper (in Aegypto) sub Constantino imperatore de|functus fuerat, recitavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com to him out of Aufreke,</L>
<L N="295">&THORN;at was icalled Poncian,</L>
<L>And he him tolde &thorn;e lyf of an holi man</L>
<L>And &thorn;e miracles also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Antonyn men called &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ded was tofore in good hour</L>
<L N="300">In Constantines tyme, &thorn;e emperour.</L>
<L>&THORN;oruh &thorn;eose ensaumples loue hed him take<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Horum exemplis Augustinus vehementer exarsit ita, quod socium suum Alipium tam vultu quam mente turbatus invasit et fortiter excla|mavit: Quid patimur, quid audimus? surgunt indocti et coelum rapiunt, et nos cum doctrinis nostris in infernum demergimur; an quia praecesserunt, pudet sequi (et non pudet nec saltem sequi)?</NOTE></L>
<L>And brenne&thorn; him wi&thorn;inne for Godus sake,</L>
<L>And his tornynge was so cler<NOTE PLACE="foot1">tornynge st. troublinge?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and in cheer</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;at on his felawe wi&thorn; open lippe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men called &thorn;o Alippe,</L>
<L>&THORN;en he cried an heih to his ere:</L>
<L>"What suffre we, what do we here?
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>Lewed men rauisschen heuen ful welle,</L>
<L N="310">And we, &thorn;at ben lettred, ben dreint in helle.</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er we schul schone nou for scham,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei ben tofore, to suwen ham?"</L>
<L>In to a gardyn &thorn;enne he ran<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et accurrens in quendam hortum sub quadam ficu se projecit, ut in eodem libro confessionum commemorat, et amarissime flens lamentabi|les voces dabat: Quamdiu, quamdiu cras et cras, sine modo, sine paululum. (Modo non habebat modum et sine paululum prodibat in longinquum).</NOTE></L>
<L>And vndur a fyge tre he leide him &thorn;an</L>
<L N="315">And &thorn;er wi&thorn; bitter wepyng</L>
<L>He made gret deol and serewyng.</L>
<L>His bok witnesset of confession</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;er he cried wi&thorn; deuocion:</L>
<L>"Hou longe, hou longe schal i sorewe</L>
<L N="320">For to morwe and to morewe?</L>
<L>Now soffre a luitel &thorn;at hit mot be".</L>
<L>&THORN;eose wordes risen al of charite,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouhte he hedde to longe iben</L>
<L>From him &thorn;at made alle &thorn;ing and men.</L>
<L N="325">Of his slou&thorn;e in &thorn;at doyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">De hac sui tar|ditate plurimum conquerebatur, (sicut postmodum in eodem libro scripsit): Heu mihi, quoniam excelsus es in excelsis et quoniam profundus in profundis et nusquam recedis et vix redimus ad te; age, domine, et fac et excita et revoca nos! accede et rape et fragra et dulcesce!</NOTE></L>
<L>He made &thorn;us his pleynyng:</L>
<L>"Allas to me! hou heih &thorn;ou art in &thorn;in heihnesse</L>
<L>And hou deop in &thorn;i deopnesse!</L>
<L>From vs &thorn;ou wolt neuermore be,</L>
<L N="330">And vnne&thorn;e we wole come to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ou now, lord, and also make</L>
<L>To stire vs, and calle a&yogh;eyn, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne slake!</L>
<L>Tac &thorn;ou hede and rauische vs,</L>
<L>Hete vs wi&thorn;inne and be swete &amp; glorious!</L>
<L N="335">I dredde my self &thorn;orwh lettyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">impedimentis omnibus sic timebam expediri, quemadmodum impediri timendum est. sero te amavi, pulchritudo tam antiqua et tam nova, intus eras et ego foras et ibi te quaerebam (et in ista formosa quae fecisti, deformis irrue|bam); mecum eras et tecum non eram, vocasti et clamasti et rupisti surditatem meam, coruscasti, splenduisti et fugasti caecitatem meam, fragrasti et duxisti spiritum et an|helo tibi, gustavi et esurio et sitio te, (tetigisti me) et exarsi in pacem tuam.</NOTE></L>
<L>To beo sped of my disiring,</L>
<L>Riht as I schulde haue had lettyng</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh myn oune dredyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art feirnes old and newe,</L>
<L N="340">Ful sore, forso&thorn;e, i may me rewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at I &thorn;e loued haue so late &mdash;</L>
<L>For i knowe nou my self al mate.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou weore wi&thorn;inne and I wi&thorn;oute:</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e to seche i was aboute;</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;ou were, forso&thorn;e, ay wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>But i ne was nout wi&thorn; &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow calledest and cri&yogh;edest of &thorn;i godnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow hast ibroken my defnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ischyned wi&thorn; brihtnes</L>
<L N="350">And driuen awey my blyndnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow hast isauered swetliche</L>
<L>And lad my spirit goodliche:</L>
<L>And now&thorn;e &thorn;at make&thorn; me</L>
<L>Forte bre&thorn;e aftur &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="355">I haue &thorn;e tasted wi&thorn; good lust:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore i hungre &thorn;e and &thorn;rust,</L>
<L>And i haue had a brennynge res</L>
<L>Forte come in to &thorn;i pees".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AMong &thorn;is grete mournyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem amarissime fleret, audivit vocem dicentem sibi: Tolle lege, tolle lege.</NOTE></L>
<L N="360">And &thorn;is bitter wepyng</L>
<L>He herde a vois, and tok gret hede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seide to him: "tac &thorn;ou and rede!</L>
<L>Tac and red!" hit seide eftsones.</L>
<L>&THORN;en tok he hit to him for &thorn;e nones,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ape|ruitque statim codicem apostolicum et (conjectis oculis ad primum capitulum) legit: In|duimini dominum Jesum Christum: et statim omnes ab eo dubietatis tenebrae diffugerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">&THORN;e book of &thorn;e apostles pistles,</L>
<L>And opened hit &mdash; &thorn;er weore &thorn;istles! &mdash;</L>
<L>He fond iwriten hol and sum:</L>
<L>Induimini dominum Jhesum Cristum,
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sei, whose wite list:</L>
<L N="370">"Beo &yogh;e iclo&thorn;ud wi&thorn; Jhesu Crist".</L>
<L>And anon riht wi&thorn; &thorn;at lokyng</L>
<L>Alle maner of misdoutyng</L>
<L>Of derknesse fleyh from his herte.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e mene while him sore smerte,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Interim autem tam vehementissimo dentium dolore torqueri coepit, ut fere (sicut ipse ait) ad credendam opinionem Cornelii philosophi duceretur, qui summum bonum animae in sapientia, summum vero bonum corporis in nullum sentiendo dolo|rem posuerat.</NOTE></L>
<L N="375">For he hedde so gret an ache</L>
<L>Of seknesse of &thorn;e to&thorn;-ache &mdash;</L>
<L>For he was fallen in &thorn;at dolour, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was in point to ha bileeued an errour</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cornelius &thorn;e philosofre</L>
<L N="380">Heold sum tyme wi&thorn; open profre:</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e soule &thorn;e grettest godnes</L>
<L>In wisdom stod awes<NOTE PLACE="foot1">awes st. iwis?.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e bodi &thorn;e most good</L>
<L>In feling of non ache stood.</L>
<L N="385">&THORN;e ache for &thorn;e tyme was so stronge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tam vehemens autem ille dolor fuit, quod etiam loquelam amisit, quocirca (ut in libro confessionum refert) in tabulis cereis scripsit ut omnes pro eo orarent ut dolorem illum dominus mitigaret. Ipse igitur cum aliis genua flexit et subito sanum se sensit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he lafte &thorn;e speche of his tonge.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore in a waxed table</L>
<L>He wrot &thorn;at alle men, wi&thorn;outen fable,</L>
<L>For him schulde prei&yogh;e God witerly</L>
<L N="390">&THORN;at ache to hele of his merci.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne alle men wi&thorn; deuocioun,</L>
<L>And he also, kneoleden adoun:</L>
<L>And sodeynliche he feled wel,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ache was passed eueridel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="395">TO seint Ambrose lettres he sent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Insinuavit ergo per litteras sancto viro Ambrosio suum votum, ut moneret quid sibi de libris sanctis legendum esset, quo aptior fieret fidei christianae.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde sende him his entent</L>
<L>As him &thorn;hou&yogh;te best in his wit,</L>
<L>What bokes &thorn;enne of holy writ</L>
<L>Best him were forte rede,</L>
<L N="400">To leorne &thorn;e rihte wey to lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte beo &thorn;e more apt</L>
<L>To cristene fei&thorn;, as he hedde schapt.</L>
<L>Seint Ambrose him bad: deuoutelye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At ipse jussit Ysaiam prophetam eo, quod evangelii et vocationis gentium prae|nuntiator aptior videatur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e book of &thorn;e prophete Ysaye</L>
<L N="405">Tofore al o&thorn;ure he schulde rede &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schulde lerne to gete him mede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at bok teche&thorn; wel</L>
<L>&THORN;e callyng to God bi &thorn;e gospel</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e folk rediliche, &mdash;</L>
<L N="410">And bad him studie bisiliche.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cujus principium cum Augustinus non intelligeret, totum aliud tale esse arbitrans distulit, ut illud relegeret, cum in scriptis sanctis magis exercitatus esset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Austin bigon &thorn;at redyng,</L>
<L>But he vndurstod not &thorn;e biginning,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at hit was to him so hard,</L>
<L>He caste to abyde til afturward,</L>
<L N="415">Til he cou&thorn;e more of holy writ,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;erwi&thorn; he mihte acorde his wit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT ester whon &thorn;at feste schulde bi holde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Adveniente vero paschali tempore Augustinus, cum esset anno|rum XXX, cum filio suo Adeodato (puero valde ingenioso), 431 quem Augustinus in sua adolescentia, dum adhuc gentilis et philosophus esset, genuerat,</NOTE></L>
<L>Austin, &thorn;at was &thorn;ritti winter olde,</L>
<L>And his sone, &thorn;at men called &thorn;o</L>
<L N="420">"Godus&yogh;ift", and Alippe also,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">necnon et cum Alipio 435 amico suo,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his modur prei&yogh;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot2">meritis matris et praedicatione Ambrosii sacrum baptisma suscepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seint Ambrosus preching</L>
<L>Weoren icristenet alle &thorn;re</L>
<L>In &thorn;e nome of &thorn;e trinite.</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;enne, as &thorn;e bok telle&thorn; vs,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc, sicut fertur, Ambrosius Te Deum laudamus, inquit et Augustinus Te dominum confitemur, respondit et sic tunc ipsi duo hunc hymnum alter|natim composuerunt et usque in finem decantaverunt, (sicut etiam testatur Honorius in libro suo qui dicitur speculum ecclesiae; in aliquibus autem libris antiquis titulus talis praeponitur: Canticum ab Ambrosio et Augustino compilatum).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ambros bigon Te Deum laudamus,</L>
<L>And Austin onswered wi&thorn;outen wondur</L>
<L>Te dominum confitemur,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ei tweyne wi&thorn; herte glade
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="69"></L>
<L N="430">An ende of &thorn;at ympne &thorn;ei made.</L>
<L>His sone, &thorn;at cald was "Godus&yogh;ift",</L>
<L>He gat whon he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on no &thorn;rift,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at he was an he&thorn;en man</L>
<L>And tauhte philosofye &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="435">And Alippe was a frend ful dere</L>
<L>To Austin al wei, wi&thorn;outen were.</L>
<L>AUstin aftur his cristendom, as &thorn;e bok sei&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Protinus autem in fide catholica mirabiliter confirmatur, spem omnem quam habebat in sae|culo dereliquit et scholis quas regebat abrenuntiavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was so wondurlich confermed in &thorn;e fei&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hope &thorn;at he in &thorn;e world had</L>
<L N="440">He fleyh awey and waxed al sad,</L>
<L>And his scolus he forsok</L>
<L>&THORN;at he rad inne vppon &thorn;e bok.</L>
<L>Hou muche swetnesse of heuenlich loue<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quanta autem dulcedine divini amoris extunc frueretur, ipse in hoc libro confessionum aperit dicens:</NOTE></L>
<L>He hedde wi&thorn;inne for God aboue,</L>
<L N="445">In his bok he telle&thorn; opunliche</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; &thorn;us deuoutliche:</L>
<L>"Min hert &thorn;ou hast ischoten and me,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">vgl. V. 31.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sa|gittaveras tu cor meum caritate tua et gestabam verba tua transfixa in visceribus, et exempla servorum tuorum, quos de nigris lucidos et de mortuis vivos feceras, con|gesta in sinum cogitationis meae urebant et assumebant(!) gravem torporem, et adscen|denti a convalle plorationis et cantanti canticum graduum dederas sagittas acutas et carbones vastatores (462 Zus.). nec satiabar in illis diebus dulcedine mirabili consi|derare altitudinem consilii divini super salutem generis humani (470 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Deore lord, wi&thorn; &thorn;i charite,</L>
<L>And i bar &thorn;i wordus stiked</L>
<L N="450">In my guttus, faste ipriked,</L>
<L>And ensaumplus of &thorn;i seruauns dere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whuche &thorn;ou madest here<NOTE PLACE="foot1">of &thorn;e whuche = of those which.</NOTE></L>
<L>From blaknesse to turne to liht,</L>
<L>From de&thorn; also to lyue ful riht,</L>
<L N="455">I hem bar longe in my &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And in to slou&thorn;e &thorn;ei me brouht(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot1">in to st. out of?</NOTE></L>
<L>To him &thorn;at com doun fro &thorn;e valeye</L>
<L>Of wepyng, and song bi &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>&THORN;e louely song of degres,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;ou &yogh;af, forso&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen les,</L>
<L>Scharpe arwes and coles wastyng,</L>
<L>To amende wi&thorn; my liuing;</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur i nas fulled at &thorn;at tyme,</L>
<L>At vndurne, noon, euesong ne prime,</L>
<L N="465">Of &thorn;at wondurful swetnes</L>
<L>&THORN;at i hedde in my dissches:</L>
<L>To consydre &thorn;e heihnes</L>
<L>Of diuyne counseil and godnes</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e hele of monkynde,</L>
<L N="470">&THORN;at &thorn;oruh sunne was put bihynde.</L>
<L>Muche haue i wept in ympnes and &thorn;i song,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quan|tum flevi in hymnis et canticis tuis suave sonantis ecclesiae vocibus commotus acriter, voces illae influebant auribus meis et eliquabatur veritas tua in cor meum et curre|bant lacrymae et bene mihi erat cum iis &mdash; tunc enim in ecclesia Mediolanensi haec cantica instituta sunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Stered wi&thorn; swetnes of holichirches vois among,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke voices flowen in to myn eres</L>
<L>And from myn e&yogh;en ronnen doun &thorn;e te|res &mdash;</L>
<L N="475">And wel was me &thorn;at &thorn;ei were smerte,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i so&thorn;nes melted in myn herte. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. melte&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme furst in godus louyng</L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirche of Melan was ordeynd syn|gyng. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I cried a loud cry<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et clamabam clamore alto cordis mei: "O in pace, o in id ipsum", o qui dixit: "dormiam (et requiescam) et somnum capiam" &mdash; tu es enim in id ipsum, qui non mutaris, et in te requies obliviscens laborum omnium;</NOTE></L>
<L N="480">Wi&thorn; myn herte, al on heih:</L>
<L>O in pace, O in idipsum,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">u. 2) sind aus dem 4. Psalm.</NOTE></L>
<L>O qui dixit dormiam &amp; capiam sompnum.</L>
<L>Tu es enim in idipsum</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen chaungyng bo&thorn;e hol and sum &mdash;</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;at is to sei: a in pees and in &thorn;i self one,
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>A, &thorn;ou seist i schal slep and take nap|ping sone(!);</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art in &thorn;i self onliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuermore chaungest sikerliche,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e my restyng is,</L>
<L N="490">For&yogh;etynge al trauayles iwis.</L>
<L>&THORN;at psalme i radde al wi&thorn; lykyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">legebam totum psalmum illum et ardebam, qui fueram latrator amarus et cae|cus adversus litteras de melle coeli mellitas et de lumine tuo luminosas (498 Zus.), et super scripturas huiusmodi tabescebam, Christe Jesu adjutor meus. quam suave mihi subito est factum carere suavitatibus nugarum mearum, et quas amittere metus fuerat, jam dimittere gaudium erat</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; loue of herte wi&thorn;inne brennyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum tyme was a bitter berkere</L>
<L>And also a blynd herknere</L>
<L N="495">A&yogh;eynes lettres goode and mete,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hony of heuene ihonied swete</L>
<L>And liht inouh weren of &thorn;i liht<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Das Attribut geht in einen Nebensatz &uuml;ber.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at schine&thorn; euere so feir and briht;</L>
<L>And i tapissed vndur such lettring,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">tapissed v. frz. se tapir?</NOTE></L>
<L N="500">Swete Jhesu Crist, myn helpyng!.</L>
<L>Hit is waxen swete to me sodeynlye</L>
<L>To leue &thorn;e swetnesses of japerye &mdash;</L>
<L>Such tyme i dredde such japes to lete,</L>
<L>Nou is my joye wi&thorn; hem not meete &mdash;</L>
<L N="505">&THORN;ou &thorn;reuh hem out, wi&thorn;outen les,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ejiciebas enim eas a me, vera tu et summa suavitas, ejiciebas et intrabas pro iis omni voluptate dulcior: sed non carni et san|guini (510 Zus.), omni luce clarior: sed omni secreto interior, omni honore sublimior: sed non sublimibus in se.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ou art icalled verrey swetnes,</L>
<L>In stude of hem &thorn;ou come in to me</L>
<L>Swetter &thorn;en lust of vanite &mdash;</L>
<L>But nou&thorn;ur to flesch nou&thorn;ur to blod,</L>
<L N="510">But to my spirit wi&thorn; mylde mod, &mdash;</L>
<L>Brihtor to me &thorn;en eny liht,</L>
<L>Priuiest of alle &thorn;ing wi&thorn;inne wi&thorn; riht,</L>
<L>Hy&yogh;est in worschipe and nobelte</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at hei&yogh; of hem self nou&yogh;t be".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="515">AFtur &thorn;at he tok wi&thorn; him to go<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post hoc, assumtis Nebrodio et Euodio et matre, ad Africam remeabat, sed cum essent apud Hostiam Tyberinam, pia mater ejus de|functa est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nebridie, Euodie, and his modur also,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Enodie.</NOTE></L>
<L>And torned a&yogh;eyn stillelike</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cuntreye of Affrike.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei weore comen wel afyn</L>
<L N="520">To &thorn;e &yogh;ates of Tiberyn(!),</L>
<L>&THORN;er bifulle &thorn;orwh Godus gras</L>
<L>&THORN;at his modur ded &thorn;er was.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Austin &thorn;ouhte on his lynage<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post cujus mortem reversus est Augustinus ad agros proprios, ubi cum his qui sibi adhaerebant, jejuniis et orationibus Deo vacabat, libros scribebat et in|doctos docebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wente hom to his heritage.</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;en in wakyng and good preyere</L>
<L>He serued God, &thorn;at bouht him dere,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ure also &thorn;at dwelled wi&thorn; him</L>
<L>At &thorn;at ilke same tym,</L>
<L>He wrot bokes of holy writ</L>
<L N="530">And tauhte hem &thorn;at weoren lewed of wit.</L>
<L>His fame &thorn;en sprong wondur wyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fama autem ejus ubique diffundebatur et in omnibus libris suis et actibus admirabilis habebatur (534 Zus.). Refugiebat autem ad aliquam civitatem accedere quae episcopo careret, ne ipsum in praedicto officio impediri contingeret.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wondurful he was holden on vche syde</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in his bokes and in his dede,</L>
<L>And euermore God was his spede.</L>
<L N="535">He wolde ra&thorn;ur holde him self at home</L>
<L>&THORN;en at eni such cite come</L>
<L>&THORN;er as &thorn;e bisschop ded was,</L>
<L>Leste he hedde beo chosun in &thorn;at cas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;e cite of Yppon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Eodem tempore apud Hypponem erat quidam vir magnarum opum, qui Augustino misit, quod, si ad eum accederet et verbum ex ore suo audiret, saeculo renuntiare posset (548 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="540">Dwelled &thorn;at tyme a riche mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to seint Austyn sent to seye:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he wolde take &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Touward him, &thorn;at was so cou&thorn;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he miht here of his mou&thorn;</L>
<L N="545">Goddus word preched holliche,
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>He wolde forsake verreyliche</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e world and to God turne</L>
<L>And for his sunnes make deol and morne.</L>
<L>Whon seint Austin herde of &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod Augustinus ubi comperit, illuc concitus ivit; audiens autem Valerius Hypponensis episcopus famam ejus, ipsum plurimum renitentem in ecclesia sua presbiterum ordinavit, (nonnullis quidem lacrymas suas superbe inter|pretantibus et tamquam eum consolantibus et dicentibus, quia et locus presbiteri, licet ipse majori dignus esset, appropinquaret tamen episcopatui).</NOTE></L>
<L N="550">&THORN;ider he wente anon iwis.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e bisschop Valerius</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at cite herde hit was &thorn;us,</L>
<L>And of Austines goode fame</L>
<L>And also of his grete name,</L>
<L N="555">He made him in his oune chirche</L>
<L>Chef prest, &thorn;erinne to worche.</L>
<L>Seint Austin wepyng hit longe forsok,</L>
<L>But atte laste he hit to him tok.</L>
<L>Anon riht &thorn;er a munstre he mad<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui statim mona|sterium clericorum instituit et coepit vivere secundum regulam a sanctis apostolis con|stitutam; de cujus monasterio fere X episcopi sunt electi.</NOTE></L>
<L N="560">Of clerkes, lyf to lede ful sad,</L>
<L>And bigon to lyue on &thorn;at same manere</L>
<L>As &thorn;e apostles duden in eor&thorn;e here &mdash;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at munster aftur weren chose</L>
<L>Ten bisschopus, &thorn;at men weren of good lose.</L>
<L N="565">And for &thorn;e bisschop of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et quia praedictus episcopus erat graecus et minus in latina lingua et litteris doctus, Augustino potesta|tem tribuit ut contra morem orientalis ecclesiae coram se in ecclesia praedicaret; unde cum multi episcopi (!) derogarent, ille de hoc non curabat, dummodo per eum fieret quod per se fieri non valebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was a Greke, in verite,</L>
<L>And luytel cou&thorn;e of latyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he &yogh;af to seint Austin</L>
<L>Pouwer to preche for him &thorn;e fey,</L>
<L N="570">A&yogh;ein &thorn;e custum of &thorn;at cuntrey;</L>
<L>Men &thorn;erfore &thorn;e bisschop duden blame,</L>
<L>But he of &thorn;at tok no schame</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh ano &thorn;ur for him preched wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e</L>
<L>On latin, &thorn;at better &thorn;en he cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;At tyme Austin wi&thorn; disputyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Eo tempore Fortunatum presbiterum Manichaeum et alios haereticos praecipue rebaptisatores Donatistas et Manichaeos convicit, abs|tulit et confutavit (582 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouercom &thorn;e Manaches erryng</L>
<L>And a prest, &thorn;at men called Fortunat,</L>
<L>&THORN;at principal heretyk was of &thorn;at,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Donatistes, &thorn;at weren fayn</L>
<L N="580">To ben ibaptised a&yogh;ayn</L>
<L>A&yogh;eines holichurches fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>As vr bocus teche&thorn; and sei&thorn;,</L>
<L>He drof awey wi&thorn; his clergyse,</L>
<L>And stabled &thorn;e fei&thorn; on &thorn;at wyse.</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;en bisschop Valerius wex aferd<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Coepit autem Valerius formidare ne sibi Augu|stinus tolleretur et ab alia civitate in episcopum peteretur &mdash; nam sibi aliquando abla|tus fuisset, nisi eum ad locum secretum transire curasset, ita ut inveniri minime po|tuisset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lest Austin from him schulde beo reued</L>
<L>And &thorn;at of men asked he schulde be</L>
<L>To bisschop of ano&thorn;ur cit&eacute;&eacute;, &mdash;</L>
<L>For, nedde he onus him isent</L>
<L N="590">To a place, to bi hud priuement,</L>
<L>He hedde iben lad him fro</L>
<L>And sone aftur mad bisschop &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;en gat he leue of &thorn;e erchebisschope<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Impetravit igitur ab archiepiscopo Carthaginiensi ut ipse cederet et Augustinum Hypponensi ecclesiae in episcopum promoveret.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Cartus wi&thorn; god hope</L>
<L N="595">Of his bisschophed to sees,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Austin mihte wi&thorn;outen les</L>
<L>&THORN;erof ben his successour</L>
<L>And hit gouerne wi&thorn; honour.</L>
<L>Long tyme Austin &thorn;at forsok,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sed cum hoc Au|gustinus omnimode recusaret, compulsus tamen et coactus succubuit et episcopatus curam suscepit (602 satyr. Zusatz).</NOTE></L>
<L N="600">But atte laste he hit tok,</L>
<L>Sumwhat compelled he was &thorn;erto &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er beo&thorn; but fewe &thorn;at nou don so! &mdash;.</L>
<L>Aftur, whon he hedde lerned more,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod in se fieri non debuisse, ut suo vivente episcopo ordinaretur, postea et dixit et scripsit propter concilii universalem prohibi|tionem, quam postmodum ordinatus didicit (603)</NOTE></L>
<L>Gretliche him for&thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;erfore
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="72"></L>
<L N="605">&THORN;at he tok such dignite &thorn;on,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;e bisschop was lyues mon,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e bidding of holichurche;</L>
<L>And for o&thorn;ur men schulde not so worche,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nec quod sibi factum esse do|luit aliis fieri voluit; unde etiam sategit ut in conciliis episcoporum constitueretur ut omnia statuta patrum ordinandis deberent ab ordinatoribus intimari.</NOTE></L>
<L>He made him bisy wi&thorn; herte and wil</L>
<L N="610">&THORN;at bisschops schulde ordeyne in heore counsyl</L>
<L>&THORN;at to him &thorn;at schulde bisschop ord|eynd be</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e constitucions in verite</L>
<L>Of vr eldre faderes his ordeynours</L>
<L>Schuld him furst schewe wi&thorn; honours.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">him wiederholt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="615">&THORN;erfore he seid he felde for no&thorn;ing God so wro&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ipse autem de se dixisse postmodum legitur: In nulla re mihi dominum sentio sic iratum sicut in hoc, quod, quum non essem dignus poni ad remum, posuit me ad amplustre in apice regiminis ecclesiae.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him also, o&thorn;ur hedde him lo&thorn;,</L>
<L>As whon he put him to &thorn;e he&yogh;e dignite</L>
<L>Of holy churche gouernour to be,</L>
<L>Whon he nas wor&thorn;i in no wyse</L>
<L N="620">Vnne&thorn;e (beo) do to such on seruyse.</L>
<L>His clo&thorn;inge and his ornement<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vestimenta ejus et calceamenta et ornamenta alia nec nitida nimium nec abjecta plurimum, sed ex moderato et competenti habitu erant; ipse enim de se dixisse legitur: Fateor, de pretiosa veste erubesco et ideo, cum datur mihi, vendo eam, ut, quia vestis non potest esse communis, pretium sit commune.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nas nou&thorn;ur to precious, ne torent</L>
<L>Ne abhominable to monnus siht,</L>
<L>But mesurable euen for&thorn; riht.</L>
<L N="625">Often tyme he wolde seyn:</L>
<L>"Of precious clo&thorn;us am I nou&yogh;t fayn</L>
<L>But ra&thorn;ur aschomed, sikerly,</L>
<L>&THORN;en to han lykyng &thorn;erby;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, whon &thorn;ei ben &yogh;iue to me,</L>
<L N="630">I hem sulle, so mot i &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. do to st. to do oder beo do to; oder do st. &thorn;o?</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e clo&thorn; may not comuyn be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prys &thorn;erof may wel, parde".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIs mete, luytel &thorn;ouh hit were,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Mensa frugali et parca semper usus est (634 Zus.) et inter olera et legumina propter (infirmos et) hospites plerumque carnes habebat (638 Zus.); in ipsa autem mensa magis lectionem vel disputationem quam epulationem diligebat (642 Zus.), et contra pestem detractionis in ea sic scriptum habebat: Quisquis amat dictis absentem rodere vitam, hanc mensam indignam noverit esse sibi.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wolde hit &yogh;iue wi&thorn; god chere;</L>
<L N="635">O&thorn;urwhile in his potage,</L>
<L>For gestes &thorn;at coomen to his hostage,</L>
<L>Flesch he let seo&thorn;e for heor mete,</L>
<L>And he also wi&thorn; hem wolde ete.</L>
<L>He loued ra&thorn;er at such sittyng</L>
<L N="640">To here a lessun o&thorn;ur disputyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;en his wombe to fol to fille &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was euermore his wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was writen on his mete bord</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes bacbyters &thorn;is same word:</L>
<L N="645">"Who so loue&thorn; wi&thorn; his seying</L>
<L>In absence of men blame heor liuyng,</L>
<L>He may wite riht wel iwis:</L>
<L>&THORN;is bord to him vnwor&thorn;i is".</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, whon he bad to his fest<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nam et aliquando, cum quidam sibi familiarissimi coepiscopi ad detractionem linguam laxassent, adeo dure eos redarguit, ut diceret, quod, nisi desisterent, aut versus ipsos deleret (!) aut mensa recederet.</NOTE></L>
<L N="650">Bisschops &thorn;at he loued aller best,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei bigonne to bacbyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;erof he wolde hem &thorn;en edwyte</L>
<L>And hem blame for heor speche</L>
<L>And seye &thorn;at he wolde for wreche</L>
<L N="655">Ou&thorn;ur &thorn;enne hem a&yogh;eynseye</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles aryse and gon his weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO &thorn;e mete he hedde ibeden ones<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quadam vice cum quosdam suos familiare(s) ad prandium invitasset, unus illorum curiosior caeteris coquinam ingressus est, cumque omnia fri|gida reperisset, reversus ad Augustinum interrogavit quid ciborum ipse pransur us paterfamilias praeparasset. Cui Augustinus, nequaquam talium epularum curiosus, respondit: Et ego vobiscum (nescio) (!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Gode frendes of his for &thorn;e nones;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren aftur sent,</L>
<L N="660">On into &thorn;e kuchen went,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>Forte loke what &thorn;ei schulde haue;</L>
<L>He fond &thorn;erinne nou&thorn;ur cok ne knawe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e her&thorn;es weren al cold &mdash;</L>
<L>He wondred &thorn;erfore monyfold;</L>
<L N="665">To &thorn;e halle he wente him in</L>
<L>And asked of seint Austin</L>
<L>What he hedde arayed forte ete</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he hedde bede to mete.</L>
<L>Seint Austin nas not curious</L>
<L N="670">Of metes and drinkes not costous,</L>
<L>On onswerd &thorn;en on &thorn;is manere:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. on st. and oder he?</NOTE></L>
<L>"Lo i my self am wi&thorn; &yogh;ou here".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE seide he hedde lerned &thorn;reo &thorn;inges<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tria a beato Ambrosio se didicisse ait: primum est, quod uxorem cuiquam nunquam peteret,</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftur seint Ambrosus techinges:</L>
<L N="675">&THORN;e furste was, wi&thorn;outen rage</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde make no mariage,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;at mon and &thorn;e wyf,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">causa prima est, ne illi inter se non conveniant et sibi maledicant,</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei weoren weri of &thorn;at lyf,</L>
<L>Him wolde curse in certeyn</L>
<L N="680">For &thorn;at ilke bargeyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde was, wi&thorn;outen fayle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">secundum: quod mi|litare volentem ad hoc non commendaret,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde not cumforte to batayle</L>
<L>A kniht &thorn;at wolde him &yogh;iue to fiht</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur men to putte at fliht,</L>
<L N="685">For hit miht falle of &thorn;at doyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">causa secunda est, ne militantes calumniam exerceant et in eum alii culpam re|fundant,</NOTE></L>
<L>He mihte men greue in heore &thorn;ing</L>
<L>And do also muche wronge</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at he werred amonge;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;en him &thorn;ei wolden blame</L>
<L N="690">For his counseil, and &thorn;at were schame.</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh he weore beden to feste to cum,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tertium: quod ad convivia invitatus non iret;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde was, he schulde him hold at hom,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;at him ful &thorn;er such a chaunce<NOTE PLACE="foot2">causa tertia est, ne forte temperantiae modum perdat (695-6 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he loste his temperaunce</L>
<L N="695">In etyng and drynkyng,</L>
<L>In spekyng and al o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN him self he was so pure<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tantae autem puritatis et humilitatis fuit, ut ipsa etiam minima peccata, quae apud nos nulla vel minima reputantur, in libro confessionum de his confiteatur et de his coram Deo humiliter se accuset.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of meknes hedde so gret cure,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e leste maner sinne<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. And st. &THORN;at.</NOTE></L>
<L N="700">&THORN;at eny mon falle&thorn; inne</L>
<L>To God vr lord he wolde him schriue</L>
<L>And mekeliche acuse his lyue</L>
<L>In his bok of confessioun swi&thorn;e wel &mdash;</L>
<L>Witnesse&thorn; hit so eueridel.</L>
<L N="705">For &thorn;ere he accuse&thorn; him self at al<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nam ibidem accusat se de eo quod, cum puer esset, ludebat ad pilam, dum ad scholam ire deberet;</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou he pleyed at &thorn;e bal,</L>
<L>Whyl he was child, and raged also,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at he scholde to scole han go;</L>
<L>And hou he nolde don his entent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">item de eo quod no|lebat legere vel addiscere, nisi a parentibus vel magistro urgeretur;</NOTE></L>
<L N="710">Forte lerne, ne take talent,</L>
<L>Til his frendes him wolde peyne</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles his maister him constreyne;</L>
<L>And, whil he was child, &thorn;at he wolde rede<NOTE PLACE="foot2">item de eo quod fabulas poetarum (sicut fabulam Aeneae), cum adhuc esset puer, libenter legebat et Didonem (dem engl. Dichter ist diese eine unbekannte Frau) mortuam (propter amorem) plorabat;</NOTE></L>
<L>Poetes fables &mdash; &thorn;at nas no nede,</L>
<L N="715">And for he made ones gret wepyng</L>
<L>For a wommones dying;</L>
<L>And for he stal out of his frendes celere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">item de hoc quod de cellario parentum (vel mensa) aliquid furabatur, et pueris ludentibus daret (720 Zus.);</NOTE></L>
<L>Mete, his felawes forte bere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was wont wi&thorn; to pleye,</L>
<L N="720">As children don ofte in &thorn;e weye;</L>
<L>And hou he wolde wi&thorn; queyntyse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">item de eo quod in ludo puerorum fraudulentas victorias exercebat;</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>Casten his wit and diuise</L>
<L>Hou he mihte most propurly</L>
<L>Of his felawes haue &thorn;e victory;</L>
<L N="725">And hou &thorn;at he was so bold,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">item de eo quod pirum de quadam arbore vicina (vineae suae), cum adhuc esset amorum XVI, furatus fuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon he was sixtene &yogh;er old,</L>
<L>Peres to stele from a tre</L>
<L>Of his neih&yogh;ebors, saun&yogh; cunge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE accused him also wi&thorn; deuociun<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(In eo|dem quoque libro de confessionibus) accusat se de ipsa modica delectatione quam aliquando in comedendo sentiebat, dicens: Sic me docuisti ut quemadmodum medi|camenta sic alimenta sumturus accedam (736 Zus.); sed dum ad quietem satietatis ex indigentiae molestia transeo, in ipso transitu insidiatur mihi laqueus concupi|scentiae: ipse enim transitus voluptas est et non est alius quo transeatur, quam quo transire cogit necessitas, et cum salus sit causa edendi et bibendi, adjungit se tamquam pedissequa periculosa jucunditas et plerumque praeire conatur, ut ejus causa fiat quod salutis causa me facere vel dico vel volo.</NOTE></L>
<L N="730">Of &thorn;at luttel delectaciun</L>
<L>&THORN;at he feled in his etyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;is was his seying:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou hast me tau&yogh;t, lord, on &thorn;is maneer:</L>
<L>Riht so to take my mete heer</L>
<L N="735">Riht as i schulde a medecyn</L>
<L>Proporciont, bo&thorn;e good and fyn.</L>
<L>But whon nede me take&thorn; mi bodi to fille,</L>
<L>Concupiscence is aboute mi soule to spille:</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e pas &thorn;at i mot go,</L>
<L N="740">Whon neode dryue&thorn; me &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at paas is voluptuosite,</L>
<L>&thorn;er nis non o&thorn;ur wey, whon neode driue&thorn; me;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cause of vche monnes mele</L>
<L>Schulde ben onliche monnes hele,</L>
<L N="745">But voluptuosite euene&thorn; him to as a fot page</L>
<L>&THORN;at prese&thorn; tofore wi&thorn; gret outrage,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cause of hele to putte away,</L>
<L>And he for cause him self do&thorn; for&thorn; lay,</L>
<L>To ete or drinke whon I am pliht &mdash;</L>
<L N="750">&THORN;e cause schal be hele ful riht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>DRonkenesse is fer fro my &thorn;ouht &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ebrietas longe est a me &mdash; misereberis ne appropinquet mihi! crapula autem nonnunquam subrepit servo tuo &mdash; misereberis ut longe fiat a me! et quis est, domine, qui non aliquando rapiatur aliquan|tulum extra metas necessitatis? quisquis ille est, magnus profecto est, magnificet nomen tuum; ego non sum, quia homo peccator sum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ha merci on me, lord, &thorn;at he neih&yogh;e me nou&yogh;t! &mdash;</L>
<L>Glad of chere drinke wol me make,</L>
<L>But &thorn;i merci, lord, hit may slake.</L>
<L N="755">And who is he, lord, more o&thorn;ur lasse</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;urwhile ne schal passe</L>
<L>&THORN;e boundes of neode in etynge</L>
<L>And also in his drinkynge?</L>
<L>Whateuer he beo, wi&thorn;outen let,</L>
<L N="760">He may beo called wondur gret</L>
<L>And &thorn;i name worschipe may he</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e niht and day, whereuer he be;</L>
<L>I am not he, lord, sikerly!</L>
<L>For a sunfol mon am I".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="765">HE hedde him self in his purpose<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Habebat etiam se su|spectum de olfactu, dicens: De illecebra (!) odorum non satago nimis, cum absunt, nec requiro, cum adsunt, non respuo, paratus iis etiam semper carere: ita mihi videor et forsitan fallor (so Gr&auml;sse, der engl. Dichter interpung. anders und versteht anders);</NOTE></L>
<L>Suspecte in sauour of his nose,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he sei&thorn; wi&thorn; dolour:</L>
<L>"In vnlofsum sauour</L>
<L>I haue coueyted not muche,</L>
<L N="770">Whon hit is from me, verreyliche,</L>
<L>Ne i ne seche hit nou&yogh;t, parde,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur aske, whon hit is a&yogh;eines me;</L>
<L>And whon such sauours ben me by,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">such st. swet, als Gegensatz zu vnlofsum 768?</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem am I al redi,</L>
<L N="775">&THORN;auh i wolde say &thorn;ei lakken to me (!),</L>
<L>Bigyled par auenture miht I be.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>&THORN;er may no mon, so mot i &thorn;ryue,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">nemo enim securus esse debet in ista vita, quae tota tentatio nominatur, verum qui fieri potuit ex deteriori melior, non fiat ex meliori deterior.</NOTE></L>
<L>Beon siker, whil he is here alyue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is lyf here of renoun</L>
<L N="780">Nis no&thorn;ing but temptacioun;</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er a mon &thorn;at feble is</L>
<L>Bettre mihte beo mad to blis,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at of a good mon he neor not mad<NOTE PLACE="foot1">So st. se?</NOTE></L>
<L>Worse, o&thorn;ur elles al to bad".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="785">ALso of his herynge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Iterum de au|ditu confitetur dicens: Voluptates aurium tenacius me implicaverant et subjugaverant, sed resolvisti et liberasti me; cum mihi accidit ut me amplius cantus quam res quae canitur moveat, poenaliter me peccare confiteor et tunc mallem non audire cantan|tem.</NOTE></L>
<L>He confessed him, seyinge</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e lustes of his ere</L>
<L>Hedde him brouht in gret fere</L>
<L>And ifolden him strongliche</L>
<L N="790">And vndurgon him vyleynliche:</L>
<L>"But, lord, of &thorn;i godnesse</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast me vnbounde what more and lesse.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e song to my ere</L>
<L>Is more likyng, whon I hit here,</L>
<L N="795">&THORN;en is &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at men don synge,</L>
<L>I knoweleche: I sunge in herynge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en were me leuere here no synginge</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;erinne haue such lykinge".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE accused him self eke: in seoinge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Accusat etiam se de visu, sicut de eo quod aliquando nimis libenter vidit canem currentem (et de eo), quod per agrum casu transiens venationem (libenter) pro|spexit (et de eo quod domi existens araneas muscas suis retibus capientes nimis attente conspexit). Ideo autem de his coram domino confitetur, ut ibidem dicit, quia ali|quando haec a bonis meditationibus avertunt et orationes interrumpunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="800">&THORN;at he hedde had to muche likynge,</L>
<L>To seo houndes rennynge</L>
<L>In eny maner of huntynge &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at vsed he nou&yogh;t wilfuliche,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if hit ful so sodeynliche<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &yogh;af st. &yogh;if.</NOTE></L>
<L N="805">As he passed on feld bi<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;e st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>On his romyng, sikerli.</L>
<L>Herof he wolde him confes</L>
<L>Tofore vr lord of his mekenes;</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; &thorn;at his skile was whi,</L>
<L N="810">For such maner of veneri</L>
<L>Torned awey from God his &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And breeken preyeres al to nouht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE accused him self ek of delyt<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Accu|sat etiam se de appetitu laudis et motu inanis gloriae (816-8 Zus.), dicens: Qui laudari ab hominibus vult vituperante te, non defendetur ab hominibus (judicante te) nec eripietur damnante te; laudatur homo propter aliquod donum quod dedisti ei, et tamen plus gaudet se laudari quam donum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde in appetyt</L>
<L N="815">In veinglorie of preisyng,</L>
<L>Whon he hit herde of his cunnyng</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur of o&thorn;ur vertuwes</L>
<L>&THORN;at God him sende, or goode &thorn;ewes,</L>
<L>And he wolde seye &thorn;en:</L>
<L N="820">"He &thorn;at wole beo heried of men,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou, lord, wolt him blame,</L>
<L>&THORN;er may nomon defende &thorn;at schame;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou, lord, dampne him,</L>
<L>Nomon him saue may at &thorn;at tym.</L>
<L N="825">A mon is preised onliche</L>
<L>For &thorn;i &yogh;ifte specialiche,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it mon ha&thorn; more lykyng</L>
<L>In his owne preisyng</L>
<L>&THORN;en to preise &thorn;i special &yogh;ift:</L>
<L N="830">&THORN;at is vuel don, beo my &thorn;rift.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WE ben tempted day bi day<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tentamur his tentationibus quotidie sine cessatione, quotidiana fornax est humana lingua. verumtamen nollem ut vel augeret mihi gaudium cuiuslibet boni mei suffragatio oris alieni; sed auget, fateor, non solum (!), sed vituperatio minuit. contristor autem aliquando laudibus meis, cum ea laudantur in me in quibus mihi ipse displiceo, vel etiam bona minora vel levia pluris existimantur quam existimanda sunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of mony maner of assay,</L>
<L>But vr fourneis brennynge</L>
<L>Is monnes tonge in spekynge.</L>
<L N="835">Neuer&thorn;eles i wolde nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit schulde falle in my &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>&THORN;at i schulde beo &thorn;e more glad
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>For ano&thorn;ur mon me preised had</L>
<L>Of eny maner of goodnesse,</L>
<L N="840">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at hit beo more or lesse;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;ouh a luytel hit eche my blis,</L>
<L>Blame hit amenuse&thorn; sone, iwis.</L>
<L>In herte I am ay sori,</L>
<L>Whon men me pre(i)sen hertely</L>
<L N="845">In suche &thorn;inges as me displese,</L>
<L>In my self a ben non ese,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">a st. and?</NOTE></L>
<L>Or whonne luytel or luyte god<NOTE PLACE="foot1">luytel st. liht?</NOTE></L>
<L>Is mad more, beo &thorn;e rod,</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;ei ben al togeder wor&thorn; &mdash;</L>
<L N="850">Aftur men trouwe not euen for&thorn;!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEretykes so he schent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Haereticos vir iste sanctus vali|dissime confutabat, ita ut ipsi inter se publice praedicarent (852 Zus.) peccatum non esse interficere Augustinum, quem tamquam lupum occidendum dicebant, et occisori|bus omnia sua peccata a Deo dimittenda asserebant. Multas ab iis insidias pertulit, ita ut sibi aliquo pergenti in via insidias ponerent, sed Dei providentia itineris errore seducuntur, ut invenire eum non possent.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei him hated in heor entent</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei preched openliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit nas no sunne dedliche</L>
<L N="855">Seint Austin for to sle,</L>
<L>For to a wolf lyk was he,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he schulde haue remissioun</L>
<L>Of his sunnes euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at him wolde don of dawe</L>
<L N="860">And no&thorn;ing spare for Godus awe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei setten a wayte ofte, him to slo,</L>
<L>But &thorn;orwh Godus grace he skaped euermo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EUere he hedde mynde on &thorn;e pore<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Compauperum semper memor erat iisque ex his quae habere poterat liberaliter exhibebat, nam et de vasis dominicis propter pauperes et captivos aliquando jubebat frangi et conflari et indigentibus dis|pensari.</NOTE></L>
<L>And wi&thorn; hem he parted euermore</L>
<L N="865">Such as he hedde, gladliche,</L>
<L>In sum tyme &thorn;at so muche</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e vessel of seluer and golde</L>
<L>Of holichirche, taken him to holde,</L>
<L>He wolde breke and melte hit smal,</L>
<L N="870">&THORN;e mescheuous to parte wi&thorn; al.</L>
<L>He nolde neuere buye hous ne toun,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. buylde st. buye.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Domum vel agrum sive villam nunquam emere voluit; multas etiam hereditates sibi dimissas respuit eo, quod mortuorum filiis vel propinquis potius ipsa deberi dicebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were &thorn;ei neuere of so gret renoun;</L>
<L>In so muche &thorn;at mennes heritage,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him was laft, as mon of age,</L>
<L N="875">He lafte to heore kinnes men</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur to heore children &thorn;at liueden &thorn;en.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e possessiouns of his churche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In his quoque quae in ecclesia possidebat, intentus amore vel implicatus non erat, sed die ac nocte de scripturis et de rebus divinis cogitabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hedde he no &thorn;ou&yogh;t ne wil to worche,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t to loue hem ouerwel,</L>
<L N="880">But &yogh;af his wit eueridel</L>
<L>Niht and day to holy writ &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; he occupyed his wit.</L>
<L>For to buylde eny newe plas,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fabricarum quoque novarum nunquam studium habuit, dejurans in iis implicatio|nem sui animi, quem semper liberum habere volebat ab omni molestia corporali, ut libere vacare posset continuae meditationi et assiduae lectioni. Non tamen illa aedi|ficare volentes prohibebat, nisi forte immoderate fieri conspexisset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Luytel &thorn;eron his &thorn;ou&yogh;t was,</L>
<L N="885">For he wolde nou&yogh;t his wit defoule</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; worldly &thorn;inges, bote beo soule</L>
<L>And freo in good &thorn;enkynge</L>
<L>And in lessounes redynge.</L>
<L>But forbeode wolde he nouht</L>
<L N="890">Hem &thorn;at buylden hedden &thorn;ouht &mdash;</L>
<L>To curious &thorn;ei schulde not be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at onliche forbede wolde he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEm he wolde preise outerlye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Laudabat quoque plurimum illos quibus moriendi desiderium inerat, et super hoc trium episco|porum exempla saepius recitabat:</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hedden desyr forte dye.
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="77"></L>
<L N="895">&THORN;enne ensaumples he wolde hem tel</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo bisschops, &thorn;at he louede wel:</L>
<L>Of seint Ambrose whon he schulde dye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ambrosius enim, cum in extremis esset et ro|garetur ut prolongationem vitae sibi precibus obtineret, respondit: Non sic vixi ut me pudeat inter vos vivere, nec mori timeo, quoniam bonum habemus dominum &mdash; quod responsum Augustinus mirabiliter extollebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou &thorn;e peple him preyed deuoutelye</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde wi&thorn; his preyere</L>
<L N="900">Sumwhat leng&thorn;en his lyf here,</L>
<L>And he onswerde wi&thorn; vois ful cleer:</L>
<L>"I haue not liued on &thorn;at maner<NOTE PLACE="foot1">vgl. Ambr. 363 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at I am aschomed nou</L>
<L>Forte liue amonges &yogh;ou,</L>
<L N="905">Nou&thorn;ur to dye I haue no drede:</L>
<L>We han a lord wol quyte vr mede".</L>
<L>Seint Austin preised muche &thorn;is onswere,</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;at he was on eor&thorn;e here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E secunde ensaumple was of a bis|schope,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Addebat quoque de alio episcopo (910 u. 912 Zus.), cui cum diceretur eum ecclesiae multum necessarium fore et ideo adhuc eum dominus liberaret (engl. dir.), ait: Si nunquam, bene, si aliquan|do, quare non modo?</NOTE></L>
<L N="910">A mon &thorn;at was of studefast hope,</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;e peple gan to seye,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e gost schulde taken his weye:</L>
<L>"To holichirche &thorn;ou hast ben good</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in word, dede and mood,</L>
<L N="915">God &thorn;erfore, as nou&thorn;e leeue we,</L>
<L>Wole &thorn;at &thorn;ou delyuered be".</L>
<L>&THORN;en he onswerde and seide &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;at beo neuer, wel is vs;</L>
<L>And eny tyme &yogh;if hit schal beo,</L>
<L N="920">Whi not nou? hit wolde lyke me".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF &thorn;e &thorn;ridde bisschop he tolde eke:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">De aliquo quoque episcopo ajebat (Cyprianum referre,) quod, cum infirmitate gravi laboraret, adhuc sibi sanitatem restitui exorabat; cui ju|venis speciosus apparens cum indignatione infremuit et ait: Pati timetis, exire non|vultis, quid faciam vobis?</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he was wondur seke,</L>
<L>He preyed to God ful hertily</L>
<L>To sende him hele for his merci;</L>
<L N="925">To him apeered a wel feir childe,</L>
<L>Ac spac to him wi&thorn; maners wylde</L>
<L>And seide: "&yogh;e mouwe suffre no wo,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;e wol nou&yogh;t hennes go,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore wot i neuer nou</L>
<L N="930">What me is best to do wi&thorn; &yogh;ou".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF wymmen, i telle &yogh;ou in certayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Feminarum nullam unquam nec etiam germanam sororem aut fratris sui filias, quae Deo pariter serviebant, secum habitare permisit (936 Zus.); dicebat enim, quod, etsi de sorore et nepotibus nulla mali posset oriri suspicio, tamen, quia tales personae sine aliis sibi necessariis esse non possent et ad eas etiam alii adventarent, ex illis possent infirmiores aut humanis tentationibus commoveri aut certe malis hominum suspicionibus infamari.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t his sustur Germayn,</L>
<L>His bre&thorn;eres douhtres neuer &thorn;e mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God almihti seruede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="935">He nolde soffre wi&thorn; him to dwelle,</L>
<L>For temptyng of &thorn;e deuel of helle;</L>
<L>He seide: &thorn;ou&yogh; men hadde no suspe|cioun</L>
<L>Of his suster or neuew, in feld ne toun,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it, for &thorn;ei miht not ben wi&thorn;oute</L>
<L N="940">Seruauns, to ben hem aboute,</L>
<L>And beo cause of heore dwellyng<NOTE PLACE="foot1">And ist zu tilgen, wenn man nicht ein Anacoluth annehmen will.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur wymmen schulde beo to hem com|yng,</L>
<L>And of hem &thorn;enne ful lihtlyche</L>
<L>Men mihte beo stured foliliche</L>
<L N="945">O&thorn;ur elles wikked-tonged men</L>
<L>Wolde speke vuel of hem &thorn;en.</L>
<L>He wolde neuer him self alon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Nunquam cum mu|liere solus loqui volebat, nisi secretum aliquod interesset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Speken wi&thorn; no wommon,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;er weore gret priuete,</L>
<L N="950">Bi &thorn;e wey of charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was such a benfesour<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Consanguineis sic bene|fecit, non ut divitias haberent, sed ut aut non aut minus egerent.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>To his kunrede wi&thorn; honour</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei nedde no gret richesse</L>
<L>Ne to gret neode to more ne lesse.</L>
<L N="955">Ful selde, forso&thorn;e, was his maner<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Raro pro aliquo aut litteris aut verbis intercedere volebat (958 Zus.), recolens quendam philo|sophum contemplatione famae amicis non multa praestitisse, et saepe dicebat: Plerum|que potestas quae petitur premit (966 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>For eny mon to make preyer</L>
<L>Or lettres sende for benefyce &mdash;</L>
<L>Such maner doyng he huld a vice;</L>
<L>Of a philosofre he hedde a &thorn;ouht</L>
<L N="960">&THORN;at to his frendes luytel &yogh;af or nouht,</L>
<L>Forte geten him eny name,</L>
<L>Mon to bi holden of gret fame.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ofte tyme was his seying:</L>
<L>"Pouste &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;orwh askyng</L>
<L N="965">Holde&thorn; a mon o&thorn;ur while doun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh he beo of gret renoun".</L>
<L>Ful selden whon &thorn;at he wrot<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem id faciebat, sic stylum temperabat, ut onerosus non esset, sed mereretur urbanitate dictaminis exaudiri.</NOTE></L>
<L>For eny mon, God hit wot,</L>
<L>His askyng schuld not beo so large</L>
<L N="970">&THORN;at hit schulde bere eny gret charge,</L>
<L>But &thorn;orwh his corteis endityng</L>
<L>Men schulde take hede of his preying.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE hedde leuere &thorn;e causes here<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Volebat potius inter ignotos quam inter amicos causas audire; dicens, quia inter illos poterat libere iniquum cognoscere et unum ex his amicum esset facturus: pro quo scilicet justitia mediante sententiam daret, ex amicis vero esset unum perditurus: sci|licet contra quem proferret sententiam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bitwene twei enemys on his manere</L>
<L N="975">&THORN;en bitwene frendes tweyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was his skile, as he wolde seyn:</L>
<L>For bitwene enemys he miht</L>
<L>Freoliche knowe bi word and siht</L>
<L>&THORN;e wikkednes of &thorn;at on or bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="980">And whe&thorn;er to o&thorn;ur weore more lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And such grace God miht him sende:</L>
<L>&THORN;e ton he mihte make his frende:</L>
<L>Him &thorn;at he schulde &yogh;iue fore &thorn;e sentence</L>
<L>Bi rihtwysnes, wi&thorn;oute reuerence;</L>
<L N="985">&YOGH;if &thorn;ei were his frendes bo&thorn;e two,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ones frendschipe schulde pas him fro:</L>
<L>&THORN;e sentence a&yogh;eynes whom</L>
<L>He schulde &yogh;iue and eke &thorn;e dom.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HE was prey&yogh;ed forte preche<NOTE PLACE="foot2">A multis ecclesiis invitabatur et ibi verbum domini praedicabat et multos ab errore convertebat. Aliquando a proposito digressionem facere consueverat in praedicatione (et tunc dicebat Deum hoc) ad pro|fectum salutis alicuius (ordinasse),</NOTE></L>
<L N="990">To moni a churche, Godus word to teche,</L>
<L>And so he dude to Godus honour</L>
<L>And torned moni on from heore errour.</L>
<L>O&thorn;urwhyle in his prechinge</L>
<L>He wolde turne from his furst biginnynge</L>
<L N="995">And take &thorn;enne o&thorn;ur mateere</L>
<L>&THORN;at profyted to summe &thorn;at weren &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>As hit bifel bi a chapman<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sicut in quodam Manichaeorum negotiatore patuit, qui in praedicatione quadam Augustini, ubi ipse digressionem faciens contra hunc errorem praedicaverat (1004 Zus.), conversus fuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e Manachees secte was &thorn;an:</L>
<L>Vppon a day he herde Austin</L>
<L N="1000">Preche wondur wel and fyn.</L>
<L>Seint Austin turned his mater fro</L>
<L>And a&yogh;eines &thorn;e Manachees preched &thorn;o</L>
<L>And eke a&yogh;eynes heore errour,</L>
<L>As a clerk of alle &thorn;e flour.</L>
<L N="1005">&THORN;e chapmon &thorn;orwh his preching</L>
<L>Torned al to his teching</L>
<L>And forsok &thorn;at ilke lore</L>
<L>&THORN;at he heold wi&thorn; &thorn;erbifore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Ulke tyme weren he&thorn;en men icome<NOTE PLACE="foot1">he&thorn;en st. Go&thorn;en?</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Eo tempore, dum Gothi (!) Romam cepissent, ydololatrae et infideles christianis plurimum insultabant; propter quod Augustinus librum de civitate Dei composuit, in quo justos in hac vita debere premi, impios autem florere ostendit,</NOTE></L>
<L N="1010">And hedden taken &thorn;e cite of Rome:</L>
<L>&THORN;en alle &thorn;e he&thorn;ene men</L>
<L>Maden asaut vppon &thorn;e cristen.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at cause Austyn in good fey</L>
<L>Made &thorn;e bok "de Ciuitate dei",
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="79"></L>
<L N="1015">In &thorn;e whuche is his seying</L>
<L>&THORN;at rihtwys men in &thorn;is liuyng</L>
<L>Schul not beo of reputacioun</L>
<L>But ra&thorn;ur euer beo put adoun,</L>
<L>And wikked men wi&thorn; honoure</L>
<L N="1020">Schul her beo maistres and bere &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er he speke&thorn; of citees tweyn:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">ubi de duplici civitate, scilicet Jerusalem et Babylone et earum regibus agit, quia rex Jerusalem Christus, rex Baby|lonis dyabolus:</NOTE></L>
<L>Jerusalem and Babileyn,</L>
<L>And also of heore twey kynges,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;he among o&thorn;ur &thorn;inges:</L>
<L N="1025">&THORN;at of Jerusalem kyng is Crist,</L>
<L>Of Babiloyne &thorn;e deuel vntrist;</L>
<L>&THORN;eose twei citees on heor maners<NOTE PLACE="foot2">quas duas civitates (ut ibidem dicit) duo amores sibi fabri|cant (!), quia civitatem dyaboli construxit amor sui (!) crescens usque ad contemtum Dei, civitatem Dei amor Dei crescens usque ad contemtum sui.</NOTE></L>
<L>Geeten hem twey louyers:</L>
<L>&THORN;e deueles cit&eacute;&eacute; loue&thorn; nouht<NOTE PLACE="foot1">fehlt &thorn;at vor loue&thorn;?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1030">But him self in dede and &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And waxe&thorn; for&thorn; wi&thorn; wylde blood</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he haue forsaken God,</L>
<L>Godus cit&eacute;&eacute; is aboue</L>
<L>And onliche is in Godus loue</L>
<L N="1035">And make&thorn; mon wi&thorn;outen wrake</L>
<L>Him self dispise for Godus sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e &yogh;er of vr lord of heuene<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In diebus autem ejus, anno scilicet domini CCCCXL (engl. &mdash;XI) Wandali totam Africae provinciam occupaverunt vastantes omnia nec parcentes sexui, ordini vel aetati. Post hoc autem ad Hypponensium civitatem pervenerunt et ipsam manu valida obsederunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Four hundred and eke elleuene</L>
<L>Wandaly &thorn;e prouince tok</L>
<L N="1040">Of Aufrike &mdash; so sei&thorn; &thorn;e bok &mdash;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wasted al, as men ful wylde,</L>
<L>And spared nou&thorn;ur mon, wommon ne childe</L>
<L>Ne men of ordre of holichurche:</L>
<L>Such grisly werkes &thorn;ei gonne worche.</L>
<L N="1045">And so &thorn;ei wenten wi&thorn;outen reuerence</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute; of Iponence.</L>
<L>&THORN;er dwelled Austyn a mon ful old,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sub hac tribulatione Augustinus prae caeteris suae senectutis amarissimam et lugubrem duxit vita n fueruntque sibi lacrymae ejus panes die ac nocte, cum alios videret occi|sos, alios effugatos, ecclesias sacerdotibus viduatas, civitates cum accolis dissipatas.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at tribulacion hedde monyfold,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;at st. and?</NOTE></L>
<L>His teres to him weren his bred</L>
<L N="1050">Niht and day for &thorn;at qued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he say&yogh; so men slayn</L>
<L>And summe to fleo weoren ful fayn</L>
<L>And churches prestes hedde non,</L>
<L>Men fro citees weren awey gon.</L>
<L N="1055">Neuer&thorn;eles in &thorn;at offence<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Inter tot tamen mala cujusdam sapientis sententia se consolabatur dicentis: Non erit magnus magnum putans quod cadunt ligna vel lapides et moriuntur mortales.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was cumforted beo a sentence</L>
<L>Of a wys monnes seying</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner in his writyng:</L>
<L>"He may not beo gret of sped</L>
<L N="1060">&THORN;at take&thorn; to muchel hed</L>
<L>&THORN;auh tren and stones falle</L>
<L>And eor&thorn;ly men dyen, gret and smalle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;En his bre&thorn;eren euerichon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Convocatis autem fratribus dixit iis: Ecce rogavi dominum ut aut nos ab his pe|riculis eruat aut patientiam tribuat aut me de hac vita suscipiat, ne tot calamitates videre compellar.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tofore him he calde anon</L>
<L N="1065">And seide: "i haue ipreyed vr lord,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; &thorn;ouht and wi&thorn; word,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde of his god wil</L>
<L>Delyuere vs of &thorn;is peril</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur elles wi&thorn;outen offence</L>
<L N="1070">&YOGH;if vs good pacience</L>
<L>Or elles take me &thorn;is lyf fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;at i seo not so muche wo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GOd graunted him &thorn;e &thorn;ridde askyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Sod st. God.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ecce tertium quod petivit obtinuit: et tertio obsidionis mense febribus laborans lecto decubuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e &thorn;ridde mone&thorn; of &thorn;e beseching
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="80"></L>
<L N="1075">Of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute; he fel seek</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e feuere to bedde went ek.</L>
<L>He vndurstod wel, certeynly,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Intelligens autem dissolutionem sui corporis imminere, VII psalmos poenitentiales sibi scribi fecit ipsosque in loco contra parietem positos, lecto decubans, legebat et ubertim ac jugiter lacrymas fundebat, et ut (Deo vacaret liberius et) ejus intentio a nullo impediri posset, ante X dies sui exi|tus nullum ad se ingredi praecepit, nisi vel cum medicus ingrederetur vel cum sibi refectio portaretur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at dissolued scholde be his bodi.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen psalmus al on a rowe</L>
<L N="1080">He let writen vppon a wowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, as he in his beodes lay,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">beodes st. bedde?</NOTE></L>
<L>Miht hem sigge eueriday;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">he ist versteckt.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wolde hem seye deuoutliche,</L>
<L>Wepe &thorn;erto wel tenderliche,</L>
<L N="1085">And, for &thorn;at he nolde nou&yogh;t be let</L>
<L>To don as he his herte hedde set,</L>
<L>Ten dayes bifore his dy&yogh;ing</L>
<L>&thorn;er moste nomon come in his seoing,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if his leche were in ilet</L>
<L N="1090">O&thorn;ur elles a mon &thorn;at brouht him met.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A seek mon to him com<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam autem aeger ad eum venit et ut sibi manum im|poneret et ab infirmitate curaret, ipsum instanter rogavit. Cui Augustinus respondit: Quid est hoc, fili, quod loqueris? putas, quod, si tale quid facere possem, mihi hoc ipsum non conferrem? Ille autem instabat asserens sibi in visione praeceptum esse ut ad eum accederet et sanitatem reciperet. Videns autem fidem ejus pro ipso oravit et sanitatem recepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>And preyed him for Godus dom</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde on him holde his honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his seknes mihte awey fonde,</L>
<L N="1095">And &thorn;at he wolde him sumwhat fele,</L>
<L>For, he seide, he schulde so cacche hele.</L>
<L>Austin onswerde on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Whi spekest &thorn;ou so, my bro&thorn;ur dere?</L>
<L>Trouwest not &thorn;ou, &yogh;if i miht do so,</L>
<L N="1100">I wolde my self hele and for&thorn; go?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon seide: he hedde comaundement</L>
<L>In a visioun, verreyment,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at I schulde to &yogh;ou go,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if i wolde haue hele of my wo".</L>
<L N="1105">Whon Austin sauh his fei&thorn;fulnes,</L>
<L>He preyed to God of his godnes</L>
<L>&THORN;at his wille were &thorn;at mon to hele.</L>
<L>And so he was sone eueridele.</L>
<L>He heled mony a sek man<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Energumenos multos curavit et plura alia miracula fecit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1110">And mony a miracle dude he &thorn;an.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN his two and twenti&thorn;e bok<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In libro XXII de civ. Dei duo miracula de se tamquam de quodam alio refert dicens:</NOTE></L>
<L>De ciuitate dei whose luste lok,</L>
<L>He may fynde miracles tweyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at he telle&thorn;, in certein,</L>
<L N="1115">As &thorn;ei weore ano&thorn;ur monnes doyng &mdash;</L>
<L>But God hem wrouht for his preying.</L>
<L>In his bok &thorn;us he sayde:</L>
<L>"At Iponence I wot a mayde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hypponensem quandam virginem scio, quae cum se oleo perunxisset, cum pro illa orans presbyter lacrymas suas instillaverat, mox a daemone fuisse sana|tam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; oyle enoynted hire had:</L>
<L N="1120">&THORN;erfore &thorn;e deuel made hire mad;</L>
<L>But a prest for hire wepte sore</L>
<L>To God, &thorn;at heo schulde not beo lore:</L>
<L>And anon heo dilyuered was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fend in &thorn;at cas".</L>
<L N="1125">"Also", he seide, "i knewh a bisschope<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In eodem etiam libro sic ait: Scio etiam episcopum semel pro ado|lescente, quem non vidit, orasse illumque illico daemonio caruisse. Nullum autem dubium videtur, quin de se ipso loquatur, sed humilitatis causa se ipsum noluit no|minare. &mdash; In eodem quoque libro de civ. Dei sic ait, quod, cum quidam infirmus in|cidi deberet et de ejus morte ob incisionem plurimum timeretur, et infirmus multis lacrymis Deum exoraret, cum eo et pro eo Augustinus oravit, et sine incisione aliqua integram sanitatem recepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at preyed to God wi&thorn; good hope</L>
<L>For a &yogh;ong mon, &thorn;at he not sawe,</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;e deuel heold in awe:</L>
<L>And anon riht, verreyment,</L>
<L N="1130">He was saued from &thorn;at cumbrement".</L>
<L>&THORN;is tales he tolde &thorn;us of his mekenes,</L>
<L>For me schulde not knowe his holynes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e same bok also we fynde
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>A good miracle, to haue in mynde:</L>
<L N="1135">A seek mon &thorn;er was &mdash; &thorn;e bok telle&thorn; hit &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his hele schulde ha be kit;</L>
<L>He was adred and hedde gret any&yogh;e:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he were kut, &thorn;at he schulde dy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>He wepte &thorn;erfore wi&thorn; al his miht</L>
<L N="1140">And preyed to God bo&thorn;e day and niht,</L>
<L>And seint Austin also wi&thorn; him</L>
<L>Preyed to god &thorn;at ilke tym,</L>
<L>So longe he preyed to God and bad</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;outen eny cuttyng hele he had.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1145">WHon &thorn;at seint Austines bre&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Denique dissolutione corporis appropinquante hoc memoriale docuit: nullum videlicet hominem quantumcunque excellentis meriti sine confessione et eucharistia debere transire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bigon to schorten and drawe to de&thorn;,</L>
<L>He tauhte vche mon to haue in mynde,</L>
<L>And for no&thorn;ing leue hit behynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;auh a mon beo neuer so wor&thorn;i</L>
<L N="1150">In his liuynge here deuoutli,</L>
<L>He schulde euer &thorn;enke on &thorn;is cas:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen schrift and hosel &thorn;at he ne pas.</L>
<L>His limes weore hole and sounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad extremam autem horam veniens membris omnibus sui corporis incolumis, integro adspectu atque auditu,</NOTE></L>
<L>Riht as he wente on &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L N="1155">His siht was cler and his heryng</L>
<L>Euene to his dy&yogh;ing.</L>
<L>As his bre&thorn;eren toforen him stod,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">coram po|sitis fratribus et orantibus migravit ad dominum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Preying to God wi&thorn; dreri mood,</L>
<L>Tofore hem alle bo&thorn;e best and most</L>
<L N="1160">To God &thorn;en he &yogh;eld &thorn;e gost,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;eer of his age wi&thorn;outen wene<NOTE PLACE="foot2">anno aetatis suae LXXVII (engl. &mdash;VI), episcopatus vero XL,</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;reo score and sixtene,</L>
<L>And of his bisschophed in feer</L>
<L>Euene &thorn;e fourti&thorn;e &yogh;er.</L>
<L N="1165">He made no testament &thorn;an,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Testamentum nullum fecit, quia, unde faceret, pauper Christi non habuit. Floruit(!) circa annos domini CCCC.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he was Cristes pore man</L>
<L>And hedde no&thorn;yng wherof to make &mdash;</L>
<L>Al he forsok for Cristes sake.</L>
<L>He passed his wei on &thorn;is maner</L>
<L N="1170">&THORN;e date of vr lord four hundred &yogh;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Austin, of wisdom schining briht,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Itaque Augustinus, sapientiae lumen perfulgidum, propugnaculum veritatis et fidei munimentum, omnes ecclesiae doctores tam ingenio quam scientia vicit incom|parabiliter, florens tam exemplis virtutum quam affluentia doctrinarum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Defensour of so&thorn;fastnes and riht</L>
<L>And parfyt kepere of &thorn;e fei&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. profyt st. parfyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer o&thorn;ur doctours, as men sei&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1175">In wit and connynge, he passe&thorn; alle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;(oute) comparisun, gret o&thorn;ur smalle,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. wi&thorn; st. wi&thorn;oute.</NOTE></L>
<L>He floure&thorn; wi&thorn; ensaumples of vertuwes in liuing</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; affluence wonderliche in teching.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore seint Remigious<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unde et beatus Remigius Hieronymum et quosdam alios doctores commemorans, sic concludit: Hos omnes Augustinus ingenio et scientia sua vicit, nam licet Hiero|nymus VI millia volumina Originis se legisse fateatur, iste tamen tanta scripsit, ut non solum diebus ac noctibus scribere libros ejus quis non possit, sed nec legere qui|dem occurrat.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1180">Of Jerom and o&thorn;ur doctours glorious</L>
<L>Make&thorn; mynde, but he conclude&thorn; hit</L>
<L>&THORN;at Austin passe&thorn; alle in cunnynge of wit:</L>
<L>For, &thorn;ouh seint Jerom &thorn;e clerk<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;orwh st. &thorn;ouh.</NOTE></L>
<L>Parfourned so gret a werk</L>
<L N="1185">&THORN;at six &thorn;ousend volumes he dude rede</L>
<L>Of Origenes, wi&thorn;outen drede,</L>
<L>Seint Austin so moni wrot,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou&yogh;t onliche &mdash; God hit wot! &mdash;</L>
<L>Nihtes no dayes no mon miht</L>
<L N="1190">Alle his bokes write out fulle riht,</L>
<L>Ne, &thorn;ouh he mihte him gete gret mede,</L>
<L>His bokes alle ouerrede.
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="82"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VOlusian, to whom Austin<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Volusianus autem, cui Augustinus epistolam scripsit, sic de eo dicit: Legi Dei deest quidquid Augustino contigerit ignorare.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wrot mony a pistel good and fyn,</L>
<L N="1195">Sei&thorn; of him, as he wel wist:</L>
<L>"What &thorn;ing &thorn;at seint Austin nist,</L>
<L>Hit nas nou&yogh;t in Godus lawe".</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;erfore Volusians sawe<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Volusians st. Jeroms, der auch V. 1213 gemeint ist.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hierony|mus(!) quoque in quadam epistola scribens Augustino ait: Duobus libellis tuis eru|ditissimis et omni eloquentiae splendore fulgentibus respondere non potui, certe quid|quid dici potuit et assumi ingenio et de scripturarum hauriri fontibus, a te positum at|que disertum est, sed quaeso reverentiam tuam, parumper patiaris me tuum laudare ingenium.</NOTE></L>
<L>In a pistel &thorn;at he sent</L>
<L N="1200">To seint Austyn, wi&thorn; good entent:</L>
<L>"To &thorn;i tweyn luttel bokes,</L>
<L>In whuche may seo wel, whose lokes,</L>
<L>Schynynge wi&thorn; feirnesse of eloquensye,</L>
<L>Mai I not onswere wi&thorn; tonge ne e&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="1205">For, certes, whateuer a mon mai take of wit</L>
<L>And drawe vp from &thorn;e welle of holi writ,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hit is declared and set</L>
<L>To clerkes wit wi&thorn;outen let.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore i preye &thorn;i reuerence,</L>
<L N="1210">Soffre me of &thorn;i pacience</L>
<L>A luytel to worschipe &thorn;i wit,</L>
<L>For alle o&thorn;ur passe&thorn; hit".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E same clerk of him writ in &thorn;e bok<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hieronymus(!) etiam in libro de XII doctoribus sic de eo scribit: Augustinus episcopus volans per montium cacumina quasi aquila et ea quae sunt in montium radicibus non considerans, multa coelorum spatia terrarumque situs et aqua|rum circulum claro sermone pronuntiat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e twelue doctours, hose luste to lok,</L>
<L N="1215">And sei&thorn;: "seint Austin was a bisschop fleoing</L>
<L>Ouur &thorn;e hexte of &thorn;e mountayns wi&thorn; hi&yogh;ing,</L>
<L>As an egle, wi&thorn;outen drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e feet of &thorn;e mountayns tok non hede,</L>
<L>But of heuene &thorn;e brode space</L>
<L N="1220">And &thorn;e cyte of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e in vche place</L>
<L>And &thorn;e viroun of &thorn;e wattres wondurliche</L>
<L>He schewed to alle men openliche".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Jerom hedde him in loue and re|uerence:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Denique in quanta eum reverentia et dilectione Hieronymus habuit, patet in epistolis quas eidem misit, in quarum una sic dicit: Domino sancto ac beatissimo papae Hieronymus. omni quidem tempore beatitudinem tuam eo quo decet honore veneratus sum et habitantem in te dilexi do|minum salvatorem, sed nunc, si fieri potest, cumulo aliquid addimus et plena com|plemus, ut absque nominis tui mentione ne unam horam quidem praeterire patia|mur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at witnesse&thorn; a pistle, of his sentence</L>
<L N="1225">Wherin he wrot on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e schulle nou&thorn;e ihere:</L>
<L>"To an holy and blessedest pope Austin</L>
<L>Jerom recomaunde&thorn; him.</L>
<L>Eueri tyme &thorn;i blessedhed</L>
<L N="1230">Wi&thorn; such worschipe as biseme&thorn;, bi mi hed,</L>
<L>I honoured tide, tyme and our,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. And st. I.</NOTE></L>
<L>And i loued &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; in &thorn;e, vr sa|ueour;</L>
<L>But nou&thorn;e, &yogh;if hit mihte beo so,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e heep sumwhat we adden &thorn;erto,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. help st. heep.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1235">And fulliche hit to folfulle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al vr herte and vr wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;outen mencioun</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i name of renoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wondur gret honour</L>
<L N="1240">We mowe not suffre passe an hour".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN ano&thorn;ur pistle eke he sei&thorn;:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Idem in alia epistola ad eundem: Absit autem ut quidquam de libris beatitudinis tuae attingere audeam, sufficit enim mea probare et aliena non carpere.</NOTE></L>
<L>"God forbeode hit and good fei&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schulde beo so hardi</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in holinesse to touche bocus any;
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="83"></L>
<L N="1245">Hit soffise&thorn; to me proue myn owne doyng</L>
<L>And of o&thorn;ur mennes entremete no&thorn;ing".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Gregori ek, &thorn;e grete clerk,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Gregorius quoque in epistola ad Innocentium Africae praefectum de ejus libris sic ait: Quod expositionem sancti Iob vobis transmitti voluistis, vestro studio congaudemus, sed si delicioso cupitis pabulo saginari, beati Augustini compatrio|tae vestri opuscula legite et ad comparationem illius similaginis nostrum furfurem non quaeretis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comende&thorn; seint Austines werk</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his wit verreylike</L>
<L N="1250">In a pistel &thorn;at he sent to Aufrike</L>
<L>To Innocent, &thorn;at prefecte was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; forso&thorn;e on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"We beo&thorn; riht glad of &yogh;or moode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e to vs senden for goode</L>
<L N="1255">For &thorn;e exposicioun of Jobs lyf;</L>
<L>But, so mote we euer &thorn;ryf!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &yogh;e coueyte to beo fed</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; dilicious foodus to &yogh;or hed,</L>
<L>Tac hede of &thorn;e werk &thorn;on</L>
<L N="1260">Of seint Austin, &yogh;or contre mon,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e compar(i)soun of his whete flour</L>
<L>Seche&thorn; not or bren &mdash; hit were errour".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN his registre he sei&thorn; also<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Idem quoque in registro sic ait: Legitur, quod beatus Augustinus nec cum sorore habitare consensit dicens: quae cum sorore mea sunt, sorores meae non sunt. docti ergo viri cautela magna nobis debet esse instructio.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of seint Austin &thorn;is word wel &thorn;ro:</L>
<L N="1265">&THORN;at wi&thorn; his suster wolde he not dwelle,</L>
<L>"&THORN;erfore he wolde sey ful welle:</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke wymmen &thorn;at wi&thorn; my suster be</L>
<L>Sustres beo &thorn;ei nouht to me.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cautel of &thorn;is mon so wys</L>
<L N="1270">Schulde beo ensaumple to vre auys".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Ambrose in his preface<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In prae|fatione quoque Ambrosiana sic legitur: Magnificentiam tuam in mortificatione Au|gustini adoramus tua (in omnibus) operante virtute, ut nullis promissis blandimento|rum fallacium vir tuo ignitus spiritu vinceretur, quia eum ita omni genere pietatis imbueras, ut ipse tibi ara et sacrificium et sacerdos esset et templum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of seint Austin sei&thorn; in &thorn;at place:</L>
<L>"&THORN;i mihtinesse we worschupe&thorn;, lord,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in dede and in word</L>
<L N="1275">And of &thorn;e stablyng of seint Austin</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh &thorn;in owne vertu diuin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so wi&thorn; &thorn;e holigost</L>
<L>Enspiret &mdash; riht wel &thorn;ou wost &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ouercome miht he not be</L>
<L N="1280">Wi&thorn; no falles of vanite;</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; al maner of pite,</L>
<L>Of mekenes and of charite</L>
<L>&THORN;ou him foundedest on good wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was to &thorn;e auter and sacrifice</L>
<L N="1285">And also temple and eke prest &mdash;</L>
<L>His doynge to &thorn;e was honest".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E clerk seint Prosper<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Beatus igitur Prosper in tertio libro de vita contemplativa sic de eo dicit: Sanctus Au|gustinus episcopus acer ingenio, suavis eloquio, saecularis literaturae peritus, in ecclesiasticis laboribus operosus, in quotidianis disputationibus clarus, in omni sua actione compositus, in quaestionibus solvendis acutus, in convincen|dis haereticis circumspectus, in expositione fidei nostrae catholicus, in expla|nandis scripturis canonicis cautus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sei&thorn; in his &thorn;ridde bok &thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made her in his lyf</L>
<L N="1290">Of &thorn;e lyf contemplatyf,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is maner, hose loke&thorn; hit:</L>
<L>"Seint Austin was a bisschop of scharp wit,</L>
<L>Softe mon in spekynge,</L>
<L>And in seculer lettrure cunnynge,</L>
<L N="1295">In holichirche werk and fulle werkere,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. and st. a?</NOTE></L>
<L>And in eueriday disputisouns clere,</L>
<L>And in alle his doynges</L>
<L>Manerliche of alle &thorn;inges,</L>
<L>To assoyle questions he was scharp,</L>
<L N="1300">To ouercome heretykes wise of carp,</L>
<L>And riht trewe" &mdash; as Prosper sei&thorn; &mdash;</L>
<L>"In exposicion of &thorn;e fei&thorn;,</L>
<L>And wondur war in expleyting
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Of holy mennes writyng".</L>
<L N="1305">Seint Bernard, God hit wot,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Bernardus quoque sic de eo scribit: Au|gustinus hic est validissimus malleus haereticorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of seint Austin &thorn;us he wrot:</L>
<L>"Austin is beetel strongest to felle,</L>
<L>Heretykes resouns forte quelle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel longtyme after &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post hoc autem, cum barbara gens(!) terram illam occupasset et sancta loca profanaret, fideles cor|pus Augustini ceperunt et ipsum in Sardiniam transtulerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1310">&THORN;at &thorn;e he&thorn;ene folk of Barbare(!)</L>
<L>Occupyed &thorn;at ilke londe</L>
<L>And holi places destruyeden wi&thorn; heor honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;er seint Austin buried was;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore byful &thorn;is ilke cas</L>
<L N="1315">&THORN;at cristene men token his bodi</L>
<L>And translated hit in to Sardini.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt bifel &thorn;enne atte last,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Transactis autem ab ejus obitu annis CCLXXX (!) circa annos domini DCCXVIII(!) Liprandus devotus Longobardorum rex, audiens Sardiniam (a Saracenis) depopulatam, sollemnes illuc nuntios misit, ut doctoris sancti reliquias Papiam deferrent,</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon two hondred &yogh;er and XXX<SUP>ti</SUP> wer past,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;er of vr lord bidene</L>
<L N="1320">Fyf hondred and eihte tene:</L>
<L>&THORN;er com to &thorn;e heryng</L>
<L>Of Ludbrande, &thorn;e noble kyng</L>
<L>Of Longobardis, &thorn;at distruyed</L>
<L>Was Sardinie. &thorn;erfore anuyed</L>
<L N="1325">He was. he sende &thorn;ider &thorn;o</L>
<L>Messagers, &thorn;at weren &thorn;ro,</L>
<L>Seint Austins relikes as a drurye</L>
<L>For to bere to Papye.</L>
<L>&THORN;is messagers gret &yogh;iftus &yogh;auen<NOTE PLACE="foot2">qui magno pretio dato corpus sancti Augustini tulerunt et ipsum usque Januam deportaverunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1330">Seint Austines bodi forte hauen,</L>
<L>And for&thorn; wi&thorn; hem &thorn;ei gonne hit walwe,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come to &thorn;e toun of Janwe.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e goode kyng herde of &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod devotus rex audiens, usque ad praedictam civitatem cum magno gaudio eidem obviavit et reverenter excepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes &thorn;e bodi he wente, iwis,</L>
<L N="1335">Wi&thorn; joye, and wi&thorn; reuerence</L>
<L>He hit receyued wi&thorn;oute offence.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwe whon hit was day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem mane vellent corpus deducere, nullo modo de loco moveri potuit, donec rex votum emisit, quod, si se inde duci permitteret, ibidem in suo nomine ecclesiam fabricaret. Cum autem votum fecisset, statim sine difficul|tate inde deductum est, rex autem quod voverat implevit et ibidem in honorem sancti Augustini ecclesiam construxit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolde haue lad hit for&thorn; on way.</L>
<L>&THORN;er bifel a wondur cas:</L>
<L N="1340">&THORN;ei miht not meue hit from &thorn;e plas,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e kyng a vow hedde mad</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if he suffrede him &thorn;ennes be lad,</L>
<L>He wolde riht &thorn;ere wi&thorn;outen blame</L>
<L>Buylde a chirche in his name.</L>
<L N="1345">When &thorn;e kyng hedde mad &thorn;e vou,</L>
<L>Lihtliche inou &mdash; i telle hit &yogh;ou &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei toke wi&thorn; hem for&thorn; &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng a churche let buylde riht &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;at o&thorn;urday wi&thorn; god wil<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Idem miraculum die sequenti in qua|dam villa episcopatus Terdonensis, quae dicitur Cassellae, contigit et eodem modo ibidem in honore sancti Augustini ecclesiam fabricavit (1356 Zus.); in|super villam ipsam cum omnibus suis appendentiis concessit servientibus ecclesiae Augustini perpetuo possidendam.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1350">&THORN;e same miracle of his bodi bifil</L>
<L>In a toun of &thorn;e bisschopriche</L>
<L>Of Terdonence, sikerliche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men callen &thorn;ere Cassel;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e same maner &thorn;e kyng riht wel</L>
<L N="1355">Let buylde a chirche of seint Austyn,</L>
<L>A wondur noble, feir and fyn;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilke same toun<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. In st. And, wie 1680.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;e possessioun</L>
<L>He graunted and &yogh;af wi&thorn;outen ende,</L>
<L N="1360">For &thorn;ei of him schulde haue sum muynde,</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at in seruise diuyn
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>In &thorn;at chirche seruen seint Austin.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng hedde gret &thorn;enkynge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quia vero rex viderat sancto complacere ut in suo nomine ecclesia fieret ubicumque mansisset, et timens ne in alio loco quam ubi desiderabat, locum sibi eligeret, in omni loco ubi de nocte cum corpore hospita|batur in honorem ipsius ecclesiam construebat, sicque cum magno gaudio Papiam de|ducitur et in ecclesia s. Petri, quae coelum aureum dicitur, honoriftce collocatur. &mdash; &mdash; (Folgen jetzt die Miracula:)</NOTE></L>
<L>Leste he to Papye him schulde not bringe;</L>
<L N="1365">&THORN;erfore, to plese &thorn;at seint wi&thorn; his miht,</L>
<L>Whereuer &thorn;e bodi lay al niht</L>
<L>&THORN;er a churche he let buylde,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ur hit were in toun or felde.</L>
<L>&THORN;us wi&thorn; joye ful goodlye</L>
<L N="1370">He brouhte &thorn;e bodi to Papye.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e chirche of seint Petre</L>
<L>Worschipfuliche in a fertre</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodi was leid wi&thorn; mylde steuene &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at chirche is called "&thorn;e guyldene he|uene". &mdash; &mdash; &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">sind 2 Zeilen Raum gelassen f&uuml;r eine Ueberschrift (etwa Miracula).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1375">A muleward &thorn;er was in &thorn;at cuntre,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Molendarius quidam in beatum Augustinum specialem devotionem habens cum quandam infirmitatem (quae dicitur phlegma sal|sum) in tibia pateretur, beatum Augustinum devote in sui adjutorium invocabat. Cui per visum s. Augustinus apparuit et tibiam manu palpans integrae restituit sanitati. Qui excitatus se liberatum invenit et Deo et beato Augustino gratias reddidit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde a gret enfermete</L>
<L>Vppon his leg for &thorn;e none,</L>
<L>Hit was so sor: he miht not gone;</L>
<L>But euere he hedde in feld and toun</L>
<L N="1380">In seint Austin deuocioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he preyed him deuouteliche</L>
<L>To ben his help certeynliche.</L>
<L>Seint Austin for his deuociun</L>
<L>Apered to him bi a uisioun<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. aui|sioun.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1385">And hondled his leg softe and wel:</L>
<L>And hit was hol &thorn;en eueridel.</L>
<L>Whon he awok, he fond hit so &mdash;</L>
<L>A wondur glad mon was he &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Almihti God and seint Austin</L>
<L N="1390">He &thorn;onked &thorn;enne wi&thorn; herte fyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A child &thorn;er was wi&thorn; wo bigon:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam puer cum vitio lapidis premeretur et de consilio medicorum incidi de|beret, mater pueri, mortis sibi timens periculum, beatum Augustinum devote in sui filii subsidium invocavit, statimque fusa oratione puer lapidem cum urina emisit et plenam sanitatem recepit (1404 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e seeknesse of &thorn;e ston;</L>
<L>Leches putte his frendes in witte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he moste nedes beo kitte.</L>
<L N="1395">But &thorn;e modur hedde gret drede</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;orwh &thorn;at cuttynge he schuld be dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to seint Austin &thorn;an</L>
<L>Deuoutliche preyede &thorn;at womman,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; word and wi&thorn; herte mylde,</L>
<L N="1400">&THORN;at he schulde helpe and hele hir chylde.</L>
<L>Anon riht &thorn;enne &thorn;e chyld, iwis,</L>
<L>A gret stone al out dude pis<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. stond st. stone.</NOTE></L>
<L>And was al hol of &thorn;at seknes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onked God of his goodnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1405">IN an hous of religious,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In monasterio, quod Elemosina dici|tur, monachus quidam in vigilia s. Augustini raptus in spiritu vidit nubem (splendi|dam) coelitus delapsam et super nubem Augustinum sedentem pontificalibus insigni|tum, cujus oculi quasi duo solis radii totam illam ecclesiam illuminabant et odor inde nimius exhalabat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at men callen Almous,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e vigile of seint Austin</L>
<L>A monk was rauissched &thorn;erin</L>
<L>In spirit and sauh such a cas:</L>
<L N="1410">&THORN;at a cloude from heuene sliden doun was,</L>
<L>And seint Austin &thorn;eron sittyng</L>
<L>In bisschops clo&thorn;ing, him &thorn;hou&yogh;te, wel semyng,</L>
<L>And his tweyn e&yogh;en verreyliche</L>
<L>To twei sonne bemus weren liche,
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="86"></L>
<L N="1415">&THORN;at al &thorn;at churche lihted &thorn;o,</L>
<L>A wondur gret swetnesse com him fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Bernard &thorn;orwh Godus miht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sanctus quoque Bernardus dum quadam vice in matu|tinis exsistens aliquantulum obdormivisset et de quodam tractatu Augustini lectiones legerentur, vidit quendam pulcherrimum juvenem ibi stantem, de cujus ore tantus in|undantium aquarum impetus exibat, quod totam illam ecclesiam videretur replere. Qui Augustinum esse non dubitavit, qui fonte doctrinae totam ecclesiam irrigavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was at matins on a niht,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e legende good and fyn<NOTE PLACE="foot1">legende st. lessoun?</NOTE></L>
<L N="1420">Was rad of a trete of seint Austin;</L>
<L>&THORN;e while a luytel on slepe he fil,</L>
<L>&THORN;ouh hit were not wi&thorn; his wil,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te he say &thorn;at ilke tym</L>
<L>A feir child stondynge beo him,</L>
<L N="1425">Of whos mou&thorn; out &thorn;er ran</L>
<L>So grete cours of watres &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit semed to him wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit fulde &thorn;e chirche eueridel.</L>
<L>Whon he awok, he wuste wel afyn</L>
<L N="1430">&THORN;at &thorn;at was seint Austin,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; his goode teching</L>
<L>Fulled holichirche wi&thorn; god lyuyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A mon &thorn;at louede him hertilike<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quidam s. Augustinum valde diligens monacho custodi corporis s. Augustini pecuniam magnam dedit, ut sibi s. Augustini digitum unum daret; sed ille accepta pecunia digitum cuiusdam mortui sericis involutum sibi tribuit, simulans esse digitum Augustini. Quem ille reverenter accipiens semper devotissime adorabat et ori oculis|que apponens crebro pectori adstringebat.</NOTE></L>
<L>Coueyted of him to haue a relyke:</L>
<L N="1435">&THORN;erfore ful deuoutely</L>
<L>To a monk &thorn;at kepte &thorn;e bodi</L>
<L>He &yogh;af for seint Austines sake,</L>
<L>On of his fingres him forto take,</L>
<L>A gret summe of good money.</L>
<L N="1440">&THORN;e monk &thorn;enne tok al in god fey,</L>
<L>But he him &thorn;ou&yogh;t sumwhat on gyle:</L>
<L>And a ded monnes fynger he rayed &thorn;at while,</L>
<L>Wrapped hit in a selkene clo&thorn;,</L>
<L>And tok hit &thorn;e mon wi&thorn;outen o&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1445">He seide: hit was of seint Austyn</L>
<L>A fingre and a relyke fyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon hit tok reuerentliche</L>
<L>And worschiped hit deuoutliche,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his e&yogh;en and his mou&thorn;,</L>
<L N="1450">He hit cussed, as &thorn;ing selcou&thorn;.</L>
<L>But God tok hede to his fei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cuius fidem Deus intuens, digito illo projecto unum digitum s. Augustini tam mirabiliter quam misericorditer sibi dedit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;orwh his miht, as &thorn;e bok sei&thorn;,</L>
<L>And a verrei fingre of seynt Austin</L>
<L>Him sende of his merci diuin,</L>
<L N="1455">And &thorn;at o&thorn;ur anon riht</L>
<L>Was don awey &thorn;orwh Godus miht.</L>
<L>Whon he to his cuntreye com, anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui cum repatriasset et multa ibi miracula fierent, fama usque Papiam delata est. Sed cum praedictus monachus assereret, quod cuiusdam mortui digitus ille esset, sepulchrum aperuerunt et unum deesse de ejus digitis invenerunt. Unde abbas re cognita monachum ab officio deposuit et dire afflixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mony miracles &thorn;er weoren don.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fame sprong so brod wi&thorn; hy&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="1460">Til hit com to Papye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e monk &thorn;at him bygyled hadde</L>
<L>Seide &thorn;at men weren waxen al madde,</L>
<L>For he him bigyled on his maner</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a ded monnes fynger.</L>
<L N="1465">But whon &thorn;e toumbe was vndon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei founden &thorn;at &thorn;er lakked on</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fyngres of his honde.</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne &thorn;ei &thorn;onked Godus sonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e abbot of his offyce</L>
<L N="1470">Remued &thorn;e monk, &thorn;at was so nyce,</L>
<L>And punissched him for &thorn;at doyng</L>
<L>Of such a fals begyling.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Burgoyne in a munster swet,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Apud Burgundiam in monasterio, quod dicitur Fontanetum, erat quidam monachus, Hugo nomine, s. Augustino valde devotus, qui in ejus scriptis miro desiderio pascebatur, quem etiam crebra supplicatione rogaverat ut ipsum ex hac luce migrare non sineret, nisi in die suae sacratissimae sollemnitatis. Ipse igitur XV die ante festum ejusdem sic coepit duris febribus aestuare, ut in vigilia ipsius super humum tamquam moriens poneretur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is icalled Fountanet,</L>
<L N="1475">&THORN;er was a monk, god mon and truwe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men called &thorn;o Daun Huwe,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;at &thorn;at.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>To seint Austin he was deuout,</L>
<L>To rede his bokus he was about.</L>
<L>He preied seint Austin deuoutlye</L>
<L N="1480">&THORN;at, what tyme &thorn;at he schulde dye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit scholde falle on his festeday &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us hertiliche he dude him pray.</L>
<L>Fiftene dayes tofore &thorn;at solempnite</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; brenynge feuere taken was he,</L>
<L N="1485">And riht vppon seint Austines eue</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al his rihtes and good bileue</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e grounde he was for&thorn; leyde,</L>
<L>Forte dye, as alle men seide.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirche an old monk sat,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ecce plures decori ac fulgentes viri amicti albis ecclesiam dicti monasterii processionaliter intraverunt, quos sequebatur quidam reverendus pontifica|libus insignitus: quidam autem monachus in ecclesia consistens hoc videns, obstupuit et quinam essent vel quo pergerent inquisivit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1490">Seyinge his psauter vppon a mat,</L>
<L>And sauh a siht of gret delyt:</L>
<L>A cumpaygnye, clo&thorn;ed in whit,</L>
<L>Entringe wi&thorn; deuocioun</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e churche on a processioun,</L>
<L N="1495">Beohynde hem alle &thorn;er com a man</L>
<L>Al lyk a bisschop iclo&thorn;ed &thorn;an.</L>
<L>&THORN;e monk sumdel aferd was,</L>
<L>But he asked on of hem &thorn;e cas,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ei weren and whodur &thorn;ei went,</L>
<L N="1500">Whi &thorn;ei come so, to what entent.</L>
<L>And anon riht in &thorn;at tym<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui unus eorum dixit, quod s. Augustinus esset cum suis canonicis, qui ad devotum suum morientem pergeret, ut ejus animam ad regnum gloriae deportaret.</NOTE></L>
<L>On of hem onswerde him</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Austin wi&thorn; his chanouns</L>
<L>Was icomen for &thorn;e nones,</L>
<L N="1505">To fette &thorn;e monkes soule to blis</L>
<L>&THORN;at him tofore hedde serued, iwis.</L>
<L>&THORN;o al &thorn;at feire cumpaygnie<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Post hoc illa reverenda processio ad infirmarium ingreditur; ubi cum aliquamdiu mansisset, sancta illa anima a carne soluta est, quam dulcis amicus et ab hostium insidiis securam reddidit et ad coeli gaudia introduxit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wenten euene to fermerie.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei a while hedden beo &thorn;erin,</L>
<L N="1510">&THORN;e soule from &thorn;e bodi dude twin</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ilke monk holye</L>
<L>&THORN;at for&thorn; was leid forte dye,</L>
<L>And seint Austin and his cumpaygnye</L>
<L>&THORN;at soule token to glorie</L>
<L N="1515">And diliuerde hit from &thorn;at enemye</L>
<L>&THORN;at to monkynde ha&thorn; euer envye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VPpon a tyme wi&thorn;outen drede<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Legitur quoque, quod, dum Augustinus in carne vi|veret et quaedam relegeret, ante se transire vidit daemonem librum humeris bajulan|tem. Qui ab eo protinus adjuratur ut, quae ibi scripta lateant, sibi pandat. Qui pec|cata hominum ibidem esse asserit scripta, quae undecumque collegit et in eo reposuit. Moxque ei praecepit ut, si aliquid suorum peccatorum ibi scriptum retineret, sibi legendum continuo manifestet (engl. dir.). Ostenso autem loco nihil Augustinus ibi scriptum reperit nisi quod quadam vice completorium ex oblivione dimisit,</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Austin vppon a bok gon rede,</L>
<L>W(h)il &thorn;at he liuede, wi&thorn; good entent:</L>
<L N="1520">He sauh wher a fend wend</L>
<L>And a gret bok in his nek</L>
<L>Trussed, in &thorn;e maner of a sek.</L>
<L>Anon him coniured seint Austyn</L>
<L>To schewe him what was writen &thorn;erin.</L>
<L N="1525">And he seide: "sunnes, wi&thorn;outen doute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue gedered of mennes aboute".</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou hast eny &thorn;er of myn,</L>
<L>Schewe me anon!" qua&thorn; seint Austyn.</L>
<L>And he him schewed wel a fyn</L>
<L N="1530">&THORN;at he hedde for&yogh;eten ones a cumplyn.</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;e fend him scholde abyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">praecipiensque dyabolo ut suum praestolaretur adventum, ecclesiam est ingres|sus et completorium devote dixit et solitas orationes complens peregit, reversusque dixit ei ut praedictum locum sibi ostenderet iterum relegendum (engl. dir.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Til he coome to him &thorn;at tyde.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e chirche he hyed sumwhat
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>And seide &thorn;e cumplin &thorn;at he for&yogh;at,</L>
<L N="1535">And his orisouns euerichon,</L>
<L>As he was wont forte don.</L>
<L>Whon he com to &thorn;e fend a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>"Scheuh me &thorn;e place" he gon seyn,</L>
<L>"&THORN;er &thorn;at i was set in &thorn;i boke,</L>
<L N="1540">Let me seo, red and loke!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend turnde faste, he cou&thorn;e not fynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui dum crebro revolveret et tandem locum vacuum reperisset, iratus dixit: Turpiter me decepisti, poenitet me quod librum meum tibi ostendi, quia peccatum tuum orationum tuarum virtute delevisti. Et his dictis confusus evanuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wox al wro&thorn; as &thorn;e wynde</L>
<L>And seide: "me for&thorn;inke&thorn; i schewed &thorn;e</L>
<L>Mi bok, for &thorn;ou hast bigyled me</L>
<L N="1545">And don awey wi&thorn; &thorn;i preyere</L>
<L>&THORN;i synne &thorn;at was writen here".</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend vanissched &thorn;enne away,</L>
<L>Seynt Austin nomore of him saih.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A wommon dwelled sum men among<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum quaedam mu|lier a quibusdam malitiosis injuriam pateretur, illa ad beatum Augustinum accessit, ut super hoc ejus consilium imploraret. Quae cum ipsum studentem invenisset et eum reverenter salutasset, ille nec ad eam respexit nec quidquam sibi respondit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1550">Sumtyme, &thorn;at dude hire muche wrong,</L>
<L>And &thorn;en heo went to seint Austin</L>
<L>To place &thorn;er he sat in,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">a fehlt vor place.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forte aske counseil of him</L>
<L>What hire weore best do for &thorn;at tym.</L>
<L N="1555">Heo fond him studying bisiliche,</L>
<L>And heo saluwed him reuerentliche,</L>
<L>But he biheold on hire no&thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ne onswerd nouht to hire seying.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wommon gan in hire hert caste<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Co|gitans illa ne forte ob nimiam sanctitatem in faciem mulieris nollet intendere, propius accessit et negotium diligenter exposuit; sed ille nec se ad eam convertit nec respon|sum aliquod sibi dedit, ideoque illa cum tristitia magna recessit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1560">&THORN;at &thorn;e holy mon was so studefaste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde not in no cas</L>
<L>Biholde a wommon in &thorn;e fas;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore heo neihhed him ner,</L>
<L>Tolde him &thorn;e cas of hire daunger.</L>
<L N="1565">But he tornd him nou&yogh;t to hire</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;af hire non onswere,</L>
<L>And heo &thorn;erfore wi&thorn; sori cher</L>
<L>Wente hir hom in heuy maner.</L>
<L>Afturward what more and lesse<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Altera autem die, cum Augustinus missam celebraret et dicta mulier interesset, post elevationem corporis rapta in spiritu vidit se positam ante tribunal sanctissimae trinitatis, ubi vidit Augustinum facie inclinata de trinitatis gloria attentissime et sublimissime dispu|tantem (1580 Zus.),</NOTE></L>
<L N="1570">On a day seint Austyn wente to messe;</L>
<L>&THORN;is wommon stod &thorn;ere and herde hit,</L>
<L>And was rauissched in hire spirit</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e sacringe in verite</L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;e he&yogh;e trinite:</L>
<L N="1575">&THORN;er heo sauh wi&thorn;outen dred</L>
<L>Seint Austin, enclyning wi&thorn; his hed,</L>
<L>As bisi as he mihte beo, iwis,</L>
<L>Disputyng of &thorn;e grete blis</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at blisful trinite &mdash;</L>
<L N="1580">God &yogh;if vs grace &thorn;at siht to se! &mdash;</L>
<L>A vois to hire seide cler and fyn:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">factaque est vox ad eam dicens: Cum ad Augustinum ivisti, ille sic de trinitatis gloria attentissime disputabat et ideo, quod ibi fueris, penitus non advertit; sed ad eum secure redeas, quia et eum clementem invenies et consilium sa|lubre reperies. Quod cum fecisset, Augustinus benigne eam audivit et consilium sa|lubre donavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Whon &thorn;ou were at seint Austyn,</L>
<L>He was so ifulled of charite,</L>
<L>To dispute of &thorn;e blis of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L N="1585">&THORN;at of &thorn;e tok he non hede,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur to counseil no to rede.</L>
<L>Bote go nou to him safliche,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;at mekeliche</L>
<L>He schal &thorn;e &yogh;iue good counsayle,</L>
<L N="1590">&THORN;e beste to don, wi&thorn;outen fayle".</L>
<L>As heo was beden, so dude heo,</L>
<L>And good counseil &thorn;en &yogh;af hire he.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="89"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SUm tyme a mon &thorn;er was<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fertur quoque, quod, dum quidam vir sanctus in spiritu raptus sanctos in gloria conspexisset et b. Augustinum minime vidisset, quendam de sanctis, ubinam A. esset, percunctatus est. Qui respondit: A. residet in excelsis, ubi disputat de gloria excellentissimae trinitatis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at bifel such a cas:</L>
<L N="1595">&THORN;at rauissched was in his spirit</L>
<L>In to blis wi&thorn; gret dilyt:</L>
<L>&THORN;er he sauh angeles monye</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur seintes in gret glorie,</L>
<L>But, for seint Austin he sauh nouht,</L>
<L N="1600">He wondrede gretliche in his &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>He asked &thorn;en on of hem</L>
<L>Wher seint Austin mihte ben.</L>
<L>And he seide: he was an heih,</L>
<L>As a wys clerk and a sleih</L>
<L N="1605">Disputyng in diuinite</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e heinesse of &thorn;e trinite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALso sum tyme men of Papye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum quidam Papienses a mar|chione Malaspinae in carcere detinerentur, ab iis omnis potus penitus est interdictus, ut posset ab iis magna pecunia extorqueri. Unde plerique jam spiritum exhalabant, quidam vero urinam bibebant.</NOTE></L>
<L>Weren itake for envye</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e marchiun of Malaspyn</L>
<L N="1610">And in a prison put strong wi&thorn;in;</L>
<L>For couetyse of heore moneye</L>
<L>&THORN;ei forbed vppon al weye</L>
<L>&THORN;at men schulde &yogh;iue hem no drinke,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;our swet ne sour, in hem to sinke.</L>
<L N="1615">&THORN;erfore summe di&yogh;ed &thorn;er in</L>
<L>And summe dronken heore oune vrin.</L>
<L>Amongus hem was a &yogh;ong felawe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At quidam juvenis inter eos, qui in b. Augu|stinum magnam devotionem habebat, ipsum in sui adjutorium invocavit. Tunc circa noctis medium s. Augustinus praedicto adolescenti apparuit et quasi manum ejus dextram apprehendens usque ad flumen Graveloni (1626 Zus.) ipsum deduxit ibique cum folio vitis in aqua madefacto sic ejus linguam refrigeravit, ut (qui urinam bibere cupierat) de potu nectaris non curaret.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at of seint Austin stod gret awe</L>
<L>And worschiped him hedde ofte tym:</L>
<L N="1620">&THORN;erfore he preyed he schulde helpe him.</L>
<L>&THORN;e nexte niht at hei&yogh; midniht</L>
<L>Austin apeered to him ful riht</L>
<L>And lad him bi &thorn;e riht hond</L>
<L>For&thorn; wi&thorn; him vppon druy&yogh;e lond,</L>
<L N="1625">Til he com to &thorn;e flod of Grauel &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony a mon knowe&thorn; riht wel;</L>
<L>&THORN;er Austin dupped a leef of a vyn</L>
<L>In &thorn;at flod wel ofte &thorn;erin,</L>
<L>&THORN;erwi&thorn; his tonge he moysted &thorn;an:</L>
<L N="1630">&THORN;erof was he a wel fayn man,</L>
<L>He &thorn;hou&yogh;te him so at ese, verreyment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he tok non hede of pyement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A prouost of a chirche collegial<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Praepositus cuiusdam ecclesiae in b. Augustinum magnam devotionem habens, cum per tres annos gravem infirmitatem in|currisset, ita ut de lecto surgere non valeret, adveniente sollemnitates. Augustini, cum jam in vigilia ad vesperas pulsaretur, (1643 Zus.) ad rogandum s. Augustinum tota devotione se contulit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loued seint Austin wi&thorn; his herte al.</L>
<L N="1635">But at a tyme him tok seknes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;reo &yogh;er wi&thorn;outen les</L>
<L>He kepte his bed as mon beddered,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mihte not sture out of &thorn;e sted.</L>
<L>Tyme of &yogh;eer com &thorn;en, parde,</L>
<L N="1640">Of seint Austines day &thorn;e solempnete.</L>
<L>Vppon his euen to euensong</L>
<L>Men rongen &thorn;o &thorn;reo peles long.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he herde &thorn;e swete soun,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; god herte and deuocioun</L>
<L N="1645">He dressed him to seye his preyere</L>
<L>To seint Austin wi&thorn; gode chere.</L>
<L>Seint Austin apeered &thorn;o to him<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui in albis Augustinus apparens, eidem ter citato proprio nomine dixit: Ecce assum totiens a te rogatus, surge cito et celebra mihi officium vespertinum. Qui sanus surgens (cunctis stupentibus) ecclesiam intravit et officium devote peregit (1657-8 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Al in whit, &thorn;e same tym,</L>
<L>And called him &thorn;ries bi his name</L>
<L N="1650">And seide to him: "her I ame</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast cleped so ofte si&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;at i nou seie, to me nou li&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Arys vp swi&thorn;e, and dwelle not long,</L>
<L>And go to churche and do euensong!"
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="90"></L>
<L N="1655">And so he dude anon riht:</L>
<L>And was al hol &thorn;orwh Godus miht</L>
<L>And &thorn;e preyere of seint Austine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at grete clerk is of dyuyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A schepherde bitwenen his scholdres twein<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum cuidam pastori saevum ulcus inter scapulas ortum esset, adeo morbus invaluit, ut jam totis esset viribus destitutus. Qui dum ad s. Augustinum preces emitteret, eidem Augustinus in visu apparuit et super locum infirmum manum apponens perfecte eum sanavit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1660">A gret bocche hedde and a uylein,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">bocche = botch, a swelling of the skin.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at him dude so muche wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at his mihtes were neih ago.</L>
<L>But to seint Austin he preyed fast</L>
<L>To sende him hele, atte last.</L>
<L N="1665">Seint Austin in a uisioun</L>
<L>Apered to him in his deuocioun</L>
<L>And leide his hond vppon &thorn;e sore:</L>
<L>And hit was hol for euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;At same mon afturward &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Idem quoque vir procedente tempore oculorum lumine est privatus. Qui cum s. Augustinum se|dulo invocaret, quodam die circa meridiem eidem apparuit et oculos manibus suis tergens pristinam sibi sanitatem restituit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1670">Lost &thorn;e siht of his e&yogh;en two.</L>
<L>To seint Austin his herte he lende</L>
<L>And preyed, his siht him forte sende.</L>
<L>Vppon a day aftur &thorn;e meridien</L>
<L>Austin apeered to him &thorn;en</L>
<L N="1675">And wiped his e&yogh;en wi&thorn; his honde:</L>
<L>And he was hol &thorn;orwh Godus sonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ABoute ni&yogh;ene hundred &yogh;er<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Circa annum domini DCCCCXII viri quidam graviter infirmi numero plus quam XL de Germania et Gallia Romam ibant ad limina apostolorum visitanda; quorum quidam scamnis in terra curvi se ve|hentes, alii cum baculis se sustentantes, alii privati oculis post alios se trahentes, alii contractas manus et pedes habentes pergebant. Qui montes transeuntes ad locum, qui dicitur Carbonaria, pervenerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And twelue of &thorn;e date of vr lord in fer</L>
<L>&THORN;er bifel such a chaunce</L>
<L N="1680">&THORN;at fourti sum of men of Germayn in Fraunce<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. in st. and; sollte es mehr als ein blosser Schreibfehler sein?</NOTE></L>
<L>Toward Rome wente wi&thorn; gret dilyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy apostles to visyte:</L>
<L>Summe were crupeles in carres led,</L>
<L>And summe were blynde and harde bisted,</L>
<L N="1685">And summe wi&thorn;outen staues mi&yogh;t not stonde,</L>
<L>And summe hedden lost bo&thorn;e fot and honde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at passeden ouer hulles monye<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;at st. &thorn;ei?</NOTE></L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come to &thorn;at place, called Carbo|narie.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei weoren comen almost &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum autem paene ad locum, qui Cana dicitur, advenissent, qui tribus millibus a Papia distat, (1692 Zus.) s. Augustinus pontificalibus indutus, de quadam ecclesia in honore ss. Cosmae et Damiani con|structa exiens, eisdem apparuit eosque salutans, quo tenderent requisivit. Qui cum ei quo tenderent respondissent, adjecit: Ite Papiam et de coenobio s. Petri, quod dicitur Coelum Aureum, interrogate et ibi misericordiam habebitis quam optatis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1690">To a place, men clepen Can,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is fro Papye but &thorn;reo mile,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ei rested a luytel while,</L>
<L>Out of a chirche &mdash; &thorn;at mani a man</L>
<L>Knowe&thorn;: &mdash; of seint Cosme and Damian</L>
<L N="1695">Com seynt Austin in bisschopes wede</L>
<L>To &thorn;is cumpaigni and bad god spede</L>
<L>And asked hem whodur &thorn;ei scholde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei seiden to Rome &thorn;at &thorn;ei fayn wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;en he hem bad &thorn;at in hi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="1700">&THORN;ey schulden wende to Papye,</L>
<L>&thorn;at "aftur seint Petres churche wi&thorn; mylde steuene<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. &thorn;at st. &thorn;er?</NOTE></L>
<L>Aske&thorn;, &thorn;at men calle&thorn; "&thorn;e guyldene he|uene!"</L>
<L>&THORN;er schul &yogh;e fynden &thorn;at merci"</L>
<L>He seide, "&thorn;at &yogh;e sechen, sikerli".
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="91"></L>
<L N="1705">&THORN;en &thorn;ei him asked what he hiht.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui cum eum de nomine suo interrogassent, ait: Ego sum Augustinus, quon|dam Hypponensis civitatis episcopus &mdash; statimque ab oculis eorum evanuit. Illi autem Papiam pergentes, cum ad dictum monasterium pervenissent, coeperunt omnes voces levare ac unanimiter conclamare: Sancte Augustine, adjuva nos</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en onswerde he anon riht:</L>
<L>"Mi nome is Austin, wite &yogh;e wel, men,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum tyme was bisschop of Iponen",</L>
<L>And &thorn;enne anon from heore e&yogh;e-siht</L>
<L N="1710">He vanissched &thorn;orwh Godus miht.</L>
<L>Te Papye whon &thorn;ei weren come,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e munstre &thorn;e wey &thorn;ei nome,</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;ei liften heore vois at ones</L>
<L>And cried riht &thorn;us for &thorn;e nones:</L>
<L N="1715">"Seint Austin confessour glorious,</L>
<L>Haue merci nou and help &thorn;ou vs!"</L>
<L>At &thorn;is cri &thorn;er comen anon<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ad quorum clamores cives et monachi (excitati ad tam grande spectaculum) confluebant, et ecce ex nervorum distentione sanguis multus coepit effluere, ita ut ab introitu coe|nobii usque ad tumbam s. Augustini tota terra sanguine videretur respersa. Cum autem ad sepulcrum s. Augustini venissent, omnes sanitati sunt integrae restituti, acsi nulla in eorum corporibus laesio exstitisset.</NOTE></L>
<L>Monkes and o&thorn;ur men mony on:</L>
<L>&THORN;er mihte men seo &thorn;e traces of bledyng</L>
<L N="1720">Of heore veynes streynyng,</L>
<L>From &thorn;e churche dore wel a fyn</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei come to &thorn;e tumbe of seynt Austin:</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;ei weren heled alle, parde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no sore on hem men mihte se.</L>
<L N="1725">From &thorn;at tyme for&thorn; &thorn;e grete fame<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Coepit extunc fama s. Augustini crebrescere et multitudo languentium ad ejus tumulum adventare, qui omnes sanitatis beneficia reportantes suae salutis pignora relinquebant, factumque est ut tanta prae|dictorum pignorum fuerit multitudo, ut inde totum oratorium s. Augustini et porticus plena essent, ita ut eundi et redeundi impedimentum non modicum generarent. Qua|propter monachi necessitate compulsi ea inde removeri fecerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Encresed of seint Austines name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at muche pepele afturward</L>
<L>&THORN;at seke weoren wenten &thorn;iderward,</L>
<L>And of heore seknesse feir and wel</L>
<L N="1730">Weren iheled eueridel.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er weore laft so mani</L>
<L>Signes of wax, verreyli,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Austines chapel</L>
<L>And &thorn;e porche &thorn;erof eueridel</L>
<L N="1735">Weoren so ful, &thorn;at no wiht</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur in ne out passe miht.</L>
<L>Neode drof &thorn;e monkes to take away</L>
<L>Mony of &thorn;e signes, day bi day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIt is an old notabilite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Notandum, quod, cum tria sint quae a mundanis hominibus appetuntur: scilicet divitiae, deliciae et honores, vir iste sanctus tantae perfectionis exstitit, quod ipse divitias contemsit, honores respuit, voluptates abhorruit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1740">&THORN;at &thorn;reo &thorn;ingus &thorn;er be</L>
<L>&THORN;at worldliche men disiren here:</L>
<L>Riches, delices, and worschipes in feere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is seint was of so gret parfecciun</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of &thorn;eos &thorn;inges hedde abhomina|ciun.</L>
<L N="1745">&THORN;at he dispised so riches,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod enim divitias contemneret, ipse testatur in libro Soliloquiorum, ubi ratio eum interrogat dicens: Divitias nullas cupis? et respondet Augustinus: Hoc quidem nec nunc primum; nam cum XXX annos agam, XIV fere anni sunt ex quo ista cupere destiti nec aliud in his praeter necessa|rium victum cogitavi, prorsus unus Ciceronis liber mihi facile persuasit nullo modo esse appetendas divitias.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e bok "Soliloquijs" he bere&thorn; witnes;<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. he ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;er Resun aske&thorn; him &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Of richesse whe&thorn;ur &thorn;ou beo couetous?"</L>
<L>Seint Austin &thorn;er onswere&thorn; him</L>
<L N="1750">And sei&thorn;: "&thorn;is nis not &thorn;e furste tym,</L>
<L>For i am now of &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;he fourtene ben passed her</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en i hedde no coueytyng</L>
<L>But onliche to mete, drinke and clo&thorn;ing:</L>
<L N="1755">For vppon Ciceronis oune boke</L>
<L>I lernde wel whon I dude loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at i schulde on none wyse</L>
<L>Of richesse haue no coueytise".
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="92"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>REsun him asked also<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod autem honores respuerit, in eodem libro testatur, ubi ratio eum interrogat dicens: Quid honores? et respondet Augustinus: Fateor eos modo ac paene his diebus cupere destiti.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1760">In &thorn;e same bok &thorn;erto:</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er he tok ouht to gret kepe</L>
<L>To eny worldly worschepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he onswere&thorn; godliche</L>
<L>And sei&thorn;: "I knowleche outurliche</L>
<L N="1765">I haue hem laft for euermo,</L>
<L>Whil niht and day mai come and go".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LVst also and dilytinge<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Voluptates quoque et de|licias (Gr&auml;sse: divitias) contemsit et quantum ad concubitum et quantum ad gustum. Quantum ad primum, interrogat eum ratio dicens in eodem libro: Quid uxor? nonne te delectat pulchra, pudica, morigerata, dives, praesertim si certus sis nihil ex ea te molestiae esse passurum?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of fleschlich likyng or tastinge</L>
<L>He forsok, as &thorn;e same bok telle&thorn; vs,</L>
<L N="1770">And sei&thorn; and telle&thorn; riht &thorn;us:</L>
<L>Resun him aske&thorn; of a wyf:</L>
<L>Wher he hedde lykynge in &thorn;at lyf,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at heo weore feir and clene,</L>
<L>Feir-manered, wi&thorn;outen wene,</L>
<L N="1775">And &yogh;if &thorn;at he wuste sikerliche</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo weore wondur riche,</L>
<L>Nomeliche &yogh;if he wuste sikerliche his ese,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde soffre no disese.</L>
<L>Austin onswere&thorn; anon riht:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">et respondet Augustinus: Quantumlibet velis eam depingere atque cumulare bonis omnibus, nil mihi tam fugiendum quam concubitum esse decrevi. Cui ratio: Non ego quaero quid decreveris, sed utrum ad hoc alliceris? et respondet Augustinus: Prorsus nihil in hujusmodi quaero, nihil desidero, etiam cum onere, horrore et aspernatione talia recordor.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1780">"&THORN;auh &thorn;ou hire peynted neuer so briht</L>
<L>And rikene as muche goodnesse</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou const, bo&thorn;e more and lesse,</L>
<L>I haue icast ouer alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To fleo flescliche doyng".</L>
<L N="1785">Qwa&thorn; Resun &thorn;enne: "I aske &thorn;e nouht</L>
<L>What to do &thorn;ou hast cast in &thorn;i &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>But whe&thorn;er wi&thorn; loue o&thorn;ur wi&thorn; awe</L>
<L>&THORN;yn herte &thorn;erto weore ouht idrawe?"</L>
<L>Austin onswerde wi&thorn;outen ire:</L>
<L N="1790">"In such &thorn;ing haue I non disyre;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if hit falle out to my mynde,</L>
<L>Hit is wi&thorn; horrour a(n)d dispisynge".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>REsun him asked: of his dilyt<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quantum ad secundum, in|terrogat eum ratio dicens: Quid de cibis? et respondet Augustinus: Sive de cibo et potu sive de balneis caeteraque corporis voluptate nihil interroges; tantum ab ea peto quantum in valetudinis spem conferri potest.</NOTE></L>
<L>In mete and drinke hou stod hit.</L>
<L N="1795">And he onswerde wi&thorn;outen sca&thorn;e:</L>
<L>"Of mete, drinke ne of ba&thorn;e</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur of o&thorn;ur bodiliche lustus</L>
<L>Aske me nou&yogh;t, as &thorn;houh &thorn;ou nustes;</L>
<L>I ne aske no more, my lyf to lede,</L>
<L N="1800">But onliche on such &thorn;inges &thorn;at me do&thorn; nede".</L>
<L>God &yogh;iue ou grace wi&thorn; herte glade</L>
<L>To preye for him &thorn;at &thorn;is lyf made.</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
</LG>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000099.tif" N="93">
<HEAD>7. Savinian &amp; Savina.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">7) Das Orig. s. Leg. Aur. cap. 127: de sanctis Saviniano et Savina. Der Titel im Ms. ist blos Sauina.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SVm tyme &thorn;er was an he&thorn;en man<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vgl.: Savinianus et Savina fuerunt filii Savini (viri nobilissimi, sed) pagani, qui de prima uxore Savinianum (!) genuit, de secunda Savi|nam filiam generavit (et ex nomine suo ambos vocavit).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at men called Sauyn &thorn;an.</L>
<L>Of his furste wyf he gat a childe</L>
<L>And called him Sauyn, god and mylde,</L>
<L N="5">Of his secunde wyf also</L>
<L>A feir douhtur he gat &thorn;o</L>
<L>And called hire rihte name</L>
<L>Sauyna, wommon of gode fame.</L>
<L>Sauyn &thorn;e &yogh;onge rad on a boke<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Legens autem Savinianus versum illum: Adsperges me domine etc., quid hoc esset quaerebat, sed intelligere non valebat.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">On a tyme as he gon loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;is vers, wi&thorn;outen mor:</L>
<L>Asperges me domine &amp; mundabor.</L>
<L>What was &thorn;erof &thorn;e vndurstondyng,</L>
<L>Cou&thorn;e he not wite for no&thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="15">In to his chaumbre he wente him &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Unde intrans in cubiculum in cinere et cilicio prostratus jacebat, dicens se malle mori quam non intelligere sensum verbi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leide him in askes and in an here,</L>
<L>And seide he hedde leuer dye &thorn;en</L>
<L>But he mihte wite what &thorn;at was to men.</L>
<L>An angel seide to him &thorn;is red:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. And st. an.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui apparens angelus dixit: Noli te usque ad mortem affligere, quoniam invenisti gratiam apud Deum, et cum baptizatus fueris, nive candidior eris et tunc intelliges quod nunc quaeris.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">"Trouble not &thorn;i self riht to bi ded,</L>
<L>For riht here in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of God &thorn;ou hast ifounden grace;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou art cristned, wite wel nou,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt beo whittore &thorn;en is &thorn;e snouh,</L>
<L N="25">And &thorn;en scha(l)t &thorn;ou riht wel wite<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. schat st. schalt.</NOTE></L>
<L>What is to sei &thorn;at &thorn;ou sauh write".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e angel was gon him fro,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Recedente angelo (laetus efficitur et) ydola de caetero venerari contemnens a patre plurimum objurgatur. Cum ergo pater saepius sibi diceret: Melius est ut, quia Deos non adoras, tu solus moriaris, quam nos omnes in morte tua insimul invol|vamur,</NOTE></L>
<L>Idoles and maumetes he forsok &thorn;o</L>
<L>And worschiped hemnomore aftur &thorn;at tym.</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;erfore his fader was wro&thorn; wi&thorn; him</L>
<L>And seide: "beter is, wi&thorn;outen drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou al one beo dede</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou vr godus nult not honoure,</L>
<L>&THORN;en alle we dyen in on vre".</L>
<L N="35">Priueliche fleih he &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot2">latenter aufugit et ad urbem Trecasinam devenit. Cumque super fluvium Secanae venisset et ut ibi ex eo baptizaretur, dominum exorasset, ibidem baptizatus est, dixitque ei dominus: Nunc invenisti quod tamdiu quaerendo laborasti. Statimque in terra baculum fixit et facta oratione baculus ille coram multis adstantibus frondes et flores produxit, ita quod MCVIII viri domino crediderunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute; of Tetrasinan.</L>
<L>Whon he com to &thorn;e watur of Secan,</L>
<L>&THORN;er preyed he God, as a good man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristendom he wolde him sende.</L>
<L N="40">And so hit was, er he &thorn;eonne wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;en seide vr lord: "&thorn;at &thorn;ou hast souht,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast nou founden &mdash; leose hit nouht!"</L>
<L>He stiked &thorn;er his staf adoun</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;en his orisoun &mdash;</L>
<L N="45">Toforen alle &thorn;at &thorn;er weren &thorn;at vre</L>
<L>Hit bar leues and eke floure.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at for &thorn;at miracle &thorn;o</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousund an hundred and ei&yogh;te &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Men bileeued in vr lord</L>
<L N="50">And worschuped him wi&thorn; herte and word.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e emperour Aurelean<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Imperator autem Aurelianus hoc audiens, milites ad eum capiendum plures direxit, qui eum orantem invenientes ad ipsum accedere timuerunt, (imperator autem plures prioribus misit, qui venientes cum eo orante pariter oraverunt) surgentesque(!) dixerunt: Imperator desi|derat te videre (61 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>Herde of such a maner man,</L>
<L>&THORN;ider he sente mony knihtes
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>Him to take and bringe for&thorn; rihtes.</L>
<L N="55">Whon &thorn;ei comen to &thorn;e watur syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei founden him preyinge in &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weren aferd him to lette,</L>
<L>But, whon he ros, &thorn;ei him grette</L>
<L>And seiden: "sire, wite &thorn;ou parde,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e emperour desyre&thorn; to seo &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Go we &thorn;erfore to Aurelian!"</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at he was ibrouht &thorn;an,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Qui cum venisset et nollet sacrificare, manus ejus et pedes fecit ligari et vectibus ferreis caedi. Cui Savinianus: Adauge tormenta, si potes.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he nolde not do sacrifise</L>
<L>To heore maumetes on heore gyse,</L>
<L N="65">Fot and hond he let him bynde</L>
<L>And al to-beten bifore and bihynde.</L>
<L>Sauiniam seide &thorn;enne anon riht:</L>
<L>"Puyt for&thorn; mo tormens, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou miht!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour comaunded anon &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc jussit eum in media civitate ligari super scamnum (72 Zus.) et sup|positis lignis, oleo et igne incendio concremari. Rex autem intuens vidit eum in media flamma stantem pariter et orantem. Stupefactus in suam faciem cecidit et surgens ei dixit:</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">In &thorn;e middel of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute;</L>
<L>Schulde beo bounde to a piler,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mihte feor no ner,</L>
<L>And wode and oyle put to him &thorn;an</L>
<L>And fuir, to brenne Sauinian.</L>
<L N="75">Whon &thorn;e emperour him sauh in his tur|ment</L>
<L>Preye to God wi&thorn; good entent,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he was neuer &thorn;e wors</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fuir, at &thorn;at cours</L>
<L>For wonder in &thorn;at ilke stounde</L>
<L N="80">He fel doun griuelyng to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>And ros vp wod as eny hare</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;eose wordus &thorn;are:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou wode best, wi&thorn; &thorn;i doyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Fera mala, non tibi sufficiunt animae quas decepisti, nisi et nos per magicam artem decipere moliaris.</NOTE></L>
<L>Suffise&thorn; not &thorn;i deseyuyng</L>
<L N="85">Of mennes soules, so mote &thorn;ou &thorn;riue,</L>
<L>But wi&thorn; wicchecraft vs deceyue".<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;ou fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>Sauiniam seide to him &thorn;o:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui Savinianus: Adhuc multae animae et tu ipse per me sunt domino crediturae (90 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;it &THORN;orwh me schullen soulus mo</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;i self beo tornd to God,</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;auh &thorn;ou beo nou ful wilde of mod".</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour comaundede in &thorn;at stoun|de:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Cum autem imperator ex hoc nomen Dei blasphemasset), in crastinum jussit eum ad stipitem ligari et sagittari; sa|gittae autem a dextris et a sinistris in a&euml;re suspendebantur nec aliqua eum laesit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwe he schulde beo bounde</L>
<L>To a stok and &thorn;enne beo schote</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; arwes from hed to fote.</L>
<L N="95">Whon &thorn;ei schoten, his bodi to peire,</L>
<L>&THORN;e arwes hengen in &thorn;e eire</L>
<L>On his luft syde and his riht arm,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. luft st. left.</NOTE></L>
<L>But he him self hedde non harm.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour ful wro&thorn; hym leete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Altera die imperator ad eum veniens dixit ei: Et ubi est Deus tuus? veniat nunc et de sagittis istis te liberet. Statimque una de illis sagittis (exsiliens) regem in oculo percussit et penitus excaecavit. Unde iratus jussit eum in carcere recipi et in crastino decollari.</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">Ano&thorn;ur day bad men him schete</L>
<L>And seide: "wher is &thorn;i God? &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&thorn;ou aus nou corrig.</NOTE></L>
<L>Let him saue &thorn;e from &thorn;eos arwes nou".</L>
<L>On of &thorn;at same arwes wi&thorn;outen ly&yogh;e</L>
<L>Hutte &thorn;e emperour in &thorn;e e&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="105">And for he hedde lost his e&yogh;e-siht,</L>
<L>He comaundede him to prisun anon riht,</L>
<L>And he bad also wi&thorn; sorwe</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulde gurde of his hed amorwe.</L>
<L>Sauinian preied God in &thorn;at cas<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Savinianus autem orans ut ad locum ubi baptizatus fuerat transferre|tur, confractis catenis (et apertis ostiis) per medios milites transiens illuc venit; quod audiens imperator jussit eum illuc insequi et capite truncari (118 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">&THORN;at he moste come to &thorn;at plas</L>
<L>&THORN;er he was cristned for Godus sake:</L>
<L>Anon his veteres al to-brake,</L>
<L>And among &thorn;e knihtes euerichon
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>To &thorn;at flod he wente anon.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;e emperour herde of &thorn;is cast</L>
<L>And bad men schulde pursuwe him fast,</L>
<L>His hed &thorn;er of to smyte &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at was his most delyte.</L>
<L>Whon Sauinian sauh ful riht<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Videns autem Savinianus milites insequentes, super aquam velut supra petram ambulavit, quousque ad locum sui baptismi pervenit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;er suwed him mony a kniht,</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e watur he wente anon,</L>
<L>As &thorn;eih he on eor&thorn;e hedde igon,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he com to &thorn;at same plas</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at he icristened was.</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e knihtes waded in ful fast<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum igitur milites transvadassent et eum percutere formidarent, dicit illis: Securi me percutite et de sanguine meo ad im|peratorem deferte, ut lumen recipiat et Dei virtutem agnoscat.</NOTE></L>
<L>And come to him atte last;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weren aferd him forte smite,</L>
<L>He bad hem not spare for no despite,</L>
<L>"And whon &thorn;at &yogh;e haue so idon,</L>
<L N="130">Take&thorn; my blod wi&thorn; ou anon</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e emperour ful riht</L>
<L>Bere&thorn; hit, &thorn;at he mowe haue his siht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mowe knowe euer afturward</L>
<L>Godus vertue, &thorn;at is vr lord!"</L>
<L N="135">Whon his hed was of ismite,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Percussus igitur caput suum levavit et passibus XLIX illud portavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his oune hondes he tok hite</L>
<L>And &thorn;orwh Godus grete graas</L>
<L>Bar hit nine and fourti paas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour afturward wi&thorn; hi&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot2">At imperator, cum de ejus sanguine oculum tetigisset, continuo sanatus est, dicens: Vere bonus et magnus est Deus christianorum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">Wi&thorn; &thorn;at blod enoynte(d) his e&yogh;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. enoynte st. enoynted.</NOTE></L>
<L>And anon riht wi&thorn;outen more</L>
<L>He sauh as wel as dude bifore,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">dude = dude he.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;en he seide wi&thorn; milde mood:</L>
<L>"Forso&thorn;e, cristen mennes God is good!"</L>
<L N="145">A wommon &thorn;at blynd hedde iben iwis<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quod audiens quaedam quae annis XL lumen amiserat, ad locum portari se fecit et facta oratione protinus lumen accepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fourti winter, herd of &thorn;is</L>
<L>And let men to &thorn;at place hire bere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er heo made hire preyere:</L>
<L>And &thorn;orwh &thorn;e grace of God almiht</L>
<L N="150">And of his seynt heo hedde hire siht.</L>
<L>&THORN;is seint was sent &thorn;us to glorie<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Passus est autem circa annos domini CCLXXIX cal. Februarii (!)</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ni&thorn;e kalende of Februarie(!).</L>
<L>But his owne susteer<NOTE PLACE="foot2">(Sed hoc ideo inseritur, ut hystoriae sororis suae, cuius festum praecipue hic recolitur, haec quoque hystoria con|jungatur).</NOTE></L>
<L>Di&yogh;ed ano&thorn;ur tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="155">Of hire now schal i tel,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e wollen lusten me wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAuina was he&thorn;ene &yogh;it<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ejus soror igitur Savina fratrem suum quotitie fleret et pro eo ydolis supplicaret, tandem sibi dormienti apparuit angelus dicens: Savina, noli flere (164 Zus.), sed quaecumque habes derelinque et invenies fratrem tuum in honore maximo constitutum.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in idoles hedde gret dilyt,</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;ede for hir bro&thorn;ur to hem fast,</L>
<L N="160">Heo wepte also. but atte last,</L>
<L>In hire slep as heo was leyd,</L>
<L>An aungel com and to hire seid:</L>
<L>"Sauina, wep &thorn;ou no more!</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;i self, beo not forlore,</L>
<L N="165">And forsak al &thorn;yn hauyng:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt fynde &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur, dwel|lyng</L>
<L>In &thorn;e moste worschupe iwis</L>
<L>&THORN;at may beo, in joye and blis".</L>
<L>Whon heo awok of hire slepyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Quae evigilans collactaneae suae dixit: Amica mea, aliquidne sen|sisti? Et illa: Etiam, domina; nam vidi hominem tecum loquentem, sed nescio qui|dem quid dicentem. Non me, inquit, accusabis? Et illa: Absit, domina; quaecun|que vis, facias, tantum non te occidas.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">Heo asked hire felawe: "sau&yogh; &thorn;ou eny &thorn;ing?"
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, heo seide, my deore ladi,</L>
<L>I saih a mon speke wi&thorn; &thorn;e, verreyli,</L>
<L>But what he seide, wot i nouht,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;eron haue I no &thorn;ouht".</L>
<L N="175">Sauyna seide: "loke &thorn;ou hit not oute".</L>
<L>"Nay, dame, qua&thorn; heo, wi&thorn;oute doute,</L>
<L>Whateuer &thorn;ou wolt, do &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ou &thorn;i self nou&thorn;ur sle ne spille".</L>
<L>Vppon &thorn;e morwe whon hit was day,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Sicque in crastino ambae recesserunt. Cum ergo pater diu fecisset eam inquiri et non invenisset, elevatis ad coelum manibus ait: Si tu es Deus potens in coelo, ydola mea comminue, quae natos meos salvare non potuerunt. Tunc dominus intonans omnia comminuit et confregit, quod multi videntes crediderunt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">Bo&thorn;e two &thorn;ei wenten heore way.</L>
<L>Hire fadur hir souhte in eueri plas &mdash;</L>
<L>No mon cou&thorn;e wite wher &thorn;at heo was.</L>
<L>His hondus &thorn;en heold he vp to heuene</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;eos wordus wi&thorn; mylde ste|uene:</L>
<L N="185">"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo God of heuene, as men letes,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">letes v. let = to pretend, vgl. Gen. u. Exod. 2168 (ags. la&eacute;tan to pretend).</NOTE></L>
<L>Lord of al: brek my maumetes</L>
<L>&THORN;at miht not saue my children twein &mdash;</L>
<L>Hem to truste is not but veyn".</L>
<L>Vr lord sende a &thorn;ondur anon</L>
<L N="190">And brac his idoles euerichon.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ulke &thorn;at se&yogh;en and &thorn;ere stood</L>
<L>Euer aftur leeued in God.</L>
<L>Sauina com &thorn;enne to Rome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Verum beata Savina Romam veniens ab Eusebio papa baptizatur et duos caecos duosque contractos sanans (V annis ibi permansit).</NOTE></L>
<L>Eusebie &thorn;e pope &yogh;af hire cristendome;</L>
<L N="195">Twey blynde heo heled &thorn;oru&yogh; Godus sonde</L>
<L>And tweyne &thorn;at weren croked, fot and honde.</L>
<L>Vppon a niht in hire slepyng<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cui dormienti apparens angelus dixit: Savina, quid est quod facis, ut tuas divitias de|serens nunc igitur in deliciis hic epuleris? surge et vade in Trecas civitatem, ut fratrem tuum ibidem invenias (205 Zus.).</NOTE></L>
<L>An angel com to hire, sey&yogh;ing:</L>
<L>"Sauina, hou hast &thorn;ow</L>
<L N="200">Forsaken &thorn;i richesse, now</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art ifed her wi&thorn; delice? &mdash;</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;ou not &thorn;erof to nice.</L>
<L>Aris vp &thorn;erfore out of &thorn;is plas</L>
<L>And go to &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute; of Thretas &mdash;</L>
<L N="205">Loke &thorn;ou beo not longe beohynde &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur &thorn;ou schalt fynde".</L>
<L>Heo seyde to hire maiden &thorn;o:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Dixit ergo famulae suae: Non oportet nos hic amplius habitare. Et illa: Domina, quo vis ire? ecce omnes valde te dili|gunt, et tu peregre mori cupis? Et illa: Deus nobis providebit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hennes forso&thorn;e we moste go".</L>
<L>"A, ladi! heo seide, whodur wol &yogh;e?</L>
<L N="210">Alle men here louen wel &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wolt go on pilgrimage,</L>
<L>To dye, or &thorn;ou come to ful age?"</L>
<L>Heo onswerd: "God al vr weye,</L>
<L>What &thorn;at vs nede&thorn;, wol purueye".</L>
<L N="215">Heo tok wi&thorn; hire barli-bred &thorn;en,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et accipiens panem hordeaceum, in urbem Ravennam devenit, veniensque ad domum cuiusdam divitis, cuius filia quasi mortua plangebatur, se ibidem a famula hospitio recipi po|stulabat. Quae ait: Domina mea, quomodo hic hospitari vales, cum filia dominae meae moriatur et omnes se graviter affligant? Non propter me, inquit, morietur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Til &thorn;at heo com to &thorn;e cite of Rauen,</L>
<L>To a riche monnes hous in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Whos douhtur was neih dede &mdash;</L>
<L>For hire hir frendes maden serwe.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;er heo asked hire herborwe</L>
<L>Of a seruaunt of &thorn;at hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire onswerde sone &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Hou mihte &yogh;e beo herborwed her,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;he my maistresse make&thorn; such cher</L>
<L N="225">And al o&thorn;ur beo&thorn; wi&thorn; del bistedde,</L>
<L>For hir douhtur is neih ded a bedde?</L>
<L>Sauina onswerde wi&thorn;outen more:</L>
<L>"Heo ne schal not dy&yogh;e &thorn;erfore".</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at hous &thorn;en heo wonde<NOTE PLACE="foot1">wonde, so Gen. u. Exod. 4136. 3782, v. winden.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Intrans igitur domum, manum puellae apprehendit et sanam ipsam erexit (232 Zus.), et cum vellent eam retinere, nullatenus acquievit.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">And tok &thorn;e child vp bi &thorn;e honde
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>And made hire hol of hire seknesse &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof made joye bo&thorn;e more and lesse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode mon of &thorn;e hous and his wyf</L>
<L>Wolden han wi&thorn;holden hire as heore lyf,</L>
<L N="235">But &thorn;erto wolde heo nou&yogh;t assent,</L>
<L>But went hire wei wi&thorn; good entent.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Cum ergo juxta Trecas ad milliare venisset, dixit famulae suae ut paulum repausarent.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon heo com to a plas</L>
<L>&THORN;at nas bote a myle from Tretas,</L>
<L>Heo seide to hire maiden &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="240">A luytel &thorn;at heo wolde reste here.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at cit&eacute;&eacute; a noble man<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Et ecce vir qui|dam nobilis Licerius de civitate veniens dixit ei: Unde estis? Cui Savina: Hinc sum de ista civitate. Et ille: Cur mentiris, cum loquela indicat te esse peregrinam? Et illa: Domine, vere peregrina sum et fratrem meum Savinianum diu perditum requiro. Cui ait: Vir ille quem quaeris ante paululum pro Christo decollatus est (255 Zus.) et in tali (!) loco sepultus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com to hem tweyne &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Lycen icalled was he,</L>
<L>And he hem asked: "whennes beo &yogh;e?"</L>
<L N="245">Sauina seide: "sire, parde,</L>
<L>I am riht of &thorn;is cuntre".</L>
<L>Lycen seide: "whi gabbest &thorn;ou?</L>
<L>&THORN;i tonge schewe&thorn; &thorn;e for a pilgrim nou".</L>
<L>Sauina seide &thorn;enne to him:</L>
<L N="250">"Forso&thorn;e, sire, I am a pilgrim,</L>
<L>And seche my bro&thorn;ur Sauinian</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ilost long tyme agan".</L>
<L>Lycen seide &thorn;an: "in certayn,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at &thorn;ou sechest was islayn.</L>
<L N="255">Hit neode&thorn; not to &thorn;e forte scof:</L>
<L>For Cristes loue his hed is of,</L>
<L>His bodi, as i &thorn;e sey, iwis,</L>
<L>In Godus place iburied is".</L>
<L>Prostrat heo fel &thorn;en to grounde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Tunc se prosternens in oratione ait: Domine, (qui me semper in castitate servasti,) non permittas me amplius duris itineribus fatigari aut corpus meum de loco isto ulterius moveri! commendo tibi famulam meam, quae pro|pter me tanta sustinuit, fratremque meum, quem hic videre non potui, fac ut in regno tuo videre merear.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">And preyed to God &thorn;us in &thorn;at stounde:</L>
<L>"Lord, on God in Trinite,</L>
<L>Suffre &thorn;ou nou me no more</L>
<L>Beo fortrauayled wi&thorn; weyes sore,</L>
<L>Ne my bodi awei to pas,</L>
<L N="265">&YOGH;if &thorn;i wille beo, out of &thorn;is plas!</L>
<L>To &thorn;e also, lord, i comende</L>
<L>Mi damysele for to defende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; me &thorn;us hiderto</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; isoffred pyne and wo.</L>
<L N="270">And my bro&thorn;ur, &thorn;at wi&thorn;outen lye</L>
<L>I wende to haue sey&yogh;en here wi&thorn; e&yogh;e,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i kyngdom mak me him seo,</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;auh i vnwor&thorn;i beo!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is orisoun whon heo hedde ised,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Finita autem oratione migravit ad dominum. Quod videns ejus famula coepit flere, quia ad sepeliendum necessaria non habebat.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Anon riht &thorn;o heo was ded.</L>
<L>Whon hir seruaunt &thorn;erof was war,</L>
<L>Heo wepte and hedde muche car,</L>
<L>For heo nedde nou&yogh;t, sikerly,</L>
<L>To burie wi&thorn; &thorn;enne &thorn;e bodi.</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e forseid mon &thorn;enne parde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Prae|dictus autem vir praeconem per civitatem misit, ut homines ad sepeliendum mulierem peregrinam venirent. Qui venientes honorifice eam sepelierunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sende a criour &thorn;orwh &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men schulde come to him,</L>
<L>To burie a wommon, a pilgrim.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ei duden so&thorn;liche</L>
<L N="285">And burieden &thorn;e bodi worschipefuliche. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dai, &thorn;at &thorn;e feste is of seint Sauin &amp; Sauina,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Hac quoque die fit festum sanctae Sabinae, quae fuit uxor Valentini militis, quae, cum nollet sacri|ficare, (sub Adriano imperatore) decollata est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is &thorn;e festeday of seint Sabina,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was a wyf of gret miht</L>
<L>To Valentinian &thorn;e kniht,</L>
<L N="290">&THORN;at, for heo nolde not do sacrifise</L>
<L>On &thorn;e he&thorn;en mennes wyse,</L>
<L>Was imartred and don to ded,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei smiten of hire hed.
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="[98]">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000105.tif" N="[99]">
<HEAD>II. Einzellegenden.</HEAD>

<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="[100]">


<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000107.tif" N="[101]">
<HEAD>1. Kindheit Jesu.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Ms. schreibt w<SUP>t</SUP> f&uuml;r wyth oder wyt (t steht h&auml;ufig st. th), &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> f&uuml;r &thorn;at, &thorn;<SUP>s</SUP> f&uuml;r &thorn;is, stets &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> und meist &yogh;<SUP>u</SUP> f&uuml;r &thorn;ou, &yogh;ou (&yogh;ou 41), q&thorn; f&uuml;r qwa&thorn;, qn f&uuml;r qwan, Jh&umacr; f&uuml;r Jhesu (vgl. die Reime Jh&umacr; vertu 563, Jh&umacr; blu 595, Jh&umacr; prow 663, doch scheint es V. 25 in Jhesum aufzul&ouml;sen); &ouml;fter sind Vocale obengeschrieben, ohne Abk&uuml;rzung zu bezeichnen, so bei &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>, &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP>, &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP>, ebenso zuweilen s, wie in wa<SUP>s</SUP>, a<SUP>s</SUP>, hy<SUP>s</SUP>. &mdash; V. 1-192 s. ebenso (aber mit vielfach verderbtem Texte) die 2. Version V. 1-210.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="a" TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Harl. 3954, fol. 70 (14. Jhdt.).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Hic incipit infancia saluatoris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrd god in trinite,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou boutyst man on rode dere:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou send hem grace, wel to the,</L>
<L>&thorn;at lystyn me w<SUP>t</SUP> mylde chere,</L>
<L N="5">For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> loue of Mary fre</L>
<L>&thorn;at helpyth vs w<SUP>t</SUP> here pre&yogh;ere!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prae&yogh;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at &yogh;e wyllyn herkyn to me,</L>
<L>A gret solace &yogh;e may here:</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at is most of vertu</L>
<L N="10">A fayir tale I wyl &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>Ryth of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chyldhod of Jhesu,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;at &yogh;e wyllyn a stounde duelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Qwan Jhesu wa<SUP>s</SUP> of Mary born &mdash;</L>
<L>Blyssyd mote &thorn;at tyme be! &mdash;</L>
<L N="15">Thre kynges komyn hym beforn</L>
<L>And dedyn hym homage &amp; feute.</L>
<L>Heroudes w<SUP>t</SUP> enuye had suorn</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu ded xuld be.</L>
<L>Mary wold not here chyld were lorn:</L>
<L N="20">Out of &thorn;at lond she gan fle,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at lond w<SUP>t</SUP> myth &amp; mayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. out of &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> w<SUP>t</SUP> myth lond; lond ist nach &thorn;at umzustellen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro kyth &thorn;er men here ne knewe;</L>
<L>She bad a man &thorn;at he xuld sayn</L>
<L>&thorn;at she kom &thorn;er qwan &thorn;at he sewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Forth went Mary w<SUP>t</SUP> Jhesu,</L>
<L>And Jochep folwyd on a rowe;</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> iewys folwyd after anone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. anon, so &ouml;fter; der Strich &uuml;ber n kann hier nur e bezeichnen sollen, wie in don, gon 520 u. &ouml;., fon 258, hom 380 (home 435), mon 506, non 584, son 621, euerychon 260; wol auch in pleyn 359 und dronkyn 100, takyn 545; in ano&umacr; 101. 254. 378 u. &ouml;. ist u st. n verschrieben, wie &ouml;fter; in an&omacr; bezeichnet der Strich <I>n</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an &thorn;at corn men shar &amp; mowe.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an for&thorn;er our lady gan gon</L>
<L N="30">Be vnkout weyis &thorn;at she ne knewe:</L>
<L>She sey lyonys, lebbardes, many on,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an began here sorwyn newe.</L>
<L>Mary seyd: "&thorn;is bestes xullyn vs slon.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> day waxit so dym!"</L>
<L N="35">Jhesu blyssyd &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> bestes Ichon:</L>
<L>More &amp; lesse he loutyd to hym.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he plur., wie 86. 87 u &ouml;.; he (hee) ist neben &thorn;ei (they) gleich h&auml;ufig gebraucht.</NOTE></L>
<L>For merthe of lebbardes &thorn;at she sey</L>
<L>Mary blyssyd here sone anone,</L>
<L>She dred no best in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wey,</L>
<L N="40">She seyde: here kar was al gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For&thorn;ermore, I &yogh;ou say,</L>
<L>Our lady went be cuntres wylde.</L>
<L>Barabas wonyd in &thorn;at way,
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>He was a thef in wode &amp; felde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. athef, a ist meist mit d. Sbst. verschmolzen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">He askyd our lady be here lay:</L>
<L>"Qwat beryst &thorn;ou?" she seyd: "a chylde".</L>
<L>Jhesu preyd, &thorn;er he lay.</L>
<L>Dysmas preyd hys fader to ben mylde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. h&es; = hys, wie 60. 124. 355. 568; 9 ist sonst Abbrev. f&uuml;r <I>us</I>, doch kommt ausgeschrieben nur hys vor wie 121. 128. 152. 163. 314. 358.</NOTE></L>
<L>Barabas seyd: "&thorn;at may not be.</L>
<L N="50">Sekerly, w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn nay,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e xul be robbyd alle III,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &yogh;e pace &thorn;is Iche way".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He tok Mary al in hey,</L>
<L>He held here stylle be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lappe.</L>
<L N="55">&THORN;an gan Dysmas for to cry:</L>
<L>"My leue fader, let hem schappe!</L>
<L>Me were leuer for to dey</L>
<L>&THORN;an here mystyd euyl happe".</L>
<L>Hys fader let hem gon sekerly,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> sone hys handes gyn to clappe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd suete Mary:</L>
<L>"My leue sone, qwyt hym &thorn;is!"</L>
<L>"Moder, w<SUP>t</SUP> me he xal dey</L>
<L>And kome w<SUP>t</SUP> me in to my blys".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">For&thorn;ermore our lady went,</L>
<L>Toward Egypt she tok &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> gate.</L>
<L>Here for to restyn she had talent:</L>
<L>Hete of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sunne mad here to suate.</L>
<L>Joshep in armys he her hent,</L>
<L N="70">For wel he vnderstod here state,</L>
<L>He tok here doun w<SUP>t</SUP> good entent</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> asse &thorn;at she on sate,</L>
<L>Vnder a tre, &thorn;at was ful hey,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> fayre flourys he made here sete.</L>
<L N="75">Mary seyde: he were ful sly</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;is freyt now myth gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Qwan Mary had mad here mone,</L>
<L>Hyre sone wyst al here wyl,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> froyt wol good wone</L>
<L N="80">He here &yogh;af, &amp; &thorn;at was scylle:</L>
<L>Jhesu spak to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre &thorn;anne:</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou loute adoun my moder tyl,</L>
<L>Tyl she &amp; Josep bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> han tanne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tane = tane, taken.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> frut ryth al here wyl".</L>
<L N="85">Onto here fot &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre gan folde,</L>
<L>Tyl he hadde takyn &thorn;at hem tyth.</L>
<L>Qwan he takyn hadde &thorn;at he wolde,</L>
<L>As it was it stod vp ryth.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;an seyd our suete lady:</L>
<L N="90">"Certes, me thrystyt wonder sore".</L>
<L>"Certes", seyt Josep, "so do I,</L>
<L>And our asse &yogh;et mekyl more.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is lond it is so dry,</L>
<L>For lak of water is al my kare".</L>
<L N="95">Jhesu spak to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre on hey</L>
<L>And bad it wyssyn water &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre &thorn;er gan spryng</L>
<L>Wellys fele &amp; water at wyl,</L>
<L>Wyn &amp; water it gan fort bryng.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;erof he dronkyne al here fyl.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mary blyssyd here sone anone</L>
<L>&amp; thankyd hym &thorn;at was so fre.</L>
<L>Jhesu seyd to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre son:</L>
<L>"In paradys &thorn;ou xalt be".</L>
<L N="105">In to paradys it was browt</L>
<L>To Ely&yogh;e &amp; Ennok hys fere.</L>
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;at al &thorn;i<SUP>s</SUP> werd hat wrout,<NOTE PLACE="foot">werd = world.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme was old but o &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> an old man &thorn;ei gun mete,</L>
<L N="110">And of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wey&yogh;e askyd resoun.</L>
<L>He seyd: "to Egypt &yogh;e ha &yogh;ete</L>
<L>XXX dayis jurne to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> toun".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Jurue.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an gan Mary to wepe,</L>
<L>For werynesse she sat doun.</L>
<L N="115">"Moder", qwa&thorn; Jhesu, "wylt &thorn;ou lete?</L>
<L>Lo here &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wallys of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> toun!"</L>
<L>It is so fayir a rych cete.</L>
<L>Lo how short he made here way.</L>
<L>"Sone", she seyd, "blyssyd &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="120">As lord &thorn;at al mythtes may!"
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>Qwan Jhesu &amp; hy<SUP>s</SUP> moder fre</L>
<L>In to Egypt weryn browt,</L>
<L>Freudes was lord of &thorn;at cete.</L>
<L>Alle hys goddes of gold were wrout;</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> puple fro fer &thorn;eder gun te,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>o</SUP> maumentes for goddes &thorn;ei sout.</L>
<L>Qwyl Jhesu duellyd in &thorn;at kuntre,</L>
<L>Alle hys goddes felle to nowt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SO it befel vpon a day<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vgl. Version b, 149 ff.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">A lytyl beforn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> none:</L>
<L>Chyldryn of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cete madyn a play,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Text ist fehlerhaft, der Tod des Judas ist nicht motivirt; die Worte 139-140 waren im Orig. wohl die Worte Jesu.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he were wone to done.</L>
<L>Jhesu here play gan to say,</L>
<L>And here play was endyd sone:</L>
<L N="135">Judas seyd wellaway,</L>
<L>He made a karful mone.</L>
<L>Anone Judas gan to dey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>A lytyl fote myth he not go.</L>
<L>Judas seyd: "&thorn;ou xalt aby&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="140">Jhesu, for &thorn;ou dedyst soo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Chyldre in to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> toun ranne</L>
<L>For dred of Judas sake,</L>
<L>Onto sere Lyne, here aldermanne,</L>
<L>Pleynt on Jhesu for to make,</L>
<L N="145">He seyd: Judas ded was &thorn;an</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ple&yogh;yng be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lake.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Juwys Jhesu gun ban,</L>
<L>On hym &thorn;ei thout to take warke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. warke = wrake, vgl. sporng 620 st. sprong.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Juwys tokyn hem to rede</L>
<L N="150">Qwat det Jhesu xuld endure;</L>
<L>Summe seyde he xuld be stonyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort fehlt, der Schreiber hat das n&ouml;rdl. dede st. dethe eliminirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hys fals lythyr kure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mary &amp; Josep were ful woo</L>
<L>For Jhesu &thorn;at was hem dere;</L>
<L N="155">Qwan &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Juwys thoutyn hym to slo,</L>
<L>&THORN;an chaungyd al here chere.</L>
<L>To &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> water Mary gan go:</L>
<L>"Leue sone, qwat dost &thorn;ou here?"</L>
<L>"Moder, I make dammys II,</L>
<L N="160">To stoppyn water here, myth &thorn;ou lere".</L>
<L>She seyde: "sone, me lyst not play,</L>
<L>In toune I herde sueche a kry:</L>
<L>But Judas ryse &amp; go hys way,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou xald dey&yogh;e w<SUP>t</SUP> gret enuy".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="165">"Moder", he seyde, "I do &thorn;i wylle,</L>
<L>Judas xal I makyn hol here.</L>
<L>And &yogh;et hym xal lykynt ful ylle<NOTE PLACE="foot">lykynt = lykyn it, wie tellyt 169. 169-172 ge|h&ouml;ren, wie die Reime zeigen, ans Ende der Strophe, sie sind vom Schreiber versetzt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">hym st. &yogh;ou? s. Vers. b, 187.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he of lyue now ne were:</L>
<L>Moder, for so&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> I tellyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;is tretour is ful of fellony&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Onto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Juwys he xal selle me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. stets on to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Among my fomen for to dey&yogh;e".</L>
<L>Jhesu &yogh;ede &thorn;at body tylle</L>
<L>And tok hym vp be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ere:</L>
<L N="175">"Judas, qwy lyst &thorn;ou so stylle?</L>
<L>My moder wold &thorn;at &thorn;ou rese were".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sere Lyne &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> maystrys alle</L>
<L>And sere Kayfas, &thorn;at was here fere,</L>
<L>On Mary &amp; Josep gun to kalle</L>
<L N="180">And seydyn to hem on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"We han thout &thorn;at &yogh;e xal alle</L>
<L>For &yogh;oure sone &thorn;at wyl not lere</L>
<L>Euer in kare &amp; wo to walle&mdash;</L>
<L>Betre &yogh;ou were to lyn on bere.</L>
<L N="185">&YOGH;yf he wold lere, &yogh;et myth he the,</L>
<L>And wysely to wysdam drawe,</L>
<L>On lytyl tyme he myth be</L>
<L>Prince &amp; kepere of our lawe".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> scole &thorn;ei hym ledde.</L>
<L N="190">Cayfas kam hym a&yogh;en,</L>
<L>A bok beforn hym he spredde</L>
<L>&amp; bad he xuld leryn w<SUP>t</SUP> wen,</L>
<L>He bad hym seyn A. b. c.,</L>
<L>For be mowt he wold hym teche.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="104"></L>
<L N="195">"Now", qwa&thorn; Jhesu, "I may wel se</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou art wrot &amp; egre of speche.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrot st. wroth.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now qwy is a beforn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> .b?</L>
<L>Tel me now, I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> beseche!</L>
<L>And ellys I xal telle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>,</L>
<L N="200">Wreth &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> not to werke wretche!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cayfas &thorn;an w<SUP>t</SUP> wordes Ille</L>
<L>Seyd to Jhesu anone ryth:</L>
<L>"Jhesu, &thorn;ou hast a wonder welle,</L>
<L>I rede &thorn;ou lere w<SUP>t</SUP> al &thorn;in myth;</L>
<L N="205">And but &thorn;ou wylt holde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> stylle,</L>
<L>To hard betyng &thorn;ou xalt be dyth".</L>
<L>Jhesu seyde: "it were no scylle,</L>
<L>I kam not hyder for to fyth".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;et", qwa&thorn; Jhesu," of myn askynge</L>
<L N="210">&thorn;ou me &yogh;euyst non answere.</L>
<L>I am ful eld, &thorn;ow I be &yogh;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I kan &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ryth wel lere.</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> I sey w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn lecyng:<NOTE PLACE="foot">lecyng st. lesyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>A is letter w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn pere,</L>
<L N="215">A is III &amp; but o thyng,</L>
<L>III partys he hat knyth in fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">knyth st. knit, wie wyth st. wit 252.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But a begynnyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> letterrure,</L>
<L>For a is lyk to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinite:</L>
<L>III partys he hat of o mesure,</L>
<L N="220">And alle III a may wel be.</L>
<L>I wyl &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lere, &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wylt dure:</L>
<L>A is lyk to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> deyte:</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> deyte is, &thorn;ou myth be sure,</L>
<L>III personys &amp; on in mageste,</L>
<L N="225">Euermore hereafter he xullyn endure</L>
<L>Indepartable alle III.</L>
<L>Now myth &thorn;ou lere, tak god kure,</L>
<L>A is most of dygnyte".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cayfas seyd in &thorn;at stonde:</L>
<L N="230">"Qwat art &thorn;ou, letterure for to lere?</L>
<L>Be Moyses lawe we han fou(n)de<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vern.: nis not st. we han</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is clergye &thorn;at &thorn;ou seyst here.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou seyst in Ilke a grounde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou art eld &amp; &yogh;yng in fere;</L>
<L N="235">&thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> sawys sotly be not sounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou art to me not dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Spek no more, I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> say,</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> holy to &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> lore:<NOTE PLACE="foot">statt &thorn;i hat Vern. my.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou myth ben al wey</L>
<L N="240">Ryth fully wys for euermore.</L>
<L>And wol &yogh;ong &thorn;at wyt is kore,</L>
<L>It is medlyd w<SUP>t</SUP> folye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at me greuyt suythe sore,</L>
<L>It katchys me to felonye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="245">Of Moyses our lawys we hadde,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lawys &thorn;ou wylt vs teche?</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> sawe, sone, I am sadde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinite to make &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> speche;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou greuyst me, I am not glad,</L>
<L N="250">To me &thorn;ou art a le&thorn;er leche:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou spekyst of god a<SUP>s</SUP> a chyld mad</L>
<L>Wel fer&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wyth wyl retche".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu a&yogh;en to hym gan spelle</L>
<L>And wold wetyn of hym anone</L>
<L N="255">&YOGH;yf he koude ony thyng telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prophetes &thorn;at weryn gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seydyn Cryst xuld dey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Here in erthe among his fone</L>
<L>And &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lawe he xuld felle:&mdash;</L>
<L N="260">"&thorn;is aute &yogh;e knowyn euerry-chone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cryst is lyth of god almyth,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lyth he is kore.</L>
<L>Isay spak aryth:</L>
<L>&thorn;at of a mayde he xuld be bore&mdash;</L>
<L N="265">&thorn;ou myth wel wetyn &thorn;at it is ryth,</L>
<L>For to by &thorn;at is forlore.
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>God is fader, &amp; Cryst is lyth,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> sone is gotyn wythoutyn ore:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For as &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sunne &yogh;euyt hys lem,</L>
<L N="270">&YOGH;yf he w<SUP>t</SUP> cloudes be not let,</L>
<L>So komyt Crist of a sunne-bem</L>
<L>In to erthe, balis to bet;</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou take wel good &yogh;em</L>
<L>How &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sunne-bem is set:</L>
<L N="275">Vndepartyd is &thorn;e strem</L>
<L>Of Crist &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sonne w<SUP>t</SUP>owtyn let.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now tak here-to good entent:</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> fader lyth in &thorn;e sonne xal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> faderes lyth may not be blent,</L>
<L N="280">Al is o lyth in deyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;an ben hee prouyd be argument</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> fader &amp; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sone o lyth ben hee,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> holygost w<SUP>t</SUP> hem present,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at fulfillyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="285">For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinite, I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>A is letter of alle chyf,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore a is al wey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Iput beforn. &thorn;at is god pref.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. god is st. is god.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> trinyte xullyn he seyn w<SUP>t</SUP> eye</L>
<L N="290">Alle &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> men &thorn;at ben hym lef;</L>
<L>&THORN;an is man a blysful pere<NOTE PLACE="foot">pere ist falsches Reimwort, Vern. liest prei&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinyte is lef.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> trinyte I haue told in heye".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers ist unn&uuml;tzer Zusatz.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an seyde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> maystrys of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lawe:</L>
<L N="295">Of deuelles &thorn;at he had clergy&yogh;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. deuell<GAP> mit dem Zeichen der Abbrev. f&uuml;r <I>er</I> st. <I>es, ys</I>, wie 384 bei hylles (Ms. hyller).</NOTE></L>
<L>"A maydyn w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn ony awe</L>
<L>Shuld beryn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> kyng of glorie.</L>
<L>Wel we wetyn &thorn;at it is knawe:</L>
<L>Old Josep weddyd Marye&mdash;</L>
<L N="300">O&thorn;er record kun we non drawe;</L>
<L>He is not Crist be prophessye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu spak w<SUP>t</SUP> mylde chere</L>
<L>Onto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Jewys &thorn;at gun cry:</L>
<L>"Faryt fayre, frendes dere!</L>
<L N="305">&YOGH;e fare foule thoru folye.</L>
<L>But o thyng xul &yogh;et &yogh;e here,</L>
<L>As seyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prophete Isaye:</L>
<L>She xal be weddyd, &thorn;at hat no pere,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> myld moder of messy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="310">Isay seyd a no&thorn;er thyng:</L>
<L>Cryst in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lawe xuld be bore&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at xuld ben in weddyng,</L>
<L>And ellys Cristes lawe is lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> prophetes spekyn of hys komyng</L>
<L N="315">At Jesse began &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> more,</L>
<L>For Crist hath no begynnyng,</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ow he be man kore,</L>
<L>Thoru myth of heuene kyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers ist unn&uuml;tzer Zu|satz, wie 293.</NOTE></L>
<L>Josep virga floruit fatu Isaye,</L>
<L N="320">Coniux, lex v<SUP>t</SUP> monuit, mater fit messye".<NOTE PLACE="foot">319-20) im Ms. in rother Schrift.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cayfas &amp; o&thorn;er Jewys mo</L>
<L>Of &yogh;yng Jhesu he haddyn maruayl</L>
<L>How &thorn;at he was kome to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor to fehlt hem?</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> clergye hym for to asayl;</L>
<L N="325">Of hem had Jhesu many foo,</L>
<L>For here wyt wol sone gan fayl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wol = wel, wie 241. 470.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many of hem awey gan go,</L>
<L>Qwan here clergye wold not avayl.<NOTE PLACE="foot">193-328) hier gehen die 2 Versionen ganz auseinander, vgl. b, 211-265. Der ganze Abschnitt 193-328 findet sich als eigenes selbst&auml;ndiges Gedicht in Ms. Vernon fol. 300 wieder (gedruckt in d. "Altengl. Legenden", Paderborn 1875, p. 212ff.), wo der zw&ouml;lfj&auml;hrige Jesus diese Disputation im Tempel zu Jerusalem mit den "maystres of the lawe" h&auml;lt, nicht mit Cayphas. Der Dichter der Kindh. Jesu scheint diesen ganzen Theil entlehnt und in sein Gedicht eingef&uuml;gt zu haben, wie er auch die Strophenform beibehalten hat. Ms. Vernon bietet den besseren Text.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>XII sparwys Jhesu mad &thorn;anne</L>
<L N="330">&amp; bad hem fly&yogh;in qwere hem thout.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Juwys gun hym banne,</L>
<L>For her halyday he halwyd nowt;</L>
<L>Hee banned hym alle &thorn;anne,</L>
<L>Beforn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> maystrys wa<SUP>s</SUP> he brout.</L>
<L N="335">Alle &thorn;ei gun Jhesu to banne,</L>
<L>He seydyn: of hem he rout nowt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hee kallyn hym &thorn;an a qwent syre,</L>
<L>Hee seydyn: he wold dystriyn here lay.</L>
<L>Jhesu seyd: "I tok non heyre,</L>
<L N="340">I made hem not but on my play.</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ow I do an o&thorn;er kure,</L>
<L>It helpyt &yogh;ou not to seyn nay.</L>
<L>I wel not duellyn, be &yogh;e sure,</L>
<L>I wel wend &amp; go my way!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">329-344) vgl. wieder b, 265-276. Der Text ist verdorben, wie die Wiederholung 331. 333. 335 zeigt.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000112.tif" N="106">
<HEAD>Hic ient ad aquam pueri cum ollis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">AFterward on an o&thorn;er day</L>
<L>Euery chyld to o&thorn;er gan telle:</L>
<L>"Wend we fort w<SUP>t</SUP> good aray</L>
<L>Onto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> water, our pottys to fylle!"</L>
<L>Alle hee lokyddyn, I &yogh;ou say,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lok&ymacr;ddyn. &mdash;</NOTE></L>
<L N="350">Qwych of hem was most snelle;</L>
<L>Hee &yogh;edyn fort in here way,</L>
<L>Ful lytyl qwyle gun &thorn;ei duelle.</L>
<L>Jhesu fyrst &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> water hent.</L>
<L>Arka dede Jhesu wrong:</L>
<L N="355">Hys pot to-brak, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> water out went.</L>
<L>Jhesu seyde: "suych xalt &thorn;ou fong".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;an Jhesu hol hys pot gan make,</L>
<L>Ant to hys frend he seyd anon:</L>
<L>"Wyl we pleyne be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lake?</L>
<L N="360">On &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sunne-bem xul our pottes gon".</L>
<L>On &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sune-bem &thorn;ei hem honge:</L>
<L>Crystes heng stylle, here gan don falle,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei brokyn, he were not stronge.</L>
<L>And Archa weppe sore w<SUP>t</SUP> alle.</L>
<L N="365">"Archa", qwa&thorn; Jhesu, &thorn;ou were to blame.</L>
<L>Qwy madyst &thorn;ou my water to shede?</L>
<L>Now hast &thorn;ou an o&thorn;er shame</L>
<L>And after &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> gylt &thorn;ou hast &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> mede".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Josep seyde al in &thorn;at throwe:</L>
<L N="370">"Jhesu is lord of gret poste,</L>
<L>Wel aut we hys myth to knowe</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> meraclys &thorn;at we se</L>
<L>Fro day to day for vs to shewe.</L>
<L>"My pot &thorn;at was brokyn on III,</L>
<L N="375">It wold ben hol, &amp; &thorn;ou wold leue:</L>
<L>Now help, Jhesu, &thorn;at art so fre!"</L>
<L>"Josep", qwa&thorn; Jhesu, "for &thorn;i sake</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> pottes xullyn ben hole anone".</L>
<L>Gret Joye &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chyldryn gun to make,</L>
<L N="380">Synggande to toune he wentyn home.<NOTE PLACE="foot">345-380) vgl. b, 325-360; beide Texte weichen von hier ab bedeutend und zuletzt ganz ab.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sythen vpon an o&thorn;er day</L>
<L>Jhesu w<SUP>t</SUP> chyldere gan to mete.</L>
<L>He seyde: "wyl we go play</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> hylles for to lepe?"</L>
<L N="385">Hee wentyn fort al in hey,</L>
<L>Jhesu &amp; hys felas alle.</L>
<L>Summe thoutyn hym to enuy</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> herte bytter as ony galle.</L>
<L>Jhesu lep for &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> maystry,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Jhesu for &thorn;e maystry lep; lep ist hinter Jhesu umzustellen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">And o&thorn;er lepyn &amp; hard gun falle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at legges &amp; armys sekyrly</L>
<L>And neckes brokyn, &thorn;ei myth not kalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But Josep &amp; an o&thorn;er, hys fere,</L>
<L>Sowyn of Jhesu gret meruayl</L>
<L N="395">And seydyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei myth lere:</L>
<L>Jhesu to vyon wold not avayl:</L>
<L>"Jhesu is lord w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn pere,</L>
<L>Noman it geynyt hym to sayl,</L>
<L>He dot hys wyl bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fer &amp; nere</L>
<L N="400">At hys lykyng w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn fayl".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu seyde: "hens wel I wende</L>
<L>And to my moder wyl I gon</L>
<L>And letyn hem lygyn in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ende,</L>
<L>For now &thorn;ei arn dede Ichon:</L>
<L N="405">To lytyl wyt he haddyn in mende,</L>
<L>For avy&yogh;en me &thorn;ei done(?).</L>
<L>Go hom, Josep, my moder frende!</L>
<L>Her owyn dedys ha hem slon".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu went aforn alone,</L>
<L N="410">Josep kom after w<SUP>t</SUP> hys fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> Jewys komyn after sone anon,</L>
<L>For to sekyn here chyldryn &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Hee askyd Josep euerry-chon</L>
<L>Of here chyldryn, qwere &thorn;ei were.</L>
<L N="415">And Josep seyde: "dede as a ston</L>
<L>Hee lyn in feld, &amp; I am here".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> Jewys madyn a foul cry,</L>
<L>Hee seydyn: "alas, how may &thorn;at be?"</L>
<L>Josep seyde: "sykerly,</L>
<L N="420">Hee deyid throu here nyste:</L>
<L>They wold lepyn &amp; enuy</L>
<L>Suete Jhesu &thorn;at is so fre,
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore dede ben they,</L>
<L>Gamyt hem non o&thorn;er gle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">Jewys seydyn on &thorn;is manere &mdash;</L>
<L>And euer &thorn;ei seydyn alas &mdash;:</L>
<L>"How scapydyst &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> fere?"</L>
<L>Josep seyde: "our wyl it nas</L>
<L>For to make Jhesu our pere:</L>
<L N="430">We wyst wel, our mayster he wa<SUP>s</SUP>;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore we ben here,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> to&thorn;ere ly dede vp &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> gras".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lydede st. ly(n) dede.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Alas", seyde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Jewys Ichone,</L>
<L>"An hard hap here is befalle!</L>
<L N="435">We wylyn alle wendyn home</L>
<L>And for our chylder hys moder kalle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hee &yogh;edyn to here ryth anone</L>
<L>And on here madyn a lody cry,</L>
<L>Hee seydyn: here chylder euerry-chon</L>
<L N="440">Jhesu had slawyn throu felony;</L>
<L>"&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou xalt, or it be nyth,</L>
<L>And old Josep, &thorn;at syttyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> by,</L>
<L>Ben to-brent in fyr bryth,</L>
<L>And Jhesu in &yogh;our kompany!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="445">Mary seyde: "w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn duellyng</L>
<L>I xal wend, my sone to seche.</L>
<L>For hem ne make &yogh;e no wepyng,</L>
<L>For, &yogh;yf he wyl, he may hem leche &mdash;</L>
<L>He kan do more wonder thyng</L>
<L N="450">&THORN;an to helyn hem w<SUP>t</SUP> hys speche:</L>
<L>So is hys myth, &thorn;ou he be &yogh;yng.</L>
<L>It fallyt not &yogh;ou to take wreche".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mary fort &thorn;an gan she go,</L>
<L>She sey qwere here sone gan pley,</L>
<L N="455">And &thorn;er kom ryth anone</L>
<L>Josep to hym in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wey.</L>
<L>Mary seyde: "sone, be our fon</L>
<L>We be dempt for to dey.</L>
<L>My leue sone, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chyldryn Ichon</L>
<L N="460">&thorn;ou &yogh;yf hem lyf, I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> prey&yogh;e!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu seyde anon ryth:</L>
<L>"Moder, &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wyl xal be do".</L>
<L>He bad Josep anon aplyth</L>
<L>Onto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tounys ende go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. toun&es;.</NOTE></L>
<L N="465">"Byd hem komyn hom be my myth,</L>
<L>Reny(n)g as faste as ony roo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. renyg &mdash; 487 &mdash; 530 vgl. b, 361&mdash;396 (ganz abweichend).</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at my moder may sen aplyth</L>
<L>&thorn;at I am frend a&yogh;en my foo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Josep &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chylder gan to kalle:</L>
<L N="470">Wol suethe hee komyn rennyng.</L>
<L>Here frendes bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> in boure &amp; halle</L>
<L>For hem here handes gun wryng:&mdash;</L>
<L>A gret joy &thorn;er was befalle</L>
<L>Qwan hee sowyn hem leuyng.</L>
<L N="475">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> chylder kome w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at in hast</L>
<L>Beforn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> grete of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cete;</L>
<L>Of hem hee gun to queryn fast:</L>
<L>"How were dede &amp; leuyn &yogh;e?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hee toldyn anon of &thorn;at meruayl,</L>
<L N="480">How Jhesu myth done al hy<SUP>s</SUP> wyl:</L>
<L>"We greuyd hym &mdash; it wold not vayl,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore we fellyn dede ston-styl;</L>
<L>And now we ben w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn fayl</L>
<L>Kome to lyue w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn Il.</L>
<L N="485">Gaynyt not hym to asayle,</L>
<L>For, &yogh;yf &yogh;e done, he wyl &yogh;ou spyl".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of here chylder hee weryn in drede:<NOTE PLACE="foot">381&mdash;487) vgl. b, 277&mdash;324 (bis auf die ersten Verse ganz abweichend).</NOTE></L>
<L>In an ouene hee letyn hem do</L>
<L>And madyn a man hem to fede,</L>
<L N="490">&thorn;at noman xuld komy(n) hem to,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. komy st. komyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;ouyn hym ful gret mede</L>
<L>&thorn;at hee xuld not komyn hem fro.</L>
<L>And &thorn;an kam Jhesu as . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach as sind etwa 5&mdash;6 Buchstaben zerst&ouml;rt, vielleicht I rede.</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hym &thorn;er kam no moo,</L>
<L N="495">Jhesu seyde: "felawe myn,</L>
<L>Qwat is &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepyst &thorn;are?"</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> man seyde: it were swyn.</L>
<L>"Swyn" qwa&thorn; Jhesu, "motyn hee ben&yogh;are"!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; as swyn he grontyn &amp; grone</L>
<L N="500">And alle hee weryn swyn in fere.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> man made &thorn;an wepyng mone</L>
<L>And went to here frendes dere,</L>
<L>He seyde how Jhesu kom alone</L>
<L>&amp; mad hem swyn thour hys powere.</L>
<L N="505">"Alas", he seydyn, "qwat xul we don?</L>
<L>Oure chylder mone ben no-qwere".
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>Hee wentyn to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ouene anon:</L>
<L>Swyn &thorn;erin gun gruntyn grylle.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> Jewys gun to seyn anone:</L>
<L N="510">"&THORN;is meruayl vs lykyt Ille.</L>
<L>Prey we help of Marye,</L>
<L>&thorn;at our chylder nowt spylle:</L>
<L>Jhesu grantyt sekyrly<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. grantyd st. grantyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys moder preyere at hyr wylle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="515">Hee told Mary an hap wa<SUP>s</SUP> falle,</L>
<L>And preydyn here of help Ichon,</L>
<L>"And namely for our chyldryn alle,</L>
<L>For wel we wetyn: Jhesu wyl done</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>i</SUP> wyl bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> in boure &amp; halle".</L>
<L N="520">Sone she grantyd w<SUP>t</SUP> hem to gone,</L>
<L>Onto here sone for hem to kalle.</L>
<L>For hem she preyid sone anone</L>
<L>Onto here sone a myld bone.</L>
<L>He grantyd here wyl ful sone:</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> chylder of wo weryn vnbounde.</L>
<L>He thankyd Mary &thorn;at had it done</L>
<L>For help &thorn;at hee in here founde;</L>
<L>Hee preyidyn here w<SUP>t</SUP> carful mone</L>
<L>&thorn;at here chylder myth go sounde.</L>
<L N="530">Jhesu grantyd hem anone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hem.&mdash;531&mdash;575 vgl. b, 397&mdash;408.&mdash;575&mdash;630 vgl. b, 545&mdash;628.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Rych man was in &thorn;at cete</L>
<L>&thorn;at to Jhesu had envye,</L>
<L>Josep fader, Braudyn hyth he.</L>
<L>Ouer hys sone he made maystrye,</L>
<L N="535">He seyd: "my sone, &thorn;ou were me dere,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ou dost a&yogh;en my wylle</L>
<L>To ben w<SUP>t</SUP> Jhesu, of hym to lere &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou were wel betre to ben stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hys loue &thorn;ou xalt be kept</L>
<L N="540">In a tour of lym &amp; ston,</L>
<L>Hys loue &thorn;ou xalt abyin, Josep,</L>
<L>Ne geynyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> no betre won.</L>
<L>To &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> xal noman komyn ne lep,</L>
<L>&thorn;er myth &thorn;ou cry &amp; kalle alon,</L>
<L N="545">&thorn;at noman of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> xal takyne kep</L>
<L>Ne for onys for to heryn &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> bon.</L>
<L>I suere be god Adonay:</L>
<L>Lyth &thorn;er &thorn;ou xalt non haue;</L>
<L>Lud &thorn;ou &thorn;ou cry wellaway,</L>
<L N="550">Non helpe geynyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;at hath &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &thorn;us shent,</L>
<L>Out of presoun xal &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> not bryng</L>
<L>Be no maner of sharment</L>
<L>&thorn;at he kan of rede &amp; syng".</L>
<L N="555">Josep seyde anon ryth:</L>
<L>"Fader, &thorn;ou myth done &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> wyl.</L>
<L>Jhesu is ful of mekyl myth,</L>
<L>He wyl not suffre me to spyl".</L>
<L>Josep left in &thorn;at prisoun,</L>
<L N="560">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> dorys weryn lokyn faste.</L>
<L>&thorn;er lay Josep al alon,</L>
<L>To hym kam Jhesu ryth in haste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Josep, felaw", qwa&thorn; Jhesu,</L>
<L>"For my loue &thorn;ou lyst here,</L>
<L N="565">&thorn;ou xalt se more of my vertu,</L>
<L>For so I wyl, my leue fere".</L>
<L>Jhesu fond a lytyl bore</L>
<L>And bad Josep hys fynger take:</L>
<L>Heyl &amp; sond as he was core</L>
<L N="570">He kam out w<SUP>t</SUP>outyn wrake.</L>
<L>Euer w<SUP>t</SUP> Jhesu he wold be,</L>
<L>Nothyng myth hym lette;</L>
<L>Euer was Jhesu hym so fre,</L>
<L>For hys felaw he hym fette.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Ad artem tingtoris Ibat.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="575">&THORN;an seyd Jhesu to Marye:</L>
<L>"Off diuers craftes I wyl say,</L>
<L>Of craft &thorn;at is of gret maystrye,</L>
<L>I xal done alle men to pay".</L>
<L>Onto a lyster hee komyn sone,</L>
<L N="580">W<SUP>t</SUP> hym komenant for to make:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. komenaut.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hee weryn acordyd ryth anone,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> dyere was glad for Jhesu sake.</L>
<L>Jhesu dede hys maystrys wylle,</L>
<L>A better seruant he had neuer none,</L>
<L N="585">For neuer he let thyng spylle,</L>
<L>Al was wel &thorn;at he gan don.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So it befel, as I &yogh;ow say:</L>
<L>Hys mayster had preyere</L>
<L>For to dynyn on a day,</L>
<L N="590">He and hys wyf in fere.</L>
<L>Clothys hadde &thorn;ei, for so&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to say,</L>
<L>To dy&yogh;yn bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fayre &amp; clere &mdash;</L>
<L>Fyner cloth to mannys pay</L>
<L>Was non in &thorn;at mestere.</L>
<L N="595">And qwan he went, he bad Jhesu</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> clothys fynly dye,</L>
<L>Scharlet, morre, grene &amp; blu,</L>
<L>"Iche cloth after &thorn;at I seye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu anone a fyr gan make,</L>
<L N="600">And went hym fort for to plye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. plye st. pleye.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys mayster saw hym be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lake,</L>
<L>Jhesu &amp; o&thorn;er chyldryn tweye.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> wyf seyd: "&yogh;onder hys our wrake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys=is mit unorgan. h.</NOTE></L>
<L>I se hem w<SUP>t</SUP> myn eye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem st. hym.</NOTE></L>
<L N="605">He hat not done &thorn;at &thorn;ou bode hym make.</L>
<L>Ryth it is &thorn;at he abye".</L>
<L>Jhesu hem se&thorn; &amp; hom hym dyth:</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> clothys were qwyte,</L>
<L>And &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fyr brynnyng bryth.</L>
<L N="610">&thorn;at mayster began to flyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu toke &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> clothys Ichon</L>
<L>And in to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> led he hem kast.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mayster seyd: "I am vndone!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou xalt abyin in hast".</L>
<L N="615">A brond he tok vp w<SUP>t</SUP> hys hond,</L>
<L>Jhesu for to smyte,</L>
<L>To throwyn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> brond wold he not wond:</L>
<L>Of Jhesu it faylyd lyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> brond bar lef &amp; blosomyd anon</L>
<L N="620">And sporng, &thorn;er it gan falle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sporng st. sprong.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster it sey &amp; dred hym sone,</L>
<L>Mercy to hym gan he kalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And euerry cloth had hys hu,</L>
<L>Ryth as it xuld haue,</L>
<L N="625">Scarlet, morre, grene &amp; bleu,</L>
<L>No betere myth men kraue.</L>
<L>Jhesu for&yogh;af hym, I &yogh;ow say,</L>
<L>And fro hym he gan wende.</L>
<L>Carpenterys craft he wol say,</L>
<L N="630">&THORN;erto he gan lende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Ad artem carpentarij Ibat.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu was bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> strong &amp; durable</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> an ex for to hewe:</L>
<L>At euery werk he was ful stable,</L>
<L>To techyn men to ben trewe.</L>
<L N="635">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster-wryth forso&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &thorn;an</L>
<L>Had a gret werk on honde,</L>
<L>For he was most crafty man</L>
<L>&THORN;at was in al &thorn;at londe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Jhesu he tok a wol fayr tre</L>
<L N="640">And bad hym hewyn faste,</L>
<L>&amp; taute hym qwere it xuld be</L>
<L>Be leyd at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> laste.</L>
<L>Jhesu it hew in gret rapyng</L>
<L>To short be IIII fote.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fote st. fete.</NOTE></L>
<L N="645">&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster made gret sorwyng,</L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre was long &amp; grete,</L>
<L>To Jhesu he seyd ful &yogh;are</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou hast don ful Ille &mdash;</L>
<L>We a(ute) han gret kare &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">das 2. Wort ist zerst&ouml;rt, nur a ist sichtbar, zu lesen scheint alle oder aute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="650">&THORN;is fayr tre to spylle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For it is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fayryst tre</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer kom in myn hond.</L>
<L>Alas, he seyde, gret kare is me,</L>
<L>For sorwe I may not stond".</L>
<L N="655">&THORN;an qwa&thorn; Jhesu: "let me se,</L>
<L>And o thyng wyl I fond:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf it myth lenger be</L>
<L>Throu myth of my hond.</L>
<L>Draw, qwa&thorn; Jhesu, at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to&thorn;er hende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hende mit unorg. h.</NOTE></L>
<L N="660">For at &thorn;is ende I wyl drawe!"</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou scornyst, me thyngkyt, leue frende,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;ou seyst in &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> sawe".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Set on &thorn;in hond", qwa&thorn; Jhesu,</L>
<L>"And drawe on god spede!"
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="110"></L>
<L N="665">"&thorn;at were a werk of lytyl prow"</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> wryth seyde, "at nede".</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou art not wys, qwa&thorn; Jhesu,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou do now my wylle".</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> carpenter seyde: "qwych Idel dede</L>
<L N="670">I wyl letyn be stylle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;an wylt not &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> maystrie wynne"</L>
<L>Qwa&thorn; Cryst, "of carpentrye?"</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster seyde: "&thorn;ou myth begynne,</L>
<L>I wyl &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> not avy&yogh;e".</L>
<L N="675">Jhesu seyde: "I wyl asay,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at I hens wende".</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster seyde: "&thorn;is iche day</L>
<L>It komyt to non ende".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu drow for he was strong,</L>
<L N="680">&THORN;at many men myth se,</L>
<L>He drow it IIII fote long,</L>
<L>Ryth as it xuld be.</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> mayster seyde: "it were wrong,</L>
<L>Maystyr but &thorn;ou be;</L>
<L N="685">Mythty &thorn;ou art, &amp; myld among,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>i</SUP> pere is nowt", qwa&thorn; he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu went &thorn;at same day</L>
<L>Fro hym, as I &yogh;ou telle,</L>
<L>No more craftes wold he asay,</L>
<L N="690">No lenger wold he duelle.</L>
<L>He went fort in hys way,</L>
<L>&THORN;<SUP>e</SUP> lawe to fulfylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">631&mdash;692) vgl. b, 730&mdash;753 (ganz abweichend).</NOTE></L>
<L>Cryst vs chylde, &thorn;at best may,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chylde st. shilde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> peyne of helle!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit infancia saluatoris.</TRAILER>
</LG>


</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="b" TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000117.tif" N="[111]">
<HEAD>b) aus Ms. Harl. 2399, fol. 47 (15. Jhdt.).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Ms. (15. Jhdt.) ist in einer nachl&auml;ssigen und schwer lesbaren Schrift von ver|schiedenen H&auml;nden geschrieben: so wechselt die Hand v. 241-260, ferner 534-545, 545-565, 565 bis zum Schluss; dieser Wechsel verr&auml;th sich auch in graphischen Be|sonderheiten. Von v. 630 an hat eine andere Hand in den Text hinein corrigirt und ihn noch mehr verwirrt. Der Text ist sehr verderbt und fehlerhaft. Der Abdruck schliesst sich eng an die Hdschr. an. Die Abk&uuml;rzungen sind aufgel&ouml;st, die &uuml;ber ll, n, m, hinter d, g stehenden Striche sind mit <I>e</I> bezeichnet.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Pueritia vel Infancia Christi.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle-my&yogh;thty god yn trynyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bowth man on rode dere,</L>
<L>He yefe ows welle to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>A lytyl wyle &thorn;at ye wylle me hyre,</L>
<L N="5">For &thorn;e lofe of Mary fre</L>
<L>&thorn;at helpyth os alle wyth hyre preyere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. help<SUP>t</SUP>, wie stond<SUP>t</SUP> 556, obengeschr. t f&uuml;r yth, wie w<SUP>t</SUP> = wyth.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ye wyll herkene to me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; = and = if, wie &ouml;fter.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gret solase ye mow hyre:</L>
<L>Off hym &thorn;at ys most of vertu</L>
<L N="10">A lytyl tale y wol yow telle,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e chyld &thorn;at hete Jhesu,</L>
<L>&amp; ye wylle a stond dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen Jhesu was of Mary borne &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wen mit w st. wh, wie in were, wy, weder, wat, wych, auch wytte 799.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yblessy(d) mot &thorn;at tyme be! &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. yblessy.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">III kyngys knelyd hym byfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. by fore st. byforne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; dede hym omage alle &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Herod(es) hyely had sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">sore st. sworne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at Jhesu schuld dede be.</L>
<L>M(ary) wol not hyre sone were ylorne:</L>
<L N="20">(Out of) &thorn;e lond sche gan fle;</L>
<L>(For hyre) foys were my&yogh;thy of mayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. foy swere, offenbar st. foys were, foys plur. v. fo, vgl. treys, kneys, feloys, iurnyys.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Sche wen)d yn to Egyp(t), &thorn;er sche was not knowy(n)e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. egyp. knowye.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . . schuld sayn</L>
<L>. . . . . for&thorn;e, wen (&thorn;ay) sewen.</L>
<L N="25">(&THORN;e) yewys softe &thorn;em many on:<NOTE PLACE="foot">softe = sou&yogh;te, vgl. mit ft st. &yogh;t rofte 693, ofte 508, dofter 518. 528; neben ft begegnet auch wt, wth: wrowt 268, wrowth 219, &thorn;owt 266, browt 272, owth 656, bowth 414, selbst sowfte 130, sow&yogh;th 223, daneben &yogh;t, th.</NOTE></L>
<L>(&THORN;en men) hyre corne repyd &amp; mew.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyre poss. plur., so 85. 100. 130. 139 u. &ouml;., neben here 174. 198. 636. 728, selten &thorn;er 84.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Fyrd)ermore sche gan gone</L>
<L>(In) yldernys, &thorn;at was fayr of hew.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor yldernys ist vielleicht w ausgefallen; doch vgl. orlle 111 (= worle 532), ordes 384 ohne w im Anlaut, sore st. swore 17.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>(Sch)e say lyonys, lypardus, many on,</L>
<L N="30">(&amp; o&thorn;er) best(es) fowle &amp; grymme.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. best.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Mary) sayd: "we byn slayn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">byn = ben, vgl. ye byn 229, byn 3 pl. 291. 292. 300. 499 neben byth 296, beth 350, bu&thorn; 611; y steht viel|fach st. e, wie in ynde 203, fyld 522, lyrne 210, hyre 4, wypte 303, grytte 460, fur|&yogh;yfe praet. 627, vnny&thorn;e 136, lyuer 56, nydys 159 u. a.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Alas,) &thorn;ys day waxyd alle dymme!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">20-32) Die Anf&auml;nge der Verse sind abgerissen.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">waxyd st. waxyth.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu blessyd &thorn;e bestys euery on:</L>
<L>Lasse &amp; more lowtyd to hym.</L>
<L N="35">Mary blessyd hyre sone flesch &amp; bon,</L>
<L>For yoe hyre hert reiosyd wythynne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yoe = joy, reiosyd rejoiced.</NOTE></L>
<L>For byrdys songes sche hyrd &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>He s(a)yde hyre drede was alle agon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he syde; he fem.</NOTE></L>
<L>For drede(!) of b(e)stes yn &thorn;at way.</L>
<L N="40">Fyrdyrmore sche wente anone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">36-40) Diese Verse sind offenbar verderbt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(In &thorn;at) contre, &thorn;at wasse west &amp; wylde,</L>
<L>Barabas wonyde yn &thorn;at way,</L>
<L>&thorn;at owtlays was, as y yow telle.</L>
<L>. . h(e) sayd: "womman, by &thorn;e laye!<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor he scheint ein kleines Wort ausgefallen.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Wat beryst &thorn;ou?" Mary sayd: "a chyld."</L>
<L>Jhesu lowe, &thorn;er he lay.</L>
<L>The sone bade &thorn;e fader be myld.</L>
<L>"So myld, sone, y wylle be to day,</L>
<L>Weder &thorn;ou well, wythoutyn nay:</L>
<L N="50">Y wyl robbe hem al III,</L>
<L>Certeynly, &thorn;ys ylke day".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He toke Yosef wyth vylonye,</L>
<L>And he toke Mary by &thorn;e lappe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bygan Dysmas to crye:</L>
<L N="55">"Lefe fader, let them schape!<NOTE PLACE="foot">schape escape.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me were lyuer to day for ay</L>
<L>&THORN;en he toke on them no happe".<NOTE PLACE="foot">he ist plur., obwohl diese Form sonst nicht wieder begegnet. no happe st. onhappe?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e fader foryefe hym sycurly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym plur., wie 635. 636. 672. 698. 751. 796, daneben ham 231. 266. 385. 434, hem, them (&thorn;em).</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys sone for yoye began to chappe(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. chappe st. clappe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">&amp; made myr&thorn;e &amp; melody.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd anon mylde Mary:</L>
<L>"Lefe sone, quyte hym thys!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thus st. thys.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Dame, on my ry&yogh;th hond he schalle day<NOTE PLACE="foot">day, Orig. dy; auch 56. 159. 184. 196. 234 u. &ouml;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; come wyth me yn to blysse".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">F(yrder) more ow(re) l(ad)y went,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonne schon &thorn;at tyme ful hote:</L>
<L>To rest hyre Mary had talent</L>
<L>&amp; sayd: "for hete y wax al mate".</L>
<L>Josef hyre yn hys armys hent,</L>
<L N="70">For he vnderstod hyre state,</L>
<L>&amp; toke hyre down yn good entent</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mule, were-apon sche sate;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a pon, so stets.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnder a tre, &thorn;at (was) ful hye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">was fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth fayr flowres he made hyre sete.</L>
<L N="75">Mary sayd: he were ful slee</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;ys tre ony frute may&yogh;th gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wen Mary &thorn;us had menyd hyre mone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;<SUP>s</SUP> st. &thorn;us.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here sone wyst welle wat was hyre wylle;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at frute, &thorn;at wasse goode, y wene,</L>
<L N="80">He yeafe hys moder, &amp; &thorn;at was schele:</L>
<L>Jhesu spake to &thorn;e tree anone:</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou by adon my moder tylle,</L>
<L>Tylle sche &amp; Yosef bothe calle<NOTE PLACE="foot">calle falscher Reim zu v. 85, st. haue tane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;y frute wat &thorn;at ys &thorn;er wylle".</L>
<L N="85">The tre to hyre fete gan falle,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;at &thorn;ay had take &thorn;at &thorn;ay wylle.</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ey had take wat &thorn;ay wolde,</L>
<L>As hyt was fu(r)st, hyt stod uppe welle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fust.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;en sayd myld Mary:</L>
<L N="90">"Sertys, me &thorn;orstyth swy&thorn;e sore".</L>
<L>Yosep sayd: "a&thorn;orste am y,</L>
<L>&amp; yet our mule hath meke more.</L>
<L>(Al) &thorn;ys londe ys so drye,</L>
<L>For fawt of wete ys alle my care".</L>
<L N="95">Jhesu spake to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>ke tree hym bye:</L>
<L>". . . . more wylle hym water &thorn;are".</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e rowte sone gan water spryng,</L>
<L>Wyllys fayr, bothe water &amp; wyne at wylle,</L>
<L>Plenty of al both he gan brynge.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;erof &thorn;ey dronkyn alle hyre fylle.
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>Mary blessyd hyre sone blod &amp; bone</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ankyt hym &thorn;at was so fre.</L>
<L>Jhesu spake to &thorn;e tree anone:</L>
<L>"Yn paradyse &thorn;ou schalt ybore be".</L>
<L N="105">"&thorn;er com angelys many onne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. con st. com.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wyth gret ly&yogh;th, &thorn;at men may&yogh;th se,</L>
<L>An toke &thorn;e bronchys euery-chone<NOTE PLACE="foot">an st. and.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; left &thorn;er no&thorn;yng of &thorn;e tree,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &amp; left &thorn;er <I>of hym</I> no&thorn;yng of &thorn;e tree.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn to paradyse &thorn;ey hyt browt</L>
<L N="110">Tylle Ennoc &amp; Hely, hys fere.</L>
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;at alle &thorn;ys orlle hath wrowt,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme was old bot &thorn;e tyme of o yere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WYth a wold yew gan &thorn;ay mete<NOTE PLACE="foot">wold st. old, auch 526, wie woder st. oder 361.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e way hy askyd hym by reson.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hy plur., nur hier, sonst &thorn;ay, &thorn;ey (they), &thorn;e 606.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">He sayd: "to Yegypte hafe ye yette</L>
<L>&THORN;yrty yurnyys of good mylyn".<NOTE PLACE="foot">mylyn st. mylon?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an bygan Mary to grete.</L>
<L>For werynys sche sat hyre done.</L>
<L>Dame", sayd Jhesu, "&thorn;y greuyng &thorn;ou lete!</L>
<L N="120">Loe here ys &thorn;e wallys of Egypte towne":<NOTE PLACE="foot">loe = lo; die Hs. schreibt gern oe: soe, froe, woe, goe, toe, doe, sloe, ae in nae 283.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er wasse Egypte, &thorn;e ryche syte:</L>
<L>So shorte he mad &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>"Lefe sone, yblysyd &thorn;ou be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sworte st. shorte.</NOTE></L>
<L>As lord &thorn;at alle my&yogh;tys may!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="125">Wen Jhesu &amp; hys moder fre</L>
<L>Yn to Egypte &thorn;ey were ybroth,</L>
<L>Frawd was lord of &thorn;at contre.</L>
<L>Alle hys goodes of gold he had wroth;</L>
<L>(Pil)gremys come by &thorn;yrty &amp; &thorn;ree,</L>
<L N="130">(&THORN;e)se maumentes for hyre goodes &thorn;ay sowfte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. m&amacr;metes.</NOTE></L>
<L>(W)en Jhesu wallyde yn &thorn;at syte,</L>
<L>(A)ll ys goodes fyl to no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Frawdys was wro&thorn;e &amp; nydel ode(!),<NOTE PLACE="foot">ode st. wode?</NOTE></L>
<L>He smete hym sylfe yn &thorn;e hede<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede st. hefid, heuid.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">&thorn;at hys nose &amp; mowth was al blod:</L>
<L>Vnny&thorn;e was any lyfe on hym ylefyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Algates Frawdes herde say</L>
<L>&thorn;at Jhesu schuld by lord of alle,</L>
<L>As prophetes tolde yn hyre lay</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;at Jhesu schuld be my&yogh;thys of alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">my&yogh;thys Superl., wie formes 673, sonst endet der Sup. auf yst.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wase of Jhesu dred &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>ke day:</L>
<L>&amp; mercy he gan to hym calle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. falle st. calle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu sayd not onys nay,</L>
<L>He foryefe hys synnys alle.</L>
<L N="145">Jhesu tok them euery-chone</L>
<L>&thorn;at wyld come to hys mercy;</L>
<L>&THORN;ay &thorn;at nolde, were ysloe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ysloe st. yslone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn loge prison for to lye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WYth chyldern of &thorn;e towne Jhesu gan wynne</L>
<L N="150">On a day byfore &thorn;e none</L>
<L>To a water &thorn;er hyt gan rynne,</L>
<L>To pley as &thorn;ey were ywonyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wonyd st. wone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu bade &thorn;e water &thorn;at ranne blyne:</L>
<L>Anone he made hyt stonde sone.</L>
<L N="155">Yudas py&yogh;th a staffe &thorn;er anne<NOTE PLACE="foot">anne st. ynne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; vndede &thorn;at Jhesu had done.</L>
<L>"Judas", sayd Jhesu, "&thorn;ou schalt abye<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Judas sayd &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> Jh&umacr; &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou ayenst me hast (doe)".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. name st. doe; name m&uuml;sste jedenfalls nome lau|ten als part. v. nimen, im Sinne von practise, conceive.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nydys behowys Judas to day,</L>
<L N="160">A fot fyrder &thorn;an my&yogh;th he not goe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e chyldern of &thorn;e town &thorn;an ranne</L>
<L>For drede of hyre feloys sake</L>
<L>To syre Lenye, &thorn;e aldurmanne,</L>
<L>Playnt for Jhesu &thorn;ay gan make</L>
<L N="165">&amp; sayd &thorn;at Judas dede wasse &thorn;anne</L>
<L>For he playd yn &thorn;e lake.</L>
<L>Alle Juys Jhesu gan blame<NOTE PLACE="foot">blame st. banne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sayd: on hym &thorn;ay wold take wrake.
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>All &thorn;e Jwys toke hyre rede</L>
<L N="170">Wat deth &thorn;at he schuld hafe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay sayd: &thorn;ey wyld steyn hym to deth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">deth st. ded, der Schreiber hat die n&ouml;rdl. Form (noch in v. 176) eliminirt. steyn wie beyn st. ben 318, aber stennyd 536.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hys fader schal day &amp; hys moder bothe".<NOTE PLACE="foot">bothe st. bathe?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mary &amp; Josep were ful (woe)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ware st. woe.</NOTE></L>
<L>For here sone &thorn;at was them dere;</L>
<L N="175">For &thorn;e yewys wyld them sloe,</L>
<L>Hyt was no wonder: &thorn;owrfe dede chonge chere.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e water was Mary goe:</L>
<L>"My lefe sone, wat dowst &thorn;ou here?"</L>
<L>"Dame, y make dryuyngys toe,</L>
<L N="180">To chyppe &thorn;e water, as ye may lere".</L>
<L>"Leue sone, me lystyth not to play,</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e town y herd swche a crye:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a swche a crye.</NOTE></L>
<L>But Jwdas ryse &amp; goe hys way,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;re we schullun day".<NOTE PLACE="foot">schullun wie knowun 230, (schullyn 604, scholon 766).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">"Moder, for to fulfylle &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L>Judas schal ryse vp ful &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Hyt schalle leke yow ful ylle &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">leke = like, lekyd 481.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt were beter he were dede are".</L>
<L>Jhesu went &thorn;e body tylle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. stylle st. tylle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">&amp; toke hym vppe by &thorn;e arme:</L>
<L>"Judas, wy lyyst &thorn;ou so stylle?</L>
<L>My moder wolde not &thorn;ou schalt hafe har|me.</L>
<L>"Sertynly, dame, y telhyt &thorn;e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">telhyt = tel hyt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ys traytyr ful of felony</L>
<L N="195">To &thorn;e Juys schalle syl me,</L>
<L>Among my fomen for to day".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syre Leneye &amp; &thorn;e maystrys alle</L>
<L>&amp; Cayphas, &thorn;at was here fere,</L>
<L>On Mary &amp; Yosep gan &thorn;y calle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;y, auch 266, wohl st. &thorn;ay &thorn;<SUP>a</SUP>y verschrieben.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">&amp; sayde to hem saue: "vs here!<NOTE PLACE="foot">saue = sawe?</NOTE></L>
<L>We ow&yogh;te yow honge &amp; hewe ful smale</L>
<L>For yowre sone, &thorn;at ys (yow) dere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">yow fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn hys ynde fowle mot hym falle<NOTE PLACE="foot">ynde = ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at on hys yow&thorn;e wyl not lere.</L>
<L N="205">Wold Jhesu lerne, &yogh;et my&yogh;th he &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; he wyld cast hym sylfe &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>On of &thorn;ys days he my&yogh;t be</L>
<L>A buschype &amp; kepe oure lawe".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A boke Cayphas toke, yn Jhesu ys hond he bede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he st. hyt? bede v. beoden.</NOTE></L>
<L N="210">And bade hym lyrne wyth alle hys mayn.</L>
<L>Jhesu askede hym yn &thorn;at stede:</L>
<L>"Say, wat y &thorn;ynke kan &thorn;ou me say?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">say st. sayn.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cayphas onsueryd &amp; sayd: "nay,</L>
<L>By hym that alle &thorn;ys worle hath wroth!</L>
<L N="215">Y not ner by ny&yogh;t noder by day<NOTE PLACE="foot">ner auch 292, nere 338.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wat &thorn;ou &thorn;enkyst yn &thorn;y &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now &thorn;ou wost not my &thorn;owth,</L>
<L>Sy(re) Cayphas, ne Zakarye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Sy st. Syre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Who hath yowre lawys wrowth?"</L>
<L N="220">He sayd: "Aron, Enok &amp; Elye,</L>
<L>Samuel owre lays browth,</L>
<L>Ysaac, Yacob &amp; Dauy,</L>
<L>Moyses owre lays sow&yogh;th</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e montyn of Synay,<NOTE PLACE="foot">montyn (montene 762, montayn 232, montanys 282) vgl. sertyn 193, resynys 235, traytyr 194, buschyp 208.</NOTE></L>
<L N="225">Abram bygan to spelle &mdash;</L>
<L>Now ys a &thorn;owsant wynter (gone);<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. fehlt gone.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was neuer no man our lays my&yogh;th fel(l)e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fele st. felle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sethen were &thorn;ay neuer ondone".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Go way," sayd Jhesu, "ye byn welle madde,</L>
<L N="230">&YOGH;e ne knowun not of clergy.</L>
<L>Moyses ham of my fader hadde</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e montayn of Synay,
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>Abraham prechyde as y hym bade,</L>
<L>&amp; sayd: a man for folke schalle day".</L>
<L N="235">For Jhesu ys resynys &thorn;ay wax al madde</L>
<L>&amp; cast on hym a loud crye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay sayd: "&thorn;ou gabbyst, &amp; &thorn;at ys &thorn;e schame,</L>
<L>&thorn;at may neuermore be:</L>
<L>God had neuer chyldys name</L>
<L N="240">&thorn;at any erthyly man hath".<NOTE PLACE="foot">237-240) dieselben Verse auch 417-420.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">hath falsches Reimwort, st. my&yogh;t se, wie 420.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo was they &mdash; so mut they the!<NOTE PLACE="foot">mut = must, may, dieselbe Form Destr. of Troy 4865.</NOTE></L>
<L>He that schope cornelys &amp; corne,</L>
<L>As Abraham seyde so schalle hyt be,</L>
<L>&amp; off a meyde he was borne.</L>
<L N="245">"My fader syttyth &amp; lokyth on me:</L>
<L>There y am, he ys me byforne".</L>
<L>For Jhesu ys reson they gan fle,</L>
<L>For Jhesu ys reson they were forlorne.</L>
<L>Syre Cayphas toke vp a &yogh;erde</L>
<L N="250">&amp; smote Jhesu on the hede: &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede st. hevid.</NOTE></L>
<L>They alle wyst not how hyt ferde,</L>
<L>But Cayphas there hys lyffe levyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Y have getyn at my hart rowte",<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor rowte fehlt a; rowte violent movement.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mary seyde wyth mekylle care,</L>
<L N="255">"Leve sone, by Cayphas ys blode".<NOTE PLACE="foot">blode st. lote? od. blote?</NOTE></L>
<L>"Dame, he schalle aryse fulle sone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone st. &yogh;are.</NOTE></L>
<L>Apon me he schalle holde a mote</L>
<L>And do so to-bete my body bare</L>
<L>That a fly schalle not set hyre fote</L>
<L N="260">In alle my body, dame, for sare".</L>
<L>&THORN;an Mary ly&yogh;st no songe</L>
<L>Suche sowrow on hyre sone to see.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sowrow, dieselbe Schreibung 301. 385. 389. 482, sp&auml;ter sorow.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;e &thorn;arnet lete hym lyfe so longe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;arnet = &thorn;ar not.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone, but yf &thorn;y wylle be".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">XII sparowys Jhesu made of clay</L>
<L>&amp; bade ham fle as &thorn;y &thorn;owt.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chyldern to &thorn;e towne to hyre way<NOTE PLACE="foot">to verschr. st. toke? oder = te, wie to in Sir Gaw. 1671?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sayde: Jhesu on hyre sabate day wrowt.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e yuys Jhesu gan banne</L>
<L N="270">For &thorn;at day halewede nowt,<NOTE PLACE="foot">he liegt im Verbum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ay wryyd hym by hys name,</L>
<L>&amp; byfore &thorn;e justys he was browt.</L>
<L>"Wat art &thorn;ou? a, sely syre,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ert abute to dystrye our lawe".<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawe st. lay.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">Jhesu sayd: "y toke no hyre,</L>
<L>Y dede hyt no&yogh;th but yn my play".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SYthen apon a noder day</L>
<L>Wyth chyldern of &thorn;e town Jhesu gan mete.</L>
<L>He sayd to them: "wylle we goe play</L>
<L N="280">Among &thorn;e hyllys, &thorn;er for to lepe"?</L>
<L>For&thorn;e lepe Jhesu, so dede &thorn;ay,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e montanys &thorn;at were wyde.</L>
<L>Osep wol lepe, Jhesu sayd nae:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Osep &ouml;fter st. Josep, auch in der Mitte des Verses. nae st. nay.</NOTE></L>
<L>He wolde no&yogh;th deth schulde hym dere.</L>
<L N="285">"Osep", sayde Jhesu, "hade &thorn;e, welle fare(!),<NOTE PLACE="foot">hade st. hale? oder = hede?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou schalt not lepe here.</L>
<L>Oure feloys schalle by hurte ful sore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">by = be. auch 138. 306.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ay wolle algate be my pere".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e towne &thorn;ay toke here gates gayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ff. der Text ist hier sehr verderbt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">No more but &thorn;ay too.</L>
<L>"Y trowe our chyldern byn slayn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y st. we? es sind die Worte der Juden.</NOTE></L>
<L>We wot ner weder oure chyldern byn goo".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. goo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Osep sayde: "hyt ys not&yogh; to weyn.</L>
<L>For to lepe we made ows men(!):<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. men, st. vien? oder st. bayn?</NOTE></L>
<L N="295">Ayenst Jhesu we had no mayn,</L>
<L>For alle our feloys byth sclayn".</L>
<L>"How schapyst &thorn;ou &thorn;at wase hys fere?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser Vers steht ohne Beziehung.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ayenste Jhesu we had no my&yogh;th.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ay wolde be algates hy(s) pere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hy st. hys.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">Owre feloys byn to deth ydyth".
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="116"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gre(te) sowrow &thorn;e Juys gan make &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gre st. grete.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at many men made yn &thorn;at syte &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; wypte for hyre chyldern sake.</L>
<L>Mary &amp; Josep were &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort (ny?) fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="305">"But ye on Jhesu wol take wrake,</L>
<L>Ye schal by hongen al &thorn;ree".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>hong</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mary to hyre sone sche gan make,</L>
<L>&amp; yn hys moder he had pyty:</L>
<L>"Osep, felow, &thorn;ou art mysse-kende.</L>
<L N="310">&amp; for my moder schal hafe no blame,</L>
<L>Goe vppe to &thorn;e towne ys ende</L>
<L>&amp; clype &thorn;em home al by name!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mame st. name.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Osep clepe them, as &thorn;ay hete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">hete st hy&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>To towne &thorn;ay we(n)t alle bydene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wet st. went.</NOTE></L>
<L N="315">&THORN;e Juys were glad of &thorn;at sythe,</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ey hyre chylder my&yogh;th sene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>see</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ay askede of &thorn;em anon ry&yogh;th:</L>
<L>Were so longe &thorn;ay had beyn.</L>
<L>"For to lepe had we hy&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="320">&amp; Jhesu dede ows tray &amp; tene.</L>
<L>We were dede, for sothe ywysse,</L>
<L>But hys mercy was more:</L>
<L>For we wende we had lost owre blysse.</L>
<L>We wolle lere &amp; lorne hys lore".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">SYthen ylke a chyld to oder gan telle:</L>
<L>Ofter water &thorn;ay were schent<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ofter = after, wie 836; schent St. sent.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wythout &thorn;e cete at a wylle.</L>
<L>&amp; Jhesu wyth them, &thorn;ys good sone, went.</L>
<L>&THORN;ay lokyd wych schuld be snelle,</L>
<L N="330">Bot frust Jhesu hys water hente.</L>
<L>On of hys feloys was schelle,</L>
<L>Brake Jhesu ys pot &amp; hym schent.</L>
<L>"Achas, &thorn;ou ert to blame</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou my water hast sede &amp; doe me tene.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sede st. shede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="335">Er &thorn;at we come home,</L>
<L>Alle to scherdys schalle be &thorn;yne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu gaderyd hys scherdys yn haste,</L>
<L>&thorn;er he left nere a one,</L>
<L>Blessyd them &amp; togedere raste.</L>
<L N="340">"&YOGH;ut, feloys, hyt ys not none:</L>
<L>Y rede &thorn;at we pley &amp; reste</L>
<L>&amp; honge owre pottes yn &thorn;e sunne-beme,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sun-beme me &thorn;ynkyth hyt ys beste".</L>
<L>So wente &thorn;ay for to done:</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;e Juys brake hyre pottes on hye;</L>
<L>Achas fryst bygan to wepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd Jhesu: "sycurly,</L>
<L>Now on-hanges, &amp; ano&thorn;er wylle kepe".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Osep sayde: "yf &thorn;y wylle be,</L>
<L N="350">Me &thorn;ynkyth of wyt we beth to sclowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sclowe = slowe; das Ms. schreibt &ouml;fter sc st. s, so sclayn, sclo, sclake 401, scley 401, sclepe 699, poscte 351, auch sch in schlon 666, scheche 528. 529. 531, schent 326.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou art lord of al poscte,</L>
<L>Welle ou&yogh;t we alle &thorn;e knowe</L>
<L>Euery day &thorn;y myracles to se &mdash;</L>
<L>So ofte &thorn;ou wylt them schowe.</L>
<L N="355">My pycher &thorn;at ys brokyn a-&thorn;ree</L>
<L>Wylle be hole, yf &thorn;ou &thorn;er yn blowe".</L>
<L>"Osep, felow, for &thorn;y sake</L>
<L>Yowre pycharus schalle be hole (anone)".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ynow st. anone, falscher Reim zu 356.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grete yoe &thorn;e chylderne gan make,</L>
<L N="360">To towneward &thorn;ay songe euery-chone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SYthen eueriche Jew to woder tolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">woder = oder.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Jhesu ys myracle &amp; many mo:</L>
<L>"Yf he hafe owre chyldern yn honde,</L>
<L>Ywysse he wylle them alle sclo.</L>
<L N="365">Y rede we gete a man stronge</L>
<L>Owre chyldern to kepe &amp; wyth &thorn;em to holde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at none goe fro hym wyth wronge,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;ay be wyxyn men bolde".</L>
<L>Jhesu cam &thorn;at man by:</L>
<L N="370">"Wat kepyst &thorn;ou?" he sayd: "swyne".</L>
<L>"Swyne" sayd he, "schal &thorn;ay be,</L>
<L>For &thorn;y word &thorn;ou schal not lyne".
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="117"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At tyme at none wen men schuld ete,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e town &thorn;ay gan goe.</L>
<L N="375">&thorn;er men (herde) gruntyng grete &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">herde fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt ware not chylder &thorn;at fered soe.</L>
<L>"Were was &thorn;ou &thorn;at schuldyst hem kepe?"</L>
<L>"Y com not a fote ham froe,</L>
<L>Stylle y sate yn &thorn;at stede".</L>
<L N="380">"Cam any man by &thorn;e &thorn;o?"</L>
<L>"Jhesu askyd wat was &thorn;er ynne,</L>
<L>y onsweryd &amp; sayd: swyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &amp; st. y.</NOTE></L>
<L>He tornyd away &thorn;at tyme</L>
<L>&amp; my ordes, he sayd, y schulde not lyyne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Grete sowrow was among ham alle,</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ay &thorn;ys swyne my&yogh;t see.</L>
<L>"Adonay ys come", &thorn;ay calle,</L>
<L>"Kynge of ywys! wat may &thorn;ys be?</L>
<L>Swche sowrow was neuer vythyn &thorn;ys walle".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. byth yn st. wythyn.</NOTE></L>
<L N="390">Mary &amp; Yosep were ful mylde,</L>
<L>Mercy to Jhesu &thorn;ay gan calle</L>
<L>&amp; prayd hym helpe for cheryte.</L>
<L>Jhesu toke &thorn;e swyne euerychone</L>
<L>&amp; blessyd them alle wyth hys holy honde:</L>
<L N="395">&amp; wen &thorn;ay had hys blessynge take,<NOTE PLACE="foot">take st. tone.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;ay were frust, vp gan &thorn;ay stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For Osep hys sone ys sake<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hier fehlt die Bezeichnung des Vaters.</NOTE></L>
<L>Yn &thorn;e myddyl of &thorn;e fyld he mad a towre,</L>
<L>Osep hys sone he gan take</L>
<L N="400">&amp; loke hym fast yn &thorn;at bowre:</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;i solas &thorn;ou schal sclake,</L>
<L>Jhesu schal not be &thorn;y socowre".</L>
<L>&amp; yet for &thorn;e chyld ys sake</L>
<L>Jhesu cam to &thorn;e bowre.</L>
<L N="405">Jhesu ganne walke &thorn;e towre abow(t)e:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. abowe st. abowte.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Osep, y am come &thorn;e fore.</L>
<L>Put owt &thorn;i lytyl fynger!" &amp; &thorn;erwyth he plucked hym out<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. but put owt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Euen at a newgarus hole.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hole st. bore. newgar = navegar, auger.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e Jewys mayd a grete gaderynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mayd = mad, ebenso 456. 459. 491, vgl. deyd 471, askeyd 438. 417-20 ebenso 237-40.</NOTE></L>
<L N="410">Jhesu ys myracles &thorn;er &thorn;ay sowth.</L>
<L>"Ys &thorn;y fader heue kynge?"</L>
<L>He sayd ful wyse: "wete ye no&yogh;th?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;e fende to helle can brynge</L>
<L>Wyth my blode hyt schal be bowth;</L>
<L N="415">For Adam ys synnys &amp; Eue ys cown|selynge</L>
<L>Many sowlys to pyne were broth".</L>
<L>&THORN;ay sayd: "&thorn;ou gabbyst, &amp; &thorn;at ys &THORN;e schame,</L>
<L>&thorn;at may neuermore bee:</L>
<L>Gode had neuer chylde name,</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;at euer eny erlyche man my&yogh;th se".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu my&yogh;th not &thorn;e Juys queme,</L>
<L>Alle to hym &thorn;ay gan say:</L>
<L>"To be a wycche hyt may &thorn;e seme,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ert abowte to strye our lay".</L>
<L N="425">Alle &thorn;e Juys Jhesu gan deme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">strye = distrye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;en sayd on: ys good, anoder sayd nay,</L>
<L>H(al)ely &thorn;ay gan hym fleme &amp; wyld hym hent</L>
<L>Wythout harnys &thorn;at ylke day.</L>
<L>To Na&yogh;aret was Jhesu went</L>
<L N="430">By &thorn;e gates &thorn;at were fulle gayn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Der Vers im Ms. doppelt: to na&yogh;aret was Jhesu went &mdash; ye to na&yogh;areth he was went.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er hadde Yosep ful meny a frende:</L>
<L>Of Jhesu ys comyng &thorn;ay were ful fayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WYth chyldern of &thorn;e towne Jhesu kame yfere</L>
<L>And wyth ham alle to schole he went.</L>
<L N="435">Mayster Juby sayd: "wylte &thorn;ou lere?"</L>
<L>He tok hym a boke wyth good entent.</L>
<L>Jhesu askeyd, &thorn;at he my&yogh;th hyre,</L>
<L>A. b. c, &amp; wat hyt menyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;e mayster chongyt chere</L>
<L N="440">&amp; for schame held hym schent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mayster Jube had hys lesson fulfylled</L>
<L>As Dauyd &thorn;e profyt told yn hys lore:
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>To a maydyn meke &amp; mylde</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost fro hym schuld fare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym st. hy?</NOTE></L>
<L N="445">Of hyre body to bere a chylde,</L>
<L>&amp; for alle &thorn;at clene mayde as sche was &yogh;are(!).</L>
<L>"&YOGH;yf no&yogh;t were &thorn;y werkys wylde,</L>
<L>Y wylle say &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;ylke were</L>
<L>As Dauyd &thorn;e profyt told byfore".</L>
<L N="450">"Redelyche hyt am y;</L>
<L>For Adam ys synnys &thorn;at was forlore,</L>
<L>Wyth my deth y schal hym bye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sythyne apon a noder daye</L>
<L>Wyth chylderne Jhesu ganne mete,</L>
<L N="455">Sum wold play &amp; sum sayd naye.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sune-beme Jhesu mayd hys sete.</L>
<L>As he dede, so wend &thorn;ay:</L>
<L>&THORN;ay fylle adown, &amp; neuer &thorn;e bet(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. neu mit liegendem d als Abbrev.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu lawe &amp; mayd hys play.</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;ay &thorn;at lefyt, sore &thorn;ay gan grytte.</L>
<L>Summe brake legge &amp; sum &thorn;e &thorn;ye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">legge ist &uuml;ber durchstrichenem nekke &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum &thorn;e hed &amp; summe &thorn;e arme,</L>
<L>Sum &thorn;e hypys &amp; summe &thorn;e knee:</L>
<L>&thorn;er schapyd non wythoutyn harme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">A nolde wyfe come by &thorn;e strete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">a nolde = an olde.</NOTE></L>
<L>For drede to &thorn;e town sche ranne.</L>
<L>Wyth syre Melchy sche ganne mete.</L>
<L>"&THORN;y sone ys dede, syr Lyuyan.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lyuy &amacr;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y sawe Jhesu on &thorn;e sunne bem sytte;</L>
<L N="470">Alle &thorn;e Jwys may Jhesu banne:</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ay lyen deyd vnder hys fete</L>
<L>More chyldern &thorn;an y telle kan."</L>
<L>The ywys rongyn hyr comyn belle</L>
<L>&amp; gaderyd them togedere euery-chone,</L>
<L N="475">&amp; &thorn;ay sayd: &thorn;ay wolde Jhesu quelle,</L>
<L>Sum wyth stafe &amp; sum wyth stone,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ay sayd: &thorn;ay wlde Jhesu sloe,</L>
<L>But he here chyldern wyld safe.</L>
<L>&thorn;er my&yogh;th no ywe on fote goe,</L>
<L N="480">Euery-chone to towne &thorn;ay gan drawe.</L>
<L>&thorn;at Mary lekyd ful ylle:</L>
<L>"Leue sone, let &thorn;ys sowrow sesse!</L>
<L>For my lofe, yf hyt be &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L>Lette ows be sumware yn pese!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="485">&THORN;o Mary for &thorn;e chyldern made hyre pray(e)r<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prayr st. prayere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ay schulde ryse &amp; gone,</L>
<L>Jhesu blessyd &thorn;em alle &thorn;at there were:</L>
<L>And wen &thorn;ay had hys beneson,</L>
<L>&THORN;ay rose vp alle hole &amp; fere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hold' st. hole.</NOTE></L>
<L N="490">Seche mode was neuer none:</L>
<L>&THORN;ay hopyd &amp; sungyn &amp; mayd good chere<NOTE PLACE="foot">hopyd = hoppyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at were byhaymyd(!) alle byforne.</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ay were dede, Jhesu bade ham ryse</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;afe ham both speche &amp; lyfe.</L>
<L N="495">"We schuld hym lofe, &amp; we were wyse,</L>
<L>Euery chylde, man &amp; wyfe".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sythyn apon a noder morow</L>
<L>Mary sayd: "my sone, &thorn;ou rewe!</L>
<L>&thorn;ys folkys nere for honger byn lore".<NOTE PLACE="foot">byn &uuml;bergeschr.; folkys st. folk ys? s. 781.</NOTE></L>
<L N="500">Josepf hys powyr welle knew.</L>
<L>Jhesu toke a barly corne,</L>
<L>Yn mydde &thorn;e felde he hyt sewe,</L>
<L>&amp; bade &thorn;e pynder blow hys horne:</L>
<L>&amp; euer(i)che man made harwyst newe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. euer che.</NOTE></L>
<L N="505">&THORN;ay repyd &amp; bunde schefys grete,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at corne &thorn;ay were ful fayn.</L>
<L>"He &thorn;at send ows al &thorn;at mete,</L>
<L>We ofte to lofe hym, soth to sayne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sadrac was a man of grete power</L>
<L N="510">&amp; enperour of &thorn;at syte:</L>
<L>"Here ys Sydrac, my dofter dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fayryst womman of &thorn;ys contre.</L>
<L>Jhesu, wult &thorn;ou here? hyre!<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor hyre ist hafe durchgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>A weddyt man yf &thorn;ou wylt be,</L>
<L N="515">Ouer alle my lond y make &thorn;e pere.</L>
<L>Yff &thorn;ou wulte, &thorn;an mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;e".</L>
<L>Melchy sayd: "&thorn;ou fayr knafe,</L>
<L>My dofter ys cortes &amp; fyne;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou wylt my dofter hafe,</L>
<L N="520">Many yeftys y wulle &thorn;e yefe.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="119"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y wlle &thorn;e yefe oxyn &amp; plowe,</L>
<L>Downys &amp; dalys, fyldes &amp; fenne,</L>
<L>&amp; my wodys euery bowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ys myne, euery delle".<NOTE PLACE="foot">delle = dele, unrichtiges Reimwort.</NOTE></L>
<L N="525">"Go way", sayd Jhesu, "y am woe,</L>
<L>Y wend &thorn;at ye had be wolde men.</L>
<L>My modyr ys fayr ynowe(!)</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;y dofter, &amp; scheche tenne.</L>
<L>Ye may yefe me no scheche myde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">myde = mede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="530">For yowre yftys wolde not gayne.</L>
<L>Werto scheche &thorn;ynge wulde ye me be(de)?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mebe oder meve?, st. me bede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e worle hyt ys myne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(Alle the Juis Jhesu rad</L>
<L>For to take that hyme was bede:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. that &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP>, doppelt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="535">"(Or thor&yogh;) the law thow shalt be lad<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die ersten 2 Buchst. sind unleserlich, vr oder ve? Ms. ther st. thor&yogh; (l. wether?)</NOTE></L>
<L>Among vs alle &amp; stennyd to deth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. I st. &amp;, deth st. ded.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thow shalt ches whether thow wolt wed.</L>
<L>Jhesu, trou the note in the lore".</L>
<L>From the Juis faste he fled,</L>
<L N="540">They fond nothinge ther he was ere;</L>
<L>To Gerico was Jhesu went,</L>
<L>Thei fond nothinge ther Jhesu stode,</L>
<L>Thei wote not whether he is went:</L>
<L>For hym thei mornid mayne and mode.)<NOTE PLACE="foot">533&mdash;44) von and. Hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="545">A dyer yn hys dore he stode,</L>
<L>Jhesu cam walkyn by &thorn;e strete:</L>
<L>So fayr a chyld of flaysce &amp; blodde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. flayste st. flaysce.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t he sowe neuer &yogh;ete.</L>
<L>Ayenst Jhesu fast he ede<NOTE PLACE="foot">ede st. &yogh;ode.</NOTE></L>
<L N="550">&amp; wyth &thorn;e chyld he gan mete:</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou ert welcome, freely fode!</L>
<L>Ware were &thorn;ou borne &amp; bygete?"</L>
<L>"Yn &thorn;e borow of Bethelem</L>
<L>Of a may y was borne:</L>
<L N="555">Y am &thorn;e same, as me may sen;</L>
<L>My fader stondyth me byforne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lefe sone, wylt &thorn;ou me say</L>
<L>A lytyl &thorn;ynge for cheryte:</L>
<L>Of a sterre &thorn;at rose byforne &thorn;e daye,</L>
<L N="560">&thorn;at many erthely men my&yogh;th se?</L>
<L>Men sayd yn Bethelem hyt lay,</L>
<L>Now ys XII vynter &amp; &thorn;ree".<NOTE PLACE="foot">vynter mit v st. w, wie vulvus 647.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hyt lad &thorn;re kyngys &thorn;e ry&yogh;th way</L>
<L>For to seke my moder &amp; mee;</L>
<L N="565">My fadur lente hym &thorn;at ly&yogh;th</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey schulde no&yogh;th go ylle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Erowde schuld haue no my&yogh;th,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ha&umacr; = haue, wie 575 ser&umacr; = serue. Die neue Hand verr&auml;th sich in den h&auml;ufigen Abbrev. n &umacr; m d' (der Strich bezeichnet <I>e</I>); sie schreibt ferner can kan st. gan: 588. 593. 647. 758. 762, u. liebt o und u in den Endsilben, z. B. bei chyldron 593 chyldrun 729 (chyldryn 680. 716 &mdash; die erste Hand schrieb chyldern, chylder), scholon 766, sython 716, wekod 609 u. a.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he &thorn;ou&yogh;t hym to spylle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e dexter on Jhesu dede calle:</L>
<L N="570">"Knowst &thorn;ou owte of mystere?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, syre, I kan craftus alle,</L>
<L>I haue no meystere for to lere".</L>
<L>"Go we home to me halle!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou mayst so serue to be my pere.</L>
<L N="575">"Dame, &thorn;ys chylde schalle serue walle.</L>
<L>For my son make hym gode chere!</L>
<L>He may so serue to bene my eyre.</L>
<L>Leue dame, be hym mylde!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyfe vnsweryde hym ful feyre:</L>
<L N="580">"&thorn;ou art welcome, my chylde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Maystur Abakor Iweddude schulde be,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at ys buschop of oure lawe,</L>
<L>Thys clo&thorn;e ha&thorn; gewe to me;<NOTE PLACE="foot">clo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> plur.</NOTE></L>
<L>To lyte hym, I wolle &thorn;e schewe.</L>
<L N="585">Do hem in lomus &thorn;re!"</L>
<L>"Euerychon, syre, &thorn;at &yogh;e my&yogh;th know".</L>
<L>"Make gode for cherite!"</L>
<L>&amp; Jhesu fast he can blow(!).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. blowe, st. bow?</NOTE></L>
<L>"To oure behouy&thorn; me . . . .<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort fehlt (schede?).</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">Do now wel, my swete sone!"</L>
<L>"Maystur, &thorn;e dar haue no drede,</L>
<L>Lo how sone hyt schalle be do".<NOTE PLACE="foot">do st. done.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="120"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Chyldron of &thorn;e towne Jhesu can calle,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey pleyde yn &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L N="595">Jhesu toke &thorn;e clo&thorn;us alle,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey leyen at hys fete,</L>
<L>In on lede he lete hem falle</L>
<L>&thorn;at schulde haue on sundur mete,</L>
<L>Ande se&thorn;en to pley hym at &thorn;e balle</L>
<L N="600">Wyth hys felouse he wulde not lete.</L>
<L>&thorn;at wyfe seyde to syre Gurgye:</L>
<L>"I wend, we haue a wekyde hyne.</L>
<L>But we &thorn;e sunnere home vs hye,</L>
<L>All owre clo&thorn;ys we schullyn tyn".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="605">Home &thorn;ey wente, as &thorn;ey were rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">red, Orig. rad = afraid.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tylle here howse &thorn;e comme sone.</L>
<L>Styl &thorn;ey stode, as &thorn;ey were madde:</L>
<L>"He schalle abye, by sunne &amp; mon!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. non st. mon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kalle vs in &thorn;at wekod ladde!"</L>
<L N="610">"Were hast &thorn;ou &thorn;ys clo&thorn;ys don?"</L>
<L>"In &thorn;at lede, syre, &thorn;ey bu&thorn; stadde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey may byle, hyt is no none".<NOTE PLACE="foot">byle = bele, boyl.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e dexter toke vp a fyre-brond<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a fayre y brond st. a fyre brond.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ande &thorn;ou&yogh;t to smyte Jhesu sare: &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sure st. sare.</NOTE></L>
<L N="615">In mydde &thorn;e flowre hyt gan stonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gam st. gan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Flowryde fayre &amp; fruyt hyt bare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Clo&thorn;ys out of &thorn;e lede he hyt drew,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor clo&thorn;ys (Ms. clo&thorn;<SUP>s</SUP>) fehlt &thorn;e. hyt ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sum blew, grene &amp; eke (rede),<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &amp; eke dr o&umacr; d. i. droue, flascher Reim zu ynowe; das Reimwort ist offenbar rede.</NOTE></L>
<L>(&amp;) o&thorn;er hewys fayre ynowe &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L N="620">Come neuer soche in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>Jhesu stode, at hem lowe:</L>
<L>"Mayster, &thorn;e darde haue no drede,</L>
<L>I haue don welle ynow;</L>
<L>To make sorow hyt ys no nede".</L>
<L N="625">&THORN;an askede he Jhesu mercy.</L>
<L>Jhesu sayde not onys nay,</L>
<L>He fur&yogh;yfe hys maystur syk(er)ly.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fur&yogh;yfe praet. Ms. sykly st. sykerly.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sethen he wen(t) to hys play.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wen st. went.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Was a chylde &thorn;at het Ernald,</L>
<L N="630">Hys fader of Jowys was rychyste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. Jows, dieses ist von and. Hand in yowyn corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu for&thorn;e by name hym callyd.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym st. he? Ms. nan st. name. callyd st. cald.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Go we for&thorn;e to that forest!</L>
<L>We chyldron wul togedere holde,</L>
<L>For wylde bestys in here neste".</L>
<L N="635">Jhesu sayde wyth hym he walde:</L>
<L>"Go we, lete hym do here best".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. to, in do corr.; vor best ist nest durchgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sorow", quo&thorn;e Arnalde, "at hyt fle<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyt st. hym?</NOTE></L>
<L>Ar for eny be adredde!" &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ar = or, oder st. at = &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>For the furst best &thorn;at he may se</L>
<L N="640">Away fro Jhesu he fledde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Owere a water &thorn;at was so depe</L>
<L>A tre &thorn;er lay ouer a croke:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e chyldron on a hepe</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e tre-croppe he(m) toke;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. hem.</NOTE></L>
<L N="645">Stylle &thorn;ey sate &amp; euur wepte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wepte st. wepe.</NOTE></L>
<L>My&yogh;t no for scham on o&thorn;er loke.</L>
<L>Vuluus in to &thorn;e tre kan crepe</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e chyldron out of schoke.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey were falle bysydys &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="650">Drownyd were &thorn;ey euerychon.</L>
<L>"Vengit" seyd Jhesu, "schall I be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vengit, in vengyt corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e weld bestus I wyl alle sclon".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mary come in &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>To seche here sone was alle here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="655">He askede euery man in &thorn;at cyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. he, v. a. H. in she corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;efe soche man say &thorn;ay owthe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an askede a man: "wat ys he?"</L>
<L>"Hit ys my sone, &thorn;at y haue ofre".<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte = au&yogh;te, oder st. softe = so&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sertes, dame, dede ys he.</L>
<L N="660">Hys fete to wode hym browthe:<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys v. a. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>I saw wylde wuluus &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Scley Arnalde &amp; hys ferus alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferus v. a. H. in felas corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Leonus on hem, so mot y &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">es fehlt ein Verb?</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;e were alyfe, hyt my&yogh;th not be".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ye st. &thorn;e.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="121"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="665">&THORN;e amperowre grete sorow ha&thorn; hente<NOTE PLACE="foot">amperoure wird auch sonst von den Vornehmsten gebraucht, s. 630.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hys son &thorn;at was so schlon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">schlon v. a. H. in schlayn corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;e wode he ha&thorn; ysende</L>
<L>Of hys folke wel gode wone.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e wode &thorn;ey were lente,</L>
<L N="670">Sum wyt stafes &amp; summe wyth ston.</L>
<L>Jhesu to lyonus ha&thorn; yhente,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to = two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bytwene hym to &thorn;an wold he gone,</L>
<L>The formes fote on hys schuldur lente</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hendy &yogh;ede hym byte(?).<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort ist unrichtig, st. by.</NOTE></L>
<L N="675">&THORN;ey alle drust no&yogh;t come hem hende,</L>
<L>Bote of &thorn;ys seyte &thorn;ay were sory.<NOTE PLACE="foot">seyte = si&yogh;te. &thorn;ys u. &thorn;ay sind v. a. H. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Wy wepe &yogh;e now? Ben &yogh;e madde?</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he wolle no&yogh;t come me nere,</L>
<L>Tel my wy &yogh;e ben vngladde?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. my wy by &yogh;e ben.</NOTE></L>
<L N="680">"We wete no&yogh;t were oure chyldryn ere".<NOTE PLACE="foot">ere = are, sonst ben, byn.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Arnalde, &thorn;y sone, hydur (ows) ladde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor ladde sind einige Buchst. verwischt, wahr|scheinl. ows.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at schulde haue ben myn balduste fere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ham st. haue. Ms. scheinbar balenste.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lefte me alon bestadde</L>
<L>Wyth wylde bestys fy&yogh;tynge here,</L>
<L N="685">He lefte me alon in &thorn;ys stede.</L>
<L>Drownyde be &thorn;ay euerychon &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ys I haue done by my rede.</L>
<L>The wylde bestus I wylle alle sclon".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The emp(er)owre sorely frede</L>
<L N="690">And sayde &thorn;an: "&thorn;ys ys my &thorn;ou&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &yogh;ou&yogh;t st. &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</NOTE></L>
<L>Go we swy&thorn;e in to &thorn;e stede</L>
<L>&thorn;er they were to de&yogh;t ybro&yogh;th".<NOTE PLACE="foot">de&yogh;t = deth.</NOTE></L>
<L>So Jhesu wyth hem sone &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Of here mon rofte he no&yogh;th.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. m&omacr;, v. a. H. ist y (m&omacr;y d. i. mony?) angesetzt. Ms. h&emacr; st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L N="695">Wylde bestus &thorn;ey saw hem blede,</L>
<L>Ande fonde &thorn;e chyldron &thorn;at &thorn;ey so&yogh;te.</L>
<L>In to vaynus &thorn;ay haue hem caste,</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e cyte kon &thorn;ey schake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kor st. kon.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nedus behouyde hym to reste,</L>
<L N="700">They fyle on sclepe &thorn;at schulde wake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyle = fyll, fell. Ms. schulde e wake.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e folke sclepe &amp; my&yogh;t no&yogh;t blyne,</L>
<L>Ne to wake &thorn;ey hade no mayne.</L>
<L>Jhesu blessyde &thorn;at was &thorn;er Inne</L>
<L>And keuerede hyt wyth clo&thorn;ys agayn.</L>
<L N="705">Jhesu fast to &thorn;e wode gan rene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rene st. ryne, to run. Nach 706 fehlen mehrere Verse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hys felouse folouydde hym folle fayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Among hem alle was sorow ynow,</L>
<L>Wane euery burgeyse brout a bere.</L>
<L>"Wylde bestus forde he(m) drewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. hem. forde = forthe. drewe st. drow, wie 617.</NOTE></L>
<L N="710">Were byn oure chyldryn &thorn;at schulde be here?"</L>
<L>Mary stode &amp; at hem hee lawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hee fem., wie 729. 38. 655. lawe st. lowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ey askede wy she made seche chere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ey st. she (oder he?).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">woow = wrong, sin.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Woman", &thorn;ey sayde, &thorn;ou hast grete woow.</L>
<L>Oure chyldrun were &thorn;e no&thorn;ynge dere".</L>
<L N="715">"Syre, hyt is not longe gon</L>
<L>Sython y my&yogh;t yowre chyldryn see</L>
<L>Vndur a hasul euery-chon,</L>
<L>Gedere notes vndur a tre".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gerede st. gedere oder gedrede.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e emperoure sekede sore</L>
<L N="720">For hys sone &thorn;at was hym holde:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ef he on l(yu)e ware<NOTE PLACE="foot">von lyue ist nur l sichtbar.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me were lyuer &thorn;an alle my golde.</L>
<L>Lef woman, &yogh;ef &thorn;y wylle ware,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in lef ist <I>ef</I> v. a. H. eingeschr., die auch &uuml;ber m in womon einen <I>m</I> bezeichnenden Strich gesetzt hat (: womman).</NOTE></L>
<L>Brynge vs &thorn;ore &yogh;ef &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde,</L>
<L N="725">I gefe &thorn;e a hundurede ponde &amp; more,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef he lyue man &amp; molde".<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; = an = on.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Of &thorn;y golde kepe I none.</L>
<L>Go wyth me, I woll &yogh;ow wysse".</L>
<L>Hee lade hem to here chyldrun euery|chon &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor hee ist v. a. H. s (: shee) gesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="730">My&yogh;t noman speke o&thorn;ur blysse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. o&thorn;ur st. &thorn;our (&thorn;urgh)?.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>IN to Anfryte hade Jhesu ty&yogh;th,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Anfryte st. Aufryke; Amfreke 755. 764. Vor hade steht unn&uuml;tzes a.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er to dwelle hade he &thorn;ou&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Josep was a scle wry&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Alle hys bolys wit hym hy browte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in bolys ist bol v. a. H. eingeschr., das urspr. Wort ist nicht mehr erkennbar; bole = the round stem of a tree, so in Troy Book 4960 u. Allit. Poems ed. Morris, B 662.</NOTE></L>
<L N="735">Syre Schallyn &thorn;e ryche kynge hyth.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in Schallyn ist llyn v. a. H., das urspr. Wort scheint schar zu sein.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Seche a man lange haue I sou&yogh;th;</L>
<L>I wolde haue a laddur dy&yogh;th</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ese II treys, fey(r) Iwroute.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. fey&ymacr;, der Strich v. a. H.; st. feyr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Do now wel, as y &thorn;e sey,</L>
<L N="740">Ande loke no longer be hit leuud,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. be h&amacr; st. be hit?</NOTE></L>
<L>Or I &thorn;e swere by my laye:</L>
<L>Olde man, I wolle haue &thorn;y hede".<NOTE PLACE="foot">hed st. heuid.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Joseph hem felde &amp; hadde &thorn;e wow:</L>
<L>&THORN;e on tre berst fer fro &thorn;e rote;</L>
<L N="745">Hit is schortor fer now</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e oder by fyue fote.</L>
<L>Josep to &thorn;e wode hym drew:<NOTE PLACE="foot">drew st. drow.</NOTE></L>
<L>He dirst not abyde &thorn;e Jewys mote.</L>
<L>Jhesu sthode vndur a bow:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. schode oder sthode?</NOTE></L>
<L N="750">"Abyte, Joseph, y be &thorn;y bote.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a byte st. abyde; vor be ist v. a. H. schall &uuml;bergeschr.; Orig. wohl bes mit Bed. des Fut.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hold &thorn;e &thorn;are, &amp; I schalle here!"</L>
<L>Bytwene hym to &thorn;ey drew hyt oute.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to = two, wie 764.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Comfort, Joseph, here &thorn;ou mayste lere;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Jewys haue &thorn;ou no dowte".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="755">Wythout Amfreke &thorn;re myle &amp; more</L>
<L>Men fet water at a welle,</L>
<L>A ryche man &thorn;at wonyt &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="foot">on in wonyt v. a. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e pore he kan hit sylle.</L>
<L>Jhesu wende wyth hym &thorn;are.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. sende, v. a. H. in wende corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="760">Sykerly, as y yow telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y v. a. H. &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e water in hys lappe awey he bore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bore st. bare, u. 755 more st. mare.</NOTE></L>
<L>On a hye montene he kan hyt hefe,</L>
<L>He leyde hyt in a stondynge stone:</L>
<L>And to stremus to Amfreke rene:<NOTE PLACE="foot">rene praet., Orig. ryne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="765">&thorn;at on hed Yor, &thorn;e odur: dan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yor u. dan v. a. H. eingeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer scholon of renynge blyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. blym st. blyne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ay askyde Jhesu, as he sate:</L>
<L>"Wat kynnus man kalle &thorn;ey &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"Jhesu, Dauyde sone, y hatte,</L>
<L N="770">Lord of alle poste".</L>
<L>"Adonay, ert &thorn;ou &thorn;at,</L>
<L>Kynge of Jewys &thorn;at schalle be?</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou be lorde of alle &thorn;at,</L>
<L>We pray &thorn;e helpe for cheryte!"</L>
<L N="775">"For to water &thorn;at I haue browt(!)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. for to water; for st. fro, to st. &thorn;e, oder = tone, the one?</NOTE></L>
<L>For to sette here wythout swynges,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. swynges st. swynke. 777 u. 8) me = my.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hyt schalle to me de&thorn; be browth</L>
<L>Galle &amp; eyselle to me drynke".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(To) Galy(l)ee was Jhesu wente:<NOTE PLACE="foot">To fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L N="780">&THORN;ere was weddud archet(r)eclyn;</L>
<L>Mikul folke &thorn;er was lente.<NOTE PLACE="foot">folke v. a. H. in folkes corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>In medde &thorn;e feste he lakede wyne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die a. H. corr. in: In <I>&thorn;e</I> medde <I>of</I> &thorn;e feste <I>the</I> l. w.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e boteler seyd: "Icham schent!</L>
<L>Allas, my seruyse I schalle tyne!"</L>
<L N="785">Wyth carful herte hys mone he ment.</L>
<L>And Mary had pyte of &thorn;at hyne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&uuml;ber of ist v. a. H. at &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Go to my sone ande aske hym grace:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. asked st. aske.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;ef &thorn;at hys swet wylle be,</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;ys folke in &thorn;ys plase</L>
<L N="790">He sende &thorn;e wyn gode plenty".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e boteler on hys kneys hym sette</L>
<L>And prayde hym help pur cherite,</L>
<L>Grete terys &thorn;er he grette.</L>
<L>And Jhesu of hym toke grete pyte:<NOTE PLACE="foot">toke v. a. H. &uuml;bergeschr.,</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="123"></L>
<L N="795">Syx fesselus for&thorn;e &thorn;ey fette<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar sette st. fette.</NOTE></L>
<L>As ful of water as &thorn;ey my&yogh;t be;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of <I>a</I> water.</NOTE></L>
<L>To blesse hym wolde Jhesu not lete:&mdash;</L>
<L>Com neuer no soche wyn in &thorn;at contray:</L>
<L>Syx wessulus ful of wyne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wessulus mit w st. v, wie welonye 810; 795 fesselus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="800">Sum wytte &amp; summe rede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wytte = white.</NOTE></L>
<L>Summe clerat gode &amp; fyn,</L>
<L>Kom neuer soche yn &thorn;at stede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e boteler fylde &amp; to &thorn;e kyng bare,</L>
<L>And he dranke to &thorn;e quone hym by<NOTE PLACE="foot">quone ist v. a. H. in queyne corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="805">And bade &thorn;e boteler feche more:<NOTE PLACE="foot">more st. mare.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sertes, &thorn;ou seruyst ows wykely!<NOTE PLACE="foot">wykely st. wykedly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ware was &thorn;ys gode wyn lenger ayre?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar syre, der Reim erfordert are.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Alle gon, syre, sothefastly.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ef Jhesu, Mary sone, ne were,<NOTE PLACE="foot">were st. ware.</NOTE></L>
<L N="810">We hauid had grete welonye:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hau&umacr; oder hauid?</NOTE></L>
<L>Oure wyn was alle gon,</L>
<L>Store was vs left no&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of water in &thorn;e stondynge stone</L>
<L>Jhesu gode wyn ha&thorn; made &amp; wrowt".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="815">He hade &thorn;e botelere, as he hede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede st. yode.</NOTE></L>
<L>Brynge god wyn fyrst to honde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">honde st. hande.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Wen &thorn;ey ben gladde in mayn &amp; mode,</L>
<L>Lete no wyket wyne byfore hym stonde!"</L>
<L>He askede wy &thorn;e wyne was so god.</L>
<L N="820">"My fadur hyt blessyde wyth hys hande.</L>
<L>That schalle by delyd, my fleyche &amp; blode,</L>
<L>Among crystynmen yn lande,</L>
<L>Hyt schalle alleway be the more</L>
<L>And neuer more &thorn;e lesse".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mtore st. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="825">&thorn;ys &thorn;ey trowyde on hys lore</L>
<L>And leuyd aftur yn hys professye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. leuyf st. leuyd.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nyne &amp; twenty &yogh;ere olde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Tyne st. nyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was Jhesu Cryst: at hys tryste</L>
<L>In a monteyn wonyde a man bold,</L>
<L N="830">Men clepyd hym Jh&omacr;n &thorn;e baptyste:</L>
<L>Ledde hym to flym Jordayne,</L>
<L>Baptysyd hym &amp; callyde hym Cryst.</L>
<L>Lorde, yf &thorn;y wylle be don,</L>
<L>Len vs to be at &yogh;owre vprys(t)e!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. to len (= grant) oder leu; to ist zu til|gen. Ms. vpryse, Orig. vpryste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="835">&THORN;o was hys chyldehode alle agon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;o was hys chyldehode was.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hys manhod com ofter ay.</L>
<L>After more loke &yogh;e none:</L>
<L>For&yogh;et &thorn;ys not, I wold &yogh;ow rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">836&mdash;8) sind durch Correctur der andern Hand verderbt; in 836 ist com v. d. a. H. eingeschrieben; 837&mdash;8 lauten urspr.: after more loke &yogh;e none: for &yogh;et &thorn;<SUP>s</SUP> (?) know I wold &yogh;ow . ., in 837 ist none durchgestr. u. euer a too erg&auml;nzt, in 838 hat die a. H. know durch|gestr. u. not &uuml;bergeschr., u. hinter &yogh;ow rede (st. say?) erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fader &amp; sone &amp; holy gost</L>
<L N="840">And Mary moder, I blessyd &yogh;e be</L>
<L>For youre holy my&yogh;tus most!<NOTE PLACE="foot">your blys v. a. H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Grante vs your blys par cheryte!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.&mdash;&mdash;</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod dominus Joh(an)nes architenens ca|no(ni)cus bodminie et natus in illa. deo gracias<NOTE PLACE="foot">Derselbe Name ist fol. 47 am Schlusse eines der K. J. vorangehenden Gedichtes unterzeichnet mit den Worten: Explicit contemplationem bonam. Quod dominus Joh(an)nes arcuarius Cano|nicus Bodmine. deo gracias; bei arcuarius ist dann von and. Hand &uuml;bergeschrieben: arcuarius Bouyer. Am Rande von fol. 48 steht in grossen Buchst.: J. bow . . scrip. . hoc ue(rsum), und links auf der gegen|&uuml;berstehenden Seite: Si uis veritatem scire: ff.; beide Randnoten stehen offenbar im Zusammenhang; jenes J bow ist unvollst&auml;ndig statt J(ohannes) Bow(yer), lat. Arcitenens. Bowyer ist also der Name des Unterzeichners.</NOTE>.</L>
<L>Et sic finitur pueritia domini nostri Jesu Cristi.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="song"><PB REF="00000130.tif" N="[124]">
<HEAD>2. Canticum de Creatione<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Version ist bereits edirt in W&uuml;lcker's Anglia Bd. I, Heft 2.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="a" TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Trin. Coll. Oxf. 57, fol. 156 (gedichtet 1375).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu Crist, heuene kynge,</L>
<L>And his moder, &thorn;at swete &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Grante hem &thorn;e blesse of heuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at willen in pes a whyle be stille</L>
<L N="5">And wi&thorn; guod herte and wille</L>
<L>Lesteny to my steuene:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And y shel telle &yogh;ow beforn</L>
<L>How Adam &amp; Eue paradys lorn</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh &thorn;e fendis wyle,</L>
<L N="10">And also of &thorn;e rode treo</L>
<L>&THORN;at god on deyde for &yogh;ow &amp; meo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wille dwelle a whyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;if &yogh;e wille &yogh;eue lestyng,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shollen here ri&yogh;t guod &thorn;yng,</L>
<L N="15">Er &yogh;e hannes wende:</L>
<L>Pardoun &yogh;e mowe &thorn;erwi&thorn; wynne</L>
<L>And &thorn;e betere &yogh;ow kepe fram dedly synne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wille haue it in mende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &yogh;e haue herd told &amp; rad</L>
<L N="20">How &amp; whanne god &thorn;is world mad,</L>
<L>And Adam, as was his wille;</L>
<L>Eue he made to his make;</L>
<L>Al paradys he gan hem take,</L>
<L>His wille to fulfille,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">And bad hem bo&thorn;e wi&thorn;oute stryf</L>
<L>Na&yogh;t eten of &thorn;e tre of lyf.</L>
<L>Bote whanne he was hem fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel hem &thorn;o&yogh;te to begyle:</L>
<L>And cam &thorn;uder wi&thorn;ynne a whyle</L>
<L N="30">And tysede Eue &thorn;erto,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyde: "ete&thorn; an appel tyth,</L>
<L>And be&thorn; as wyse as god almyth".</L>
<L>&THORN;us he tariede hem &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And dude furst Eue, &amp; su&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e man,</L>
<L N="35">Taken an appel &amp; byten &thorn;eran.</L>
<L>Anon bo&thorn;e naked &thorn;e&yogh; were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er cam an angel anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In his hond a swerd bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And bad hem fro paradys go,</L>
<L N="40">Into &thorn;is worlde to leue wi&thorn; care,</L>
<L>And alle here ofspring for eueremare,</L>
<L>For synne &thorn;at &thorn;e&yogh; hadde do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us out of paradys he hem &thorn;rest.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e&yogh; &yogh;eden for&thorn; in to &thorn;e west</L>
<L N="45">And maden here dwellynge &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere dwellede &thorn;e&yogh; sore waymantende</L>
<L>Sixe dayes fulle to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in sorwe &amp; in care.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="125"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whanne hem hongrede, for faute of mete,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e&yogh; &yogh;eden and sou&yogh;ten somwhat to ete.</L>
<L>Bote whanne &thorn;e&yogh; founde non,</L>
<L>Eue &thorn;o spak wi&thorn; pyte:</L>
<L>"Lord, me hongre&thorn; sore", quad she,<NOTE PLACE="foot">quad ist im Ms. stets durch qd bezeichnet.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Why, wile &yogh;e nowhy&thorn;er gon</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="55">To seken somwhat to oure fode,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at god, &thorn;e lord of gode,</L>
<L>Wile on vs take mercy</L>
<L>And &yogh;euen vs a&yogh;en &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&THORN;at we were ynne, &thorn;orgh his grace".</L>
<L N="60">Anon for&thorn; wenten hy</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ey&yogh;te dayes so&yogh;ten aboute,</L>
<L>Bote mete founde &thorn;e&yogh; non saundoute</L>
<L>Such as hy hadden byfore.</L>
<L>Anon to Adam Eue gan seye:</L>
<L N="65">"Sire, for honger y ne&yogh; deye,</L>
<L>Wolde god ded y wore!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;at god is wro&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Wel y wot it is for me".</L>
<L>Adam answerde &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="70">"His creature is gret, &amp; ay shel be;<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret = grit, earth.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wha&thorn;er it be for &thorn;e or me,</L>
<L>Sertis, y wot neuere".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eft seyde Eue wi&thorn; ruful chere:</L>
<L>"Lord, y praye &yogh;ow sle me here,</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;at god me namore se</L>
<L>Ne non angel in heuene aboue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at god for my loue</L>
<L>Namore be wro&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne seyde Adam wi&thorn; ruful ble:</L>
<L N="80">"Eue, let swiche wordis be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god vs eft no&yogh;t werye!</L>
<L>Eue, &thorn;ow were mad of me,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore in no wyse how it be</L>
<L>&THORN;e wile y no&yogh;t derye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="85">Bote rys, &amp; go we eft wi&thorn; mod</L>
<L>For to seken vs sum fod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne deye for mys!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; sou&yogh;ten aboute wi&thorn; sory mynde,</L>
<L>Bote swich my&yogh;te &thorn;e&yogh; nowher fynde</L>
<L N="90">As hy hadden in paradys,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote &thorn;er &thorn;e&yogh; founden such mete</L>
<L>As bestis and briddes ete.</L>
<L>Adam tolde Eue his &thorn;o&yogh;te:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is mete god &yogh;af bestis to.</L>
<L N="95">Go we sorwen &amp; nomen also<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nomen st. monen?</NOTE></L>
<L>In his si&yogh;t &thorn;at vs wro&yogh;te,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for oure trespas do penaunce,</L>
<L>Fourty dayes wi&thorn;outen distaunce,</L>
<L>And praye god, kyng of ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="100">&YOGH;if he vs wolde for&yogh;euen his mod</L>
<L>And granten vs som lyues fod,</L>
<L>Wherwi&thorn; we lyuen my&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us to Adam &thorn;o seide Eue:</L>
<L>"Tel me, lord, at wordis breue,</L>
<L N="105">What is penaunce to say?</L>
<L>And how mowe we penaunce do?</L>
<L>&THORN;at we namore byhoten him to</L>
<L>&THORN;an we fulfelle may:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In aunter &yogh;if oure god dere</L>
<L N="110">Wile no&yogh;t heren oure preyere</L>
<L>Bote turne his face fro vs,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at we oure penaunce breke".</L>
<L>&THORN;an anon gan Adam speke</L>
<L>And seide to Eue ri&yogh;t &thorn;us:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="115">"Fourty dayes &thorn;ow my&yogh;t do,</L>
<L>And y rede &thorn;ow do so,</L>
<L>For oure synnes sake,</L>
<L>And y fourty &amp; seuene wile fulfelle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god wile of his guod wille</L>
<L N="120">On vs eny mercy take:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For on &thorn;e seuende day god made ende,</L>
<L>Of his work guod and hende</L>
<L>He restyde him &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore rys and tak a ston,</L>
<L N="125">To Tygre flod gynne &thorn;ow gon,</L>
<L>And do as y &thorn;e say:
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="126"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vppon &thorn;at ston loke &thorn;at &thorn;ow stonde,</L>
<L>Vp to &thorn;e nekke in &thorn;e stronde,</L>
<L>Til fourty dayes don be,</L>
<L N="130">Of &thorn;y mouth let no word reke &mdash;</L>
<L>We be no&yogh;t wor&thorn;y to god to speke:</L>
<L>Oure lippes vnclene be,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;e&yogh; byten &thorn;e appel a&yogh;ens his steuene.</L>
<L>And y shel fourty dayes &amp; seuene</L>
<L N="135">Be in &thorn;e fflom Jordon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;it oure lord aboue &thorn;e sky</L>
<L>On vs wile haue eny mercy</L>
<L>For oure mochel mon".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eue &yogh;ede for&thorn; to Tygre flod,</L>
<L N="140">To don here penaunce wi&thorn; carful mod,</L>
<L>As Adam hadde here tauth;</L>
<L>And he him dede to Jordon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erynne stod oppon a ston,</L>
<L>&THORN;e water his nekke rauth.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">&THORN;e her of here heuedis &thorn;at was long</L>
<L>Spradde abrod on &thorn;e water strong &mdash;</L>
<L>Ruthe hadde ben to se.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seyde Adam to Jordon:</L>
<L>"Water, come &amp; make &thorn;y mon</L>
<L N="150">And waymente here wi&thorn; me!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gadere alle &thorn;e fisches &thorn;at in &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>And do hem come aboute me,</L>
<L>To helpen me make mone &mdash;</L>
<L>No&yogh;t for &yogh;ow, bote al for me:</L>
<L N="155">For neuere &yogh;ut seny&yogh;ede &yogh;e</L>
<L>Ne wra&thorn;&thorn;ede &yogh;oure god one,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;orgh no synne loste &yogh;oure fode;</L>
<L>Bote y sennede a&yogh;ens god in mode</L>
<L>And wrathede my lord so fre.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;erfore y bydde &yogh;ow alle in route</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e gaderen me aboute,</L>
<L>And sorwi&thorn; alle for me!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;orgh synne y loste my lyues fode".</L>
<L>&THORN;o alle &thorn;e fisches in &thorn;e flode</L>
<L N="165">Gadreden him aboute.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e flod no&yogh;t ne ran,</L>
<L>Bote stod stille &thorn;at tyme &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Sertis wi&thorn;outen doute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us stod Adam in al &thorn;at drede,</L>
<L N="170">Al hid in water, saue his hede,</L>
<L>And longe to god gan calle:</L>
<L>His voys wax hors, his cheke sor.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e bestis &thorn;at weren &thorn;or</L>
<L>For him sorweden alle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="175">&THORN;us seuentene dayes and more</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fisches sorweden &thorn;ore</L>
<L>And waymentide wi&thorn; Adam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel &thorn;erwi&thorn; hadde enuye,</L>
<L>And as an angel for&thorn; gan flye,</L>
<L N="180">To Tygre flod he cam</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;er Eue stod in water depe.</L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;e deuel se&yogh; here wepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan he wepen sore,</L>
<L>And seide to Eue anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="185">"Kom out of &thorn;e water tyt</L>
<L>And sese, &amp; sorwe namore!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For god ha&thorn; herd &yogh;oure sorwe ywis,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &yogh;ow acorded is</L>
<L>For &yogh;oure penaunces sake.</L>
<L N="190">O&thorn;ere angelis &amp; y preyede for &yogh;ow so<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ope st. o&thorn;ere verschrieben.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at god me bad to &yogh;ow go,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow out of &thorn;e water to take</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;euen &yogh;ow, &thorn;at &yogh;e hadde beforn,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure fode &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;orgh synne lorn:</L>
<L N="195">&THORN;us bad me god of my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore com out and go wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at place y lede &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &yogh;oure fode is dy&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eue wende wel it hadde ben so.</L>
<L N="200">Out of &thorn;e water she wente &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L>As gras hire body was grene.</L>
<L>For cold of &thorn;e water broun</L>
<L>Anon to &thorn;e erthe she fel adoun,</L>
<L>As ded she hadde bene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="205">So al a day she lay al mast.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel op tok here atte last.</L>
<L>To Adam she gan go,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e deuel wi&thorn; here ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whanne Adam of hem hadde a sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="210">Al wepynge criede he &thorn;o:
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="127"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A, Eue, what is &thorn;y chaunce?</L>
<L>Why hastow broken &thorn;y penaunce?</L>
<L>Why lete &thorn;ow him gyle &thorn;e so</L>
<L>&THORN;at made vs lese paradys</L>
<L N="215">And also alle &thorn;e ioyes &amp; blys</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay longe&thorn; &thorn;erto?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne &thorn;at Eue &thorn;o vnderstod</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was &thorn;e deuel wod</L>
<L>&THORN;at here fro &thorn;e water gan calle</L>
<L N="220">And hadde here gyled eft &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>Doun she flat here face to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nywede here sorwes alle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wepynges &amp; cares &thorn;o nywede hy.</L>
<L>Adam &thorn;o spak ful pitously:</L>
<L N="225">"A, deuel, wo &thorn;e be!</L>
<L>What eyle&thorn; &thorn;e so agayn vs meue,</L>
<L>And hast so twyes deseyued Eue,</L>
<L>Hire penaunce dedest here fle?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What euel haue we don &thorn;e to</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;at &thorn;ow vs dest so mochel wo,</L>
<L>Or what trespasede we ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e in word or dede,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er dede &thorn;e eny euel or quede</L>
<L>Or wi&thorn; dede o&thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="235">What eyle&thorn; &thorn;e a&yogh;ens vs?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e deuel answerde &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Adam, y &thorn;e telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o y was in heuene wi&thorn; angeles route,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fro ioye y was put oute,</L>
<L N="240">In to &thorn;e pyne of helle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And loste al my ioye and blis,</L>
<L>And in to &thorn;e pyne of helle ywis!</L>
<L>And al it was &thorn;orgh &thorn;e".</L>
<L>"&THORN;orgh me?" quad Adam, "how my&yogh;te it so?</L>
<L N="245">Sertis, y knew &thorn;e no&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L>How my&yogh;te it &thorn;anne &thorn;orgh me be?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or what dede y &thorn;at sholde &thorn;e dere?"</L>
<L>"Nau&yogh;t", seide &thorn;e deuel &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>"Bote &thorn;orgh &thorn;e &thorn;us it is:</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;at same day god made &thorn;e,</L>
<L>After his owene liknesse to be,</L>
<L>I loste al my blis:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o god hadde &yogh;eue &thorn;e lyf &amp; grace</L>
<L>And made &thorn;e lich his owene face,</L>
<L N="255">Mi&yogh;hel &thorn;o ledde &thorn;e</L>
<L>Beforn &thorn;e face of god almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow sholdest worschepen him ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o anon seide he:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo, y haue mad Adam</L>
<L N="260">Lich me, and &yogh;euen him nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;o wente Michel ful glad</L>
<L>And bad vs come, bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge &amp; age,</L>
<L>For to honuren godis ymage,</L>
<L>As god him selue bad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Mi&yogh;hel &yogh;ede him selue &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And worschypede &thorn;e wi&thorn; glade chere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne me he bysou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To gon &amp; worschipen godis ymage.</L>
<L>And y answerde as man in rage:</L>
<L N="270">Nay, &thorn;at owe y nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Michel me wolde haue conpelled &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>I sayde to him: "what wiltow do?"</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wordis grete &amp; grym,</L>
<L>"He is wors &thorn;an am y,</L>
<L N="275">&THORN;erfore y owe no&yogh;t, sikerly!</L>
<L>For to worscipen him:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I was &thorn;e ferste creature of gras,</L>
<L>And longe, er he, mad y was: &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us answerde y Mi&yogh;hel &mdash;</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;erfore he owi&thorn; wi&thorn; leme &amp; lym</L>
<L>Worschipen me, and y no&yogh;t hym,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it sholde be wel".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o alle &thorn;e angelis herden &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;at fellen wi&thorn; me out of blis,</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;e&yogh; wolde no&yogh;t worschipen &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ut bad me Michel wi&thorn; word od</L>
<L>Worschipen &thorn;e, or elles god</L>
<L>Wolde wrathen me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne seide y wi&thorn;outen oht:</L>
<L N="290">What, &thorn;e&yogh; god be wi&thorn; me wroht,</L>
<L>What fors shel it be?</L>
<L>I shel sette my place euene</L>
<L>Aboue &thorn;e sterres of &thorn;e heuene,</L>
<L>And ben as guod as he.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="128"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="295">God wax wroht wi&thorn; me in hast</L>
<L>And dede me, &amp; myne angeles, fast</L>
<L>Fro heuene to fallen &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;orghe &thorn;e we lorn oure blis</L>
<L>And oure mery dwellynge, ywis,</L>
<L N="300">And fellen doun in to wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne we were &thorn;us fro blesse rut</L>
<L>And &thorn;ow in &thorn;at blisse put,</L>
<L>&THORN;o hadde y to &thorn;e enuye</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow sholdest in &thorn;at blisse byde</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;at we losten for oure pryde.</L>
<L>&THORN;y womman &thorn;o temptide y</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To taken &thorn;e appel on &thorn;e treo</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwi&thorn; to gylen &thorn;eo &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;orghe here y dede</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at &thorn;ow fro blisse were put out,</L>
<L>As y aforhand was saun dout</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at mery stede".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne Adam hadde herd &thorn;e deuel &thorn;us told,</L>
<L>He wepte teres manyfold,</L>
<L N="315">And loude &thorn;us cride he:</L>
<L>"Al my ioye and my blis,</L>
<L>Lord god, in &thorn;yn hond is:</L>
<L>Help, &yogh;if &thorn;y wille be,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is deuel, myn aduersarie,</L>
<L N="320">Haue power no lenger me to tarie;</L>
<L>&THORN;at blisse a&yogh;en &yogh;if me</L>
<L>And teche me somwhat me to were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is fend namore me dere,</L>
<L>Lord, y praye &thorn;e!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="325">For he is abouten me to traye".</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e deuel vanschede awaye.</L>
<L>An angel &thorn;o cam fro heuene</L>
<L>And seide: "Adam", as god gan sende:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wilt fro &thorn;e deuel &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L N="330">Worsche after my steuene:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. worsche st. worche.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God bit &thorn;e wi&thorn; glade mod</L>
<L>Taken &thorn;e tende part of &thorn;y guod</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e nywe&thorn; by &yogh;ere &mdash;</L>
<L>Loke his wille &thorn;at &thorn;ow fulfil!</L>
<L N="335">Bere it to an he&yogh; hil,</L>
<L>And do it setten a fere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And lete it brenne wi&thorn;oute gref,</L>
<L>In to gret spyt and repref</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e deueles alle &mdash;</L>
<L N="340">As &thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;e tende ordre were</L>
<L>In heuene wi&thorn; oure lord dere,</L>
<L>Til synne made hem to falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wilt &thorn;us tyden wel,</L>
<L>&thorn;ow my&yogh;t &thorn;e kepen fro &thorn;e deuel"</L>
<L N="345">&THORN;e angel &thorn;o wente him fro.</L>
<L>Adam stod stille in his penaunce</L>
<L>Fourty dayes, wi&thorn;outen destaunce,</L>
<L>And seuene dayes &yogh;ut mo,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al wey in &thorn;e water Jordon.</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;anne seide Eue to him anon:</L>
<L>"Adam, leue now &yogh;e!</L>
<L>For no&thorn;er &thorn;e ferste tyme ne now</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel my&yogh;te no&yogh;t gylen &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>Bote ay deseyuede me;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="355">In herte y was no&yogh;t stedefast,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er ferste tyme ne last,</L>
<L>Bote brak my godis lore.</L>
<L>I am wel wor&thorn;y for to deye:</L>
<L>Sle me, Adam, y &yogh;ow preye,</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at god se me namore!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Or hyde me fro godis si&yogh;t!</L>
<L>I am no&yogh;t wor&thorn;y wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>To dwellen here, y seye.</L>
<L>Bote in &thorn;e west y wil go wone</L>
<L N="365">At &thorn;e goynge doun of &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L>Alone, til y deye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche dede hire for&thorn; in to &thorn;e west,</L>
<L>Euere sorwynge wi&thorn;outen rest,</L>
<L>Wepynge euen &amp; morn</L>
<L N="370">In here dwellynge &thorn;at was wyld,</L>
<L>And hadde in here wombe conseyued a child</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;re monthes aforn.
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="129"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in here herte &thorn;o &thorn;o&yogh;te hy</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel hadde here gyled twy &mdash;</L>
<L N="375">So badde was here grace &mdash;</L>
<L>And wax ashamed, as sei&thorn; &thorn;is rym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at she dorste neuere after &thorn;at tym</L>
<L>Loken Adam in &thorn;e face.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for hy ne dorste his face yse,</L>
<L N="380">A whyt veyl &thorn;o tok she</L>
<L>And heng aforn hire eye. &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e skele wi&thorn;oute dred</L>
<L>&THORN;at wymen keuercheres on here hed</L>
<L>Weren, wi&thorn;oute lye. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Whanne tyme kom of here peynes smerte,</L>
<L>She cride loude wi&thorn; voys and herte:</L>
<L>"God, to &thorn;e y mone,</L>
<L>Dere lord, haue mercy on me!</L>
<L>Help, god, &yogh;if &thorn;y wille be,</L>
<L N="390">Me &thorn;at am alone!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euere she cride wi&thorn; ruly chere.</L>
<L>Bote god nolde here yhere</L>
<L>Ne sente hire non helpe.</L>
<L>"Allas, she sayde in here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="395">I se &thorn;at it avayle&thorn; me nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at y crie &amp; &yogh;elpe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lord! &thorn;o&yogh;te she in herte and word,</L>
<L>Who shel tellen Adam, my lord,</L>
<L>Of my sorwe and care?</L>
<L N="400">"I praye &yogh;ow, li&yogh;t of firmament,</L>
<L>Sonne &amp; mone, wi&thorn; guod entent,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e eastward whanne &yogh;e fare,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Telle&thorn; Adam, my lord dere,</L>
<L>How y am stad in sorwes here!"</L>
<L N="405">&THORN;e eyr bar it for&thorn; anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorwe &thorn;at she &thorn;ere gan mene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Adam in &thorn;e east, y wene,</L>
<L>Herde al here mochel mon,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide &thorn;us wi&thorn;oute wrake:</L>
<L N="410">"Al &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;at Eue gynne&thorn; make</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at y wel here.</L>
<L>In hap &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel dere hire nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For to drawen fro god hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I wil go visiten hire &thorn;ere".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="415">Adam &yogh;ede to hire &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>And fond hire liggynge on &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Makynge sorwe &amp; del.</L>
<L>Whanne hy him herde, &thorn;us seide sche:</L>
<L>"Sythen Adam, my lord, say me,</L>
<L N="420">Myn herte is refresched wel.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lord Adam, quad sche, for loue</L>
<L>Prey for me to god aboue</L>
<L>He helpe me of my wo!"</L>
<L>So Adam preyede for hire him selue,</L>
<L N="425">&THORN;at &thorn;er kome angeles twelue</L>
<L>And stoden aboute hire &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Some on &thorn;e left halue, some on ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And Michel &thorn;e archangel in &thorn;at si&yogh;t</L>
<L>On here ri&yogh;t side stod he,</L>
<L N="430">And touchede here face to &thorn;e brest,</L>
<L>And to here he seide ful prest:</L>
<L>"Now, Eue, yblessed &thorn;ow be,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For loue of Adam, &thorn;y lord:</L>
<L>For god of heuene herde his word &mdash;</L>
<L N="435">His preyere to god was mylde.</L>
<L>&THORN;orghe his preyere we ben her kome,</L>
<L>Angeles, to helpe &thorn;e, alle and some.</L>
<L>Rys &amp; grey&thorn;e &thorn;e to chylde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eue di&yogh;te here to childyng.</L>
<L N="440">And &thorn;o &thorn;e child, wi&thorn;oute lesyng,</L>
<L>Anon was fallen here fro,</L>
<L>Op he sterte in &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>And &yogh;ede &amp; gaderede floures on grounde</L>
<L>And bar his moder &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="445">&THORN;us he pleyde wi&thorn; his dame.</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; callede him Kaym to his name &mdash;</L>
<L>Bote sethen he wro&yogh;te care.</L>
<L>Adam &thorn;o ledde wi&thorn;outen stryf</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e his sone &amp; his wyf</L>
<L N="450">To &thorn;e east, to dwellen &thorn;are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o sente god Mi&yogh;hel</L>
<L>To techen Adam to labouren wel,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to diche and delue</L>
<L>And sowe sedes on erthe to growe,</L>
<L>For to fynden hem mete ynowe,</L>
<L N="455">His children &amp; him selue;
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="130"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He tau&yogh;te hem trauayle for here mete,</L>
<L>How &thorn;e&yogh; my&yogh;te hem frutes gete</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swet &amp; swynkynge sore &mdash;</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;us bad &thorn;e angel to Adam,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e frut &thorn;at after him cam</L>
<L>So sholde &thorn;e&yogh; euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eft trauaylede Eue &mdash; and ferde wel;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at child &thorn;e&yogh; namede Abel</L>
<L N="465">To his ri&yogh;te name.</L>
<L>&THORN;us in writ y haue it sayn</L>
<L>&THORN;at Abel and his bro&thorn;er Kaym</L>
<L>Dwellede togydere in same.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Adam &thorn;anne &thorn;us seyde Eue:</L>
<L N="470">"Sire, she seyde, &yogh;e mowe me leue,</L>
<L>Slepynge y say a sy&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Me &thorn;o&yogh;te Kaym tok Abellis blod</L>
<L>And sop it op as he were wod".</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide Adam ful ry&yogh;t:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="475">"I drede me he shel him sle.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sondred shel &thorn;e&yogh; be</L>
<L>For drede of after clap".</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; maden Kaym a tylman,</L>
<L>And Abel a schepherde &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="480">Bote such &yogh;ut was here hap</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at Kaym for his false tidynge &mdash;</L>
<L>For he ty&thorn;ede of &thorn;e worste &thorn;ynge,</L>
<L>And Abel of his beste &mdash;</L>
<L>For wrathe &thorn;o Kaym wax ner wod,</L>
<L N="485">For to spillen his bro&thorn;eres blod,</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e Abel he &thorn;reste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whanne he deyde, he &yogh;ede to helle,</L>
<L>Euermore &thorn;er to dwelle,</L>
<L>For his false ty&thorn;ynge. &mdash;</L>
<L N="490">&THORN;erfore wel to tenden bu&thorn; lef,</L>
<L>Or elles &yogh;ow falle&thorn; a gret myschef</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure laste endynge. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;anne Adam, &yogh;e mowe me leue,</L>
<L>An hondred wynter knew no&yogh;t Eue</L>
<L N="495">Flesliche for &thorn;is stryf.</L>
<L>Tyl an angel kom fro heuene</L>
<L>And bad Adam in his steuene</L>
<L>Eft gon knowen his wyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne &yogh;ede Adam and knew his wyf:</L>
<L N="500">Ano&thorn;er child &thorn;e&yogh; bro&yogh;te for&thorn; blyf.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne Adam to Eue gan sayn:</L>
<L>"He shel hote Seth, so wile we;</L>
<L>In stede of Abel shel he be</L>
<L>&THORN;at Kaym, his bro&thorn;er, ha&thorn; slayn".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">&YOGH;ut after he gat &thorn;retty sones mo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;retty dou&yogh;tres and two,</L>
<L>&THORN;us in writ fynde y.</L>
<L>Many a &yogh;er &thorn;us leuede he &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And hem &thorn;e&yogh; norscheden &amp; bro&yogh;ten for&thorn; mo,</L>
<L N="510">&THORN;e worlde to multiply.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e tyme Adam sholde deye,</L>
<L>He spak to Eue, as y &yogh;ow seye,</L>
<L>Meke wordis and bonere:</L>
<L>"Let gaderen alle myne children hider,</L>
<L N="515">My sones &amp; dou&yogh;tres alle togyder,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y mowe se hem here!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I shel sone deye, as y gesse,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore ferst y wolde hem blesse:</L>
<L>&THORN;e betere my&yogh;te &thorn;e&yogh; be".</L>
<L N="520">Sone &thorn;e&yogh; come alle &thorn;yder ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Alle byfore here faderes si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In &thorn;re partyes stoden he,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Byforn &thorn;ere Adam began to preye</L>
<L>To god &thorn;at sit in heuene heye.</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;e&yogh; criden alle in &thorn;at stede:</L>
<L>"Fader", &thorn;e&yogh; seyden, "what eyle&thorn; &thorn;e?</L>
<L>Why hastow called vs &thorn;e to se?</L>
<L>Why lystow in &thorn;y bede?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Adam answerde to hem &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="530">"A, children, me is ful wo</L>
<L>Of siknesse &thorn;at y haue".</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e&yogh; alle, as y gesse,</L>
<L>For to wyten what was siknesse</L>
<L>Faste on him gonne craue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="535">"Fader", quad Seth, "y trowe wel</L>
<L>&thorn;ow desyre to ete sum del</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e frut of paradys</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow of ete som tyme: for soth,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore y leue wi&thorn;outen oth</L>
<L N="540">Sike here &thorn;at &thorn;ow lys.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="131"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tel me &thorn;erfore wi&thorn;outen mo</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wilt y &thorn;uder go</L>
<L>And preye god wi&thorn; wille;</L>
<L>&THORN;us y wile do, &yogh;if &thorn;ow rede,</L>
<L N="545">And casten doust on myn hede,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e &yogh;atis lyn stille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Til &thorn;at god of his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wil me by his angel bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Senden &thorn;erof, y gesse".</L>
<L N="550">"I desyre it no&yogh;t", quad Adam &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"Bote in my body fro top to to</L>
<L>I haue gret siknesse".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne seide Seth wi&thorn;outen lye:</L>
<L>"I not what siknesse is, sikerlye!</L>
<L N="555">Why, wile &yogh;e vs no&yogh;t telle?"</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide Adam: "my children dere,</L>
<L>Lestene&thorn; alle, and y shel here</L>
<L>Tellen wi&thorn;oute dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne god made &yogh;oure moder &amp; me</L>
<L N="560">And putte vs in paradys for to be,</L>
<L>And bad vs wi&thorn; word &amp; &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e frutes taken oure fille:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tre of wit of guod and ille</L>
<L>He bad vs taken ri&yogh;t no&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="565">&THORN;at in myddes of paradys stod &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us he bad vs for oure guod,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we hadden had gras &mdash;</L>
<L>And &yogh;af me my&yogh;t of nor&thorn; and est,</L>
<L>And &yogh;oure moder, wi&thorn; south &amp; west,</L>
<L N="570">To don what oure wille was,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And, vs to kepen, angeles two.</L>
<L>Bote, whanne &thorn;e tyme was komen &thorn;o</L>
<L>Fro vs &thorn;at &thorn;e&yogh; moste wende,</L>
<L>For to honuren here god of my&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="575">&THORN;o &thorn;e deuel anon ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Kam &thorn;uder vs to schende,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;oure moder so temptide he</L>
<L>To taken an appel of &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>And faste &thorn;eron sche gnew,</L>
<L N="580">And cam &amp; bro&yogh;te ano&thorn;er mete.</L>
<L>And whanne y hadde &thorn;erof also eten,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. eten &thorn;erof also.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone changede oure hew.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God wax wro&thorn; wi&thorn; vs wel tyt,</L>
<L>And seide to me anon ryt:</L>
<L N="585">Adam, for &thorn;y trespas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow hast don &thorn;at y forbed</L>
<L>And wro&yogh;t after &thorn;y wyues red,</L>
<L>&THORN;is ioye lost &thorn;ow has,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to &thorn;y body also y dresse<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ospringe st. ofspringe, so auch V. 829.</NOTE></L>
<L N="590">Sixty and two dyuerse siknesse</L>
<L>For &thorn;y trespasynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to greuen wi&thorn; sorwe and wo,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e top to &thorn;e to,</L>
<L>And after alle &thorn;yne ospringe,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="595">In to alle &thorn;yne membres y hem prest,</L>
<L>Hed and armes, body and brest.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seide oure lord on hy".</L>
<L>Whanne Adam hadde &thorn;us told hem alle,</L>
<L>Loude he gan to crie and calle</L>
<L N="600">For his grete malady,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide: "a, what shel y do?</L>
<L>So mochel siknesse come&thorn; me to,</L>
<L>Al my body to dere!"</L>
<L>Whanne Eue herde him so cry,</L>
<L N="605">Sore sche wepte, sikerly,</L>
<L>And seide to god ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Lord god of ri&yogh;twysnesse,</L>
<L>Let me al &thorn;is siknesse,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e trespas was myn!</L>
<L N="610">"Adam, sche seide, y praye &thorn;e</L>
<L>Of &thorn;y siknesse parte wi&thorn; me,</L>
<L>Let me haue sum of &thorn;y pyn!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;orghe me &thorn;ow hast &thorn;is ille".</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide Adam Eue tille:</L>
<L N="615">"Rys, &amp; tak Seth wi&thorn; &thorn;e!</L>
<L>Poudere on &yogh;oure heuedes &yogh;e do &mdash;</L>
<L>Signe of meknesse it longe&thorn; to &mdash;</L>
<L>To paradys gatis go &yogh;e!
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="132"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And, Seth, sone wi&thorn;oute drede</L>
<L N="620">A grene wey shel &thorn;e &thorn;uder lede,</L>
<L>And steppes sere of hew &mdash;</L>
<L>For whanne we breken godis komande|ment,</L>
<L>Oure synne was so gret, &thorn;at, &thorn;er we went,</L>
<L>Neuere after gras ne grew.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="625">Sorwi&thorn; &thorn;ere wi&thorn; herte and word,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at in aunter god, oure lord,</L>
<L>For ruthe of &yogh;ow haue mynde</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e tre of mercy blyf,</L>
<L>Where out renne&thorn; oyle of lyf,</L>
<L N="630">His angel wil doun sende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of oyle taken &yogh;ow som del,</L>
<L>Wherwi&thorn; &yogh;e mowen oynten me wel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at my siknesse mow slake</L>
<L>Wherynne y am now sore ybounde".</L>
<L N="635">Bo&thorn;e Eue and Seth &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>&YOGH;eden for&thorn; for his sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And as &thorn;e&yogh; &yogh;eden to paradys ward,</L>
<L>By &thorn;e weye it fel hem hard:</L>
<L>An addre to hem gan lepe</L>
<L N="640">And al to-bot Seth in &thorn;e face.</L>
<L>For sorwe Eue waylede hire grdce</L>
<L>And pytously gan wepe:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Wo is me wrecche in &thorn;is sel!</L>
<L>I am corsed, y wot wel,</L>
<L N="645">And alle &thorn;at breken godis heste;</L>
<L>Ful y am of kare and wo".</L>
<L>To &thorn;e addre seide she &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Sey, &thorn;ow cursede beste!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>How were &thorn;ow so hardy here,</L>
<L N="650">Or how were &thorn;ow of such powere,</L>
<L>Godis liknesse to dere,</L>
<L>For to byten him such a wounde?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e addere &thorn;us in &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>To Eue answerde &thorn;ere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="655">"Wenestow no&yogh;t", he seide, "Eue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god &thorn;erto &yogh;af vs leue</L>
<L>To noyen &yogh;ow fable,</L>
<L>And alle oure malis he sterede to &yogh;ow?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>mal</ABBR>; der Strich &uuml;ber l kann hier, wie in <ABBR>angel</ABBR> plur. 190. 283. 874. 877. 1130, karnel 800. 806. 893, <ABBR>Abell</ABBR> gen. 472, wol nur <I>is</I> bezeichnen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote o &thorn;yng, Eue, telle me now:</L>
<L N="660">How my&yogh;te &thorn;y mouth be able</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To eten of &thorn;e frut of &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at god forbed Adam and &thorn;e</L>
<L>Vp peryl for to spille?</L>
<L>&THORN;o hadde we no powere</L>
<L N="665">To deren &yogh;ow for neuere.</L>
<L>Sethe &yogh;e broken his wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a&yogh;en his biddynge fre</L>
<L>Eten &thorn;e appel of &thorn;e tre:</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t &thorn;o, as y gesse,</L>
<L N="670">Whanne &yogh;e hadde &thorn;us eten &yogh;oure ban,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ow to deren oure power gan</L>
<L>And oure hardynesse".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne seide Seth to &thorn;at qued:</L>
<L>"God blame &thorn;e for &thorn;at ded</L>
<L N="675">&THORN;at &thorn;ow hast &thorn;us byten me!</L>
<L>Parte awey out of oure si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Fro me, ymage of god almy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;erne y bidde &thorn;e fle!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Schet &thorn;y mouth &amp; spek namore</L>
<L N="680">And gref his liknesse no&yogh;t so sore,</L>
<L>Til god eft grante it &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>&THORN;anne spak &thorn;e addre as a qued:</L>
<L>"I wil don as &thorn;ow me bed:</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e now gynne y te"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="685">And vanschede out of here si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And Eue and Seth &yogh;eden ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>For&thorn; to paradys &yogh;ate:</L>
<L>And fellen on here knees bare</L>
<L>And sy&yogh;heden and wepten sare,</L>
<L N="690">Whanne &thorn;e&yogh; come &thorn;erate,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And preyden god, hei&yogh;est of nam,</L>
<L>To haue mercy on Adam,</L>
<L>Sik in leme and lyth,</L>
<L>And hem senden his angel fro hy</L>
<L N="695">To &yogh;euen hem of &thorn;e tre of mercy</L>
<L>Oyle, to helen him wyth,
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As god byhet him longe er &thorn;at.</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e&yogh; in here preyeres sat,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;hel aperede &thorn;an</L>
<L N="700">And seide: "Seth, what sechest &thorn;ow here?</L>
<L>I am Michel, &thorn;e angel dere,</L>
<L>Ordeyned abouen man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wep namore, &thorn;us rede y,</L>
<L>For oyle of &thorn;e tre of mercy,</L>
<L N="705">To anoynten &thorn;y fader Adam</L>
<L>For &thorn;e siknesse &thorn;at he is in,</L>
<L>For &thorn;erof shelt &thorn;ow no&yogh;t wyn &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e to tellen y kam;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &yogh;ow &thorn;erof god wil non sende</L>
<L N="710">Til in &thorn;e laste dayes ende</L>
<L>&THORN;at fyue &thorn;ousand &yogh;er ben past</L>
<L>And fyue hondred &yogh;ut &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>Bote to paradys &yogh;ate &thorn;ow go</L>
<L>And loke in &thorn;er in hast!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="715">Seth &thorn;o &yogh;ede to paradis &yogh;ate</L>
<L>And putte in his heued &thorn;erate:</L>
<L>And se&yogh; merthis ynowe:</L>
<L>Of alle manere men my&yogh;te descrie</L>
<L>&THORN;enken wi&thorn; herte, sen wi&thorn; eye,</L>
<L N="720">And briddes syngynge on bowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;ut more, as y &yogh;ow telle:</L>
<L>In myddes of paradys a welle,</L>
<L>Foure stremes rennynge &thorn;er fro &mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;o foure stremes clere</L>
<L N="725">Kome&thorn; al &thorn;e water &thorn;at is here.</L>
<L>More &yogh;ut se&yogh; he &thorn;o:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vp by &thorn;e welle stonden he se&yogh;</L>
<L>A mochel treo and an he&yogh;,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; bowes grete &amp; stark;</L>
<L N="730">&THORN;o in &thorn;ou&yogh;t wondrede he</L>
<L>For &thorn;er was oppon &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>No &thorn;er leues ne bark.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As he stod &amp; wondrede &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>He &thorn;o&yogh;te on &thorn;e steppis sere:</L>
<L N="735">Anon he sikede sare,</L>
<L>And to him &thorn;is &thorn;o&yogh;t kam</L>
<L>&THORN;at for Eue synne, &amp; Adam,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tre was so bare,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;eron wi&thorn;oute wane</L>
<L N="740">Adam and Eue eten here bane.</L>
<L>A&yogh;en he wente &thorn;e angel to;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he had se&yogh;e in si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his tonge anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>He tolde &thorn;e angel &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="745">&THORN;e angel him bad wi&thorn;outen lye</L>
<L>Eft gon loken what he seye.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &yogh;ede he &amp; lokede more:</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e bare tre he se&yogh; wounde</L>
<L>An hydous addre in &thorn;at stounde &mdash;</L>
<L N="750">&THORN;erof he dradde him sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And al &thorn;e angel he gan tel.</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel &thorn;o bad him wi&thorn;oute dwel</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde tyme ful ryue</L>
<L>At &thorn;e &yogh;atis in to loke.</L>
<L N="755">And for&thorn; he wente, as sei&thorn; &thorn;is boke,</L>
<L>And lokede in ful blyue:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at same bare tre he se&yogh;</L>
<L>Woxsen, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, to heuene an he&yogh; &mdash;</L>
<L>He wondrede of &thorn;at sy&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L N="760">And in &thorn;e hey&yogh;este crop of &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>A &yogh;ong child lyn se&yogh; he,</L>
<L>As it hadde be bore &thorn;at ny&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e swa&thorn;yng cloutis wounde;</L>
<L>&THORN;o lokede he dounward to &thorn;e grounde:</L>
<L N="765">And se&yogh; &thorn;e rote ful ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Lasten doun, as y &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e depe put of helle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he se&yogh; ful tyth</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His bro&thorn;eres soule, Abel.</L>
<L N="770">&THORN;o wente he a&yogh;en in &thorn;at sel</L>
<L>And tolde Mi&yogh;hel his cas,</L>
<L>What he se&yogh; aboue and doun.</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel anon gan it expoun</L>
<L>And tolde him what it was:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="775">"&THORN;at child &thorn;ow se&yogh;e in &thorn;e crop of &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Godis sone of heuene is he</L>
<L>&THORN;at wepe&thorn; &amp; make&thorn; gret mon</L>
<L>For &thorn;e synne &mdash; wiltow leue? &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Adam &amp; &thorn;y moder Eue</L>
<L N="780">A&yogh;ens him hauen don,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="134"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he shel wypen awey &thorn;at gelt,</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;at tyme is fulfelt</L>
<L>&THORN;at y beforn tolde here:</L>
<L>He is &thorn;at oyle of mercy</L>
<L N="785">&THORN;at god byhot sikerly</L>
<L>Adam, &thorn;y fader dere,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he is &thorn;at best louede godis sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at shel kome on erthe to wone</L>
<L>And, bapty&yogh;ed in fflom Jordon,</L>
<L N="790">Alle &thorn;at ben cristene, sikerly,</L>
<L>He shel wi&thorn; oyle of mercy</L>
<L>Anoynten hem euerychon;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He shel fordon &thorn;e fendis my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And leden &thorn;y fader to blesse bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="795">Whanne tyme come&thorn; &thorn;erto".</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e angel hadde &thorn;us told byfore,</L>
<L>He tok his leue wi&thorn;outen more,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en to his fader to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote ferst &thorn;at angel &yogh;af him &thorn;re</L>
<L N="800">Karnelis of &thorn;at appel-tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at his fader hadde of byte,</L>
<L>And seyde: "wi&thorn;ynne &thorn;is &thorn;ridde day</L>
<L>&THORN;y fader shel deyen wi&thorn;outen nay,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ow shelt wel wyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="805">Whanne he is ded and buried shel be,</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;ese karnelis alle &thorn;re</L>
<L>And in his mou&thorn; do hem lay!</L>
<L>And sone after &thorn;ow shelt se</L>
<L>How &thorn;e&yogh; sholle springen alle &thorn;re.</L>
<L N="810">And &yogh;ut y can &thorn;e say:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e frut &thorn;at shel hongen on &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure alder leche shel he be</L>
<L>And hele &yogh;oure fader fro wo,</L>
<L>And shel delyuere fro siknesse</L>
<L N="815">Him and many mo, y gesse,</L>
<L>To ioye wi&thorn; him to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whanne &yogh;oure fader deyth, saunfayle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e shollen se gret meruaille</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e li&yogh;tis of &thorn;e firmament".</L>
<L N="820">Whanne he hadde told him &thorn;us wordes breue,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he and his moder Eue</L>
<L>Homward faste &thorn;e&yogh; went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne &thorn;e&yogh; were to Adam kome,</L>
<L>Eue &thorn;o tolde him al &amp; some</L>
<L N="825">How &thorn;e addere hadde Seth byte.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide Adam to his wyf:</L>
<L>"Lo, Eue, what sorwe and stryf</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh &thorn;e to vs is smyte,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To vs &amp; to alle oure ospringe!</L>
<L N="830">&THORN;erfore, Eue, oppon alle &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Tel alle &thorn;y children tille,</L>
<L>Whanne y am ded, what sorwe &amp; kare</L>
<L>We haue had &amp; &yogh;ut shel mare</L>
<L>For oure dedis ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="835">And hy &thorn;at comen after vs, y wene,</L>
<L>Shullen haue mochel anger &amp; tene</L>
<L>For synne &thorn;at we haue do,</L>
<L>And willen vs curse, whanne hem gynne&thorn; greue,</L>
<L>And seyn: Adam, oure fader, and Eue</L>
<L N="840">Al &thorn;is shopen vs to".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne Eue herde Adam &thorn;us telle,</L>
<L>She wep sore wi&thorn;outen dwelle,</L>
<L>For care hire herte wax cold.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Seth aforn his fader gan cum</L>
<L N="845">And tolde Adam alle and sum</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e angel hadde him told.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne Adam hadde it herd al sayn,</L>
<L>He lawe&thorn; lowde: so he was fayn,</L>
<L>For alle his grete mones,</L>
<L N="850">And seyde: "lord, y &thorn;anke &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at y may fynden glad to be</L>
<L>In al my lyf tyme ones!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now is my lyf long ynou&yogh;:</L>
<L>God, take my soule to &yogh;ow,</L>
<L N="855">&THORN;at art of my&yogh;t most,</L>
<L>For y haue leued in &thorn;is world here</L>
<L>Neghe hondred &amp; &thorn;retty &yogh;ere".</L>
<L>&THORN;o &yogh;af he op his gost:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us deyde he anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="860">&THORN;e mone &amp; &thorn;e sonne losten here li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And seuene dayes shone namore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Eue and Seth his body beclepte,</L>
<L>And for him faste &thorn;e&yogh; wepte</L>
<L>And waymenteden ri&yogh;t sore.
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="865">And as &thorn;e&yogh; &thorn;us maden here mon,</L>
<L>An angel perede to hem anon</L>
<L>At Adames heued ful ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And seyde: "rys, Seth, y bidde &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And kome hider &amp; stond by me</L>
<L N="870">And se what god of my&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ordeyne&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;y fader to do!"</L>
<L>And (Seth) anon op ros &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Seth fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>To don as he bad:</L>
<L>And se&yogh; manye angelis make gret sere,</L>
<L N="875">Syngynge &amp; trompynge wi&thorn; glad chere &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan Seth wexen glad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e angelis alle criden wi&thorn; o steuene:</L>
<L>"Blessed be &thorn;ow, lord of heuene,</L>
<L>For loue of Adam, &thorn;y man,</L>
<L N="880">&THORN;at &thorn;ow on him wilt haue mercy!"</L>
<L>Seth se&yogh; god &thorn;o, sikerly,</L>
<L>His faderes soule take &thorn;an</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And tok Mi&yogh;hel, &thorn;e angel bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And seyde: "kep me &thorn;is soule ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="885">In peynes, wi&thorn;outen mys,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e laste dayes ben falle</L>
<L>&THORN;at y shel his sorwes alle</L>
<L>Turnen in to blys:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne shel he sitten wi&thorn; herte glad</L>
<L N="890">In his trone &thorn;at him mad".</L>
<L>Seth tok his faderes body</L>
<L>And beriede it in &thorn;e vale of Ebron,</L>
<L>And putte &thorn;o &thorn;re karnel(<I>is</I>) anon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. karnel, sonst (800. 806. 956) <ABBR>karnel</ABBR>.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his mouth witterly,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="895">Vnder his tonge he hem frauth,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e angel hadde him tauth.</L>
<L>&THORN;o sixe dayes were gon,</L>
<L>Eue to Seth &thorn;us gan seye:</L>
<L>"Tak &amp; make tables tweye</L>
<L N="900">Of al oure lyf anon,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tweye of erthe &amp; tweye of ston,</L>
<L>Writ &thorn;eron oure lyf anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at we haue had here!</L>
<L>For longe er domesday falle</L>
<L N="905">&THORN;is worlde shel ben fordon alle,</L>
<L>By water or by fere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;if it be by water fordon,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne shollen &thorn;e tables of ston</L>
<L>Lasten, wi&thorn;outen lye;</L>
<L N="910">&YOGH;if it &thorn;orghe fer be bro&yogh;t to nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne sholle &thorn;e tables of erthe wro&yogh;t</L>
<L>Lasten sikerlye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne she hadde al &thorn;us told,</L>
<L>Doun she knelede wi&thorn; herte cold</L>
<L N="915">And op here hondis hild,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us to god cride she:</L>
<L>"Lord, haue mercy on me!"</L>
<L>Anon here gost she &yogh;ild.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o, as here sones &amp; dou&yogh;tres echon</L>
<L N="920">For here sorwede &amp; makede mon,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;hel to hem kam &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>And seide: "loke no lengere, Seth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. seth = sethen?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an sixe dayes for hire deth</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e sorwe namore!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="925">For &thorn;e seuende day, wi&thorn;oute lesynge,</L>
<L>Is tokne of a&yogh;en risynge,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e seuende day also</L>
<L>God restide wi&thorn; body and &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of alle workes &thorn;at he wro&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="930">&THORN;erfore y bidde &yogh;ow so do".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o wro&yogh;te Seth his moderes wil:</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tables gan fulfil</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; dede &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Salamon, &thorn;e wyse man,</L>
<L N="935">Fond &thorn;e tables longe after &thorn;an.</L>
<L>As he god bysou&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To schewen him wi&thorn;outen mys</L>
<L>What bytokne&thorn; &thorn;e tablys,</L>
<L>Or who &thorn;at hem sou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>God &thorn;o sente him his angel</L>
<L N="940">And tolde him al fayre &amp; wel</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e&yogh; were wro&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="136"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And what tokne &thorn;at it was.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o archilaykas</L>
<L N="945">Salamon dede hem calle &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is to sayn: wi&thorn;oute trauaylle</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;outen wit saunfayle</L>
<L>Seth wrot hem alle:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For an angel held his hond ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="950">Of godis komynge &thorn;us spak he tyt:</L>
<L>"Lo, god shel come, quad he,</L>
<L>In his wonderful dremes of drede,</L>
<L>And shel redressen mannes nede</L>
<L>In ri&yogh;t and in leute.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="955">Of &thorn;is matere now lete we be,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e karnelis speke we</L>
<L>In Adames mouth &thorn;at were set.</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; woxen alle &thorn;re wi&thorn;outen wrong</L>
<L>Ech of an elne long</L>
<L N="960">Sone wi&thorn;outen let;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;e&yogh; stoden in erthe &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Al most two &thorn;ousand &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And woxen no&thorn;er more ne les,</L>
<L>Bote al wey stoden liche grene.</L>
<L N="965">Whanne Moyses fond hem &thorn;er bydene,</L>
<L>&THORN;us seide he, as y ges:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ese &yogh;erdis alle &thorn;re</L>
<L>Tokne&thorn; &thorn;e holy trenite"</L>
<L>&THORN;us propheciede he his steuene.</L>
<L N="970">And whanne &thorn;e&yogh; sholden hem drawen out,</L>
<L>It wax so swete hem about:</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; wende &thorn;e&yogh; hadde ben in heuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o was Moyses glad, y wene,</L>
<L>And wond hem in a clo&thorn; ful clene,</L>
<L N="975">And wi&thorn; him for&thorn; were bro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And c &thorn;e &yogh;erdes, whyle he wonede &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>In wildernesse foure &amp; fourty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Many meracles he wro&yogh;t:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who so were sik, as sey&thorn; &thorn;is geste,</L>
<L N="980">Or venympd wi&thorn; eny wikked beste,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;erdis he moste kis:</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne he wax hol anon.</L>
<L>And sethen out of &thorn;e flynt-ston</L>
<L>Moyses dede ywis</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="985">Water out rennen &thorn;orghe here vertew.</L>
<L>And whanne Moyses, y telle &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>Wiste &thorn;orghe godis sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sholde deye, &thorn;o wente he</L>
<L>To Thabor helle, and &thorn;e &yogh;erdis &thorn;re</L>
<L N="990">He sette in erthe to stonde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And made &thorn;ere his graue in grounde,</L>
<L>And wente &thorn;uder &amp; deyde &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>So stoden &thorn;e &yogh;erdis stille</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &yogh;er, til Dauid kynge</L>
<L N="995">Reynede in Jude wi&thorn;oute lesyng:</L>
<L>As it was godis wille,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An angel him bad wi&thorn;oute lye:</L>
<L>"Dauid, go to Arabye</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mount Thabor blyue</L>
<L N="1000">And bringe to Jer(usa)lem wi&thorn;oute les</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;re &yogh;erdes &thorn;at Moyses</L>
<L>Sette &thorn;ere by his lyue!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;orghe hem god wile help sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;orghe a crois, to mankende".</L>
<L N="1005">Dauid &thorn;o dwelde nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;e neghende day &thorn;ere was he,</L>
<L>And drow op &thorn;e &yogh;erdis &thorn;re,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e angel hadde him tou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swich swete sauour &thorn;o gonne &thorn;e&yogh; fele:</L>
<L N="1010">&THORN;at &thorn;e &yogh;erdis were holy &thorn;e&yogh; wisten wele.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cride Dauid wi&thorn; voys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;orghe prophecie sai&thorn; ri&yogh;t &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is day is helthe &yogh;euen to vs</L>
<L>&THORN;orgh vertew of &thorn;e crois".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1015">&THORN;o wente he hom wi&thorn;outen let</L>
<L>And &thorn;o&yogh;te where he my&yogh;te hem set.</L>
<L>In a cisterne he let hem reste</L>
<L>For to ben fresch al &thorn;at ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he my&yogh;te on morwe tyt</L>
<L N="1020">Setten hem where him leste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &thorn;e morwen he ros erly,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cisterne he gan him hy:</L>
<L>And fond hem alle &thorn;re</L>
<L>Woxen in to on &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L N="1025">And rote fast in &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof meruaylede he.
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for &thorn;e meracle &thorn;at &thorn;er was wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>He wolde hem remeuye nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For god bad roten hem &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="1030">Bote &thorn;ere it stod and wax op ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Gret &amp; long, &thorn;orgh godis my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t ful &thorn;retty &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For Dauid wolde wyte wi&thorn; herte triwe</L>
<L>How mochel eny &yogh;er it grewe,</L>
<L N="1035">A rynge of seluer rounde</L>
<L>He dude make and don on &thorn;e tre:</L>
<L>&THORN;erby eche &yogh;er wyten wolde he</L>
<L>How mochel it wax &thorn;at stounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us he se&yogh; by &thorn;at rynge</L>
<L N="1040">&THORN;at euery &yogh;er, wi&thorn;oute lesynge,</L>
<L>Liche mochel it grew,</L>
<L>&THORN;orghe &thorn;e grace &thorn;at god gan sende,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e &thorn;retty &yogh;eres ende &mdash;</L>
<L>Euere it was of on hew.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1045">Whanne &thorn;e &thorn;retty wynter was do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tre wax no lenger &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L>Bote al wey held his colour.</L>
<L>After vnder &thorn;at tre wi&thorn; herte &amp; &thorn;o&yogh;t</L>
<L>Dauid for synne &thorn;at he hadde wro&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1050">Wep teres ri&yogh;t sour,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wi&thorn; sorwe &amp; herte vnglad</L>
<L>&THORN;is salme: Miserere he mad.</L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;e sauter was do,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e worschipe of god almy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1055">In Jer(usa)lem cite ful ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>A temple gan he &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;eron wi&thorn; glade chere</L>
<L>Dede worchen foure &amp; twenty &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>An angel &thorn;o tolde him ry&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="1060">"&thorn;ow shelt no&yogh;t enden &thorn;is work of wynne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow hast don so mochel synne</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e kyng of my&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote Salamon, &thorn;y sone &yogh;ynge,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e shel ben kynge</L>
<L N="1065">And &thorn;is work fulfelle".</L>
<L>Sone after deyde Dauid &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And Salamon, his sone dere,</L>
<L>Held &thorn;e kyngdom at wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And parformede &thorn;at work also,</L>
<L N="1070">Fulle &thorn;retty wynter and two.</L>
<L>A bem &thorn;o faillede hem on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; senten to seche, saun doute,</L>
<L>In forestis &amp; wodes al aboute,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;e&yogh; my&yogh;te fynde non</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1075">&THORN;at to &thorn;at work my&yogh;te be bro&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at work was ne&yogh; al wro&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Salamon &thorn;eron gan rewe.</L>
<L>And as he stod as him ne rou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at tre he him by&thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1080">&THORN;at in &thorn;e cisterne grewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; felden it doun, and gonne it werche,</L>
<L>And maden a bem to &thorn;e cherche</L>
<L>Of leng&thorn;e &thorn;retty cubitis &amp; on,</L>
<L>A cubyte lengere &thorn;an &thorn;e make.</L>
<L N="1085">Whanne it was wro&yogh;t, &thorn;e&yogh; gonne it take</L>
<L>And drowen it op anon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And whanne &thorn;e&yogh; hadde it op left</L>
<L>And gonnen for to marken eft,</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; failede a fote of lengthe;</L>
<L N="1090">And eft &thorn;e&yogh; markeden, as y gesse,</L>
<L>Bote to &thorn;at work it wolde no&yogh;t dresse.</L>
<L>&THORN;o toke &thorn;e&yogh; it wi&thorn; strengthe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And, as Salamon to hem sayd,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cherche &thorn;e&yogh; it layd;</L>
<L N="1095">Ano&thorn;er bem sou&yogh;ten he</L>
<L>And maden op &thorn;at work of wen.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bad Salamon &thorn;at alle men</L>
<L>Sholde honuren &thorn;at tre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>It was custom of contre &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1100">Dyuerse tymes in &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>To komen &thorn;at temple to</L>
<L>And worschipen god &thorn;erynne &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>And &thorn;at tre &thorn;at lay on grounde.</L>
<L>Bote ones befel it so:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1105">As &thorn;e&yogh; were alle in &thorn;e temple boun,</L>
<L>A woman on &thorn;at tre sette hire doun,</L>
<L>Here name was Maximille:</L>
<L>Anon here clothes woxen a fere.</L>
<L>And she anon wi&thorn; ruful chere</L>
<L N="1110">Cride loude &amp; schylle:
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="138"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A, my lord god, Crist Jhesus!"</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e gewes hire herde crye &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Skolde &thorn;e&yogh; gonne hire calle</L>
<L>And, for she cride Jhesu Crist in soun,</L>
<L N="1115">Anon wi&thorn; stones wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e &thorn;e&yogh; stanede hire alle &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche was &thorn;e ferste wi&thorn;oute blame</L>
<L>&THORN;at martrid was for Cristis name.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gewes &thorn;o token &thorn;at tre</L>
<L N="1120">And beren it out wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>And in a dep dich adoun</L>
<L>&THORN;erynne &thorn;rewe it he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote god, &thorn;at wot of alle dede,</L>
<L>Honurede &thorn;at tre for mannes nede:</L>
<L N="1125">Betwixe ondren &amp; non</L>
<L>God sente eche day an angel bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at tre he wente ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e water &thorn;anne sterede ful son.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And who so my&yogh;te in &thorn;at water tiht</L>
<L N="1130">Bathen him after &thorn;at angelis fliht,</L>
<L>What siknesse &thorn;at he had,</L>
<L>Sone he wax hol ywis.</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e gewes wisten &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e&yogh; token here rad</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1135">And drowen op &thorn;at tre riche,</L>
<L>And sone after ouer a diche</L>
<L>&THORN;at tre &thorn;e&yogh; deden leye,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erouer leten it ligge</L>
<L>For to ben a fot-brigge</L>
<L N="1140">To men &thorn;at &yogh;eden &thorn;at weye,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;us, y telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holynesse of &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>Sholde be fordo</L>
<L>&THORN;orghe &thorn;e stappes of synful men</L>
<L N="1145">&THORN;at &thorn;eron sholde gon and ren &mdash;</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;ut was it no&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone after &thorn;at, verrayment,</L>
<L>&THORN;o Sibile sage to Jer(usa)lem went,</L>
<L>To heren of Salamones wit,</L>
<L N="1150">And kam by &thorn;at ilche tre:</L>
<L>Anon she fel doun on &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>And faire worschipede hit,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;eron wolde she no&yogh;t go</L>
<L>Bote in &thorn;e water wente &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="1155">And so honurede she &thorn;at tre,</L>
<L>And seide: "&thorn;e tyme is comynge ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at it shel beren &thorn;e kyng of my&yogh;t"</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;erof propheciede she.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Stille &thorn;er lay &thorn;is tre of gode,</L>
<L N="1160">Til god were dampned to deye on rode</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e gewes felle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wilt wite what tyme it is</L>
<L>Fro tyme &thorn;at god made paradys</L>
<L>And man, &thorn;erynne to dwelle:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1165">Til &thorn;at Nowelis flod were</L>
<L>Two &thorn;ousand two hondred &amp; twelf &yogh;ere &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;us we fynden <I>vs</I> selue;</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;e flod to Abraham,</L>
<L>As oure bok witnesse&thorn; ham,</L>
<L N="1170">Neghene hondred &yogh;er &amp; twelue;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And fro Abraham to Moysen,</L>
<L>As clerkes don <I>vs</I> to ken,</L>
<L>Foure hondred &yogh;er &amp; &thorn;retty;</L>
<L>And fro Moyses to Dauid kyng</L>
<L N="1175">Fyue hondred &amp; two, wi&thorn;oute lesyng,</L>
<L>To kounten ri&yogh;t trewely;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And for&thorn; fro Dauid &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>To Babiloyne &thorn;e delyuering</L>
<L>Fyue hondred &yogh;er were &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="1180">And fro &thorn;at deliuerynge, we sayn &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e incarnacioun of Jhesu</L>
<L>Fyue hondred &yogh;er &amp; mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And fro &thorn;e incarnacioun of Jhesu</L>
<L>Til &thorn;is rym y telle &yogh;ow</L>
<L N="1185">Were turned in to englisch,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &thorn;re hondred &amp; seuenty</L>
<L>And fyue &yogh;ere witterly.</L>
<L>&THORN;us in bok founden it is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ferst &thorn;is was mad in Ebrew,</L>
<L N="1190">And sethen turned to latyn new,</L>
<L>And now to englisch speche.</L>
<L>Praye we for him &thorn;at ha&thorn; it wro&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god, as he him dere abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Be his soule leche;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1195">And to mede of his makyng,</L>
<L>And <I>vs</I> alle, for oure heryng,</L>
<L>Praye we wi&thorn; one steuene</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu Crist, oure sauyour,</L>
<L>And his moder, &thorn;at swete flour,</L>
<L N="1200">Grante <I>vs</I> &thorn;e blesse of heuene.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="b" TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000145.tif" N="[139]">
<HEAD>b) aus Ms. Auchinl. Edinb. Advoc. Libr. <NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Version des Ms. Auchinl. ist in 2 Bruchst&uuml;cken erhalten: das erste, 2 foll. (v. 1-352) ist jetzt in Mr. David Laing's Privatbesitz, nachdem diese 2 Bl&auml;tter fr&uuml;her als Deckel von blank paper books gedient hatten, welche vor 1750 von einem Professor von S. Andrews als "note books" angekauft wurden. Der andere Theil findet sich fol. 14-16 in Ms. Auch., als 8 tes St&uuml;ck dieser Samm|lung (die ersten 5 sind ausgefallen, das Ms. beginnt jetzt mit 6: Gregorius). Beide Fragmente sind von David Laing in: A Penniworth of witte: Florice and Blauncheflore: &amp; other pieces of ancient Engl. po&eacute;try selected from the Auch. Ms. Printed at Edinburgh for the Abbotsford Club 1857 heraus|gegeben. &mdash; Die Ausgabe dieser Fragm. folgt hier mit Erlaubniss Furnivall's nach einer auf meine Bitte von Miss Toulmin Smith f&uuml;r die Early Engl. Text Soc. angefertigten Abschrift des Ms. f&uuml;r das 2. Fragm., w&auml;hrend das erste auf Laing's Ausg. basirt.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>Li&yogh;tbern, &thorn;at angel bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Answerd anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Ich was ar &thorn;e warld bigan,</L>
<L>Er euer god maked man;</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;erfore", he seyd, "so mot yt be:</L>
<L>He schal first anoure me".</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd &thorn;e messanger</L>
<L>To Li&yogh;tbern, &thorn;at is now Lucifer:</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;ou do godes comandment,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;ou art inobedient</L>
<L>And wre&thorn;&thorn;est god almi&yogh;ti &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>And so mi&yogh;t &thorn;i mir&thorn;e be forlore".</L>
<L>Li&yogh;tbern answerd anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch pride &thorn;at in his word was li&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="15">"He schal comen al to late</L>
<L>Mi mir&thorn;e for to abate.</L>
<L>Ichil go sitten in my see</L>
<L>And be more master &thorn;an he".</L>
<L>And anon ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;at . . .</L>
<L N="20">He sett him in his owen . . .</L>
<L>And &thorn;o Li&yogh;tbern hade seyd so,</L>
<L>Mani &thorn;ousend angels and mo</L>
<L>Sayd: &thorn;ai nold in non manere</L>
<L>Anour Adam no Eue, his fere.</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;us in heuen pride bigan</L>
<L>While god in er&thorn;e made man.</L>
<L>&THORN;o swete Jhesus, &thorn;at was wiis,</L>
<L>Was comen out of paradis</L>
<L>To heuen, &thorn;er he . . . . .</L>
<L N="30">And hadde maked men of mold,</L>
<L>He sey&yogh;e where Li&yogh;tbern set,</L>
<L>And bad him loke to his fet.</L>
<L>And Li&yogh;tbern anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>For pride &thorn;at in him was li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="35">In holy writ we heren telle:</L>
<L>He sanke adoun in to helle;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he &thorn;oled michel schame &mdash;</L>
<L>Satanas is now his name.</L>
<L>And alle angels in heuen &thorn;at wer,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at him ani wittnesse bere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was wor&thorn;i to sitten in se</L>
<L>&THORN;er swete Jhesu was won to be:</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e pouwer of godes mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Seuen days and seuen ni&yogh;t</L>
<L N="45">Angels fellen adoun in to helle:</L>
<L>In holy writ we heren it telle,</L>
<L>For pride &thorn;at was in hem li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of heuen blis &thorn;ai lorn &thorn;e si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And as we finden in lectrure &mdash;</L>
<L N="50">Y not whe&thorn;er it be in holy scripture &mdash;:</L>
<L>&THORN;o Li&yogh;tbern sat in his se</L>
<L>And seyd he was wor&thorn;ier &thorn;an he:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mone bar him witnesse,</L>
<L>It waxe&thorn; and wanie&thorn; more and lesse;
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="140"></L>
<L N="55">&THORN;e se &thorn;urch vertu of godes mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ebbe&thorn; and flouwe&thorn; day and ni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;is tvay no habbe neuer rest,</L>
<L>Nai&thorn;er bi est no bi west.</L>
<L>In heuen Pride first bigan</L>
<L N="60">In angels, ar it cam in man;</L>
<L>And for it com out of heuen</L>
<L>And was &thorn;e form sinne of seuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>Of alle sinnes Pride is king.</L>
<L N="65">Lete we now Pride be,</L>
<L>And to Adam wende we,</L>
<L>And loke we hou him spet</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;urch his wiues abet</L>
<L>And &thorn;urch &thorn;e fendes entisement</L>
<L N="70">He brak godes comandment.</L>
<L>God &mdash; yblisced mat he be! &mdash;</L>
<L>He forbede Adam an appel-tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne schuld of liif no lim</L>
<L>No frout &thorn;erof nim.</L>
<L N="75">&THORN;e fende in licknesse of an adder</L>
<L>Clombe opon &thorn;e tre wi&thorn;outen ladder</L>
<L>And cleped to him Adames wiif,</L>
<L>For to apair Adames liif.</L>
<L>And Eue to &thorn;e nadder cam,</L>
<L N="80">And at &thorn;e nadder an appel nam:</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende gat alle &thorn;at he fond,</L>
<L>And tok it Eue in hir hond</L>
<L>And seyd: "ete &thorn;ou, and Adam, of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schul ben al so wiis</L>
<L N="85">As god, &thorn;at sitt in . . .,</L>
<L>And witten alle his . . .</L>
<L>. . &yogh;e no schuld nou&yogh;t se no here</L>
<L>Which godes . . . . . ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he it &yogh;ou forbede</L>
<L N="90">Ite schuld nou&yogh;t comen in &yogh;our hede".</L>
<L>Eue of &thorn;e nadder &thorn;e appel nam,</L>
<L>And to Adam anon him cam</L>
<L>And seyd: "do as Ich &thorn;e rede:</L>
<L>And it schal be &thorn;e best dede</L>
<L N="95">&THORN;at euer &yogh;ete &thorn;ou dest ywis:</L>
<L>Ete of &thorn;e appel &thorn;at here is,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt be, wi&thorn;outen lesing,</L>
<L>Also wise of alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at it forbede</L>
<L N="100">It schuld nou&yogh;t comen in &thorn;ine hed".</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e fendes comberment</L>
<L>And &thorn;urch his wiues enticement</L>
<L>Godes comandment he breke:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he and his wiif eke</L>
<L N="105">Se&thorn;&thorn;en hem rewe bo&thorn;e ful sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai leueden &thorn;e fendes lore.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e boke it is ywrite:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ai hadde of &thorn;e appel bite,</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er of o&thorn;er aschamed was</L>
<L N="110">And hiled her kinde wi&thorn; more and gras.</L>
<L>Adam was of god afli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And went and hidde him anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And god out of heuen cam</L>
<L>And cleped anon after Adam.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;an seyd swete Jesus:</L>
<L>"Adam, Adam, why destow &thorn;us?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ybrou&yogh;t &thorn;i selue in wo</L>
<L>And Eue, &thorn;i gode wiif, al so;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast min hest ybroke,</L>
<L N="120">For so&thorn;e, Adam, ichil be wroke;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e haue ydon a sori dede,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e, &yogh;e schul haue &yogh;our mede".</L>
<L>&THORN;o Jesu hadde to hem speke</L>
<L>And told hem &thorn;at he wald ben awreke &mdash;</L>
<L N="125">Yblisced be his nam seuen! &mdash;,</L>
<L>He stey&yogh;e of him in to heuen.</L>
<L>And &thorn;er after anon ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>He sent to hem an angel bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a brenand swerd,</L>
<L N="130">And drof hem in to miduerd,</L>
<L>Adam and Eue, his wiif,</L>
<L>In care &thorn;er to leden her liif.</L>
<L>Gret pite it was to here</L>
<L>Of Adam and of Eue his fere,</L>
<L N="135">Hou &thorn;ai wepen and grad allas,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ai schulden for her trespas</L>
<L>Out of paradys ygon &mdash;</L>
<L>It was pite to heren her mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Adam in to er&thorn;e cam,</L>
<L N="140">Bowes leues and gras he nam:</L>
<L>A lo&yogh;e he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to biginne,</L>
<L>He and his wiif to crepen inne.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;e lo&yogh;e was ymaked,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai lay &thorn;e[r]in all star naked,</L>
<L N="145">Sex days and sex ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For hunger wel iuel ydi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Euerich day &thorn;ai sou&yogh;ten mete,</L>
<L>Bot nowhar &thorn;ai no cou&thorn;e it gete.
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>&THORN;o sex days weren agon</L>
<L N="150">And &thorn;ai no founde mete non,</L>
<L>Eue bigan for to crie:</L>
<L>"Allas, Adam, for hunger we dye!</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;ou art inne,</L>
<L>Certes, alle it is for mi sinne.</L>
<L N="155">Adam, ich beseke &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Sle me, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille be:</L>
<L>For, wer ich out of godes si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Par auentour, Adam, &thorn;an &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>O&yogh;ein in to paradys wende</L>
<L N="160">And haue &thorn;e blis wi&thorn;outen ende".</L>
<L>"A, woman", qua&thorn; Adam &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"Allas, why seydestow so?</L>
<L>Wostow make me so wode</L>
<L>To sle min owhen flesche and blode?</L>
<L N="165">Bo&thorn;e in flesche and in bon</L>
<L>Jesus Crist ha&thorn; made ous on:</L>
<L>He made &thorn;e of mi ribbe &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;test be me no ner sibbe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest more so,</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;ou wilt bring ous in more wo:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god sende on ous his curs,</L>
<L>&THORN;an schul we fare &thorn;e wors.</L>
<L>Bot go we for&thorn; and seche mete,</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at we may ani gete</L>
<L N="175">And for fau&yogh;t dye we nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we mow finden ou&yogh;t".</L>
<L>&THORN;ai went for&thorn; and mete sou&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>And of hem seluen litel rou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>Astay went to seche mete,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;ai sey&yogh;en bestes stonden and ete;</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ai no cou&thorn;e finde non,</L>
<L>As wide as &thorn;ai cou&thorn;e gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyd Adam &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"No hadde wret&thorn;ed swete Jhesus,</L>
<L N="185">He wald haue sent ous mete anou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Hongend opon ich bou&yogh;,</L>
<L>As he do&thorn; &thorn;is wilde bestes,</L>
<L>And whe hadden holden his hestes;</L>
<L>Bot for we haue his hest ybroke,</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;erfore he wil ben awroke.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, Eue, mi rede it is:</L>
<L>For whe han don amis,</L>
<L>Go we out of &thorn;is wode schawes</L>
<L>And liue we in pennaunce fourti dawes:</L>
<L N="195">And at &thorn;e fourti dawes ende</L>
<L>God almi&yogh;ti, &thorn;at is so hende,</L>
<L>And we mi&yogh;ten his loue gete,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wolde he send ous mete".</L>
<L>"Sir", qua&thorn; Eue to Adam &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="200">"&THORN;at wold bring me more wo,</L>
<L>So long penaunce for to take,</L>
<L>Bot ich it mi&yogh;t an ending make;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if mi penance weren ybroke,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wold god ben awroke</L>
<L N="205">And be wro&thorn;er &thorn;an he is,</L>
<L>And ich dede eft amis".</L>
<L>"Eue", qua&thorn; Adam anon ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>"Nou&yogh;t bot do &thorn;an what &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Wende to &thorn;e water of Tiges anon</L>
<L N="210">And step in opon a ston;</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ou art comen in,</L>
<L>Wad in vp to &thorn;i chin</L>
<L>And fond to stond &thorn;erin all stille</L>
<L>Fourti days to fulfille.</L>
<L N="215">And Jchil in to &thorn;e flom go</L>
<L>And stond &thorn;erin fourti days and also</L>
<L>Sex days mo and sex ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e help of godes mi&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For in sex dayes and seuen ni&yogh;t</L>
<L N="220">Alle &thorn;e warld was maked and di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And fulfild on &thorn;e seuen day;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, as for&thorn; as y may,</L>
<L>Jchil fond to helden stille</L>
<L>Sex days more to fulfille.</L>
<L N="225">&THORN;at ich rede we biginne</L>
<L>And do penaunce for our sinne.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e penaunce wil be so hard,</L>
<L>Par auentour &thorn;an afterward</L>
<L>God, &thorn;at ha&thorn; &yogh;euen ous liif so,</L>
<L N="230">Wald sende ous sustenance &thorn;erto".</L>
<L>Eue vnderstode his rede</L>
<L>And dede as Adam hir bede.</L>
<L>As it telle&thorn; in &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>Ai&thorn;er at o&thorn;er leue tok;</L>
<L N="235">Eue in to Tiges wode</L>
<L>And vp to &thorn;e chin sche stode,</L>
<L>And in to &thorn;e flum wode Adam</L>
<L>And his penaunce vndernam.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ai hadde stonden &thorn;are</L>
<L N="240">In miche wo and miche care,</L>
<L>Tventi days stonden inne</L>
<L>In &thorn;o to waters in pine:
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>&THORN;e fende &thorn;ou&yogh;t him to awreke</L>
<L>And her penaunce for to breke.</L>
<L N="245">And formast he com to Eue,</L>
<L>To brengen hir in misbileue &mdash;</L>
<L>For Eue hadde leued his lore,</L>
<L>He hoped &thorn;at sche wald more &mdash;</L>
<L>And seyd: "Eue, wele is &thorn;e!</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;i lord sent &thorn;e word bi me</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i trespas is for&yogh;eue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dost o&yogh;ains his leue.</L>
<L>Com out of &thorn;at water anon!</L>
<L>And as so swi&thorn;e astow mi&yogh;t gon</L>
<L N="255">Go and sigge Adam so,</L>
<L>And bring him out of his wo!</L>
<L>And Ichil go &thorn;ider wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>And say him as Ichaue don to &thorn;e".</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at tiding Eue was glad</L>
<L N="260">And dede as &thorn;e fende hir bad:</L>
