<L>&amp; dyed anon in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>&amp; as &thorn;e angel hadde yseyd:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e li&yogh;tnisse was aleyd,</L>
<L>Sonne &amp; mone lorn her li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="530">Sex days &amp; sex ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Eue bigan to wepe &amp; crie,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he sey&yogh;e Adam dye;</L>
<L>&amp; Se&thorn; made reweli mon</L>
<L>&amp; fel doun on his fader anon,</L>
<L N="535">&amp;, as it telle&thorn; in &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>In his armes his fader he tok,</L>
<L>&amp; ful bitterliche he wepe.</L>
<L>&amp; god almi&yogh;ti &thorn;erof toke kepe,</L>
<L>&amp; sent adoun an angel bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="540">&THORN;at seyd to Se&thorn; anon ri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Arise, &amp; lete &thorn;i sorwe be!</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ine ey&yogh;en &thorn;ou schalt se,</L>
<L>God, &thorn;at al &thorn;e warld schal glade,</L>
<L>What he wil do wi&thorn; &thorn;at he made".</L>
<L N="545">God, &thorn;at sit in heuen hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Tok Adam soule, &thorn;at Se&thorn; it sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; bitok it seyn Mi&yogh;hel</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: "haue, loke &thorn;is soule wel,</L>
<L>&amp; put it in sorwe &amp; &thorn;esternisse,</L>
<L N="550">Out of ioie &amp; alle li&yogh;tnisse,</L>
<L>Til fiue &thorn;ousend winter ben ago,</L>
<L>Tvo hundred &amp; ei&yogh;te &amp; tventi mo,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e time &thorn;at he ete</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at appel him &thorn;ou&yogh;t so swete:</L>
<L N="555">So long for his gilt</L>
<L>In his ward he schal be pilt</L>
<L>&THORN;at maked him min hest breke;</L>
<L>So long ich wil ben awreke,</L>
<L>On him, &amp; alle his blod eke,</L>
<L N="560">Mi comandment for he breke.</L>
<L>&amp; whan &thorn;at terme is ago,</L>
<L>To ioie schal turn al his wo:</L>
<L>&amp; afterward &thorn;an schal he</L>
<L>Sitten in &thorn;ilke selue se</L>
<L N="565">&THORN;at Li&yogh;tbern sat, min angel bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Er pride was in his hert ali&yogh;t".</L>
<L>&THORN;us seyd Jhesus, &thorn;at sitt an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en in to heuen he stei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e time &thorn;at cas fel</L>
<L N="570">&THORN;at curssed Kaim slou&yogh; Abel</L>
<L>Til Adam dyed opon mold,</L>
<L>As swete Jhesus Crist wold,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete lay Abel aboue er&thorn;e:</L>
<L>Til Jhesu Crist &mdash; herd mot he wer&thorn;e &mdash;</L>
<L N="575">Bad his angels &thorn;at &thorn;ai scholde</L>
<L>Biry &thorn;e bodis vnder molde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e angels al wi&thorn;outen chest</L>
<L>Dede anon godes hest,</L>
<L>I(n)to clo&thorn;es &thorn;e bodi &thorn;ai feld.</L>
<L N="580">Eue &amp; hir children stode &amp; biheld</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;ilke selue stede,</L>
<L>&amp; hadde wonder what &thorn;ai dede:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai no hadde ar &thorn;an</L>
<L>Neuer sen biry no man.</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;an seyd an angel, &thorn;er he stode,</L>
<L>To Eue &amp; to al hir brode:</L>
<L>"Take &yogh;eme hou we do!</L>
<L>&amp; her afterward do so:</L>
<L>Birie&thorn; alle so &thorn;at dyen</L>
<L N="590">As &yogh;e se wi&thorn; &yogh;our ey&yogh;en</L>
<L>&THORN;at we don &thorn;is bodis here &mdash;</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &yogh;e in &thorn;e selue manere"!</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e angels had seyd &thorn;us,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wenten o&yogh;ain to swete Jhesus,</L>
<L N="595">To heuen &thorn;er &thorn;ai formast were,</L>
<L>&amp; leued Eue &amp; hir children &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Sex days after Adam was dede,</L>
<L>God almi&yogh;ti an angel bede</L>
<L>Go tellen Eue, Adames wiif:</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;e terme was comen of hir liif.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Eue wist sche schuld dye,</L>
<L>Sche cleped for&thorn; hir progenie,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e &yogh;onger &amp; &thorn;e eldre,</L>
<L>Hir childer &amp; hir childer childre,</L>
<L N="605">&amp; sayd, &thorn;at alle mi&yogh;ten here:</L>
<L>"&THORN;o ich &amp; Adam, mi fere,</L>
<L>Breken godes comandment,</L>
<L>Anon his wret&thorn;e was ysent</L>
<L>On ous, &amp; on our progenie:
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="610">&amp; &thorn;erfore merci &yogh;e schul crie,</L>
<L>&amp; bo&thorn;e bi day &amp; eke bi ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Do&thorn; penance bi al &yogh;our mi&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou, Se&thorn;, for ani &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Ich comand &thorn;e on mi blisceing</L>
<L N="615">&THORN;at &thorn;i fader liif be write,</L>
<L>&amp; min also, eueri smite,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e bigining of his liif</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was maked, &amp; ich, his wiif,</L>
<L>&amp; hou we were filed wi&thorn; sinne,</L>
<L N="620">&amp; what sorwe whe han liued inne,</L>
<L>&amp; in whiche maner &thorn;at &thorn;ou seye</L>
<L>Rediliche wi&thorn; &thorn;ine ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;i fader soule to pine sent,</L>
<L>For he brak godes comandment.</L>
<L N="625">Alle &thorn;is loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou write,</L>
<L>As wele as &thorn;ou kanst it dite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;o &thorn;at be now &yogh;ong childre</L>
<L>Mai it see, &amp; her elder,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at here after be bore,</L>
<L N="630">Hou we han wrou&yogh;t here bifore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mowe taken ensaumple of ous</L>
<L>&amp; amenden o&yogh;ain Jhesus".</L>
<L>&THORN;o Eue hadde &thorn;us yseyd</L>
<L>&amp; hir erand on Se&thorn; yleyd,</L>
<L N="635">Sche kneled adoun &amp; bad hir bede,</L>
<L>&amp; ri&yogh;t in &thorn;ilke selue stede</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle her kin stoden &amp; sey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Where, sche dyed biforn her ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;t as Eue was dede,</L>
<L N="640">Her children token hem to rede</L>
<L>&amp; beren hir &thorn;ilke selue day</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e stede &thorn;er Adam lay,</L>
<L>&amp; biried hir in &thorn;ilke stede</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;e angels dede</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;at biried Adam &amp; Abel:</L>
<L>&THORN;erof &thorn;ai token hede ful wel.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o sche was in er&thorn;e ybrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai were sori in her &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; wopen &amp; made miche wo,</L>
<L N="650">&THORN;o Adam &amp; Eue was ago,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e an euen &amp; a morwe</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wopen &amp; made miche sorwe.</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;e four dayes ende</L>
<L>Jhesu made an angel wende,</L>
<L N="655">&amp; seyd, &thorn;er &thorn;ai wepen sore:</L>
<L>"Dole&thorn; sex days, &amp; na more,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen day rest of &yogh;our sorwe,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e aneuen &amp; a morwe!</L>
<L>For god &thorn;at alle &thorn;e warld ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="660">&amp; alle &thorn;e warld made of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As him &thorn;ou&yogh;t it wald be best,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen day he toke rest.</L>
<L>&amp; ano&thorn;er &thorn;ing witterly:</L>
<L>It bitokne&thorn; &thorn;e day of merci:</L>
<L N="665">&THORN;e seuenday was sononday,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at day schal be domesday</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e soules &thorn;at wele haue wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at day schul to rest be brou&yogh;t".</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e angel hadde his erand seyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. To st. &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="670">&THORN;at god almi&yogh;ten hadde on him leyd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. al mi&yogh;ten st. almi&yogh;ti.</NOTE></L>
<L>In to heuen &thorn;e way he nam &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wist neuer whar he bicam.</L>
<L>Se&thorn; anon ri&yogh;t bigan,</L>
<L>Of Adam, &thorn;at was &thorn;e forme man,</L>
<L N="675">Al to gider he wrot his liif,</L>
<L>As Eue hade beden, Adames wiif.</L>
<L>As telle&thorn; &thorn;e boke, &thorn;at wele wot,</L>
<L>In ston alle &thorn;e letters he wrot,</L>
<L>For fir no water opon mold</L>
<L N="680">Neuer greuen it no schold.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Se&thorn; hadde writen Adames liif,</L>
<L>&amp; Eues, &thorn;at was Adames wiif:</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;ilke selue stede</L>
<L>&THORN;er Adam was won to bide his bede,</L>
<L N="865">In &thorn;ilke stede &thorn;e bok he leyd &mdash;</L>
<L>As wisemen er &thorn;is han yseyd &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er Adam was won to biden his bede,</L>
<L>&amp; leued it in &thorn;ilke stede.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er it lay alle Noes flode</L>
<L N="690">&amp; no hadde nou&yogh;t bot gode.</L>
<L>Long after N[o]es flod was go,</L>
<L>Salamon &thorn;e king com &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was air of Dauid lond:</L>
<L>&amp; Adames liif &thorn;er he fond,</L>
<L N="695">&amp; al in ston writen it was,</L>
<L>&amp; damaghed non letter &thorn;er nas.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at euer Salamon cou&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ink in hert or speke wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>On word he no cou&thorn;e wite
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="147"></L>
<L N="700">Of alle &thorn;at euer was &thorn;er write,</L>
<L>He no cou&thorn;e o word vnderstond</L>
<L>&THORN;at Se&thorn; hadde writen wi&thorn; his hond.</L>
<L>&amp; Salamon, &thorn;at was wiis,</L>
<L>Bisou&yogh;t &thorn;e king of paradys</L>
<L N="705">&THORN;at he schuld for his mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Sende him grace fram heuen li&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;t haue grace to wite</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing weren &thorn;ere ywrite.</L>
<L>God &mdash; yblisced mot he wer&thorn;e! &mdash;</L>
<L N="710">He sent an angel in to er&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tau&yogh;t Salamon eueri smite</L>
<L>Alle Adames liif ywrite,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd to Salamon ywis:</L>
<L>"Here, &thorn;er &thorn;is writeing is,</L>
<L N="715">Ri&yogh;t in &thorn;is selue stede</L>
<L>Adam was wont to bid his bede.</L>
<L>&amp; here &thorn;ou schalt a temple wirche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal be cleped holi chirche;</L>
<L>&THORN;er men schal bid holy bede,</L>
<L N="720">As Adam dede in &thorn;is stede".</L>
<L>&amp; Salamon &thorn;e king anon</L>
<L>Lete reren a temple of lime &amp; ston:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first chirche vnder sonne</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer in warld was bigonne.</L>
<L N="725">Now haue &yogh;e herd of Adames liif</L>
<L>&amp; of Eue, &thorn;at was his wiif,</L>
<L>Whiche liif &thorn;ai ladden here on mold</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en diden, as god wold.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o Adam in er&thorn;e was ded,</L>
<L N="730">For sinne &thorn;at com of her sed</L>
<L>God sent Noes flod</L>
<L>&amp; adrenched al &thorn;e blod &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">blod st. brod?</NOTE></L>
<L>Swich wreche god nam</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at of Adam cam &mdash;</L>
<L N="735">Saue Noee &amp; his wiif,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god hadde graunted liif,</L>
<L>&amp; his children &thorn;at he hadde,</L>
<L>To schip wi&thorn; him &thorn;at he ladde.</L>
<L>Of Noee se&thorn;&thorn;en &amp; of his childer</L>
<L N="740">We be&thorn; ycomen alto gider.</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ai leued in swiche sinne</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e liif &thorn;ai liueden inne</L>
<L>Sodom &amp; Gomore, &thorn;at wer &thorn;o</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e noble cites tvo,</L>
<L N="745">Bo&thorn;e sonken in to helle,</L>
<L>As we here clerkes telle.</L>
<L>&amp; ano&thorn;er noble cite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was yhoten Niniue,</L>
<L>Was in &thorn;ilke selue cas;</L>
<L N="750">Bot as &thorn;e prophete Jonas</L>
<L>Bad for hem day &amp; ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>To swete Jhesu ful of mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; made bo&thorn;e king &amp; quene</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at o&thorn;er pople bidene</L>
<L N="755">In her bedes he made hem wake</L>
<L>&amp; hard penaunce he dede hem take:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;ai were to penaunce pilt,</L>
<L>God for&yogh;af hem her gilt;</L>
<L>&THORN;us Niniue saued was</L>
<L N="760">&THORN;urch bisekeing of Jonas.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete after Noes flod</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at com of Noees blod,</L>
<L>Weren he neuer so holy man,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e sinne &thorn;at Adam bigan</L>
<L N="765">&THORN;er most non in heuen com,</L>
<L>Er god hadde his conseyl nome</L>
<L>To li&yogh;ten in &thorn;e virgine Marie</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e rode wald dye,</L>
<L>For to biggen ous alle fre &mdash;</L>
<L N="770">Yherd &amp; heyed mot he be!</L>
<L>Now haue &yogh;e herd of swete Jhesus,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e bok telle&thorn; ous,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e warld hou it bigan</L>
<L>&amp; hou he made of mold man</L>
<L N="775">Jhesu &thorn;at was nomen wi&thorn; wrong</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;oled mani paines strong</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e Jewes, &thorn;at wer felle,</L>
<L>To bring Adam out of helle:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ous grace for to winne</L>
<L N="780">&THORN;e ioie &thorn;at Adam now is inne.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000154.tif" N="[148]">
<HEAD>3. Magdalena.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="a" TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Laud 108, fol. 190.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SLei&yogh;e men and egleche,: and of redes wise and bolde,</L>
<L>Lustniez nou&thorn;e to mi speche,: wise and vnwise, &yogh;ongue and olde:</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing ich eov nelle rede ne teche: of none wichche ne of none scolde,</L>
<L>Bote of a lif &thorn;at may beo leche: to sunfule men of herte colde.</L>
<L N="5">Ich nelle eov no&thorn;er rede ne rime: of kyng ne of eorl, of kny&yogh;ht ne of swein,</L>
<L>Ake of a womman ichchulle ov telle: &thorn;at was sunful and forlein:</L>
<L>A swy&thorn;e fol wumman heo bicam,: and &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace heo was ibrou&yogh;ht a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e heo is to Crist icome,: &thorn;e fayre Marie Maudeleyn.</L>
<L>Of hire ichulle &yogh;eou telle nou&thorn;e: al hou and &yogh;ware heo was ibore,</L>
<L N="10">&YOGH;if &yogh;e to me wullez iheore: and habben of god &thorn;onk &thorn;are fore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is word Marie so is bri&yogh;h(t)nesse: and bitokne &thorn;e steorre of &thorn;e se,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bri&yogh;hnesse. bitokne st. bitokneth.</NOTE></L>
<L>And soruwe also and biturnesse,: ase &thorn;e bok tellez me;</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane a man fielez in is heorte: &thorn;at he hauez muche misdo,</L>
<L>And him &thorn;are fore biguynnez to smeorte,: &thorn;at is to him bitur and wo,</L>
<L N="15">He mournez and he sikez ofte:: &THORN;is ilke Marie fierde also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at was hire leof and softe: was seth&thorn;e hire fulle fo.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Castel of Magdale: &thorn;is faire wumman was ibore:</L>
<L>Heo was icleoped in propre name: &thorn;e Maudeleyne ri&yogh;ht &thorn;arefore.</L>
<L>To speken of hire ich am wel fous,: and it likez me ful murie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fous, 189, 457 vouse, = ready.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">Ire fader was hoten Sire Titus,: and hire moder Dame Euchirie,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Ire st. hire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire bro&thorn;ur was cleoped Lazarus,: and Martha was hire soster:</L>
<L>Heo was debonere and pitiuous: and heo was a seli foster.</L>
<L>Heore fader and heore moder bo&thorn;e: comen of riche kunne,</L>
<L>Of bolde kyngus and of quienes,: men of muchele wunne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">wunne winne = wealth.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">Of castles and of tounes,: of londes and of &thorn;eodes,</L>
<L>Of halles and of boures,: of palefrei&yogh;es and of stedes;</L>
<L>Large huy weren of heore metes: to heom &thorn;at hadden neode,</L>
<L>To men goinde and eke sittinde,: &thorn;at heore bonene wolden heom beode.</L>
<L>Wyse men and sley&yogh;e: oueral huy weren itolde.</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;o &thorn;at huy scholden dei&yogh;e,: and so huy weren iholde:</L>
<L>Heore londes and heore leodes: huy delden alle a-&thorn;reo,
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>Tounes and heore &thorn;eodes,: heore guod and heore feo,</L>
<L>To feoffen heore children: &thorn;arewiz echon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wiz = with, z f&uuml;r th ist h&auml;ufig im Ms. Laud 108.</NOTE></L>
<L>For huy ne scholden nou&yogh;t striue: &yogh;wane huy heom weren atgon.</L>
<L N="35">Wel sone &thorn;ere aftur,: &thorn;o huy nede scholde,</L>
<L>Deiden fader and moder,: ase Jesu Crist it wolde.</L>
<L>Bi heom men duden sone: ase huy ou&yogh;ten to done:</L>
<L>And to heore longue home: brou&yogh;ten heom ful sone.</L>
<L>Jesu Crist of heouene: of heom habbe merci</L>
<L N="40">And for is names seouene: fram helle heom waraunti!</L>
<L>Huy di&yogh;hten heore londes: among heom alle &thorn;reo,</L>
<L>And with heore hondene delden: heore gold and heore feo:</L>
<L>To Marie bilefde: &thorn;e castel Magdale,</L>
<L>&THORN;arefore Maudeleyne: formest icleoped was heo;<NOTE PLACE="foot">steht im Ms. hinter dem vorigen Verse, wie 269.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Lazarus hadde &thorn;at haluendel: of al Jerusalem,</L>
<L>Of wodes and fieldes and of sart (!): al mest to Bedlehem;</L>
<L>Martha was ifeoffed: with &thorn;e Betanie</L>
<L>And also with Genezarez,: bote &thorn;e bok us lie.</L>
<L>Marie heo ne tolde nou&yogh;t: bote al of hire pruyde,</L>
<L N="50">Ake &thorn;aron was al hire &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,: and faire hire to schruyde,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e for to walke aboute: to don hire flechses wille,</L>
<L>To gon and eorne feor and neor,: bo&thorn;e loude and stille;</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e, heo was riche inou&yogh;h,: and so heo moste nede:</L>
<L>Manie riche men hire lei&yogh;en bi: and &yogh;euen hire gret mede.</L>
<L N="55">Lazarus spendede al is &thorn;ou&yogh;ht: opon his chiualerie,</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingus ne tok he no &yogh;eme,: ne to housebondrie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e selie Martha, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur suster,: heo was of redes guode,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ei heo and hire soster: neren nou&yogh;t of one blode.</L>
<L>Martha nam hire bro&thorn;ur lond: and hire sustres also,</L>
<L N="60">And dude heom teolien wel inou&yogh;,: ase wys man scholde do;</L>
<L>&THORN;arewith heo fedde alle heore men,: and clo&thorn;ede heom also,</L>
<L>Pouere men and wummen,: &thorn;at weren neodfole and in wo.</L>
<L>So fair womman nas &thorn;are non: in none kunnes londe</L>
<L>Ase Marie was of bodie,: and of fote and honde;</L>
<L N="65">So more fairore &thorn;at heo bicam,: &thorn;e more of hire was prys:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pris mit &uuml;bergeschr. y.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more fol womman heo wax: and sunful and unwys.</L>
<L>Hire ri&yogh;hte name Marie: oueral heo les &thorn;arefore,</L>
<L>Sunfole wumman men cleopeden hire: bihinde hire and bifore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is wumman hadde iheord: &thorn;at hire name was ilore,</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at heo was so bigyled and bicherd,: wo was hire &thorn;arefore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bicherd, auch 440, = deceived.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o men hire cleopeden sunfule: and lieten hire ri&yogh;hte name,</L>
<L>Heo wax kareful and dreori of &thorn;ou&yogh;ht: and gan sore to schame.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nolde heo nomore: bifore &thorn;e riche men come;</L>
<L>In to hire castel for sorewe: heo hauez hire inome,
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>For to ore louerd cam and prechede: oueral in &thorn;at londe.</L>
<L N="75">Martha hire suster ofte bifore opbraid: hire schame and hire schonde</L>
<L>And chidde hire ful ofte: for hire lecherie,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e fastinde and eke ful,: &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;hte it drie.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he = heo, wie 86, 158, 542.</NOTE></L>
<L>A man of &thorn;at contreye: &thorn;at hei&yogh;hte Symond leperous,</L>
<L>Also &thorn;e bok us tellez,: bad ore louerd to is hous,</L>
<L N="80">And is deciples tweolue: with him, to &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>For he ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;ht him sulf: fram heom alle ete.</L>
<L>Marie &thorn;is iheorde: and &thorn;arof was ful glad,</L>
<L>A smeorieles to grei&thorn;i: &thorn;arto he was ful rad,</L>
<L>Heo wende to Symundes hous,: &thorn;at noman hire ne bad,</L>
<L N="85">To ore louerd Jesu Crist;: and ful sore heo was of-drad,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he was so sunful,: bifore ore louerd to come,</L>
<L>Careful heo was and sore aferd: forto beon inome,</L>
<L>Heo ne dorste ore louerd repie nou&yogh;ht: bihinde ne bifore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">repie, 110 reppe, = touch</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne noman hire nolde cleopie,: and &thorn;at hire grefde sore.</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;o ore louerd was isete: in Symundes house &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And his apostles to &thorn;e mete,: &thorn;at with him &thorn;o were,</L>
<L>Ore louerd sat and &thorn;ou&yogh;hte muche,: ake bote luyte he ne eet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">eet aus eat corrig.</NOTE></L>
<L>Marie &thorn;at was so sunful: heo crep doun to is fiet,</L>
<L>Heo custe is fiet and wusch also: with hire wete teres,</L>
<L N="95">And wipede heom afturward: with hire &yogh;eoluwe heres,</L>
<L>Out of hire boxe heo nam: oynement ful guod</L>
<L>And smeorede ore louerdes heued: with ful blisful mod.</L>
<L>Judas was &thorn;are biside and smulde hit,: and &thorn;arefore he was nei&yogh;h wod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swote smul him culde nei&yogh;h: and gremede is sorie blod,</L>
<L N="100">And bad don up &thorn;at riche &thorn;ing: &thorn;at heo ore louerd gan with smeore;</L>
<L>To spene it so in wasting,: he seide, it was gret lure,</L>
<L>And seide: "it mai beon isold ful deore,: to bugge with muchel mete,</L>
<L>Pouere men &thorn;arewith to freueri: of drunch and of mete".<NOTE PLACE="foot">st. of drunch and of mete ist am Rande nebengeschr.: to drinke and to ete, um den identischen Reim zu vermeiden.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o saide ore louerd to Judas:: "lat &thorn;ou &thorn;is wumman beo!</L>
<L N="105">Ful guod weork it was and is: &thorn;at heo wurchez in me;</L>
<L>For ai schulle &yogh;e pouere with eov habbe,: and so ne worth eov me.</L>
<L>&THORN;i toungue moste bien ischaue,: to speche heo is to freo".</L>
<L>Symund leprous iheorde &thorn;is;: he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte wel manifold</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if &thorn;es profete were also wys: ase he is fore itold,</L>
<L N="110">He nolde soffri &thorn;is fole wumman: his bodi enes to reppe,</L>
<L>For no weork &thorn;at heo can do: toward him enes steppe.</L>
<L>Ore louerd wuste is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,: ake &thorn;arof stod him non ey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>"Symund, &thorn;ou &thorn;enchest muche for nou&yogh;ht.: sum&thorn;ing ichulle &thorn;e sei&yogh;e".</L>
<L>"Maister, seye", seide Symound,: "ich it bidde &thorn;e!</L>
<L N="115">For &thorn;ou noldest for no &thorn;ing: segge onri&yogh;ht to me".</L>
<L>"An vsurer was &yogh;wilene: &thorn;at hadde dettores tweyne,
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>&THORN;at swy&thorn;e longue &yogh;wyle: dette him scholden beyne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">n in beyne &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at on him scholde fifti panes: and twenti &thorn;arto,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur him scholde of dette: fifti panewes also.</L>
<L N="120">And no&thorn;ur of heom nadde: &yogh;wareof &thorn;e dette forto &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>Huy &yogh;olden, &thorn;o he it creuede,: ase &thorn;e bok us telde(!).</L>
<L>&YOGH;we&thorn;ur of heom tweine: cudde him more loue &thorn;o?"</L>
<L>"Maister, he &thorn;at more &yogh;af,: me &thorn;inche, so mote i go".</L>
<L>"For so&thorn;e, Symund leperous,: &thorn;ou hauest idemed ari&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="125">For seth&thorn;e ich cam into &thorn;in hous,: &thorn;ou ne custest me no-wi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou ne wusche nou&yogh;t mine fiet: with watur ne with teres,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou ne wypedest heom nou&yogh;ht &yogh;uyt: with clo&thorn;e no with heres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">s in heres ist von and. Hand angesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Min heued on none halue: with no manere oynement</L>
<L>Ne smeordest, with none salue: ne with no piement;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. smeredest smeordest, doppelt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">Seth&thorn;e ich cam in to &thorn;in hous,: &thorn;is wumman nolde blinne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wumnan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mine fiet to wasche and cusse: withouten and withinne,</L>
<L>And to wipen heom seth&thorn;e afturward: with hire faire here,</L>
<L>Min heued also to smeorien: with riche oynement and dere.</L>
<L>"Op aris, &thorn;ou wumman,: &thorn;ine sunnes &thorn;e beoth for&yogh;yue!</L>
<L N="135">Also ich nou&thorn;e can and may,: of me &thorn;ou art ischriue".</L>
<L>Marie &thorn;e Maudeleyne: ore swete louerd hire schrof,</L>
<L>Swete Jesu Crist out of hire: seue deuelene he drof.</L>
<L>Ore louerd makede hire is procuratour,: his leof and is hostesse;</L>
<L>Heo louede him with gret honour: in pays and in destresse.</L>
<L N="140">Martha hire suster was ful sik,: and so heo hadde ibeo ful &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>At hire bi hinde heo hadde ibled: seuen &yogh;er and more;</L>
<L>Heo ne mi&yogh;hte for no&thorn;ing: no leche-craft afongue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">craft ist am Rande zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Are ore louerd, heouene king,: among heom &thorn;are gan &yogh;ongue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af hire is swete blessingue: and helde hire of hire sore</L>
<L N="145">And bad hire beon hol and sound;: and so heo was euereft-more.</L>
<L>Heore beire bro&thorn;ur Lazarus: was swy&thorn;e sikel a man.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jesus hereborewede at heore hous,: &yogh;wane he bi heom cam,</L>
<L>And his apostles alle,: &yogh;wane huy &thorn;are forth come:</L>
<L>Heore in huy gonne cleopie: an ase heore owene it nome;<NOTE PLACE="foot">an = and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Al swuch ase &thorn;are inne was: huy eten and huy drounke &mdash;</L>
<L>Men habbez ofte note of &thorn;ing: &thorn;at luytel it habbut swounke.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Jesus hadde &thorn;are ibeo: ase longue ase he wolde,</L>
<L>He wente to an o&thorn;ur contreye,: for men iseon him scholde.</L>
<L>Marie he &yogh;af is blessingue: and Martha and Lazarus,</L>
<L N="155">Muchele and luttle, elde and &yogh;ongue,: &thorn;at woneden in heore hous.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at he was iwend,: Marie was egleche:</L>
<L>Crist hire hauede aboute isent: to sarmoni and to preche;</L>
<L>To sunfole men he was ful rad: to wissi and to teche,</L>
<L>And to sike men heo wa(s) ful glad: to beon heore soule leche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wa st. was.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="152"></L>
<L N="160">Mani on to cristinedom: heo brou&yogh;hte, and out of sunne,</L>
<L>Fram lecherie and horedom,: &thorn;oru schrift, to joye and alle wunne.</L>
<L>Aftur ore louerdes passione: in &thorn;e &thorn;ritten &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Giwes weren proute and grimme,: olme and of lu&thorn;ere chere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">olme, altn. &oacute;lms = furious.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Steuene to de&thorn;e huy stenden,: &thorn;at was ore louerd ful deore,</L>
<L N="165">And manie men huy flemden: &thorn;at Cristes limes were.</L>
<L>Non apostle ne moste liue: in giwene londe,</L>
<L>Alle huy weren of londe idriue: with wrath&thorn;e and ny&thorn;e and onde.</L>
<L>Seint Maximus was &thorn;o: with godes apostles bicome;</L>
<L>Sixti ant ten deciples: togadere heom hadden inome;</L>
<L N="170">Marie &thorn;e Maudeleyne: and hire bro&thorn;ur Lazarus</L>
<L>And heore suster Martha: and &thorn;e bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>Mani mo of cristine men,: wel mo &thorn;ane i can nemne,</L>
<L>Weren ihote fleme,: and some to quelle and brenne.</L>
<L>Huy weren in a schip ipult: withouten ster and ore,</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;at huy scholden beon furfaren: and ne libben nomore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">furfaren st. spilt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no&thorn;ur ido with heom: no&thorn;ur watur ne bred,</L>
<L>For huy scholden of-hongrede beon: and sone &thorn;are-afturward ded.</L>
<L>Huy schypeden in &thorn;e salte se,: ase Jesu Crist it wolde,</L>
<L>Forto &thorn;at tyme scholde beo: &thorn;at huy ariui scholde.</L>
<L N="180">To Marcile &thorn;e wynd heom drof,: a gret name-couth cite.</L>
<L>Euerech of heom o&thorn;ur schrof,: are huy comen out of &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>Huy ne founden &thorn;are no freond: &thorn;at wolde heom hereboruwe,</L>
<L>Cristine man ne no giv,: an eue no&thorn;ur a moruwe,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;yuen heom mete ne drinke no&thorn;ur: ne lissen heore soruwe,</L>
<L N="185">Ne noman, for loue ne for swunch: &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;hten of bugge ne borewe.</L>
<L>In one olde porche: huy stunten al &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Withoute li&yogh;ht of torche,: withoute fuyr and candle bri&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>&THORN;e porche was an old hous,: of olde weorke iwrou&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hold mit wegpunctirtem h.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;udere in huy weren alle wel vouse: &thorn;at of &thorn;e se weren ibrou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="190">For huy nusten elle-&yogh;ware: &thorn;at huy stunte mi&yogh;hte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">elle st. elles.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote huy hadde gre(t) schame and teone,: and giwes with heom to fi&yogh;hte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. gre st. gret.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are huy duelden al &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht: forto it was day a moruwe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarasins heom boden fi&yogh;ht,: to echen heore soruwe.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at fram &thorn;e se: &thorn;uder weren icome,</L>
<L N="195">Huy nusten &yogh;wodere huy mi&yogh;hte fleo;: for&thorn;i huy weren inome.</L>
<L>Huy weren ihote ope lyf and lime: Jesu Crist fursake,</L>
<L>And, with &thorn;retningue and with strif,: to heore false godus take.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Marie Maudeleine: heo sai&yogh;h &thorn;at folk arise,</L>
<L>Riche and pouere, kny&yogh;ht and sweyn,: to don &thorn;at sacrefise:</L>
<L N="200">Heo was anuyd and of-drad,: &thorn;at hire bigan to grise;</L>
<L>To speken of god heo was ful rad,: and so dude on hire wise.</L>
<L>Op heo stod with wordes bolde,: with bri&yogh;ht neb and glade chere,</L>
<L>And seide: "herkniez to me, &yogh;unge and elde,: &thorn;at wullez beon Cristes:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das Reimwort fehlt.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>Ne bilieuez nou&yogh;ht opon Mahun,: ne on Teruagaunt, is fere,</L>
<L N="205">For huy beoth bo&thorn;e deue and doumbe: and huy ne mouwen iseo ne ihere,</L>
<L>Ne huy ne mouwen eov helpe nou&yogh;ht: of none kunnes &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei men of heom &yogh;elpen ou&yogh;t,: ne no guod to eu bringue:</L>
<L>For huy bez doumbe and deue,: crokede and eke blinde,</L>
<L>Heore mi&yogh;hte is fallen to grounde: biforen and bihinde.</L>
<L N="210">Ake &yogh;e schulle lieuen on Jesu Crist,: oure hei&yogh;e heouene kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;is worldes maister is,: withoute ani ending,</L>
<L>For he may don is wille: of euereche cunnes &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e wilniez with ri&yogh;hte: and withouten suneguyng;</L>
<L>He is withoute &thorn;e biguynningue: and he is withouten ende,</L>
<L N="215">Withoute fuyl&thorn;e and sunegyng,: so corteys and so hende</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at man with skile him biddez: he wole him &yogh;yue and sende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">biddez st. bit.</NOTE></L>
<L>To man &thorn;at goth and eke rit,: &thorn;at wole to him wende;</L>
<L>He is wuryte of alle &thorn;ing,: he makede heouene and helle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wuryte st. wuyrte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne may no kayser ne no kyng: his vertues alle telle;</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e man &thorn;at him seruez wel: ne may him no feond cwelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. dwelle, in cwelle corrig.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake huy &thorn;at wullez a&yogh;ein him fi&yogh;hte: to grounde he wole heom felle;</L>
<L>He makede day and eke ny&yogh;ht,: steorrene and sonne and mone;</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;at trewe is and louez him ari&yogh;t: he wole graunti him is bone,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he biddez him with treou&thorn;e: he it grauntez him ful sone,</L>
<L N="225">He helpez bo&thorn;e king and kny&yogh;ht,: &thorn;e pouere alle mididone".</L>
<L>A riche prince of sarazins: &thorn;udere was icome,</L>
<L>With him is wyf and his mayne: &thorn;at with him he hadde inome.</L>
<L>To Maries prechingue: he lustnede ful sone;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at heo was so fair a &thorn;ing,: to hire huy token guod gome.</L>
<L N="230">&THORN;e sarazins onvele: weren fulle of ny&thorn;e and hete.</L>
<L>&THORN;o it was time of mele,: huy wenden to heore mete;</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy comen hom vnsele: and &thorn;arto weren isete,</L>
<L>Cristes men to delen guod: ful clene huy hadden for&yogh;ete.</L>
<L>&THORN;are weren of cristine men: mo &thorn;ane sixti and tene;</L>
<L N="235">Noman nadde reu&thorn;e of heom,: and &thorn;at was &thorn;are isene:</L>
<L>Huy weren witoute mete and drunch,: in gret hongur and in teone,</L>
<L>Ne huy ne duden no weork ne swunch,: ne no&thorn;ing men nolde heom lene.</L>
<L>Hit was in one ny&yogh;hte: aftur &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is riche princes wif: in hire bedde lay:</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;are cam Marie Maudeleyne: and biforen hire heo stod:</L>
<L>"Dame, me &thorn;inchez &thorn;ou art vnhende;: for &thorn;ou hast muche guod,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ich habbe gret feorlich: and muche me &thorn;inchez wunder</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou last Jesu Cristes folk: &thorn;us steorue for hungur;</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;if &thorn;ou o&thorn;ur &thorn;i louerd: lissi heore kare,</L>
<L N="245">Wite &yogh;e midiwisse: sorewe eou schal beon ful &yogh;are:</L>
<L>Swuch a fierd schal opon eov come: &thorn;at schal eov so furfare</L>
<L>And aquellen eou and eouwer folk,: huy nellez eov no&thorn;ing spare".
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>&THORN;is riche princes wif &thorn;is word: nolde hire louerd nou&yogh;ht telle &mdash;</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e, heo was puyrliche vnwys,: in sawe and in spelle.</L>
<L N="250">&THORN;e o&thorn;ur ny&yogh;ht &thorn;e Maudeleyne: eftsone &yogh;eode hire to</L>
<L>And spak to hire wel stuyrneliche,: and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde nyht also;</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt heo nolde hire erinde: to hire louerd do.</L>
<L>Marie cam &thorn;e feor&thorn;e ny&yogh;ht: and bifore &thorn;e prince heo stod:</L>
<L>"Slepestou, tyraunt, &thorn;ou deueles kny&yogh;ht,: of Sathanasses blod?</L>
<L N="255">&THORN;i wif, &thorn;e naddre, heo is amad,: ich holde hire puyr wod:</L>
<L>Heo nolde &thorn;e telle &thorn;at ich bad,: for vuele ne for guod.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hauest mete and drunch inov&yogh;: and luytel o&thorn;ur care,</L>
<L>And soffrest Cristes men with wou&yogh;h: for hungur &thorn;us furfare!</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ou amendi heore stat sone,: &thorn;e is sorewe al &yogh;are:</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;are schal so strong folk come &thorn;e a&yogh;ein: &thorn;at wollez &thorn;e luytel spare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. stronk st. strong.</NOTE></L>
<L>With sweord and spere huy schullen &thorn;e sle: and al &thorn;i folk furfare".</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne &yogh;eode fram him: and liet him ligge &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;e quiene awok and si&yogh;hte sore: and tolde hire louerd so;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;hte him &thorn;at he iwarned was: &thorn;reo ny&yogh;htes and mo.</L>
<L N="265">Heo tolde him &thorn;at hire was iseid: and also ihote to do<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. said in seid corr., wie 281.</NOTE></L>
<L>Feden Jesu Cristes men: and lissi heom of heore wo,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur heom scholde sorewe inov&yogh;: and kare comen heom to.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;e prince: "Dame, &yogh;wat schulle we do<NOTE PLACE="foot">u. 9 sind im Ms. ein Vers.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;isse opene warningue: &thorn;at is icome us to?"</L>
<L N="270">"Betere is &thorn;at we Cristes men: swy&thorn;e wel heom fiede and schruyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ene we tellen luyte of heom: in vilte o&thorn;ur in pruyde".</L>
<L>Huy token Jesu Cristes men: and ladden hom to heore inne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hom st. heom.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at heom was neod huy founden heom: with loue and alle wunne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne heom radde wel: to witien heom fram sunne,</L>
<L N="275">So &thorn;at heom ne &thorn;orte neuere drede: of Sathanases kunne.</L>
<L>Opon a day heo bigan: godes word forto preche</L>
<L>And of godes lawe, with gret wit,: ase heo &thorn;ar mi&yogh;hte a-reche;</L>
<L>To leden heore lyf in guod fey: alle heo gan heom teche,</L>
<L>And forto louie god and don awey: wrath&thorn;e and onde and wreche.</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e prince saide &thorn;o to hire: with egleche wordes and bolde:</L>
<L>"Mi&yogh;ht &thorn;ou proui with treu&thorn;e,: &thorn;at &thorn;ou prechest may beo wel iholde?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne seide: "&yogh;e,: ich am redi eov to teche,</L>
<L>Bi ore maistres conseile: and mid is holie speche</L>
<L>&THORN;at is seinte Petre of Rome,: hov &yogh;e schullen on take</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;e blisse of heouene for to afongue: and &thorn;e feondes lore forsake".</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;e prince anon: and is wyf also:</L>
<L>"We beoz bo&thorn;e redie anon: &thorn;ine wille forto do,</L>
<L>So ase &thorn;i louerd is: of so muchel mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may, &yogh;wane he wole,: at is wille alle &thorn;ingus di&yogh;hte:</L>
<L N="290">Bide &thorn;ine louerd, heoue king,: &thorn;at is us alle aboue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">heoue, auch 437. 575.</NOTE></L>
<L>So ase he may don alle &thorn;ing,: and also for is moder loue,
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>And for &thorn;ine bisechingue,: &thorn;at he &yogh;yue a child &thorn;at beo a sone:</L>
<L>And at &thorn;ane forewarde: we wollez with eov wone,</L>
<L>Ore kinedom also forth with us: his owene we wollez bicome,</L>
<L N="295">And we wollez &yogh;elden a&yogh;ein to is men: &thorn;at we heom habbez binome".</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide Marie &thorn;e Maudeleine:: "&thorn;at nelle ich nou&yogh;ht bileue,</L>
<L>A preiere to mi louerd to make: nele me no&thorn;ing greue.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. no &thorn;inging.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ich bidde &thorn;e, swete Jesu Crist,: &thorn;at makedest sonne and mone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is prince siende a child,: and &thorn;at it beo a sone".</L>
<L N="300">Heo bad with guode heorte and milde.: heo was iheord ful sone:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke ny&yogh;ht huy geten a child,: ase god heom &yogh;af grace to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e prince wuste: &thorn;at is quiene was with childe,</L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;ht toward Jesu Crist: he wax meoke and milde.</L>
<L>Huy leten heore vuele dedes: &thorn;at weren so wikke and wilde,</L>
<L N="305">And aftur godes dedes: huy wrou&yogh;hten a gonne buylde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a st. an, and.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o swor &thorn;e prince and seide: "bi heued min,: wiende ichulle to Rome</L>
<L>And bicome a pilegrim: and don aftur &thorn;e holie dome,</L>
<L>And with seint Petur ichulle speke: and don aftur is redes,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it is so ase Marie seiz: of Jesu Cristes dedes;</L>
<L N="310">And &yogh;if &thorn;at ich him finde: at &thorn;e court of Rome,</L>
<L>Of him ichulle vnderfongue: fulloutht and cristindome".</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;e lauedi: "ichulle wiende with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;are &thorn;ou art icristned,: ichulle also beo;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane &thorn;ou comest hidere a&yogh;ein,: ich may come with &thorn;e".</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;o seide &thorn;e prince lei&yogh;inde: to is wif agame:</L>
<L>"And beo nou&thorn;e ase &thorn;ou seist,: mi leoue swete dame,</L>
<L>Bote in schipe wexez ofte soruwe,: peril and teone and grame;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou art nou&thorn;e with childe,: couth is &thorn;at guode fame:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e se &thorn;ou mi&yogh;htest: ful sone hente schame &mdash;</L>
<L N="320">&YOGH;uyt hadde ich leouere ich were ihuld,: and euere to ligge lame.</L>
<L>Ake bilef &thorn;ou athom and reste &thorn;e wel,: and &yogh;em alle ore &thorn;ingues!</L>
<L>At mine a&yogh;ein-come god siende me: of &thorn;e guode ti&thorn;ingues!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o spak &thorn;e lauedi, &thorn;e quiene,: and feol adoun to is fote:</L>
<L>"Leue louerd, &thorn;ou let beo &thorn;at,: and graunte me &thorn;at ich mote!</L>
<L N="325">&THORN;is ilke sorewe wole me aslen,: bote &thorn;ou do me bote".</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot seide &thorn;e leuedi,: and weop wel swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>Deolful and dreori heo ful adoun,: and seide ofte: "sire, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>Hov mi&yogh;hte ich libbe and beon glad: bote we to gadere wore?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. were, in wore corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>We loueden us so &yogh;oungue,: and nou&thorn;e we beoth sumdel hore".</L>
<L N="330">So longue and &yogh;eorne &thorn;is lauedi bad: hire louerd &thorn;at was so hende</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hire grauntede, and was ful glad,: with him forto wiende.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hire aus him corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For neodfole bisokne: of heom and heore men</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie blessingue with hire hond: Marie makede on heom,</L>
<L>For no wickede gost: bi &thorn;e weye ne scholde hem derie,</L>
<L N="335">&THORN;e holie rode tokningue: fram seoruwe heom scholde werie.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="156"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Marie heo mauden wardein: of heom and of heore schipe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swete holie Maudeleyne,: in Cristes wurthschipe,</L>
<L>For heo was &thorn;e kingue of heouene: leof and deore and queme,</L>
<L>And bitoken hire ech-del: to witien and to &yogh;eme.</L>
<L N="340">Huy nomen with heom into heore schip: bred inov&yogh; and wyn,</L>
<L>Venesun of heort and hynd: and of wilde swyn,</L>
<L>Huy nomen with heom in heore schip: al &thorn;at hem was leof,</L>
<L>Gies and hennes, crannes and swannes,: and porc, motoun and beof;</L>
<L>For huy scholden passi: &thorn;e grickische se,</L>
<L N="345">And for &thorn;at huy nusten hou longue: huy scholden &thorn;are-inne be.</L>
<L>Huy drowen op seil and ore: and schipeden anon ri&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Alle, &thorn;e lasse and &thorn;e more,: eorl, baroun and kny&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Huy nadden bote seue ny&yogh;ht: iseiled in &thorn;at flod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy neren sore of-dradde:: &thorn;e se wax stuyrne and wod.</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;e se bigan to flowen,: and &thorn;e wawes forto arise:</L>
<L>Some bigonne to swounen,: and heore heortene sore agrise.</L>
<L>&THORN;e se bigan to ebbi,: and &thorn;e wynd ful stuyrne to blowe.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e quiene on hire bedde lay,: hire token ful strongue &thorn;rowes,</L>
<L>Heo swounede ful ilomeliche: and harde pinede &thorn;arefore,</L>
<L N="355">So forto &thorn;at hire &yogh;oungue sone: were of hure ibore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at child ibore was,: &thorn;e moder bigan to deye.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk gradde allas allas,: and weopen with heore eye.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e leuedi was ded,: aftur &thorn;at &thorn;et child was ibore,</L>
<L>Huy ne mi&yogh;hten it bileue: to make deol &thorn;are fore.</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at child wolde souke,: and it nuste &yogh;wam,</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no milk aboute,: ne no mielch wumman.</L>
<L>"Allas", quath &thorn;e prince,: "&thorn;at ich euere was ibore!</L>
<L>Wo is me for &thorn;is &yogh;unge child,: and for mi quien &thorn;at ich habbe ilore!</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e it mot nede deye,: for souke ne hath i(t) non,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. i non st. it non.</NOTE></L>
<L N="365">Ne i not in none halue: &yogh;wat me is best to don".</L>
<L>&THORN;e schipmen hieten with stuyrne mod: &thorn;at men ne schulden nou&yogh;ht spare</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede quien to casten in &thorn;at flod,: o&thorn;ur elles huy mosten furfare</L>
<L>"&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at bodi is here with us,: &thorn;e stormes beoth so kete,</L>
<L>To quellen us huy &thorn;enchez,: and &thorn;at huy nellez lete".</L>
<L N="370">Huy nomen up &thorn;ad dede bodi,: in to &thorn;e se forto caste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ad st. &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Abidez &yogh;uyte and herkniez me!": &thorn;e prince gradde faste,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &yogh;e nellez for mi loue it lete,: ne for loue of mi wif,</L>
<L>Spariez for mi luytel sone,: so &thorn;at he mouwe habbe is lyf:</L>
<L>For &yogh;if is moder mouwe &yogh;uyt: of hire suoweningue awake,</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;anne may mi luytel sone: to hire tete take".</L>
<L>Huy lokeden heom biside: and sei&yogh;en an hei&yogh;h hurst</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e feor in &thorn;e se,: and &thorn;e prince it isai&yogh; furst.</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at wel more wisdom: to &thorn;e bodie it were</L>
<L>To burien it opon &thorn;et hei&yogh;e hurst,: &thorn;ane fisches it eten &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;o huy comen &thorn;udere,: huy ne mi&yogh;hten make no put:</L>
<L>&THORN;e hurst was al of harde stone,: ech faste in o&thorn;ur iknut.
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Huy nomen &thorn;e quiene and hire child: and wounden in a mantel,</L>
<L>And leide opon &thorn;e hei&yogh;e hurste: in a grene cantel;</L>
<L>Huy leiden &thorn;at childes mouth: to &thorn;e moder tete.</L>
<L N="385">&THORN;o &thorn;e prince &thorn;at isai&yogh;h,: with wepingue is neb he gan wete.</L>
<L>With gret deol &thorn;e quiene and hire child: &thorn;are huy gonne lete</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;et hurst &thorn;at was so hei&yogh;h: and hard and wilde and kete.<NOTE PLACE="foot">t in &thorn;et &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prince wep and wende forth: with his schip in &thorn;e se.<NOTE PLACE="foot">with = to.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Marie Maudeleyne", quath &thorn;e prince, "alas,: &thorn;at euere kneu ich &thorn;e!</L>
<L N="390">To don &thorn;is pelrimage: &yogh;wy raddest &thorn;ou me?</L>
<L>&THORN;ov bede &thorn;i god a bone: &thorn;at mi wif with childe scholde be:</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e is ded &thorn;us sone: bo&thorn;e hire child and heo.</L>
<L>Al mi lond and al mi &thorn;ing: ich habbe itake &thorn;e</L>
<L>To witen and to wardi;: &yogh;wi schal it &thorn;anne &thorn;us be?</L>
<L N="395">Mi wif and mi &yogh;ungue child,: Marie, ich bitake</L>
<L>To Jhesu Crist, &thorn;i owene louerd,: &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing of nou&yogh;ht gan make,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if he is so corteys and mi&yogh;htful: ase &thorn;ou seidest to me,</L>
<L>He saue mi wif and mi child,: furfare &thorn;at ich ne be".</L>
<L>To his schyp he wende,: and so forz in &thorn;e se.</L>
<L N="400">God hem to Rome sende,: for &thorn;udere wolden he.</L>
<L>Seinte Petur wuste wel: &thorn;at &thorn;e prince cam;</L>
<L>With milde mod and fair compaygnie: a&yogh;eines him he nam.</L>
<L>Petur axede him fram &yogh;wanne he cam,: and &yogh;wodere he wiende wolde.</L>
<L>"To Rome" he seide, "&thorn;en wey ich take: and speke with &thorn;e ischolde".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. icholde mit &uuml;bergeschr. s.</NOTE></L>
<L N="405">He tolde of Marie Maudeleyne,: hou he to hire cam,</L>
<L>And hou he Cristus sixti men: and tene to him nam,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vgl. 169, 234.</NOTE></L>
<L>He tolde him of is child,: he tolde him of is wif,</L>
<L>Hov he with milde heorte: for heom &thorn;olede strif.</L>
<L>Seinte Petur creoysede him: opon is ri&yogh;ht scholder,</L>
<L N="410">Of &thorn;at Marie hauede iseid: he hauede game and wonder,</L>
<L>And seide: "prince, welcome &thorn;ou be,: and &thorn;ine kni&yogh;htes alle!</L>
<L>Pays and grace with &thorn;e beo,: and joye &thorn;e mote on falle</L>
<L>In bour and in halle,: in field and in toun also,</L>
<L>In castel no&thorn;ur in boure: ne wor&thorn;e &thorn;e neuere wo,</L>
<L N="415">In watur and in londe: and in alle stude</L>
<L>God &thorn;e fram harme schilde,: and &thorn;at ich habbe i bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wif slepe nou&thorn;e: and &thorn;i sone him reste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ey st. &thorn;y.</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne weope nou&yogh;t for hem: ne make deol ne cheste!</L>
<L>Mi louerd is swi&thorn;e mi&yogh;thful,: he wole don is wille,</L>
<L N="420">And he is also quoynte and sley: bo&thorn;e loude and stille,</L>
<L>He can &yogh;yuen and binimen,: borewi and eke &yogh;ielde</L>
<L>For soruwe blisse, &yogh;wane his wille is,: in toune, in watere, in fielde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he is wroth, he doth wreche,: ake &thorn;at fallez ful sielde;</L>
<L>Ake of(te) gret fuyr and eke stuyrne: wext of a luytel spielde".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of st. ofte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="425">Petur ladde &thorn;ene riche man: a&yogh;ein to Jerusalem,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;annes &thorn;ene wey he man: with him to Bedlehem,
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>Fram &thorn;annes to &thorn;e flym Jordan,: an long bi &thorn;e strem &mdash;</L>
<L>I segge it ase ich ov telle can,: in boke and nou&yogh;ht in drem.</L>
<L>He schewede him Caluarie,: &thorn;are god was don on rode,</L>
<L N="430">His fiet and is hondene: al hou huy ronnen on blode,</L>
<L>He tolde him of &thorn;e &thorn;ornes: &thorn;at on his heued stode,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e nailes &thorn;at in is fiet: and in his hondene wode,</L>
<L>And &yogh;et he tolde him of &thorn;e spere: &thorn;at to &thorn;e heorte him stong,</L>
<L>And hou he an hei&yogh;h opon &thorn;e rode: deide with muche wrong,</L>
<L N="435">Hou he into helle cam: with Sathanas to fi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>And is folk &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne was: hou he it gan out di&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>Hou he aros, and to heoue steu&yogh;: to is fader sete</L>
<L>And sat him &thorn;are-inne, for he was gleu&yogh;,: and was him swy&thorn;e imete.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e prince hadde iheord: seint Peteres lore,</L>
<L N="440">He carede laste he were bicherd,: for he hadde ibeo &thorn;are so &yogh;ore;</L>
<L>He hadde ileorned swi&thorn;e wel: al clanliche his bileue,</L>
<L>His oures and is sauter ech-del.: &thorn;o seide he: "god it &yogh;eue</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich were sone: in mine owene contreye,</L>
<L>And al mi folk with flechs and blod,: ri&yogh;ht ase ich wolde, sei&yogh;e!"</L>
<L N="445">Seint Petur he bad par charite: cristni him anon</L>
<L>And al is o&thorn;ur mayne,: and laten heom wende hom</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne habben guod day,: "and &yogh;if us &thorn;ine blessingue!</L>
<L>We wollez so bliue so we mouwen: don us to schipijngue".</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou schalt withouten cristindom: wienden into &thorn;ine londe &mdash;</L>
<L N="450">Ne drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;th, for &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht it don: withoute schame and schonde!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne schal beon with &thorn;e: and to &thorn;e heo schal fongue,</L>
<L>Lazarus and Martha, al &thorn;re: bi &thorn;e huy schullen stonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;ou schalt icristned beo: &thorn;oru Jesu Cristes sonde,</L>
<L>And muche folk also of &thorn;ine contreye &mdash;: ne &thorn;inche &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to longue!</L>
<L N="455">An holi man schal cristni eov,: &thorn;e bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at can is mester don swi&thorn;e wel: in Jesu Cristus hous,</L>
<L>He wole beo &yogh;ep and eke rad,: sley and eke vous,</L>
<L>To cristni manie he wole beo glad: to is louerd Jesous &mdash;</L>
<L>He were a fol and unwis: &thorn;at ne were of glad and bli&thorn;e".</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;e prince tok leue of seint Petur: and &thorn;onkede him fale si&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince saide: "holie fader,: haue nov wel guod day!</L>
<L>Ichulle wienden hamward: so bliue so ich may".</L>
<L>He dude him into &thorn;e salte flod.: his schip bigan to go,</L>
<L>So bliue, for &thorn;e wind was guod,: a(s) swaluwe swift o&thorn;ur flo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a st. as.</NOTE></L>
<L N="465">Withinne &thorn;e seuenni&yogh;htte: &thorn;udere he was icome</L>
<L>&THORN;are he a&yogh;ein is wille bilefde: is wif and is sone.</L>
<L>Huy isei&yogh;en bi &thorn;e stronde: a luytel child gon pleye</L>
<L>With publes on is honde: bifore hem in &thorn;e weye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince stap out of &thorn;e schipe,: of hem alle he was &thorn;e furste,</L>
<L N="470">Opon &thorn;e stronde he &yogh;af a lupe,: he hi&yogh;ede him to &thorn;e hurste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at child was swi&thorn;e sore of-drad,: &thorn;o &thorn;e prince cam,</L>
<L>To his moder he was wel rad: and aboute &thorn;e necke hire nam.
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>&THORN;e leuedi lai wel stille and slep: opon a grene cantel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child for fere orn to hire: and crep under hire mantel.</L>
<L N="475">&THORN;o saide &thorn;at child: "hiderward: a &thorn;ing, me &thorn;ou&yogh;hte, i sai&yogh; come,</L>
<L>Of him ich am ful sore adrad: laste we beon inome".</L>
<L>"Beo stille, mi sone, mi leoue child!: he is mi worldes fiere.</L>
<L>For gladnesse wepe he wole: &thorn;at us findez here".<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach &thorn;at fehlt he?</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prince cam and fond hire &thorn;er: ligginde on &thorn;e hurste,</L>
<L N="480">&THORN;are ase he bilefde hire er,: and &thorn;at chil sek hire breste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">chil st. child.</NOTE></L>
<L>For joye he weop and sat on is knen: and heold up his honde:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at ich euere moste &thorn;is iseo,: ich &thorn;onki ore louerdes sonde.</L>
<L>A, swete Marie Maudeleine,: &thorn;at me wolde nou ri&yogh;ht &thorn;inche murie</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;hte &thorn;is wumman quikie a&yogh;ein: and liuen and hire sturie".</L>
<L N="485">&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;at word iseid,: his wif bigan to wake,</L>
<L>Of a swume heo schok and braid,: and sone bigan awake;<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach and fehlt seide, oder and ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And (seide): "&thorn;e hende Marie Maudeleyne: heo hath i&yogh;iue me space,</L>
<L>Fram de&thorn;e to liue heo hauez me ibrou&yogh;t: &thorn;oru hire louerdes grace,</L>
<L>Heo hauez ifed me and mi sone: and idon us alle guode;</L>
<L N="490">To seggen it &thorn;e &yogh;wi scholde ich schone?: &thorn;at &yogh;elde hire &thorn;e rode!</L>
<L>Heo hauez ibeon min hou(s)wif,: mi mayde and mi norice,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hou wyf.</NOTE></L>
<L>And bote ich &thorn;e (seide) hou heo heold mi lif,: for so&thorn;e, ich were nice.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach &thorn;e fehlt seide.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at seint Petur hath: seth&thorn;e ischewed &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;e swete Marie Maudeleyne: it hauez ischewed me:</L>
<L N="495">Heo me hauez on hire hond ilad: ouer &thorn;e salte strem</L>
<L>And set&thorn;e for&thorn;ere-more: to Jerusalem,</L>
<L>And set&thorn;e heo me ladde: Bedlehem for to seo,</L>
<L>&THORN;udere ase seint Petur: bifore ladde &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e to &thorn;e flum Jordan: heo ladde me ful ra&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="500">Withoute harme and si&yogh;ht of man: and withoute schame and sca&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And oueral heo me ladde,: mi louerd, &thorn;are &thorn;ou were;</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;ou scholdest joyful beo,: nou&thorn;e ri&yogh;ht heo brou&yogh;hte me here".</L>
<L>Quath &thorn;e prince: "ich &thorn;onki god almi&yogh;hti: &thorn;at ich eov habbe aliue.</L>
<L>Arisez bo&thorn;e, &yogh;if &yogh;e mouwen,: and go we to schipe ful bliue!"</L>
<L N="505">Huy duden heom to &thorn;e watere: and schipeden alle anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd was blowinde swi&thorn;e wel,: and heore schip bigan to gon.</L>
<L>Huy gonne to seili swi&thorn;e: in &thorn;at salte fom,</L>
<L>And hi&yogh;eden heom ful bliue,: &thorn;at huy weren at hom.</L>
<L>Withinne a quartron of &thorn;e &yogh;ere: huy comen to Marcilie.</L>
<L N="510">Mani men of feor and ner: of heom gonne speke and spilie,</L>
<L>Manie hem hadden togadere inome,: eorl, baron, kny&yogh;ht and swein,</L>
<L>Are huy weren to londe icomen,: for to wenden heom a&yogh;ein,</L>
<L>Sarazins and &thorn;e giwes some,: and &thorn;e Marie Maudeleyn.</L>
<L>Martha cam and Lazarus,: of heom huy weren ful glad,</L>
<L N="515">And &thorn;e holie bischop Maximus,: to heom he was ful rad,</L>
<L>And manie of cristine men,: huy neren no&thorn;ing of-drad
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>To comen and gon a&yogh;einest him: and don &thorn;at he heom bad.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e prince and is wyf: weren icome to londe,</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;e Maudeleyne withoute strif: ireuested &thorn;are huy founde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o huy comen fram schipes bord,: Marie huy founden stonde</L>
<L>Forto prechen godes word: to heom &thorn;at were on londe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince tok is wif and is sone: with heorte guod and swete,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tok tok.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e Maudeleyne huy comen: and fellen doun to hire fete,</L>
<L N="525">And tolden hire al heore lijf: &thorn;at heom bifeol in &thorn;at weye,</L>
<L>Pays and loue, harm and strif,: al huy gonne hire sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Huy lieten &thorn;ane bischop Maximus: cristni heom anon,</L>
<L>Marie and Martha and Lazarus: huy brou&yogh;hten heom &thorn;aron.</L>
<L>&THORN;e children and &thorn;e wummen alle: &thorn;at weren in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="530">Alle huy nomen cristindom,: and &thorn;at was &thorn;oru godes sonde.</L>
<L>Ich wot, huy nomen heore false godes: and casten heom &thorn;are doune,</L>
<L>And brenden al to poudre: feor fram euerech toune;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hinter poudre ist im Ms. fram toune durchgestrichen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Huy duden arere churches: ouer al &thorn;e contreies,</L>
<L>And priories wurche,: and manie guode abbeies,</L>
<L N="535">And preostes huy gonne makien: oueral in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>Sudecknes and o&thorn;ur clerkus,: to serui heom to honde.</L>
<L>Huy mauden Lazarus bischop,: &thorn;e Maudeleynes bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie bischop Maximus: maude also mani ano&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>&THORN;o al &thorn;at lond cristine was: and al &thorn;at folc &thorn;are-inne,</L>
<L N="540">Marie bi&thorn;ou&yogh;hte a wonder cas:: and stal awey fram hire kunne,</L>
<L>In to wildernesse he wende,: al forto wonien &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he st. heo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Swuch grace god hire sende,: heo was &thorn;are &thorn;ritti &yogh;eres.</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no watur aboute,: ne &thorn;are ne wax no treo</L>
<L>&THORN;at ani best mi&yogh;hte onder at-route: &thorn;e betere an ayse to beo.</L>
<L N="545">For so&thorn;e ichulle &yogh;eov telle: of a ferliche wonder:<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle st. say.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aungles comen euereche day: ri&yogh;ht abouten ondern,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. onden mit &uuml;bergeschr. r &uuml;ber n.</NOTE></L>
<L>And nomen swi&thorn;e softeliche: &thorn;e Marie Maudelein<NOTE PLACE="foot">softeliche st. softe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And beren hire op in to &thorn;e lofte,: and brou&yogh;hten hire eft a&yogh;ein.</L>
<L>Men nusten hou heo leouede,: for noman ne sai&yogh;h hire ete;</L>
<L N="550">Ake some huy onderstoden: &thorn;at heo liuede bi aungelene mete.</L>
<L>A preost &thorn;are was in Marcilie: &thorn;at wilned swi&thorn;e muche</L>
<L>For to leden elinge lif, . &thorn;e betere fram sunne him wite:<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor wite fehlt to.</NOTE></L>
<L>He maude him a wonijngue: in &thorn;at wildernesse</L>
<L>&THORN;are Marie, &thorn;e swete Maudeleine,: wonede in clennesse;</L>
<L N="555">He ne bulde nou&yogh;ht fram Marie: bote a wel luyte mile;</L>
<L>For to quemen god he it dude,: and he &yogh;eld wel is &yogh;wile.</L>
<L>He hadde wunder for &thorn;at he sai&yogh;h: &thorn;at &thorn;e aungles comen ofte</L>
<L>Aboute onderne eche daye,: ase he stod in is crofte,</L>
<L>And hou huy beren &thorn;e Maudeleyne: an hei op on lofte,</L>
<L N="560">And also hou huy brou&yogh;hten hire a&yogh;ein: and setten hire adoun wel softe.
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>&THORN;e preost aros opon a day: and wende neor &thorn;e stude:</L>
<L>He wolde iwite &yogh;wat he isai&yogh;h,: and &thorn;arefore he it dude;</L>
<L>To &thorn;ulke stude he cam so nei&yogh;h: al bote a stones caste:</L>
<L>&THORN;o bigonne hise &thorn;eon to schrinke: and to croki swi&thorn;e faste;</L>
<L N="565">Adrad he was, and turnde a&yogh;ein,: and so he moste nede;</L>
<L>Ne knev he nou&yogh;t &thorn;e Maudeleyne: ne hire guode dedes.</L>
<L>Eftsone he &yogh;eode him &thorn;udeward:: is fiet bigonne folde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;udeward st. &thorn;uderward.</NOTE></L>
<L>His heorte and his inneward: him gonnen al to colde;</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;hte it was sum derne &thorn;ing: o&thorn;ur som holi priuete,</L>
<L N="570">Icomen fram &thorn;e heuene king,: &thorn;at he ne scholde it nou&yogh;ht iseo.</L>
<L>He sat adoun opon is kneon: and bad ore louerd &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he moste iwite and seon: &yogh;wat &thorn;at feorlich were;</L>
<L>He gradde on eornest and on game:: "&thorn;ou best in &thorn;ine celle,</L>
<L>Ich halsni &thorn;e a godes name: of &thorn;i stat &thorn;at &thorn;ou me telle!"</L>
<L N="575">Heo bigan to tellen: wordes him a&yogh;ein:</L>
<L>"I segge it &thorn;e for so&thorn;e,: ich am Marie Maudeleyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e kingue of heoue: of mine sunnes ich me schrof,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heone.</NOTE></L>
<L>And foule deuelene seouene: out of me he drof.</L>
<L>Ich habbe iwoned nou&thorn;e here: fulle &thorn;ritti &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="580">Ake i ne sai&yogh;h neuere noman &thorn;us nei&yogh;h: bote &thorn;e nou&thorn;e her.</L>
<L>Of no &thorn;ing &thorn;at ani man: of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e euere biswonk,</L>
<L>I ne et, seth&thorn;e ich hidere cam,: no mete, ne no drunch ne dronk;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Godes aungles euerech day: habbe me here inome</L>
<L>An ibore me alnewey,: &yogh;wane ischolde come,<NOTE PLACE="foot">an st. and.</NOTE></L>
<L N="585">An hei&yogh;h to heouene lofte,: euere &yogh;wane i ete scholde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. it st. i.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hidere a&yogh;ein wel softe,: &yogh;wane ich mi sulf wolde.</L>
<L>Ich halsni &thorn;e a godes name: &thorn;at &thorn;ou wende to Marcilie,</L>
<L>And with mine freond withoute blame: loke wel &thorn;at &thorn;ou spilie:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gret wel Martha, mi soster, ofte,: and mi bro&thorn;er Lazarus,</L>
<L N="590">And also gret ofte swi&thorn;e wel: &thorn;ene bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>And seie hem wel ichulle comen: a sonenday at eue,</L>
<L>With heom for to wonie: and euere with heom bileue &mdash;</L>
<L>For ischal to paradis: newene fram heom fare,</L>
<L>Ake mi bodi, for so&thorn;e iwis,: bileue schal with heom &thorn;are;</L>
<L N="595">Sei&yogh;e heom &thorn;at huy kepen me: aftur &thorn;e midni&yogh;hte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. mid ri&yogh;hte.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;are ich hopie for to beo: &thorn;oru godes swete mi&yogh;hte".</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie preost him wende forth: and dude hire herinde anon<NOTE PLACE="foot">herinde mit unorg. h.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop Maximus,: ase heo bad him don.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie bischop Maximus: was glad of &thorn;at sonde,</L>
<L N="600">And for &thorn;at ti&thorn;ingue he &thorn;onkede god: and to him heold up is honde.</L>
<L>Hire soster and hire bro&thorn;er: weren &thorn;arof wel fayn:</L>
<L>"Nou comez oure maister sone,: &thorn;e Marie Maudeleyn".</L>
<L>Of &thorn;isilke ty&thorn;ingues: huy weren swi&thorn;e glad</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy hadden iheord,: ake some weren of-drad
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="162"></L>
<L N="605">&THORN;at huy bitrayde weren;: ake &thorn;e bischop Maximus</L>
<L>Wuste wel &thorn;at hit was sothz;: to seon hire he was joyous,</L>
<L>And to witen hire stat euerechdel: he was wel corajous.</L>
<L>For to seon &thorn;ane messager: &thorn;ene sonenny&yogh;ht he wakede</L>
<L>And al ny&yogh;ht was in heore queor,: and his oresones he makede:</L>
<L N="610">Bifore &thorn;e hei&yogh;e auter ore louerd he bad: &thorn;at he moste iseo</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleynes face,: &thorn;at he &thorn;e gladdore mi&yogh;hte beo.</L>
<L>Sone aftur &thorn;e midni&yogh;ht,: are ani koc him crev,</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam a wonder muche li&yogh;ht,: ake no wynd &thorn;are ne blev:</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungles comen fram heouene: and brou&yogh;hten &thorn;e Marie,</L>
<L N="615">Huy seiden &thorn;e salmus seouene: and &thorn;e letanie;</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e eor&thorn;e huy gonne hire holden: swi&thorn;e longue stounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle heo makede hire preyere,: and seth&thorn;e lieten hire to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam wit hire swuch a smul: among heom euerechon,</L>
<L>In churche, in halle and in bour,: &thorn;at swuch ne smulden huy neuer er non.</L>
<L N="620">&THORN;e bischop for &thorn;e muchele lij&yogh;ht: and for &thorn;at swote smullingue</L>
<L>Sumdel &thorn;arefore he was aferd,: and a luyte him drov&yogh; bihinde.</L>
<L>Marie turnede, of wordes freo: and of vilenie quijt and sker,</L>
<L>And seide: "fader, &yogh;wy wolt&thorn;ou &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter fleo?: abid, and cum me ner!"</L>
<L>He sai&yogh;h hire neb, and turnde a&yogh;ein,: so bri&yogh;ht so sonne-bem,</L>
<L N="625">Of &thorn;at swete Maudeleine,: so lij&yogh;ht so ani leom.</L>
<L>Heo saide: "fader Maximus,: par seinte charite,</L>
<L>Schrift and hosel ich &yogh;uyrne,: sone &thorn;ou graunte it me!"</L>
<L>Huy cleopeden alle &thorn;e preostes: and &thorn;e clerkus euerechon</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ur ministres,: and duden hire wille anon.</L>
<L N="630">Heo it aueng wepinde: with guod deuocion,</L>
<L>And wel sore sichinde: heo lay hire sulf adoun</L>
<L>And seide: "Jhesu, &thorn;at deidest opon &thorn;e treo,: al mi stat &thorn;ou wost;</L>
<L>Into &thorn;ine hondene ich bitake &thorn;e: mi lijf and mi gost".</L>
<L>Anon ri&yogh;ht heo &yogh;af up hire lijf: and hire gost iwis.</L>
<L N="635">Heo was ilad withouten strif: anon ri&yogh;ht to paradys.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bischope &thorn;ou&yogh;hte murie: and &thorn;e clerkes echon,</L>
<L>And anon ri&yogh;ht gonne hire burien: in a marbreston.</L>
<L>Seue ni&yogh;ht &thorn;are-afturward,: &thorn;at day &thorn;at heo ibured was,</L>
<L>Ni&yogh;ht and day &thorn;at smul was &thorn;are &mdash;: it was a wonder cas.</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;e bischop &thorn;ou&yogh;hte murie,: and bad, &yogh;wane he ded were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men him scholden burien: bisiden hire ri&yogh;ht &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Maudeleine: &thorn;is is &thorn;e ri&yogh;hte endingue.</L>
<L>God us schilde fram peyne: and to heouene us bringue!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="b" TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000169.tif" N="[163]">
<HEAD>b) aus Ms. Auchinl. Edinb. Advoc. Libr., fol. 62-65<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Version ist bereits edirt In "Legendae Catholicae", ed. Turnbull 1840 (nur in wenigen Exemplaren vorhanden). Der Text folgt hier nach einer neuen Abschrift des Ms. von Miss Toulmin Smith; Mr. Furnivall hatte die G&uuml;te, deren Aufnahme in diese Sammlung zu gestatten. Ausserdem ist eine Abschrift E. K&ouml;lbing's zu Rathe gezogen.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>&amp; Martha keped swi&thorn;e wel</L>
<L>Hir londes euerich a del;</L>
<L>Sche &yogh;af hir al to almose-dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pouer to clo&thorn;e &amp; to fede.</L>
<L N="5">&amp; &thorn;e Maudelein Marie</L>
<L>Sche hir &yogh;aue al to folie,</L>
<L>To wille of bodi sche hir ches,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir kinde name sche les<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nanre st. name.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; was ycleped, as swiche schul,</L>
<L N="10">Mari &thorn;e sinful.</L>
<L>Bot as Jhesu preched &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Our bileue, &amp; elles-where,</L>
<L>&amp; Marie it vnderstode,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sche wex dreri of mode;</L>
<L N="15">Sche sou&yogh;t Jhesu for hir misdede</L>
<L>&amp;, &thorn;ere he was, to him sche &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>In halle wi&thorn; Simound leprous,</L>
<L>Where sche fond him in an hous,</L>
<L>&amp; his deciples, &thorn;er &thorn;ai sete,</L>
<L N="20">Wi&thorn; Simound leprous, atte mete.</L>
<L>Bot for hir sinne &amp; hir misgong,</L>
<L>&amp; for men were hem among,</L>
<L>Sche no durst hir nou&yogh;t for&thorn; pilt &mdash;</L>
<L>For euer he schone&thorn; &thorn;at ha&thorn; misgilt.</L>
<L N="25">Bot &thorn;at sche durst do, sche it dede:</L>
<L>An oinement sche brou&yogh;t hir mide,</L>
<L>Tofore Jhesu at his fete</L>
<L>Sche kneled adoun, &amp; sore wepe,</L>
<L>Sche wesche his fet wi&thorn; hir tere,</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en wiped hem wi&thorn; hir here,</L>
<L N="30">&amp; wi&thorn; oinement hem smerd.</L>
<L>When Simounde &thorn;at ysei&yogh;e &amp; herd,</L>
<L>Anon in hert he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;at he godes sone were</L>
<L>And a prophete witterlie,</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;an wist he wele sikerlie</L>
<L>What &thorn;is woman were, &amp; who:</L>
<L>He suffred hir nou&yogh;t touche him so".</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan Jhesu Simon vpbreyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. go oder so?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of his &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &amp; to him seyd:</L>
<L N="40">"Simounde, se&thorn;en ich com to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nere so curteise to &yogh;iue me</L>
<L>No water to mi sore fete;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en sche com, nou&yogh;t sche lete</L>
<L>For to wasche hem wi&thorn; hir tere,</L>
<L N="45">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en wiped hem wi&thorn; hir here:</L>
<L>No &thorn;ou ne &yogh;eue me no lent</L>
<L>To min fet non oinement,</L>
<L>&amp; sche wi&thorn; oinement wel riche</L>
<L>Hem ha&thorn; yheled wel softliche".</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;us gan Jhesu Simond vpbreyd,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o to &thorn;e Maudelein seyd:</L>
<L>"Woman, for &thorn;e loue &thorn;ou hast to me</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ine sinnes for&yogh;iue y &thorn;e". &mdash;</L>
<L>Sinful man, haue &thorn;is in &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="55">&amp; loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou for&yogh;ete it nou&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. in in, doppelt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hou sche loued god in hert miche</L>
<L>&amp; he it hir &yogh;ald wel sweteliche;
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>So dere nis &thorn;ing to god aboue</L>
<L N="60">As of mannes hert trewe loue;</L>
<L>To euerich sinne his loue is salue,</L>
<L>Astow mi&yogh;t sen on ich halue. &mdash;</L>
<L>In graue sche sou&yogh;t him, &thorn;er he lay,</L>
<L>When his deciples weren oway;</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;erfore Jhesu schewed him first</L>
<L>To hir after his vprist.</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er honour Jhesu hir dede</L>
<L>Toforn &thorn;e iewes in a stede:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at sche wepe, Jhesu gan wepe,</L>
<L N="70">&amp; he &thorn;at four dayes depe</L>
<L>Ded smelland had lain in graue,</L>
<L>God made him eft his liif to haue:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was Lazar, hir bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Martha, hir soster, he dede ano&thorn;er:</L>
<L N="75">Martha hadde an iuel strong,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir hadde holden seuen &yogh;er long:</L>
<L>&amp; god hir made hole &amp; fere</L>
<L>For Maris loue &amp; hir preiere.</L>
<L>After &yogh;eres tviis seuen</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at Jhesu Crist stei&yogh;e in to heuen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at pined was opon &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e iewes fals &amp; wode:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e deciples &thorn;at Jhesu hadde</L>
<L>In wide londes &thorn;an weren yspradde;</L>
<L N="85">Bot euer &thorn;ai gun for to preche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ri&yogh;t bileue &thorn;e folk to teche.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e apostles &thorn;er was &thorn;an</L>
<L>Maximin, a wel gode man,</L>
<L>To whom Petre bitau&yogh;t hadde</L>
<L N="90">&THORN;e Maudeleine &amp; to him badde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld togider go,</L>
<L>For doute of &thorn;e iewes, euermo:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelein &amp; Maximin,</L>
<L>Lazar, Martha &amp; Martin,</L>
<L N="95">Wi&thorn; hem &thorn;er was Martinian,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Martiman?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;er was ano&thorn;er man</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at he was born</L>
<L>His ei&yogh;e-si&yogh;t he hadde forlorn</L>
<L>&amp; for his godenisse god almi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="100">Him &yogh;af &thorn;ere his ei&yogh;e-si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewes gun hem togider calle,</L>
<L>&amp; her conseil token alle</L>
<L>In an eld schippe to don hem &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen seil, wi&thorn;outen ore.</L>
<L N="105">Wel fast wepe &thorn;at compeinie</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren in &thorn;e schippe wi&thorn; Marie.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e see &thorn;ai weren ypilt,</L>
<L>To be bo&thorn;e dreynt &amp; spilt.</L>
<L>Bot god, &thorn;at al &thorn;ing may se,</L>
<L N="110">In lond, in water, were &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L>He made hem alle to ben oliue,</L>
<L>&amp; at Marsil for to ariue.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai founde &thorn;er no wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem wold herberwe &thorn;at ni&yogh;t</L>
<L N="115">No hem help wi&thorn; non almose-dede.</L>
<L>Into an old porche &thorn;ai &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at stode toforn a mannes hous.</L>
<L>&THORN;urch &thorn;e grace of swete Jhesus</L>
<L>&THORN;ai lay &thorn;er, what &thorn;e day gun dawe,</L>
<L N="120">&amp; of &thorn;at rist &thorn;ai were ful fawe.</L>
<L>When it was day, &thorn;ai token hede</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;e folk to toun &yogh;ede</L>
<L>&amp; in to her temple &thorn;ai gun gon</L>
<L>To anour her maummettes of tre &amp; ston.</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e Maudeleine &thorn;o &amp; hir fere</L>
<L>Wenten in to &thorn;e temple &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;e Maudelein gan preche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk &thorn;e ri&yogh;t bileue to teche,</L>
<L>Of Jhesus in Carnacdun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. carnacdum st. Capharnaum?</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">&amp; hou he suffred passioun</L>
<L>For hir &amp; ous and al mankinde&mdash;</L>
<L>Of dedely sinne god ous vnbinde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani of ous &thorn;er-in be.</L>
<L>Amen, seyt alle par charite.</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;e folk of hir gret wonder hadde,</L>
<L>Of hir bileue &thorn;ai held hir madde;</L>
<L>Wonder &thorn;ai hadde more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>Of hir faucoun &amp; hir fairnisse.</L>
<L>No wonder, &thorn;ei in hir mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="140">More swetnisse were cou&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;an in ani o&thorn;er mi&yogh;t be:</L>
<L>For Jhesu, &thorn;at dyed on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; derwor&thorn;i kisse &amp; wi&thorn; wepe</L>
<L>Lete hir kisse his fair fet.</L>
<L N="145">Of &thorn;at lond &thorn;e prince &thorn;o,</L>
<L>He &amp; his wiif, bigun to go</L>
<L>Her maumettes to honour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t gete a child in bour.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;is herd &thorn;e Maudelain,</L>
<L N="150">Fast sche preched &thorn;er-o&yogh;ain.</L>
<L>O ni&yogh;t to bed &yogh;ede &thorn;ai to,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince &amp; his wiif also;</L>
<L>Wel fair in armes togider &thorn;ai lain:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ider com &thorn;e Maudelain</L>
<L N="155">In meteing to hem tvay alon,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e wiif sche made hir mon</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: "se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at &yogh;e so riche be,</L>
<L>Godes men whi suffre &yogh;e</L>
<L>To die for hunger &amp; for chele,</L>
<L N="160">&amp; &yogh;e haue plente of alle wele?"</L>
<L>Sche bad &thorn;e wiif hir lord say,</L>
<L>&amp; so him bidden &amp; so him pray,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e gode men &thorn;at were &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Schuld be holpen &thorn;urch her praiere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">u. &ouml;. Ms. anscheinend durch &thorn;urth st. &thorn;urch.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">&THORN;e wiif drad in hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche no durst say him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;e Mari Maudelein</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er ni&yogh;t com ogain</L>
<L>&amp; seyd as &yogh;e han yherd.</L>
<L N="170">&THORN;at wiif was sore aferd,</L>
<L>Sche no durst nou&yogh;t to hir lord sain</L>
<L>No for &thorn;e pouer bid no prain.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelain hir gan to hi&yogh;e</L>
<L>&amp; cam o&yogh;ain &thorn;e &thorn;ridde si&thorn;e</L>
<L N="175">&amp; schewed her to hem bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grim loke &amp; wi&thorn; wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; a brenand chere,</L>
<L>As al &thorn;e house were afere;</L>
<L>Sche seyd to him: "awake, tirran!</L>
<L N="180">Remembre &thorn;e of &thorn;i fader Satan!</L>
<L>&THORN;i wiif, &thorn;at is &thorn;ere bi &thorn;e brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer nold telle &thorn;e nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ichir seyd &amp; badde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ligge in glotonie al sadde</L>
<L N="185">In &yogh;our palais white so milk,</L>
<L>Honged wi&thorn; riche clo&thorn;es of silk;</L>
<L>&amp; godes men &thorn;at lin in wo,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen herberwe &yogh;e leten hem go!</L>
<L>Y warn &thorn;e now, &thorn;ou wreche vnkinde,</L>
<L N="190">Ano&thorn;er answere &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t finde</L>
<L>&THORN;e pouer what &thorn;ou hast &yogh;euen &amp; lent".</L>
<L>&THORN;us sche seyd, &amp; oway went.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince &thorn;o of his slepe woke,</L>
<L>His wiif in his armes toke,</L>
<L N="195">&amp; seyd: "wostow, dame, what ich herd?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiif o&yogh;ain answerd:</L>
<L>"Sir, so grete drede is to me comen</L>
<L>&THORN;at nei&yogh;e mi liif is me binomen.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enke&thorn;, sir, &thorn;at better is if</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at we do as sche ous bit,</L>
<L>&THORN;an god, of whom sche ginne&thorn; to preche,</L>
<L>Take on ous hard wreche".</L>
<L>A morwe &thorn;o &thorn;e prince aros,</L>
<L>Of his sweuen sore him agros;</L>
<L N="205">&THORN;e Maudelain &amp; alle her feren</L>
<L>He ladde hem hom, as &yogh;e may heren,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mete &amp; drink he hem fedde</L>
<L>&amp; wi&thorn; riche clo&thorn;es hem schredde.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;at pople &thorn;urch vertu</L>
<L N="210">Sche gan preche of Jhesu,</L>
<L>His passioun &amp; his vprist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mani man &thorn;erof agrist;</L>
<L>Mani man to hir &thorn;er come</L>
<L>&amp; vnderfenge cristendome.</L>
<L N="215">&THORN;e wiif &yogh;ede to &thorn;e Maudelain</L>
<L>&amp; anon sche gan hir frain</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at sche hadde power &amp; mi&yogh;t</L>
<L>Forto avowe her lawe ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche of preched ni&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
<L N="220">Sche seyd: "&yogh;a, dame, par ma fay!</L>
<L>&THORN;erto ich am redi ywis,</L>
<L>For our lawe oft proued is</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; fele miracles &thorn;at god wil schewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at stable is our lay &amp; trewe,</L>
<L N="225">Ri&yogh;t as seint Peter ous teche&thorn;,</L>
<L>Our maister, in Rome, &thorn;er he preche&thorn;".</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince &amp; his wiif gun seyn:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;i lord so prein</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at &thorn;ou so preche&thorn; ous,</L>
<L N="230">A child &thorn;at he wald sende ous,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wold we leuen sikerly</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is god almi&yogh;ti".</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelain answerd o&yogh;en:</L>
<L>"Leten &thorn;erfore schal it nou&yogh;t ben".</L>
<L N="235">To Jhesu Crist sche bad a bone:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiif a child conseiued sone.
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;e prince &thorn;at gan se,</L>
<L>To Rome sore longed he</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as a pilgrim for to go,</L>
<L N="240">To wite of Peter &yogh;if it wer so,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it of Jhesu were &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>To wite &thorn;e so&thorn;e he was ful fawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e princes wiif gan to say:</L>
<L>"Sir, &yogh;if &yogh;e schul wende &thorn;at way,</L>
<L N="245">To passe &thorn;ider wi&thorn;outen me</L>
<L>No wold neuer god it schuld so be;</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &yogh;e go, &thorn;an wil y go,</L>
<L>&amp; when &yogh;e ride, ichil also,</L>
<L>When &yogh;e duellen, &thorn;an wil y &mdash;</L>
<L N="250">No no&thorn;er schal it be, sikerly".<NOTE PLACE="foot">no no&thorn;er st. non o&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e prince seyd: "dame, nay,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; me wenden &thorn;ou ne may.</L>
<L>No were &thorn;e se neuer so milde,</L>
<L>&amp; a woman were wi&thorn; childe</L>
<L N="255">In schippe wi&thorn; trauail bistadde,</L>
<L>Alle we mi&yogh;t be sore adradde:</L>
<L>Men wold siggen in a while</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai weren in gret perile:</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;if sche soner were vnbounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. sche sche.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">Sche mi&yogh;t dye in a stounde</L>
<L>In schippe bifor ous euerichon.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;ou may nou&yogh;t wi&thorn; me gon;</L>
<L>At hom nedes y mot &thorn;e leten,</L>
<L>Our godes for to kepen".</L>
<L N="265">"For al loue, leman", sche seyd,</L>
<L>Lete now &thorn;at wille be doun aleyd!"</L>
<L>Sche wepe &amp; crid &amp; prayd him so</L>
<L>&THORN;at he graunt hir wi&thorn; him to go.</L>
<L>A schippe &thorn;ai gun to puruayen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;ai &thorn;ai.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">&amp; richelich wi&thorn;in to laien</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;ing &thorn;at hem nede stode;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en al her o&thorn;er gode</L>
<L>&THORN;ai bitau&yogh;ten &thorn;e Maudelain</L>
<L>To kepen, what &thorn;ai com o&yogh;ain.</L>
<L N="275">&amp; in to schippe &thorn;ai deden hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>So swi&thorn;e so &thorn;ai mi&yogh;ten go.</L>
<L>No haue &thorn;ai nou&yogh;t sailed ari&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bot a day &amp; on ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e se wel hard bigan</L>
<L N="280">To &yogh;ellen &amp; to belien &thorn;an.</L>
<L>&THORN;e schippemen &thorn;o gun fast rowen,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e wawes o&yogh;ain to &thorn;rowen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of hem alle &thorn;er was non</L>
<L>&THORN;at times among hem euerichon</L>
<L N="285">&THORN;at he ne wende haue forgon his liif;</L>
<L>&amp; nameliche &thorn;e princes wiif:</L>
<L>What for drede &amp; what for wo,</L>
<L>Hard sche gan to trauail &thorn;o.</L>
<L>A fair knaue-child &thorn;er was born;</L>
<L N="290">Ac &thorn;e moder liif it was forlorn.</L>
<L>Grete pite men mi&yogh;t &thorn;er sen</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at child no mi&yogh;t nou&yogh;t ben</L>
<L>Yholpen certes in maner non,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;e moder liif it hadde forgon,</L>
<L N="295">&amp; hou it seke &thorn;e moder tete,</L>
<L>Kinde sustenaunce for to gete.</L>
<L>&amp; when it no milk gete mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader &thorn;an wel sore he si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He seyd: "allas, hir fode is wane;</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;is grom is his moders bane.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en it may no lenger no fode haue,</L>
<L>Dye nedes most &thorn;e knaue".</L>
<L>Wel sore wepe &thorn;o &thorn;e pilgrim &mdash;</L>
<L>Ha, god almi&yogh;ti! wo was him:</L>
<L N="305">He sei&yogh;e his wiif dede him biforn,</L>
<L>&amp; his sones help was forlorn.</L>
<L>He wepe we[l] sore &amp; seyd: "allas!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. we st. wel.</NOTE></L>
<L>So michel as mi wille was</L>
<L>Bi mi wiif to han a knaue,</L>
<L N="310">Her bo&thorn;er liues now lorn ich haue!"</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e schippemen gun to crien</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;at ded bodi hei&yogh;en,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e anon &thorn;ai gun it kippe,</L>
<L>To slinge it out of &thorn;e schippe,</L>
<L N="315">&amp; swore: &thorn;ai schuld neuer more</L>
<L>Haue miri weder whiles it war &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Sum nomen &thorn;e heued &amp; sum &thorn;e fete.</L>
<L>"Ha, leue lordinges, abide&thorn; &yogh;ete!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim &thorn;an seyd so &mdash;</L>
<L N="320">Ha, Jhesu Crist! what him was wo! &mdash;</L>
<L>"Suffre&thorn;, &yogh;if it be &yogh;our wille,</L>
<L>Hir bodi awhile to ligge stille!</L>
<L>So michel pain is in hir ycliue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ete ich wene wele &thorn;at sche liue"
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="167"></L>
<L N="325">&THORN;e prince seyd, &amp; sore wepe.</L>
<L>Of a grete roche he tok gode kepe,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at it better were</L>
<L>&THORN;at his wiif were birid &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an in &thorn;e se-grounde to li&yogh;en.</L>
<L N="330">To &thorn;e schippemen he gan crien,</L>
<L>Grete tresore he &yogh;af hem to mede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schuld hir &thorn;ider lede.</L>
<L>When sche was to &thorn;at roche ybrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;an mi&yogh;t &thorn;ai for hard nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="335">On non wise graue maken,</L>
<L>Hir bodi in for to taken.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sou&yogh;t &thorn;ai on ich side</L>
<L>Where &thorn;ai mi&yogh;t hir best hide.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim his wiif adoun he leyd,</L>
<L N="340">Wi&thorn; his sone, &amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en seyd,</L>
<L>Wel sore wepeand wi&thorn; his ei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>"Allas &amp; walawo, Marie!</L>
<L>In iuel time &amp; sori while</L>
<L>Com &thorn;ou into mi lond Marsile.</L>
<L N="345">Mi wiif a child conceiued &thorn;urch &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;us ded for &thorn;at sche schuld be.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en al mi godes, &thorn;at ich au&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;i god &amp; &thorn;e ich it bitau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he be god almi&yogh;ti,</L>
<L N="350">Now on hir soule haue merci,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is child he kepe fram care</L>
<L>&amp; lete it neuer nou&yogh;t forfare!"</L>
<L>His mantel riche of he dede</L>
<L>&amp; leyd it on hem in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L N="355">&THORN;e child vnder &thorn;e [mantel]lappe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Im Ms. ist ein Wort verwischt, es scheint mantel.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lay &amp; seke &thorn;e moders pappe.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;en to schippe he gan to gon &mdash;</L>
<L>A sori man was he on!</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so to Rome he tok &thorn;e way.</L>
<L N="360">Seint Peter o&yogh;ain him com &thorn;at day;</L>
<L>When &thorn;at he sei&yogh;e &thorn;e croice on him,</L>
<L>He gan to aske &thorn;e pilgrim</L>
<L>Whennes he com, &amp; whider he wold.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim al &thorn;e so&thorn;e him told,</L>
<L N="365">Alle his anoye he gan him telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e se him bifelle.</L>
<L>When seint Peter &thorn;e so&thorn;e yherd</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pilgrim hou it ferd,</L>
<L>He seyd: "pes be now wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="370">&amp; ful welcome artow to me!</L>
<L>Loke atow no more wepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">atow = &thorn;at &thorn;ow.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;i wiif li&thorn; stille on slepe,</L>
<L>&amp; also do&thorn; &thorn;i sone hir by.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof be &thorn;ou trust sikerly</L>
<L N="375">&THORN;at god, &thorn;at is so ful of mi&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ing he may dele &amp; di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God of heuen he may &yogh;euen</L>
<L>&amp; alle his &yogh;iftes he may binimen &mdash;</L>
<L>He may &thorn;e wele do o&yogh;ain comen</L>
<L N="380">Al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &thorn;e binomen;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i sorwe schal &thorn;e &yogh;ete</L>
<L>Turn &thorn;e to blis &amp; to swete".</L>
<L>Seint Peter &thorn;e pilgrim ledde</L>
<L>Into &thorn;at plas &thorn;er Jhesu bledde,</L>
<L N="385">&amp; where he was don on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>&amp; his sepu(l) cre he lete him se.</L>
<L>Seint Peter &thorn;er he gan preche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sike he heled &amp; was her leche;</L>
<L>Mani fair miracle he gan don,</L>
<L N="390">As he wi&thorn; &thorn;e pilgrim gan gon</L>
<L>&amp; schewed him &thorn;at stede ywis</L>
<L>Where Jhesu stei&yogh;e to heuen blis.</L>
<L>In fay when he was stedefast,</L>
<L>At Peter he tok his leue in hast,</L>
<L N="395">For to wende homward o&yogh;ain,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere he lete &thorn;e Maudelain.</L>
<L>To schippe anon he is ywent.</L>
<L>Gode winde on hast god ha&thorn; hem sent.</L>
<L>Opon a day sone after &thorn;at</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e prince in &thorn;e schippe sat</L>
<L>&amp; loked for&thorn; &thorn;urch godes gras:</L>
<L>Anon he was war of &thorn;e plas</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at he hadde ben at ere</L>
<L>&amp; his tvay leue leten &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="405">When he gan &thorn;at roche sen,</L>
<L>Wel sore him longed &thorn;er to ben;</L>
<L>Florines he gan &thorn;e schippemen bede</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai schuld him &thorn;ider lede.</L>
<L>&amp; what for mede &amp; praying,</L>
<L N="410">To &thorn;at roche &thorn;ai gan him bring.</L>
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ai nei&yogh;e &thorn;at roche were,</L>
<L>A litel child &thorn;ai sei&yogh;en &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Adoun at &thorn;e fot of &thorn;e hille:</L>
<L>&THORN;e se it was comen tille,</L>
<L N="415">&THORN;erwi&thorn; it made michel gale</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret stones &amp; wi&thorn; smale,</L>
<L>&amp; playd wi&thorn; burbels of &thorn;e water.</L>
<L>Wel ioieful &thorn;an was &thorn;e fader:</L>
<L>As it is euer childes wone,</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;er playd his litel sone.</L>
<L>When &thorn;at &thorn;e child of hem was war</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e schippe &thorn;at hem bar,</L>
<L>It ran oway sore aferd,</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at neuer sei&yogh;e man in erd;</L>
<L N="425">He crepe for drede, &amp; hidde him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bitvix his moder tetes to.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bitbir st. bitvix.</NOTE></L>
<L>For ioie &thorn;e pilgrim wepe sore,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t he wald wite more:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;at stede he gan to gon</L>
<L N="430">&THORN;er he hadde his wiif ydon</L>
<L>&amp; his &yogh;ong sone also,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-bifore &yogh;eres tvo.</L>
<L>Als he lete hem, he fond hem bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Yhiled vnder his mantel-clo&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="435">He drou&yogh; &thorn;e mantel bi &thorn;e lappe:</L>
<L>&THORN;e child lay, seke &thorn;e moders pappe.</L>
<L>Vp in his armes he hir toke</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gode wille, so seyt &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>&amp; seyd: "Marie, wele were me,</L>
<L N="440">&amp; it so mi&yogh;t now be</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich mi&yogh;t now haue &thorn;e liif,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mi sone, here of mi wiif!</L>
<L>Bot to &thorn;e gode hope ich haue:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at sentest me &thorn;is knaue,</L>
<L N="445">&THORN;at now al &thorn;is to &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; now bo&thorn;e kept hem here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t now wi&thorn; &thorn;i preiing</L>
<L>Mi wiif ogain to liue bring".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;i st. mi.</NOTE></L>
<L>As he bigan swiche mone to make,</L>
<L N="450">His wiif bigan &thorn;o to awake.</L>
<L>Vp sche aros &amp; gan to seyn:</L>
<L>"Yblisced be &thorn;e Maudelain!</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t swete &amp; ioieful is &thorn;i mede</L>
<L>To helpen hem &thorn;at haue nede.</L>
<L N="455">When ich in schippe trauaild sore,</L>
<L>A swete midwiif &thorn;ou were me &thorn;ore".</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilgrim at hir asked &thorn;an:</L>
<L>"Artow aliue, mi leman?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;a, sir", sche seyd, "sikerly".</L>
<L N="460">Ri&yogh;tes now &thorn;an com y</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e stedes euerichon</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e &amp; Peter han ygon".</L>
<L>Wel radiliche sche gan to say</L>
<L>Alle toknes bi &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="465">&amp; him rekned eueri stede</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e miracles &thorn;at Peter dede.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie &amp; blis, gamen &amp; gle,</L>
<L>To schippe &thorn;ai wenten al &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&amp; after in a litel while</L>
<L N="470">&THORN;ai ariued in Marcile,</L>
<L>Opon her owen lond o&yogh;ain.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ai founde &thorn;e Maudelain,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t wi&thorn; hir deciples alle.</L>
<L>Vnto hir fet &thorn;ai gun to falle,</L>
<L N="475">&amp; alle &thorn;e so&thorn;e he gan hir telle</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e way what hem bifelle;</L>
<L>He &amp; his wiif &amp; his grom,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai gun hir aske cristendom.</L>
<L>Maximin &thorn;er water toke,</L>
<L N="480">Oile &amp; crisme &amp; a boke,</L>
<L>&amp; cristned hem &thorn;at ich day.</L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ai liued in godes lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bigun &thorn;ai forto falle</L>
<L>In her temple &thorn;e maumetes alle,</L>
<L N="485">Chirche &thorn;ai gun forto arere.</L>
<L>Lazar, hir bro&thorn;er, was bischop &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint Mari &thorn;e Maudelain</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e holi man Maximin,</L>
<L>Also it was our lordes wille,</L>
<L N="490">Ano&thorn;er lond &thorn;ai wenten tille,</L>
<L>Ac &thorn;ere no founde &thorn;ai no wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at hem wold herberwe day no ni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;urch miracles mani on</L>
<L>&THORN;e pople gun fast to hem gon;</L>
<L N="495">Cristendom &thorn;ai gun taken,</L>
<L>&amp; chirches fast &thorn;ai gun maken.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai made Maximin to be</L>
<L>Bischop ouer hem in &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelein bi&thorn;ou&yogh;t hir &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="500">Oway fram him sche gan to go;</L>
<L>In godes loue sche wold ben</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at neuer sche schuld sen
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>After &thorn;at time non er&thorn;eliche man.</L>
<L>In to a wildernisse sche went &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="505">A stede was &thorn;o &thorn;er-o&yogh;ain &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ider went &thorn;e Maudelain &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at godes angels hadde ywrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at stede no grewe ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Gras, water, frout, corn no tre;</L>
<L N="510">&THORN;erbi men mi&yogh;t it wite &amp; se</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu, &thorn;at sche loued so miche,</L>
<L>He fedde hir &thorn;ere gostliche,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t flescheliche, as we ben here.</L>
<L>Sche was to &amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach was fehlt &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="515">&THORN;at hir neuer man sei&yogh;e no herd.</L>
<L>Listne&thorn; now al hou sche ferd!</L>
<L>Euerich day times seuen</L>
<L>&THORN;er com angels doun fram heuen</L>
<L>&amp; bar hir vp vnto &thorn;e sky,</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;e Maudelain Marie, on hy;</L>
<L>&amp; when sche was so hei&yogh;e yborn,</L>
<L>Ysett sche was Jhesu biforn;</L>
<L>Alle maner ioie &amp; blis sche sei&yogh;e &thorn;er;</L>
<L>Efsones adoun &thorn;ai hir bere.</L>
<L N="525">&THORN;us was Marie born &amp; fedde</L>
<L>&amp; in to heuen blisse yledde</L>
<L>Euerich day ri&yogh;t seuen si&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore sche was ri&yogh;t glad &amp; bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L>To er&thorn;elich mete hadde sche no nede:</L>
<L N="530">Wi&thorn; so gret ioie sche com &amp; &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nei&yogh;e-hond &thorn;er woned a prest</L>
<L>&THORN;at gode wille hadde in his brest</L>
<L>Holy liue al forto liuen,</L>
<L>As men &thorn;at hem to penaunce &yogh;euen;</L>
<L N="535">A celle he lete make him &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelain a litel fro;</L>
<L>&amp; when his celle was ywrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Maudelain no wist he nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot on a day &thorn;urch godes grace,</L>
<L N="540">As he biheld vnto &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;at &thorn;e Maudelain was inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at whilom was so ful of sinne:</L>
<L>He sei&yogh;e &thorn;e angels adoun comen,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e angels anon hir vp nomen</L>
<L N="545">&amp; bar hir vp swi&thorn;e an hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e prest, &thorn;at &thorn;er was nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>It hadde wi&thorn; his ei&yogh;en sen,</L>
<L>&amp; hou &thorn;ai brou&yogh;ten hir doun o&yogh;en,</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e wald wite ari&yogh;t</L>
<L N="550">Of &thorn;at wonderliche si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For&thorn; he &yogh;ede wi&thorn; holy bede</L>
<L>Towardes &thorn;at ich holi stede</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;e angels comen adoun</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ioie &amp; wi&thorn; mirie soun.</L>
<L N="555">Bot a stones cast he nas &thorn;erfro</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nas &thorn;at stede comen to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no mi&yogh;t stire lim non</L>
<L>O fot for&thorn;er for to gon.</L>
<L>Bot when he turned him o&yogh;ain,</L>
<L N="560">To go framward &thorn;e Maudelain,</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
</LG>

<P>(Hier fehlen 12 Verse, die mit einem illuminirten Buchstaben der R&uuml;ckseite ausgeschnitten sind.)</P>

<LG TYPE="stanza"><L>&THORN;at non er&thorn;elich man liuing</L>
<L>Was wor&thorn;i for to se &thorn;at &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bigan he for to crie:</L>
<L>"In &thorn;e name of god &amp; Marie</L>
<L N="565">Y bid &thorn;e, in &thorn;e name of Crist:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ere gost &amp; list,</L>
<L>A godes halue &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou speke now to me,</L>
<L>What &thorn;ing &thorn;ou art &thorn;at &thorn;ou me kenne".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. kene st. kenne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="570">&THORN;e Maudelain answerd &thorn;enne:</L>
<L>"Mi leue frende, at wordes fewe,</L>
<L>Com for&thorn; to me, y schal &thorn;e schewe</L>
<L>Bitven ous tvay here wel stille!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt ywiten alle &thorn;i wille".</L>
<L N="575">Toward &thorn;e place he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>"Com for&thorn;", sche seyd, "&amp; haue no drede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou schal wele witen &amp; se</L>
<L>So michel so &thorn;ou wilt on me.</L>
<L>Herdestow euer in spelle yminne</L>
<L N="580">Of a woman &thorn;at was in sinne</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristes fet wesche wi&thorn; hir ter</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en wiped hem wi&thorn; hir her?</L>
<L>He for&yogh;af hir for hir godenisse</L>
<L>Alle hir sinnes more &amp; lesse".</L>
<L N="585">&THORN;e prest wel fair hir answerd:</L>
<L>"Oftsi&thorn;es ich it haue yherd;</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;at was, it is now gon</L>
<L>To &amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;ere euerichon".
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>"For so&thorn;e", sche seyd, "&thorn;ou seyst ari&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="590">In &thorn;is stede bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ichaue yben to &amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer er man wist me here,</L>
<L>Bot as god ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;e</L>
<L>Now for to sen &amp; speke wi&thorn; me;</L>
<L N="595">Euerich day icham wel soft</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; godes angels born aloft</L>
<L>Seuen si&thorn;es atte lest;</L>
<L>Joie ich biheld aldermest,</L>
<L>Gret mir&thorn;e &amp; blis &thorn;er y se;</L>
<L N="600">&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en adoun &thorn;ai bring me.</L>
<L>Bot now &thorn;an schal ich hennes wende</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at blis wi&thorn;outen ende,</L>
<L>As icham warned of lord min.</L>
<L>Go to &thorn;e bischop Maximin</L>
<L N="605">&amp; telle him alle astow hast sain</L>
<L>&amp; herd here of &thorn;e Maudelain,</L>
<L>&amp; biseche him fair &thorn;at he</L>
<L>&THORN;e next sononday &thorn;at now schal be</L>
<L>In to his chapel stille he go,</L>
<L N="610">Him self alon wi&thorn;outen mo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at time &thorn;at he is won to arise</L>
<L>Vnto his morwen seruise;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he schal finde me him biforn</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; godes angels &thorn;ider born" &mdash;</L>
<L N="615">A voice &thorn;e prest herd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Of an angel also it were,</L>
<L>Bot man no woman no sei&yogh;e he non.</L>
<L>To Maximin ri&yogh;t he gan gon</L>
<L>&amp; teld him of &thorn;e Maudelain</L>
<L N="620">What he hadde of hir sain.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he &thorn;is tiding herd &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Maximin, &thorn;e holi man,</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked hei&yogh;eliche Jhesu Crist</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of &thorn;at tiding wist</L>
<L N="625">&THORN;at sche him &thorn;e bode sent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. iche tim st. sche him?</NOTE></L>
<L>In to his chapel &thorn;o he went.</L>
<L>Amiddes &thorn;e quer he sei&yogh;e &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudelain wi&thorn; his ei&yogh;en tvo</L>
<L>A &yogh;erdes leng&thorn;e lift an hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="630">&amp; angels fele bo&thorn;e fer &amp; nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Abouten hir &thorn;ai gun stond,</L>
<L>&amp; sche held vp bo&thorn;e hir hond,</L>
<L>To Jhesus Crist hir bone sche badde.</L>
<L>&amp; Maximin was sore adradde,</L>
<L N="635">&THORN;at he no durst nou&yogh;t to hir gon.</L>
<L>&amp; Marie seyd to him anon:</L>
<L>"Gostliche fader, &thorn;ou com me to,</L>
<L>No fle &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;i douhter so!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e way to hir &thorn;o he toke.</L>
<L N="640">Hir face schon, so seyt &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>So fair &amp; wonderlich bri&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e he it biheld mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al for &thorn;e li&yogh;t &amp; for &thorn;e lem</L>
<L>&THORN;at schon as &thorn;e sonne-bem.</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;e bischop &thorn;o bigan to calle</L>
<L>&THORN;e prestes &amp; &thorn;e clerkes alle;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere toforn hem euerichon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; salt teres sone anon</L>
<L>Of Maximin sche nam hir fode,</L>
<L N="650">&THORN;e flesche of Jhesu &amp; his blod.</L>
<L>&amp; when sche was yhosled so,</L>
<L>Toforn &thorn;e auter sche &yogh;ede hir &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e grounde sche hir spradde,</L>
<L>&amp; to him &thorn;at sche loued hadde</L>
<L N="655">Ouer al &thorn;inges most,</L>
<L>Sche &yogh;ald him &thorn;e holy gost.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ros &thorn;er so swete a smal</L>
<L>In &thorn;at chapel oueral</L>
<L>&THORN;at it filled euerich wi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="660">Wel nei&yogh;e al &thorn;e seuen ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en in &thorn;at ich stede</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;e Maudelain was dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holi man Maximin</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; michel honour birid hir &thorn;erin,</L>
<L N="665">&amp; bad, him when &thorn;at he ded were</L>
<L>&THORN;ai schuld ligge him bi hir &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Ich biseche &yogh;ou alle &thorn;at han yherd</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Maudelain hou it ferd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e biseche al for him</L>
<L N="670">&THORN;at &thorn;is stori in Inglisse rim</L>
<L>Out of latin ha&thorn; ywrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For alle men latin no conne nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Jhesu Crist for his holy grace</L>
<L>He &yogh;iue ous al mi&yogh;t &amp; space,</L>
<L N="675">&THORN;urch schrift &thorn;at he make ous clene,</L>
<L>As was Marie &thorn;e Maudelene;</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mot to &thorn;at ioie wende</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer schal lest wi&thorn;outen ende.</L>
<L>Amen, amen, sigge al we,</L>
<L N="680">God it ous graunt par charite!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000177.tif" N="[171]">
<HEAD>4. Marina.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Harl. 2253, fol. 64 b<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die, meist lyrischen, Gedichte dieser Hs. geh&ouml;ren nicht alle demselben Verfasser an; so zeigt Marina (mehr s&uuml;dlichen Dial.) andere sprachliche Eigenth&uuml;mlichkeiten als z. B. Harrowing of Helle dess. Ms. &mdash; Eine andere Leg. der Marina enth&auml;lt die n&ouml;rdl. Evangeliensammlung des Ms. Vernon (ed. in Herrig's Archiv LVII, p. 259); eine Prosaversion die altengl. Uebertragung der Leg. Aur. (Ms. Egert. 876, fol. 124)</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herke&thorn; hideward &amp; beo&thorn; stille,</L>
<L>Y preie ou, &yogh;ef hit be or wille:</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;e shule here of one virgine,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wes ycleped seinte Maryne.</L>
<L N="5">Hit wes a mon by oldre dawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at muche louede godes lawe</L>
<L>&amp; strein&thorn;ede him bi al ys miht</L>
<L>To serue god bo day &amp; nyht;</L>
<L>He wes a mon of werkes gode,</L>
<L N="10">&amp; wel he louede is soule fode.</L>
<L>He bysohte louerd Jesu</L>
<L>To sende in him sum vertu,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend to shende &amp; is myht,</L>
<L>&amp; god to seruen, &thorn;at is best ryht.</L>
<L N="15">Hit bifel is wyf wes ded;</L>
<L>&amp; he bi&thorn;ohte him such a reed:</L>
<L>He wolde be monke in alle wyse</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;elden him to godes seruise.</L>
<L>&amp; so he dude wi&thorn;oute les:</L>
<L N="20">Marie milde to wyf he ches,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e ordre dude vnderfonge.</L>
<L>He wes &thorn;erinne swi&thorn;e longe,</L>
<L>Seue &yogh;er &amp; sumdel mo:</L>
<L>&THORN;o war&thorn; &thorn;is monke swi&thorn;e wo</L>
<L N="25">For is dohter from him wes;</L>
<L>Nyht ne day ne heuede he pes,</L>
<L>He mournede &amp; wep among</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;ohte o day seue &yogh;er long</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne may is dohter sen;</L>
<L N="30">In more serewe ne may mon ben;</L>
<L>For duel &amp; serewe he morne&thorn; so</L>
<L>&thorn;at al is mur&thorn;e is turnd to wo.</L>
<L>Gret duel to him forso&thorn;e he nom.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &thorn;at seh, &amp; to him com</L>
<L N="35">&amp; bed him telle for whet &thorn;ing</L>
<L>He wes in so muche mournyng.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ah y &thorn;e telle, hit helpe&thorn; noht,</L>
<L>Y ne may hit leten of my &thorn;oht".</L>
<L>"Why hit be, &thorn;ou telle hit me,</L>
<L N="40">Ant y wol fonde to helpe &thorn;e".</L>
<L>"&THORN;e to telle nully spare</L>
<L>For why hit is &thorn;at y care.</L>
<L>&THORN;o my wyf wes to god ygon,</L>
<L>Ant alle myn children, boten on,</L>
<L N="45">&YOGH;ore is &thorn;at ich &thorn;at on seh,</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at hit nere me neh".</L>
<L>"&THORN;arefore doute &thorn;e noht!</L>
<L>&THORN;at child shal hider ben ybroht</L>
<L>Ant sustened in &thorn;is abbe,</L>
<L N="50">Sone, for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>We&thorn;er his hit grom o&thorn;er mayde?"</L>
<L>"Sire, a grom", forso&thorn;e he sayde &mdash;</L>
<L>He nolde be knowe for no &thorn;yng</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit wes a mayde &yogh;yng.</L>
<L N="55">"Nou wend &amp; seh wher hit be,</L>
<L>Ant bring hit bifore me!"</L>
<L>"God &thorn;e &yogh;elde, &thorn;at best may.</L>
<L>"Sire, haue wel godneday!"</L>
<L>Nou is &thorn;is monke for&thorn; ywend,</L>
<L N="60">&amp; glad is of &thorn;e auauncement
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is child shal vnderfonge;</L>
<L>He hy&yogh;ede blyue &amp; nes nout longe.</L>
<L>A robe he dude hire apon</L>
<L>Ant euesede hire ase a mon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">euesien = tondere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="65">&THORN;e maidnes nome wi&thorn;oute lees</L>
<L>Maryne ycleped wes:</L>
<L>Hire fader hire made be cleped Maryn &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; nou heo ys don in shryn.</L>
<L>Hire fader hire brohte to &thorn;at abbe &mdash;</L>
<L N="70">Feir chil it ys forte se.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e wel it wes ytaht;</L>
<L>Hit wolde aryse to &thorn;e mydnaht</L>
<L>Ant go to matines &thorn;e monkes yfere,</L>
<L>Ant wel leornede huere manere.</L>
<L N="75">Sone &thorn;erafter &thorn;e habit he nom,</L>
<L>Ant holi monke &thorn;is may bicom.</L>
<L>Such cas &thorn;is child wes byfalle:</L>
<L>His fader wes ded &mdash; so we shulen alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &amp; &thorn;e couent bo</L>
<L N="80">Loue&thorn; Maryn, &thorn;e &yogh;onge monke, so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hue him putten to baylye</L>
<L>Ant maden him maister of panetrie.</L>
<L>He heueden a stude &thorn;erbiside,</L>
<L>Ant Maryn moste &thorn;ider ryde;</L>
<L N="85">&THORN;ider he eode to houses neode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. honses.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ant for no shome, god forbeode.</L>
<L>&THORN;er wes a deye in &thorn;at won<NOTE PLACE="foot">deye st. deyer?</NOTE></L>
<L>A dohter heuede, a feyr womon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ider com a knyht of valour</L>
<L N="90">Ant louede &thorn;is may par amour;</L>
<L>So he speken ant weren at on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; childe wes &thorn;at womon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide hire moder wi&thorn; wordes milde:</L>
<L>"Leue dohter, &thorn;ou art mid childe.</L>
<L N="95">Who is &thorn;e fader? tel me anon!"</L>
<L>"&THORN;e &yogh;onge monke, bi seint Jon!"</L>
<L>"Wher mette &yogh;e on yfere?"</L>
<L>"Y (n)the berne &thorn;er we were,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ythe st. yn the?</NOTE></L>
<L>Ant toke me for&thorn; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e pes;</L>
<L N="100">Al to so&thorn;e so hit wes".</L>
<L>Hit byfel &thorn;e child wes bore</L>
<L>Ant ybroht &thorn;e monke byfore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e word sprong to al &thorn;e couent:</L>
<L>&THORN;e tolde &thorn;e monke him yshent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e = &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">Lutel he speke ant sihte sore,</L>
<L>And seide on god, me leh, wel more.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot lette after &thorn;e monke sende,</L>
<L>Ant seide: "&thorn;ou ne dudest nout ase hende</L>
<L>To bynymen &thorn;at may hire wareisoun,</L>
<L N="110">For enykunnes gersoun.</L>
<L>Al to so&thorn;e y &thorn;e sugge</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hit shalt ful dere abugge,</L>
<L>Penaunce &thorn;e tid alle gate:</L>
<L>Buen yput out at &thorn;e &yogh;ate.</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;re &yogh;er &thorn;er &thorn;ou shalt ligge</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;i gult ful deore abugge.</L>
<L>"Bringe&thorn; him out, &thorn;at y se,</L>
<L>Y preye ou for &thorn;e loue of me!"</L>
<L>"Ich habbe ysunged: merci y crie.</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ou me help, sone Marie!</L>
<L>Help me, &yogh;ef &thorn;i wille beo,</L>
<L>Louerd, &thorn;at restest on rode treo!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e monke is to &thorn;e &yogh;ate ybroht,</L>
<L>For al is bone him geyne&thorn; noht;</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;o he wes at &thorn;e &yogh;ate out &thorn;rast,</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;at child wes on him cast.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he dre&yogh;ede muche wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chil &amp; &thorn;e monk al so,</L>
<L>Ant heden de&yogh;ed for pouerete,</L>
<L N="130">Nede help of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere monkes be:</L>
<L>Vch day heo him &yogh;euen an hyse bred;</L>
<L>Elles for hunger he heuede be ded.</L>
<L>Ant him arewede ful sore</L>
<L>&thorn;at he heuede le&yogh;e &thorn;er so &yogh;ore.</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;enne speke &thorn;e porter:</L>
<L>"Habbe&thorn; reu&thorn;e of &thorn;is monke her,</L>
<L>Ant bitime doh him to de&thorn;e!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doh st. do&thorn;.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hunger her he liue&thorn; vnne&thorn;e".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne speke &thorn;e priour &mdash;</L>
<L N="140">God him &yogh;eue muchel honour! &mdash;:</L>
<L>"Tymliche he shal tolyured be<NOTE PLACE="foot">tolyured = delivered (so 145).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ourh myn help &amp; my pouste".</L>
<L>&THORN;e priour com to &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L>Ant seide: "sires, verreyment,</L>
<L N="145">Deliure we &thorn;is prisoun among vs alle;</L>
<L>We nuten wet cas vs may byfalle".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne saide &thorn;e abbot:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at is soht, god hit wot".<NOTE PLACE="foot">soht st. soth.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>He letten after him sende,</L>
<L N="150">For he wes bo&thorn;e god &amp; hende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he wes after ysent,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he tolde him al yshent:</L>
<L>He wende forte ha ben anhon,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er a worse de&thorn; ydon.</L>
<L N="155">He com byfore &thorn;e abbot.</L>
<L>"Maryn, &thorn;unche&thorn; &thorn;e god</L>
<L>Such penaunce forte dreye</L>
<L>For eny cunnes foleye?"</L>
<L>"Jesu, &yogh;ef &thorn;i wille be,</L>
<L N="160">Y preye &thorn;at &thorn;ou for&yogh;eue me</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich habbe misdon a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Merci y crie par charite".</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;ah his herte wes ful lyht,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heuede be so ydyht</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;ourh penaunce &thorn;er forte ligge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioie of hyre ne may mon sugge.</L>
<L>Heo liuede &thorn;er inne wi&thorn; muche wo</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;er forso&thorn;e ant namo.</L>
<L>Nou heo is ded wyterly,</L>
<L N="170">Hyre soule is wi&thorn; oure leuedy.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne spec a monk to ano&thorn;er:</L>
<L>"Gowe whosshen vr dede bro&thorn;er!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ah he habbe don a synne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et he is bro&thorn;er of her ynne".</L>
<L N="175">A nome &thorn;e body &amp; brohte to ba&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at he wes ded so ra&thorn;e!</L>
<L>"Hit is a wommon", seide &thorn;at on.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at is so&thorn;, bi seint Jon!</L>
<L>"Jesu shilde vs from pyne,</L>
<L N="180">For we han lowen on Maryne</L>
<L>Ant penance duden hire on stronge</L>
<L>Ant letten hire pyne to longe".</L>
<L>Letten after &thorn;e abbot sende</L>
<L>Ant tolden him &thorn;e ord &amp; ende,</L>
<L N="185">Ant &thorn;e couent eueruchon,</L>
<L>Ant shouueden hit wes a womon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. shonneden.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot for duel falle&thorn; to grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he li&thorn; a longe stounde.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o he mihte vp stonde,</L>
<L N="190">&YOGH;erne &thorn;onke&thorn; godes sonde,</L>
<L>He ant &thorn;e monkes alle ifere<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor ant sind 2 oder 3 Buchstaben ausradirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er men mo &thorn;er were.</L>
<L>"Nou hit is &thorn;us bifalle,</L>
<L>We moten &thorn;enchen among vs alle</L>
<L N="195">Hire onoure in alle wyse,</L>
<L>For heo is ded in godes seruise;</L>
<L>&amp; heo mey to him biseche</L>
<L>For ous, &thorn;at is oure soule leche".</L>
<L>&THORN;e wommon &thorn;at on Marine &thorn;e child ber</L>
<L N="200">Nuste &thorn;at heo wes mayden er;</L>
<L>So sone so Marine wes ded,</L>
<L>Such shute com in &thorn;e womones hed</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ah heo cou&thorn;e lutel god,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er after wax riht wod;</L>
<L N="205">&amp; com &thorn;ider ase ley Marine,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; muche shome &amp; muche pine.</L>
<L>&THORN;er heo lay mid vnsounde</L>
<L>Fourteniht faste ybounde,</L>
<L>&amp; soffrede &thorn;er muche wo,</L>
<L N="210">O &thorn;at fourteniht were ago.</L>
<L>&THORN;is monkes heden muche care</L>
<L>&thorn;at heo hire se&yogh;en so fare,</L>
<L>&amp; bysohten Jesu for loue of Marine</L>
<L>Delyueren hire of &thorn;ilke pyne.</L>
<L N="215">Whil heo &thorn;er aboute speke,</L>
<L>Anon riht hire bondes breke,</L>
<L>&amp; toc to hire womones cunde</L>
<L>Ant war&thorn; in to hire ryhte munde,</L>
<L>Ant kneulachede ho hade misdon</L>
<L N="220">To bere &thorn;at child hire apon,</L>
<L>&amp; tolde opeliche alle byfore</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;at child wes geten &amp; bore,</L>
<L>&amp; bisohte him for&yogh;euenesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at is kyng of heuene blisse.</L>
<L N="225">To &thorn;ilke blisse god vs sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at leste&thorn; euer wi&thorn;outen ende.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at made &amp; wrot &thorn;is vie</L>
<L>&amp; hyre ha&thorn; in memorie,</L>
<L>From shome Crist him shilde</L>
<L N="230">Leuedi, &yogh;ef &thorn;i wille be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou haue merci of me</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;ine childe!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000180.tif" N="[174]">
<HEAD>5. Eufrosyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Legende ist bereits in E. K&ouml;lbing's Engl. Stud. Bd. I abgedruckt.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Vernon, fol. 103.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Alisaundre, &thorn;at grete citee,</L>
<L>&THORN;er was a mon of muche pouste,</L>
<L>Pathnucius forso&thorn;e he hiht;</L>
<L>He kepte wel &thorn;e heste of god almiht.</L>
<L N="5">A wyf he tok of grete blode,</L>
<L>&THORN;e w&yogh;uche was euere meoke &amp; gode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">speire = dispeyre, so auch v. 497.</NOTE></L>
<L>But fruit com non bitwene hem two,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore hem was ful wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mon was sori and in gret speir,</L>
<L N="10">For he hedde of his bodi non heir</L>
<L>&THORN;at his goodes in toun and feelde</L>
<L>After his de&thorn; scholde gouerne and welde.</L>
<L>Vppon a day he him bi&thorn;ouht</L>
<L>And preyed to god, &thorn;at vs ha&thorn; bouht,</L>
<L N="15">To seende him a child, as he wel may,</L>
<L>His good to hauen aftur his day.</L>
<L>And his wyf bo&thorn;e day and niht</L>
<L>Dude almesdeede al &thorn;at heo miht,</L>
<L>And preyed to god, heuene kyng,</L>
<L N="20">To graunten hem heore askyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;en wente &thorn;is goode mon feor &amp; nere,</L>
<L>To witen &yogh;if he mihte ou&yogh;wher here</L>
<L>Aftur sum good holy mon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wolde heere his preyere anon:</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;orw hos preyere he hopede wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at god wolde graunte him eueridel.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne he wente in to an abbey,</L>
<L>Where was an holy mon, as I ow sey,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was abbot of &thorn;at place &mdash;</L>
<L N="30">In him god schewed bo&thorn;e vertu &amp; grace.</L>
<L>And whon he hedde dwelled &thorn;ere a stounde,</L>
<L>He tolde &thorn;e abbot hol and sounde</L>
<L>What was his comyng, wherfore &amp; whi.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot of him hedde reu&thorn;e for&thorn;i</L>
<L N="35">And hertly to god made his preyere</L>
<L>To sende him a child, &yogh;if his wille were.</L>
<L>And Jhesu Crist, maydenes sone,</L>
<L>Graunted &thorn;e abbot al his bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;E wyf conseiued &amp; bar a childe,</L>
<L N="40">A douhtur, &thorn;at was meke &amp; mylde.</L>
<L>And whon he say &thorn;e abbotes liuinge,</L>
<L>He wolde neuer go fro &thorn;at wonynge,</L>
<L>But brou&yogh;te his wyf in to &thorn;e abbey,</L>
<L>&THORN;er to dwelle bo&thorn;e niht &amp; day.</L>
<L N="45">&THORN;e child &thorn;ei toke, as I ow say,</L>
<L>And Eufrosyne &thorn;ei cleped &thorn;at may.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;at heo was twelf &yogh;er olde,</L>
<L>Heo was cristened in water colde.</L>
<L>Hire fader &amp; moder weore glad &amp; bly&thorn;e</L>
<L N="50">And &thorn;onked god mony a si&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at hedde graunted to hire such grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was so goodlich &amp; feir of face.</L>
<L>And whon hit was at twelf &yogh;er ende,</L>
<L>Hir moder di&yogh;ed &amp; to god gan wende.</L>
<L N="55">Hire fadur liued, &amp; tau&yogh;t hire lettrure,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wit &amp; wisdam, beo &yogh;e sure.</L>
<L>&THORN;en wox heo wys &amp; lerned so faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir fader merueiled &thorn;erof atte laste.
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>Hire loos sprong &thorn;orw al &thorn;e cite</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at a wisor creature mi&yogh;te non be.</L>
<L>And for hir wisdam &amp; hire feirnesse</L>
<L>Heo was desyret of more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>To wedden hire to heore sones &yogh;inge,</L>
<L>And sum striuen wi&thorn; hir fader for &thorn;at &thorn;inge.</L>
<L N="65">&THORN;en was &thorn;er a noble mon of &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>&THORN;at passed alle o&thorn;ure of riches &amp; fee;</L>
<L>He asked Pathnucius dou&yogh;ter feire</L>
<L>His sone to wedden &thorn;at was his heire.</L>
<L>And hire fader verrament</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;erof was fayn &amp; to him asent.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. a sent.</NOTE></L>
<L>He tok his dou&yogh;ter, as &yogh;e may here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of elde XVIII &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t hire to &thorn;e abbeye</L>
<L>&thorn;er he was wont to bidde &amp; preye,</L>
<L N="75">And tok wi&thorn; him muche o&thorn;ur goode</L>
<L>And &yogh;af &thorn;e monkes, to buggen hem foode.</L>
<L>TO &thorn;e abbot &thorn;en he brou&yogh;te &thorn;at maide.</L>
<L>"&THORN;e fruit of &thorn;i prai&yogh;ers, lo her!" he saide,</L>
<L>"Preye for hire to god almiht:</L>
<L N="80">Forte marien hire I haue Itiht".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot bad hire to &thorn;e hoste be brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>To speke wi&thorn; hire &thorn;er ha&thorn; he &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;ei &thorn;idere Icomen were,</L>
<L>He blessed hire wi&thorn; goode chere,</L>
<L N="85">And seyde: "dou&yogh;tur, I counseyle &thorn;e</L>
<L>To liue in pacience and humilite,</L>
<L>In chastite also, I rede,</L>
<L>And ouer alle &thorn;ing &thorn;i god &thorn;ou drede".</L>
<L>&THORN;en dwelled &thorn;ei &thorn;ere &thorn;reo dayes stille</L>
<L N="90">And herden heore seruise wi&thorn; gode wille.</L>
<L>Pathnucius of hire lyuinge was wel payed</L>
<L>And of hir holynesse; he meruayled &amp; sayd:</L>
<L>"&THORN;eose seruauns of god Iblesset &thorn;ei beo</L>
<L>&THORN;at liuen as angles in heore degre,</L>
<L N="95">And aftur &thorn;is wi&thorn;outen drede</L>
<L>Euerlastynge lyf schal ben heore meede".</L>
<L>&THORN;en wax his herte in god studefaste</L>
<L>And to his seruise holliche him caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;en aftur &thorn;reo dayes Pathnucius went</L>
<L N="100">To &thorn;e abbot wi&thorn; good entent</L>
<L>And seide: "fader, I preie &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Cum spek wi&thorn; my douhter fre</L>
<L>And prey for hire, as I truste on &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For we wol walken in to &thorn;e cite".</L>
<L N="105">And whon &thorn;e abbot was comen &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>Heo felde at his feet vppon &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>And seide: "fader, &thorn;ou preye for me</L>
<L>To &thorn;e holy trinite</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde of his godnes</L>
<L N="110">Mi soule wynne to his blis".</L>
<L>HE tok his hond &amp; blessed hire &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;eos wordes, as &yogh;e schul here:</L>
<L>"God, &thorn;at knowest mon er he weore Ibore,</L>
<L>Let &thorn;is creature neuere ben forlore</L>
<L N="115">And graunt hire felauschipe &amp; part also</L>
<L>In heuene, whon heo schal heonnes go!"</L>
<L>&THORN;enne tok &thorn;ei heore leue of &thorn;at holy mon</L>
<L>And wente in to &thorn;e cite anon.</L>
<L>And whon hire fader bi wei or streete</L>
<L N="120">Eny of &thorn;eose monkes cou&thorn;e fynden or mete,</L>
<L>To his hous he wolde hem bringe</L>
<L>To preye for his douhter in alle &thorn;inge.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne hit bifelde vppon a day</L>
<L>&thorn;at a gret feste scholde ben in &thorn;e abbay.</L>
<L N="125">&THORN;e abbot a monk to Pathnucius sent</L>
<L>And bad him cum &thorn;ider wi&thorn; good entent.</L>
<L>And whon &thorn;e monk com to his hous,</L>
<L>He asket after Pathnucius.</L>
<L>His seruauns seiden wi&thorn;outen weere</L>
<L N="130">He walked for&thorn; riht nou heere.</L>
<L>And Eufrosyne, &thorn;at noble may,</L>
<L>Asked &thorn;e monk wi&thorn;oute delay:</L>
<L>"Sei me, bro&thorn;er, for charite</L>
<L>How mony monkus atome beo &yogh;e?"</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;e monk hire tolde witterli:</L>
<L>"We ben &thorn;re hundret &amp; two &amp; fifti".</L>
<L>&THORN;en spac &thorn;at mayden to him anon:</L>
<L>"What, &amp; &thorn;er coome to &yogh;ou a mon</L>
<L>&thorn;at wolde aske &thorn;e hous for charite,</L>
<L N="140">Wolde not &yogh;or abbot graunten, &yogh;e?"</L>
<L>He onswerde &amp; to hire sayde:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;us, &thorn;erof we ben riht wel apayde,
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>And for &thorn;eose wordes more and las:</L>
<L>Qui venit ad me, non eiciam foras".</L>
<L N="145">&THORN;En Eufrosyne, &thorn;at mayden good,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e monk speek &thorn;er heo stood</L>
<L>And seide: "&thorn;ou tel me holliche</L>
<L>&YOGH;if alle &thorn;e monkes preien &amp; fasten Iliche".</L>
<L>&THORN;e monk onswerde wi&thorn;outen lesynge:</L>
<L N="150">"In comuyn we pre&yogh;en bo&thorn;e olde &amp; &yogh;inge,</L>
<L>But fastynge is, as hit is skil,</L>
<L>To take or leue whe&thorn;er we wil".</L>
<L>"To &thorn;is lyf", heo seide anon riht,</L>
<L>"I &thorn;ou&yogh;t to come, &yogh;if &thorn;at I miht.</L>
<L N="155">But &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of mi fader sore I dredde,</L>
<L>For he ha&thorn; &thorn;ou&yogh;t me forte wedde".</L>
<L>&THORN;e monk seide: "suster, for charite!</L>
<L>Let neuer mon defoulen &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;i fairnesse, &thorn;at is so briht,</L>
<L N="160">Soffrun schome bi day nor niht;</L>
<L>But wedde &thorn;e to Crist &thorn;at &yogh;iue &thorn;e may</L>
<L>Heuene after &thorn;in endyng day,</L>
<L>And in to sum abbeye &thorn;ou do &thorn;e gon</L>
<L>And chaunge &thorn;in abyte sone anon!"</L>
<L N="165">&THORN;en of his counseil heo was apayd.</L>
<L>"But ho may schere me &thorn;enne?" heo said,</L>
<L>"For wi&thorn; no lewed mon wolde I dele,</L>
<L>For he wolde not my counseil hele".</L>
<L>&THORN;E monk seide &thorn;en to hire anon:</L>
<L N="170">"Wi&thorn; me to &thorn;e abbey &thorn;i fader schal gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo dayes wi&thorn; us &thorn;er schal he dwelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;en sent &thorn;ou aftur a monk ful snelle</L>
<L>Priueliche, wi&thorn;oute lettynge,</L>
<L>And he schal comen for eny &thorn;inge".</L>
<L N="175">And as he stod &amp; speek wi&thorn; &thorn;at mayde,</L>
<L>Hire fader com in &amp; to &thorn;e monk sayde:</L>
<L>"What is &thorn;i wille? bro&thorn;ur, tel me!"</L>
<L>"Vr abbot" he seide, "sent to &thorn;e</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e comen on his blessynge,</L>
<L N="180">To eten wi&thorn; him, wi&thorn;outen dwellynge".</L>
<L>Pathnucius was glad &amp; wi&thorn; him &yogh;ode</L>
<L>To &thorn;e feeste wi&thorn; herte goode.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo dayes wi&thorn; &thorn;e abbot he dwelled &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Eufrosyne sent hire messagere</L>
<L N="185">To &thorn;e abbeye, as I ow telle,</L>
<L>And seide to him &thorn;e wordes felle:</L>
<L>"What monk &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst furst Ise,</L>
<L>Prei him &thorn;at he wolde come wi&thorn; &thorn;e".</L>
<L>Whon he com &thorn;ider wi&thorn;outen lette,</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;orw grace of god a monk he mette;</L>
<L>&THORN;en he him preyed wi&thorn; herte fyne</L>
<L>To come &amp; speke wi&thorn; Eufrosyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e monk him wente wi&thorn; herte meke.</L>
<L>And heo him mette &amp; to him speeke:</L>
<L N="195">"Blesse me", heo seide, "fader, apliht!"</L>
<L>And he hire blesset, &amp; sat doun riht.</L>
<L>&THORN;en Eufrosyne seide to him anon:</L>
<L>"Mi fader is a ful good mon,</L>
<L>A riche mon, of muche miht,</L>
<L N="200">And serue&thorn; god bo&thorn;e day &amp; niht;</L>
<L>A wyf he hadde, &amp; heo is dede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heo hadde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was my mooder, wi&thorn;oute drede;</L>
<L>And mi fader for his riches, I wot wele,</L>
<L>Wolde take me to &thorn;e world &thorn;at is so frele,</L>
<L N="205">And I nolde for no richesse here</L>
<L>Beo defoulet wi&thorn; &thorn;e world in non manere.</L>
<L>But euere I drede my fader so</L>
<L>&THORN;at I not neuure what I schal do.</L>
<L>Al niht I lay, &amp; sleep riht nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="210">And preyed to god, &thorn;at us ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To sende me merci &amp; sum tokenyng;</L>
<L>And so I beo&thorn;ouhte me in &thorn;e morwening</L>
<L>To sende to &thorn;e abbey aftur sum wiht,</L>
<L>To counseile me what best do miht<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach what fehlt wohl I, oder do = cause.</NOTE></L>
<L N="215">Sum word of soule-hele forte lere.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I preye &thorn;e, fader deore,</L>
<L>Tech me godes lore wi&thorn; good entent,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art holliche fro god Isent".</L>
<L>&THORN;E monk to hire speek wi&thorn; gret wit:</L>
<L N="220">"&THORN;us hit is seid in holy writ:</L>
<L>Hose wol not for loue of me</L>
<L>Forsake his fader &amp; al his fee,</L>
<L>His modur, his bre&thorn;uren his sustren bo&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bo&thorn;e = and.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi disciple he may not ben for so&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="225">I con no more to &thorn;e say</L>
<L>But, &yogh;if &thorn;ou seo &thorn;at &thorn;ou wel may</L>
<L>Temptacion of flesch wi&thorn;stonden ariht,</L>
<L>Forsake alle &thorn;ing for god almiht.</L>
<L>&THORN;i fader richesses, beo &thorn;ou bold,</L>
<L N="230">Schul fynden eires monyfold:
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>Hous of almus &thorn;er beo&thorn; Inouwe</L>
<L>In &thorn;is cuntreye, bo&thorn;e hei&yogh;e &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>Pilgrimus, prisouns, as we knowe wele,</L>
<L>Faderles children monie &amp; fele:</L>
<L N="235">On heom his richesse he may sette</L>
<L>To godes worschupe wi&thorn;outen lette.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wolt only don after me:</L>
<L>Leose not &thorn;i soule, I counseile &thorn;e".</L>
<L>And heo onswerde wi&thorn; milde chere:</L>
<L N="240">"I truste holliche on &thorn;i preyere;</L>
<L>Now for soule I schal trauayle,</L>
<L>For I truste to god hit wol me auayle".</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy mon seide to hire &thorn;o:</L>
<L>"Let neuer &thorn;ulke desyr fro &thorn;e go,</L>
<L N="245">For nou is tyme of penaunce".</L>
<L>And heo onswerde wi&thorn;outen distaunce:</L>
<L>"For al myn desir to folfille,</L>
<L>To trauayle &thorn;e hit was my wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou blesse me nou &amp; for me pray,</L>
<L N="250">And &thorn;e her of myn hed &thorn;ou schere away!"</L>
<L>HE ros vp, as heo him beede,</L>
<L>And cut &thorn;e her of hire hede,</L>
<L>And clo&thorn;ede hire in a cote good,</L>
<L>And preyed to him &thorn;at di&yogh;ed on rood</L>
<L N="255">And seide: "lord god in trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow saue &thorn;i seruaunt &thorn;at loue&thorn; &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>And whon he hedde seid &thorn;eos wordes apli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He went his wei anon ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;En Eufrosyne &thorn;ou&yogh;te: "sikerly,</L>
<L N="260">&YOGH;if I go to a nonneri,</L>
<L>Mi fader wol seche me &amp; fynde me &thorn;are,</L>
<L>To take me out wol he not spare</L>
<L>And make me iweddet also swi&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;en schuldi neuere beo glad ne bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="265">&THORN;erfore wol I to an abbey gon</L>
<L>&THORN;er as beo&thorn; men, and wymmen non".</L>
<L>Hire owne aray &thorn;er heo forsook,</L>
<L>And monnes clo&thorn;ing to hire heo took.</L>
<L>And anon as hit was niht,</L>
<L N="270">Heo made hire redi and for&thorn; hire diht,</L>
<L>Fiue hundret schilyng wi&thorn; hire heo tok,</L>
<L>And priueliche al &thorn;at niht heo wok.</L>
<L>And erly on &thorn;e morn, as I telle &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Hire fader com in to &thorn;e cit&eacute;&eacute;;</L>
<L N="275">As god wolde, to chirche he went.</L>
<L>And Eufrosyne &thorn;e wei to &thorn;e abbey hent</L>
<L>&thorn;er as hire fader was knowen wel.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e porter heo spak also snel:</L>
<L>"Go prey &thorn;e abbot", heo seide, "anon,</L>
<L N="280">To speke heere wi&thorn; a straunge mon</L>
<L>&THORN;at fro &thorn;e paleys is come nou riht!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e porter wente for&thorn; wi&thorn; al his miht</L>
<L>And tolde &thorn;e abbot word &amp; ende.</L>
<L>For&thorn; wi&thorn; him &thorn;en gon he weende.</L>
<L N="285">And whon Eufrosyne sai&yogh; him &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>Heo fel doun flat vppon &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>He tok hire vp &amp; blessed hire furst,</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;ei talket what so hem lust.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot seide: "sone, what is &thorn;i wille?"</L>
<L N="290">And heo onswerde wi&thorn; wordes stille:</L>
<L>"I haue dwelled at &thorn;e palys</L>
<L>And liued in joye &amp; muche delys;</L>
<L>And, for me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;is world nis nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To chaunge my liuynge I haue &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="295">Wherfore I prey ow, fader deere,</L>
<L>Graunte me to dwelle wi&thorn; ou heere!</L>
<L>For I haue riches gret plente,</L>
<L>And al schal comen hider to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at god wol &yogh;iue me grace</L>
<L N="300">Him to seruen here in &thorn;is place".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot seide to him riht &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou art welcome, dwelle here wi&thorn; vs.</L>
<L>What is &thorn;i name?" &thorn;en seide he.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he st. she?</NOTE></L>
<L>"Smaragdus" heo seide, "men callen me".</L>
<L N="305">&THORN;e abbot seide: "&thorn;ou art ful &yogh;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bihoue&thorn; a maister for eny &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>To teche &thorn;e rule &amp; &thorn;i seruise</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lyuyng of monkes in alle wyse".</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbot heo speek ri&yogh;t &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="310">"As &thorn;ou biddest, so schal I do".</L>
<L>And tok to him &thorn;er as he stode</L>
<L>Fyf hundred schilynges &thorn;at weore goode,</L>
<L>And seide: "tak &thorn;is in parti of pay,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at o&thorn;ur schal comen ano&thorn;ur day,</L>
<L N="315">&YOGH;if hit beo so in alle manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may susteyn &amp; dwellen heere".</L>
<L>&THORN;E abbot let callen anon riht</L>
<L>A noble monk, Agapitus he hiht,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>Smaragdus to him bitok he &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="320">His rule to teche him and to lere,</L>
<L>And him to gouerne in such asyse</L>
<L>To passen his mayster in alle wyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;en kneled he doun, as hit was skil,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei him receyued wi&thorn; good wil;</L>
<L N="325">Agapitus, his mayster mylde,</L>
<L>In to a celle brou&yogh;te &thorn;at noble childe.</L>
<L>And for he was so feyr, wi&thorn;oute lye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend to him hedde gret envye;</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;at he was in &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;e werk of god forte wirche,</L>
<L>He tempted &thorn;e bre&thorn;eren &thorn;orw his queyn|tyse</L>
<L>In idel &thorn;ou&yogh;t in mony a wyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wente to &thorn;e abbot &amp; tolde him alle</L>
<L>What caas among hem was bifalle.</L>
<L N="335">&THORN;e abbot &thorn;is herde &amp; Smaragdus let fette,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;eos wordus wi&thorn;outen lette:</L>
<L>"Sone, &thorn;i grete feirenes</L>
<L>Make&thorn; vr bre&thorn;uren to &thorn;enken amis;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore I comaunde &thorn;ou sitte alone</L>
<L N="340">In a celle, nowhoder to gone"</L>
<L>And bad his mayster also anon</L>
<L>To ordeyne him a place, &thorn;erinne beo don.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to fehlt vor beo.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so he dude, as l ou say,</L>
<L>&THORN;erin to lyuen bo&thorn;e niht &amp; day.</L>
<L N="345">And euur he lyued in so gret penaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;at his maister merueiled wi&thorn;oute di|staunce</L>
<L>And tolde his bre&thorn;uren of his godnesse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei &thorn;onked god bo&thorn;e more &amp; lesse.</L>
<L>NOu of &thorn;is matere I &thorn;enke to stinte;</L>
<L N="350">Of Pathnucius to telle I haue Iminte</L>
<L>Hou he com hom to his oune place,</L>
<L>To seon his douhtur feir of face.</L>
<L>And whon he com in, he fond hire nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore muche serwe was in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="355">And asked his seruauns al bideene</L>
<L>Wher was his douhtur, &thorn;at was so schene.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei onswerde anon riht:</L>
<L>"Forso&thorn;e, we se&yogh;en hire to niht,</L>
<L>But al &thorn;is day wi&thorn;outen doute</L>
<L N="360">We cou&thorn;e not seon hire walke aboute".</L>
<L>&THORN;en supposed hir fader &thorn;at he hedde hire fet</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde hire wedde wi&thorn;oute let;</L>
<L>He bad a seruaunt &thorn;ider to gon;</L>
<L>But word of hire ne herde &thorn;ei non.</L>
<L N="365">And whon hir hosebonde hit herde, his fader also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hir st. his.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ei woxen sori and weore ful wo,</L>
<L>To Pathnucius hous &thorn;ei comen vchon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wepten &amp; sorwed &amp; made muche mon,</L>
<L>And seiden: "sum mon wi&thorn; tresoun</L>
<L N="370">Ha&thorn; lad hire awey out of &thorn;is toun".</L>
<L>His men anon heore hors &thorn;ei hent,</L>
<L>To sechen hire for&thorn; beo&thorn; &thorn;ei went,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bi water and bi londe,</L>
<L>In caues &amp; wildernes, I vndurstonde,</L>
<L N="375">Hous of nonnes also &thorn;ei sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But word of hire ne herde &thorn;ei nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"Alas", seide Pathnucius, "my dou&yogh;ter dere,</L>
<L>Mi solas, myn e&yogh;en-si&yogh;t, &amp; al my chere,</L>
<L>Ho ha&thorn; my tresour Inome me fro?</L>
<L N="380">Allas, my riches awey is go!</L>
<L>Allas, my vyne ho ha&thorn; Ischent?</L>
<L>Allas, my lanterne ho ha&thorn; Iqueynt?</L>
<L>Allas, myn hope ho ha&thorn; bigylet?</L>
<L>Allas, my dou&yogh;ter ho ha&thorn; defuilet?</L>
<L N="385">Allas, what wolf my lomb ha&thorn; spied?</L>
<L>Allas, what place &thorn;at hire ha&thorn; wri&yogh;ed?</L>
<L>Allas, for deol I droupe and dare,</L>
<L>I clynge as cley&yogh;, Icau&yogh;t in care,<NOTE PLACE="foot">zu I clynge as cley&yogh; vgl. Gregor. Ms. Vern. v. 43 As &thorn;ou seost clei&yogh; clyngen on cliue in someres day aboute &thorn;e none.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wayle, I wandre, I wake, I walke,</L>
<L N="390">I stunte, I stonde, vnstabli I stalke,</L>
<L>For hire &thorn;at was so witti and wys,</L>
<L>Of alle gentrise heo bar &thorn;e prys.</L>
<L>Allas, eor&thorn;e, &thorn;ou dost me pyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hulest &thorn;e blod of Eufrosyne".</L>
<L N="395">Whon Pathnucius hed seid &thorn;is wordes alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e peple &thorn;at &thorn;er was in &thorn;e halle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e citeseyns eueruchone,</L>
<L>For hire &thorn;ei wepten &amp; made muche mone.
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>&THORN;En Patnucius &thorn;is serwe mi&yogh;t not drye;</L>
<L N="400">To &thorn;e abbey faste &thorn;en gon he hy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e abbotes fet he fel doun &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And seide: "fader", wi&thorn; mylde chere,</L>
<L>"Ne cece &thorn;ou not to preye &thorn;is stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at Eufrosyne mou&yogh;te ben Ifounde;</L>
<L N="405">For I ne con witen in no manere</L>
<L>What is bifalle to my douhter dere".</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;e abbot herde &thorn;is, he made gret mone,</L>
<L>And sent after his monkes euerichone</L>
<L>And seide: "bre&thorn;eren, for charite,</L>
<L N="410">Preye we to god for his pite</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wold schewen us bi sum tokenyng</L>
<L>What caas bifallen is to &thorn;at mayden &yogh;yng".</L>
<L>&THORN;en al &thorn;at wike &thorn;ei faste and prayden;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ei herde no &thorn;ing of &thorn;at mayden,</L>
<L N="415">As &thorn;ei weore wont bifore to heere</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ei to god made heore preyere;</L>
<L>For Eufrosyne preyde so day and niht</L>
<L>&THORN;at god schulde not outen hire to nowiht:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore to &thorn;e abbot verrament</L>
<L N="420">God wolde not hire schewe, ne to &thorn;e couent.</L>
<L>&THORN;E abbot to Patnucius &thorn;enne he sayd:</L>
<L>"Of godes sonde holt &thorn;e apayd,<NOTE PLACE="foot">holt st. hold; Vern. hat oft t am ende st. d, so wint, grount, auch im partic. et st. ed.</NOTE></L>
<L>And keep his lore in alle wyse,</L>
<L>For whom he loue&thorn;, he wol chastise.</L>
<L N="425">For&thorn;i to &thorn;i douhter is nou&yogh;t bifalle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen his wil &thorn;at welde&thorn; alle;</L>
<L>But, for heo is sumwhere in godes seruise,</L>
<L>God wol not outen hire, as I deuyse.</L>
<L>In wikked werk &yogh;if heo weore tayn,</L>
<L N="430">God wolde not leten vs trauaylen in vayn.</L>
<L>Such trust in god forso &thorn;e Ichaue:</L>
<L>Er &thorn;en &thorn;ou dye, &thorn;ou schalt hire haue".</L>
<L>&THORN;en Pathnucius &thorn;onket god almi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And lay&yogh; in his preyers bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="435">&THORN;En hit bifel vppon a day</L>
<L>To &thorn;e abbey Pathnucius tok &thorn;e way;</L>
<L>Tofore &thorn;e abbot of gret renoun,</L>
<L>At his feet he fel adoun</L>
<L>And seide: "fader", in &thorn;at stounde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at st. &thorn;is?</NOTE></L>
<L N="440">"I am so harde wi&thorn; serwe Ibounde</L>
<L>For my douhter, &thorn;at was so fre,</L>
<L>Allas in world &thorn;at wo is me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &thorn;o wi&thorn; dreri mood</L>
<L>Speek to him, &thorn;er he stood:</L>
<L N="445">"We han a monk among us here,</L>
<L>An holy mon wi&thorn;outen peere,</L>
<L>Icomen he was fro &thorn;e palys;</L>
<L>Go spek wi&thorn; him al &thorn;yn deuys!"</L>
<L>And he seide: "fayn I wol gon".</L>
<L N="450">After Agapitus &thorn;ei sende anon:</L>
<L>"Tak Pathnucius &amp; &thorn;e wey him teche</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;yn disciple to haue a speche!"</L>
<L>&THORN;en tok he him anon riht</L>
<L>And brouht him &thorn;ider wi&thorn; al his miht.</L>
<L N="455">And assone as heo hire fader bihulde,</L>
<L>Al wi&thorn; teres heo was folfulde.</L>
<L>And whon Pathnucius sei&yogh; him so don,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;te hit was for deuocion;</L>
<L>He kneu&yogh; hire not, for so&thorn;e to sey,</L>
<L N="460">For hire chere was clene Itornd awey:</L>
<L>For abstinence hit was not sene,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wakynge &amp; weping also, I wene.</L>
<L>Hire coule toforen hire face heo do&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>To ben Iknowen hire was ful lo&thorn;.</L>
<L N="465">Heo blessed hem, and seeten doun,</L>
<L>And bigon a tale of deuocioun,</L>
<L>Hou men scholde kepen hem out of sinne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse of heuene for to winne,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; good lyuinge and chastite,</L>
<L N="470">Wi&thorn; almesdede and charite;</L>
<L>And hou men scholde not heore children Ioue</L>
<L>More &thorn;en god, &thorn;at sit aboue;</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at holy writ bere&thorn; witnes</L>
<L>Hou pacience bi desese Ipreued is.</L>
<L N="475">Heo sauh what sorwe hire fader made,</L>
<L>And of him compassion heo hade;</L>
<L>Of him to be knowen wolde heo nouht,</L>
<L>And to cumforten him was al hire &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>And seide: "sire, trustne to me,</L>
<L N="480">God wol neuere deseyuen &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For, &yogh;if &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter weore ou&yogh;wher amis,</L>
<L>God wolde schewe &thorn;e of his godnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou&thorn;er &thorn;e deuel ne no wikked wiht</L>
<L>Scholde binymen hire soule, &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;i siht;
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="180"></L>
<L N="485">But I truste in god so wonder wel</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ha&thorn; taken hire to good counseil.</L>
<L>For god almihti sei&thorn; him self:</L>
<L>Hose loue&thorn; his fader bi eny half</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur his moder in eny degre,</L>
<L N="490">He nis not wor&thorn;i to come to me;</L>
<L>And hose wol not his richesse forsake,</L>
<L>Him to me wol I not take.</L>
<L>God, he is of such pouwere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him lust, to schewen &thorn;e here.<NOTE PLACE="foot">here accus. fem., aber 514 hire im reim.</NOTE></L>
<L N="495">Soffre nou, soffre, &amp; hold &thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>And let not serwe &thorn;i seluen spille,</L>
<L>Ne waxe &thorn;ou no&thorn;ing in dispeyre,</L>
<L>But &thorn;onk &thorn;i god bo&thorn;e wel and feire!</L>
<L>Agapitus, mi maister, ofte ha&thorn; me tolde</L>
<L N="500">Of Pathnucius tales monyfolde,</L>
<L>And hou for his dou&yogh;tur he made muche mone,</L>
<L>For he hedde no mo but hire alone,</L>
<L>And sodeynliche awei heo was nome,</L>
<L>And cou&thorn;e neuer here wher heo was bi|come.</L>
<L N="505">He tolde me &thorn;at &thorn;e abbot &amp; al &thorn;e couent</L>
<L>Hedde preyed to god wi&thorn; on assent;</L>
<L>To me he speek to don &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>And bad preie for hire a goddes name.</L>
<L>And &thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;at I vnwor&thorn;i be,</L>
<L N="510">A synful creature, as &thorn;inke&thorn; me,</L>
<L>To god I haue preid wi&thorn; herte &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To sende &thorn;e soffraunce, as he &thorn;e wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And to folfulle al &thorn;i desyre,</L>
<L>As may be best for &thorn;e and hire.</L>
<L N="515">To seo &thorn;e, ofte desyret Ichaue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if eny cumfort bi me mihtest haue".</L>
<L>And leste he kneuh hire at &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>Bi hire speche, heo bad him wende.</L>
<L>And whon Patnucius went &amp; outward stepte,</L>
<L N="520">Hire ei&yogh;en erende and for him wepte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">erende st. ernde, s&uuml;dl. form = ronne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire face was pale as eny leed,</L>
<L>For fastynge &amp; penaunce heo was neih ded.</L>
<L>&THORN;En Patnucius was Icumfortet wel,</L>
<L>And wente to &thorn;e abbot also snel</L>
<L N="525">And seide: he was as liht &thorn;at stounde</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei he hedde his douhtur founde.</L>
<L>He speek to &thorn;e abbot &amp; al &thorn;e couent</L>
<L>To preye for him, &amp; hom he went.</L>
<L>And Smaragdus liued in &thorn;at maneere</L>
<L N="530">Folliche VIII &amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;en a gret seknesse him toke,</L>
<L>And dyed &thorn;ervppon, as sei&thorn; &thorn;e boke.</L>
<L>&THORN;en hit bifel vppon a day</L>
<L>Patnucius wente to &thorn;e abbay,</L>
<L N="535">And saluwede &thorn;e monkes euerichon,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en to &thorn;e abbot is he gon</L>
<L>And seide: "fader, &yogh;if &yogh;e wolde,</L>
<L>Speke wi&thorn; Smaragdus fayn Icholde".</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot let calle Agapitus</L>
<L N="540">And bad him lede Pathnucius</L>
<L>To Smaragdus celle anon riht,</L>
<L>"For wi&thorn; him to speke he ha&thorn; Itiht".</L>
<L>And whon he com in, &thorn;er he lay seke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. c&omacr;m st. com in.</NOTE></L>
<L>He custe him wepinge &amp; to him speeke:</L>
<L N="545">"Allas", he seide, "nou wo is me!</L>
<L>Wher beo&thorn; &thorn;i bihestes &thorn;at &thorn;ou bihihtest me?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seidest I schulde my douhter seone;</L>
<L>But nou schal I liue in serwe and teone.</L>
<L>Allas, who wol cumforte me at myn ende?</L>
<L N="550">Allas, whoderward nou schal I wende?</L>
<L>Allas, ho may me ou&yogh;t avayle?</L>
<L>Allas, myn harmes I wepe and wayle,</L>
<L>For hit is gon VIII. and &thorn;ritti &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en I lees my douhter dere.</L>
<L N="555">For hire I haue preyed niht &amp; day,</L>
<L>But no&thorn;ing of hire witen I may.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wo and serwe me halt so swi&thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schal neuer beo glad ne bly&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For trust heraftur schal I haue non,</L>
<L N="560">But in to helle wepen and gon".</L>
<L>&THORN;En Smaragdus sai&yogh; him sore wepinge,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wolde not stinte for no &thorn;inge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">culle = kill.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide to hym: "on goddes halue,</L>
<L>Mon, &thorn;enkestou forte culle &thorn;i selue?
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="181"></L>
<L N="565">&THORN;enk &thorn;at god is of such pouwere</L>
<L>And knowe&thorn; alle &thorn;ing bo&thorn;e fer &amp; nere!</L>
<L>Now of &thorn;i serwe &thorn;ou make an ende!</L>
<L>For god, &thorn;at is curteis and hende,</L>
<L>Schewed to Jacob &thorn;orw his graas</L>
<L N="570">His sone Josep wher &thorn;at he was.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore hertiliche I preye &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;reo dayes go not from me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;en Pathnucius &thorn;ou&yogh;te in &thorn;at tyde:</L>
<L>For he bad him &thorn;reo dayes abyde,</L>
<L N="575">&thorn;at god wolde schewen him in sum manere</L>
<L>Wher &thorn;at his douhtur bicomen were.</L>
<L>And whon hit was comen &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L>He com to him and bigon to say:</L>
<L>"Bro&thorn;er, Ichaue abiden here wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;reo dayes fulle, as &thorn;ou beede me".</L>
<L>&THORN;En Eufrosyne wuste wel anon</L>
<L>Hire tyme was come &thorn;at heo schulde gon;</L>
<L>To hire heo called Pathnucius</L>
<L>And speek to him and seide &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="585">"Almihti god of his goodnes</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; disposet for my wrecchednes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;orw his vertu and his miht</L>
<L>Mi desyr to an ende is fully diht,</L>
<L>And, for Ichaue bore me so monliche,</L>
<L N="590">I schal haue a croune in heuene-riche.</L>
<L>Nou wol I no lengore helen hit wi&thorn; &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For certes, I am &thorn;i douhter fre,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou mi fader, &thorn;at seost me in siht;</L>
<L>Nou haue I holden &thorn;at I haue hiht.</L>
<L N="595">Gode fader, let nomon herof wite ne knowe</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ou &thorn;i self, hei&yogh;e ne lowe,</L>
<L>Let no mon me wassche ne come me to</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou &thorn;i self, fader! I preye &thorn;ou do.</L>
<L>Also I hihte &thorn;e abbot of gret honour</L>
<L N="600">&thorn;at he schulde haue bo&thorn;e riches &amp; tresour,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god almihti wolde leue me grace</L>
<L>To sosteynen and dwellen in &thorn;is place:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, fader, for charite</L>
<L>Folful my wil &mdash; and prey for me!"</L>
<L N="605">And whon heo hedde seid &thorn;is wordes ari&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Heo &yogh;af &thorn;e spirit to god almiht,</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;at tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>At &thorn;e kalendes of Janiuere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Janinere st. Janiuere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whon Pathnucius hed herd &thorn;eos wordes alle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. papnucius mit &uuml;bergeschr. h.</NOTE></L>
<L N="610">He swouned anon &amp; doun gon falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;en com Agapitus faste rennynge</L>
<L>And fond hire ded, &amp; him swounynge.</L>
<L>He cast vppon him watur colde</L>
<L>And rered him vp, as god wolde,</L>
<L N="615">And seide: "sire, what is come &thorn;e to?"</L>
<L>And he onswerde wi&thorn;outen mo:</L>
<L>"Nou let me dye &amp; go my way,</L>
<L>For I haue seye wondres to day".</L>
<L>He ros vp and on hire face fulle</L>
<L N="620">And wept &amp; cri&yogh;ed as he wolde spille,</L>
<L>And seide: "allas, my douhter fre,</L>
<L>Whi noldestou schewen &thorn;e er to me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mihten bo&thorn;e in same</L>
<L>Haue died togedere in godes name?</L>
<L N="625">Allas, from me hou hastou hed?<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor hed fehlt &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is wrecched world hou hastou fled?</L>
<L>Hou artou &thorn;us priueliche gon away</L>
<L>In to heuene blisse &thorn;at laste&thorn; ay?"</L>
<L>Agapitus herde &thorn;eos wordes vchon;</L>
<L N="630">He merueiled muche, &amp; to &thorn;e abbot is gon</L>
<L>And told him fro biginnyng to &thorn;e ende.</L>
<L>And he wi&thorn; him &thorn;ider gon wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot fel doun wi&thorn;outen were</L>
<L>And cri&yogh;ed to hire wi&thorn; wepynge cheere</L>
<L N="635">And seide: "Eufrosyne, Cristes spouse,</L>
<L>Prey for vs and for vr house</L>
<L>To god, &thorn;at sit in trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mowe come his face to se</L>
<L>And to haue part of his blis</L>
<L N="640">Wi&thorn; his seyntes, &thorn;er as he is!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &amp; couent wi&thorn; mylde mood</L>
<L>Buried &thorn;at bodi &thorn;at was so good.</L>
<L>And whon alle &thorn;e monkes weore comen &thorn;ider</L>
<L>And se&yogh;en &thorn;at miracle al to gider,</L>
<L N="645">&THORN;ei &thorn;onked god &thorn;at in so frele a kynde</L>
<L>Such vertu &amp; miracle wolde to hem sende.
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>&thorn;er was a monk &amp; hadde but on ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And he hire custe; wi&thorn;oute lye:</L>
<L>As sone as he hedde Idon &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="650">His ei&yogh;en weoren bo&thorn;e in his hede.</L>
<L>And whon alle men sei&yogh;e &thorn;is miracle done,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;onked god, &thorn;at sit in trone.</L>
<L>&THORN;en weore &thorn;ei cumforted &amp; gladed miche,</L>
<L>And buried hire in toumbe riche.</L>
<L N="655">&THORN;en tok hire fader al his riches</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t hit to chirche wi&thorn;outen lees,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e worschip of god he hit bisette.</L>
<L>And dwelled &thorn;er wi&thorn;outen lette</L>
<L>In &thorn;e same selle &thorn;er his dou&yogh;ter was,</L>
<L N="660">He liued &amp; dyed in &thorn;at plas.</L>
<L>And after hir de&thorn; folliche ten &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. his st. hir.</NOTE></L>
<L>Holliche he lyuede in &thorn;is world heere;</L>
<L>&THORN;en he tok his leue and to god he went.</L>
<L>Bi his dou&yogh;ter &thorn;ei leyde him, verrement&mdash;</L>
<L N="665">Vche &yogh;eer &thorn;ei don his mynde-day holde</L>
<L>Anon to &thorn;is day, as hit is tolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e abbot &amp; &thorn;e couent wi&thorn; good chere</L>
<L>Worschipeden god al Ifeere.</L>
<L>And so do we him, &thorn;at sit aboue,</L>
<L N="670">&THORN;at he wolde for &thorn;at maydenes loue</L>
<L>Graunten vs heuene wi&thorn;outen eende,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; him &thorn;erin for to leende.</L>
<L>God graunte vs grace &thorn;at hit so be!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN, AMEN for charite.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000189.tif" N="[183]">
<HEAD>6. Cristine,<LB>von Willam Paris<NOTE PLACE="foot">So nennt sich der Dichter v. 515, Dienstmann des Sir Thomas Brawchaump, dem er mit r&uuml;h|render Treue in den Kerker gefolgt ist, wo er diese Legende dichtet, vgl. V. 497 ff.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Arundel 168 fol. 2<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dass. Ms. enth&auml;lt ausser Cristine: Dorothe, Capgrave's Catharine (bereits edirt) u. Lydgate's Marienleben.</NOTE> (15. Jhdt.).</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynte Cristyne was a maide bryghte,</L>
<L>As clerkis in bokes hathe rede &amp; seene,</L>
<L>Sche seruede gode bothe daye ande nyghte,</L>
<L>As martyr shulde ande virgyne clene.</L>
<L N="5">In Itayle she was borne, y wene,</L>
<L>Ande come of kynne, were grete of myghte;</L>
<L>Bute she forsoke theme alle bedene</L>
<L>And holle hire herte to Criste she highte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She was so faire, thate maidene mylde,</L>
<L N="10">That euery wighte that ones hire see,</L>
<L>If it were mane, womane or childe,</L>
<L>She wane theire lofe with hire beaute.</L>
<L>Suche grace of gode forsothe hade shee</L>
<L>To flee alle vice and werkes wilde,</L>
<L N="15">Ande fully purposede hire to be</L>
<L>Goddes owne seruaunte &amp; maide vnfylde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vrbane highte hire fadere ywisse,</L>
<L>A wykkede tyrande &amp; a wode &mdash;</L>
<L>It was of hyme as of moo is:</L>
<L N="20">A sherew may gete a childe righte goode;</L>
<L>Ande so dide Vrbane, be the rode:</L>
<L>If he were mane that dide amysse,</L>
<L>Yit gate he Cristyne mylde of mode</L>
<L>That is with Criste in heuene blysse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Many mene desirede that may</L>
<L>Ande wolde hafe weddede hire, if &thorn;ei myghte &mdash;</L>
<L>Whan thei mighte se hire one a daie,</L>
<L>Thei ferde &thorn;e better a fulle seuennyghte;</L>
<L>Hir chere was suche in alle mens sighte:</L>
<L>It made ylke mane to other saye:</L>
<L N="30">"Truly, this is &thorn;e gentileste wighte</L>
<L>That euer we see &mdash; this is no naye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hir kynne wolde gife hire to righte none,</L>
<L>For she shulde lyfe in mawmentrye;</L>
<L>But in a toure ofe lyme &amp; stone</L>
<L N="35">Hyre fader ordeyne hire to lye,</L>
<L>Ande twelfe maydens to be hire bye,</L>
<L>Of whiche she myghte triste neuer one:</L>
<L>For theie were ordeyne for to aspie</L>
<L>How that she lyuede &amp; made hyr mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="40">Goddes of golde &amp; siluer brighte</L>
<L>That may hade with hire in hire toure,</L>
<L>That she shulde wurchipe daie &amp; nyghte,</L>
<L>Ande whene hire liste to do theme hon|oure.</L>
<L>But sodenly ther come socoure</L>
<L N="45">Fro gode, that is moste of myghte:</L>
<L>He made that maye to haue sauoure</L>
<L>To brynge hire soule to heuene lyghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The holy goste in Cristyne is,</L>
<L>And he hathe tawghte hire to forsake</L>
<L N="50">Hire fals goddes ilkone, ywisse,</L>
<L>That are but stonys &amp; stokkes blake:
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>Ande fulle purpose now wille she take</L>
<L>To drede no dede, but thinke of blysse.</L>
<L N="55">Thus gode cane of vncrystyne make</L>
<L>Right holy martirs to be his.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus some haue grace or thei borne be,</L>
<L>As hade &thorn;e baptiste goode seint Johne;</L>
<L>Ande somme in tendre age, parde,</L>
<L N="60">As Cristyne hade, that faire womane;</L>
<L>Ande some in elde whene youghte is gone,</L>
<L>As in Poules lyfe we may see;</L>
<L>Ande some whene thei shalle die anone,</L>
<L>As Barabas thefe, that honge so hye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">Encens she hade, and sho it hyde</L>
<L>Vp in a wyndowe preuely:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. prenely.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ande with goode herte she it dyde,</L>
<L>For she thoughte neuer to sacrifie</L>
<L>To no fals goddes of mawmentrie,</L>
<L N="70">For drede of none that wolde hire byde;</L>
<L>She preyede to Criste &thorn;at she myghte dye</L>
<L>And martire be, or that betyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To ite befelle vpone a daie<NOTE PLACE="foot">To = till.</NOTE></L>
<L>That Vrbane wolde his doughter se.</L>
<L N="75">Ande Cristyne maydyns alle thei saie:</L>
<L>"Vrbane sire, we telle the:</L>
<L>Thi doughter, &amp; oure lady free,</L>
<L>Dispice oure goddes &amp; &thorn;aire araie</L>
<L>Ande sais truly &thorn;at she wille be</L>
<L N="80">A cristene womane, if &thorn;at she maye".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vrbane saide: "late me alone,</L>
<L>For I wille to my dougthire goo:</L>
<L>With faire wordes y shalle anone</L>
<L>Make hire to lefe, if she saie soo.</L>
<L N="85">Ande truly, but she sacrifice doo,</L>
<L>She shalle be wrouthe, or I, &thorn;e tone &mdash;</L>
<L>For it wille breke myne herte in too</L>
<L>To witte my doughter so begoone".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vrbane went with sobere schere</L>
<L N="90">To Cristyne chambire alle one hye,</L>
<L>Ande saide: "Cristyne, my doughter dere!</L>
<L>Se, I ame comme to sitte the bye,</L>
<L>Ande als, to se the sacrifie</L>
<L>To alle oure goddes of grete powere:</L>
<L N="95">That was &thorn;e cause, sekyrly,</L>
<L>My faire doughter, &thorn;at I sitte here".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Thi doughter, Vrbane, clepe me noghte,</L>
<L>For fadere wille y neuer clepe the:</L>
<L>For one Jhesu is alle my thoughte,</L>
<L N="100">Ande his childe, sire, wille y be.</L>
<L>Ande &thorn;erfore speke nomore to me</L>
<L>Of maumentrie, of metalle wroughte,</L>
<L>But speke of gode in mageste,</L>
<L>For he alone me made &amp; boughte!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">"My faire doughter", Vrbane saide,</L>
<L>"Wurchupe noghte one gode alone:</L>
<L>Vnehappe the o&thorn;er be euylle paide,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vn happe.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou wille do theme wurchupe none;</L>
<L>But gete thank of theme ilkone:</L>
<L N="110">Thane nedes the noghte be afrayed;</L>
<L>Ande think how alle thi kinne has done.</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ou thus, as I hafe &thorn;e prayede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&thorn;ou wenes &thorn;ou speke righte welle ywisse,</L>
<L>But as a fole &thorn;ou spekes me to</L>
<L N="115">That knew no truethe nere thought of blysse.</L>
<L>But here, Vrbane, how I wille do:</L>
<L>The fadire in heuyne, &thorn;e sone also,</L>
<L>The holy goste &mdash; the thirde he is &mdash;,</L>
<L>To this y wille, &amp; to no moo,</L>
<L N="120">With alle myne herte do sacrifice".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Sene &thorn;ou wille wurchipe goddes three,</L>
<L>Whi wurchups &thorn;ou no&yogh;t o&thorn;er also?"</L>
<L>Cristyne saide: "fole, I telle it the:</L>
<L>Thies three are one gode &amp; nomoo".</L>
<L N="125">Thus Vrbane wente away hire froo</L>
<L>Als wrothe as he myghte be;</L>
<L>Hyme thoughte his hert wilde breke in too</L>
<L>For Cristyns lofe, his doughter free.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Anone after wene he was gone,</L>
<L N="130">Seinte Cristyne went &thorn;e mawmentes to</L>
<L>Ande caste theme downe euerylkone,</L>
<L>Ande byrste &thorn;er legges &amp; armys in too;
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>The plates of siluer &amp; golde also</L>
<L>She pekyde alle of, &thorn;at was &thorn;eme one,</L>
<L N="135">Ande caste it oute away hire froo</L>
<L>To pore goddes-mene that hade righte none.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vrbane come ano&thorn;er daie</L>
<L>Ande wolde have wurchupe his goddes alle:</L>
<L>He fonde righte none &mdash; thei were awaye.</L>
<L N="140">One Cristyns maydyns he dyde calle:</L>
<L>"What hathe Cristyne, my doughter smalle,</L>
<L>Done with oure goddes? telle me, I saye!"</L>
<L>Thei sai: "&thorn;i doughter made theme falle,</L>
<L>Oute at &thorn;e wyndow alle are thei".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">Vrbane saide: "so myghte I thee,</L>
<L>My doughter is a cursyd wyghte.</L>
<L>Maidons, said Vrbane, how durste she</L>
<L>Thus breke oure goddes so myche of myghte?"</L>
<L>Thei answerde alle with wordes one highte:</L>
<L N="150">"She auntrede hire, as ye may see.</L>
<L>Now are thei alle in peces dyghte.</L>
<L>Sire, make theme hole! late se, cane ye?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Have of hire clothes", quad Vrbane thoo,</L>
<L>"Ande bringe hire faste me here before!</L>
<L N="155">Ande ye twelfe mene shalle to hire goo<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye st. yet?</NOTE></L>
<L>Ande bete hire, nakyd as she was bore!"</L>
<L>Thei bete hire, to thei myghte nomore,</L>
<L>Thei stent as mene that myghte no&yogh;t do.</L>
<L>It semyde bi hire she felt no sore,</L>
<L N="160">For thus she saide hire fadire to:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Withoutyne honour &amp; shame, I say,</L>
<L>Abhomynabille to gode arte &thorn;ou!</L>
<L>Se, thi mens myghte es alle away,</L>
<L>&thorn;er strenghte is gone, thei wot no&yogh;t how.</L>
<L N="165">Aske helpe to theme of thi goddes now!</L>
<L>If thei may do owghte, now assay!</L>
<L>More betynge &thorn;ane &thorn;ou ordeyne now</L>
<L>For my goddes lofe abyde I may".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bowndene in cheynes &thorn;at maydene swete,</L>
<L N="170">Cristyne, was in depe prisone.</L>
<L>Hire modire herde telle &thorn;at, where she sete:</L>
<L>She tere hire clothes ande felle in swone,</L>
<L>Ande after she hyede to &thorn;at dongione &mdash;</L>
<L>She hade so weppede: hire chekes were wete.</L>
<L N="175">Whane she se Cristyne, she felle downe</L>
<L>Anone to hire doughter fete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She saide: "Crystyne, my doughter dere,</L>
<L>Of bothe myne yene &thorn;ou arte the lighte,</L>
<L>Alas, that euyre I se the here</L>
<L N="180">In suche disease as &thorn;ou arte dyghte!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou wote &thorn;ou may make vs lighte,</L>
<L>Vrbane thi fader, &amp; me in fere:</L>
<L>Have mercy one me, gentille wighte,</L>
<L>Ande, faire doughter, amende our chere!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">Seinte Cristyne saide hire modere to:</L>
<L>"Wherto thi doughter clepes &thorn;ou me?</L>
<L>Wote &thorn;ou note wele &thorn;at I hate soo</L>
<L>After my gode in magestie?</L>
<L>Criste, godes sone, forsothe highte he &mdash;</L>
<L N="190">For the ande me he suffirde woo:</L>
<L>Therfore his seruaunte wille I be &mdash;</L>
<L>Iwisse, I wille none other do".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire moder se she hade no myghte,</L>
<L>With no faire speche, to turne hire mode:</L>
<L N="195">She wente oute as a sorye wighte,</L>
<L>That mete ner drynke myght do hire goode.</L>
<L>Thane Vrbane aste hire woo it stoode:<NOTE PLACE="foot">aste = asked. woo = how.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ande Cristyne answers she tolde righte;</L>
<L>Therfore he farede as he were wode,</L>
<L N="200">Ande for his doughter sore he sighte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Do feche hire forthe, saide Vrbane,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e barre that she were brouth:</L>
<L>Ande I shalle assay, ife I cane,</L>
<L>To make hire turne hire wikkede thoughte.</L>
<L N="205">She saide my doughter was she noghte,</L>
<L>Thus coppide the kene, one me begane;<NOTE PLACE="foot">coppyd = disputed, fought.</NOTE></L>
<L>She braste my goddes so richely wrouthe:</L>
<L>What wondur ife I were worthe &thorn;ane?"
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before &thorn;e barre now Cristyne is &mdash;</L>
<L N="210">Gode graunte hire grace righte wele to saie!</L>
<L>Vrbane bade hire: "do sacrifice</L>
<L>To oure goddes, that moste may!</L>
<L>For truly, ife &thorn;ou ous say nay,</L>
<L>Grete peyne shalle make &thorn;e leue &thorn;i mysse.</L>
<L N="215">Ne clepe &thorn;e doughter neuer I may,</L>
<L>Ne neuer wille do, but &thorn;ou do thus".<NOTE PLACE="foot">thus st. this.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thane saide Cristyne, &thorn;at maydyne bryght,</L>
<L>To hire fadire, that sate so hye:</L>
<L>"Se, suche grete grace &thorn;ou has me highte</L>
<L N="220">The devels doughter nomore to be.</L>
<L>What childe commes of &thorn;e devele, saide she,</L>
<L>The devele may be his name oryght;</L>
<L>Thou arte, fadir, y telle it the,</L>
<L>Of Satane fende, &thorn;at cursyde wyghte".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">Vrbane commaundede thane anone:</L>
<L>Hire flesche, &thorn;at was so white &amp; shene,</L>
<L>It sulde be scrapede of bi the bone</L>
<L>With hokyde nayles, sharpe &amp; kene;</L>
<L>He bade that alle hire lymmes bedene</L>
<L N="230">Thei shulde be brokyne, one be one.</L>
<L>It was grete pete, wo hade it seene,</L>
<L>Of suche a mayde, be seinte Johne!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whene seinte Cristyne hire flesche se,</L>
<L>She toke a pece that was of kytte,</L>
<L N="235">And euene she caste at Vrbans eye;</L>
<L>&amp; he hade not blenchyde, she hade hyme hitte.</L>
<L>Thus saide &thorn;e maydyne, fulle of wytte,</L>
<L>To hyme &thorn;at shulde hire fadir be:</L>
<L>"Haue here a morcelle, teraunte! take ite!</L>
<L N="240">Of &thorn;e flesche was getyne of the".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thane Vrbane fulle of ire so wode</L>
<L>Vpone a whele he layd &thorn;at maye;</L>
<L>Fulle grete fyer, to chaunge hire mode,</L>
<L>He bade make vnder, as she lay;</L>
<L N="245">Fulle of oile &thorn;e fier powrede thei.</L>
<L>Fro hire it wente &mdash; she felyde but goode.</L>
<L>Ite brent of mene to dede &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Fyftene hundrithe, aboute &thorn;at stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire fadire wende &thorn;at she had wroughte</L>
<L N="250">By wichecrafte or so (r) cerrie;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. socerrie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Therfore had he myche thoughte &mdash;</L>
<L>He couthe note sytte ner stande ner lye,</L>
<L>Bute bade his mene agayne in hye</L>
<L>That she shulde be to presone broughte.</L>
<L N="255">Now Criste hire help, &amp; our ladie,</L>
<L>As he one rode that maydene boughte!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whane daie was gone, &amp; comme was nyghte,</L>
<L>Aboute hire neke &thorn;i honge a stone &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> st. &thorn;ei.</NOTE></L>
<L>It was righte heuy &amp; nothinge lighte,</L>
<L N="260">Thai caste hire in &thorn;e see anone.</L>
<L>Whene &thorn;ei that dulfulle dede hade done,</L>
<L>Ther come angels fro heuyne so bryghte</L>
<L>Ande helde hire vp &thorn;e water anone,</L>
<L>Thoroughe goddes grace &amp; his grete myghte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">Than Criste come downe hyme self Iwysse</L>
<L>Ande baptyste Cristyne in the see,</L>
<L>Ande in hire lyfe writene is</L>
<L>That thies same wordes to hire saide he:</L>
<L>"In my fadir, &amp; als in me,</L>
<L N="270">Jhesu Criste, goddes sone of blisse,</L>
<L>Ande in &thorn;e holy goste, vs three,</L>
<L>I baptise the in watire this".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Criste cristynde Cristyne with his honde&mdash;</L>
<L>He was godfadir &amp; preste &thorn;at nyghte,</L>
<L N="275">Ande after Criste, I vnderstonde,</L>
<L>Cristyne may be hire name orighte:</L>
<L>Thane after hir godfadir so she highte,</L>
<L>Criste, that in &thorn;e see hire fonde.</L>
<L>Hir muste nedis be one holy wighte</L>
<L N="280">Thate Criste thus baptiste in &thorn;e stronde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Criste hire betaughte seint Mighelle to:</L>
<L>Ande he to londe broughte hire anone.
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>Hire fadir herde telle &thorn;at ite was soo:</L>
<L>He wiste in worlde what he myghte done;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he wiste in worlde, auch 482.</NOTE></L>
<L N="285">For ire he smote him selfe righte sone</L>
<L>In mydis the fronte &mdash; he was so woo.</L>
<L>Whene he hire se, he lokyde hire one</L>
<L>Ande thus he spake &thorn;at may dene to:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"What whichecrafte is this &thorn;at &thorn;ou cane,</L>
<L N="290">Thate see ne londe may make &thorn;e dye?"</L>
<L>She saide: "fulle vnhappy mane!</L>
<L>Of Criste &thorn;is grace resceyuede haue I".</L>
<L>"Do haue hire vp anone in hye</L>
<L>In depe prisone!" quad Vrbane thane,</L>
<L N="295">"Hire hede shalle ofe fulle sekyrly</L>
<L>To morne, ife I be lyuand mane".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yit ife he saide alle in play,</L>
<L>Yite saide he sothe, &thorn;at cursyd wighte:</L>
<L>For he was dede, or it was daie,</L>
<L N="300">Ande Cristyne lyuede, &thorn;at maydene brighte.</L>
<L>Thus he thrette hire ouer nyghte</L>
<L>Thate she shulde one &thorn;e morne alway;</L>
<L>Yit was he dede for alle his myghte,</L>
<L>Ande Cristyne lyuede a merye maye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">Thane came Dyons with euylle spede</L>
<L>Tho make an ende ofe &thorn;at virgyne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">tho st. to. Ms. anende.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he ordeynde as hote as glede</L>
<L>A grete vesselle of hyrne fyne</L>
<L>Fulle ofe oile, pyche &amp; rosyne &mdash;</L>
<L N="310">It wellede so hote: alle mene myght drede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erin caste thei faire Cristyne.</L>
<L>But she lay stille &amp; toke none hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Foure mene rokede hire to &amp; froo,</L>
<L>To make hire payne more violente,</L>
<L N="315">Ande als, for Cristyne shulde also</L>
<L>The soner be to pouder brente.</L>
<L>Ther she laye als innocente</L>
<L>In credylle rokkede, &thorn;at felyde no wo.</L>
<L>She thankede gode: she was not shente</L>
<L N="320">With tourmentynge that thei couthe doo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She saide: "I thankyt &thorn;e, heuyne kynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thankyd st. thanke, oder st. thank yt?</NOTE></L>
<L>That &thorn;ou has ordeynde thus for me:</L>
<L>As twys borne childe &thorn;at were righte yonge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yonge st. yynge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Twys in credelle rokkede to be".</L>
<L N="325">Dyons lokyde one hire &amp; see</L>
<L>How that she lay &amp; felt nothinge:</L>
<L>For sorow &amp; care so wrothe was he,</L>
<L>He thoughte he wolde him selfe hynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther saide Dyons to Cristyne thoo:</L>
<L N="330">"Sene thies tormentes greues not the,</L>
<L>Thaie are oure goddes &thorn;at help &thorn;e soo,</L>
<L>For thei wolde &thorn;ou conuertyde shulde be.</L>
<L>Therfore, Cristyne, goo with me,</L>
<L>Forthink &thorn;at &thorn;ou has done heme too!</L>
<L N="335">For thei wolle have ofe &thorn;e pete</L>
<L>Ande mercy, ife &thorn;ou thus wille doo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>She saide: "Dyons, &thorn;e devels owne sone!</L>
<L>Thi tormentes truly drede I noghte.</L>
<L>Ande syne &thorn;ou haue thus begone,</L>
<L N="340">Let noghte, to &thorn;i malice be wroghte</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou me to dethe haue broughte.</L>
<L>Vrbane &amp; &thorn;ou togedire shalle wone</L>
<L>In dyrnesse grete &amp; sorow vnesoughte,</L>
<L>Ande bothe togedir to drynke of a towne".<NOTE PLACE="foot">towne st. tonne.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="345">Thane Dyons: "kytt of hire tresse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bad fehlt?</NOTE></L>
<L>Let noght if hire here be brighte,</L>
<L>Ande shaue hire hede, yit neuer &thorn;e lesse</L>
<L>Do nakyne hire in alle mene sighte;</L>
<L>Thoroughte oute alle &thorn;e cite lede &thorn;at wyghte,</L>
<L N="350">To Apolyne, late hyme redresse:</L>
<L>So grete, l wote, is his myghte,</L>
<L>He may amende hire wikkedenesse".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thai lede hire forthe in &thorn;at araye</L>
<L>Thoroughte oute &thorn;e cete longe &amp; wyde.</L>
<L N="355">Whene wyfs &amp; wemene se that may</L>
<L>That alle was bare, both wombe &amp; syde &mdash;</L>
<L>She had no clothe, hire with to hyde:</L>
<L>Therfore one Dyons alle criede thei:</L>
<L>"Vengeaunce, Dyons, one &thorn;e betyde!</L>
<L N="360">Thou dos alle womene shame this daie".
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whene she was broughte, that maydyne free,</L>
<L>To Apolyne, sche saide fulle sone:</L>
<L>"In Cristis name y commaunde the:</L>
<L>In poudire thou falle downe anone".</L>
<L N="365">Apolyne felle &thorn;er downe one &thorn;e stone</L>
<L>In poudire, &thorn;er alle mene myghte see.</L>
<L>Thoroughte this miracle, whane it was donne,</L>
<L>Thre thowsande sar&yogh;yns conuerted she.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whane Dyons herde that ite was soo,</L>
<L N="370">Thate Cristyne hade Apolyne schente:</L>
<L>For ferde his herte ite braste in too.</L>
<L>Thus Dyons diede, &amp; neuer repente.</L>
<L>Suche grace gode to Cristyne sente</L>
<L>That she ofe peyne felte no woo;</L>
<L N="375">Bothe hire enmys now ere thei wente,</L>
<L>Thei may no more do hire too.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vrbane &amp; Dyons are now paste,</L>
<L>Of Cristyne haue thei no more myghte.</L>
<L>Thane come &thorn;e thirde schrew at &thorn;e laste:</L>
<L N="380">Julyane, wele y wote, he highte.</L>
<L>Thus begane &thorn;ate curside wighte:</L>
<L>He bade his mene do ordene faste</L>
<L>An ovene als hote as fiere so brighte,</L>
<L>Ande &thorn;erin Cristyne shulde thei caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="385">Whene ite was hote &mdash; it shone as shene</L>
<L>As any fiere that euer myghte be &mdash;,</L>
<L>Thane Julyane saide, &thorn;at was so keene:</L>
<L>"Do put hire inne anone, late see!"</L>
<L>Thei caste hire inne withoute pete.</L>
<L N="390">Thei wende thei shulde hire neuer haue sene;</L>
<L>But of that hete no more felte she</L>
<L>Thane sche in a bathe hade beene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fyve daies togedire, daie be daie,</L>
<L>Sche welkide &thorn;erin to &amp; froo;</L>
<L N="395">She songe &thorn;er as a mery maye,</L>
<L>Aungels ande she togedire also.</L>
<L>Alle that Juliane dide hire to</L>
<L>Ofe grete tormentes &amp; paynes alway,</L>
<L>She feled no greuaunce ne no wo,</L>
<L N="400">For alle turnyde hire to aungels playe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whene Julyane herde ite greuede hire noghte,</L>
<L>But thate sche songe with aungels brighte:</L>
<L>He wende by wychecrafte &thorn;at sche hade wrouthe &mdash;</L>
<L>He hade no grace to know the righte.</L>
<L N="405">But sone he callede ano&thorn;er wighte &mdash;</L>
<L>To slee Cristyne was his thoughte &mdash;</L>
<L>I haue herde telle: Marces he highte.</L>
<L>Ande sexte serpens he withe hyme broughte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Marces crafte forsothe was this,</L>
<L N="410">That he couthe charme his serpens so:</L>
<L>What beste hyme liste to do mys,</L>
<L>Anone to dethe thei wolde ite do.</L>
<L>Now are theie put seint Cristyne to.</L>
<L>She hathe no drede ofe theyme Iwysse.</L>
<L N="415">Bute loke vpone theme who thei goo:</L>
<L>Abowte hire neke ther playinge is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For swette hire neke was wondre wete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">too = two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Too wormes lykkyde ite clene away;</L>
<L>Too wente downe vneto hire fete:</L>
<L N="420">Thai lykkyde theme clene, &amp; &thorn;er thei lay;</L>
<L>At hire pappis too honge to playe,</L>
<L>As thei wolde soke that maydyne swete.</L>
<L>To do hire harme no myghte hade thei.</L>
<L>This saw Julyane, &thorn;er he seete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="425">Julyane saide to Marces thane:</L>
<L>"Thou saide &thorn;i bestis wolde slee hire sone:</L>
<L>Make thame to smyte hire, if &thorn;ou cane!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou wote wille yit thei haue note done".<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille st. welle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Marces beganne his charme anone,</L>
<L N="430">To make thame by&yogh;te thate blissede wo|mane.</L>
<L>Bute thei lefte Cristyne euerychone,</L>
<L>Ande slow hyme thate the charme begane,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Cristyne lokede who Marces lay</L>
<L>That schulde haue made the wormes to by&yogh;te:
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="189"></L>
<L N="435">She bade the serpens voyde awaye</L>
<L>In to deserte, nomane to smyte;</L>
<L>She bade Marces ryse vp tyte:</L>
<L>Ande he stode vp before that may.</L>
<L>Thane Juliane hade so grete dispyte:</L>
<L N="440">Hyme thought his herte schulde breste &thorn;at day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire paps were als rounde ywys(s)e</L>
<L>As an appille, thate growes in felde:</L>
<L>Thai kitte theme of &mdash; &thorn;e more dole is,</L>
<L>Whene she was twelue yere of elde.</L>
<L N="445">The mylke stremyde oute, alle mene be|helde,</L>
<L>Ande some were sory that se this;</L>
<L>Bute Juliane wolde hyme neuer yelde</L>
<L>Ne neuer ones forthinke his mys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Cristyne saide: "with herte &amp; thoughte</L>
<L N="450">I thanke (the), gode in mageste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor gode fehlt the.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ofe alle that &thorn;ou has for me wroughte,</L>
<L>To make mene knowe &thorn;e myghte ofe the.</L>
<L>In alle my peynes &thorn;ou has kepte me,</L>
<L>That fiere ne watire greuyde me no&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="455">Therefor me thinke righte longe to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To thi faire blisse, thate I were broughte".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Juliane wondrede who she myghte</L>
<L>In hire grete tormentes jangille so.</L>
<L>Therefore he bade a wykkyde wighte:</L>
<L N="460">"Kytte oute hire tonge: it dos me woo".</L>
<L>Ande whane hire tonge lay at hire too,</L>
<L>She spake als wele, &thorn;at maydyne brighte,</L>
<L>As neuer ite hade be kytte hire froo.</L>
<L>Thei herde ande seye, alle mene, with sighte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="465">She toke hire tonge vpe, where ite lay,</L>
<L>Ande euene sche caste it at Juliane eye,</L>
<L>That aftire neuermore alway</L>
<L>One thate syde myghte he no&yogh;t see.</L>
<L>For she hyme hite, softely smylide she;</L>
<L N="470">He for wrethe lyste nothinge playe;</L>
<L>He saide: "vengeaunce come one the!</L>
<L>Thou arte a wyche, y dare wele say".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With his one eye he lokyde asyde</L>
<L>Ande thus he spake &thorn;e tonge vneto:</L>
<L N="475">"Whiles &thorn;ou waste in hire mouthe so wyde,</L>
<L>Thane withe &thorn;i wordes thou wroughte me woo;</L>
<L>Thi stroke greues me more &thorn;ane soo,</L>
<L>For ite hathe made myne eye out glyde;</L>
<L>Thi wordis as wynde flyede too &amp; froo,</L>
<L N="480">Bute strokes are sore ande euylle to byde".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fore ire &amp; wrethe he was so woo:</L>
<L>He wiste in worlde whate he do myghte;</L>
<L>Bute thre arraws he shette hire to.</L>
<L>Ande too ageyne hire herte theie lyghte,</L>
<L N="485">The thirde hite in hire syde fulle righte.</L>
<L>Bute whene Cristyne was smytene so,</L>
<L>Hire soule wente vp to heuene so brighte,</L>
<L>Where she shalle feele of peynes no moo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire bodye lyethe in stronge castylle&mdash;</L>
<L N="490">Ande Bulstene, seith the boke, it highte&mdash;</L>
<L>Where many seke mene haue hade hele</L>
<L>Ande blynde also haue hade here sighte.</L>
<L>Truly y trowe: ife any wighte</L>
<L>Praye hertely to that damesele,</L>
<L N="495">She wille hyme helpe withe alle hire myghte,</L>
<L>Ife theire desire be goode &amp; leele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Cristyne, helpe thoroughte thi prayere</L>
<L>Thate we may fare &thorn;e better for the</L>
<L>Thate hathe bene longe in prisone here,</L>
<L N="500">The Ile of Mane of &thorn;at stronge cuntre.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sire Thomas Brawchaump, ane erle was he,</L>
<L>In Warwike-shire was his powere,</L>
<L>Now is he of so poure degre:</L>
<L>He hathe no mane saue one squiere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="505">Where are his knyghtes &thorn;at withe hyme yede</L>
<L>Whane he was in prosperite?</L>
<L>Where are the squiers now at nede,</L>
<L>That sumtyme thoughte &thorn;ei wolde note flee?
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>Of yomene hade he grete plente,</L>
<L N="510">Thate he was wonte to clothe &amp; feede:</L>
<L>Nowe is &thorn;er none of &thorn;e mene</L>
<L>Thate ous dare se, &thorn;er lorde, fore drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In prisone site &thorn;er lorde alone,</L>
<L>Ofe his mene he hath no moo &mdash;</L>
<L N="515">Bute Willam Parys, be seint Johne!</L>
<L>That withe his wille wolle no&yogh;t hime fro.</L>
<L>He made this lyfe in ynglishe soo,</L>
<L>As he satte in prisone of stone,</L>
<L>Euer as he myghte tent &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="520">Whane he had his lordes seruice done.</L>
<L>Jhesu Criste, goddeste sone of myghte,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou come downe to mende oure mysse</L>
<L>Ande in a clene virgyne &thorn;ou lyghte,</L>
<L>Marie, &thorn;at now thi modire is:</L>
<L N="525">Thou graunte alle grace &thorn;at hath herde this,</L>
<L>In heuene of the to haue a sighte,</L>
<L>To se the sitte there in thi blisse</L>
<L>Withe seint Cristyne, &thorn;i maydyne brighte!</L>
<L>Explicit vita sancte Cristine virginis</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
</LG>


</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000197.tif" N="[191]">
<HEAD>7. Dorothe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Leg. ist eine freie Uebertragung der lat. Leg. de s. Dorothea in d. Leg. Aur. &mdash; Eine andere Hs. ders. Leg., Ms. Arund. 168, ist vielfach verderbt, besonders durch Auslassung von Versen, enth&auml;lt aber den in Ms. Harl. ausgefallenen Schluss (V. 235-244). &mdash; Varianten des Ms. Ar.:</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Harl. 5272.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O glorious virgyne and mertir Dorothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">glorius. o st. and. martire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whos fader was called Dorotheus,</L>
<L>Thy moder was named Theodore:</L>
<L>Thow vowdest chastite vnto &thorn;i spouse Jhesus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou vowede castite to.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">Lyke as thy stori schewith vnto vs,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leke os (= as) the storye.</NOTE></L>
<L>And comest of the noble blode of senatours<NOTE PLACE="foot">commyste. of vor sen. fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Rome. but then betyde hit thus<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ane betydede &thorn;us.</NOTE></L>
<L>That there were many persecutours,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er. many fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tyrans cruelle that wolde not suffre<NOTE PLACE="foot">tirandes. suffire.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Cristis servantis in pees to be.</L>
<L>Wherefore thi fader as goddis lovere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">loffere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dispisynge alle here ydolatrie,<NOTE PLACE="foot">desirynge(!). her.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lefte Rome for there iniquite</L>
<L>And alle his londis and grete possessione<NOTE PLACE="foot">landes.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">That he had there, and toke the se</L>
<L>For drede of there persecucione,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With his trewe wife Theodore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">true wiffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And dowghtris II, Cristem and Kalixtem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cristiane &amp; Kalixtiane.</NOTE></L>
<L>And come in to Capadocie,<NOTE PLACE="foot">came</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">A worthy kyngdom, a noble reaume.<NOTE PLACE="foot">reine.</NOTE></L>
<L>When they were passed thorow the streme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ouer st. thorow.</NOTE></L>
<L>They come to the cite of Cesare;<NOTE PLACE="foot">came in to. Cesarie.</NOTE></L>
<L>There woned he like a pilgryme,</L>
<L>And begate the, o blissed Dorothe! &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">the fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="25">Of whos life and conuersacione</L>
<L>I purpos in Englissch for to write.<NOTE PLACE="foot">purpose. ynglishe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche comme of the Romayne generacione,<NOTE PLACE="foot">come. romans.</NOTE></L>
<L>And put in Jhesu alle hire delite,</L>
<L>Sche lefte the customes and the ry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="30">Of ydoles worschip and of here sacrifice:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Therefore sche was had in grete despite</L>
<L>For kepynge of the cristen gyse. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This virgyne, as sone as sche was bore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">os she. ybore.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was bapti&yogh;ed fulle prevely<NOTE PLACE="foot">baptisyde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">And enformed in Cristis lore<NOTE PLACE="foot">of. st. in.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of the holy bischop Appol(i)nary,<NOTE PLACE="foot">worthi st. holy. appolionaer.</NOTE></L>
<L>That gaue hire to namen one eythire partye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">gaf. name. of ow&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of fader and moder, by composicione:<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hire fadire &amp; hire modire bi compassione(!).</NOTE></L>
<L>So sche was named Dorothe<NOTE PLACE="foot">was she.</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">Thorow that holy mann is discrecion.<NOTE PLACE="foot">the st. that. mans.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche was replet with goddis grace,</L>
<L>A vesselle chosen vertuous to holde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">chosyne vertuse.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fayrest of beawte that in that kyngdom was:</L>
<L>Therefore hire name fulle faire was tolde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ferre st. faire.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">Sche was a schepe of Cristis owne folde<NOTE PLACE="foot">fadirs enf.</NOTE></L>
<L>And folowid hire fader is informacione;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wurchupe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Worldis worschip, tresowre and golde</L>
<L>Sche had in grete abhominacione.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in grette domynacione(!).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche lyved in devout chastite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyffede in fulle devoute.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">In thow&yogh;t and worde and dede also.<NOTE PLACE="foot">and vor worde fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>The fende envied at hir virginite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In vyede. (Harl. hat hinter virginite noch: bothe two).</NOTE></L>
<L>That cruelle enemy, that cursed foo:</L>
<L>Many a sotillte caste he tho<NOTE PLACE="foot">sotille. thoo.</NOTE></L>
<L>To haue withdrawen hire purpos trewe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tho.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">But sche loved one trewely, and no moo,</L>
<L>That was hire lord and spouse Jhesu.<NOTE PLACE="foot">spose.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This fendis malice my&yogh;t not suffre<NOTE PLACE="foot">The fendes malys. suffire.</NOTE></L>
<L>This blessid virgyne in pees to be:<NOTE PLACE="foot">blissede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anone he styred a carnalle luferre<NOTE PLACE="foot">fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">Withe the flamynge darte of lecherie &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">flaumynge.</NOTE></L>
<L>His name was Fabricius, and was bayly</L>
<L>Of that londe &mdash;: whan thardoure of con|cupiscence<NOTE PLACE="foot">whome &thorn;e ardowre (Harl. whan = wham).</NOTE></L>
<L>Had so ouercome that he sent for Dorothe,</L>
<L>To haue hire to his obedience.<NOTE PLACE="foot">at st. to. obidience.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">He promysed to wed hir after the lawe</L>
<L>And to geve hire tresoure infenyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">giffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle thes profers they were but rawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">there st. thes.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nor nothynge plesynge to hire delite:</L>
<L>By ryches and deynte this sche set but lite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be. deyntes she sette bo lyte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="70">In heuen was hire conuersacion,</L>
<L>Therefor sche helde but in dispite<NOTE PLACE="foot">helde it.</NOTE></L>
<L>The goodis of worldly dominacione.<NOTE PLACE="foot">goddis.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Withe stable purpos and trewe entent</L>
<L>Sche seide: "I haue vowed my virginite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">saide.</NOTE></L>
<L N="75">And I schalle trewly pay my rent</L>
<L>To the seconde persone in trinite:<NOTE PLACE="foot">trenite.</NOTE></L>
<L>He is my spouse, and euermore schalle be,</L>
<L>That for me schedde his precious blode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">shede. precius.</NOTE></L>
<L>There is no loue so trewe as he<NOTE PLACE="foot">law st. loue.</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">That deyde for me vpone the rode".<NOTE PLACE="foot">for me dyede one.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When Fabricius this wordes herde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">whane. thies wordis harde.</NOTE></L>
<L>That sche was stedefaste in Cristis byleve,</L>
<L>Lyke a wode mane than he ferde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">thene. farde.</NOTE></L>
<L>He thow&yogh;t that mayden for to greve<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e st. that.</NOTE></L>
<L N="85">And from hire purpos hire to meve:<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ordeyned of boylynge oyle a tonne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ordeynde. oyle fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>The virgines constaunce for to preve:<NOTE PLACE="foot">constans.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow&yogh; drede he wend hire loue haue wonne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">thoroughte. went. lofe for (to) haue.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But sche abode stedefastly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bot. fulle stedfastely.</NOTE></L>
<L N="90">And thow&yogh;t hit a fulle esy payne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">it. easi. 91 und 92 fehlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow Cristes helpe that was nye</L>
<L>Sche felt grete ioy in stede of payne,</L>
<L>Anoynted in bawme as sche had leyne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">baine. loyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche made suche contenaunce (&amp; suche chere)<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; suche chere (fehlt in Harl.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="95">That for the myracle that there was seyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">mirakylle. seene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many there turned, goddis law to lere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fabricius seide that thorow enchauntment.</L>
<L>And wichecraft that sche had wrou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">have wrouthe.</NOTE></L>
<L>The feruor of the oyle was schent.</L>
<L N="100">Sche scholde not scape so sone, he thow&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">shuld no&yogh;t sckape.</NOTE></L>
<L>He put here in prison in a voghte;<NOTE PLACE="foot">But her in a prisoune he then brought (dieser Vers ist sp&auml;ter am Rande u. in den Text eingetragen).</NOTE></L>
<L>IX dayes and ny&yogh;tis there sche was stille,</L>
<L>Of mete ne drynke sche had ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; st. ne.</NOTE></L>
<L>He thow&yogh;t that virgine forto spille.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="105">But with angels mete fed sche was<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bote. fede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And swetly norysschynge alle that sesone:<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. norysschynge with &thorn;e fode of grace.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">And swetely norysshede. this st. that.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche was fulfilled with the fode of grace,</L>
<L>That, whan sche come oute of prisone,</L>
<L>Hit semed a verry gostly visione<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ite semyde. very gostely.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">To beholde hire face fulle of beaute:</L>
<L>Sche was moche fairere to loke vppone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">myche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Than euer sche was wonte to be.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The peple mervayled sche was so faire</L>
<L>And was so longe without fode<NOTE PLACE="foot2">withoutyne.</NOTE></L>
<L N="115">And closid in prisone from the eyre.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>But then Fabricius with egre mode<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ane. egure.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bade the virgine, there as sche stode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Behelde &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>Worschip his goddis, or sche schulde deye.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ande bade hire worchippe. die.</NOTE></L>
<L>But with parfite herte and reson gode<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hert.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">Alle his ydols sche did defye.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dide.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I schalle worschip" seide Dorothe,</L>
<L>"God that made alle thynge of nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For alle thi goddis deuelis be,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle fehlt. devyls.</NOTE></L>
<L>Enemys to hym &thorn;at alle thynge wrou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">enmys. thingis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">Jhesu Crist, that with thy precious blode me bou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Crist fehlt. has boughte, me fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Knelynge on grounde y prey to the:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">one &thorn;i grounde. pray.</NOTE></L>
<L>Turne this ydole in to ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thies ydolls vneto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow power of thy mageste!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thorowe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Schew that there is no god but one!"</L>
<L N="130">Then Fabricius lifte vp on hie<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. liften.</NOTE></L>
<L>A pilere of a mawment there vpone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">a peloure &amp; a.</NOTE></L>
<L>So schewid forthe his ydolatrie.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">schewede he.</NOTE></L>
<L>But angels of heuen were there fulle nye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">heuyne &thorn;er were.</NOTE></L>
<L>And cast (hit) downe in wondire wise.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">caste theme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="135">Amonge the partees of &thorn;e pilere &thorn;ei found hit lye;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">par|tis. pilours. fonde it.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit had no power to aryse.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">agayne to ryse.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fendis that in that ydole were<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e ydolls.</NOTE></L>
<L>Withe lowde noyse cryed "o Dorothe"</L>
<L>In diuerse partyes of the eyre,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">"Whate have we displesid the?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tres|passede to the.</NOTE></L>
<L>In paynys and turmentis wastethe we be<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wastede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow thi prayere that persithe hevene".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pershyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>There were conuertid opynlye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">conuertede were oppenly.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many one that hird that stevene;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">harde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">And alle they suffred martirdom<NOTE PLACE="foot2">suffirde.</NOTE></L>
<L>That folowid the lore of Dorothe.</L>
<L>And in a gybbet sche was nome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gebet. wonne st. nome.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire feet hangynge toward the skye,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fete hangyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle to-raced was hire body<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="150">Withe hokys of yren, and with roddis bete,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of hyrne. bette.</NOTE></L>
<L>Withe fleylis brusched fulle cruelly:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">flailis brysyde.</NOTE></L>
<L>This to here lawes they did hire threte.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;us to theire. trete.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it wolde they schewe more tyranny:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">yitte. schew hire. tyrantrie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Brennynge fagottis ordeyned were,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">brynnynge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">Vnto hire pappes they did ham tye &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pappis. heme.</NOTE></L>
<L>This to this virgyn they did there.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thus &thorn;is, to fehlt. dere st. there.</NOTE></L>
<L>After this tormentrie and this fere</L>
<L>Sche was put in prison, halfe dede and more,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Thei pute hire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto the morow that sche schulde appere<NOTE PLACE="foot2">morne. apere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">Openly this tyrans tofore.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Openly vneto &thorn;e tyrandis as sche dide before.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When that sche come in here presence,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">came. &thorn;er st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche was alle hole, without infirmyte:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">withoutyne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle that were comen to that audience<NOTE PLACE="foot2">come into.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>Merveyled how that hit my&yogh;t be.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">that fehlt. myghte so be.</NOTE></L>
<L N="165">Then seide the president: "O fayre may|den Dorothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">maide.</NOTE></L>
<L>Turne to oure lawes and do honoure<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vneto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnto oure goddis that my&yogh;ti be,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e schalle haue the more favoure.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">&yogh;e st. &thorn;ou.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">ande &thorn;ou schalte.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thow art chastisede ynow for thyne offence<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;i.</NOTE></L>
<L N="170">And that thow hast oure goddis defyed".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">In &thorn;at.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche bowid not for alle his eloquence &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">no&yogh;t. alle fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire hert in Criste was trewly tyed.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">god st. Criste.</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er crafte then he aspied:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Ano&thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>And send Cristem and Kalixtem, hire sustres bothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sent for. sisturs.</NOTE></L>
<L N="175">That for fere of dethe hadden denyed<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hade.</NOTE></L>
<L>Goddis lawe, thow&yogh; they were lothe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thow.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For that they schulde revoke the spirite<NOTE PLACE="foot2">that fehlt. speryte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of god that was hire sustere withynne.</L>
<L>But sche was stedefaste and wolde not flytte<NOTE PLACE="foot2">178-9: of gode &thorn;at was stedfaste &amp; wolde not flitte.</NOTE></L>
<L N="180">In no wise, to consent to synne.</L>
<L>But mekely then sche did begynne</L>
<L>To stable hire sustris in goddis lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sistire.</NOTE></L>
<L>And put awey the errour that they were ynne:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">and to pute awaie.</NOTE></L>
<L>And they consented vnto hire sawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">consentynge to.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="185">When Fabricius herd of there conuer|sacione,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">whane, &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>He comaunded the sustres bothe two<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sistirs. too=two.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bake to bake forto be boundene<NOTE PLACE="foot1">boundene st. boundon.</NOTE></L>
<L>And than in fyre forto be doo.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">than fehlt. fier.</NOTE></L>
<L>They were b(r)ennyd and martird soo,</L>
<L N="190">The sustres II, Cristenn and Kalixtem,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thies sisters too.</NOTE></L>
<L>And passid oute of this exile and this woo<NOTE PLACE="foot2">exille.</NOTE></L>
<L>Evene strey&yogh;t to the blisse of heuene.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Euyne forthe to.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Then seide Fabricius to Dorothe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vneto.</NOTE></L>
<L>"How longe schalle we suffre this dery|sione<NOTE PLACE="foot2">dirisione.</NOTE></L>
<L N="195">Withe thi wichecraft and thy sorcery?<NOTE PLACE="foot2">socerie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hit is to vs a grete abhusione.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">abusione.</NOTE></L>
<L>Do sacrifice to oure goddis anone,</L>
<L>Or ellis fulle sone thow schalt be dede;</L>
<L>For ordeyned is thi confusione:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">confucione.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">Do sacrifice or lees thyne hed".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">or elles lose &thorn;i hede.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dorothe answerd with glad chere:</L>
<L>"Brynge forthe alle thi turmentrie,</L>
<L>And thow schalt fynde me redy here<NOTE PLACE="foot2">shalle.</NOTE></L>
<L>To suffre alle thi tiranny</L>
<L N="205">For Jhesu, my spous, whom worschip y:</L>
<L>For in his gardyn of delycis<NOTE PLACE="foot2">delice.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aples and roses that smelle swetely,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">appuls. swetly.</NOTE></L>
<L>I schalle plante, with o&thorn;er spicis:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There schalle y be mery for euermore,</L>
<L N="210">In his blisse, eternally,</L>
<L>For trew kepyng of his lore".</L>
<L>At hire wordis Fabricius had envie,</L>
<L>In his wodenesse he seide (sche) schulde abye.</L>
<L>Withe staves hire visage they al to-rent,</L>
<L N="215">Tille they that bete hire were wery.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to = till.</NOTE></L>
<L>This virgyn suffred alle here turment.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hire.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hire face was swellid and alle to-blowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">alle to-blowe st. also blo.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">and also blo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle to-raced and alle torne.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">rasyde. to-torne.</NOTE></L>
<L>To prison sche was comaunded soo,</L>
<L N="220">There to abyde vnto the morne.</L>
<L>But he that was of a wirgyne borne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">But fehlt. God st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hire lorde and spous, Criste Jhesu,</L>
<L>Made hire fresche as rose on thorne,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">as freche os.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bry&yogh;t of colowre and fayre of hewe.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hew.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="195"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="225">Vppone the morow sche was forthe brow&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">morne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Then seide Fabricius with egre con|tenaunce:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">egire.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Thow schalt haue now that thow haste sow&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Oure goddis on the schalle take ven|geaunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">shalle take on the.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thow schalt do hem no more grevaunce.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">theme.</NOTE></L>
<L N="230">This day thow schalt lese thyne hed:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">daie. shalle lose thie hede.</NOTE></L>
<L>This is thy jugement and thi penaunce:</L>
<L>For blasphem of oure goddis thow schalt be dede".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">blasphemynge. shalle. ded.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As sche was lad vnto hire martirdom<NOTE PLACE="foot2">led to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Witheout the wallis of the cite,</L>
<L N="235">Seide to hire in skorne and illusione<NOTE PLACE="foot2">said.</NOTE></L>
<L>Theophilus, the prothonotarye<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. prothonatorye.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;ane sais the prothanarie(!).</NOTE></L>
<L>Of that reame: "O thow virgyne Dorothe,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">reine.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of the roses and aples &thorn;at in &thorn;i spouses gardyn growe<NOTE PLACE="foot2">and of &thorn;i appels. spouse. grow.</NOTE></L>
<L>I prey the sende some vnto me".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pray. send. to st. vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L N="240">Sche seide: "I schalle sende the inowe".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">send. ynow.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;it this was in the wyntire is sesone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wynter, is fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Contrarye to nature and to kynde,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">vneto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nothyng acordynge vnto resone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">frute of floures.</NOTE></L>
<L>Frute and floure that tyme to fynde.</L>
<L N="245">But on hire spous was alle hire mynde,</L>
<L>To whom sche felle on kneys to pray:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">knes.</NOTE></L>
<L>"My lorde, that alle may lose and bynde,</L>
<L>Take hede whate thi seruaunt wolle seye!<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wol saie.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I prey for alle that with devocione<NOTE PLACE="foot2">pray. that fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="250">Vnto the prey with trewe entent,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">y pray.</NOTE></L>
<L>That mynde haue one thi seruantis pas|sione,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">of st. on.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hirynge or redynge, that take talent<NOTE PLACE="foot2">herynge. that fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>But to my name: that thow assent<NOTE PLACE="foot1">but to st. vnto?</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">Vnto.</NOTE></L>
<L>To delyuere hem from here disese,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">theme. fro &thorn;er disease.</NOTE></L>
<L N="255">From angre and from combrement,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fro. comprement.</NOTE></L>
<L>And that they mow the trewly please,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">may.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From false name and schamefulle pouerte,</L>
<L>And afore there ende trew contricion,</L>
<L>From myschefe that they delyuered be,</L>
<L N="260">And graunte hem of here synnes remys|sione;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">theme. &thorn;er.</NOTE></L>
<L>And they that bene in oure ladyes prysone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Also theme. be. lady presone.</NOTE></L>
<L>That with childe-byrthe bene grevid,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">childis byrth. agreuyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>Graunt hem sone ease of here burdone,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sone fehlt. byrdene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thorow my preyere to be releuyd!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="265">And where the story is of my passione,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">my fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>In howse or eny dwellynge place,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">any.</NOTE></L>
<L>Neyther fyre ne leven hit ouercome!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">no&thorn;er fier nor leuyne. one comme.</NOTE></L>
<L>And whan hire preyere ended was,</L>
<L>A voyce was hirde thorow goddis grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And was(!) herd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="270">That seide: "o virgyne Dorothe,</L>
<L>Alle thi preyere purchased thow haste.<NOTE PLACE="foot1">haste st. has.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">has st. haste.</NOTE></L>
<L>Come, swete trewe-loue and spous, to me!"<NOTE PLACE="foot2">trulofe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Then the virgyne leyde downe hire hede,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">layde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Redy vnto the turmentowre.</L>
<L N="275">And sodenly in hire si&yogh;t apperid<NOTE PLACE="foot2">appered.</NOTE></L>
<L>A childe, that clothed was in purpure,</L>
<L>Barfote, white loxe crispe and pure,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. white st. withe.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">with lokes bothe crispe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fulle of goldyn sterrys was his garment;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">gold ster|res.</NOTE></L>
<L>A baskot he helde of swete odowre<NOTE PLACE="foot2">basket.</NOTE></L>
<L N="280">Withe roses and aples, hire to present.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">appuls.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Then seide that virgyne vnto the childe:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e st. that. &thorn;at childe.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Myne owne gode lorde, now I &thorn;e pray<NOTE PLACE="foot2">my nowne.</NOTE></L>
<L>In the lowlyeste wise with wordis mylde:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&amp; with.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bere this to Theophle the scrybe, and seye<NOTE PLACE="foot2">to &thorn;e phile &thorn;e scribe(!). saye.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="196"></L>
<L N="285">That I haue kept my promysse and my day".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">promyse.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so sche toke hire martyrdom,</L>
<L>This virgyne Dorothe, this blessid may,</L>
<L>Deoclisian and Maximian &thorn;ene emper|ouris of Rome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">&thorn;e st. &thorn;ene. emperour.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of Fabricius here bayly in that contrey,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">And st. of. &thorn;er. cuntre.</NOTE></L>
<L N="290">That put hire to hire passione</L>
<L>The VIII day from the Idus of Februarij;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fro Idus of februare.</NOTE></L>
<L>The date from Cristis incarnacione</L>
<L>IIC IIIIXX VIII yeris were gone<NOTE PLACE="foot2">and VIII yers.</NOTE></L>
<L>That sche suffred dethe for Crist Jhesu<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. Jhesus.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">deth. Criste.</NOTE></L>
<L N="295">And alle hire enemys so ouercome,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">enmyse.</NOTE></L>
<L>This blessid Dorothe that was so trewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This childe come vnto Theophle,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">childe fehlt. Theophile.</NOTE></L>
<L>In the president palis as he stode,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">presidente place. as fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And schewid hym the roses and the aples,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">hym fehlt. &thorn;e appuls and roses.</NOTE></L>
<L N="300">And seide: "Dorothe, my suster good,</L>
<L>That promysed the, whan that sche yode<NOTE PLACE="foot2">that nach whan fehlt. &yogh;oode.</NOTE></L>
<L>To suffre dethe, after thi desyre,</L>
<L>Aples and roses, there as thow stode:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">she st. thow.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now hast thow that thow dedest require:<NOTE PLACE="foot2">diddyste.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="305">From the paradis of hire spous Jhesus<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fro.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sche hathe sende the this present".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">sent.</NOTE></L>
<L>The childe vanyssched, when he had seide this.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">thus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Then Theophle loued god omnipotent</L>
<L>That suche comfort to hym had sent,</L>
<L N="310">He seide there was no god but the god of Dorothe;<NOTE PLACE="foot2">bot god, the fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle his mysbeleue he did repent,</L>
<L>And worschippid one god in trenite,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">worchupe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"That in the monthe of Februarie,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">mo|neth. februare.</NOTE></L>
<L>When grete colde congeileth the grownde,</L>
<L N="315">Sendithe aples and flowris swete and savourie,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">Ms. savioure.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot2">and flowris fehlt. saverie st. sauioure.</NOTE></L>
<L>There as he wolle his grace be founde.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">wille. be vor founde fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>He may lose alle that is bownde:</L>
<L>Blessid be his holy name,</L>
<L>That hathe brow&yogh;t me in this stownde<NOTE PLACE="foot2">has me broughte into.</NOTE></L>
<L N="320">Out of the fendis cursed frame".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">fame.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Then thorow Theophle is predicacione<NOTE PLACE="foot2">is fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle that cite conuerted was.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">couerted.</NOTE></L>
<L>When the tyran see alle theire conuer|sione,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">tirande saw alle &thorn;is couersacione.</NOTE></L>
<L>He cryed out and seide: "alas!</L>
<L N="325">This is a wondirfulle cas</L>
<L>That alle owre goddis bene this forsake".<NOTE PLACE="foot2">alle fehlt. &thorn;us.</NOTE></L>
<L>Withe mo peynes the scribe he did deface</L>
<L>Then Dorothe suffred for Crist is sake;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At last, to schew his tyranny,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">at &thorn;e laste. tirannye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="330">He leet hewe his body in pecis smale,<NOTE PLACE="foot2">lete hew. smalle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And cast hit in dyuerse partie,</L>
<L>That wilde bestis to hit schulde falle<NOTE PLACE="foot2">shuld to it.</NOTE></L>
<L>And o&thorn;er fowlis devowre hit alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot2">oder foules devowred.</NOTE></L>
<L>But afore that Theophilus<NOTE PLACE="foot2">Theophelus.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="inter">(Der Schluss fehlt, da ein Blatt im Ms. ausgerissen ist; derselbe lautet in Ms. Arund. 168:)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="335">With grete devocione did crie and calle</L>
<L>To Dorothe spouse, Criste Jhesus,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After cristene feith was bapti&yogh;ed,</L>
<L>And receyued oure lord in fourme of brede:</L>
<L>And went, with martirdome glorified,</L>
<L N="340">To &thorn;e prince of martris and &thorn;e hede,
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>That rose vp aftir &thorn;at he was III daies dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;us endith &thorn;e storie of blessed Dorothe.</L>
<L>Criste graunte vs with hire to fede</L>
<L>In presence of &thorn;e holy Trinite.</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit vita sancte Dorothee.</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Darauf folgt in lateinischen Versen:</HEAD>
<L>In quacunque domon(ome)n fuit vel imago</L>
<L>Virginis eximie Dorothee virginis alme,</L>
<L>Nullus abortiuus infans nascetur in illa</L>
<L>Nec domus nec ignis furtique pericula sentit.</L>
<L>Nec quisquam inibi poterit mala morte perire,</L>
<L>Celestique pane moriens qui moriatur (!).</L>
</LG>
<P>Deuota oracio ad sanctam Dorotheam.</P>
<P>Sancta Dorothea virgo &amp; martir, o casti|tate fallerata(!), humilitate coronata, pa|ciencia ornata, virtutum floribus fulcita, temperancia pollita, o preciosa margarita, sancta virgo Dorothea, cor mundum in nobis crea.
</P>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000204.tif" N="[198]">
<HEAD>8. Erasmus.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="a" TYPE="version">
<HEAD>a) aus Ms. Harl. 2382.</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle cristen peple, listeneth ye &amp; here</L>
<L>Of an holi bisshop and a martere,</L>
<L>Whos name is cleped seynt Erasmus,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e boke seith &amp; trew men telle vs.</L>
<L N="5">Of an holy man here may men rede,</L>
<L>What merite thei may haue &amp; what mede</L>
<L>That wolle worshipe god &amp; hym deuotely</L>
<L>Euery day, with thre thynges pryncipally.</L>
<L>Which bene thes, as ye may here:</L>
<L N="10">With deuote pater noster or other prayere,</L>
<L>And with an almesdede, lasse other more,</L>
<L>Of mete or of money yeven to &thorn;e pore,</L>
<L>Or els candel-light more or lasse</L>
<L>Brennyng at evesong, matynes, or masse.</L>
<L N="15">Who thes thynges doth for &thorn;is martires sake,</L>
<L>Thes rewardes folwyng truly shal he take:</L>
<L>One is: that he shal haue to his levyng</L>
<L>Resonable substance to his endyng;</L>
<L>Another is this: that any of his foone</L>
<L N="20">Hyndryng or harme shal thei do hym none,</L>
<L>Yf his cause be trew &mdash; this is certan, &mdash;</L>
<L>Thurgh the prayere of this holy mane,</L>
<L>And what he wol axe resonably,</L>
<L>That wolle god hym graunte of his mercy;</L>
<L N="25">Another is this &mdash; that hym shalle plese:</L>
<L>He shalle be delyuered of al his disese;</L>
<L>Another is this, as the boke seith:</L>
<L>He shalle dye in rightfulle byleve &amp; feithe,</L>
<L>And sothely, or &thorn;e soule fro &thorn;e body twyne,</L>
<L N="30">He shalle haue contricion &amp; shrift of his syn,</L>
<L>And he shalle receyue, or he be ded,</L>
<L>Cristes owne body in forme of bred,</L>
<L>And he shalle haue afore his endyng</L>
<L>The holy sacrament of anoyntyng.</L>
<L N="35">And he shalle come to thilke ioy &amp; blisse</L>
<L>In the which truly this holy martir ys,</L>
<L>The verry blisse of heuen &thorn;at neuer shal haue ende &mdash;</L>
<L>God yeue vs alle grace theder for to wende.</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIres, ye shul vnderstond, as we writene fynde,</L>
<L N="40">That this holi man was punyshed &amp; pynde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e contre of Champayn, as &thorn;e boke tellis</L>
<L>And as men reporte &thorn;at in that place dwellys.</L>
<L>Whos day falleth in somer on the thirde day</L>
<L>Of Juyne, the next moneth after May.</L>
<L N="45">And vpon &thorn;e sonday he had most woo &mdash;</L>
<L>Of hem y shal tells somwhat, or y go, &mdash;</L>
<L>Vnder two fals tirantes ful vntrewly,</L>
<L>That were fals traytoures to god almyghty:</L>
<L>The name of &thorn;e firste was Dioclician,</L>
<L N="50">And the secunde was Maximyane.</L>
<L>Tofore Dioclician this man was broght.</L>
<L>He spett on hym &amp; sett hym al at noght,</L>
<L>And put hym in prisone &amp; dede hym mykel dere</L>
<L>And layd on hym yre, as moche as he myght bere.
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="199"></L>
<L N="55">And after &thorn;at this tray (tur) dud take hym oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tray st. traytur? oder &thorn;at ist zu tilgen.</NOTE></L>
<L>And his body naked &amp; bare al aboute</L>
<L>Vnto a strong piler he dud hym fast bynde</L>
<L>And bete hym al aboute before &amp; eke be|hynde,</L>
<L>And of his bare body, &thorn;at was faire &amp; freshe,</L>
<L N="60">With pynchons &amp; pynsons thei rent away &thorn;e fleshe,</L>
<L>And buffeted hym, as thei were mad &amp; wode,</L>
<L>That alle his faire body ran alle of blode.</L>
<L>But in &thorn;e mene tyme, as trew men telle,</L>
<L>Dyoclician deyde, that was fals &amp; felle.</L>
<L N="65">And after shrewe anone cam anothe(r),</L>
<L>Maximian, in malice which was his bro|ther;</L>
<L>He was a fals shrewe, this Maxymyan,</L>
<L>Vnto this holy bisshop: he was his bane.</L>
<L>For he lete ordeyne an hidous gret fornace</L>
<L N="70">With pych &amp; hote leed &amp; brynston in brace</L>
<L>And vndernethe a fire brennynge fast,</L>
<L>And theron &thorn;is holy man anone he dede cast;</L>
<L>And al his bare body ther in dud bathe,</L>
<L>But, blessid be god! he had no maner scathe.</L>
<L N="75">And than &thorn;is fals tyrant, ful of vnsele,</L>
<L>Toke an hevy haberioune of yre &amp; of stele</L>
<L>And leyd it in the fire, til it was glowyng,</L>
<L>And put it on &thorn;is seynt al naked stondyng;</L>
<L>But thurgh goddes grace he felt no more smert</L>
<L N="80">Than doth any man &thorn;at wereth a softe shert.</L>
<L>Than was this tyrant as wode as an hare,</L>
<L>For he coude no craft to bryng &thorn;is seynt to care.</L>
<L>And this tirante a newe iette dud aray:</L>
<L>Apone two trestellis a long bord dud he lay</L>
<L N="85">And this holi man he lete bynde to that borde,</L>
<L>And to his felle turmentoures this was his worde:</L>
<L>"Kyt ye with a knyf his body round aboute,</L>
<L>That his guttes &amp; entrailes may comen oute,</L>
<L>And wynde hem vp after &thorn;at apon a long spete:</L>
<L N="90">And lete hym than after &thorn;at do alle his profete".</L>
<L>And as this tirant bade, anone it was done,</L>
<L>And his kene tormentours redely &amp; sone.</L>
<L>And there this holy man withyn short space</L>
<L>He yeaue vp the gost, as goddes wille was.</L>
<L N="95">Fro &thorn;e woo of this world thus dud he wende</L>
<L>To ioy &amp; to blisse that neuer shal haue ende.</L>
<L>God of his goodnes &amp; of his gret grace</L>
<L>Thurgh help of &thorn;is seynt bryng vs to &thorn;at place!</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Oratio ad Erasmum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Erasmus, thu holi bisshopp</L>
<L N="100">And goddes owne martir, as we tristly hopp:</L>
<L>As thu on &thorn;e sonday offred vp thi good</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of oure lord &thorn;at dyed on &thorn;e rood,</L>
<L>And as &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> on &thorn;e sonday suffrest &thorn;i disese</L>
<L>For oure lordes loue, whom &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> woldest plese:</L>
<L N="105">Thu receyue oure prayer and oure offryng</L>
<L>To the worship of god &amp; his plesyng,</L>
<L>And saue vs alle from al maner payne,</L>
<L>Yf it be goddes wille and also thyne,</L>
<L>And saue vs alle fro hem &thorn;at ben oure foone,</L>
<L N="110">Both bodely and gostly &thorn;at vs disese none,</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e mercy of god &amp; also &thorn;i mede</L>
<L>Graunte vs repentance for oure mysdede,
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>And houslyf to our gostly helthe, or we hens wende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sacrament of anoyntyng at our last ende!</L>
<L N="115">When we be ded &amp; in peyn for synne,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fire of purgatorie, when we be there ynne:</L>
<L>Help vs in that woo, be it more or lesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we may come to ioye aboue &thorn;er al|way is blisse!</L>
<L>ALmyghti god in Trinite,</L>
<L N="120">One in godhed &amp; persones thre,</L>
<L>Fader and sone and holy gost,</L>
<L>That art lord of myghtes most:</L>
<L>We pray the, lord, that thu here vs</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of synt Erasmus!</L>
<L N="125">Whos good werkes &amp; good lyvyng</L>
<L>Vnto the, lord, was ful plesyng:</L>
<L>Worshipp to the he dede alway,</L>
<L>But pryncipally on the sonday,</L>
<L>With mattynes, masse and orisone</L>
<L N="130">And other workes of deuocione.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sonday euermore thus wold he wirke:</L>
<L>He taught the peple, prechyng in the kyrke,</L>
<L>And on the sonday he yeaue his good</L>
<L>To the pore peple for here bodely food &mdash;</L>
<L N="135">Thus he fed hem with goddis worde,</L>
<L>(&amp;)settyng hym honestly at his owne borde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; fehlt. hym = hem.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in the sonday he fond gret light</L>
<L>Brennyng in &thorn;e churche faire &amp; bright</L>
<L>In worship &amp; honour of god in Trinite</L>
<L N="140">And of the seyntes that in heuen be.</L>
<L>And on the sonday, lord, for thi loue</L>
<L>He suffred shame and gret reproue</L>
<L>For many yeris, as many men say;</L>
<L>He had gret turmentry on the sonday:</L>
<L N="145">On the sonday ful evel he was arayd</L>
<L>Thurgh II tyrantes, aforne as y sayd,</L>
<L>And thus on the sonday ful paciently</L>
<L>He suffred most part of his turmentry,</L>
<L>And on the sonday forsoth he was slayne</L>
<L N="150">For the loue of god, this is certayne,</L>
<L>And on the sonday he went to blisse &mdash;</L>
<L>God bryng vs theder, whan his wille ys.</L>
<L>GOd, &thorn;at of thi goodnes &amp; of &thorn;i gret grace</L>
<L>Yeaue to this holiman wil, tyme and space</L>
<L N="155">To suffre gret peyne, his pacience to prove,</L>
<L>Lord, to thi plesaunce &amp; to his behove,</L>
<L>Thurgh thyn ordynance dedest make his ende,</L>
<L>Fro this worldes woo to blisse &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> dedest hym wende:</L>
<L>Thus, goodnes of god, graunte vs kepe oure wayes</L>
<L N="160">To worshipe god euer kepyng his holy dayes,</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e sonday to halwe so holy</L>
<L>As dud this holyman lyvyng here bodely:</L>
<L>To folwe his techyng &amp; prechyng in good wise,</L>
<L>With deuote prayers heryng dew seruise,</L>
<L N="165">And other good dedes as dud this holi man,</L>
<L>Euery man in his degre as he may &amp; can;</L>
<L>To worshipe &thorn;e, god, as this goodman dede,</L>
<L>With loue &amp; parfite charite, as oure bokes bidde,</L>
<L>And so to suffre here both wele &amp; woo</L>
<L N="170">In this wrecched world, or we hens go:</L>
<L>To which ioy and blisse, good god, bryng vs</L>
<L>Thurgh help of &thorn;is holy man seynt Eras|mus!</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN!</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Non noceat facinus: mihi, me iuuet almus Erasmus.</L>
<L>O sacer Erasme,: meritis precibusque re|gas me!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>
</LG>


</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="b" TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000207.tif" N="[201]">
<HEAD>b) aus Ms. Bedford, fol. 280.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle cristen folke, &yogh;e listen and lere</L>
<L>Of an holy buysshope &amp; a martere,</L>
<L>Whos name is clepede seynte Erasmus,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e boke says &amp; trewe men telle vs.</L>
<L N="5">Of an holy man here may men rede</L>
<L>Whate merite &thorn;ey may haue &amp; what mede</L>
<L>That wille worship god &amp; hym deuoutely</L>
<L>Euery sonday, withe thre &thorn;inges princi|paly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;inges be &thorn;ay, as &yogh;e shall here:</L>
<L N="10">Withe a deuoute pater noster or o&thorn;er praiere,</L>
<L>And withe som almesdede, lesse or more,</L>
<L>Of mete or of mony geuyn to &thorn;e pore,</L>
<L>Ande withe som candel-lighte more or lesse</L>
<L>Brennynge ate evynsonge, matens or messe.</L>
<L N="15">He &thorn;at doos &thorn;ese &thorn;re &thorn;inges for &thorn;is mar|tur sake,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. marur.</NOTE></L>
<L>These rewardes folowyng forso&thorn;e shal he take:</L>
<L>On is &thorn;is: &thorn;at he shalle haue to his le|uynge</L>
<L>A resonable fode to his last endynge;</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er is &thorn;is: &thorn;at any of his foone</L>
<L N="20">Henderynge or harme to hym schalle do none,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if his cause be trew &mdash; &thorn;is is certan, &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;rou&yogh;te &thorn;e prayere of &thorn;is holy man,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;at he askis resonabbly,</L>
<L>God wille ite graunte hym of his mercy;</L>
<L N="25">An o&thorn;er is &thorn;is &mdash; &thorn;at schall hym plese:</L>
<L>He shalle be releued of all maner desese;</L>
<L>Aud an o&thorn;er is &thorn;is, as &thorn;e boke sey&thorn;e:</L>
<L>He shalle dey in &thorn;e ri&yogh;t beleue &amp; feythe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tasel = teasel, fuller's thistle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all so, or &thorn;e soule fro &thorn;e body twy(n),<NOTE PLACE="foot">Das vorletzte Wort ist unleserlich, scheinbar balst.</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">He shall haue shryfte &amp; contricion for his sy(n),</L>
<L>Moreouer he shalle resceyue, or he be dede,</L>
<L>Cristes owne bodey in &thorn;e forme of brede,</L>
<L>And he shalle reseyue afore his endyng</L>
<L>The holy blessed sacremente of annoyn|tyng.</L>
<L N="35">And so shalle he come to &thorn;at ioye &amp; blys,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whiche as we trow &thorn;is holy man is,</L>
<L>Thate is &thorn;e blys of hevyn &thorn;at neuer shalle ende &mdash;</L>
<L>God geue vs all grace &thorn;edyr for to wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sers, &yogh;e shall vnderstand, as we wretyn fynd,</L>
<L N="40">&thorn;at &thorn;is holy man was ponysshed &amp; pynde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cuntre of Champayne, as &thorn;e boke telles</L>
<L>And as men reporte &thorn;at in &thorn;e cuntre dwelles.</L>
<L>Whos day falles in &thorn;e somer on &thorn;e &thorn;rid day<NOTE PLACE="foot">In brandlet ist die letzte Silbe durch Corr. unleserlich.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Juyn, next monythe after May.</L>
<L N="45">And on &thorn;e sonday he had his most woo,</L>
<L>Of whiche I shall tell iou, or I hens goo,</L>
<L>Vnder two fals tyrauntes ful vntreuly,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were fals traytours to god allmyghty:</L>
<L>&THORN;e name of &thorn;e fyrst was callid Dioclician,</L>
<L N="50">And &thorn;e secund was callid Maximian.
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="202"></L>
</LG>
<LIST>
<HEAD>These ben &thorn;e passions &thorn;at &thorn;e suffred only on &thorn;e sonday for &thorn;e loue of god:</HEAD>
<ITEM>&THORN;e first was inprisonyng, tyll turmentours come.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e II was byndyng to a pyler withe sharpe cordes.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e III was betyng all naked withe scourges of lede.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e IV was betyng withe &yogh;erdys made of brymbles.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e V was betyng withe grete balled battes.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e VI was brennyng withe torchys on iche place.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e VII was rakes of yren rendyng his flesshe.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e VIII was tynes brennand prikkyng &thorn;e flessh.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<LIST>
<HEAD>These passions he suffred vnder Dioclician of &thorn;e turmentours of Turry(?):</HEAD>
<ITEM>&THORN;e IX was stokkyng, fettryng &amp; manaclid agayn.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e X was dryuand grete nayles in his body.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XI was drauyng vp withe cordes &thorn;e body be a poly.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XII was nyppyng his body withe pynsons.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XIII was dryuand oute his tethe withe betylles.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XIV was persyng his flesshe withe fyre forkis.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XV was pyche, ter, leed, brynston, &amp; oyle boylyng.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XVI was bounden to a borde withe a grete peys of leede.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<LIST>
<HEAD>These he suffred of &thorn;e turmentours of . . (der Name fehlt):</HEAD>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XVII was paryng of his nayles of fyngres &amp; toys.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XVIII was betyng on his body withe brennyng malles.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XIX was drawyng out his tethe withe hote pynsons.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XX was boylyng in a lede ful of oyle.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXI was annoyntyng his body withe hote pyche &amp; ter.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXII was a brennyng helme set on his hede.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXIII was hanggyng vp by &thorn;e fete &amp; peyses be &thorn;e nek.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXIV was a fleshoke rendyng his flesshe.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXV<SUP>ti</SUP> was brennyng horse-combes to currey hym withe.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXVI<SUP>ti</SUP> was plukkyng his flesshe withe fullers combes.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXVII<SUP>ti</SUP> was a brennyng myter set vp on his hede.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXVIII was rubbyng his body withe fullers tasels.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXIX was rubbyng his body withe a ba . . prik.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXX was sheryng his flesshe with cikels.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXI was castyng hym oftyn on &thorn;e tyndes of an harow.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXII was betyng withe scourgis fulle of ballis of tree.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXIII was scorgynge hym withe cheynnes of yren.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXIIII was crownyng him withe garlondis of thornis.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXV was turnyng oute his ien withe wymbles.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXVI was brennyng eggys bounden to his arme-holys.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXVII was layde on a brennynge stone withe fyyr vnder.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXVIII was a brennynge haburgeon cast vpon hym.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XXXIX was sawynge withe sawes of tree.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XL was a myter brennyng set on his hed ageyne.</ITEM>
<ITEM>
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="203">&THORN;e XLI was brennynge hym in a hote ouen.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLII was persyng his body withe hote yren spyttes.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLIII was brennyng on a brandlete(?) bounden &thorn;erto.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLIIII was hangyng be &thorn;e handis on a Jebet. (Hier ein Zwischenraum, f&uuml;r eine Ueberschrift).</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLV was: &thorn;ey dyd hym gon barefote vpon colis.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLVI was brennyng platys leyde to his body.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLVII was hangen on cros like seynt Petir.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e LXVIII was cuttyng his flesshe withe rasers.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e XLVIV was liggand on a bedde and fyre &thorn;ervnder.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e L was wyndyng his gottis out withe wyndelas.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e LI was beting, bunchyng, &amp; byndyng to a peler.</ITEM>
<ITEM>&THORN;e LII was puttyng salt in his body after his guttes were oute. &amp; sithen byryed withe angelys in Champayne.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P>Darunter folgt in roth, aber ausgewischt mit schwarz:</P>
<P>Quicumque hanc antiphonam cum oracione subscripta corde contrito quali die dominica deuote dixerit in honore sancti Erasmi Episcopi &amp; martiris, deus ipsi pro|uidebit de omnibus sibi nessessarijs, absque eucaristia et sacra vnxcione non mo|rietur, ab omnibus inimicis tutus erit, et decem milia dierum indulgencie pro mer|cede habebit.</P>
<P>(Das angezeigte Gebet folgt aber nicht, doch ist L&uuml;cke von 1&frac12; Spalten daf&uuml;r gelassen).
</P>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="argument"><PB REF="00000210.tif" N="[204]">
<HEAD>9. A disputisoun bytwene a cristenemon and<LB>a Jew<NOTE PLACE="foot2">3 Strophen dieses Gedichts, V. 145-192, sind abgedruckt in Warton's Hist. of Engl. Litt. (ed. Hazlitt III, 181-3). Es ist im Dialekte und wahrscheinlich vom Dichter der Susanna.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>(Sir Water's wunderbarer Sieg &uuml;ber einen Juden).</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Vernon, fol. 301.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle bli&thorn;e mote &thorn;ei be</L>
<L>&THORN;at folyes ble&thorn;eliche wole fle.</L>
<L>How hit bitidde bi&yogh;onde s&eacute;&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e I wol &yogh;ow say.</L>
<L N="5">In &thorn;e toun of Parys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a cit&eacute;&eacute; of prys,</L>
<L>Twey men mette &thorn;at weore wys,</L>
<L>And wente bi &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei weore clerkes of diuinite,</L>
<L N="10">Crafti men in heore degre.</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;er maister wolde be,</L>
<L>Fonde&thorn; &yogh;if &thorn;ei may.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei desputed so faste</L>
<L>While &thorn;e day mihte laste,</L>
<L N="15">Nou&thorn;er o&thorn;er cou&thorn;e caste,</L>
<L>Beo rihtwys lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e ton was of Engelonde,</L>
<L>A cristene mon, Ich vnderstonde;</L>
<L>He hedde Isouht ouer &thorn;e sonde</L>
<L N="20">Wondres to se:</L>
<L>He hedde Ilernd of clergys,</L>
<L>As men do&thorn; &thorn;at beo&thorn; wys:</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at most is of prys</L>
<L>Maister moste be.</L>
<L N="25">&THORN;e to&thorn;er was a jeu&yogh; riht,</L>
<L>A mon muchel of his miht;</L>
<L>To his trou&thorn;e hedde he tiht</L>
<L>Trewe as &thorn;e tre:</L>
<L>&THORN;at wol I apertly preue:</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;ulke lay &thorn;at he on leeue,<NOTE PLACE="foot1">me fehlt vor mihte.</NOTE></L>
<L>For no gold &thorn;at (me) mihte him &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Chaunge wolde not he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e cristene mon seide, as he &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"Lo &yogh;onde vr god, &thorn;at vs bou&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="35">O&thorn;er trouwe &thorn;ou hit nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bi daye nor bi niht?</L>
<L>Certeynliche, &yogh;onde is he</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs di&yogh;ede on &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>And also bouwed him to be</L>
<L N="40">In a buyrde briht,</L>
<L>As heo wemles was,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e cler as &thorn;e glas;</L>
<L>Bitwene oxe and an as</L>
<L>Ibore was &thorn;at kniht</L>
<L N="45">At &thorn;e &yogh;ol ful &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Al for vr welfare.</L>
<L>Woldest &thorn;ou leeue on my lare,</L>
<L>&THORN;i lykyng were liht".
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&THORN;e jeu&yogh; sone seide &thorn;are:</L>
<L N="50">"Ar we for&thorn;ere fare &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er is o god, and no mare,</L>
<L>Hei&yogh;ly in holde,</L>
<L>And, as I trowe, in &thorn;e trone,</L>
<L>He schop &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e moone;</L>
<L N="55">But he hedde neuer no sone</L>
<L>For synful was solde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete god calle we &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is semely to se:</L>
<L>O&thorn;er may &thorn;er non be,</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;onger ne olde.</L>
<L>Wharto makestou &thorn;i mone?</L>
<L>I trouwe, &thorn;i wit beo &thorn;e wone;</L>
<L>Al mis artou gone</L>
<L>Heer on &thorn;is wolde".<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wolde st. molde?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="65">&THORN;e cristen mon stonde&thorn; stille,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;en he talke&thorn; him tille</L>
<L>And sei&thorn; &thorn;at "&thorn;i wikked wille</L>
<L>Schal worche &thorn;e ful wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou leuest not in &thorn;e mes,</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;at euer god &thorn;er in is:<NOTE PLACE="foot">is st. es.</NOTE></L>
<L>For&thorn;i lyking is &thorn;e les<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach for&thorn;i fehlt &thorn;i?</NOTE></L>
<L>And loren artou so,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;i careful kynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer bicom of his strende.</L>
<L N="75">Men schal in baret &thorn;e bynde</L>
<L>And bete &thorn;e ful blo.</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou schalt of &thorn;is world wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be tau&yogh;t to &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>And euermore wi&thorn;outen ende</L>
<L N="80">In to &thorn;e pyne go".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e jeu&yogh; bigon him to greue:</L>
<L>"&THORN;at wol I apertly preue,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of Adam and of Eue</L>
<L>Of hem we weore alle Iwrouht.</L>
<L N="85">And I dar wage wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>Tonnes of wyn &thorn;re</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schal lete &thorn;e him se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seist &thorn;at &thorn;e bouht,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e vuel and &thorn;e gode:</L>
<L N="90">Hou he was don on &thorn;e roode;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at bi him stoode</L>
<L>Whon he to de&thorn;e was brouht.</L>
<L>So const &thorn;ou not do</L>
<L>For al &thorn;i clergye; &thorn;erto,</L>
<L N="95">As haue I reste o&thorn;er ro,</L>
<L>&THORN;i reson is nou&yogh;t".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon mildely gon malt:</L>
<L>"I telle &thorn;e, truwaunt fortalt:</L>
<L>Men schal in prison &thorn;e palt</L>
<L N="100">And putte &thorn;e to pyne,</L>
<L>But &yogh;if &thorn;ou lete me him se</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vs dyede on &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e maystrie &yogh;eue I &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e and alle &thorn;yne.</L>
<L N="105">Loke &thorn;ow holde &thorn;at we say!</L>
<L>To morwe, set we &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>We schal wende on vr way</L>
<L>To winne vs &thorn;e wyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at fayles of his fare,</L>
<L N="110">Al loren is his lare;</L>
<L>He may droupe and dare</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal his trou&thorn;e tyne".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;ei woke al &thorn;e niht,</L>
<L>Til on &thorn;e morwen at day-liht</L>
<L N="115">&THORN;e cristene mon ros riht,</L>
<L>And radly gon say</L>
<L>His matyns in &thorn;e mornyng;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e his masse gon he syng,</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked vr lord in alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="120">As he &thorn;at most may.</L>
<L>Soone &thorn;ei metten, as &thorn;ei miht.</L>
<L>"Haue I don", he seide, "artou diht</L>
<L>For to holde &thorn;at &thorn;ou hiht?</L>
<L>&THORN;is is vr day.</L>
<L N="125">O&thorn;er a nay, or a &yogh;a?</L>
<L>Soone tel &thorn;ou me swa!"</L>
<L>Him grauntes forto ga,</L>
<L>And went on heore way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon seide son,</L>
<L N="130">Whon his masse was don:</L>
<L>"I wol take god me vppon
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>And bere him wi&thorn; me:</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e in lond and in leode</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e lasse is my drede:</L>
<L N="135">&THORN;e mon &thorn;at to him take&thorn; hede</L>
<L>&THORN;e better he may be.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis non enemy in helle</L>
<L>Non so fers ne so felle,</L>
<L>And he here of vre lord telle,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at on is in &thorn;re:</L>
<L>For al &thorn;e gold in &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>He wolde not byde him a stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde freschly founde</L>
<L>And awey fle".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="145">For&thorn; heo wenten on &thorn;e feld</L>
<L>To an hul &thorn;ei biheold.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eor&thorn;e cleuet as a scheld</L>
<L>On &thorn;e grounde grene.</L>
<L>Sone fond &thorn;ei a stih:</L>
<L N="150">&THORN;ei went &thorn;er-on radly;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristene mon hedde ferly</L>
<L>What hit mihte mene.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at sti&yogh; lay a strete,</L>
<L>Clene Ipauet wi&thorn; grete.</L>
<L N="155">&THORN;ei fond a maner &thorn;at was meete</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; mur&thorn;es ful schene,</L>
<L>Wel coruen and wrouht,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; halles hei&yogh;e vppon loft.</L>
<L>To a place weore &thorn;ei brouht</L>
<L N="160">As paradys &thorn;e clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er was foulene song,</L>
<L>Muche mur&thorn;es among &mdash;</L>
<L>Hose lenge wolde long,</L>
<L>Ful luitel him &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L N="165">On vche a syde of &thorn;e halle</L>
<L>Pourpul, pelure and palle;</L>
<L>Wyndouwes I &thorn;e walle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">I = In, wie 306.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was wonderli Iwrouht.</L>
<L>&THORN;er was dosers on &thorn;e dees</L>
<L N="170">Hose &thorn;e cheef wolde ches,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere ricchere wes</L>
<L>In no sale souht.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e mot and &thorn;e molde</L>
<L>Schon al on red golde.</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;e cristen mon hedde ferli on &thorn;at folde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ider was brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er was erbes growen grene,</L>
<L>Spices springynge bitwene &mdash;</L>
<L>"Such hedde I non sene,</L>
<L N="180">Forso&thorn;e, as I say".</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;restel song ful schille,</L>
<L>He newed notes at his wille;</L>
<L>Feire floures to fille.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at ist zu tilgen?</NOTE></L>
<L>Feire in &thorn;at fey.</L>
<L N="185">And al &thorn;e Rounde table good</L>
<L>Hou Arthur in eor&thorn;e &yogh;od,</L>
<L>Sum sat and sum stod</L>
<L>O &thorn;e grounde grey &mdash;</L>
<L>Hit was a wonderful siht:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Im Ms. fehlt hier ein Vers.</NOTE></L>
<L N="190">As &thorn;ei weore quik men diht,</L>
<L>To seo hou &thorn;ey play.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e jew&yogh; sone in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>He spak &thorn;er a word of pryde &mdash;</L>
<L>Hose wol lenge and abyde</L>
<L N="195">May lusten and lere.</L>
<L>Til a nonnerie &thorn;ei came &mdash;</L>
<L>But I knowe not &thorn;e name:</L>
<L>&THORN;er was mony a derwor&thorn;e dame</L>
<L>In dyapre dere.</L>
<L N="200">Squi&yogh;ers in vch a syde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e wones so wyde.</L>
<L>"Heer schul we lenge and abyde,</L>
<L>Auntres to heere".</L>
<L>&THORN;enne swi&thorn;e speke&thorn; he</L>
<L N="205">Til a ladi so fre</L>
<L>And bidde&thorn;: &thorn;at he welcome be,</L>
<L>"Sire Water, my feere".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;er was bordes Iclo&thorn;ed clene</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; schire clo&thorn;es and schene.</L>
<L N="210">Se&thorn;&thorn;e a wasschen, I weene,</L>
<L>And wente to &thorn;e sete.</L>
<L>Riche metes was for&thorn; brouht</L>
<L>To alle men, &thorn;at good &thorn;ouht &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon wolde nouht</L>
<L N="215">Drynke nor ete.
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>&THORN;er was wyn ful clere</L>
<L>In mony a feir maseere,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er drynkes &thorn;at weore dere</L>
<L>In coupes ful gret.</L>
<L N="220">Si&thorn;&thorn;e was schewed hem bi</L>
<L>Mur&thorn;e and munstralsy,</L>
<L>And preyed hem do gladly</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; rial rehet.<NOTE PLACE="foot">rehet = cheer, afrz. rehaiter.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By &thorn;e bordes vp &thorn;ei stode.</L>
<L N="225">Or &thorn;ei for&thorn;ere &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>So weore &thorn;ei war of a rode</L>
<L>Ful ra&thorn;e, as I rede,</L>
<L>And a bodi &thorn;er-vppon</L>
<L>&THORN;at woundes hedde mony on;</L>
<L N="230">Bi him stod Marie and Jon,</L>
<L>Wepynde good spede,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur apostles of prys,</L>
<L>Poul and Peter &thorn;e wys</L>
<L>And seint Jon &thorn;e Baptys,</L>
<L N="235">Was douhti of dede.</L>
<L>Whon he was schewed to &thorn;e siht,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of leom and of liht</L>
<L>&THORN;e mon &thorn;at most was of miht,</L>
<L>His woundes gon blede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="240">&THORN;e jeu&yogh; sone seide he:</L>
<L>"Holden is &thorn;at I hihte &thorn;e".</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er seide: "&thorn;at schal I se,</L>
<L>Certeynly, ful sone".</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristen mon hedde a derwor&thorn; &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="245">On his bodi he gon hit brynge:</L>
<L>&THORN;at a prest schulde wi&thorn; synge</L>
<L>Whon masse schulde be don.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be god so fre</L>
<L>&THORN;at for me di&yogh;ed on &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="250">Here &thorn;i sone mai &thorn;ou se"</L>
<L>And heold him abouen.</L>
<L>Whon he was schewed to &thorn;e siht,</L>
<L>He barst &thorn;e buyldynge so briht.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e was derk as &thorn;e niht</L>
<L N="255">Heore sonne and heore mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;e gere &thorn;at was gay</L>
<L>Was &thorn;enne Iwasted away.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristene mon gon say:</L>
<L>"Beon &thorn;eos &thorn;i godes here?"</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;e jeuh onswerde him wi&thorn; nay</L>
<L>And ofte merci gon him pray:</L>
<L>"I wol leue my lay</L>
<L>And on &thorn;i lore lere.</L>
<L>Sore I doute me of dred.</L>
<L N="265">I haue ilost my wed:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at are for&thorn; fled</L>
<L>Was fendes in feere,</L>
<L>Non good, but al ille".</L>
<L>No more he tented hem tille.</L>
<L N="270">Heo &thorn;o stoden ope hulle</L>
<L>&THORN;er &thorn;ey furst were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;us he &yogh;eldes him &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Al for his welfare.</L>
<L>He seide: "of blisse I haue be bare</L>
<L N="275">Se&thorn;&thorn;en I was furst born.</L>
<L>Now knowe I wel &thorn;at hit mai be</L>
<L>&THORN;at ofold god is in &thorn;re:</L>
<L>Whuch &thorn;at &thorn;ou brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;is day at morn.</L>
<L N="280">He is vre heuene kyng,</L>
<L>Makere of alle &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>And schop &thorn;e fruit for to spryng,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e curnel and corn".</L>
<L>&THORN;us he rapes of his res,</L>
<L N="285">To vre God he him ches,</L>
<L>Let al his lu&thorn;ernes,</L>
<L>Was poynt to be lorn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ei wente to &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L>Acordet, as &thorn;ei scholde be.</L>
<L N="290">Who was payed bote he,</L>
<L>And ei&thorn;er of o&thorn;er!</L>
<L>He &thorn;onked god his swete sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hedde brou&yogh;t out of bonde,</L>
<L>Wel Iwonne to his honde,</L>
<L N="295">Bli&thorn;ely his bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Mete and drynke &thorn;ei hedde at wille,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;outen grucchyng or grille</L>
<L>In trou&thorn;e tente &thorn;ei &thorn;er tille,</L>
<L>And lafte al &thorn;at o&thorn;er.</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;e mon &thorn;at ha&thorn; synne Iwrou&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>And si&thorn;en repentes him ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God is apayed, &thorn;at vs bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Leeue we non o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What was &thorn;e monnes nome Ilyk</L>
<L N="305">But Sir Water of Berewyk?</L>
<L>He was wonynge I &thorn;e ryk,</L>
<L>At Roome was called.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope &yogh;af him pouste &mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at mony mon mihte se &mdash;</L>
<L N="310">Penitauncer for to be</L>
<L>Of &yogh;onge and of olde,</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e to soyle and to schriue</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to mon and to wyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. two st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>Eke to mende heore lyue</L>
<L N="3">And to &thorn;e trou&thorn;e holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne tok &thorn;ei &thorn;e jeu&yogh;</L>
<L>Anon cristend hym neu&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;us to vre god he hym kneu&yogh;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eply him &yogh;olde.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="life"><PB REF="00000215.tif" N="[209]">
<HEAD>10. Roberd of Cisyle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese Legende, die bekanntlich schon von Utterson, Halliwell und Hazlitt nach verschiedenen Mss. edirt ist, folgt hier in einer gereinigten Ausgabe, auf Grund|lage der engverwandten Mss. Vernon (V) und Trin. Coll. Oxf. 57 (T), die dem Orig. am n&auml;chsten stehen, mit Vergleichung des Ms. Harl. 1701 (H), welches die Verse an meh|reren Stellen anders ordnet und Zus&auml;tze (es z&auml;hlt 476 V.) aufweist, und Harl. 525 (Ha), welches noch bedeutendere Abweichungen zeigt und den Text vielfach frei ver&auml;ndert. Das sich an Harl. 525 anschliessende, vom Originale am weitesten entfernende Ms. Cbr. Ff II, 38 (514 V.) ist f&uuml;r die Textkritik fast werthlos und nur hie und da zu|gezogen. (Die letzte der bekannten Hss. Cbr. Ji IV, 8, habe ich nicht benutzen k&ouml;nnen). Ich habe geglaubt, auch in graphischer Hinsicht mich von den Hss. nicht entfernen zu d&uuml;rfen, obwohl das Original wahrscheinlich einige abweichende Formen hatte (z. B. vielleicht ich st. ech, swich st. such, gilt pilt st. gult pult, chirche &ouml;fter no st. ne u. a.); doch ist einheitliche Schreibung durchgef&uuml;hrt. Ob das s&uuml;d-mittell&auml;ndische Original &thorn;ei (&thorn;ai) oder heo (he?) als pron. plur. 3 hatte, ist schwierig zu entscheiden; V hat in der Regel heo (&thorn;ei nur 175), die and. Mss. &thorn;e&yogh;, &thorn;ey.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PRinces proude &thorn;at be&thorn; in pres,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T in pes. Ha princis. bene. preesse.</NOTE></L>
<L>I wil &yogh;ou telle &thorn;ing nobles.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V I wol, T ich wille, H I wyl. V ou, not les. T &thorn;yng nobles. H of &thorn;yng no les. Ha: A thing I wulle yow telle &thorn;at is no lees.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Cisyle was a noble kyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Ha Cesile, H Cysylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fair and strong and sumdel &yogh;yng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H fayre, stronge, sumdele (H hat oft e am Ende). Ha yonge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">He hadde a bro&thorn;er in grete Rome,<NOTE PLACE="foot">V hedde.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pope of alle Cristendome;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Ha of alle, V of al, H ouer al.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er bro&thorn;er in Almayne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">V he hedde st. bro&thorn;er, Alemayne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Emperour, &thorn;at Sarzins wrou&yogh;te payne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V An Emperour. H whom st. &thorn;at. V sara&yogh;ins, T sarsynes, H sa|rysyns. Ha sarysinys wrought ageyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng was hote Kyng Roberd;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha called. V Ha Robert.</NOTE></L>
<L N="10">Neuer man wiste him ferd;<NOTE PLACE="foot">V ne wuste, T H Ha wiste. T H Ha aferd, V fert.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was kyng of gret honour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H grete honoure. Ha of mikelle.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;at he was Conquerour;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H And yclepyd he was, Ha He was cleped a.</NOTE></L>
<L>In al &thorn;e worlde nas his per,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wordle. H In alle &thorn;e worlde ne was, Ha In noo lond was. H Ha pere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kyng ne prince, fer no ner.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Die Mss. lesen ne st. no.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">H Forto acounte; Ha (C) Kyng ne duke. H Ha nere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">And for he was of chiualrye flour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And fehlt in Ha. V chiualrie, T cheualrie, H chyualry. H floure.</NOTE></L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er was mad Emperour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H made.</NOTE></L>
<L>His o&thorn;er bro&thorn;er Godes vikere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">V godes, T godis, H goddys.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pope of Rome, as I seide ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope was hote Pope Vrban:<NOTE PLACE="foot">VT was hote, H hyghte. Ha He was cleped.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">He was good to God and man;<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ha: he louede bo&thorn;e, Ha god a man.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e emperour was hote Valemounde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H hyghte syre, Ha was cleped sir Valamond.</NOTE></L>
<L>A strengur werreour was non founde<NOTE PLACE="foot">VH strengur, T strengere, Ha stronger. T werrour, H Ha werryoure, V weorreour. V nas, T Ha was, H was neuer none. Ha found.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>After his bro&thorn;er of Cisyle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H: He sente aftyre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;at I schal telle a while.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T wham. &thorn;at fehlt in H Ha. H y shal &yogh;ow, Ha I wulle speke. T shel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="25">&THORN;e kyng &thorn;ou&yogh;te he hadde no per<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha That st. &thorn;e. H pere.</NOTE></L>
<L>In al &thorn;e worlde, fer no ner;<NOTE PLACE="foot">V H no, T Ha ne. Ha ferre. H Ha nere.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t he hadde pride,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H In &thorn;at, and fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he was nounper in ech a side.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V T nounpeer, H nom pere; Ha hadde no pere in neuer a syde. V vch a, T H eche (Orig. ich?).</NOTE></L>
<L>At midsomer, a seynt Jones ni&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ha: And in (Ha on) a ny&yogh;t of seynt Jone (so auch C.).</NOTE></L>
<L N="30">&THORN;e kyng to cherche com ful ri&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H: The kyng come to &thorn;e cherche anone; Ha: The baptist, &thorn;e kynge to cherche wold gone (C: Thys kynge to &thorn;e churche come). V churche, al. cherche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Forto heren his euensong.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V Ha heeren, T H here. T eue|song, H euynsong.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he dwelled &thorn;er ful long:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he &thorn;oghte hys dwellyng. V Ha dwelled, T dwelde. V H ful, T Ha to.</NOTE></L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;te more in worldes honour<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha: His &thorn;ought was more in. H on worldly onoure. T worl|dis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an on Crist, oure saueour.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V &thorn;en, al. &thorn;an. V Ha in, T H on (C of). Ha Jhesu. V vr, al. oure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">In Magnificat he herde a vers:</L>
<L>He made a clerk hit him rehers<NOTE PLACE="foot">T it. Hreherce, Ha to rehers.</NOTE></L>
<L>In langage of his owne tonge &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">T owe. H tunge.</NOTE></L>
<L>In latyn he niste what &thorn;ei songe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V nuste, T nyste. H: For he wyste nat, Ha: In lateyn he ne west &thorn;at. V heo, T &thorn;e&yogh;, H Ha &thorn;ey.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e vers was &thorn;is, I telle &thorn;e:</L>
<L N="40">Deposuit potentes de sede</L>
<L>Et exaltauit humiles &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">V exultavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e vers, wi&thorn;outen les.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha That. T wi&thorn;oute.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e clerk seide anon ri&yogh;t:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H seyd anone.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sire, such is Godes mi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Sere. V T such, H swych, Ha soche.</NOTE></L>
<L N="45">&THORN;at he may make hey&yogh;e lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">T he&yogh; &amp; lowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And lowe hey&yogh;e, in litel &thorn;rowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T low he&yogh;, H &thorn;e lowe hyghe, H low hye. T Ha in a. V. luytel.</NOTE></L>
<L>God may do, wi&thorn;oute ly&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H he st. god. T don wi&thorn;outen. V ly&yogh;e, al. lye.</NOTE></L>
<L>His wille in twynklyng of an ei&yogh;e".<NOTE PLACE="foot">V wil. T twyng|lynge, Ha twenkelyng. H ye, Ha a nye.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng seide wi&thorn; herte vnstable:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ha (C) &thorn;oght st. herte. Ha vn|stabill.</NOTE></L>
<L N="50">"Al &yogh;oure song is fals and fable.<NOTE PLACE="foot">V T al &yogh;or (T &yogh;oure) song, H Thys song. Ha: ye rede and synge false in fable.</NOTE></L>
<L>What man ha&thorn; such pouwer<NOTE PLACE="foot">V mon. Ha &thorn;at st. such.</NOTE></L>
<L>Me to bringe lowe in daunger?<NOTE PLACE="foot">H Ha: To bringe me. Ha in soche, lowe fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>I am flour of chiualrye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha: My name is.</NOTE></L>
<L>Min enemys I may distrye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H enmyys, T myne enemyes. T H destroye, V distruye.</NOTE></L>
<L N="55">Noman liue&thorn; in no londe<NOTE PLACE="foot">T Ha leue&thorn;. H There ys noman &thorn;at lyue&thorn; yn londe, Ha Noman leueth now in londe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at me may wi&thorn;stonde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">H That may a&yogh;en me. Ha me may now.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an is &thorn;is a song of nou&yogh;t".<NOTE PLACE="foot">H songe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is errour he hadde in &thorn;ou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">H yn hys &thorn;o&yogh;t. Ha: This is errour &thorn;enne he thought.</NOTE></L>
