<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>aus Ms. Vernon fol. 393. &THORN;is tretys is hou &thorn;e word was wrou&yogh;t and Adam and Eue, &amp; &thorn;e wo &thorn;at Adam &amp; Eue in heore lyue hedden.</HEAD>
<P>Alle &thorn;at bileeuen on Jhesu Crist, lustene&thorn; and &yogh;e mowen heere how muche is &thorn;e miht of vre heuene kyng! Furst he schop heuene, &amp; si&thorn;en &thorn;e eor&thorn;e, to beren treo &amp; gras. &THORN;e eor&thorn;e was druy&yogh;e &amp; wi&thorn;outen moisture; &thorn;er nas no &thorn;ing &thorn;at was quik, nei&thorn;er more ne lasse. &verbar; &THORN;e holigost was euere, wi&thorn;outen bigin(n)ing, &amp; schal be wi&thorn;outen endyng. &verbar; God as his wille was, behihte to make liht. And &thorn;o he made angelus, of a swi&thorn;e fair bleo. &verbar; Sachel was &thorn;e furste angel &thorn;at Crist made, and si&thorn;en he hihte Lucifer, &thorn;at &thorn;orw pruide was forloren. &verbar; God seih &thorn;at hit was good to alle goode werkes: wel fayre he departed &thorn;e derke from &thorn;e liht. &verbar; Liht he cleped &thorn;e day, &amp; &thorn;e derknesse &thorn;e niht. Of euen &amp; of morewen he made a day. &amp; se&thorn;&thorn;en o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing, as I wol &yogh;ow tellen. &verbar; On &thorn;e secunde day he schop &thorn;e firmament, &thorn;at is abouen vs &mdash; vr lord bring vs alle &thorn;ider, &yogh;if hit beo his swete wille. &THORN;e watres vndur heuene Crist made togeder weende, and alle heore stremes, in a luytel stounde, and sende hem for&thorn;, for &thorn;at &thorn;e druye eor&thorn;e schulde bringe for&thorn; fruit; and &thorn;o he cleped &thorn;is water gedering. Crist seih &thorn;at hit was good. Of euen &amp; of morwen he made &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day. &verbar; &THORN;e feor&thorn;e day &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e mone he sette in &thorn;e firmament, &amp; sterres ful brihte; &thorn;e sonne he sette to &thorn;e day, &thorn;e mone to &thorn;e ni&yogh;te. &verbar; &THORN;e fif&thorn;e day Crist comaundet fissches in water forto swymme, mony beestes &amp; foules to be vnder &thorn;e firmament fli&yogh;t. And &thorn;o he maked &thorn;e whal, most of alle fissches, and alle maner beestes he made &thorn;er-myde, &amp; bidde&thorn; hem &thorn;at heo schulden waxe &amp; multiplye, &amp; &yogh;af hem his blessyng. &verbar; &THORN;e sixte day wolde god enden his werkes: hors &amp; re&thorn;eren he made, forte suffren wo, and alle maner beestes &thorn;at gon vppon fote.</P>
<P>And &thorn;o he made paradys, bi&yogh;onde &thorn;e mount of Asye, in pe Est-londe. Hit is wel euene &amp; swi&thorn;e round abouten, wi&thorn; a brennyng wal from heuene to &thorn;e grounde. &verbar; &THORN;e mur&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;er-inne is, non eor&thorn;lich may hit telle no seo. &THORN;er-inne growe&thorn; &thorn;e treo of lyf, &thorn;at stont &thorn;er wel faire&mdash;hose ete&thorn; of &thorn;at fruit, schal he neuer dy&yogh;en. 
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="221"> &THORN;er-inne springe&thorn; a welle, &thorn;at was mad wi&thorn; godis hondes; foure stremes &thorn;er rennen out of in to diuerse londes: &verbar; Fyson hette &thorn;at on strem &thorn;at come&thorn; from &thorn;at welle; &verbar; ano&thorn;ur hette Gyson, &thorn;at is of more prys: he passe&thorn; bi ano&thorn;er coost swi&thorn;e &yogh;eorne wi&thorn;-alle &thorn;at colde is inne Ifounden, and preciouse stones and &yogh;eem-stones &thorn;er ben swi&thorn;e noble forto staunche blood; &verbar; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde hette Eufrates: &thorn;at watur is swi&thorn;e swift; &verbar; &thorn;e feor&thorn;e hette Tygre: &thorn;at is briht &thorn;orw charbuncle-stones &thorn;at liggen &thorn;er-inne.</P>
<P>&THORN;O after he made mon of er&thorn;e, in flesch and bon, in &thorn;e vale of Ebron. &verbar; God reste &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e day; no&thorn;ing wolde he worche, for &thorn;ulke day men schulde herien god of heuene. &verbar; &THORN;er-aftur god bad foure angelus &thorn;at heo schulden seche &thorn;ulke monnes nome &thorn;at he hedde Imaad. &verbar; Seint Mihel wente in to &thorn;e est: he seih &thorn;er a sterre &thorn;at was swi&thorn;e briht: Anatalim was &thorn;at sterre Ihote, wi&thorn; &thorn;e furste lettre A; and soone he com a&yogh;eyn. &verbar; Gabriel in to &thorn;e west-half wente: and he sei&yogh; in &thorn;e firma|ment a sterre &thorn;at hihte was Dysus; &thorn;e furste lettre D &thorn;er-of soone he brou&yogh;te. &verbar; Raphael com to &thorn;e north: he say &thorn;er a sterre &thorn;at is Iclepet Arcis; anon he fleyh a&yogh;ein, wi&thorn; &thorn;e furste lettre A &thorn;at he con wi&thorn; him bringe. &verbar; For&thorn; him wente Vriel, riht in to &thorn;e sou&thorn;; Messembrion hihte &thorn;e sterre &thorn;at he sih &thorn;ere; wi&thorn; &thorn;e furste lettre M he wente swi&thorn;e a&yogh;eyn &amp; brouht hit tofore god wi&thorn; &thorn;e o&thorn;ur &thorn;reo. God took &thorn;eos foure lettres &amp; bad Vriel rede; &amp; he radde: Adam.</P>
<P>Crist maade Adam Ilyk to his owne ymage &amp; bleu&yogh; on him &thorn;e spirit of lyf wi&thorn; his swete mou&thorn;, and seide: "Lo, Adam is on of vs, connynge bo&thorn;e good and vuel. I wol &thorn;at &yogh;e honoure him". Seynt Mihel was &thorn;e furste &thorn;at dude him honour; and also &thorn;e o&thorn;ur angelus aftur him. &verbar; &THORN;o hit com to Sachel &thorn;at he schulde honoure him, so muche was his pryde &thorn;at he mi&yogh;t not lowen him, and seide: "I was er Adam". &THORN;o seide Micael to him: "&thorn;ou schalt honoure Adam; or god wole reyne wreche on &thorn;e". "&YOGH;e, &yogh;if he beo wro&thorn; wi&thorn; me, I wot where to abyden: I schal sette my seete in &thorn;e north-syde, and I wol be lyk &thorn;e hexte &thorn;at is abouen vs. &THORN;erfore I nul not honoure Adam, for ei&yogh;e ne for loue". And seide: "whuch of &yogh;ow seih me be maad?", as &thorn;eih he seide: I was er eny of &yogh;ou weore, I wol be euere to &thorn;e hexte. &verbar; And a vois seide abouen: "I was er &thorn;en &thorn;ou". And &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;af kepe to &thorn;at word, bilaften stille; and &thorn;e o&thorn;ure fellen adoun &thorn;at cosented to Lucifer, for heo neoren not stable toforen. And &thorn;enne weore &thorn;ei stabelichet in &thorn;at ilke while &thorn;at heo hedden &thorn;enne, bo&thorn;e &thorn;e goode &amp; vvuel, so &thorn;at heo ne mihte neuer out &thorn;er-of: and after &thorn;at while heo beon pynet, summe more &amp; summe lasse; and also to &thorn;e o&thorn;er: in heuene is heore joye. And he and alle his feeren fullen out of heuene; heo fullen out as &thorn;ikke as &thorn;e drift of &thorn;e snouh. &verbar; Summe astunte in &thorn;e eyr, and summe in &thorn;e eor&thorn;e. &verbar; &YOGH;if eny mon is elue Inome o&thorn;ur elue Iblowe, he hit ha&thorn; of &thorn;e angelus &thorn;at fellen out of heuene.</P>
<P>&THORN;O paradis was Imaad, god nom Adam bi &thorn;e hond and brouht him &thorn;er|inne, and brouhte alle beestes and foules toforen him. And he &yogh;af alle nome after heore kuynde. And he seih &thorn;at vchon hedde his make &amp; he hedde non. God nolde not &thorn;at Adam schulde libbe &thorn;er alone: he caste sleep in him, and made Eue of his owne ribbe, for &thorn;at he scholde haue al his wille. And to him he &yogh;af alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;o was o lyue, &verbar; &thorn;e fissches &amp; &thorn;e foules he &yogh;af to heore hondes, and alle manere of beestes, al but &thorn;e appel-tre &thorn;at he him forbade. &verbar; &thorn;o was Adam wel Inouh, &amp; riht wys of witte.&mdash;Now is heere a skile whi to asken weore whi &thorn;at wymmen ben feirore &thorn;en men bi kuynde; herto wol I onswere: for wommon was maad in pa|radis of Adames ribbe, and mon was maad of eor&thorn;e &amp; of foul fen; &thorn;erfore is wom|monnes 
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="222"> fel cleror &thorn;en monnes. &verbar; Al &thorn;e blisse of paradys was taken to Adam &amp; to Eue, his make, but &thorn;e treo of wisdom &thorn;at was forboden hem bi &thorn;e heste of god.</P>
<P>Adam hedde &thorn;e north-syde &amp; &thorn;e est of paradys, and Eue hedde to hire dele &thorn;e sou&thorn; &amp; &thorn;e west. Heo hedden two angelus to kepen hem &amp; to wissen hem, &thorn;at heo ne schulde haue no doute, for no maner drede. &verbar; Ti&thorn;inges coome anon to &thorn;e angelus &thorn;at kepten hem, &thorn;at heo schulden come anon to worschupe god almihti &amp; him to honoure. Assoone as &thorn;e angelus weore went for&thorn;, to seon heore creatour, &thorn;o was &thorn;e stude empti &thorn;er &thorn;ei hedden Iben. &verbar; &thorn;e angelus of helle, &thorn;at weore maad wi&thorn; Cristes hond, hedden gred envye of Adames joye &amp; of his blisse. &verbar; &THORN;e fend com as a neddre forte begylen Eue, and seide to hire: "What ha&thorn; god forboden ow?". And Eue tolde him a long tale, al what god hedde Iseid. And be hire tellyng &thorn;e schrewe fond wey of hire frelete. &verbar; "Ete nou", he seide, "of &thorn;is fruit, and &thorn;ou schalt eeuene ben lyk Crist; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt cunne &thorn;e goode &amp; &thorn;e vuel &mdash; bote &thorn;ou ete &thorn;er-of now, I holde &thorn;e for wood". And Eue &thorn;orw &thorn;e fendes red eet of &thorn;is fruit, and Adam for hire loue &amp; &thorn;at him rewed ful sore. &verbar; As soone as heo hedden &thorn;er-of eten, &thorn;ei knewen wel &thorn;at heo weren naket &mdash; and &thorn;at hedde Sathanas maad &thorn;orw his tresun. &verbar; Wi&thorn; leues of a fyger heo hudden heore bodies, &amp; hedden muche schome; and &thorn;er-of hedde Sathanas muche gle and game. &verbar; What god spak to Adam, &yogh;e schul wite sone.</P>
<P>Oure lord seide to Adam: "Wher art &thorn;ou nou? tel me, Adam, whi eet &thorn;ou of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. me me.</NOTE> &thorn;e tre?" "&thorn;e wommon &thorn;at &thorn;ou betoke me, lord, dude me ete &thorn;er-of". God seide &thorn;o to Adam: "For &thorn;ou hast don bi Eues lore, &thorn;ou schalt hit abugge afturward: &thorn;ou schalt fare in to &thorn;esternesse, and from bodilich hele in to serwe &amp; wo". &verbar; And &thorn;enne spak god to Eue: "Whi hast &thorn;ou &thorn;us Iwrouht?" And heo onswerd and seide: "Lord, &thorn;e eddre ha&thorn; bitrayet me". &THORN;o he spac to Eue &amp; seide: "Wommon! for &thorn;ou art vnwrast, in muchel trauayl &thorn;ou schalt ben, &amp; vnder monnes heste, children &thorn;ou schalt bere wi&thorn; muchel pyne &amp; wo, &amp; al &thorn;at of &thorn;e come&thorn;, &amp; al &thorn;in ofspring". &verbar; And god asket &thorn;e eddre: whi he dude so. And he seide: "for I hedde to hem envye". And "Neddre, for &thorn;ou bitrayedest mon wi&thorn; nuy &amp; wi&thorn; oonde, &thorn;i breste schal ben &thorn;i feet, and eor&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt eten, and men schal wayte &thorn;e to sl&eacute;&eacute;; vppe &thorn;i breste &thorn;ou schalt slyden, feet ne tit &thorn;e neuer noone. And whon &thorn;ou schalt don &thorn;i kuynde, &thorn;ou schalt smiten &thorn;in hed in to &thorn;in makes mou&thorn;e, &amp; heo schal byten hit of; wi&thorn; &thorn;yne furste kundles<NOTE PLACE="foot">kundles = young, s. Bestiary V. 620.</NOTE> &thorn;ow schalt bersten on-&thorn;reo". &verbar; &THORN;o seide (god) to Adam: "Go out of paradis! and &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">god fehlt im Ms.</NOTE> schul come to &thorn;at stude &thorn;at &yogh;e schulle agrysen of". &verbar; &THORN;o com &thorn;e angel Cherubim wi&thorn; a swerd brennynge &amp; drof hem out of paradys. &verbar; &THORN;o was Adam &amp; Eue brou&yogh;t in to &thorn;at stude &thorn;er he was Imaad. God &yogh;af hem curteles tweyne of beestes felles, &thorn;at heo hedden vppon, bitokened &thorn;at heo &amp; heore ofspring schulde dye in eor&thorn;e. &THORN;er heo lyueden heore lyf in &thorn;e wrecched weopes dale. &verbar; Ofte heo weoren a-cold and sore of-hungred; eddren mihte hem styngen, foules and beestes hem mihte to-tere; &thorn;e watur &thorn;at bifore hem bare, hem mihte adrenche.</P>
<P>Adam maad him an hous, forto wonen inne; swinke he moste &amp; trauaylen, &amp; Eue moste spynne. &THORN;er heo woneden ei&yogh;te dayes, in &thorn;ulke wonynge, in serwe &amp; in muche teone. &thorn;er-aftur he eode al one fourtene niht, bi water and bi londe, wi&thorn;ou|ten eny lyflode. And &thorn;er he com to Eue a&yogh;eyn &amp; tolde hire &thorn;is ty&thorn;inge &thorn;at he ne mihte fynde but more &amp; gras, &amp; &thorn;at schulde &thorn;e beestes of &thorn;e lond ete, for god hit ha&thorn; &yogh;euen to hem. &verbar; "Weilawey", qua&thorn; Eue, "Ichaue Iwrouht ful euele, for Ich 
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="223"> haue Ibrouht &thorn;e in muchel serwe &amp; care. &verbar; Adam, I bidde &thorn;e, qua&thorn; Eue, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be|nyme me my lyf, for Ichaue brouht &thorn;e in muchel serwe &amp; wo". &verbar; "Beo stille", qua&thorn; Adam, "hou miht I so do wi&thorn; my flesch and wi&thorn; my blode? Ac we schul do penaunce &amp; bidde god of merci, &yogh;if we mihte eny &thorn;ing amende". "Such penaunce" qua&thorn; Eue, "wol I haue as I mihte studefastlyche and wel ouer-come". "We schul hope" qua&thorn; Adam, "of for&yogh;iuenesse. Stond &thorn;ou in &thorn;is water of Tygre, vp to &thorn;i chinne &thorn;er-inne, XXX dayes; and alle &thorn;e while &thorn;ou art &thorn;er-inne, spek &thorn;ou no word: for vre lippes ben vnwor&thorn;i to speken eny &thorn;ing to god, for we eeten of &thorn;e fruit &thorn;at he us hedde for|boden. In &thorn;ulke manere I wol soffre penaunce in &thorn;e flum Jordan fourti dayes". Eue stod in hire penaunce, til eihte dayes weoren ago: &thorn;o com &thorn;e fend in &thorn;e liknesse of an angel to hire. And Eue loked vppon him: &amp; sore heo bigon to siken and<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. s&thorn;ken.</NOTE> wepte wel sore &amp; hire hondes gan to wringen. And &thorn;e angel made muche mornynge, &amp; seide &thorn;o to Eue: "Cum vp of &thorn;e water! for we angelus of heuene han preyed for &thorn;e: so &thorn;at Jhesu Crist ha&thorn; vnderfongen &thorn;i penaunce, for &thorn;ou wold so ble&thorn;eliche dwelle &thorn;er-in so longe. I am set to bringe &yogh;ow &thorn;er &yogh;e schul haue mete, such as &yogh;e weore wont to haue &amp; eeten in paradys". &verbar; &THORN;e corsud angel nom Eue vp bi &thorn;e hond &amp; ladde hire to druye londe; as soone as Eue was comen vp of &thorn;e water, hire bodi was grene as eni gras. &verbar; &THORN;e angel ladde Eue for&thorn;, forte heo coomen to flum Jordan, &thorn;er heo sei&yogh;en Adam stonde. &THORN;o &thorn;at Adam sauh &thorn;e angel leden Eue, he cri&yogh;ed to hire wi&thorn; muche serwe &amp; seide to hire: "Eue, Eue, wher is now &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t? al is for nou&yogh;t &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast Idon". &verbar; Anon heo wuste &thorn;o &thorn;at heo was bigiled. Heo &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;at hire herte wolde to-berste: so sore heo was agreued; adoun heo fel in a swoune, &amp; bigon to tere hire her &mdash; &thorn;o was al hire serwe Idoublet, more &thorn;en hit was toforen. Adam cursed &thorn;e fend &amp; seide to him: "Whi art &thorn;ou vr aduersarie &amp; vre foo? constou euer siggen &thorn;at we benomen &thorn;e eny joye o&thorn;er eny blisse, or &thorn;at we duden &thorn;e eny vnriht?" &verbar; &THORN;o &thorn;e fend onswerde wi&thorn; wel sori cheer: "Adam, al ich wite hit &thorn;e &amp; Eue, &thorn;i fere, &thorn;e cumpaignye of angelus &amp; heuene -blisse Ichaue for|loren. &verbar; Furst &thorn;o &thorn;ou was Ischapet and Imaad mon, &thorn;o was I comaundet of god &thorn;at I schulde honoure &thorn;e; and I seide I nolde not honoure &thorn;e, for no &thorn;ing; and &thorn;er|fore was god wro&thorn; wi&thorn; me: for &thorn;ulke vnboxumnesse was I put out of my sege of heuene". &verbar; &THORN;o spak Adam and seide: "What mihte we don &thorn;er-to? we ne knewe &thorn;e nou&yogh;t".</P>
<P>ADam heold vp his honden to &thorn;e heuene &amp; seide: "Haue merci of me, god omni|potent: in &thorn;i swete hondes I betake my soule, &amp; do &thorn;is feondes from vs &thorn;at don vs al &thorn;is wo. &verbar; I beseche god almihti to &yogh;iue me &thorn;ulke seete &thorn;at he ha&thorn; forloren". And &thorn;enne at &thorn;ulke wordus &thorn;e fend wente away. And Adam stod stille &amp; abod his pe|naunce. And &thorn;o he hedde don his penaunce, he com vp, &amp; a &thorn;under-blast com, and he and Eue, his wyf, wenten togedere: &amp; &thorn;o was Caym bi&yogh;eten. &verbar; &THORN;o seide Eue to Adam: "Ich mot fleo, for no lengur in &thorn;is sory lyf may I heer dwelle. &verbar; Bilef &thorn;ou her, lord, al one, and ich wol weenden to &thorn;e worldes ende, in to &thorn;e west". &verbar; Eue &thorn;o went hire for&thorn;, touward &thorn;e west-syde. And &thorn;er heo made hire a logge, forte wonen inne, for chele of snou&yogh; &amp; of forst &amp; for alle maner wikked wederes. Eue was wi&thorn; childe er heo went from Adam. So twelue mone&thorn; heo dwellet &thorn;ere. And whon &thorn;e tyme was comen &thorn;at &thorn;e child schulde boren be, heo was so sore adred &thorn;er-of &thorn;at heo forlees nerhonde hire witte. Ofte heo bad merci to god abouen, ac heo nas no&thorn;ing 
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="224"> herd of hire biddynge. Heo sent hire steuene &amp; hire sonde bi &thorn;e heuene to Adam, hire lord, how heo was bistad. &verbar; And Adam was strongliche aferd and gretliche abascht, &thorn;o he herde hire, leste &thorn;e fend weore Icomen hire to bitrayen. &verbar; &THORN;o &thorn;is ti&thorn;in|ges weore come to him &thorn;orw &thorn;e firmament, he wente to hire sone anon. &THORN;o &thorn;at Eue him seih, for blisse heo gon to weopen, &verbar; and seide: "Lord, wel is me &thorn;at I &thorn;e seo on lyue! sone so I &thorn;e se&yogh;e, I ne felede no&thorn;ing of alle my pyne. &verbar; Nou bidde god &thorn;at he me wol vnbynde of my serwe&mdash;for no&thorn;ing &thorn;at I bidde I may fynde no grace". &verbar; &THORN;o bad Adam to god his help &amp; his grace.</P>
<P>&THORN;Er coomen twelue angelus from heuene &amp; nomen Eue and seiden heo weoren Icome forto helpen hire, for Adames loue; "hi&yogh;e &thorn;e blyue, &thorn;at &thorn;i child weore boren! for &thorn;ou schalt haue help of vs". &THORN;at child was soone Iborn: Caym was &thorn;e childes nome. &verbar; &THORN;o nom Adam Eue, his wif, and his child, &amp; wenten a&yogh;eynward to &thorn;e Est|lond. &THORN;o god &yogh;af Adam diuerse seedes, &amp; tau&yogh;te him to tilye &amp; to sowe, so &thorn;at he mihte her-afturward bo&thorn;e repe &amp; gedere; and &thorn;at he schulde nym &yogh;eme to &thorn;e tilynge of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e, for hem and for heore ofspring &thorn;at aftur hem comen. And bad Adam to &yogh;euen him &thorn;e ti&thorn;e dole &thorn;at coome of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e. And &thorn;en seide Adam: "Lord, nym &thorn;e haluendole!" "Nay", seide vr lord, "hit schal &thorn;e tyme come &thorn;at &thorn;e ti&thorn;e dole schal beo binomen me for fals couetyse of &thorn;e fendes lore". &verbar; Adam bi&yogh;at ano&thorn;er child: Abel was his name. &THORN;eose two children wonede to gedere, &amp; swonken for heore mete, &thorn;orwh &thorn;e teching of heore fader. &verbar; Eue seide to Adam: "Icham sore agast &thorn;at Caym wol sle Abel, his bro&thorn;er: &thorn;erfore hit bihoue&thorn;, &yogh;if we wol wel do, to parte hem a-twynne". &verbar; &THORN;o was Caym maad tilyere, and Abel heerde of scheep and of o&thorn;ur beestes. &verbar; Abel was ti&thorn;er good of alle &thorn;inges &amp; &thorn;onked god swi&thorn;e wel; &verbar; and Caym ti&thorn;ed falslich, and brak godes hestes, for he wi&thorn;heold alwey &thorn;e beste dole &amp; &yogh;af god of &thorn;e worste. &verbar; Crist vnderfong wel fayre &thorn;e ti&thorn;e of Abel: for &thorn;e smoke wente euene vpward, as hit brende; and &thorn;e smoke of Caym wente dounwart, for he ti&thorn;ede falsliche. &verbar; &THORN;is was &thorn;e lawe of &thorn;e olde testament forto brenne alle maner ti&thorn;e: for &thorn;at god schulde ben heried of &thorn;at smoke &thorn;at coome vpward &thorn;e heuene. Abel hedde of god loue and grace, and &thorn;erfore Caym was wro&thorn; &amp; bigon to teren his visage. &verbar; &THORN;er-aftur god asket Caym whi he was so proud &amp; so stout &thorn;at he totaar his visage, and seide; "&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wel dost, &thorn;ou schalt wel fynde; and &yogh;if &thorn;ou eny &thorn;ing vuel dost, &thorn;ou schalt beo bounden wi&thorn; sunne". &verbar; After &thorn;is seide Caym to Abel: "Go we now to &thorn;e feelde forto witen vr fader bestes!" &verbar; So heo wenten for&thorn; I-feere. And &thorn;er Caym slouh Abel: wi&thorn; &thorn;e cheke-bon of an asse he smot him on &thorn;e hed; and &thorn;er he bilafte ded in &thorn;e feld of Damasse. &verbar; God asket of Caym: "Wher is &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur?" And Caym onswerde and seide: "I nam not his kepere". &verbar; "What hastou Ido?" qua&thorn; god to Caym, "&amp; wher hastou ibeon? &THORN;e vois of Abels blod crie&thorn; to heuene to me". &verbar; God &yogh;af Caym &thorn;er his curs for he hedde Iculd his bro&thorn;er &amp; sched his blod, and seide: "&thorn;e eor&thorn;e crie&thorn; to me on &thorn;e for &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don, and wol putte &thorn;e awey from his face, and alle &thorn;inges schul ben a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e, beestes and foules schul sle &thorn;e". &thorn;en seide Caym: "Nou I wot &thorn;at mi sunne is so muche &thorn;at I may haue no for&yogh;iuenesse. Nou, lord", seide Caym, "schal alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at come&thorn; to me, sle me?" "Nay", seide vr lord, "I schal sette a token vp on &thorn;e, &thorn;at alle &thorn;at sle Caym, seuenfold schal his synne be more". &verbar; And &thorn;o sette Crist a marke vp on him: &thorn;at he waggede alwey for&thorn; wi&thorn; his heued. &THORN;o tok Caym his wyf Calmana, &thorn;at was his suster, wi&thorn; him, &amp; al &thorn;at he hedde, and anon riht went him awey from &thorn;e face of god, in to &thorn;e lond of Edom, wi&thorn; serwe &amp; wi&thorn; wo.
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="225"></P>
<P>And whon Adam wuste &thorn;at Abel was slayn, his herte bigon to waxe cold&mdash;nas neuer mon for his child so wo. Adam seide: "&thorn;ou&yogh; I &thorn;ole wo hit is good riht; for &thorn;at I nolde not holde godes hestes, I haue forlore paradys, and nou for Abel my sone ne wor&thorn; I neuer bli&thorn;e". &verbar; &THORN;er-aftur an hundred &yogh;eer Adam wi&thorn; Eue engendrede no fruit, ac euere he was in serwe &amp; in wepyng. &verbar; &THORN;o &thorn;e hundred &yogh;eer weoren passet, him com aleggaunce of his wo: &verbar; Crist sent his angel, &amp; brouhte ti&thorn;ing &thorn;at heo schulden a-semble &amp; engendre fruit. &verbar; &THORN;o heo geeten a child: &thorn;at hihte Seth. &verbar; Adam hedde XXX sones &amp; moni dou&yogh;tres, wi&thorn;outen Caym &amp; Abel. &THORN;e children of Adam multipli&yogh;ed swi&thorn;e. And Adam comaunded to Seth &thorn;at non of his kuynde schulde felauschupe wi&thorn; Caymes kuynde ne wedde non wyues in Caymes kuynde&mdash;for &thorn;o &thorn;at coomen of Se&thorn;es kuynde ben cleped godes sones, and Caymes kuynde to(!) men sones. &verbar; And &thorn;enne at &thorn;e fiftene hondred winteres ende heo bigunnen to don heore lecherie priueliche, &amp; afturward openliche. &verbar; And &thorn;o afturward heo weddeden &thorn;e to kuynde in to &thorn;at o&thorn;ur, &amp; geeten geauns. And &thorn;enne god tok wreche &amp; adreynte al &thorn;e world, but eihte soules, at Noe flood&mdash;god was agreuet &thorn;er-of &amp; seide &thorn;at him for&thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;at he hedde Imaad mon; so he nom veniaunce of hem for heore foule synne.</P>
<P>Adam liuede heere in serwe &amp; in wo nyn hundret &yogh;er and more. Whon hit come&thorn; to &thorn;e day &thorn;at he schulde dye, he let sende aftur alle his sones, and seide: "Ich wot wel: whon I am ded, to helle mot ich wende". And whon heo weoren alle Ico|men forto seon heore fader, heo askeden what him eiled. "Me is vuele", qua&thorn; Adam, "for seknesse &amp; for wo: I am biset wi&thorn; vuel in herte &amp; syde and in vche a lime, &thorn;at I may not longe liue. &verbar; For &thorn;o &thorn;at I trespaset &amp; agult to god, VII and &thorn;ritti vueles he dude in my bodi. I wrecche, what schal I do?" &thorn;o Eue him onswerde, wel sore wepynge: "Lord", heo seide, "do in me Adames wo, for hit is not for his gult, ac hit is for myn". &verbar; Adam bad Eue and Seth weenden to paradis anon, &thorn;e whiles he weore on lyue, "and bidde &thorn;e angel &thorn;at he sende me hele&thorn;e; for wel I wot: whon I am ded, to helle me tit to weende". &verbar; And &thorn;o Seth seide to his fader: "I not what I may do: for to paradys I con no way". &verbar; "Sone", seide Adam, "&thorn;at gras &thorn;e wol techen: for al &thorn;e wey as we out eode &thorn;e gras is &thorn;er vnlikelich, for &yogh;it in to &thorn;is day nolde hit not arysen for &thorn;e sinnen &thorn;at we duden in paradys. Go anon for&thorn;, leue sone, &amp; do as I &thorn;e teche". &verbar; Seth bad his fader his blessing, and went anon his wey. Wel sore wepyng heo eoden in to paradis, for &thorn;e wey was long and brod. &THORN;er com &thorn;e fend as a neddre &amp; stynged Se&thorn; wel vuele. Eue weop sore &amp; seide to &thorn;e cursede wiht: "Whi artou so hardi to fihte wi&thorn; godes ymage?" &verbar; Seth acursed &thorn;e fend &amp; wa|riede him. And heo eoden for&thorn; on heore way, riht to &thorn;e &yogh;ates of paradis. Ac in|nore heo ne mi&yogh;te winne. &verbar; Ac &thorn;ere heo se&yogh;en &thorn;e blisse of mony maner foules, &amp; muche mur&thorn;e, &amp; joye inouh: and &thorn;at watur schon as brihte as &thorn;e sonne-beem, and &thorn;e blosmes weoren so fayre on vche maner treo &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te hem biholde for heor fairnesse, &thorn;e stones on &thorn;e grounde weoren as brihte as hit weore brenninde laite; &verbar; he sei&yogh; &thorn;ere angelus of wondurfol heuh&mdash;and al &thorn;ulke blisse lees Adam &thorn;orw &thorn;e gilerie of &thorn;e feend! &amp; &thorn;at we mowe sore rewe. &verbar; &THORN;e oyle of merci he asked ful sore wepynge, as his fader him hedde Itau&yogh;t. &verbar; And &thorn;o &thorn;e angel spac to Se&thorn; and bad him weende a&yogh;eyn, "and sei to Adam: whon &thorn;at V &thorn;ousend &yogh;eer and an hundret beon Ipasset, &thorn;en wol godus sone come in to flum Jordan, forto beo baptised &thorn;er-inne, of water &amp; of &thorn;e holy gost, for hel&thorn;e of Adam and of al his osprunch; &amp; er ne tit him none hele". &verbar; &THORN;e angel tok an appel and &yogh;af hit to Seth and bad him beren 
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="226"> hit to Adam, "and sei him &thorn;at he knowe&thorn; hit wel: for heo weoren alle at his comaun|dement, til &thorn;at he agulte god". &verbar; &THORN;reo curnels of an appel &thorn;e angel tok to Seth and bad him wite hem wel forte &thorn;at Adam weore ded, "and &thorn;enne do &thorn;at on in his mou&thorn;, and &thorn;e o&thorn;ure in his neose-&thorn;urles"! Swete spices he &yogh;af him, and seide to him: "Weent hom a&yogh;eyn anon: for Adam, &thorn;i fader, schal hastiliche dye". &verbar; Seth turnede a&yogh;ein, wel sore wepynge and wi&thorn; mournynge chere, for &thorn;at he schulde departe from &thorn;at grete blisse. And whon he com to his fader, he fel vppon his knes &amp; honoured him, and seide: "Leoue fader, hit ne helpe&thorn; not to &thorn;e forte beseche after hel&thorn;e, in to &thorn;at fiue &thorn;ousend &yogh;eer &amp; an hundret be gon: &thorn;enne wol godes sone ben bapti&yogh;ed in &thorn;e flum Jordan, for &thorn;e hele&thorn;e of &thorn;e &amp; of alle &thorn;ine: of alle maner vueles &thorn;ou schalt haue boote". Of &thorn;at word was Adam fayn &amp; swi&thorn;e glad, and &yogh;eorne cri&yogh;ede merci to god of heuene, for he nedde neuere in al his lyue so muche joye as he hedde &thorn;o. And &thorn;o louh(!) Adam and neuer aryst.</P>
<P>Adam seide: "Lord, &yogh;if hit weore &thorn;i wille, hit weore tyme now &thorn;at myn olde bones mihte ligge stille: for se&thorn;&thorn;e I com from paradis, Ichaue liued heere in muchel care. And whon Ich am ded, I wot wel &thorn;at I schal weende to helle. &verbar; I ne recche", qua&thorn; Adam, "&thorn;auh I beo pyned in alle skinnes wo, for Ich hope &yogh;it to come to &thorn;e blisse of paradis". &verbar; Adam eet &thorn;at appel &thorn;at Se&thorn; hedde Ibrouht him, and of no maner euel &thorn;ing he nedde no drede. And &thorn;eraftur sone dayes, as &thorn;e angel hedde told to Se&thorn;, he wente to Adam &amp; fond his limes colde. &verbar; &THORN;enne seide Adam to his sones &thorn;at weoren &thorn;o abouten him: "I am IX C &yogh;er old and XXX<SUP>ti</SUP>. As swi&thorn;e as Ich am ded, burie mi bodi in &thorn;e vale of Ebron &verbar;" &thorn;o Adam hedde so iseid, he lay stille &amp; &yogh;af vp &thorn;e gost. &verbar; In &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he dyede, &thorn;e day turned in to derknesse, and nei&thorn;er sonne ne mone ne sterre ne &yogh;af no liht. &verbar; Se&thorn; bicluppet &thorn;e bodi of his fader in his armes &amp; leide his hed wel feire in his barme; alle heo wepten &amp; maden serwe, til &thorn;at &thorn;e angel of god come to hem &amp; beed hem leuen &amp; be stille, &amp; seide to Se&thorn;: &verbar; "Lo, what god wol do wi&thorn; Adam, &thorn;i fader". &thorn;er comen &thorn;e angelus of heuene &amp; herieden god wi&thorn; swete song, for Adames soule, and amonges hem Se&thorn; feled vre lordes hond ouer Adam &thorn;er he lay, and seide &thorn;o to seint Mihel: "I betake in to &thorn;in hond Adam &amp; his osprunch, in serwe &amp; in wo, forte &thorn;e day of grace come: &verbar; &THORN;ene I wol turne al his sorwe in to joye &amp; blisse, and euermore schal laste, &thorn;ulke selue joie &thorn;at Lucifer les &thorn;orw his pruide". &verbar; God comaundet tweyn angelus to bringe twey clo&thorn;es, of sendel and of bijs: &thorn;at on to do vppon Adam, and &thorn;at o&thorn;er to don vppon Abel, his sone. &verbar; Seint Mihel and seint Vriel, Eue &amp; Se&thorn;, buried Adam &amp; Abel in &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;at heo comen of, in &thorn;e vale of Ebron. &verbar; Seint Mihel seide to Seth: "&thorn;us &yogh;e schul burie men whon &thorn;at heo ben dede". &THORN;er was &thorn;e eor&thorn;e Ihalewed at &thorn;e burieng of Adam, of god and of his angelus. &verbar; Seth dude &thorn;e greynes of &thorn;e appel vnder Adams tonge &amp; in &thorn;e neose-&thorn;urles. &verbar; &THORN;o longe afturward sprong &thorn;reo &yogh;erdes of &thorn;is greynes, &thorn;at weoren holy &amp; gode: on whuch Jhesus schedde his blod vppon for monnes sunne.</P>
<P>NOw I haue told &thorn;e lyf of Adam. Now herkene&thorn; of his soule whoder hit was lad! &verbar; In &thorn;e ouemaste prison of helle his soule was bounden, er &thorn;e bodi were cold, and &thorn;er-inne he was foure &thorn;ousend &yogh;eer VI C and foure, &mdash;for &thorn;er nas neuere so holy mon &thorn;at he ne was brouht &thorn;ider, til Jhesu Crist suffrede de&thorn; vppon &thorn;e roode. &verbar; &THORN;er|aftur eihte dayes &thorn;at Adam was ded, Eue feled hire de&thorn; ful neih. Heo comaundet &thorn;at al hire children schulde beo brou&yogh;t toforen hire: and tolde hem in what manere heo hedde agult god, and how &thorn;at god wolde take wreche of monkuynde wi&thorn; watur &amp; wi&thorn; fuir for heore sunne: &verbar; "&THORN;erfore make&thorn; tables of stones &amp; of cley and write&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="227"> &thorn;er-inne &thorn;e lyf of oure fader and of oure moder &amp; of oure bre&thorn;eren, &thorn;at &yogh;e han of vs se&yogh;en and herd, &thorn;at hit may beo founden aftur &thorn;at we ben dede. And &yogh;if &thorn;at fuir come&thorn;, &thorn;e tables of ston schul to-bersten for &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e fuir; and &yogh;if heo ben of clay, heo wolen laste longe".</P>
<P>&THORN;O Eue hedde &thorn;us Itold, heo heef vp hire honden and heried god almihti, and &yogh;eld vp &thorn;o &thorn;e gost. &verbar; Hire children wepten for hire al &thorn;at seuen-niht: &thorn;o com seint Mihel &amp; brouht hem ti&thorn;ing and beede hem sese of heore wepynge, and seide: "Nou is &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e day: reste&thorn;, and singeth of &thorn;e heriinge of god! for &thorn;at bitokene&thorn; &thorn;e reste of &thorn;e world &thorn;at is comynge; god him seluen sesed of al his werkes on &thorn;e so|nenday". &verbar; &THORN;o coome Seth &amp; made tables of ston and of cley &amp; wrot &thorn;e lyf of his fader and of his moder and of his moder and of his bre&thorn;eren &thorn;er-vppon, and leyden hem in Adames oratorie: And &thorn;er beo weoren Ifounden aftur &thorn;e deluuie. &verbar; In &thorn;e tables weoren Iwriten al &thorn;e deedes of Adam &amp; of o&thorn;ere; ac nomon &thorn;at heom sei&yogh;e, ne cou&thorn;e rede hem. And aftur feole &yogh;eres com Salamon &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ider forte seon &thorn;e tables, and bisouhte god almihti &thorn;at he moste wite what was &thorn;er-inne. And &thorn;enne com seint Mihel to Salamon and dude him to vndurstonden what was writen in &thorn;e tables, and seide: "Ich heold Se&thorn;es finger &thorn;e whiles hit weoren a writynge wi&thorn;outen iren or steel in &thorn;e harde ston, &amp; so heo duden. &YOGH;it liggen &thorn;e tables in &thorn;at ilke stude in Adames oratorie &thorn;er he bad his beodes". &verbar; &THORN;o &thorn;e kyng dude make a temple of gold &amp; of preciouse stones: in al &thorn;e world was non such, for &thorn;e stones in &thorn;e wal schonen nih as briht as &thorn;e sonne-beem. And &thorn;at hous was clepet: &thorn;e Temple of Jerusalem. For Adames children, &thorn;o &thorn;e folk haden rif Adames pynen, but soone aftur heo hedden sone for&yogh;eten hit, for muchel misdoyng of metes &amp; drinkes &amp; heor o&thorn;ure flessches lustes: &verbar; And so heo weoren alle ablent: and &thorn;erfore god almihti adreynt al &thorn;e world; he dreynte al &thorn;at was quik abouen &thorn;e eor&thorn;e, but onliche eihte soules. Now Ichaue &yogh;ow told al of &thorn;e furste world. And to &thorn;e world &thorn;at euer schal laste, god us &thorn;ider bringe!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Eine 2. Prosaversion findet sich in der altenglischen Ucbertragung der Leg. Aur.: Ms. Egert. 876 fol. 321 (in der letzten H&auml;lfte defect) und Ms. Harl. 4775 (vollst&auml;ndig), vgl. Progr. des Gymnasiams zu Sagan 1877: Barlaam &amp; Josaphat, Einl. Dieselbe Version findet sich vcreinzelt in Ms. Bodl. 596. fol. I. mit einigen Abweichungen. Diese 2. Version schliesst sich an die Creatio Mundi des Ms. Trin. 57 an, mit der sie &ouml;fter fast w&ouml;rtlich &uuml;bereinstimmt.</NOTE></P>
